{"type":"tool_execution_end","toolCallId":"call_4OMctTF3Tl2BBcznCUaZhAHt","toolName":"mcp","result":{"content":[{"type":"text","text":"ok: true\nstatus: ready\nstate: ready\nmessage: An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\nafter_version: 17\nafter_opportunity_id: deliberation:1:C2\nmember_id: C2\ncase_id: arb-ex03a-20260629214245\nwait_reason: ready\nphase: deliberation\nopportunity_id: deliberation:1:C2\nremaining_ms: 889046\nattempts_remaining: 3\njson: {\"after_opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C2\",\"after_version\":17,\"case_id\":\"arb-ex03a-20260629214245\",\"limits\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"max_evidence_read_bytes\":65536,\"max_evidence_read_bytes_per_opportunity\":524288,\"max_evidence_reads_per_opportunity\":32,\"max_response_bytes\":131072,\"remaining_evidence_read_bytes_for_opportunity\":524288,\"remaining_evidence_reads_for_opportunity\":32},\"member_id\":\"C2\",\"message\":\"An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\",\"ok\":true,\"prompt\":\"Role: council member\\nMember ID: C2\\nDeliberation round: 1\\nProposition: For the Kalshi market \\\"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\\", the strike \\\"Ronaldo\\\" should resolve Yes because Trump said \\\"Ronaldo\\\" in public remarks at the World Cup Draw venue immediately before the formal program, and the market wording plus the governing mention-market terms did not clearly exclude those event-linked remarks.\\nStandard of evidence: Preponderance of the evidence.\\nPersona:\\nYou are a careful juror and council member.\\n\\nEvaluate the record faithfully. Decide only from the evidence, the stated rules, and the applicable burden of proof. Do not favor either side, fill gaps with speculation, or ignore uncertainty.\\n\\nGive weight to reliable sources, direct evidence, consistent reasoning, and clear admissions. Discount unsupported claims, rhetorical force, irrelevant facts, and conclusions that exceed the record.\\n\\nWhen the evidence supports one answer, state it plainly. When the evidence is incomplete or balanced, say so. Be concise, honest, and exact.\\n\\nRecord:\\nOpenings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, this case is not about whether the word \\\"Ronaldo\\\" would count if President Trump clearly said it. The current packet makes that part straightforward: the market is the Kalshi PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION market titled \\\"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\\"; the strike is \\\"Ronaldo\\\"; Kalshi’s challenged resolution is No; and plaintiff seeks Yes.\\n\\nThe real dispute is temporal and contextual. Did the market phrase \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw,\\\" read with the governing mention-market terms, include public event-linked remarks at the World Cup Draw venue immediately before the formal draw program? Or did it clearly confine countable words to a narrower formal broadcast segment? Plaintiff’s position is that a No resolution cannot stand unless the record shows that the counting window clearly excluded those event-linked remarks.\\n\\nThe admitted terms matter. They define the underlying as words used by the specified entity during the specified time period. They expressly recognize event-based time periods, and they say the payout criterion is satisfied when the word is said by the entity during that period. They also contain exclusions: behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings do not count unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period; captions or text alone do not count; and the word must appear as a distinct standalone unit. Those exclusions are important, but they do not by themselves answer this case. A public remark at the event venue, tied to the Draw and immediately before the formal program, is not automatically a rehearsal, sound check, or private behind-the-scenes moment.\\n\\nAt this opening stage, the record proves the market identity, the challenged resolution, the requested resolution, and the generic governing terms. It does not yet prove the utterance itself, the exact sequence of the venue remarks, the source-agency hierarchy or any market-specific time-period language beyond the packet, or Kalshi’s reason for treating the strike as No. Those are the factual links that should decide the case under a preponderance standard.\\n\\nPlaintiff expects the decisive proof to be the full official or otherwise reliable event video or transcript, with enough surrounding context to show whether Trump said \\\"Ronaldo\\\" aloud as a standalone word; when he said it relative to the Draw event; whether the remarks were public and event-linked rather than backstage or a sound check; and whether any market-specific rule clearly excluded that segment. Plaintiff also expects the market page, archived market details, and any resolution rationale to be important because ambiguity in the market’s own event wording should not be resolved against Yes after the fact.\\n\\nThe defense will likely argue that \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw\\\" means only the formal draw ceremony or broadcast, and that anything before the formal program is outside the counting period. That theory can win only if the evidence shows a clear exclusion or a source record that separates the alleged remarks from the event itself. If the evidence instead shows public remarks at the Draw venue, officially connected to the event, immediately before the formal program, and no clear rule excluding them, then the terms favor counting the word and resolving the Ronaldo strike Yes.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the defense position is straightforward: the admitted record does not yet prove that the Ronaldo strike should resolve Yes. It proves a market title, a generic mention-market rule set, and Kalshi's challenged No resolution. It does not prove that any qualifying utterance of \\\"Ronaldo\\\" occurred during the market's countable time period.\\n\\nThe plaintiff's opening usefully narrows the dispute. This is not primarily a word-boundary case. If President Trump said \\\"Ronaldo\\\" as a standalone spoken word during the countable FIFA World Cup Draw period, the generic terms would ordinarily treat that as the kind of word that can count. The real question is whether plaintiff can carry the burden of showing that alleged pre-program, venue-adjacent remarks were part of the market's specified time period: \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\\\"\\n\\nThe case-packet terms matter, but they cut both ways. They say the underlying is words used by the entity during the specified time period. They recognize that a time period can be an event, and they allow the Exchange to specify what is included when an event is involved. They also distinguish official event presentation from material outside the event: behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are not included unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period; text or captions alone do not count; and the relevant word must be spoken aloud by the entity. Those provisions do not support a rule that every public comment inside the same building, or every press exchange near the formal program, is automatically \\\"during\\\" the Draw.\\n\\nThat is the burden problem for plaintiff. The admitted market-page file identifies the public title, contract family, strike, challenged resolution, and requested resolution. It does not supply a full market-specific source hierarchy, a formal start time, a transcript, a video, a resolution rationale, or the alleged remarks. The terms file supplies the generic framework, but not the factual bridge from \\\"immediately before the formal program\\\" to \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\\\" Without that bridge, the No resolution is not shown to be wrong by a preponderance of the evidence.\\n\\nThe defense expects the decisive proof to be source-chain evidence, not characterization. The council should want the market's full rule page if available, the source agency hierarchy, the official draw program or broadcast, any official transcript or recording of the alleged exchange, and enough surrounding timestamps to separate the formal draw from pre-event reporter access, red-carpet exchanges, arrivals, or other ancillary material. If later evidence shows that the alleged Ronaldo comment was in a segment officially presented as part of the Draw itself, plaintiff's argument becomes stronger. If the evidence instead shows a separate exchange with reporters before the draw, or an event-linked but pre-program interaction not incorporated into the official presentation, the generic terms support Kalshi's No.\\n\\nSo the defense opening is not that the word Ronaldo could never count. It is that this record has not established the necessary time-period link. The proposition asks the council to overturn No because the market wording and terms did not clearly exclude pre-program remarks. That reverses the burden. Plaintiff must show that the remarks were included in the countable period. Ambiguity about the outer edge of an event is not the same as proof that a specific pre-event utterance satisfies the payout criterion.\\n\\nArguments:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, plaintiff has now supplied the record links that were missing at opening.\\n\\nFirst, the market packet fixes what this dispute is: the Kalshi market title is \\\"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\\"; the contract family is PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION; the strike is \\\"Ronaldo\\\"; Kalshi's challenged resolution is No; and plaintiff seeks Yes. That is PX-1.\\n\\nSecond, the governing terms make this an event-period mention question, not a narrow formal-program-only question. PX-2 says the underlying is words used by the entity during the time period, recognizes that a time period may be a specific event, and sets the payout criterion as the word being said by the entity during that period. It also tells us what does not count: text/captions alone, unofficial behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, and sound checks unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. Those exclusions matter, but none says that public event-linked remarks at the venue immediately before the formal program are categorically outside \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\\\"\\n\\nThird, the source-chain evidence now points to the disputed event and the Ronaldo utterance. PX-3 is an official White House page titled \\\"President Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing,\\\" dated December 5, 2025, with a full-video link and related World Cup Draw videos. That establishes an official White House event-video source for Trump's attendance at the World Cup Drawing. PX-4 is a public YouTube watch-page metadata capture for video ID Cb2yO0lLEnM, titled \\\"Trump Talks Cristiano Ronaldo at FIFA Draw -- 'He's a Great Person'.\\\" Its description states that at the FIFA World Cup Draw Ceremony, Trump shared a story about meeting Cristiano Ronaldo at the White House, said Ronaldo was a great person, and mentioned Ronaldo spoke with his son. PX-4 is not as strong as an official transcript, and plaintiff says that plainly. But it is admitted source content that directly links Trump, Cristiano Ronaldo, and the FIFA Draw ceremony.\\n\\nOn a preponderance standard, that is enough to defeat the challenged No resolution unless the defense can supply a clearer exclusion. The market did not ask only what Trump would say during the ball-pulling segment, during the televised main show, or after a particular formal start cue. It asked what he would say \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\\\" The terms recognize event-based periods and exclude particular non-event categories. A public remark at the Draw venue, tied to the Draw, is far closer to the event period than to a rehearsal, sound check, caption, or private backstage recording.\\n\\nThe defense's burden framing is too strict. Plaintiff must prove Yes by a preponderance; plaintiff need not prove that Kalshi drafted every boundary with perfect precision. Once the admitted sources show a Ronaldo mention in connection with the FIFA Draw ceremony, the remaining question is whether the rules clearly remove that event-linked remark from the counting period. They do not. Ambiguity in a mention market's event wording should not be converted into an unstated formal-program limitation after the fact.\\n\\nProvenance and gaps: plaintiff attempted to retrieve the live Kalshi page, official/full video, caption, and transcript. Kalshi returned a Vercel security checkpoint; the local browser tool was unavailable; Python pip/ensurepip was unavailable for yt-dlp; and direct YouTube caption/open paths were throttled or unavailable. That leaves PX-4 weaker than ideal, but not weightless. PX-3 supplies official event context, PX-4 supplies the Ronaldo-at-FIFA-Draw metadata, and PX-2 supplies the rule that event-linked spoken words count absent a clear exclusion.\\n\\nThe council should resolve the proposition Yes: the Ronaldo strike should have resolved Yes because the record more likely than not shows Trump said Ronaldo in public remarks tied to the FIFA World Cup Draw, and the market wording plus governing terms did not clearly exclude those remarks.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the merits record now shows why the challenged No resolution should stand.\\n\\nPlaintiff's best point is that Trump did say the word \\\"Ronaldo.\\\" The defense does not need to fight that. The question is whether he said it during the market's countable time period: \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\\\" On that decisive question, the strongest official sources favor No.\\n\\nThe admitted GovInfo transcript, DX-1, is an official Compilation of Presidential Documents capture. Its title is not merely \\\"World Cup Draw\\\" or \\\"FIFA ceremony.\\\" It is \\\"Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw.\\\" That same transcript contains the Ronaldo passages: Trump says he met Ronaldo at the White House, later says he was \\\"not Ronaldo or Messi,\\\" and the note identifies Ronaldo among the people referenced. So DX-1 is not adverse to the defense because it confirms the word; it is decisive because it places the word in an exchange with reporters prior to the Draw.\\n\\nDX-2 supplies the timing anchor. The official FIFA Final Draw page states that the Draw at the Kennedy Center commenced at 12:00 local time on Friday, December 5, 2025. DX-1 states that the President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the Kennedy Center. A reporter exchange at 11:13, officially titled as prior to a 12:00 draw, is not more likely than not \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\\\" It is before it.\\n\\nThat reading matches the governing PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION terms. PX-2 says the payout criterion is satisfied when the word is said by the entity during the specified time period. It recognizes event-based periods and permits the Exchange to specify what is included for an event. It also treats official presentation differently from adjacent material: pre-recorded content counts if presented as part of the official event presentation, while behind-the-scenes, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings do not count unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. The point is not that this reporter exchange was a rehearsal or sound check. The point is that the terms require a link to the time period itself. Plaintiff has supplied no market-specific language saying pre-event reporter availability, arrivals, or venue interviews count as part of the Draw.\\n\\nPlaintiff's new exhibits do not fill that gap. PX-3, the White House page capture, establishes that the White House had a page titled \\\"President Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing,\\\" but plaintiff's own capture says the embedded/full video was not captured. It does not prove that the Ronaldo words occurred inside the official draw program. PX-4 is weaker still: it is metadata from a nonofficial YouTube channel. It says the clip is about Trump talking Ronaldo at the FIFA Draw, but it is not a transcript, not an official source, and not an audio extraction. When a nonofficial clip description is weighed against GovInfo's official transcript title and FIFA's official start time, the official sources control.\\n\\nNor is this a burden-shifting problem. The proposition asks the council to overturn Kalshi's No because the market supposedly did not clearly exclude remarks immediately before the formal program. But the preponderance burden is on Yes. The record must show that the strike satisfied the payout criterion. The admitted terms do not say that ambiguous pre-event remarks count by default; they say the word must be said during the specified time period. Here, the best evidence identifies the remarks as prior to the Draw and before the official commencement time.\\n\\nProvenance also matters. DX-1 is an official government transcript with a correction note and an audio-incomplete caveat. That caveat affects stray inaudible portions, but it does not weaken the title, the 11:13 timing note, or the Ronaldo passages preserved in the transcript. DX-2 is an official FIFA timing source. Plaintiff's YouTube metadata may explain why the dispute arose, but it cannot outweigh those primary sources on timing and event classification.\\n\\nThe council should resolve the proposition against plaintiff. Trump said Ronaldo, but the record more likely shows he did so in a reporter exchange prior to the FIFA World Cup Draw, not during the countable Draw event. Kalshi's No resolution should be upheld.\\n\\nRebuttals:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, defendant’s new evidence narrows the case but does not end it.\\n\\nPlaintiff accepts the important parts of DX-1 and DX-2. The GovInfo transcript is official; it labels the item an exchange with reporters \\\"Prior to\\\" the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw; it places the exchange at 11:13 a.m. at the Kennedy Center; and the FIFA capture states the draw commenced at 12:00 local time. Plaintiff should not pretend those facts are weak.\\n\\nBut defendant asks those facts to do more than they do. The market was not drafted as \\\"what will Trump say after the official 12:00 commencement,\\\" \\\"during the televised draw program,\\\" or \\\"during the ball-drawing segment.\\\" PX-1 says the public market title was \\\"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\\" That is ordinary event language, and PX-2 recognizes event-based time periods while leaving room for the Exchange to specify what is included. The record still contains no market-specific exclusion for official venue press remarks immediately before the formal program.\\n\\nDX-1 also helps plaintiff on the facts defendant originally said were missing. It confirms the relevant spoken word. Trump said he met Ronaldo, that Ronaldo is great, and that he was not Ronaldo or Messi. It also places those remarks at the Kennedy Center in a FIFA World Cup Draw-centered exchange with reporters, not in an unrelated private dinner or stale campaign setting. The transcript’s own subject metadata includes the FIFA World Cup, the Kennedy Center, news media, presidential interviews, and soccer. That is event-linked public context.\\n\\nThe terms’ exclusions do not fit defendant’s leap. PX-2 excludes captions alone, rehearsals, sound checks, behind-the-scenes content, and unofficial recordings unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. DX-1 is not a rehearsal transcript. It is not a sound check. It is not merely a caption. It is an official presidential transcript of a public reporter exchange at the venue, released in the Compilation of Presidential Documents. If Kalshi meant to exclude that category because it occurred before a formal noon commencement, the market needed to say so clearly.\\n\\nSo the dispositive question remains one of market construction: does \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw\\\" clearly exclude public, official, event-site remarks immediately before the formal program? Defendant has proved \\\"prior to\\\" the formal draw start. Defendant has not proved a clear market rule that treats the broader Draw event as beginning only at 12:00 for mention purposes.\\n\\nUnder a preponderance standard, the record now confirms the Ronaldo utterance and confirms the FIFA Draw setting. The challenged No resolution should not be upheld by importing a narrow formal-program limitation that the market title and generic terms did not state.\\n\\nSurrebuttals:\\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff's rebuttal usefully clarifies the remaining dispute: plaintiff accepts that DX-1 is official, that it labels the relevant item an exchange with reporters \\\"Prior to\\\" the FIFA World Cup Draw, that the exchange occurred at 11:13 a.m. at the Kennedy Center, and that DX-2 places the official Draw commencement at 12:00 local time. Those concessions should decide the case.\\n\\nPlaintiff's answer is that the market did not say \\\"after 12:00,\\\" \\\"during the televised program,\\\" or \\\"during the ball-drawing segment.\\\" But the market also did not say \\\"at the venue before the Draw,\\\" \\\"in pre-event reporter exchanges,\\\" or \\\"in any public remarks connected to the Draw.\\\" The phrase it chose was \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\\\" Ordinary event language has a start, and the official FIFA source fixes that start at noon. Official GovInfo then fixes this exchange at 11:13 and titles it as prior to the Draw.\\n\\nThat is not a technicality. The terms require the word to be said during the specified time period. They recognize event-based periods and allow event-specific inclusions, but no admitted market-specific rule includes pre-event press access. Plaintiff's construction would turn any event-adjacent public remark into part of the event unless expressly excluded. That reverses the payout criterion. The claimant must show the word occurred during the time period; it is not enough to show the same venue, the same general topic, and official publication.\\n\\nPlaintiff says the exclusions do not fit because DX-1 is not a rehearsal, sound check, caption, or private backstage recording. Fair enough; the defense is not relying on those categories as labels. The defense relies on the affirmative timing requirement. A remark need not be a rehearsal to be outside the event. A reporter exchange officially described as prior to a noon event and occurring at 11:13 is outside because it is before the event began.\\n\\nThe record therefore proves the wrong fact for plaintiff. It proves Trump said Ronaldo, but in a pre-event reporter exchange. The proposition requires Yes only if those words count during the FIFA World Cup Draw. On this record, they do not. Kalshi's No resolution should be upheld.\\n\\nClosings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the final record leaves one legal question.\\n\\nThe easy factual question is resolved in plaintiff’s favor: Trump said \\\"Ronaldo.\\\" The official GovInfo transcript confirms it twice in substance: he said he met Ronaldo, praised him, and later said he was not Ronaldo or Messi. That is a spoken standalone use of the strike word. The record also places the remarks at the Kennedy Center in a FIFA World Cup Draw-centered reporter exchange. This was not an unrelated dinner, a caption, an AI voice, or a social-media paraphrase.\\n\\nThe hard point is timing. Defendant has the strongest evidence on the formal program boundary: GovInfo titled the exchange as \\\"Prior to\\\" the Draw, notes 11:13 a.m., and FIFA states the Final Draw commenced at 12:00 local time. Plaintiff does not ask the council to ignore that. The question is what the Kalshi market actually required.\\n\\nPX-1 did not say \\\"after 12:00.\\\" It did not say \\\"during the televised draw program\\\" or \\\"during the ball-drawing segment.\\\" It asked, in public market wording, \\\"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\\" PX-2’s generic terms recognize event-based periods and say the Exchange may specify what is included when a time period refers to an event. They also give specific exclusions: captions alone, rehearsals, sound checks, behind-the-scenes content, and unofficial recordings unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. None of those exclusions is this case. The GovInfo transcript is an official public presidential record of an event-site reporter exchange, not a rehearsal or sound check.\\n\\nDefendant’s best argument is that ordinary events have start times. True. But this market dispute is about public remarks at the venue immediately before the formal program, in the official context of the Draw, where the market and rules did not clearly define a noon-only boundary. If Kalshi wanted that narrower rule, it could have said so in the strike, the market title, or the event inclusion language. It did not.\\n\\nThe preponderance record therefore shows: Ronaldo was spoken; the remarks were public and officially documented; they were at the Kennedy Center in the FIFA World Cup Draw setting; and the governing market language did not clearly exclude that immediately-before-program event context. The challenged No resolution depends on importing a formal commencement limitation that is absent from the market packet.\\n\\nFor that reason, the Ronaldo strike should resolve Yes.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the closing record is narrow and concrete.\\n\\nEveryone now agrees on the easy fact: Trump said \\\"Ronaldo.\\\" The official GovInfo transcript proves that. But the proposition is not simply that Trump said the word somewhere near the FIFA World Cup Draw. The proposition asks you to overturn Kalshi's No because remarks immediately before the formal program should count under a market asking what Trump would say \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\\\" Plaintiff has not carried that burden.\\n\\nThe two strongest sources are official and aligned. GovInfo, in DX-1, titles the relevant document \\\"Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw.\\\" It notes that the President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the Kennedy Center. FIFA, in DX-2, states that the Final Draw commenced at 12:00 local time. Those facts are not peripheral. They answer the timing question: the Ronaldo words were in a reporter exchange before the Draw began.\\n\\nPlaintiff's closing says the market did not specify \\\"after 12:00,\\\" \\\"during the televised draw program,\\\" or \\\"during the ball-drawing segment.\\\" True, but that does not prove Yes. The market did specify \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\\\" The ordinary function of \\\"during\\\" is to define the event period, not to include anything public, official, and thematically related that happens beforehand. A 47-minute-before reporter exchange officially titled as prior to the Draw is outside that period unless the market or governing terms affirmatively include it. The record contains no such inclusion.\\n\\nThe governing terms reinforce that conclusion. They require the word to be said by the entity during the specified time period. They recognize event-based periods and allow the Exchange to specify event inclusions. They include official-presentation concepts for material presented as part of an event. But they do not say that pre-event press availability counts by default. Plaintiff's argument turns the absence of an exclusion into proof of inclusion. That is backwards under a preponderance standard.\\n\\nPlaintiff also leans on setting: Kennedy Center, FIFA World Cup subject matter, official transcript, public reporters. Those facts show why the issue is understandable. They do not move 11:13 into a 12:00 event. A source can be official and still describe something outside the event. Indeed, that is exactly what DX-1 does: it officially documents the remarks and officially labels them prior to the Draw.\\n\\nThe weaker evidence points the same way once weighed properly. The White House page capture does not include the video or transcript. The YouTube metadata is nonofficial and not an audio transcript. Neither overcomes GovInfo's title and timing note plus FIFA's commencement time.\\n\\nSo the final answer is simple: the word was spoken, but not during the countable event period shown by the best evidence. Plaintiff has not shown that Kalshi's No resolution was wrong. The council should reject the proposition and uphold No.\\n\\nExhibits:\\n[plaintiff] PX-1 Market page packet: Ronaldo strike and challenged No resolution\\nMarket URL: https://kalshi.com/markets/kxtrumpmentionb/trump-mention-b/kxtrumpmentionb-25dec06\\n\\nPublic market title: What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\n\\nContract family: PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION\\n\\nStrike at issue: Ronaldo\\n\\nChallenged resolution: No\\n\\nRequested resolution: Yes\\n\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-2 Governing PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION terms\\n                                         NEWMENTION\\n\\nScope: These rules shall apply to this contract.\\n\\nUnderlying: The Underlying for this Contract is words used by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nRevisions to the Underlying made after Expiration will not be accounted for in determining the\\nExpiration Value.\\n\\nSource Agency: The Source Agencies are \\u003csource\\u003e.\\n\\nType: The type of Contract is an Event Contract.\\n\\nIssuance: After the initial Contract, Contract iterations will be listed on an as-needed basis at\\nthe discretion of the Exchange and corresponding to the risk management needs of Members.\\n\\n\\u003centity\\u003e: \\u003centity\\u003e refers to the speaker, writer, performer, or communicator specified by the\\nExchange. This may include (but is not limited to): a specific named individual, multiple\\nindividuals specified using AND/OR logic, an individual identified by position or title, a group,\\nband, team or collective entity, a specified member or members of a group, an organization,\\ncompany, or institutional entity, or any combination of the aforementioned.\\n\\nWhen \\u003centity\\u003e is defined by a position or title, the Contract tracks whoever holds that position\\nduring \\u003ctime period\\u003e, even if the individual holding the position changes. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a\\nspecific named individual, the identity remains consistent throughout. Name changes (e.g.,\\nstage names, married names) do not create a new entity. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a group or\\norganization and the Contract does not specify particular members, any official\\ncommunication or statement by any member or designated spokesperson counts. When using\\nAND logic, all specified entities must independently say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e. When\\nusing OR logic, at least one of the specified entities must say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nThe Exchange may specify additional conditions such as “at least X members of” a group or\\n“the majority of” a group.\\n\\n\\u003csource\\u003e: \\u003csource\\u003e refers to a Source Agency or ordered collection of Source Agencies\\nspecified by the Exchange at the time of Contract listing, which will be incorporated into the\\nSource Agency hierarchy above and used to determine the occurrence of the Underlying.\\n\\u003csource\\u003e may refer to a singular agency, multiple agencies, an agency by distinguishing\\ncharacteristics, by category or type (e.g., “official government statistical body,” “primary wire\\nservice”), or any combination thereof. When multiple agencies are specified, they may be\\napplied in the hierarchical order designated by the Exchange if so specified, with the highest-\\nranked available and responsive agency taking precedence for purposes of determining the\\nExpiration Value. A lower-ranked agency shall only be consulted if all higher-ranked agencies\\nare unavailable, unresponsive, have not reported on the Underlying by the Expiration time, or\\nif the Exchange, in its sole discretion, determines that a higher-ranked agency’s reporting is\\nincomplete, erroneous, or otherwise insufficient to determine the Expiration Value. If \\u003csource\\u003e\\ndesignates multiple agencies without specifying a hierarchical order, the Exchange shall\\nresolve any conflict between reporting agencies at its sole discretion.\\n\\n\\u003cword\\u003e: \\u003cword\\u003e refers to the particular word or phrase potentially to be mentioned by\\n\\u003centity\\u003e. It may refer to a word being said a minimum number of times. It may also refer to\\none of multiple words/phrases, any of which are acceptable (e.g., “Doge/Dogecoin”).\\n\\f\\u003ctime period\\u003e: \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific range of time, event or discrete date and\\ntime specified by the Exchange. This may be defined by, but is not limited to: a specific event\\nor context (e.g., “during the State of the Union address”), exact dates or times, relative time\\nmarkers (e.g., “before July 1, 2027,” “in Q1 2026”), event-based periods (e.g., “during any\\ncampaign rally in October 2026,” “during the awards ceremony”), and broader intervals (e.g.,\\n“Q1–Q2 2027,” “January–March 2026”).\\n\\nUnless stated otherwise, “Between” is inclusive of both endpoints, while “before” and “after”\\nexclude the specified date. \\u003ctime period\\u003e may also refer to “Any” or “None”, to multiple dates\\n(even if non-consecutive), or to a singular and discrete date or time.\\n\\nWhen \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event (such as an address, speech, performance, or\\nbroadcast), the Exchange may specify what is included, including whether it includes both live\\nand pre-recorded segments (including whether advertisements are included). Where a\\ntimezone is not specified, ET is assumed.\\n\\n\\nPayout Criterion: The Payout Criterion for the Contract encompasses the Expiration Values that\\n\\u003cword\\u003e is said by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n\\n\\nThe word must appear as a distinct, standalone unit, not buried inside another word. Plural\\nand possessive noun forms count. Other grammatical changes (tense, conjugation, derivation)\\ndo not. If \\u003cword\\u003e appears separated from other words by a space or hyphen or in a\\ncompound form with a space or hyphen, it counts. If \\u003cword\\u003e is fused into a single\\nunhyphenated word, it does not count.\\n\\nIf \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled, and the market contains a\\nstrike stating “Event does not qualify/occur”, such a strike shall resolve “Yes” and all others\\n“No”. If \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled but such strikes are NOT\\nlisted, the Contracts will resolve to the last fair price determined at the discretion of the\\nExchange. If the event is postponed, and such a postponement is announced by the end of the\\nfollowing calendar day to be rescheduled to a time within 14 calendar days, the markets shall\\nremain open. If the event captured in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast, the\\nExchange may keep the market open for 24 hours for the release of an official recording.\\nFurther granular details on conditions for these Contracts is available below.\\n\\nAdditional clarification(s):\\n\\n     Possessive noun forms of \\u003cword\\u003e, plurals, and possessive plural noun forms are\\n     INCLUDED:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigrants” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Egg” → “eggs’ shells” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Russia” → “Russia’s” counts, “Russian” does not\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e exists only in adjective form, no plural form exists:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Economic” → “Economics” does not count (“Economic” is an adjective\\n          for which “Economics” is not a plural)\\n     Plural nouns occurring within proper nouns and noun phrases are included:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Cat” → “Cats the musical” counts\\n\\f    Grammatical variations beyond plurals/possessives are NOT included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigration” does NOT count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Run” → “Running” or “Ran” do NOT count\\n    When \\u003cword\\u003e specifies a plural form, the singular does NOT count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Veterans” → “Veteran” does NOT count\\n    Words that are spelled the same as the plural form of \\u003cword\\u003e (if such exists) but are\\n    themselves not a plural noun are included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Wind” → “Winds up the clock” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Border” → “The United States has strong borders” counts\\n    Open compounds (words separated by spaces) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fire station” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “couch” → “couch potato” counts\\n    Hyphenated compounds (words connected by hyphens) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Palestine” → “pro-Palestine” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fat” → “non-fat” counts\\n    Closed compounds (single word, no spaces/hyphens) do not count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire” does not count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firefighter” does not count\\n    Multi-word \\u003cword\\u003e in larger constructions: When \\u003cword\\u003e is a multi-word phrase\\n    appearing within a hyphenated construction, it counts only if \\u003cword\\u003e appears as a\\n    complete, unmodified element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “New York” → “New York-based” counts (complete element)\\n    Portmanteaus (words blended from two words where parts of each are combined) are\\n    NOT included unless the portmanteau clearly contains \\u003cword\\u003e as a distinct, unaltered\\n    element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “MAGA” → “MAGA-nificent” counts (MAGA appears as distinct element)\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “magnificent” → “MAGA-nificent” does NOT count (portmanteau blend)\\n\\nDictionary determination: Both the Merriam-Webster Dictionary (available online) AND the\\nOxford English Dictionary shall be used to determine compound type and/or conventional\\nspelling patterns. Inclusion in either dictionary as an open or hyphenated compound shall\\nsatisfy the Payout Criterion. If neither provides clarity (or the word is not included),\\ndetermination is based on whether written as single unit (closed/doesn’t count) vs. spaces or\\nhyphens (open or hyphenated/counts) and/or context and previous usage.\\n\\nPHONETIC EQUIVALENCIES\\n\\n    Homophones (same sound, different spelling) do not count:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “write” → “right” does not count\\n    Homonyms and homographs (same spelling) COUNT regardless of meaning or\\n    pronunciation:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “bass” → both “bass guitar” and “bass fishing” count\\n    Proper and common nouns are treated identically:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Apple” → both “Apple Inc.” and “apple” (fruit) count\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Will” → both “Will Smith” and “I will go” count\\n    Minor unintentional mispronunciations COUNT if context makes intent clear:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Mamdani” → “Mandani” counts\\n    Severe mispronunciations that make \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable do NOT count.\\n    Trademarked spellings do not count, even when pronounced identically, unless the word\\n\\fitself is the same:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “lift” → “Lyft” (pronounced “lift”) does not count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “uber” → “Uber” counts\\nWords with non-standard transliteration to English count within reason, provided they are\\nphonetically equivalent:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Zelensky” → any of “Zelenski,” “Zelenskii,” “Zelensky,” or “Zelenskiy”\\n      count if pronounced equivalently\\nContractions do not count for their constituent words unless otherwise explicitly specified\\nby the Exchange:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “not” → “won’t,” “can’t,” “don’t,” “isn’t” do not count\\nNumbers spoken as words COUNT, when spoken exactly (not part of a larger number):\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “five” → saying “five” or reading “$5” aloud as “five dollars” counts,\\n      saying “five hundred” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “410” → “four hundred ten”, “four one zero” or “four ten” counts\\nOrdinals COUNT when \\u003cword\\u003e is written numerically OR a phrase that includes a\\nnumber:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “January 6” → “January 6th” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “3” (written numerically) → “3rd” (spoken as “third”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Eight War” → “8 Wars” and “Eighth War” will count\\nCardinal and ordinal number words are distinct:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “one” → “first” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “first” → “one” does NOT count\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count when pronunciation or letter-by-letter spelling\\nmatches \\u003cword\\u003e:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “NASA” (pronounced “NAH-suh”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “N-A-S-A” (spelled out) counts\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count as \\u003cword\\u003e when pronounced as the full word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Doctor” → “Dr.” (pronounced “Doctor”) counts\\nExpanded forms of acronyms do NOT count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “AI” → “artificial intelligence” does not count\\nWords in foreign languages do NOT count unless they are perfect cognates with an\\nEnglish word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fuego” (Spanish) does NOT count\\nEnglish words within foreign sentences count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “policy” → “Nuestra policy es clara” counts\\n\\u003cword\\u003e in organization/company names counts:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Securities” → “Bank of America Securities” counts\\nWords in URLs, emails, handles, and hashtags (exclusive of domain structure, email\\nprovider or symbols) are treated as compounds when spoken as complete words, with the\\ntype of compound subject to aforementioned rules:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firestation.com” pronounced “fire station dot com” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire.com” pronounced “wildfire dot com” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “apple” → “apple.com” pronounced “apple dot com” does count\\n      When presented in URL, email, handle, or hashtag form, \\u003cword\\u003e shall be treated as\\n      a compound, not a multi-word word\\nSung, rapped, or poetic words COUNT if phonetically recognizable:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “money” → “moneyyy” (extended in rap) counts\\n      Extreme distortion making \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable does NOT count.\\nPhonetic alphabet spelling (“Foxtrot India Romeo Echo” for “FIRE”) does NOT count.\\n\\fCANCELLATIONS AND DELAYS\\n\\n   The Exchange may list an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike for any Contract. If listed,\\n   such a strike refers to the structural conditions of the market, and is NOT adjudicated as a\\n   \\u003cword\\u003e needing to be said by or validated by having been said by \\u003centity\\u003e. If listed, this\\n   strike resolves to “Yes” whenever the event fails to occur or qualify under the Payout\\n   Criterion, or any other circumstance prevents normal resolution.\\n   If no such strike is listed, and \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, the following rules\\n   apply if the event is cancelled, postponed, rescheduled, or materially altered (including\\n   being closed to press) such that no video is released within one calendar day of the\\n   original start time of the event:\\n         If the event is cancelled, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price determined in\\n         the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         If the event is postponed or rescheduled, the outcome depends on whether a new\\n         date is publicly announced within one calendar day (i.e. if the event was scheduled\\n         to begin on Monday, any time up to 11:59PM on Tuesday falls within this period) of\\n         the originally scheduled start time:\\n               If no new date is announced within one calendar day, the Contract will resolve\\n               to the last fair price determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n               If a new date is announced within one calendar day, the outcome depends on\\n               when the rescheduled event is set to occur:\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls within fourteen (14) calendar days of the\\n                     originally scheduled date, the Contract shall remain open and \\u003cword\\u003e\\n                     stated during the rescheduled event will count.\\n                           The fourteen-day window begins at 12:00 AM ET on the originally\\n                           scheduled date and ends at 11:59 PM ET fourteen days later, unless\\n                           an alternate timezone is explicitly specified.\\n                           Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the State of the Union on January\\n                           15, 2026” rescheduled to January 20, 2026 → words spoken during\\n                           the rescheduled address count.\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls more than fourteen (14) calendar days after\\n                     the originally scheduled date, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price\\n                     determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         Any Contract that cannot be resolved through the Source Agency hierarchy will\\n         instead be settled at the Last Fair Price. The Exchange will disclose the methodology\\n         used to determine the Last Fair Price (e.g., Last Traded Price, Time-Weighted\\n         Average Price) at the time of Issuance.\\n         If an event begins but is interrupted, abbreviated, or ends prematurely, words\\n         stated by \\u003centity\\u003e during the portion of the event that did occur will count and the\\n         market will otherwise resolve.\\n   If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window but the venue, format, or medium\\n   changes (e.g., moved to a different location, changed from in-person to virtual (with the\\n   exception of being closed to press)), words stated during the event will count.\\n   Special condition: Across both cases, whether an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike is\\n   listed or not, if the event specified as or in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast (or\\n   relayed as such) but the live stream/broadcast does not occur, the Exchange will instead\\n   use an officially released recording as the Underlying, and may delay resolution by up to\\n   one calendar day to allow for the release of such a recording.\\n\\f          If partial snippets are released, Contracts on words that do not appear will be\\n          resolved to last fair price, and Contracts on those that do will be resolved to “Yes”.\\n          If no recording is released, the relevant outcomes triggered by the\\n          presence/absence of an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike shall occur as outlined\\n          above.\\n\\nTECHNICAL DETAILS (UNLESS OTHERWISE SPECIFIED)\\n\\n     When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, pre-recorded content broadcast,\\n     streamed, or published as part of that event is included if presented as part of the official\\n     presentation.\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the concert” with pre-recorded video interlude\\n          where entity speaks → words from interlude count\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the television appearance” with pre-taped\\n          segment aired during broadcast → words from segment count\\n     Behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are NOT\\n     included unless officially broadcast or published as part of \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n     Subtitles and captions that display \\u003cword\\u003e on screen but are not spoken aloud by\\n     \\u003centity\\u003e do NOT count.\\n     Sign language interpretation or usage by entity does NOT count as saying \\u003cword\\u003e unless\\n     the Contract explicitly specifies that sign language counts.\\n     Text that entity displays on screen (presentation slides, teleprompter visible to audience,\\n     signatures) does NOT count unless entity reads it aloud.\\n     Content generated by AI, deepfakes, or synthetic voice technology impersonating entity\\n     does NOT count unless the synthetic content is officially commissioned, authorized, or\\n     published by entity, OR the Contract explicitly specifies that AI-generated content counts.\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e is muted due to technical failure or censorship it shall not count unless\\n     corroborating contextual evidence (including surrounding speech, or an official\\n     uncensored recording or transcript) confirms that \\u003centity\\u003e specifically uttered \\u003cword\\u003e\\n     during the muted period.\\n\\nMinimum Tick: The Minimum Tick size for the Contract shall be $0.01.\\n\\nPosition Accountability Level: The Position Accountability Level for the Contract shall be\\n$25,000 per strike, per Member.\\n\\nLast Trading Date: The Last Trading Date of the Contract will be the Expiration Date. The Last\\nTrading Time will be the Expiration time.\\n\\nSettlement Date: The Settlement Date of the Contract shall be no later than the day after the\\nExpiration Date, unless the Market Outcome is under review pursuant to Rule 7.1.\\n\\nExpiration Date: When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event: The latest Expiration Date of\\nthe Contract shall be fourteen (14) calendar days after the originally scheduled date of the\\nevent. If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window, expiration will be moved to an\\nearlier date and time in accordance with Rule 7.2. When \\u003ctime period\\u003e is defined by specific\\ndates: The latest Expiration Date of the Contract shall be two weeks after the end of \\u003ctime\\nperiod\\u003e. If an event described in the Payout Criterion occurs and a consensus has been\\nreached on all terms, then expiration will be moved to an earlier date and time in accordance\\nwith Rule 7.2.\\n\\fExpiration time: The Expiration time of the Contract shall be 10:00 AM ET.\\n\\nSettlement Value: The Settlement Value for this Contract is $1.00.\\n\\nExpiration Value: The Expiration Value is the value of the Underlying as documented by the\\nSource Agency on the Expiration Date at the Expiration time.\\n\\nContingencies: Before Settlement, Kalshi may, at its sole discretion, initiate the Market\\nOutcome Review Process pursuant to Rule 7.1 of the Rulebook. If an Expiration Value cannot\\nbe determined on the Expiration Date, Kalshi has the right to determine payouts pursuant to\\nRule 7.1 in the Rulebook.\\n\\f\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-3 Official White House World Cup Drawing video page capture\\nSource capture from official White House page https://www.whitehouse.gov/videos/president-trump-attends-the-fifa-world-cup-drawing/\\nRetrieval: 2026-06-29T21:52:12Z via OpenClaw web_fetch and web.open.\\n\\nVisible page facts captured:\\n- Page title: President Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing\\n- Date shown on page: December 5, 2025\\n- Page section: Videos\\n- The page contains a link labeled View Full Video to Instagram.\\n- Related video listed: FIFA World Cup 2026 Draw at The Kennedy Center, duration 00:45, dated December 6, 2025.\\n- Related video listed: FIFA World Cup Drawing Announced to Take Place at The Kennedy Center, duration 00:56, dated August 23, 2025.\\n- Related video listed: President Trump on the 2026 FIFA World Cup, duration 01:22, dated May 6, 2025.\\n\\nRelevant extracted lines from web.open capture:\\nL142: Videos\\nL143: # President Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing\\nL145: December 5, 2025\\nL133: ... View Full Video [instagram.com] ...\\nL151: FIFA World Cup 2026 Draw at The Kennedy Center\\nL153: December 6, 2025\\nL167-L170: President Trump on the 2026 FIFA World Cup, May 6, 2025\\n\\nNotes on capture limits: readability extraction returned minimal content, so the above preserves visible lines from the page capture. The embedded/full video itself was not captured in this item.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-4 YouTube metadata capture for Ronaldo-at-FIFA-Draw clip\\nSource capture: YouTube watch page https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Cb2yO0lLEnM\\nVideo ID: Cb2yO0lLEnM\\nRetrieval: 2026-06-29T21:53:00Z via web search and curl of the YouTube watch page.\\n\\nCaptured title / page metadata:\\n- Title shown in search and page metadata: Trump Talks Cristiano Ronaldo at FIFA Draw — ‘He’s a Great Person’\\n- Channel shown in page metadata: interestingText You / @InterestingTextYou\\n- Subscriber count shown in page metadata at capture: about 10.3K subscribers\\n\\nCaptured description text from YouTube page metadata:\\n\\\"Trump Talks Cristiano Ronaldo at FIFA Draw — ‘He’s a Great Person’\\n\\nAt the FIFA World Cup Draw Ceremony, Donald Trump shared a story about meeting Cristiano Ronaldo at the White House. Trump said Ronaldo was “a great person” and even mentioned that Ronaldo spoke with his son about soccer during the visit.\\n\\nThis unexpected crossover between world politics and one of the biggest global sports stars quickly caught viewers' attention.\\n\\nTrump FIFA Draw\\nDonald Trump FIFA World Cup\\nTrump Cristiano Ronaldo\\nCristiano Ronaldo Trump meeting\\nFIFA World Cup draw 2026\\nRonaldo White House visit\\nTrump soccer comments\\nWorld Cup trending 2025\\nsports politics crossover\\nCristiano Ronaldo story\\nDonald Trump viral moment\\nFIFA draw ceremony Trump\\nWorld Cup 2026 news\\nRonaldo fan reaction\\npolitical celebrity moments\\nviral sports clips 2025\\nFIFA draw highlights\\nTrump speech FIFA\\nglobal sports news\\\"\\n\\nCapture limits and provenance caveat: direct video/caption extraction was attempted but YouTube transcript/open paths were throttled or unavailable in this environment. This item preserves the public watch-page metadata and description, not an independently extracted audio transcript. It is not an official White House or FIFA source.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-1 GovInfo official transcript: remarks prior to FIFA World Cup Draw\\nSource: GovInfo, Compilation of Presidential Documents, DCPD202501162\\nURL retrieved: https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/DCPD-202501162/html/DCPD-202501162.htm\\nRetrieval time: 2026-06-29T22:00:00Z\\nLocal captured HTML size/hash: 51,571 bytes; SHA-256 eadbceeecf3e94f5bd423bcb8e8511165fdc7265dd8c1e025870c2e8f34dfd99\\n\\nMaterial captured text from official GovInfo HTML/web.open:\\n\\nAdministration of Donald J. Trump, 2025\\n\\nTitle: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\nDate: December 5, 2025\\n\\nOpening note: [The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\\n\\nExcerpt - The President's Interest in Soccer (web.open lines 196-203):\\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\\\"football,\\\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\\n\\nExcerpt - The President's Interest in Soccer (web.open lines 322-329):\\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\\nThe President. But they have a little more speed. But no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\\n\\nTiming/context note (web.open lines 461-462):\\nNOTE: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. In his remarks, he referred to Trey Yingst, chief foreign correspondent, Fox News Channel; Cristiano Ronaldo, forward for Saudi Pro League club Al-Nass and Portugal's national soccer team; and Lionel Messi, forward for Major League Soccer club Inter Miami and Argentina's national team. A reporter referred to New York State Attorney General Letitia James.\\nThe transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\n\\nDocument category/location/name/subject metadata (web.open lines 463-468):\\nCategories: Interviews With the News Media: Exchanges with reporters, Washington, DC.\\nLocations: Washington, DC.\\nNames include: Cristiano Ronaldo and Lionel Messi.\\nSubjects include: Federation Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) World Cup; John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts; News media, Presidential interviews; Soccer.\\nDCPD Number: DCPD202501162.\\n\\nCapture limits: This item is a focused text capture of the material official transcript title, Ronaldo excerpts, timing/correction note, and metadata. It is not a full video or audio artifact. The official transcript itself notes some portions could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-2 FIFA official Final Draw start-time capture\\nSource: FIFA official page, FIFA World Cup 2026 Final Draw\\nURL: https://www.fifa.com/en/tournaments/mens/worldcup/canadamexicousa2026/live-draw\\nRetrieval time: 2026-06-29T22:01:00Z\\n\\nMaterial captured text from web search/open result:\\n- Page title/source: FIFA World Cup 2026™ Final Draw\\n- The draw takes place at the Kennedy Center in Washington DC, USA.\\n- The draw commences at 12:00 local time (17:00 UTC) on Friday 5 December 2025.\\n\\nCapture limits: This is a focused text capture of the official FIFA page timing statement located by web search. It is not a video capture of the draw ceremony.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-3 Governing PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION terms\\n                                         NEWMENTION\\n\\nScope: These rules shall apply to this contract.\\n\\nUnderlying: The Underlying for this Contract is words used by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nRevisions to the Underlying made after Expiration will not be accounted for in determining the\\nExpiration Value.\\n\\nSource Agency: The Source Agencies are \\u003csource\\u003e.\\n\\nType: The type of Contract is an Event Contract.\\n\\nIssuance: After the initial Contract, Contract iterations will be listed on an as-needed basis at\\nthe discretion of the Exchange and corresponding to the risk management needs of Members.\\n\\n\\u003centity\\u003e: \\u003centity\\u003e refers to the speaker, writer, performer, or communicator specified by the\\nExchange. This may include (but is not limited to): a specific named individual, multiple\\nindividuals specified using AND/OR logic, an individual identified by position or title, a group,\\nband, team or collective entity, a specified member or members of a group, an organization,\\ncompany, or institutional entity, or any combination of the aforementioned.\\n\\nWhen \\u003centity\\u003e is defined by a position or title, the Contract tracks whoever holds that position\\nduring \\u003ctime period\\u003e, even if the individual holding the position changes. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a\\nspecific named individual, the identity remains consistent throughout. Name changes (e.g.,\\nstage names, married names) do not create a new entity. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a group or\\norganization and the Contract does not specify particular members, any official\\ncommunication or statement by any member or designated spokesperson counts. When using\\nAND logic, all specified entities must independently say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e. When\\nusing OR logic, at least one of the specified entities must say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nThe Exchange may specify additional conditions such as “at least X members of” a group or\\n“the majority of” a group.\\n\\n\\u003csource\\u003e: \\u003csource\\u003e refers to a Source Agency or ordered collection of Source Agencies\\nspecified by the Exchange at the time of Contract listing, which will be incorporated into the\\nSource Agency hierarchy above and used to determine the occurrence of the Underlying.\\n\\u003csource\\u003e may refer to a singular agency, multiple agencies, an agency by distinguishing\\ncharacteristics, by category or type (e.g., “official government statistical body,” “primary wire\\nservice”), or any combination thereof. When multiple agencies are specified, they may be\\napplied in the hierarchical order designated by the Exchange if so specified, with the highest-\\nranked available and responsive agency taking precedence for purposes of determining the\\nExpiration Value. A lower-ranked agency shall only be consulted if all higher-ranked agencies\\nare unavailable, unresponsive, have not reported on the Underlying by the Expiration time, or\\nif the Exchange, in its sole discretion, determines that a higher-ranked agency’s reporting is\\nincomplete, erroneous, or otherwise insufficient to determine the Expiration Value. If \\u003csource\\u003e\\ndesignates multiple agencies without specifying a hierarchical order, the Exchange shall\\nresolve any conflict between reporting agencies at its sole discretion.\\n\\n\\u003cword\\u003e: \\u003cword\\u003e refers to the particular word or phrase potentially to be mentioned by\\n\\u003centity\\u003e. It may refer to a word being said a minimum number of times. It may also refer to\\none of multiple words/phrases, any of which are acceptable (e.g., “Doge/Dogecoin”).\\n\\f\\u003ctime period\\u003e: \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific range of time, event or discrete date and\\ntime specified by the Exchange. This may be defined by, but is not limited to: a specific event\\nor context (e.g., “during the State of the Union address”), exact dates or times, relative time\\nmarkers (e.g., “before July 1, 2027,” “in Q1 2026”), event-based periods (e.g., “during any\\ncampaign rally in October 2026,” “during the awards ceremony”), and broader intervals (e.g.,\\n“Q1–Q2 2027,” “January–March 2026”).\\n\\nUnless stated otherwise, “Between” is inclusive of both endpoints, while “before” and “after”\\nexclude the specified date. \\u003ctime period\\u003e may also refer to “Any” or “None”, to multiple dates\\n(even if non-consecutive), or to a singular and discrete date or time.\\n\\nWhen \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event (such as an address, speech, performance, or\\nbroadcast), the Exchange may specify what is included, including whether it includes both live\\nand pre-recorded segments (including whether advertisements are included). Where a\\ntimezone is not specified, ET is assumed.\\n\\n\\nPayout Criterion: The Payout Criterion for the Contract encompasses the Expiration Values that\\n\\u003cword\\u003e is said by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n\\n\\nThe word must appear as a distinct, standalone unit, not buried inside another word. Plural\\nand possessive noun forms count. Other grammatical changes (tense, conjugation, derivation)\\ndo not. If \\u003cword\\u003e appears separated from other words by a space or hyphen or in a\\ncompound form with a space or hyphen, it counts. If \\u003cword\\u003e is fused into a single\\nunhyphenated word, it does not count.\\n\\nIf \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled, and the market contains a\\nstrike stating “Event does not qualify/occur”, such a strike shall resolve “Yes” and all others\\n“No”. If \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled but such strikes are NOT\\nlisted, the Contracts will resolve to the last fair price determined at the discretion of the\\nExchange. If the event is postponed, and such a postponement is announced by the end of the\\nfollowing calendar day to be rescheduled to a time within 14 calendar days, the markets shall\\nremain open. If the event captured in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast, the\\nExchange may keep the market open for 24 hours for the release of an official recording.\\nFurther granular details on conditions for these Contracts is available below.\\n\\nAdditional clarification(s):\\n\\n     Possessive noun forms of \\u003cword\\u003e, plurals, and possessive plural noun forms are\\n     INCLUDED:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigrants” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Egg” → “eggs’ shells” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Russia” → “Russia’s” counts, “Russian” does not\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e exists only in adjective form, no plural form exists:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Economic” → “Economics” does not count (“Economic” is an adjective\\n          for which “Economics” is not a plural)\\n     Plural nouns occurring within proper nouns and noun phrases are included:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Cat” → “Cats the musical” counts\\n\\f    Grammatical variations beyond plurals/possessives are NOT included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigration” does NOT count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Run” → “Running” or “Ran” do NOT count\\n    When \\u003cword\\u003e specifies a plural form, the singular does NOT count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Veterans” → “Veteran” does NOT count\\n    Words that are spelled the same as the plural form of \\u003cword\\u003e (if such exists) but are\\n    themselves not a plural noun are included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Wind” → “Winds up the clock” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Border” → “The United States has strong borders” counts\\n    Open compounds (words separated by spaces) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fire station” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “couch” → “couch potato” counts\\n    Hyphenated compounds (words connected by hyphens) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Palestine” → “pro-Palestine” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fat” → “non-fat” counts\\n    Closed compounds (single word, no spaces/hyphens) do not count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire” does not count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firefighter” does not count\\n    Multi-word \\u003cword\\u003e in larger constructions: When \\u003cword\\u003e is a multi-word phrase\\n    appearing within a hyphenated construction, it counts only if \\u003cword\\u003e appears as a\\n    complete, unmodified element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “New York” → “New York-based” counts (complete element)\\n    Portmanteaus (words blended from two words where parts of each are combined) are\\n    NOT included unless the portmanteau clearly contains \\u003cword\\u003e as a distinct, unaltered\\n    element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “MAGA” → “MAGA-nificent” counts (MAGA appears as distinct element)\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “magnificent” → “MAGA-nificent” does NOT count (portmanteau blend)\\n\\nDictionary determination: Both the Merriam-Webster Dictionary (available online) AND the\\nOxford English Dictionary shall be used to determine compound type and/or conventional\\nspelling patterns. Inclusion in either dictionary as an open or hyphenated compound shall\\nsatisfy the Payout Criterion. If neither provides clarity (or the word is not included),\\ndetermination is based on whether written as single unit (closed/doesn’t count) vs. spaces or\\nhyphens (open or hyphenated/counts) and/or context and previous usage.\\n\\nPHONETIC EQUIVALENCIES\\n\\n    Homophones (same sound, different spelling) do not count:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “write” → “right” does not count\\n    Homonyms and homographs (same spelling) COUNT regardless of meaning or\\n    pronunciation:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “bass” → both “bass guitar” and “bass fishing” count\\n    Proper and common nouns are treated identically:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Apple” → both “Apple Inc.” and “apple” (fruit) count\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Will” → both “Will Smith” and “I will go” count\\n    Minor unintentional mispronunciations COUNT if context makes intent clear:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Mamdani” → “Mandani” counts\\n    Severe mispronunciations that make \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable do NOT count.\\n    Trademarked spellings do not count, even when pronounced identically, unless the word\\n\\fitself is the same:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “lift” → “Lyft” (pronounced “lift”) does not count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “uber” → “Uber” counts\\nWords with non-standard transliteration to English count within reason, provided they are\\nphonetically equivalent:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Zelensky” → any of “Zelenski,” “Zelenskii,” “Zelensky,” or “Zelenskiy”\\n      count if pronounced equivalently\\nContractions do not count for their constituent words unless otherwise explicitly specified\\nby the Exchange:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “not” → “won’t,” “can’t,” “don’t,” “isn’t” do not count\\nNumbers spoken as words COUNT, when spoken exactly (not part of a larger number):\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “five” → saying “five” or reading “$5” aloud as “five dollars” counts,\\n      saying “five hundred” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “410” → “four hundred ten”, “four one zero” or “four ten” counts\\nOrdinals COUNT when \\u003cword\\u003e is written numerically OR a phrase that includes a\\nnumber:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “January 6” → “January 6th” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “3” (written numerically) → “3rd” (spoken as “third”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Eight War” → “8 Wars” and “Eighth War” will count\\nCardinal and ordinal number words are distinct:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “one” → “first” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “first” → “one” does NOT count\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count when pronunciation or letter-by-letter spelling\\nmatches \\u003cword\\u003e:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “NASA” (pronounced “NAH-suh”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “N-A-S-A” (spelled out) counts\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count as \\u003cword\\u003e when pronounced as the full word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Doctor” → “Dr.” (pronounced “Doctor”) counts\\nExpanded forms of acronyms do NOT count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “AI” → “artificial intelligence” does not count\\nWords in foreign languages do NOT count unless they are perfect cognates with an\\nEnglish word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fuego” (Spanish) does NOT count\\nEnglish words within foreign sentences count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “policy” → “Nuestra policy es clara” counts\\n\\u003cword\\u003e in organization/company names counts:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Securities” → “Bank of America Securities” counts\\nWords in URLs, emails, handles, and hashtags (exclusive of domain structure, email\\nprovider or symbols) are treated as compounds when spoken as complete words, with the\\ntype of compound subject to aforementioned rules:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firestation.com” pronounced “fire station dot com” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire.com” pronounced “wildfire dot com” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “apple” → “apple.com” pronounced “apple dot com” does count\\n      When presented in URL, email, handle, or hashtag form, \\u003cword\\u003e shall be treated as\\n      a compound, not a multi-word word\\nSung, rapped, or poetic words COUNT if phonetically recognizable:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “money” → “moneyyy” (extended in rap) counts\\n      Extreme distortion making \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable does NOT count.\\nPhonetic alphabet spelling (“Foxtrot India Romeo Echo” for “FIRE”) does NOT count.\\n\\fCANCELLATIONS AND DELAYS\\n\\n   The Exchange may list an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike for any Contract. If listed,\\n   such a strike refers to the structural conditions of the market, and is NOT adjudicated as a\\n   \\u003cword\\u003e needing to be said by or validated by having been said by \\u003centity\\u003e. If listed, this\\n   strike resolves to “Yes” whenever the event fails to occur or qualify under the Payout\\n   Criterion, or any other circumstance prevents normal resolution.\\n   If no such strike is listed, and \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, the following rules\\n   apply if the event is cancelled, postponed, rescheduled, or materially altered (including\\n   being closed to press) such that no video is released within one calendar day of the\\n   original start time of the event:\\n         If the event is cancelled, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price determined in\\n         the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         If the event is postponed or rescheduled, the outcome depends on whether a new\\n         date is publicly announced within one calendar day (i.e. if the event was scheduled\\n         to begin on Monday, any time up to 11:59PM on Tuesday falls within this period) of\\n         the originally scheduled start time:\\n               If no new date is announced within one calendar day, the Contract will resolve\\n               to the last fair price determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n               If a new date is announced within one calendar day, the outcome depends on\\n               when the rescheduled event is set to occur:\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls within fourteen (14) calendar days of the\\n                     originally scheduled date, the Contract shall remain open and \\u003cword\\u003e\\n                     stated during the rescheduled event will count.\\n                           The fourteen-day window begins at 12:00 AM ET on the originally\\n                           scheduled date and ends at 11:59 PM ET fourteen days later, unless\\n                           an alternate timezone is explicitly specified.\\n                           Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the State of the Union on January\\n                           15, 2026” rescheduled to January 20, 2026 → words spoken during\\n                           the rescheduled address count.\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls more than fourteen (14) calendar days after\\n                     the originally scheduled date, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price\\n                     determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         Any Contract that cannot be resolved through the Source Agency hierarchy will\\n         instead be settled at the Last Fair Price. The Exchange will disclose the methodology\\n         used to determine the Last Fair Price (e.g., Last Traded Price, Time-Weighted\\n         Average Price) at the time of Issuance.\\n         If an event begins but is interrupted, abbreviated, or ends prematurely, words\\n         stated by \\u003centity\\u003e during the portion of the event that did occur will count and the\\n         market will otherwise resolve.\\n   If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window but the venue, format, or medium\\n   changes (e.g., moved to a different location, changed from in-person to virtual (with the\\n   exception of being closed to press)), words stated during the event will count.\\n   Special condition: Across both cases, whether an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike is\\n   listed or not, if the event specified as or in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast (or\\n   relayed as such) but the live stream/broadcast does not occur, the Exchange will instead\\n   use an officially released recording as the Underlying, and may delay resolution by up to\\n   one calendar day to allow for the release of such a recording.\\n\\f          If partial snippets are released, Contracts on words that do not appear will be\\n          resolved to last fair price, and Contracts on those that do will be resolved to “Yes”.\\n          If no recording is released, the relevant outcomes triggered by the\\n          presence/absence of an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike shall occur as outlined\\n          above.\\n\\nTECHNICAL DETAILS (UNLESS OTHERWISE SPECIFIED)\\n\\n     When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, pre-recorded content broadcast,\\n     streamed, or published as part of that event is included if presented as part of the official\\n     presentation.\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the concert” with pre-recorded video interlude\\n          where entity speaks → words from interlude count\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the television appearance” with pre-taped\\n          segment aired during broadcast → words from segment count\\n     Behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are NOT\\n     included unless officially broadcast or published as part of \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n     Subtitles and captions that display \\u003cword\\u003e on screen but are not spoken aloud by\\n     \\u003centity\\u003e do NOT count.\\n     Sign language interpretation or usage by entity does NOT count as saying \\u003cword\\u003e unless\\n     the Contract explicitly specifies that sign language counts.\\n     Text that entity displays on screen (presentation slides, teleprompter visible to audience,\\n     signatures) does NOT count unless entity reads it aloud.\\n     Content generated by AI, deepfakes, or synthetic voice technology impersonating entity\\n     does NOT count unless the synthetic content is officially commissioned, authorized, or\\n     published by entity, OR the Contract explicitly specifies that AI-generated content counts.\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e is muted due to technical failure or censorship it shall not count unless\\n     corroborating contextual evidence (including surrounding speech, or an official\\n     uncensored recording or transcript) confirms that \\u003centity\\u003e specifically uttered \\u003cword\\u003e\\n     during the muted period.\\n\\nMinimum Tick: The Minimum Tick size for the Contract shall be $0.01.\\n\\nPosition Accountability Level: The Position Accountability Level for the Contract shall be\\n$25,000 per strike, per Member.\\n\\nLast Trading Date: The Last Trading Date of the Contract will be the Expiration Date. The Last\\nTrading Time will be the Expiration time.\\n\\nSettlement Date: The Settlement Date of the Contract shall be no later than the day after the\\nExpiration Date, unless the Market Outcome is under review pursuant to Rule 7.1.\\n\\nExpiration Date: When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event: The latest Expiration Date of\\nthe Contract shall be fourteen (14) calendar days after the originally scheduled date of the\\nevent. If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window, expiration will be moved to an\\nearlier date and time in accordance with Rule 7.2. When \\u003ctime period\\u003e is defined by specific\\ndates: The latest Expiration Date of the Contract shall be two weeks after the end of \\u003ctime\\nperiod\\u003e. If an event described in the Payout Criterion occurs and a consensus has been\\nreached on all terms, then expiration will be moved to an earlier date and time in accordance\\nwith Rule 7.2.\\n\\fExpiration time: The Expiration time of the Contract shall be 10:00 AM ET.\\n\\nSettlement Value: The Settlement Value for this Contract is $1.00.\\n\\nExpiration Value: The Expiration Value is the value of the Underlying as documented by the\\nSource Agency on the Expiration Date at the Expiration time.\\n\\nContingencies: Before Settlement, Kalshi may, at its sole discretion, initiate the Market\\nOutcome Review Process pursuant to Rule 7.1 of the Rulebook. If an Expiration Value cannot\\nbe determined on the Expiration Date, Kalshi has the right to determine payouts pursuant to\\nRule 7.1 in the Rulebook.\\n\\f\\n\\n[defendant] DX-4 Market packet: Ronaldo strike and challenged No resolution\\nMarket URL: https://kalshi.com/markets/kxtrumpmentionb/trump-mention-b/kxtrumpmentionb-25dec06\\n\\nPublic market title: What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\n\\nContract family: PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION\\n\\nStrike at issue: Ronaldo\\n\\nChallenged resolution: No\\n\\nRequested resolution: Yes\\n\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R1 GovInfo transcript confirming Ronaldo utterances and Kennedy Center/FIFA Draw context\\nSource: GovInfo, Compilation of Presidential Documents, DCPD202501162\\nURL retrieved: https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/DCPD-202501162/html/DCPD-202501162.htm\\nRetrieval time: 2026-06-29T22:00:00Z\\nLocal captured HTML size/hash: 51,571 bytes; SHA-256 eadbceeecf3e94f5bd423bcb8e8511165fdc7265dd8c1e025870c2e8f34dfd99\\n\\nMaterial captured text from official GovInfo HTML/web.open:\\n\\nAdministration of Donald J. Trump, 2025\\n\\nTitle: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\nDate: December 5, 2025\\n\\nOpening note: [The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\\n\\nExcerpt - The President's Interest in Soccer (web.open lines 196-203):\\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\\\"football,\\\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\\n\\nExcerpt - The President's Interest in Soccer (web.open lines 322-329):\\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\\nThe President. But they have a little more speed. But no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\\n\\nTiming/context note (web.open lines 461-462):\\nNOTE: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. In his remarks, he referred to Trey Yingst, chief foreign correspondent, Fox News Channel; Cristiano Ronaldo, forward for Saudi Pro League club Al-Nass and Portugal's national soccer team; and Lionel Messi, forward for Major League Soccer club Inter Miami and Argentina's national team. A reporter referred to New York State Attorney General Letitia James.\\nThe transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\n\\nDocument category/location/name/subject metadata (web.open lines 463-468):\\nCategories: Interviews With the News Media: Exchanges with reporters, Washington, DC.\\nLocations: Washington, DC.\\nNames include: Cristiano Ronaldo and Lionel Messi.\\nSubjects include: Federation Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) World Cup; John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts; News media, Presidential interviews; Soccer.\\nDCPD Number: DCPD202501162.\\n\\nCapture limits: This item is a focused text capture of the material official transcript title, Ronaldo excerpts, timing/correction note, and metadata. It is not a full video or audio artifact. The official transcript itself notes some portions could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R2 FIFA timing capture showing formal commencement time but not market-specific exclusion\\nSource: FIFA official page, FIFA World Cup 2026 Final Draw\\nURL: https://www.fifa.com/en/tournaments/mens/worldcup/canadamexicousa2026/live-draw\\nRetrieval time: 2026-06-29T22:01:00Z\\n\\nMaterial captured text from web search/open result:\\n- Page title/source: FIFA World Cup 2026™ Final Draw\\n- The draw takes place at the Kennedy Center in Washington DC, USA.\\n- The draw commences at 12:00 local time (17:00 UTC) on Friday 5 December 2025.\\n\\nCapture limits: This is a focused text capture of the official FIFA page timing statement located by web search. It is not a video capture of the draw ceremony.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R3 Event-period terms and exclusions\\n                                         NEWMENTION\\n\\nScope: These rules shall apply to this contract.\\n\\nUnderlying: The Underlying for this Contract is words used by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nRevisions to the Underlying made after Expiration will not be accounted for in determining the\\nExpiration Value.\\n\\nSource Agency: The Source Agencies are \\u003csource\\u003e.\\n\\nType: The type of Contract is an Event Contract.\\n\\nIssuance: After the initial Contract, Contract iterations will be listed on an as-needed basis at\\nthe discretion of the Exchange and corresponding to the risk management needs of Members.\\n\\n\\u003centity\\u003e: \\u003centity\\u003e refers to the speaker, writer, performer, or communicator specified by the\\nExchange. This may include (but is not limited to): a specific named individual, multiple\\nindividuals specified using AND/OR logic, an individual identified by position or title, a group,\\nband, team or collective entity, a specified member or members of a group, an organization,\\ncompany, or institutional entity, or any combination of the aforementioned.\\n\\nWhen \\u003centity\\u003e is defined by a position or title, the Contract tracks whoever holds that position\\nduring \\u003ctime period\\u003e, even if the individual holding the position changes. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a\\nspecific named individual, the identity remains consistent throughout. Name changes (e.g.,\\nstage names, married names) do not create a new entity. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a group or\\norganization and the Contract does not specify particular members, any official\\ncommunication or statement by any member or designated spokesperson counts. When using\\nAND logic, all specified entities must independently say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e. When\\nusing OR logic, at least one of the specified entities must say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nThe Exchange may specify additional conditions such as “at least X members of” a group or\\n“the majority of” a group.\\n\\n\\u003csource\\u003e: \\u003csource\\u003e refers to a Source Agency or ordered collection of Source Agencies\\nspecified by the Exchange at the time of Contract listing, which will be incorporated into the\\nSource Agency hierarchy above and used to determine the occurrence of the Underlying.\\n\\u003csource\\u003e may refer to a singular agency, multiple agencies, an agency by distinguishing\\ncharacteristics, by category or type (e.g., “official government statistical body,” “primary wire\\nservice”), or any combination thereof. When multiple agencies are specified, they may be\\napplied in the hierarchical order designated by the Exchange if so specified, with the highest-\\nranked available and responsive agency taking precedence for purposes of determining the\\nExpiration Value. A lower-ranked agency shall only be consulted if all higher-ranked agencies\\nare unavailable, unresponsive, have not reported on the Underlying by the Expiration time, or\\nif the Exchange, in its sole discretion, determines that a higher-ranked agency’s reporting is\\nincomplete, erroneous, or otherwise insufficient to determine the Expiration Value. If \\u003csource\\u003e\\ndesignates multiple agencies without specifying a hierarchical order, the Exchange shall\\nresolve any conflict between reporting agencies at its sole discretion.\\n\\n\\u003cword\\u003e: \\u003cword\\u003e refers to the particular word or phrase potentially to be mentioned by\\n\\u003centity\\u003e. It may refer to a word being said a minimum number of times. It may also refer to\\none of multiple words/phrases, any of which are acceptable (e.g., “Doge/Dogecoin”).\\n\\f\\u003ctime period\\u003e: \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific range of time, event or discrete date and\\ntime specified by the Exchange. This may be defined by, but is not limited to: a specific event\\nor context (e.g., “during the State of the Union address”), exact dates or times, relative time\\nmarkers (e.g., “before July 1, 2027,” “in Q1 2026”), event-based periods (e.g., “during any\\ncampaign rally in October 2026,” “during the awards ceremony”), and broader intervals (e.g.,\\n“Q1–Q2 2027,” “January–March 2026”).\\n\\nUnless stated otherwise, “Between” is inclusive of both endpoints, while “before” and “after”\\nexclude the specified date. \\u003ctime period\\u003e may also refer to “Any” or “None”, to multiple dates\\n(even if non-consecutive), or to a singular and discrete date or time.\\n\\nWhen \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event (such as an address, speech, performance, or\\nbroadcast), the Exchange may specify what is included, including whether it includes both live\\nand pre-recorded segments (including whether advertisements are included). Where a\\ntimezone is not specified, ET is assumed.\\n\\n\\nPayout Criterion: The Payout Criterion for the Contract encompasses the Expiration Values that\\n\\u003cword\\u003e is said by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n\\n\\nThe word must appear as a distinct, standalone unit, not buried inside another word. Plural\\nand possessive noun forms count. Other grammatical changes (tense, conjugation, derivation)\\ndo not. If \\u003cword\\u003e appears separated from other words by a space or hyphen or in a\\ncompound form with a space or hyphen, it counts. If \\u003cword\\u003e is fused into a single\\nunhyphenated word, it does not count.\\n\\nIf \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled, and the market contains a\\nstrike stating “Event does not qualify/occur”, such a strike shall resolve “Yes” and all others\\n“No”. If \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled but such strikes are NOT\\nlisted, the Contracts will resolve to the last fair price determined at the discretion of the\\nExchange. If the event is postponed, and such a postponement is announced by the end of the\\nfollowing calendar day to be rescheduled to a time within 14 calendar days, the markets shall\\nremain open. If the event captured in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast, the\\nExchange may keep the market open for 24 hours for the release of an official recording.\\nFurther granular details on conditions for these Contracts is available below.\\n\\nAdditional clarification(s):\\n\\n     Possessive noun forms of \\u003cword\\u003e, plurals, and possessive plural noun forms are\\n     INCLUDED:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigrants” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Egg” → “eggs’ shells” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Russia” → “Russia’s” counts, “Russian” does not\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e exists only in adjective form, no plural form exists:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Economic” → “Economics” does not count (“Economic” is an adjective\\n          for which “Economics” is not a plural)\\n     Plural nouns occurring within proper nouns and noun phrases are included:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Cat” → “Cats the musical” counts\\n\\f    Grammatical variations beyond plurals/possessives are NOT included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigration” does NOT count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Run” → “Running” or “Ran” do NOT count\\n    When \\u003cword\\u003e specifies a plural form, the singular does NOT count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Veterans” → “Veteran” does NOT count\\n    Words that are spelled the same as the plural form of \\u003cword\\u003e (if such exists) but are\\n    themselves not a plural noun are included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Wind” → “Winds up the clock” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Border” → “The United States has strong borders” counts\\n    Open compounds (words separated by spaces) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fire station” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “couch” → “couch potato” counts\\n    Hyphenated compounds (words connected by hyphens) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Palestine” → “pro-Palestine” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fat” → “non-fat” counts\\n    Closed compounds (single word, no spaces/hyphens) do not count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire” does not count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firefighter” does not count\\n    Multi-word \\u003cword\\u003e in larger constructions: When \\u003cword\\u003e is a multi-word phrase\\n    appearing within a hyphenated construction, it counts only if \\u003cword\\u003e appears as a\\n    complete, unmodified element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “New York” → “New York-based” counts (complete element)\\n    Portmanteaus (words blended from two words where parts of each are combined) are\\n    NOT included unless the portmanteau clearly contains \\u003cword\\u003e as a distinct, unaltered\\n    element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “MAGA” → “MAGA-nificent” counts (MAGA appears as distinct element)\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “magnificent” → “MAGA-nificent” does NOT count (portmanteau blend)\\n\\nDictionary determination: Both the Merriam-Webster Dictionary (available online) AND the\\nOxford English Dictionary shall be used to determine compound type and/or conventional\\nspelling patterns. Inclusion in either dictionary as an open or hyphenated compound shall\\nsatisfy the Payout Criterion. If neither provides clarity (or the word is not included),\\ndetermination is based on whether written as single unit (closed/doesn’t count) vs. spaces or\\nhyphens (open or hyphenated/counts) and/or context and previous usage.\\n\\nPHONETIC EQUIVALENCIES\\n\\n    Homophones (same sound, different spelling) do not count:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “write” → “right” does not count\\n    Homonyms and homographs (same spelling) COUNT regardless of meaning or\\n    pronunciation:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “bass” → both “bass guitar” and “bass fishing” count\\n    Proper and common nouns are treated identically:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Apple” → both “Apple Inc.” and “apple” (fruit) count\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Will” → both “Will Smith” and “I will go” count\\n    Minor unintentional mispronunciations COUNT if context makes intent clear:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Mamdani” → “Mandani” counts\\n    Severe mispronunciations that make \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable do NOT count.\\n    Trademarked spellings do not count, even when pronounced identically, unless the word\\n\\fitself is the same:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “lift” → “Lyft” (pronounced “lift”) does not count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “uber” → “Uber” counts\\nWords with non-standard transliteration to English count within reason, provided they are\\nphonetically equivalent:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Zelensky” → any of “Zelenski,” “Zelenskii,” “Zelensky,” or “Zelenskiy”\\n      count if pronounced equivalently\\nContractions do not count for their constituent words unless otherwise explicitly specified\\nby the Exchange:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “not” → “won’t,” “can’t,” “don’t,” “isn’t” do not count\\nNumbers spoken as words COUNT, when spoken exactly (not part of a larger number):\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “five” → saying “five” or reading “$5” aloud as “five dollars” counts,\\n      saying “five hundred” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “410” → “four hundred ten”, “four one zero” or “four ten” counts\\nOrdinals COUNT when \\u003cword\\u003e is written numerically OR a phrase that includes a\\nnumber:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “January 6” → “January 6th” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “3” (written numerically) → “3rd” (spoken as “third”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Eight War” → “8 Wars” and “Eighth War” will count\\nCardinal and ordinal number words are distinct:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “one” → “first” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “first” → “one” does NOT count\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count when pronunciation or letter-by-letter spelling\\nmatches \\u003cword\\u003e:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “NASA” (pronounced “NAH-suh”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “N-A-S-A” (spelled out) counts\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count as \\u003cword\\u003e when pronounced as the full word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Doctor” → “Dr.” (pronounced “Doctor”) counts\\nExpanded forms of acronyms do NOT count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “AI” → “artificial intelligence” does not count\\nWords in foreign languages do NOT count unless they are perfect cognates with an\\nEnglish word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fuego” (Spanish) does NOT count\\nEnglish words within foreign sentences count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “policy” → “Nuestra policy es clara” counts\\n\\u003cword\\u003e in organization/company names counts:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Securities” → “Bank of America Securities” counts\\nWords in URLs, emails, handles, and hashtags (exclusive of domain structure, email\\nprovider or symbols) are treated as compounds when spoken as complete words, with the\\ntype of compound subject to aforementioned rules:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firestation.com” pronounced “fire station dot com” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire.com” pronounced “wildfire dot com” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “apple” → “apple.com” pronounced “apple dot com” does count\\n      When presented in URL, email, handle, or hashtag form, \\u003cword\\u003e shall be treated as\\n      a compound, not a multi-word word\\nSung, rapped, or poetic words COUNT if phonetically recognizable:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “money” → “moneyyy” (extended in rap) counts\\n      Extreme distortion making \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable does NOT count.\\nPhonetic alphabet spelling (“Foxtrot India Romeo Echo” for “FIRE”) does NOT count.\\n\\fCANCELLATIONS AND DELAYS\\n\\n   The Exchange may list an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike for any Contract. If listed,\\n   such a strike refers to the structural conditions of the market, and is NOT adjudicated as a\\n   \\u003cword\\u003e needing to be said by or validated by having been said by \\u003centity\\u003e. If listed, this\\n   strike resolves to “Yes” whenever the event fails to occur or qualify under the Payout\\n   Criterion, or any other circumstance prevents normal resolution.\\n   If no such strike is listed, and \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, the following rules\\n   apply if the event is cancelled, postponed, rescheduled, or materially altered (including\\n   being closed to press) such that no video is released within one calendar day of the\\n   original start time of the event:\\n         If the event is cancelled, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price determined in\\n         the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         If the event is postponed or rescheduled, the outcome depends on whether a new\\n         date is publicly announced within one calendar day (i.e. if the event was scheduled\\n         to begin on Monday, any time up to 11:59PM on Tuesday falls within this period) of\\n         the originally scheduled start time:\\n               If no new date is announced within one calendar day, the Contract will resolve\\n               to the last fair price determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n               If a new date is announced within one calendar day, the outcome depends on\\n               when the rescheduled event is set to occur:\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls within fourteen (14) calendar days of the\\n                     originally scheduled date, the Contract shall remain open and \\u003cword\\u003e\\n                     stated during the rescheduled event will count.\\n                           The fourteen-day window begins at 12:00 AM ET on the originally\\n                           scheduled date and ends at 11:59 PM ET fourteen days later, unless\\n                           an alternate timezone is explicitly specified.\\n                           Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the State of the Union on January\\n                           15, 2026” rescheduled to January 20, 2026 → words spoken during\\n                           the rescheduled address count.\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls more than fourteen (14) calendar days after\\n                     the originally scheduled date, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price\\n                     determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         Any Contract that cannot be resolved through the Source Agency hierarchy will\\n         instead be settled at the Last Fair Price. The Exchange will disclose the methodology\\n         used to determine the Last Fair Price (e.g., Last Traded Price, Time-Weighted\\n         Average Price) at the time of Issuance.\\n         If an event begins but is interrupted, abbreviated, or ends prematurely, words\\n         stated by \\u003centity\\u003e during the portion of the event that did occur will count and the\\n         market will otherwise resolve.\\n   If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window but the venue, format, or medium\\n   changes (e.g., moved to a different location, changed from in-person to virtual (with the\\n   exception of being closed to press)), words stated during the event will count.\\n   Special condition: Across both cases, whether an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike is\\n   listed or not, if the event specified as or in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast (or\\n   relayed as such) but the live stream/broadcast does not occur, the Exchange will instead\\n   use an officially released recording as the Underlying, and may delay resolution by up to\\n   one calendar day to allow for the release of such a recording.\\n\\f          If partial snippets are released, Contracts on words that do not appear will be\\n          resolved to last fair price, and Contracts on those that do will be resolved to “Yes”.\\n          If no recording is released, the relevant outcomes triggered by the\\n          presence/absence of an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike shall occur as outlined\\n          above.\\n\\nTECHNICAL DETAILS (UNLESS OTHERWISE SPECIFIED)\\n\\n     When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, pre-recorded content broadcast,\\n     streamed, or published as part of that event is included if presented as part of the official\\n     presentation.\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the concert” with pre-recorded video interlude\\n          where entity speaks → words from interlude count\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the television appearance” with pre-taped\\n          segment aired during broadcast → words from segment count\\n     Behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are NOT\\n     included unless officially broadcast or published as part of \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n     Subtitles and captions that display \\u003cword\\u003e on screen but are not spoken aloud by\\n     \\u003centity\\u003e do NOT count.\\n     Sign language interpretation or usage by entity does NOT count as saying \\u003cword\\u003e unless\\n     the Contract explicitly specifies that sign language counts.\\n     Text that entity displays on screen (presentation slides, teleprompter visible to audience,\\n     signatures) does NOT count unless entity reads it aloud.\\n     Content generated by AI, deepfakes, or synthetic voice technology impersonating entity\\n     does NOT count unless the synthetic content is officially commissioned, authorized, or\\n     published by entity, OR the Contract explicitly specifies that AI-generated content counts.\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e is muted due to technical failure or censorship it shall not count unless\\n     corroborating contextual evidence (including surrounding speech, or an official\\n     uncensored recording or transcript) confirms that \\u003centity\\u003e specifically uttered \\u003cword\\u003e\\n     during the muted period.\\n\\nMinimum Tick: The Minimum Tick size for the Contract shall be $0.01.\\n\\nPosition Accountability Level: The Position Accountability Level for the Contract shall be\\n$25,000 per strike, per Member.\\n\\nLast Trading Date: The Last Trading Date of the Contract will be the Expiration Date. The Last\\nTrading Time will be the Expiration time.\\n\\nSettlement Date: The Settlement Date of the Contract shall be no later than the day after the\\nExpiration Date, unless the Market Outcome is under review pursuant to Rule 7.1.\\n\\nExpiration Date: When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event: The latest Expiration Date of\\nthe Contract shall be fourteen (14) calendar days after the originally scheduled date of the\\nevent. If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window, expiration will be moved to an\\nearlier date and time in accordance with Rule 7.2. When \\u003ctime period\\u003e is defined by specific\\ndates: The latest Expiration Date of the Contract shall be two weeks after the end of \\u003ctime\\nperiod\\u003e. If an event described in the Payout Criterion occurs and a consensus has been\\nreached on all terms, then expiration will be moved to an earlier date and time in accordance\\nwith Rule 7.2.\\n\\fExpiration time: The Expiration time of the Contract shall be 10:00 AM ET.\\n\\nSettlement Value: The Settlement Value for this Contract is $1.00.\\n\\nExpiration Value: The Expiration Value is the value of the Underlying as documented by the\\nSource Agency on the Expiration Date at the Expiration time.\\n\\nContingencies: Before Settlement, Kalshi may, at its sole discretion, initiate the Market\\nOutcome Review Process pursuant to Rule 7.1 of the Rulebook. If an Expiration Value cannot\\nbe determined on the Expiration Date, Kalshi has the right to determine payouts pursuant to\\nRule 7.1 in the Rulebook.\\n\\f\\n\\n[defendant] DX-S1 GovInfo official transcript: prior reporter exchange\\nSource: GovInfo, Compilation of Presidential Documents, DCPD202501162\\nURL retrieved: https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/DCPD-202501162/html/DCPD-202501162.htm\\nRetrieval time: 2026-06-29T22:00:00Z\\nLocal captured HTML size/hash: 51,571 bytes; SHA-256 eadbceeecf3e94f5bd423bcb8e8511165fdc7265dd8c1e025870c2e8f34dfd99\\n\\nMaterial captured text from official GovInfo HTML/web.open:\\n\\nAdministration of Donald J. Trump, 2025\\n\\nTitle: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\nDate: December 5, 2025\\n\\nOpening note: [The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\\n\\nExcerpt - The President's Interest in Soccer (web.open lines 196-203):\\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\\\"football,\\\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\\n\\nExcerpt - The President's Interest in Soccer (web.open lines 322-329):\\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\\nThe President. But they have a little more speed. But no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\\n\\nTiming/context note (web.open lines 461-462):\\nNOTE: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. In his remarks, he referred to Trey Yingst, chief foreign correspondent, Fox News Channel; Cristiano Ronaldo, forward for Saudi Pro League club Al-Nass and Portugal's national soccer team; and Lionel Messi, forward for Major League Soccer club Inter Miami and Argentina's national team. A reporter referred to New York State Attorney General Letitia James.\\nThe transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\n\\nDocument category/location/name/subject metadata (web.open lines 463-468):\\nCategories: Interviews With the News Media: Exchanges with reporters, Washington, DC.\\nLocations: Washington, DC.\\nNames include: Cristiano Ronaldo and Lionel Messi.\\nSubjects include: Federation Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) World Cup; John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts; News media, Presidential interviews; Soccer.\\nDCPD Number: DCPD202501162.\\n\\nCapture limits: This item is a focused text capture of the material official transcript title, Ronaldo excerpts, timing/correction note, and metadata. It is not a full video or audio artifact. The official transcript itself notes some portions could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-S2 FIFA official draw commencement time\\nSource: FIFA official page, FIFA World Cup 2026 Final Draw\\nURL: https://www.fifa.com/en/tournaments/mens/worldcup/canadamexicousa2026/live-draw\\nRetrieval time: 2026-06-29T22:01:00Z\\n\\nMaterial captured text from web search/open result:\\n- Page title/source: FIFA World Cup 2026™ Final Draw\\n- The draw takes place at the Kennedy Center in Washington DC, USA.\\n- The draw commences at 12:00 local time (17:00 UTC) on Friday 5 December 2025.\\n\\nCapture limits: This is a focused text capture of the official FIFA page timing statement located by web search. It is not a video capture of the draw ceremony.\\n\\nSubmitted evidence:\\n[plaintiff arguments] Official White House video page capture: President Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing (ev_db357d4e9407_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-db357d4e9407)\\nSource: https://www.whitehouse.gov/videos/president-trump-attends-the-fifa-world-cup-drawing/\\nSHA-256: `db357d4e940728d417ae4f7f3caac6b78d3fd3e4aba70d46fe10c6132d45997a`\\nBytes: 1300\\nRelevance: Establishes that the White House officially published a video page titled President Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing, dated December 5, 2025, with a full-video link and related World Cup Draw videos; relevant to source chain and event context.\\n\\n[plaintiff arguments] YouTube metadata capture: Trump Talks Cristiano Ronaldo at FIFA Draw (ev_4e1045905547_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-4e1045905547)\\nSource: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Cb2yO0lLEnM\\nSHA-256: `4e10459055477440085fe5e20d970eb2488e61d13a5e2b3133a3656bed7526d7`\\nBytes: 1779\\nRelevance: Provides a public clip source and page metadata asserting that at the FIFA World Cup Draw Ceremony Trump shared a story about meeting Cristiano Ronaldo and said Ronaldo was a great person; relevant to the alleged Ronaldo utterance, though weaker than an official full transcript or video.\\n\\n[defendant arguments] GovInfo official transcript capture: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the FIFA World Cup Draw (ev_a1b1f6b1b7bd_submitted-evidence-03-defendant-a1b1f6b1b7bd)\\nSource: https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/DCPD-202501162/html/DCPD-202501162.htm\\nSHA-256: `a1b1f6b1b7bd0b691c7fe8d97467dd0d085e2b22387ae4198270764de66e56e2`\\nBytes: 3070\\nRelevance: Official transcript identifies the relevant Trump remarks as an exchange with reporters prior to the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw; it includes the Ronaldo utterances and timing/correction notes, directly bearing on whether the utterances were during the countable event period.\\n\\n[defendant arguments] FIFA official page capture: 2026 World Cup Final Draw start time (ev_3973dc8f98c0_submitted-evidence-04-defendant-3973dc8f98c0)\\nSource: https://www.fifa.com/en/tournaments/mens/worldcup/canadamexicousa2026/live-draw\\nSHA-256: `3973dc8f98c01702174f61f5548eb1e80efe64dd72b44f21ed0fa7d944f93248`\\nBytes: 598\\nRelevance: Establishes the official Final Draw start time as 12:00 local time on December 5, 2025, which helps compare the draw event period against the GovInfo transcript note that the reporter exchange occurred at 11:13 a.m.\\n\\nTechnical reports:\\n[plaintiff] Plaintiff source-search and capture ledger\\nSearched exact market/strike phrases, White House domain, public video pages, YouTube video IDs, and Kalshi live market URL. Submitted official White House page capture and YouTube metadata capture. Kalshi live page returned a Vercel security checkpoint/429; local browser was unavailable; Python pip/ensurepip unavailable for yt-dlp; direct YouTube caption/open paths were throttled or unavailable. Remaining best evidence would be a full official video/transcript or Kalshi resolution rationale if later accessible.\\n\\n[defendant] Defendant source-search and capture ledger\\nInspected current AAR evidence and exact contents of plaintiff's White House and YouTube captures. Retrieved GovInfo official HTML transcript with curl from DCPD-202501162; local full HTML was 51,571 bytes with SHA-256 eadbceeecf3e94f5bd423bcb8e8511165fdc7265dd8c1e025870c2e8f34dfd99, then submitted a focused material text capture as DX-1. Searched official draw timing and submitted the FIFA official page timing statement as DX-2. Remaining gaps: full Kalshi market source hierarchy/resolution rationale and full WH/FIFA video were not captured, but official GovInfo timing/title plus FIFA start time resolve the material timing issue.\\n\\nCall submit_council_vote with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated.\\nKeep the rationale brief: no more than three sentences.\\n\\nCouncil API instructions:\\nYou are a council member. Decide the proposition from the admitted record.\\nYou may examine admitted evidence through read-only tools when exact bytes, metadata, or exhibit contents matter.\\nDo not search the web, introduce new facts, create new evidence, or upload evidence.\\nWhen ready, call submit_council_vote exactly once with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated and a concise rationale.\\n\",\"state\":\"ready\",\"status\":\"ready\",\"tools\":[{\"description\":\"Return the current visible arbitration record for this council member.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"get_case\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"List visible immutable record evidence.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"list_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Return metadata and read limits for one visible evidence item.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"stat_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Read a bounded byte range from one visible evidence item as base64.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"length\":{\"minimum\":1,\"type\":\"integer\"},\"offset\":{\"minimum\":0,\"type\":\"integer\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\",\"offset\",\"length\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"read_evidence_range\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Submit one council vote for the current deliberation opportunity.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"rationale\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"vote\":{\"enum\":[\"demonstrated\",\"not_demonstrated\"],\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"vote\",\"rationale\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"submit_council_vote\",\"read_only\":false}],\"turn\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"completed\":false,\"deadline\":\"2026-06-29T22:18:45.386037689Z\",\"deliberation_round\":1,\"member_id\":\"C2\",\"opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C2\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"remaining_ms\":889046,\"role_id\":\"council\",\"turn_number\":10},\"wait\":{\"reason\":\"ready\",\"state_version\":14,\"version\":17}}"}],"details":{"mode":"call","mcpResult":{"content":[{"type":"text","text":"ok: true\nstatus: ready\nstate: ready\nmessage: An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\nafter_version: 17\nafter_opportunity_id: deliberation:1:C2\nmember_id: C2\ncase_id: arb-ex03a-20260629214245\nwait_reason: ready\nphase: deliberation\nopportunity_id: deliberation:1:C2\nremaining_ms: 889046\nattempts_remaining: 3\njson: {\"after_opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C2\",\"after_version\":17,\"case_id\":\"arb-ex03a-20260629214245\",\"limits\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"max_evidence_read_bytes\":65536,\"max_evidence_read_bytes_per_opportunity\":524288,\"max_evidence_reads_per_opportunity\":32,\"max_response_bytes\":131072,\"remaining_evidence_read_bytes_for_opportunity\":524288,\"remaining_evidence_reads_for_opportunity\":32},\"member_id\":\"C2\",\"message\":\"An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\",\"ok\":true,\"prompt\":\"Role: council member\\nMember ID: C2\\nDeliberation round: 1\\nProposition: For the Kalshi market \\\"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\\", the strike \\\"Ronaldo\\\" should resolve Yes because Trump said \\\"Ronaldo\\\" in public remarks at the World Cup Draw venue immediately before the formal program, and the market wording plus the governing mention-market terms did not clearly exclude those event-linked remarks.\\nStandard of evidence: Preponderance of the evidence.\\nPersona:\\nYou are a careful juror and council member.\\n\\nEvaluate the record faithfully. Decide only from the evidence, the stated rules, and the applicable burden of proof. Do not favor either side, fill gaps with speculation, or ignore uncertainty.\\n\\nGive weight to reliable sources, direct evidence, consistent reasoning, and clear admissions. Discount unsupported claims, rhetorical force, irrelevant facts, and conclusions that exceed the record.\\n\\nWhen the evidence supports one answer, state it plainly. When the evidence is incomplete or balanced, say so. Be concise, honest, and exact.\\n\\nRecord:\\nOpenings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, this case is not about whether the word \\\"Ronaldo\\\" would count if President Trump clearly said it. The current packet makes that part straightforward: the market is the Kalshi PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION market titled \\\"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\\"; the strike is \\\"Ronaldo\\\"; Kalshi’s challenged resolution is No; and plaintiff seeks Yes.\\n\\nThe real dispute is temporal and contextual. Did the market phrase \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw,\\\" read with the governing mention-market terms, include public event-linked remarks at the World Cup Draw venue immediately before the formal draw program? Or did it clearly confine countable words to a narrower formal broadcast segment? Plaintiff’s position is that a No resolution cannot stand unless the record shows that the counting window clearly excluded those event-linked remarks.\\n\\nThe admitted terms matter. They define the underlying as words used by the specified entity during the specified time period. They expressly recognize event-based time periods, and they say the payout criterion is satisfied when the word is said by the entity during that period. They also contain exclusions: behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings do not count unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period; captions or text alone do not count; and the word must appear as a distinct standalone unit. Those exclusions are important, but they do not by themselves answer this case. A public remark at the event venue, tied to the Draw and immediately before the formal program, is not automatically a rehearsal, sound check, or private behind-the-scenes moment.\\n\\nAt this opening stage, the record proves the market identity, the challenged resolution, the requested resolution, and the generic governing terms. It does not yet prove the utterance itself, the exact sequence of the venue remarks, the source-agency hierarchy or any market-specific time-period language beyond the packet, or Kalshi’s reason for treating the strike as No. Those are the factual links that should decide the case under a preponderance standard.\\n\\nPlaintiff expects the decisive proof to be the full official or otherwise reliable event video or transcript, with enough surrounding context to show whether Trump said \\\"Ronaldo\\\" aloud as a standalone word; when he said it relative to the Draw event; whether the remarks were public and event-linked rather than backstage or a sound check; and whether any market-specific rule clearly excluded that segment. Plaintiff also expects the market page, archived market details, and any resolution rationale to be important because ambiguity in the market’s own event wording should not be resolved against Yes after the fact.\\n\\nThe defense will likely argue that \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw\\\" means only the formal draw ceremony or broadcast, and that anything before the formal program is outside the counting period. That theory can win only if the evidence shows a clear exclusion or a source record that separates the alleged remarks from the event itself. If the evidence instead shows public remarks at the Draw venue, officially connected to the event, immediately before the formal program, and no clear rule excluding them, then the terms favor counting the word and resolving the Ronaldo strike Yes.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the defense position is straightforward: the admitted record does not yet prove that the Ronaldo strike should resolve Yes. It proves a market title, a generic mention-market rule set, and Kalshi's challenged No resolution. It does not prove that any qualifying utterance of \\\"Ronaldo\\\" occurred during the market's countable time period.\\n\\nThe plaintiff's opening usefully narrows the dispute. This is not primarily a word-boundary case. If President Trump said \\\"Ronaldo\\\" as a standalone spoken word during the countable FIFA World Cup Draw period, the generic terms would ordinarily treat that as the kind of word that can count. The real question is whether plaintiff can carry the burden of showing that alleged pre-program, venue-adjacent remarks were part of the market's specified time period: \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\\\"\\n\\nThe case-packet terms matter, but they cut both ways. They say the underlying is words used by the entity during the specified time period. They recognize that a time period can be an event, and they allow the Exchange to specify what is included when an event is involved. They also distinguish official event presentation from material outside the event: behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are not included unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period; text or captions alone do not count; and the relevant word must be spoken aloud by the entity. Those provisions do not support a rule that every public comment inside the same building, or every press exchange near the formal program, is automatically \\\"during\\\" the Draw.\\n\\nThat is the burden problem for plaintiff. The admitted market-page file identifies the public title, contract family, strike, challenged resolution, and requested resolution. It does not supply a full market-specific source hierarchy, a formal start time, a transcript, a video, a resolution rationale, or the alleged remarks. The terms file supplies the generic framework, but not the factual bridge from \\\"immediately before the formal program\\\" to \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\\\" Without that bridge, the No resolution is not shown to be wrong by a preponderance of the evidence.\\n\\nThe defense expects the decisive proof to be source-chain evidence, not characterization. The council should want the market's full rule page if available, the source agency hierarchy, the official draw program or broadcast, any official transcript or recording of the alleged exchange, and enough surrounding timestamps to separate the formal draw from pre-event reporter access, red-carpet exchanges, arrivals, or other ancillary material. If later evidence shows that the alleged Ronaldo comment was in a segment officially presented as part of the Draw itself, plaintiff's argument becomes stronger. If the evidence instead shows a separate exchange with reporters before the draw, or an event-linked but pre-program interaction not incorporated into the official presentation, the generic terms support Kalshi's No.\\n\\nSo the defense opening is not that the word Ronaldo could never count. It is that this record has not established the necessary time-period link. The proposition asks the council to overturn No because the market wording and terms did not clearly exclude pre-program remarks. That reverses the burden. Plaintiff must show that the remarks were included in the countable period. Ambiguity about the outer edge of an event is not the same as proof that a specific pre-event utterance satisfies the payout criterion.\\n\\nArguments:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, plaintiff has now supplied the record links that were missing at opening.\\n\\nFirst, the market packet fixes what this dispute is: the Kalshi market title is \\\"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\\"; the contract family is PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION; the strike is \\\"Ronaldo\\\"; Kalshi's challenged resolution is No; and plaintiff seeks Yes. That is PX-1.\\n\\nSecond, the governing terms make this an event-period mention question, not a narrow formal-program-only question. PX-2 says the underlying is words used by the entity during the time period, recognizes that a time period may be a specific event, and sets the payout criterion as the word being said by the entity during that period. It also tells us what does not count: text/captions alone, unofficial behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, and sound checks unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. Those exclusions matter, but none says that public event-linked remarks at the venue immediately before the formal program are categorically outside \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\\\"\\n\\nThird, the source-chain evidence now points to the disputed event and the Ronaldo utterance. PX-3 is an official White House page titled \\\"President Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing,\\\" dated December 5, 2025, with a full-video link and related World Cup Draw videos. That establishes an official White House event-video source for Trump's attendance at the World Cup Drawing. PX-4 is a public YouTube watch-page metadata capture for video ID Cb2yO0lLEnM, titled \\\"Trump Talks Cristiano Ronaldo at FIFA Draw -- 'He's a Great Person'.\\\" Its description states that at the FIFA World Cup Draw Ceremony, Trump shared a story about meeting Cristiano Ronaldo at the White House, said Ronaldo was a great person, and mentioned Ronaldo spoke with his son. PX-4 is not as strong as an official transcript, and plaintiff says that plainly. But it is admitted source content that directly links Trump, Cristiano Ronaldo, and the FIFA Draw ceremony.\\n\\nOn a preponderance standard, that is enough to defeat the challenged No resolution unless the defense can supply a clearer exclusion. The market did not ask only what Trump would say during the ball-pulling segment, during the televised main show, or after a particular formal start cue. It asked what he would say \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\\\" The terms recognize event-based periods and exclude particular non-event categories. A public remark at the Draw venue, tied to the Draw, is far closer to the event period than to a rehearsal, sound check, caption, or private backstage recording.\\n\\nThe defense's burden framing is too strict. Plaintiff must prove Yes by a preponderance; plaintiff need not prove that Kalshi drafted every boundary with perfect precision. Once the admitted sources show a Ronaldo mention in connection with the FIFA Draw ceremony, the remaining question is whether the rules clearly remove that event-linked remark from the counting period. They do not. Ambiguity in a mention market's event wording should not be converted into an unstated formal-program limitation after the fact.\\n\\nProvenance and gaps: plaintiff attempted to retrieve the live Kalshi page, official/full video, caption, and transcript. Kalshi returned a Vercel security checkpoint; the local browser tool was unavailable; Python pip/ensurepip was unavailable for yt-dlp; and direct YouTube caption/open paths were throttled or unavailable. That leaves PX-4 weaker than ideal, but not weightless. PX-3 supplies official event context, PX-4 supplies the Ronaldo-at-FIFA-Draw metadata, and PX-2 supplies the rule that event-linked spoken words count absent a clear exclusion.\\n\\nThe council should resolve the proposition Yes: the Ronaldo strike should have resolved Yes because the record more likely than not shows Trump said Ronaldo in public remarks tied to the FIFA World Cup Draw, and the market wording plus governing terms did not clearly exclude those remarks.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the merits record now shows why the challenged No resolution should stand.\\n\\nPlaintiff's best point is that Trump did say the word \\\"Ronaldo.\\\" The defense does not need to fight that. The question is whether he said it during the market's countable time period: \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\\\" On that decisive question, the strongest official sources favor No.\\n\\nThe admitted GovInfo transcript, DX-1, is an official Compilation of Presidential Documents capture. Its title is not merely \\\"World Cup Draw\\\" or \\\"FIFA ceremony.\\\" It is \\\"Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw.\\\" That same transcript contains the Ronaldo passages: Trump says he met Ronaldo at the White House, later says he was \\\"not Ronaldo or Messi,\\\" and the note identifies Ronaldo among the people referenced. So DX-1 is not adverse to the defense because it confirms the word; it is decisive because it places the word in an exchange with reporters prior to the Draw.\\n\\nDX-2 supplies the timing anchor. The official FIFA Final Draw page states that the Draw at the Kennedy Center commenced at 12:00 local time on Friday, December 5, 2025. DX-1 states that the President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the Kennedy Center. A reporter exchange at 11:13, officially titled as prior to a 12:00 draw, is not more likely than not \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\\\" It is before it.\\n\\nThat reading matches the governing PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION terms. PX-2 says the payout criterion is satisfied when the word is said by the entity during the specified time period. It recognizes event-based periods and permits the Exchange to specify what is included for an event. It also treats official presentation differently from adjacent material: pre-recorded content counts if presented as part of the official event presentation, while behind-the-scenes, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings do not count unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. The point is not that this reporter exchange was a rehearsal or sound check. The point is that the terms require a link to the time period itself. Plaintiff has supplied no market-specific language saying pre-event reporter availability, arrivals, or venue interviews count as part of the Draw.\\n\\nPlaintiff's new exhibits do not fill that gap. PX-3, the White House page capture, establishes that the White House had a page titled \\\"President Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing,\\\" but plaintiff's own capture says the embedded/full video was not captured. It does not prove that the Ronaldo words occurred inside the official draw program. PX-4 is weaker still: it is metadata from a nonofficial YouTube channel. It says the clip is about Trump talking Ronaldo at the FIFA Draw, but it is not a transcript, not an official source, and not an audio extraction. When a nonofficial clip description is weighed against GovInfo's official transcript title and FIFA's official start time, the official sources control.\\n\\nNor is this a burden-shifting problem. The proposition asks the council to overturn Kalshi's No because the market supposedly did not clearly exclude remarks immediately before the formal program. But the preponderance burden is on Yes. The record must show that the strike satisfied the payout criterion. The admitted terms do not say that ambiguous pre-event remarks count by default; they say the word must be said during the specified time period. Here, the best evidence identifies the remarks as prior to the Draw and before the official commencement time.\\n\\nProvenance also matters. DX-1 is an official government transcript with a correction note and an audio-incomplete caveat. That caveat affects stray inaudible portions, but it does not weaken the title, the 11:13 timing note, or the Ronaldo passages preserved in the transcript. DX-2 is an official FIFA timing source. Plaintiff's YouTube metadata may explain why the dispute arose, but it cannot outweigh those primary sources on timing and event classification.\\n\\nThe council should resolve the proposition against plaintiff. Trump said Ronaldo, but the record more likely shows he did so in a reporter exchange prior to the FIFA World Cup Draw, not during the countable Draw event. Kalshi's No resolution should be upheld.\\n\\nRebuttals:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, defendant’s new evidence narrows the case but does not end it.\\n\\nPlaintiff accepts the important parts of DX-1 and DX-2. The GovInfo transcript is official; it labels the item an exchange with reporters \\\"Prior to\\\" the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw; it places the exchange at 11:13 a.m. at the Kennedy Center; and the FIFA capture states the draw commenced at 12:00 local time. Plaintiff should not pretend those facts are weak.\\n\\nBut defendant asks those facts to do more than they do. The market was not drafted as \\\"what will Trump say after the official 12:00 commencement,\\\" \\\"during the televised draw program,\\\" or \\\"during the ball-drawing segment.\\\" PX-1 says the public market title was \\\"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\\" That is ordinary event language, and PX-2 recognizes event-based time periods while leaving room for the Exchange to specify what is included. The record still contains no market-specific exclusion for official venue press remarks immediately before the formal program.\\n\\nDX-1 also helps plaintiff on the facts defendant originally said were missing. It confirms the relevant spoken word. Trump said he met Ronaldo, that Ronaldo is great, and that he was not Ronaldo or Messi. It also places those remarks at the Kennedy Center in a FIFA World Cup Draw-centered exchange with reporters, not in an unrelated private dinner or stale campaign setting. The transcript’s own subject metadata includes the FIFA World Cup, the Kennedy Center, news media, presidential interviews, and soccer. That is event-linked public context.\\n\\nThe terms’ exclusions do not fit defendant’s leap. PX-2 excludes captions alone, rehearsals, sound checks, behind-the-scenes content, and unofficial recordings unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. DX-1 is not a rehearsal transcript. It is not a sound check. It is not merely a caption. It is an official presidential transcript of a public reporter exchange at the venue, released in the Compilation of Presidential Documents. If Kalshi meant to exclude that category because it occurred before a formal noon commencement, the market needed to say so clearly.\\n\\nSo the dispositive question remains one of market construction: does \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw\\\" clearly exclude public, official, event-site remarks immediately before the formal program? Defendant has proved \\\"prior to\\\" the formal draw start. Defendant has not proved a clear market rule that treats the broader Draw event as beginning only at 12:00 for mention purposes.\\n\\nUnder a preponderance standard, the record now confirms the Ronaldo utterance and confirms the FIFA Draw setting. The challenged No resolution should not be upheld by importing a narrow formal-program limitation that the market title and generic terms did not state.\\n\\nSurrebuttals:\\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff's rebuttal usefully clarifies the remaining dispute: plaintiff accepts that DX-1 is official, that it labels the relevant item an exchange with reporters \\\"Prior to\\\" the FIFA World Cup Draw, that the exchange occurred at 11:13 a.m. at the Kennedy Center, and that DX-2 places the official Draw commencement at 12:00 local time. Those concessions should decide the case.\\n\\nPlaintiff's answer is that the market did not say \\\"after 12:00,\\\" \\\"during the televised program,\\\" or \\\"during the ball-drawing segment.\\\" But the market also did not say \\\"at the venue before the Draw,\\\" \\\"in pre-event reporter exchanges,\\\" or \\\"in any public remarks connected to the Draw.\\\" The phrase it chose was \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\\\" Ordinary event language has a start, and the official FIFA source fixes that start at noon. Official GovInfo then fixes this exchange at 11:13 and titles it as prior to the Draw.\\n\\nThat is not a technicality. The terms require the word to be said during the specified time period. They recognize event-based periods and allow event-specific inclusions, but no admitted market-specific rule includes pre-event press access. Plaintiff's construction would turn any event-adjacent public remark into part of the event unless expressly excluded. That reverses the payout criterion. The claimant must show the word occurred during the time period; it is not enough to show the same venue, the same general topic, and official publication.\\n\\nPlaintiff says the exclusions do not fit because DX-1 is not a rehearsal, sound check, caption, or private backstage recording. Fair enough; the defense is not relying on those categories as labels. The defense relies on the affirmative timing requirement. A remark need not be a rehearsal to be outside the event. A reporter exchange officially described as prior to a noon event and occurring at 11:13 is outside because it is before the event began.\\n\\nThe record therefore proves the wrong fact for plaintiff. It proves Trump said Ronaldo, but in a pre-event reporter exchange. The proposition requires Yes only if those words count during the FIFA World Cup Draw. On this record, they do not. Kalshi's No resolution should be upheld.\\n\\nClosings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the final record leaves one legal question.\\n\\nThe easy factual question is resolved in plaintiff’s favor: Trump said \\\"Ronaldo.\\\" The official GovInfo transcript confirms it twice in substance: he said he met Ronaldo, praised him, and later said he was not Ronaldo or Messi. That is a spoken standalone use of the strike word. The record also places the remarks at the Kennedy Center in a FIFA World Cup Draw-centered reporter exchange. This was not an unrelated dinner, a caption, an AI voice, or a social-media paraphrase.\\n\\nThe hard point is timing. Defendant has the strongest evidence on the formal program boundary: GovInfo titled the exchange as \\\"Prior to\\\" the Draw, notes 11:13 a.m., and FIFA states the Final Draw commenced at 12:00 local time. Plaintiff does not ask the council to ignore that. The question is what the Kalshi market actually required.\\n\\nPX-1 did not say \\\"after 12:00.\\\" It did not say \\\"during the televised draw program\\\" or \\\"during the ball-drawing segment.\\\" It asked, in public market wording, \\\"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\\" PX-2’s generic terms recognize event-based periods and say the Exchange may specify what is included when a time period refers to an event. They also give specific exclusions: captions alone, rehearsals, sound checks, behind-the-scenes content, and unofficial recordings unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. None of those exclusions is this case. The GovInfo transcript is an official public presidential record of an event-site reporter exchange, not a rehearsal or sound check.\\n\\nDefendant’s best argument is that ordinary events have start times. True. But this market dispute is about public remarks at the venue immediately before the formal program, in the official context of the Draw, where the market and rules did not clearly define a noon-only boundary. If Kalshi wanted that narrower rule, it could have said so in the strike, the market title, or the event inclusion language. It did not.\\n\\nThe preponderance record therefore shows: Ronaldo was spoken; the remarks were public and officially documented; they were at the Kennedy Center in the FIFA World Cup Draw setting; and the governing market language did not clearly exclude that immediately-before-program event context. The challenged No resolution depends on importing a formal commencement limitation that is absent from the market packet.\\n\\nFor that reason, the Ronaldo strike should resolve Yes.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the closing record is narrow and concrete.\\n\\nEveryone now agrees on the easy fact: Trump said \\\"Ronaldo.\\\" The official GovInfo transcript proves that. But the proposition is not simply that Trump said the word somewhere near the FIFA World Cup Draw. The proposition asks you to overturn Kalshi's No because remarks immediately before the formal program should count under a market asking what Trump would say \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\\\" Plaintiff has not carried that burden.\\n\\nThe two strongest sources are official and aligned. GovInfo, in DX-1, titles the relevant document \\\"Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw.\\\" It notes that the President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the Kennedy Center. FIFA, in DX-2, states that the Final Draw commenced at 12:00 local time. Those facts are not peripheral. They answer the timing question: the Ronaldo words were in a reporter exchange before the Draw began.\\n\\nPlaintiff's closing says the market did not specify \\\"after 12:00,\\\" \\\"during the televised draw program,\\\" or \\\"during the ball-drawing segment.\\\" True, but that does not prove Yes. The market did specify \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\\\" The ordinary function of \\\"during\\\" is to define the event period, not to include anything public, official, and thematically related that happens beforehand. A 47-minute-before reporter exchange officially titled as prior to the Draw is outside that period unless the market or governing terms affirmatively include it. The record contains no such inclusion.\\n\\nThe governing terms reinforce that conclusion. They require the word to be said by the entity during the specified time period. They recognize event-based periods and allow the Exchange to specify event inclusions. They include official-presentation concepts for material presented as part of an event. But they do not say that pre-event press availability counts by default. Plaintiff's argument turns the absence of an exclusion into proof of inclusion. That is backwards under a preponderance standard.\\n\\nPlaintiff also leans on setting: Kennedy Center, FIFA World Cup subject matter, official transcript, public reporters. Those facts show why the issue is understandable. They do not move 11:13 into a 12:00 event. A source can be official and still describe something outside the event. Indeed, that is exactly what DX-1 does: it officially documents the remarks and officially labels them prior to the Draw.\\n\\nThe weaker evidence points the same way once weighed properly. The White House page capture does not include the video or transcript. The YouTube metadata is nonofficial and not an audio transcript. Neither overcomes GovInfo's title and timing note plus FIFA's commencement time.\\n\\nSo the final answer is simple: the word was spoken, but not during the countable event period shown by the best evidence. Plaintiff has not shown that Kalshi's No resolution was wrong. The council should reject the proposition and uphold No.\\n\\nExhibits:\\n[plaintiff] PX-1 Market page packet: Ronaldo strike and challenged No resolution\\nMarket URL: https://kalshi.com/markets/kxtrumpmentionb/trump-mention-b/kxtrumpmentionb-25dec06\\n\\nPublic market title: What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\n\\nContract family: PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION\\n\\nStrike at issue: Ronaldo\\n\\nChallenged resolution: No\\n\\nRequested resolution: Yes\\n\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-2 Governing PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION terms\\n                                         NEWMENTION\\n\\nScope: These rules shall apply to this contract.\\n\\nUnderlying: The Underlying for this Contract is words used by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nRevisions to the Underlying made after Expiration will not be accounted for in determining the\\nExpiration Value.\\n\\nSource Agency: The Source Agencies are \\u003csource\\u003e.\\n\\nType: The type of Contract is an Event Contract.\\n\\nIssuance: After the initial Contract, Contract iterations will be listed on an as-needed basis at\\nthe discretion of the Exchange and corresponding to the risk management needs of Members.\\n\\n\\u003centity\\u003e: \\u003centity\\u003e refers to the speaker, writer, performer, or communicator specified by the\\nExchange. This may include (but is not limited to): a specific named individual, multiple\\nindividuals specified using AND/OR logic, an individual identified by position or title, a group,\\nband, team or collective entity, a specified member or members of a group, an organization,\\ncompany, or institutional entity, or any combination of the aforementioned.\\n\\nWhen \\u003centity\\u003e is defined by a position or title, the Contract tracks whoever holds that position\\nduring \\u003ctime period\\u003e, even if the individual holding the position changes. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a\\nspecific named individual, the identity remains consistent throughout. Name changes (e.g.,\\nstage names, married names) do not create a new entity. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a group or\\norganization and the Contract does not specify particular members, any official\\ncommunication or statement by any member or designated spokesperson counts. When using\\nAND logic, all specified entities must independently say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e. When\\nusing OR logic, at least one of the specified entities must say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nThe Exchange may specify additional conditions such as “at least X members of” a group or\\n“the majority of” a group.\\n\\n\\u003csource\\u003e: \\u003csource\\u003e refers to a Source Agency or ordered collection of Source Agencies\\nspecified by the Exchange at the time of Contract listing, which will be incorporated into the\\nSource Agency hierarchy above and used to determine the occurrence of the Underlying.\\n\\u003csource\\u003e may refer to a singular agency, multiple agencies, an agency by distinguishing\\ncharacteristics, by category or type (e.g., “official government statistical body,” “primary wire\\nservice”), or any combination thereof. When multiple agencies are specified, they may be\\napplied in the hierarchical order designated by the Exchange if so specified, with the highest-\\nranked available and responsive agency taking precedence for purposes of determining the\\nExpiration Value. A lower-ranked agency shall only be consulted if all higher-ranked agencies\\nare unavailable, unresponsive, have not reported on the Underlying by the Expiration time, or\\nif the Exchange, in its sole discretion, determines that a higher-ranked agency’s reporting is\\nincomplete, erroneous, or otherwise insufficient to determine the Expiration Value. If \\u003csource\\u003e\\ndesignates multiple agencies without specifying a hierarchical order, the Exchange shall\\nresolve any conflict between reporting agencies at its sole discretion.\\n\\n\\u003cword\\u003e: \\u003cword\\u003e refers to the particular word or phrase potentially to be mentioned by\\n\\u003centity\\u003e. It may refer to a word being said a minimum number of times. It may also refer to\\none of multiple words/phrases, any of which are acceptable (e.g., “Doge/Dogecoin”).\\n\\f\\u003ctime period\\u003e: \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific range of time, event or discrete date and\\ntime specified by the Exchange. This may be defined by, but is not limited to: a specific event\\nor context (e.g., “during the State of the Union address”), exact dates or times, relative time\\nmarkers (e.g., “before July 1, 2027,” “in Q1 2026”), event-based periods (e.g., “during any\\ncampaign rally in October 2026,” “during the awards ceremony”), and broader intervals (e.g.,\\n“Q1–Q2 2027,” “January–March 2026”).\\n\\nUnless stated otherwise, “Between” is inclusive of both endpoints, while “before” and “after”\\nexclude the specified date. \\u003ctime period\\u003e may also refer to “Any” or “None”, to multiple dates\\n(even if non-consecutive), or to a singular and discrete date or time.\\n\\nWhen \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event (such as an address, speech, performance, or\\nbroadcast), the Exchange may specify what is included, including whether it includes both live\\nand pre-recorded segments (including whether advertisements are included). Where a\\ntimezone is not specified, ET is assumed.\\n\\n\\nPayout Criterion: The Payout Criterion for the Contract encompasses the Expiration Values that\\n\\u003cword\\u003e is said by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n\\n\\nThe word must appear as a distinct, standalone unit, not buried inside another word. Plural\\nand possessive noun forms count. Other grammatical changes (tense, conjugation, derivation)\\ndo not. If \\u003cword\\u003e appears separated from other words by a space or hyphen or in a\\ncompound form with a space or hyphen, it counts. If \\u003cword\\u003e is fused into a single\\nunhyphenated word, it does not count.\\n\\nIf \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled, and the market contains a\\nstrike stating “Event does not qualify/occur”, such a strike shall resolve “Yes” and all others\\n“No”. If \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled but such strikes are NOT\\nlisted, the Contracts will resolve to the last fair price determined at the discretion of the\\nExchange. If the event is postponed, and such a postponement is announced by the end of the\\nfollowing calendar day to be rescheduled to a time within 14 calendar days, the markets shall\\nremain open. If the event captured in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast, the\\nExchange may keep the market open for 24 hours for the release of an official recording.\\nFurther granular details on conditions for these Contracts is available below.\\n\\nAdditional clarification(s):\\n\\n     Possessive noun forms of \\u003cword\\u003e, plurals, and possessive plural noun forms are\\n     INCLUDED:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigrants” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Egg” → “eggs’ shells” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Russia” → “Russia’s” counts, “Russian” does not\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e exists only in adjective form, no plural form exists:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Economic” → “Economics” does not count (“Economic” is an adjective\\n          for which “Economics” is not a plural)\\n     Plural nouns occurring within proper nouns and noun phrases are included:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Cat” → “Cats the musical” counts\\n\\f    Grammatical variations beyond plurals/possessives are NOT included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigration” does NOT count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Run” → “Running” or “Ran” do NOT count\\n    When \\u003cword\\u003e specifies a plural form, the singular does NOT count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Veterans” → “Veteran” does NOT count\\n    Words that are spelled the same as the plural form of \\u003cword\\u003e (if such exists) but are\\n    themselves not a plural noun are included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Wind” → “Winds up the clock” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Border” → “The United States has strong borders” counts\\n    Open compounds (words separated by spaces) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fire station” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “couch” → “couch potato” counts\\n    Hyphenated compounds (words connected by hyphens) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Palestine” → “pro-Palestine” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fat” → “non-fat” counts\\n    Closed compounds (single word, no spaces/hyphens) do not count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire” does not count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firefighter” does not count\\n    Multi-word \\u003cword\\u003e in larger constructions: When \\u003cword\\u003e is a multi-word phrase\\n    appearing within a hyphenated construction, it counts only if \\u003cword\\u003e appears as a\\n    complete, unmodified element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “New York” → “New York-based” counts (complete element)\\n    Portmanteaus (words blended from two words where parts of each are combined) are\\n    NOT included unless the portmanteau clearly contains \\u003cword\\u003e as a distinct, unaltered\\n    element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “MAGA” → “MAGA-nificent” counts (MAGA appears as distinct element)\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “magnificent” → “MAGA-nificent” does NOT count (portmanteau blend)\\n\\nDictionary determination: Both the Merriam-Webster Dictionary (available online) AND the\\nOxford English Dictionary shall be used to determine compound type and/or conventional\\nspelling patterns. Inclusion in either dictionary as an open or hyphenated compound shall\\nsatisfy the Payout Criterion. If neither provides clarity (or the word is not included),\\ndetermination is based on whether written as single unit (closed/doesn’t count) vs. spaces or\\nhyphens (open or hyphenated/counts) and/or context and previous usage.\\n\\nPHONETIC EQUIVALENCIES\\n\\n    Homophones (same sound, different spelling) do not count:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “write” → “right” does not count\\n    Homonyms and homographs (same spelling) COUNT regardless of meaning or\\n    pronunciation:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “bass” → both “bass guitar” and “bass fishing” count\\n    Proper and common nouns are treated identically:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Apple” → both “Apple Inc.” and “apple” (fruit) count\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Will” → both “Will Smith” and “I will go” count\\n    Minor unintentional mispronunciations COUNT if context makes intent clear:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Mamdani” → “Mandani” counts\\n    Severe mispronunciations that make \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable do NOT count.\\n    Trademarked spellings do not count, even when pronounced identically, unless the word\\n\\fitself is the same:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “lift” → “Lyft” (pronounced “lift”) does not count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “uber” → “Uber” counts\\nWords with non-standard transliteration to English count within reason, provided they are\\nphonetically equivalent:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Zelensky” → any of “Zelenski,” “Zelenskii,” “Zelensky,” or “Zelenskiy”\\n      count if pronounced equivalently\\nContractions do not count for their constituent words unless otherwise explicitly specified\\nby the Exchange:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “not” → “won’t,” “can’t,” “don’t,” “isn’t” do not count\\nNumbers spoken as words COUNT, when spoken exactly (not part of a larger number):\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “five” → saying “five” or reading “$5” aloud as “five dollars” counts,\\n      saying “five hundred” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “410” → “four hundred ten”, “four one zero” or “four ten” counts\\nOrdinals COUNT when \\u003cword\\u003e is written numerically OR a phrase that includes a\\nnumber:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “January 6” → “January 6th” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “3” (written numerically) → “3rd” (spoken as “third”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Eight War” → “8 Wars” and “Eighth War” will count\\nCardinal and ordinal number words are distinct:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “one” → “first” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “first” → “one” does NOT count\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count when pronunciation or letter-by-letter spelling\\nmatches \\u003cword\\u003e:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “NASA” (pronounced “NAH-suh”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “N-A-S-A” (spelled out) counts\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count as \\u003cword\\u003e when pronounced as the full word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Doctor” → “Dr.” (pronounced “Doctor”) counts\\nExpanded forms of acronyms do NOT count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “AI” → “artificial intelligence” does not count\\nWords in foreign languages do NOT count unless they are perfect cognates with an\\nEnglish word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fuego” (Spanish) does NOT count\\nEnglish words within foreign sentences count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “policy” → “Nuestra policy es clara” counts\\n\\u003cword\\u003e in organization/company names counts:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Securities” → “Bank of America Securities” counts\\nWords in URLs, emails, handles, and hashtags (exclusive of domain structure, email\\nprovider or symbols) are treated as compounds when spoken as complete words, with the\\ntype of compound subject to aforementioned rules:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firestation.com” pronounced “fire station dot com” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire.com” pronounced “wildfire dot com” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “apple” → “apple.com” pronounced “apple dot com” does count\\n      When presented in URL, email, handle, or hashtag form, \\u003cword\\u003e shall be treated as\\n      a compound, not a multi-word word\\nSung, rapped, or poetic words COUNT if phonetically recognizable:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “money” → “moneyyy” (extended in rap) counts\\n      Extreme distortion making \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable does NOT count.\\nPhonetic alphabet spelling (“Foxtrot India Romeo Echo” for “FIRE”) does NOT count.\\n\\fCANCELLATIONS AND DELAYS\\n\\n   The Exchange may list an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike for any Contract. If listed,\\n   such a strike refers to the structural conditions of the market, and is NOT adjudicated as a\\n   \\u003cword\\u003e needing to be said by or validated by having been said by \\u003centity\\u003e. If listed, this\\n   strike resolves to “Yes” whenever the event fails to occur or qualify under the Payout\\n   Criterion, or any other circumstance prevents normal resolution.\\n   If no such strike is listed, and \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, the following rules\\n   apply if the event is cancelled, postponed, rescheduled, or materially altered (including\\n   being closed to press) such that no video is released within one calendar day of the\\n   original start time of the event:\\n         If the event is cancelled, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price determined in\\n         the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         If the event is postponed or rescheduled, the outcome depends on whether a new\\n         date is publicly announced within one calendar day (i.e. if the event was scheduled\\n         to begin on Monday, any time up to 11:59PM on Tuesday falls within this period) of\\n         the originally scheduled start time:\\n               If no new date is announced within one calendar day, the Contract will resolve\\n               to the last fair price determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n               If a new date is announced within one calendar day, the outcome depends on\\n               when the rescheduled event is set to occur:\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls within fourteen (14) calendar days of the\\n                     originally scheduled date, the Contract shall remain open and \\u003cword\\u003e\\n                     stated during the rescheduled event will count.\\n                           The fourteen-day window begins at 12:00 AM ET on the originally\\n                           scheduled date and ends at 11:59 PM ET fourteen days later, unless\\n                           an alternate timezone is explicitly specified.\\n                           Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the State of the Union on January\\n                           15, 2026” rescheduled to January 20, 2026 → words spoken during\\n                           the rescheduled address count.\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls more than fourteen (14) calendar days after\\n                     the originally scheduled date, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price\\n                     determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         Any Contract that cannot be resolved through the Source Agency hierarchy will\\n         instead be settled at the Last Fair Price. The Exchange will disclose the methodology\\n         used to determine the Last Fair Price (e.g., Last Traded Price, Time-Weighted\\n         Average Price) at the time of Issuance.\\n         If an event begins but is interrupted, abbreviated, or ends prematurely, words\\n         stated by \\u003centity\\u003e during the portion of the event that did occur will count and the\\n         market will otherwise resolve.\\n   If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window but the venue, format, or medium\\n   changes (e.g., moved to a different location, changed from in-person to virtual (with the\\n   exception of being closed to press)), words stated during the event will count.\\n   Special condition: Across both cases, whether an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike is\\n   listed or not, if the event specified as or in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast (or\\n   relayed as such) but the live stream/broadcast does not occur, the Exchange will instead\\n   use an officially released recording as the Underlying, and may delay resolution by up to\\n   one calendar day to allow for the release of such a recording.\\n\\f          If partial snippets are released, Contracts on words that do not appear will be\\n          resolved to last fair price, and Contracts on those that do will be resolved to “Yes”.\\n          If no recording is released, the relevant outcomes triggered by the\\n          presence/absence of an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike shall occur as outlined\\n          above.\\n\\nTECHNICAL DETAILS (UNLESS OTHERWISE SPECIFIED)\\n\\n     When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, pre-recorded content broadcast,\\n     streamed, or published as part of that event is included if presented as part of the official\\n     presentation.\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the concert” with pre-recorded video interlude\\n          where entity speaks → words from interlude count\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the television appearance” with pre-taped\\n          segment aired during broadcast → words from segment count\\n     Behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are NOT\\n     included unless officially broadcast or published as part of \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n     Subtitles and captions that display \\u003cword\\u003e on screen but are not spoken aloud by\\n     \\u003centity\\u003e do NOT count.\\n     Sign language interpretation or usage by entity does NOT count as saying \\u003cword\\u003e unless\\n     the Contract explicitly specifies that sign language counts.\\n     Text that entity displays on screen (presentation slides, teleprompter visible to audience,\\n     signatures) does NOT count unless entity reads it aloud.\\n     Content generated by AI, deepfakes, or synthetic voice technology impersonating entity\\n     does NOT count unless the synthetic content is officially commissioned, authorized, or\\n     published by entity, OR the Contract explicitly specifies that AI-generated content counts.\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e is muted due to technical failure or censorship it shall not count unless\\n     corroborating contextual evidence (including surrounding speech, or an official\\n     uncensored recording or transcript) confirms that \\u003centity\\u003e specifically uttered \\u003cword\\u003e\\n     during the muted period.\\n\\nMinimum Tick: The Minimum Tick size for the Contract shall be $0.01.\\n\\nPosition Accountability Level: The Position Accountability Level for the Contract shall be\\n$25,000 per strike, per Member.\\n\\nLast Trading Date: The Last Trading Date of the Contract will be the Expiration Date. The Last\\nTrading Time will be the Expiration time.\\n\\nSettlement Date: The Settlement Date of the Contract shall be no later than the day after the\\nExpiration Date, unless the Market Outcome is under review pursuant to Rule 7.1.\\n\\nExpiration Date: When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event: The latest Expiration Date of\\nthe Contract shall be fourteen (14) calendar days after the originally scheduled date of the\\nevent. If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window, expiration will be moved to an\\nearlier date and time in accordance with Rule 7.2. When \\u003ctime period\\u003e is defined by specific\\ndates: The latest Expiration Date of the Contract shall be two weeks after the end of \\u003ctime\\nperiod\\u003e. If an event described in the Payout Criterion occurs and a consensus has been\\nreached on all terms, then expiration will be moved to an earlier date and time in accordance\\nwith Rule 7.2.\\n\\fExpiration time: The Expiration time of the Contract shall be 10:00 AM ET.\\n\\nSettlement Value: The Settlement Value for this Contract is $1.00.\\n\\nExpiration Value: The Expiration Value is the value of the Underlying as documented by the\\nSource Agency on the Expiration Date at the Expiration time.\\n\\nContingencies: Before Settlement, Kalshi may, at its sole discretion, initiate the Market\\nOutcome Review Process pursuant to Rule 7.1 of the Rulebook. If an Expiration Value cannot\\nbe determined on the Expiration Date, Kalshi has the right to determine payouts pursuant to\\nRule 7.1 in the Rulebook.\\n\\f\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-3 Official White House World Cup Drawing video page capture\\nSource capture from official White House page https://www.whitehouse.gov/videos/president-trump-attends-the-fifa-world-cup-drawing/\\nRetrieval: 2026-06-29T21:52:12Z via OpenClaw web_fetch and web.open.\\n\\nVisible page facts captured:\\n- Page title: President Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing\\n- Date shown on page: December 5, 2025\\n- Page section: Videos\\n- The page contains a link labeled View Full Video to Instagram.\\n- Related video listed: FIFA World Cup 2026 Draw at The Kennedy Center, duration 00:45, dated December 6, 2025.\\n- Related video listed: FIFA World Cup Drawing Announced to Take Place at The Kennedy Center, duration 00:56, dated August 23, 2025.\\n- Related video listed: President Trump on the 2026 FIFA World Cup, duration 01:22, dated May 6, 2025.\\n\\nRelevant extracted lines from web.open capture:\\nL142: Videos\\nL143: # President Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing\\nL145: December 5, 2025\\nL133: ... View Full Video [instagram.com] ...\\nL151: FIFA World Cup 2026 Draw at The Kennedy Center\\nL153: December 6, 2025\\nL167-L170: President Trump on the 2026 FIFA World Cup, May 6, 2025\\n\\nNotes on capture limits: readability extraction returned minimal content, so the above preserves visible lines from the page capture. The embedded/full video itself was not captured in this item.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-4 YouTube metadata capture for Ronaldo-at-FIFA-Draw clip\\nSource capture: YouTube watch page https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Cb2yO0lLEnM\\nVideo ID: Cb2yO0lLEnM\\nRetrieval: 2026-06-29T21:53:00Z via web search and curl of the YouTube watch page.\\n\\nCaptured title / page metadata:\\n- Title shown in search and page metadata: Trump Talks Cristiano Ronaldo at FIFA Draw — ‘He’s a Great Person’\\n- Channel shown in page metadata: interestingText You / @InterestingTextYou\\n- Subscriber count shown in page metadata at capture: about 10.3K subscribers\\n\\nCaptured description text from YouTube page metadata:\\n\\\"Trump Talks Cristiano Ronaldo at FIFA Draw — ‘He’s a Great Person’\\n\\nAt the FIFA World Cup Draw Ceremony, Donald Trump shared a story about meeting Cristiano Ronaldo at the White House. Trump said Ronaldo was “a great person” and even mentioned that Ronaldo spoke with his son about soccer during the visit.\\n\\nThis unexpected crossover between world politics and one of the biggest global sports stars quickly caught viewers' attention.\\n\\nTrump FIFA Draw\\nDonald Trump FIFA World Cup\\nTrump Cristiano Ronaldo\\nCristiano Ronaldo Trump meeting\\nFIFA World Cup draw 2026\\nRonaldo White House visit\\nTrump soccer comments\\nWorld Cup trending 2025\\nsports politics crossover\\nCristiano Ronaldo story\\nDonald Trump viral moment\\nFIFA draw ceremony Trump\\nWorld Cup 2026 news\\nRonaldo fan reaction\\npolitical celebrity moments\\nviral sports clips 2025\\nFIFA draw highlights\\nTrump speech FIFA\\nglobal sports news\\\"\\n\\nCapture limits and provenance caveat: direct video/caption extraction was attempted but YouTube transcript/open paths were throttled or unavailable in this environment. This item preserves the public watch-page metadata and description, not an independently extracted audio transcript. It is not an official White House or FIFA source.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-1 GovInfo official transcript: remarks prior to FIFA World Cup Draw\\nSource: GovInfo, Compilation of Presidential Documents, DCPD202501162\\nURL retrieved: https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/DCPD-202501162/html/DCPD-202501162.htm\\nRetrieval time: 2026-06-29T22:00:00Z\\nLocal captured HTML size/hash: 51,571 bytes; SHA-256 eadbceeecf3e94f5bd423bcb8e8511165fdc7265dd8c1e025870c2e8f34dfd99\\n\\nMaterial captured text from official GovInfo HTML/web.open:\\n\\nAdministration of Donald J. Trump, 2025\\n\\nTitle: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\nDate: December 5, 2025\\n\\nOpening note: [The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\\n\\nExcerpt - The President's Interest in Soccer (web.open lines 196-203):\\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\\\"football,\\\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\\n\\nExcerpt - The President's Interest in Soccer (web.open lines 322-329):\\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\\nThe President. But they have a little more speed. But no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\\n\\nTiming/context note (web.open lines 461-462):\\nNOTE: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. In his remarks, he referred to Trey Yingst, chief foreign correspondent, Fox News Channel; Cristiano Ronaldo, forward for Saudi Pro League club Al-Nass and Portugal's national soccer team; and Lionel Messi, forward for Major League Soccer club Inter Miami and Argentina's national team. A reporter referred to New York State Attorney General Letitia James.\\nThe transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\n\\nDocument category/location/name/subject metadata (web.open lines 463-468):\\nCategories: Interviews With the News Media: Exchanges with reporters, Washington, DC.\\nLocations: Washington, DC.\\nNames include: Cristiano Ronaldo and Lionel Messi.\\nSubjects include: Federation Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) World Cup; John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts; News media, Presidential interviews; Soccer.\\nDCPD Number: DCPD202501162.\\n\\nCapture limits: This item is a focused text capture of the material official transcript title, Ronaldo excerpts, timing/correction note, and metadata. It is not a full video or audio artifact. The official transcript itself notes some portions could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-2 FIFA official Final Draw start-time capture\\nSource: FIFA official page, FIFA World Cup 2026 Final Draw\\nURL: https://www.fifa.com/en/tournaments/mens/worldcup/canadamexicousa2026/live-draw\\nRetrieval time: 2026-06-29T22:01:00Z\\n\\nMaterial captured text from web search/open result:\\n- Page title/source: FIFA World Cup 2026™ Final Draw\\n- The draw takes place at the Kennedy Center in Washington DC, USA.\\n- The draw commences at 12:00 local time (17:00 UTC) on Friday 5 December 2025.\\n\\nCapture limits: This is a focused text capture of the official FIFA page timing statement located by web search. It is not a video capture of the draw ceremony.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-3 Governing PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION terms\\n                                         NEWMENTION\\n\\nScope: These rules shall apply to this contract.\\n\\nUnderlying: The Underlying for this Contract is words used by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nRevisions to the Underlying made after Expiration will not be accounted for in determining the\\nExpiration Value.\\n\\nSource Agency: The Source Agencies are \\u003csource\\u003e.\\n\\nType: The type of Contract is an Event Contract.\\n\\nIssuance: After the initial Contract, Contract iterations will be listed on an as-needed basis at\\nthe discretion of the Exchange and corresponding to the risk management needs of Members.\\n\\n\\u003centity\\u003e: \\u003centity\\u003e refers to the speaker, writer, performer, or communicator specified by the\\nExchange. This may include (but is not limited to): a specific named individual, multiple\\nindividuals specified using AND/OR logic, an individual identified by position or title, a group,\\nband, team or collective entity, a specified member or members of a group, an organization,\\ncompany, or institutional entity, or any combination of the aforementioned.\\n\\nWhen \\u003centity\\u003e is defined by a position or title, the Contract tracks whoever holds that position\\nduring \\u003ctime period\\u003e, even if the individual holding the position changes. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a\\nspecific named individual, the identity remains consistent throughout. Name changes (e.g.,\\nstage names, married names) do not create a new entity. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a group or\\norganization and the Contract does not specify particular members, any official\\ncommunication or statement by any member or designated spokesperson counts. When using\\nAND logic, all specified entities must independently say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e. When\\nusing OR logic, at least one of the specified entities must say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nThe Exchange may specify additional conditions such as “at least X members of” a group or\\n“the majority of” a group.\\n\\n\\u003csource\\u003e: \\u003csource\\u003e refers to a Source Agency or ordered collection of Source Agencies\\nspecified by the Exchange at the time of Contract listing, which will be incorporated into the\\nSource Agency hierarchy above and used to determine the occurrence of the Underlying.\\n\\u003csource\\u003e may refer to a singular agency, multiple agencies, an agency by distinguishing\\ncharacteristics, by category or type (e.g., “official government statistical body,” “primary wire\\nservice”), or any combination thereof. When multiple agencies are specified, they may be\\napplied in the hierarchical order designated by the Exchange if so specified, with the highest-\\nranked available and responsive agency taking precedence for purposes of determining the\\nExpiration Value. A lower-ranked agency shall only be consulted if all higher-ranked agencies\\nare unavailable, unresponsive, have not reported on the Underlying by the Expiration time, or\\nif the Exchange, in its sole discretion, determines that a higher-ranked agency’s reporting is\\nincomplete, erroneous, or otherwise insufficient to determine the Expiration Value. If \\u003csource\\u003e\\ndesignates multiple agencies without specifying a hierarchical order, the Exchange shall\\nresolve any conflict between reporting agencies at its sole discretion.\\n\\n\\u003cword\\u003e: \\u003cword\\u003e refers to the particular word or phrase potentially to be mentioned by\\n\\u003centity\\u003e. It may refer to a word being said a minimum number of times. It may also refer to\\none of multiple words/phrases, any of which are acceptable (e.g., “Doge/Dogecoin”).\\n\\f\\u003ctime period\\u003e: \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific range of time, event or discrete date and\\ntime specified by the Exchange. This may be defined by, but is not limited to: a specific event\\nor context (e.g., “during the State of the Union address”), exact dates or times, relative time\\nmarkers (e.g., “before July 1, 2027,” “in Q1 2026”), event-based periods (e.g., “during any\\ncampaign rally in October 2026,” “during the awards ceremony”), and broader intervals (e.g.,\\n“Q1–Q2 2027,” “January–March 2026”).\\n\\nUnless stated otherwise, “Between” is inclusive of both endpoints, while “before” and “after”\\nexclude the specified date. \\u003ctime period\\u003e may also refer to “Any” or “None”, to multiple dates\\n(even if non-consecutive), or to a singular and discrete date or time.\\n\\nWhen \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event (such as an address, speech, performance, or\\nbroadcast), the Exchange may specify what is included, including whether it includes both live\\nand pre-recorded segments (including whether advertisements are included). Where a\\ntimezone is not specified, ET is assumed.\\n\\n\\nPayout Criterion: The Payout Criterion for the Contract encompasses the Expiration Values that\\n\\u003cword\\u003e is said by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n\\n\\nThe word must appear as a distinct, standalone unit, not buried inside another word. Plural\\nand possessive noun forms count. Other grammatical changes (tense, conjugation, derivation)\\ndo not. If \\u003cword\\u003e appears separated from other words by a space or hyphen or in a\\ncompound form with a space or hyphen, it counts. If \\u003cword\\u003e is fused into a single\\nunhyphenated word, it does not count.\\n\\nIf \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled, and the market contains a\\nstrike stating “Event does not qualify/occur”, such a strike shall resolve “Yes” and all others\\n“No”. If \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled but such strikes are NOT\\nlisted, the Contracts will resolve to the last fair price determined at the discretion of the\\nExchange. If the event is postponed, and such a postponement is announced by the end of the\\nfollowing calendar day to be rescheduled to a time within 14 calendar days, the markets shall\\nremain open. If the event captured in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast, the\\nExchange may keep the market open for 24 hours for the release of an official recording.\\nFurther granular details on conditions for these Contracts is available below.\\n\\nAdditional clarification(s):\\n\\n     Possessive noun forms of \\u003cword\\u003e, plurals, and possessive plural noun forms are\\n     INCLUDED:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigrants” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Egg” → “eggs’ shells” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Russia” → “Russia’s” counts, “Russian” does not\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e exists only in adjective form, no plural form exists:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Economic” → “Economics” does not count (“Economic” is an adjective\\n          for which “Economics” is not a plural)\\n     Plural nouns occurring within proper nouns and noun phrases are included:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Cat” → “Cats the musical” counts\\n\\f    Grammatical variations beyond plurals/possessives are NOT included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigration” does NOT count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Run” → “Running” or “Ran” do NOT count\\n    When \\u003cword\\u003e specifies a plural form, the singular does NOT count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Veterans” → “Veteran” does NOT count\\n    Words that are spelled the same as the plural form of \\u003cword\\u003e (if such exists) but are\\n    themselves not a plural noun are included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Wind” → “Winds up the clock” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Border” → “The United States has strong borders” counts\\n    Open compounds (words separated by spaces) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fire station” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “couch” → “couch potato” counts\\n    Hyphenated compounds (words connected by hyphens) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Palestine” → “pro-Palestine” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fat” → “non-fat” counts\\n    Closed compounds (single word, no spaces/hyphens) do not count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire” does not count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firefighter” does not count\\n    Multi-word \\u003cword\\u003e in larger constructions: When \\u003cword\\u003e is a multi-word phrase\\n    appearing within a hyphenated construction, it counts only if \\u003cword\\u003e appears as a\\n    complete, unmodified element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “New York” → “New York-based” counts (complete element)\\n    Portmanteaus (words blended from two words where parts of each are combined) are\\n    NOT included unless the portmanteau clearly contains \\u003cword\\u003e as a distinct, unaltered\\n    element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “MAGA” → “MAGA-nificent” counts (MAGA appears as distinct element)\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “magnificent” → “MAGA-nificent” does NOT count (portmanteau blend)\\n\\nDictionary determination: Both the Merriam-Webster Dictionary (available online) AND the\\nOxford English Dictionary shall be used to determine compound type and/or conventional\\nspelling patterns. Inclusion in either dictionary as an open or hyphenated compound shall\\nsatisfy the Payout Criterion. If neither provides clarity (or the word is not included),\\ndetermination is based on whether written as single unit (closed/doesn’t count) vs. spaces or\\nhyphens (open or hyphenated/counts) and/or context and previous usage.\\n\\nPHONETIC EQUIVALENCIES\\n\\n    Homophones (same sound, different spelling) do not count:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “write” → “right” does not count\\n    Homonyms and homographs (same spelling) COUNT regardless of meaning or\\n    pronunciation:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “bass” → both “bass guitar” and “bass fishing” count\\n    Proper and common nouns are treated identically:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Apple” → both “Apple Inc.” and “apple” (fruit) count\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Will” → both “Will Smith” and “I will go” count\\n    Minor unintentional mispronunciations COUNT if context makes intent clear:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Mamdani” → “Mandani” counts\\n    Severe mispronunciations that make \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable do NOT count.\\n    Trademarked spellings do not count, even when pronounced identically, unless the word\\n\\fitself is the same:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “lift” → “Lyft” (pronounced “lift”) does not count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “uber” → “Uber” counts\\nWords with non-standard transliteration to English count within reason, provided they are\\nphonetically equivalent:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Zelensky” → any of “Zelenski,” “Zelenskii,” “Zelensky,” or “Zelenskiy”\\n      count if pronounced equivalently\\nContractions do not count for their constituent words unless otherwise explicitly specified\\nby the Exchange:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “not” → “won’t,” “can’t,” “don’t,” “isn’t” do not count\\nNumbers spoken as words COUNT, when spoken exactly (not part of a larger number):\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “five” → saying “five” or reading “$5” aloud as “five dollars” counts,\\n      saying “five hundred” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “410” → “four hundred ten”, “four one zero” or “four ten” counts\\nOrdinals COUNT when \\u003cword\\u003e is written numerically OR a phrase that includes a\\nnumber:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “January 6” → “January 6th” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “3” (written numerically) → “3rd” (spoken as “third”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Eight War” → “8 Wars” and “Eighth War” will count\\nCardinal and ordinal number words are distinct:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “one” → “first” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “first” → “one” does NOT count\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count when pronunciation or letter-by-letter spelling\\nmatches \\u003cword\\u003e:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “NASA” (pronounced “NAH-suh”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “N-A-S-A” (spelled out) counts\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count as \\u003cword\\u003e when pronounced as the full word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Doctor” → “Dr.” (pronounced “Doctor”) counts\\nExpanded forms of acronyms do NOT count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “AI” → “artificial intelligence” does not count\\nWords in foreign languages do NOT count unless they are perfect cognates with an\\nEnglish word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fuego” (Spanish) does NOT count\\nEnglish words within foreign sentences count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “policy” → “Nuestra policy es clara” counts\\n\\u003cword\\u003e in organization/company names counts:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Securities” → “Bank of America Securities” counts\\nWords in URLs, emails, handles, and hashtags (exclusive of domain structure, email\\nprovider or symbols) are treated as compounds when spoken as complete words, with the\\ntype of compound subject to aforementioned rules:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firestation.com” pronounced “fire station dot com” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire.com” pronounced “wildfire dot com” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “apple” → “apple.com” pronounced “apple dot com” does count\\n      When presented in URL, email, handle, or hashtag form, \\u003cword\\u003e shall be treated as\\n      a compound, not a multi-word word\\nSung, rapped, or poetic words COUNT if phonetically recognizable:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “money” → “moneyyy” (extended in rap) counts\\n      Extreme distortion making \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable does NOT count.\\nPhonetic alphabet spelling (“Foxtrot India Romeo Echo” for “FIRE”) does NOT count.\\n\\fCANCELLATIONS AND DELAYS\\n\\n   The Exchange may list an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike for any Contract. If listed,\\n   such a strike refers to the structural conditions of the market, and is NOT adjudicated as a\\n   \\u003cword\\u003e needing to be said by or validated by having been said by \\u003centity\\u003e. If listed, this\\n   strike resolves to “Yes” whenever the event fails to occur or qualify under the Payout\\n   Criterion, or any other circumstance prevents normal resolution.\\n   If no such strike is listed, and \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, the following rules\\n   apply if the event is cancelled, postponed, rescheduled, or materially altered (including\\n   being closed to press) such that no video is released within one calendar day of the\\n   original start time of the event:\\n         If the event is cancelled, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price determined in\\n         the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         If the event is postponed or rescheduled, the outcome depends on whether a new\\n         date is publicly announced within one calendar day (i.e. if the event was scheduled\\n         to begin on Monday, any time up to 11:59PM on Tuesday falls within this period) of\\n         the originally scheduled start time:\\n               If no new date is announced within one calendar day, the Contract will resolve\\n               to the last fair price determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n               If a new date is announced within one calendar day, the outcome depends on\\n               when the rescheduled event is set to occur:\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls within fourteen (14) calendar days of the\\n                     originally scheduled date, the Contract shall remain open and \\u003cword\\u003e\\n                     stated during the rescheduled event will count.\\n                           The fourteen-day window begins at 12:00 AM ET on the originally\\n                           scheduled date and ends at 11:59 PM ET fourteen days later, unless\\n                           an alternate timezone is explicitly specified.\\n                           Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the State of the Union on January\\n                           15, 2026” rescheduled to January 20, 2026 → words spoken during\\n                           the rescheduled address count.\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls more than fourteen (14) calendar days after\\n                     the originally scheduled date, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price\\n                     determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         Any Contract that cannot be resolved through the Source Agency hierarchy will\\n         instead be settled at the Last Fair Price. The Exchange will disclose the methodology\\n         used to determine the Last Fair Price (e.g., Last Traded Price, Time-Weighted\\n         Average Price) at the time of Issuance.\\n         If an event begins but is interrupted, abbreviated, or ends prematurely, words\\n         stated by \\u003centity\\u003e during the portion of the event that did occur will count and the\\n         market will otherwise resolve.\\n   If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window but the venue, format, or medium\\n   changes (e.g., moved to a different location, changed from in-person to virtual (with the\\n   exception of being closed to press)), words stated during the event will count.\\n   Special condition: Across both cases, whether an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike is\\n   listed or not, if the event specified as or in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast (or\\n   relayed as such) but the live stream/broadcast does not occur, the Exchange will instead\\n   use an officially released recording as the Underlying, and may delay resolution by up to\\n   one calendar day to allow for the release of such a recording.\\n\\f          If partial snippets are released, Contracts on words that do not appear will be\\n          resolved to last fair price, and Contracts on those that do will be resolved to “Yes”.\\n          If no recording is released, the relevant outcomes triggered by the\\n          presence/absence of an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike shall occur as outlined\\n          above.\\n\\nTECHNICAL DETAILS (UNLESS OTHERWISE SPECIFIED)\\n\\n     When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, pre-recorded content broadcast,\\n     streamed, or published as part of that event is included if presented as part of the official\\n     presentation.\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the concert” with pre-recorded video interlude\\n          where entity speaks → words from interlude count\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the television appearance” with pre-taped\\n          segment aired during broadcast → words from segment count\\n     Behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are NOT\\n     included unless officially broadcast or published as part of \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n     Subtitles and captions that display \\u003cword\\u003e on screen but are not spoken aloud by\\n     \\u003centity\\u003e do NOT count.\\n     Sign language interpretation or usage by entity does NOT count as saying \\u003cword\\u003e unless\\n     the Contract explicitly specifies that sign language counts.\\n     Text that entity displays on screen (presentation slides, teleprompter visible to audience,\\n     signatures) does NOT count unless entity reads it aloud.\\n     Content generated by AI, deepfakes, or synthetic voice technology impersonating entity\\n     does NOT count unless the synthetic content is officially commissioned, authorized, or\\n     published by entity, OR the Contract explicitly specifies that AI-generated content counts.\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e is muted due to technical failure or censorship it shall not count unless\\n     corroborating contextual evidence (including surrounding speech, or an official\\n     uncensored recording or transcript) confirms that \\u003centity\\u003e specifically uttered \\u003cword\\u003e\\n     during the muted period.\\n\\nMinimum Tick: The Minimum Tick size for the Contract shall be $0.01.\\n\\nPosition Accountability Level: The Position Accountability Level for the Contract shall be\\n$25,000 per strike, per Member.\\n\\nLast Trading Date: The Last Trading Date of the Contract will be the Expiration Date. The Last\\nTrading Time will be the Expiration time.\\n\\nSettlement Date: The Settlement Date of the Contract shall be no later than the day after the\\nExpiration Date, unless the Market Outcome is under review pursuant to Rule 7.1.\\n\\nExpiration Date: When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event: The latest Expiration Date of\\nthe Contract shall be fourteen (14) calendar days after the originally scheduled date of the\\nevent. If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window, expiration will be moved to an\\nearlier date and time in accordance with Rule 7.2. When \\u003ctime period\\u003e is defined by specific\\ndates: The latest Expiration Date of the Contract shall be two weeks after the end of \\u003ctime\\nperiod\\u003e. If an event described in the Payout Criterion occurs and a consensus has been\\nreached on all terms, then expiration will be moved to an earlier date and time in accordance\\nwith Rule 7.2.\\n\\fExpiration time: The Expiration time of the Contract shall be 10:00 AM ET.\\n\\nSettlement Value: The Settlement Value for this Contract is $1.00.\\n\\nExpiration Value: The Expiration Value is the value of the Underlying as documented by the\\nSource Agency on the Expiration Date at the Expiration time.\\n\\nContingencies: Before Settlement, Kalshi may, at its sole discretion, initiate the Market\\nOutcome Review Process pursuant to Rule 7.1 of the Rulebook. If an Expiration Value cannot\\nbe determined on the Expiration Date, Kalshi has the right to determine payouts pursuant to\\nRule 7.1 in the Rulebook.\\n\\f\\n\\n[defendant] DX-4 Market packet: Ronaldo strike and challenged No resolution\\nMarket URL: https://kalshi.com/markets/kxtrumpmentionb/trump-mention-b/kxtrumpmentionb-25dec06\\n\\nPublic market title: What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\n\\nContract family: PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION\\n\\nStrike at issue: Ronaldo\\n\\nChallenged resolution: No\\n\\nRequested resolution: Yes\\n\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R1 GovInfo transcript confirming Ronaldo utterances and Kennedy Center/FIFA Draw context\\nSource: GovInfo, Compilation of Presidential Documents, DCPD202501162\\nURL retrieved: https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/DCPD-202501162/html/DCPD-202501162.htm\\nRetrieval time: 2026-06-29T22:00:00Z\\nLocal captured HTML size/hash: 51,571 bytes; SHA-256 eadbceeecf3e94f5bd423bcb8e8511165fdc7265dd8c1e025870c2e8f34dfd99\\n\\nMaterial captured text from official GovInfo HTML/web.open:\\n\\nAdministration of Donald J. Trump, 2025\\n\\nTitle: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\nDate: December 5, 2025\\n\\nOpening note: [The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\\n\\nExcerpt - The President's Interest in Soccer (web.open lines 196-203):\\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\\\"football,\\\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\\n\\nExcerpt - The President's Interest in Soccer (web.open lines 322-329):\\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\\nThe President. But they have a little more speed. But no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\\n\\nTiming/context note (web.open lines 461-462):\\nNOTE: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. In his remarks, he referred to Trey Yingst, chief foreign correspondent, Fox News Channel; Cristiano Ronaldo, forward for Saudi Pro League club Al-Nass and Portugal's national soccer team; and Lionel Messi, forward for Major League Soccer club Inter Miami and Argentina's national team. A reporter referred to New York State Attorney General Letitia James.\\nThe transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\n\\nDocument category/location/name/subject metadata (web.open lines 463-468):\\nCategories: Interviews With the News Media: Exchanges with reporters, Washington, DC.\\nLocations: Washington, DC.\\nNames include: Cristiano Ronaldo and Lionel Messi.\\nSubjects include: Federation Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) World Cup; John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts; News media, Presidential interviews; Soccer.\\nDCPD Number: DCPD202501162.\\n\\nCapture limits: This item is a focused text capture of the material official transcript title, Ronaldo excerpts, timing/correction note, and metadata. It is not a full video or audio artifact. The official transcript itself notes some portions could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R2 FIFA timing capture showing formal commencement time but not market-specific exclusion\\nSource: FIFA official page, FIFA World Cup 2026 Final Draw\\nURL: https://www.fifa.com/en/tournaments/mens/worldcup/canadamexicousa2026/live-draw\\nRetrieval time: 2026-06-29T22:01:00Z\\n\\nMaterial captured text from web search/open result:\\n- Page title/source: FIFA World Cup 2026™ Final Draw\\n- The draw takes place at the Kennedy Center in Washington DC, USA.\\n- The draw commences at 12:00 local time (17:00 UTC) on Friday 5 December 2025.\\n\\nCapture limits: This is a focused text capture of the official FIFA page timing statement located by web search. It is not a video capture of the draw ceremony.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R3 Event-period terms and exclusions\\n                                         NEWMENTION\\n\\nScope: These rules shall apply to this contract.\\n\\nUnderlying: The Underlying for this Contract is words used by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nRevisions to the Underlying made after Expiration will not be accounted for in determining the\\nExpiration Value.\\n\\nSource Agency: The Source Agencies are \\u003csource\\u003e.\\n\\nType: The type of Contract is an Event Contract.\\n\\nIssuance: After the initial Contract, Contract iterations will be listed on an as-needed basis at\\nthe discretion of the Exchange and corresponding to the risk management needs of Members.\\n\\n\\u003centity\\u003e: \\u003centity\\u003e refers to the speaker, writer, performer, or communicator specified by the\\nExchange. This may include (but is not limited to): a specific named individual, multiple\\nindividuals specified using AND/OR logic, an individual identified by position or title, a group,\\nband, team or collective entity, a specified member or members of a group, an organization,\\ncompany, or institutional entity, or any combination of the aforementioned.\\n\\nWhen \\u003centity\\u003e is defined by a position or title, the Contract tracks whoever holds that position\\nduring \\u003ctime period\\u003e, even if the individual holding the position changes. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a\\nspecific named individual, the identity remains consistent throughout. Name changes (e.g.,\\nstage names, married names) do not create a new entity. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a group or\\norganization and the Contract does not specify particular members, any official\\ncommunication or statement by any member or designated spokesperson counts. When using\\nAND logic, all specified entities must independently say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e. When\\nusing OR logic, at least one of the specified entities must say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nThe Exchange may specify additional conditions such as “at least X members of” a group or\\n“the majority of” a group.\\n\\n\\u003csource\\u003e: \\u003csource\\u003e refers to a Source Agency or ordered collection of Source Agencies\\nspecified by the Exchange at the time of Contract listing, which will be incorporated into the\\nSource Agency hierarchy above and used to determine the occurrence of the Underlying.\\n\\u003csource\\u003e may refer to a singular agency, multiple agencies, an agency by distinguishing\\ncharacteristics, by category or type (e.g., “official government statistical body,” “primary wire\\nservice”), or any combination thereof. When multiple agencies are specified, they may be\\napplied in the hierarchical order designated by the Exchange if so specified, with the highest-\\nranked available and responsive agency taking precedence for purposes of determining the\\nExpiration Value. A lower-ranked agency shall only be consulted if all higher-ranked agencies\\nare unavailable, unresponsive, have not reported on the Underlying by the Expiration time, or\\nif the Exchange, in its sole discretion, determines that a higher-ranked agency’s reporting is\\nincomplete, erroneous, or otherwise insufficient to determine the Expiration Value. If \\u003csource\\u003e\\ndesignates multiple agencies without specifying a hierarchical order, the Exchange shall\\nresolve any conflict between reporting agencies at its sole discretion.\\n\\n\\u003cword\\u003e: \\u003cword\\u003e refers to the particular word or phrase potentially to be mentioned by\\n\\u003centity\\u003e. It may refer to a word being said a minimum number of times. It may also refer to\\none of multiple words/phrases, any of which are acceptable (e.g., “Doge/Dogecoin”).\\n\\f\\u003ctime period\\u003e: \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific range of time, event or discrete date and\\ntime specified by the Exchange. This may be defined by, but is not limited to: a specific event\\nor context (e.g., “during the State of the Union address”), exact dates or times, relative time\\nmarkers (e.g., “before July 1, 2027,” “in Q1 2026”), event-based periods (e.g., “during any\\ncampaign rally in October 2026,” “during the awards ceremony”), and broader intervals (e.g.,\\n“Q1–Q2 2027,” “January–March 2026”).\\n\\nUnless stated otherwise, “Between” is inclusive of both endpoints, while “before” and “after”\\nexclude the specified date. \\u003ctime period\\u003e may also refer to “Any” or “None”, to multiple dates\\n(even if non-consecutive), or to a singular and discrete date or time.\\n\\nWhen \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event (such as an address, speech, performance, or\\nbroadcast), the Exchange may specify what is included, including whether it includes both live\\nand pre-recorded segments (including whether advertisements are included). Where a\\ntimezone is not specified, ET is assumed.\\n\\n\\nPayout Criterion: The Payout Criterion for the Contract encompasses the Expiration Values that\\n\\u003cword\\u003e is said by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n\\n\\nThe word must appear as a distinct, standalone unit, not buried inside another word. Plural\\nand possessive noun forms count. Other grammatical changes (tense, conjugation, derivation)\\ndo not. If \\u003cword\\u003e appears separated from other words by a space or hyphen or in a\\ncompound form with a space or hyphen, it counts. If \\u003cword\\u003e is fused into a single\\nunhyphenated word, it does not count.\\n\\nIf \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled, and the market contains a\\nstrike stating “Event does not qualify/occur”, such a strike shall resolve “Yes” and all others\\n“No”. If \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled but such strikes are NOT\\nlisted, the Contracts will resolve to the last fair price determined at the discretion of the\\nExchange. If the event is postponed, and such a postponement is announced by the end of the\\nfollowing calendar day to be rescheduled to a time within 14 calendar days, the markets shall\\nremain open. If the event captured in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast, the\\nExchange may keep the market open for 24 hours for the release of an official recording.\\nFurther granular details on conditions for these Contracts is available below.\\n\\nAdditional clarification(s):\\n\\n     Possessive noun forms of \\u003cword\\u003e, plurals, and possessive plural noun forms are\\n     INCLUDED:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigrants” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Egg” → “eggs’ shells” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Russia” → “Russia’s” counts, “Russian” does not\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e exists only in adjective form, no plural form exists:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Economic” → “Economics” does not count (“Economic” is an adjective\\n          for which “Economics” is not a plural)\\n     Plural nouns occurring within proper nouns and noun phrases are included:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Cat” → “Cats the musical” counts\\n\\f    Grammatical variations beyond plurals/possessives are NOT included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigration” does NOT count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Run” → “Running” or “Ran” do NOT count\\n    When \\u003cword\\u003e specifies a plural form, the singular does NOT count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Veterans” → “Veteran” does NOT count\\n    Words that are spelled the same as the plural form of \\u003cword\\u003e (if such exists) but are\\n    themselves not a plural noun are included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Wind” → “Winds up the clock” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Border” → “The United States has strong borders” counts\\n    Open compounds (words separated by spaces) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fire station” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “couch” → “couch potato” counts\\n    Hyphenated compounds (words connected by hyphens) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Palestine” → “pro-Palestine” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fat” → “non-fat” counts\\n    Closed compounds (single word, no spaces/hyphens) do not count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire” does not count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firefighter” does not count\\n    Multi-word \\u003cword\\u003e in larger constructions: When \\u003cword\\u003e is a multi-word phrase\\n    appearing within a hyphenated construction, it counts only if \\u003cword\\u003e appears as a\\n    complete, unmodified element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “New York” → “New York-based” counts (complete element)\\n    Portmanteaus (words blended from two words where parts of each are combined) are\\n    NOT included unless the portmanteau clearly contains \\u003cword\\u003e as a distinct, unaltered\\n    element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “MAGA” → “MAGA-nificent” counts (MAGA appears as distinct element)\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “magnificent” → “MAGA-nificent” does NOT count (portmanteau blend)\\n\\nDictionary determination: Both the Merriam-Webster Dictionary (available online) AND the\\nOxford English Dictionary shall be used to determine compound type and/or conventional\\nspelling patterns. Inclusion in either dictionary as an open or hyphenated compound shall\\nsatisfy the Payout Criterion. If neither provides clarity (or the word is not included),\\ndetermination is based on whether written as single unit (closed/doesn’t count) vs. spaces or\\nhyphens (open or hyphenated/counts) and/or context and previous usage.\\n\\nPHONETIC EQUIVALENCIES\\n\\n    Homophones (same sound, different spelling) do not count:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “write” → “right” does not count\\n    Homonyms and homographs (same spelling) COUNT regardless of meaning or\\n    pronunciation:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “bass” → both “bass guitar” and “bass fishing” count\\n    Proper and common nouns are treated identically:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Apple” → both “Apple Inc.” and “apple” (fruit) count\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Will” → both “Will Smith” and “I will go” count\\n    Minor unintentional mispronunciations COUNT if context makes intent clear:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Mamdani” → “Mandani” counts\\n    Severe mispronunciations that make \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable do NOT count.\\n    Trademarked spellings do not count, even when pronounced identically, unless the word\\n\\fitself is the same:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “lift” → “Lyft” (pronounced “lift”) does not count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “uber” → “Uber” counts\\nWords with non-standard transliteration to English count within reason, provided they are\\nphonetically equivalent:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Zelensky” → any of “Zelenski,” “Zelenskii,” “Zelensky,” or “Zelenskiy”\\n      count if pronounced equivalently\\nContractions do not count for their constituent words unless otherwise explicitly specified\\nby the Exchange:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “not” → “won’t,” “can’t,” “don’t,” “isn’t” do not count\\nNumbers spoken as words COUNT, when spoken exactly (not part of a larger number):\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “five” → saying “five” or reading “$5” aloud as “five dollars” counts,\\n      saying “five hundred” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “410” → “four hundred ten”, “four one zero” or “four ten” counts\\nOrdinals COUNT when \\u003cword\\u003e is written numerically OR a phrase that includes a\\nnumber:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “January 6” → “January 6th” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “3” (written numerically) → “3rd” (spoken as “third”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Eight War” → “8 Wars” and “Eighth War” will count\\nCardinal and ordinal number words are distinct:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “one” → “first” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “first” → “one” does NOT count\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count when pronunciation or letter-by-letter spelling\\nmatches \\u003cword\\u003e:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “NASA” (pronounced “NAH-suh”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “N-A-S-A” (spelled out) counts\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count as \\u003cword\\u003e when pronounced as the full word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Doctor” → “Dr.” (pronounced “Doctor”) counts\\nExpanded forms of acronyms do NOT count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “AI” → “artificial intelligence” does not count\\nWords in foreign languages do NOT count unless they are perfect cognates with an\\nEnglish word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fuego” (Spanish) does NOT count\\nEnglish words within foreign sentences count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “policy” → “Nuestra policy es clara” counts\\n\\u003cword\\u003e in organization/company names counts:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Securities” → “Bank of America Securities” counts\\nWords in URLs, emails, handles, and hashtags (exclusive of domain structure, email\\nprovider or symbols) are treated as compounds when spoken as complete words, with the\\ntype of compound subject to aforementioned rules:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firestation.com” pronounced “fire station dot com” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire.com” pronounced “wildfire dot com” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “apple” → “apple.com” pronounced “apple dot com” does count\\n      When presented in URL, email, handle, or hashtag form, \\u003cword\\u003e shall be treated as\\n      a compound, not a multi-word word\\nSung, rapped, or poetic words COUNT if phonetically recognizable:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “money” → “moneyyy” (extended in rap) counts\\n      Extreme distortion making \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable does NOT count.\\nPhonetic alphabet spelling (“Foxtrot India Romeo Echo” for “FIRE”) does NOT count.\\n\\fCANCELLATIONS AND DELAYS\\n\\n   The Exchange may list an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike for any Contract. If listed,\\n   such a strike refers to the structural conditions of the market, and is NOT adjudicated as a\\n   \\u003cword\\u003e needing to be said by or validated by having been said by \\u003centity\\u003e. If listed, this\\n   strike resolves to “Yes” whenever the event fails to occur or qualify under the Payout\\n   Criterion, or any other circumstance prevents normal resolution.\\n   If no such strike is listed, and \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, the following rules\\n   apply if the event is cancelled, postponed, rescheduled, or materially altered (including\\n   being closed to press) such that no video is released within one calendar day of the\\n   original start time of the event:\\n         If the event is cancelled, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price determined in\\n         the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         If the event is postponed or rescheduled, the outcome depends on whether a new\\n         date is publicly announced within one calendar day (i.e. if the event was scheduled\\n         to begin on Monday, any time up to 11:59PM on Tuesday falls within this period) of\\n         the originally scheduled start time:\\n               If no new date is announced within one calendar day, the Contract will resolve\\n               to the last fair price determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n               If a new date is announced within one calendar day, the outcome depends on\\n               when the rescheduled event is set to occur:\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls within fourteen (14) calendar days of the\\n                     originally scheduled date, the Contract shall remain open and \\u003cword\\u003e\\n                     stated during the rescheduled event will count.\\n                           The fourteen-day window begins at 12:00 AM ET on the originally\\n                           scheduled date and ends at 11:59 PM ET fourteen days later, unless\\n                           an alternate timezone is explicitly specified.\\n                           Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the State of the Union on January\\n                           15, 2026” rescheduled to January 20, 2026 → words spoken during\\n                           the rescheduled address count.\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls more than fourteen (14) calendar days after\\n                     the originally scheduled date, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price\\n                     determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         Any Contract that cannot be resolved through the Source Agency hierarchy will\\n         instead be settled at the Last Fair Price. The Exchange will disclose the methodology\\n         used to determine the Last Fair Price (e.g., Last Traded Price, Time-Weighted\\n         Average Price) at the time of Issuance.\\n         If an event begins but is interrupted, abbreviated, or ends prematurely, words\\n         stated by \\u003centity\\u003e during the portion of the event that did occur will count and the\\n         market will otherwise resolve.\\n   If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window but the venue, format, or medium\\n   changes (e.g., moved to a different location, changed from in-person to virtual (with the\\n   exception of being closed to press)), words stated during the event will count.\\n   Special condition: Across both cases, whether an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike is\\n   listed or not, if the event specified as or in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast (or\\n   relayed as such) but the live stream/broadcast does not occur, the Exchange will instead\\n   use an officially released recording as the Underlying, and may delay resolution by up to\\n   one calendar day to allow for the release of such a recording.\\n\\f          If partial snippets are released, Contracts on words that do not appear will be\\n          resolved to last fair price, and Contracts on those that do will be resolved to “Yes”.\\n          If no recording is released, the relevant outcomes triggered by the\\n          presence/absence of an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike shall occur as outlined\\n          above.\\n\\nTECHNICAL DETAILS (UNLESS OTHERWISE SPECIFIED)\\n\\n     When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, pre-recorded content broadcast,\\n     streamed, or published as part of that event is included if presented as part of the official\\n     presentation.\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the concert” with pre-recorded video interlude\\n          where entity speaks → words from interlude count\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the television appearance” with pre-taped\\n          segment aired during broadcast → words from segment count\\n     Behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are NOT\\n     included unless officially broadcast or published as part of \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n     Subtitles and captions that display \\u003cword\\u003e on screen but are not spoken aloud by\\n     \\u003centity\\u003e do NOT count.\\n     Sign language interpretation or usage by entity does NOT count as saying \\u003cword\\u003e unless\\n     the Contract explicitly specifies that sign language counts.\\n     Text that entity displays on screen (presentation slides, teleprompter visible to audience,\\n     signatures) does NOT count unless entity reads it aloud.\\n     Content generated by AI, deepfakes, or synthetic voice technology impersonating entity\\n     does NOT count unless the synthetic content is officially commissioned, authorized, or\\n     published by entity, OR the Contract explicitly specifies that AI-generated content counts.\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e is muted due to technical failure or censorship it shall not count unless\\n     corroborating contextual evidence (including surrounding speech, or an official\\n     uncensored recording or transcript) confirms that \\u003centity\\u003e specifically uttered \\u003cword\\u003e\\n     during the muted period.\\n\\nMinimum Tick: The Minimum Tick size for the Contract shall be $0.01.\\n\\nPosition Accountability Level: The Position Accountability Level for the Contract shall be\\n$25,000 per strike, per Member.\\n\\nLast Trading Date: The Last Trading Date of the Contract will be the Expiration Date. The Last\\nTrading Time will be the Expiration time.\\n\\nSettlement Date: The Settlement Date of the Contract shall be no later than the day after the\\nExpiration Date, unless the Market Outcome is under review pursuant to Rule 7.1.\\n\\nExpiration Date: When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event: The latest Expiration Date of\\nthe Contract shall be fourteen (14) calendar days after the originally scheduled date of the\\nevent. If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window, expiration will be moved to an\\nearlier date and time in accordance with Rule 7.2. When \\u003ctime period\\u003e is defined by specific\\ndates: The latest Expiration Date of the Contract shall be two weeks after the end of \\u003ctime\\nperiod\\u003e. If an event described in the Payout Criterion occurs and a consensus has been\\nreached on all terms, then expiration will be moved to an earlier date and time in accordance\\nwith Rule 7.2.\\n\\fExpiration time: The Expiration time of the Contract shall be 10:00 AM ET.\\n\\nSettlement Value: The Settlement Value for this Contract is $1.00.\\n\\nExpiration Value: The Expiration Value is the value of the Underlying as documented by the\\nSource Agency on the Expiration Date at the Expiration time.\\n\\nContingencies: Before Settlement, Kalshi may, at its sole discretion, initiate the Market\\nOutcome Review Process pursuant to Rule 7.1 of the Rulebook. If an Expiration Value cannot\\nbe determined on the Expiration Date, Kalshi has the right to determine payouts pursuant to\\nRule 7.1 in the Rulebook.\\n\\f\\n\\n[defendant] DX-S1 GovInfo official transcript: prior reporter exchange\\nSource: GovInfo, Compilation of Presidential Documents, DCPD202501162\\nURL retrieved: https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/DCPD-202501162/html/DCPD-202501162.htm\\nRetrieval time: 2026-06-29T22:00:00Z\\nLocal captured HTML size/hash: 51,571 bytes; SHA-256 eadbceeecf3e94f5bd423bcb8e8511165fdc7265dd8c1e025870c2e8f34dfd99\\n\\nMaterial captured text from official GovInfo HTML/web.open:\\n\\nAdministration of Donald J. Trump, 2025\\n\\nTitle: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\nDate: December 5, 2025\\n\\nOpening note: [The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\\n\\nExcerpt - The President's Interest in Soccer (web.open lines 196-203):\\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\\\"football,\\\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\\n\\nExcerpt - The President's Interest in Soccer (web.open lines 322-329):\\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\\nThe President. But they have a little more speed. But no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\\n\\nTiming/context note (web.open lines 461-462):\\nNOTE: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. In his remarks, he referred to Trey Yingst, chief foreign correspondent, Fox News Channel; Cristiano Ronaldo, forward for Saudi Pro League club Al-Nass and Portugal's national soccer team; and Lionel Messi, forward for Major League Soccer club Inter Miami and Argentina's national team. A reporter referred to New York State Attorney General Letitia James.\\nThe transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\n\\nDocument category/location/name/subject metadata (web.open lines 463-468):\\nCategories: Interviews With the News Media: Exchanges with reporters, Washington, DC.\\nLocations: Washington, DC.\\nNames include: Cristiano Ronaldo and Lionel Messi.\\nSubjects include: Federation Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) World Cup; John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts; News media, Presidential interviews; Soccer.\\nDCPD Number: DCPD202501162.\\n\\nCapture limits: This item is a focused text capture of the material official transcript title, Ronaldo excerpts, timing/correction note, and metadata. It is not a full video or audio artifact. The official transcript itself notes some portions could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-S2 FIFA official draw commencement time\\nSource: FIFA official page, FIFA World Cup 2026 Final Draw\\nURL: https://www.fifa.com/en/tournaments/mens/worldcup/canadamexicousa2026/live-draw\\nRetrieval time: 2026-06-29T22:01:00Z\\n\\nMaterial captured text from web search/open result:\\n- Page title/source: FIFA World Cup 2026™ Final Draw\\n- The draw takes place at the Kennedy Center in Washington DC, USA.\\n- The draw commences at 12:00 local time (17:00 UTC) on Friday 5 December 2025.\\n\\nCapture limits: This is a focused text capture of the official FIFA page timing statement located by web search. It is not a video capture of the draw ceremony.\\n\\nSubmitted evidence:\\n[plaintiff arguments] Official White House video page capture: President Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing (ev_db357d4e9407_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-db357d4e9407)\\nSource: https://www.whitehouse.gov/videos/president-trump-attends-the-fifa-world-cup-drawing/\\nSHA-256: `db357d4e940728d417ae4f7f3caac6b78d3fd3e4aba70d46fe10c6132d45997a`\\nBytes: 1300\\nRelevance: Establishes that the White House officially published a video page titled President Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing, dated December 5, 2025, with a full-video link and related World Cup Draw videos; relevant to source chain and event context.\\n\\n[plaintiff arguments] YouTube metadata capture: Trump Talks Cristiano Ronaldo at FIFA Draw (ev_4e1045905547_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-4e1045905547)\\nSource: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Cb2yO0lLEnM\\nSHA-256: `4e10459055477440085fe5e20d970eb2488e61d13a5e2b3133a3656bed7526d7`\\nBytes: 1779\\nRelevance: Provides a public clip source and page metadata asserting that at the FIFA World Cup Draw Ceremony Trump shared a story about meeting Cristiano Ronaldo and said Ronaldo was a great person; relevant to the alleged Ronaldo utterance, though weaker than an official full transcript or video.\\n\\n[defendant arguments] GovInfo official transcript capture: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the FIFA World Cup Draw (ev_a1b1f6b1b7bd_submitted-evidence-03-defendant-a1b1f6b1b7bd)\\nSource: https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/DCPD-202501162/html/DCPD-202501162.htm\\nSHA-256: `a1b1f6b1b7bd0b691c7fe8d97467dd0d085e2b22387ae4198270764de66e56e2`\\nBytes: 3070\\nRelevance: Official transcript identifies the relevant Trump remarks as an exchange with reporters prior to the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw; it includes the Ronaldo utterances and timing/correction notes, directly bearing on whether the utterances were during the countable event period.\\n\\n[defendant arguments] FIFA official page capture: 2026 World Cup Final Draw start time (ev_3973dc8f98c0_submitted-evidence-04-defendant-3973dc8f98c0)\\nSource: https://www.fifa.com/en/tournaments/mens/worldcup/canadamexicousa2026/live-draw\\nSHA-256: `3973dc8f98c01702174f61f5548eb1e80efe64dd72b44f21ed0fa7d944f93248`\\nBytes: 598\\nRelevance: Establishes the official Final Draw start time as 12:00 local time on December 5, 2025, which helps compare the draw event period against the GovInfo transcript note that the reporter exchange occurred at 11:13 a.m.\\n\\nTechnical reports:\\n[plaintiff] Plaintiff source-search and capture ledger\\nSearched exact market/strike phrases, White House domain, public video pages, YouTube video IDs, and Kalshi live market URL. Submitted official White House page capture and YouTube metadata capture. Kalshi live page returned a Vercel security checkpoint/429; local browser was unavailable; Python pip/ensurepip unavailable for yt-dlp; direct YouTube caption/open paths were throttled or unavailable. Remaining best evidence would be a full official video/transcript or Kalshi resolution rationale if later accessible.\\n\\n[defendant] Defendant source-search and capture ledger\\nInspected current AAR evidence and exact contents of plaintiff's White House and YouTube captures. Retrieved GovInfo official HTML transcript with curl from DCPD-202501162; local full HTML was 51,571 bytes with SHA-256 eadbceeecf3e94f5bd423bcb8e8511165fdc7265dd8c1e025870c2e8f34dfd99, then submitted a focused material text capture as DX-1. Searched official draw timing and submitted the FIFA official page timing statement as DX-2. Remaining gaps: full Kalshi market source hierarchy/resolution rationale and full WH/FIFA video were not captured, but official GovInfo timing/title plus FIFA start time resolve the material timing issue.\\n\\nCall submit_council_vote with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated.\\nKeep the rationale brief: no more than three sentences.\\n\\nCouncil API instructions:\\nYou are a council member. Decide the proposition from the admitted record.\\nYou may examine admitted evidence through read-only tools when exact bytes, metadata, or exhibit contents matter.\\nDo not search the web, introduce new facts, create new evidence, or upload evidence.\\nWhen ready, call submit_council_vote exactly once with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated and a concise rationale.\\n\",\"state\":\"ready\",\"status\":\"ready\",\"tools\":[{\"description\":\"Return the current visible arbitration record for this council member.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"get_case\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"List visible immutable record evidence.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"list_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Return metadata and read limits for one visible evidence item.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"stat_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Read a bounded byte range from one visible evidence item as base64.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"length\":{\"minimum\":1,\"type\":\"integer\"},\"offset\":{\"minimum\":0,\"type\":\"integer\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\",\"offset\",\"length\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"read_evidence_range\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Submit one council vote for the current deliberation opportunity.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"rationale\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"vote\":{\"enum\":[\"demonstrated\",\"not_demonstrated\"],\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"vote\",\"rationale\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"submit_council_vote\",\"read_only\":false}],\"turn\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"completed\":false,\"deadline\":\"2026-06-29T22:18:45.386037689Z\",\"deliberation_round\":1,\"member_id\":\"C2\",\"opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C2\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"remaining_ms\":889046,\"role_id\":\"council\",\"turn_number\":10},\"wait\":{\"reason\":\"ready\",\"state_version\":14,\"version\":17}}"}],"structuredContent":{"after_opportunity_id":"deliberation:1:C2","after_version":17,"case_id":"arb-ex03a-20260629214245","limits":{"attempts_max":3,"attempts_remaining":3,"max_evidence_read_bytes":65536,"max_evidence_read_bytes_per_opportunity":524288,"max_evidence_reads_per_opportunity":32,"max_response_bytes":131072,"remaining_evidence_read_bytes_for_opportunity":524288,"remaining_evidence_reads_for_opportunity":32},"member_id":"C2","message":"An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.","ok":true,"prompt":"Role: council member\nMember ID: C2\nDeliberation round: 1\nProposition: For the Kalshi market \"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\", the strike \"Ronaldo\" should resolve Yes because Trump said \"Ronaldo\" in public remarks at the World Cup Draw venue immediately before the formal program, and the market wording plus the governing mention-market terms did not clearly exclude those event-linked remarks.\nStandard of evidence: Preponderance of the evidence.\nPersona:\nYou are a careful juror and council member.\n\nEvaluate the record faithfully. Decide only from the evidence, the stated rules, and the applicable burden of proof. Do not favor either side, fill gaps with speculation, or ignore uncertainty.\n\nGive weight to reliable sources, direct evidence, consistent reasoning, and clear admissions. Discount unsupported claims, rhetorical force, irrelevant facts, and conclusions that exceed the record.\n\nWhen the evidence supports one answer, state it plainly. When the evidence is incomplete or balanced, say so. Be concise, honest, and exact.\n\nRecord:\nOpenings:\n[plaintiff] Council members, this case is not about whether the word \"Ronaldo\" would count if President Trump clearly said it. The current packet makes that part straightforward: the market is the Kalshi PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION market titled \"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\"; the strike is \"Ronaldo\"; Kalshi’s challenged resolution is No; and plaintiff seeks Yes.\n\nThe real dispute is temporal and contextual. Did the market phrase \"during the FIFA World Cup Draw,\" read with the governing mention-market terms, include public event-linked remarks at the World Cup Draw venue immediately before the formal draw program? Or did it clearly confine countable words to a narrower formal broadcast segment? Plaintiff’s position is that a No resolution cannot stand unless the record shows that the counting window clearly excluded those event-linked remarks.\n\nThe admitted terms matter. They define the underlying as words used by the specified entity during the specified time period. They expressly recognize event-based time periods, and they say the payout criterion is satisfied when the word is said by the entity during that period. They also contain exclusions: behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings do not count unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period; captions or text alone do not count; and the word must appear as a distinct standalone unit. Those exclusions are important, but they do not by themselves answer this case. A public remark at the event venue, tied to the Draw and immediately before the formal program, is not automatically a rehearsal, sound check, or private behind-the-scenes moment.\n\nAt this opening stage, the record proves the market identity, the challenged resolution, the requested resolution, and the generic governing terms. It does not yet prove the utterance itself, the exact sequence of the venue remarks, the source-agency hierarchy or any market-specific time-period language beyond the packet, or Kalshi’s reason for treating the strike as No. Those are the factual links that should decide the case under a preponderance standard.\n\nPlaintiff expects the decisive proof to be the full official or otherwise reliable event video or transcript, with enough surrounding context to show whether Trump said \"Ronaldo\" aloud as a standalone word; when he said it relative to the Draw event; whether the remarks were public and event-linked rather than backstage or a sound check; and whether any market-specific rule clearly excluded that segment. Plaintiff also expects the market page, archived market details, and any resolution rationale to be important because ambiguity in the market’s own event wording should not be resolved against Yes after the fact.\n\nThe defense will likely argue that \"during the FIFA World Cup Draw\" means only the formal draw ceremony or broadcast, and that anything before the formal program is outside the counting period. That theory can win only if the evidence shows a clear exclusion or a source record that separates the alleged remarks from the event itself. If the evidence instead shows public remarks at the Draw venue, officially connected to the event, immediately before the formal program, and no clear rule excluding them, then the terms favor counting the word and resolving the Ronaldo strike Yes.\n\n[defendant] Council members, the defense position is straightforward: the admitted record does not yet prove that the Ronaldo strike should resolve Yes. It proves a market title, a generic mention-market rule set, and Kalshi's challenged No resolution. It does not prove that any qualifying utterance of \"Ronaldo\" occurred during the market's countable time period.\n\nThe plaintiff's opening usefully narrows the dispute. This is not primarily a word-boundary case. If President Trump said \"Ronaldo\" as a standalone spoken word during the countable FIFA World Cup Draw period, the generic terms would ordinarily treat that as the kind of word that can count. The real question is whether plaintiff can carry the burden of showing that alleged pre-program, venue-adjacent remarks were part of the market's specified time period: \"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\"\n\nThe case-packet terms matter, but they cut both ways. They say the underlying is words used by the entity during the specified time period. They recognize that a time period can be an event, and they allow the Exchange to specify what is included when an event is involved. They also distinguish official event presentation from material outside the event: behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are not included unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period; text or captions alone do not count; and the relevant word must be spoken aloud by the entity. Those provisions do not support a rule that every public comment inside the same building, or every press exchange near the formal program, is automatically \"during\" the Draw.\n\nThat is the burden problem for plaintiff. The admitted market-page file identifies the public title, contract family, strike, challenged resolution, and requested resolution. It does not supply a full market-specific source hierarchy, a formal start time, a transcript, a video, a resolution rationale, or the alleged remarks. The terms file supplies the generic framework, but not the factual bridge from \"immediately before the formal program\" to \"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\" Without that bridge, the No resolution is not shown to be wrong by a preponderance of the evidence.\n\nThe defense expects the decisive proof to be source-chain evidence, not characterization. The council should want the market's full rule page if available, the source agency hierarchy, the official draw program or broadcast, any official transcript or recording of the alleged exchange, and enough surrounding timestamps to separate the formal draw from pre-event reporter access, red-carpet exchanges, arrivals, or other ancillary material. If later evidence shows that the alleged Ronaldo comment was in a segment officially presented as part of the Draw itself, plaintiff's argument becomes stronger. If the evidence instead shows a separate exchange with reporters before the draw, or an event-linked but pre-program interaction not incorporated into the official presentation, the generic terms support Kalshi's No.\n\nSo the defense opening is not that the word Ronaldo could never count. It is that this record has not established the necessary time-period link. The proposition asks the council to overturn No because the market wording and terms did not clearly exclude pre-program remarks. That reverses the burden. Plaintiff must show that the remarks were included in the countable period. Ambiguity about the outer edge of an event is not the same as proof that a specific pre-event utterance satisfies the payout criterion.\n\nArguments:\n[plaintiff] Council members, plaintiff has now supplied the record links that were missing at opening.\n\nFirst, the market packet fixes what this dispute is: the Kalshi market title is \"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\"; the contract family is PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION; the strike is \"Ronaldo\"; Kalshi's challenged resolution is No; and plaintiff seeks Yes. That is PX-1.\n\nSecond, the governing terms make this an event-period mention question, not a narrow formal-program-only question. PX-2 says the underlying is words used by the entity during the time period, recognizes that a time period may be a specific event, and sets the payout criterion as the word being said by the entity during that period. It also tells us what does not count: text/captions alone, unofficial behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, and sound checks unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. Those exclusions matter, but none says that public event-linked remarks at the venue immediately before the formal program are categorically outside \"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\"\n\nThird, the source-chain evidence now points to the disputed event and the Ronaldo utterance. PX-3 is an official White House page titled \"President Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing,\" dated December 5, 2025, with a full-video link and related World Cup Draw videos. That establishes an official White House event-video source for Trump's attendance at the World Cup Drawing. PX-4 is a public YouTube watch-page metadata capture for video ID Cb2yO0lLEnM, titled \"Trump Talks Cristiano Ronaldo at FIFA Draw -- 'He's a Great Person'.\" Its description states that at the FIFA World Cup Draw Ceremony, Trump shared a story about meeting Cristiano Ronaldo at the White House, said Ronaldo was a great person, and mentioned Ronaldo spoke with his son. PX-4 is not as strong as an official transcript, and plaintiff says that plainly. But it is admitted source content that directly links Trump, Cristiano Ronaldo, and the FIFA Draw ceremony.\n\nOn a preponderance standard, that is enough to defeat the challenged No resolution unless the defense can supply a clearer exclusion. The market did not ask only what Trump would say during the ball-pulling segment, during the televised main show, or after a particular formal start cue. It asked what he would say \"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\" The terms recognize event-based periods and exclude particular non-event categories. A public remark at the Draw venue, tied to the Draw, is far closer to the event period than to a rehearsal, sound check, caption, or private backstage recording.\n\nThe defense's burden framing is too strict. Plaintiff must prove Yes by a preponderance; plaintiff need not prove that Kalshi drafted every boundary with perfect precision. Once the admitted sources show a Ronaldo mention in connection with the FIFA Draw ceremony, the remaining question is whether the rules clearly remove that event-linked remark from the counting period. They do not. Ambiguity in a mention market's event wording should not be converted into an unstated formal-program limitation after the fact.\n\nProvenance and gaps: plaintiff attempted to retrieve the live Kalshi page, official/full video, caption, and transcript. Kalshi returned a Vercel security checkpoint; the local browser tool was unavailable; Python pip/ensurepip was unavailable for yt-dlp; and direct YouTube caption/open paths were throttled or unavailable. That leaves PX-4 weaker than ideal, but not weightless. PX-3 supplies official event context, PX-4 supplies the Ronaldo-at-FIFA-Draw metadata, and PX-2 supplies the rule that event-linked spoken words count absent a clear exclusion.\n\nThe council should resolve the proposition Yes: the Ronaldo strike should have resolved Yes because the record more likely than not shows Trump said Ronaldo in public remarks tied to the FIFA World Cup Draw, and the market wording plus governing terms did not clearly exclude those remarks.\n\n[defendant] Council members, the merits record now shows why the challenged No resolution should stand.\n\nPlaintiff's best point is that Trump did say the word \"Ronaldo.\" The defense does not need to fight that. The question is whether he said it during the market's countable time period: \"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\" On that decisive question, the strongest official sources favor No.\n\nThe admitted GovInfo transcript, DX-1, is an official Compilation of Presidential Documents capture. Its title is not merely \"World Cup Draw\" or \"FIFA ceremony.\" It is \"Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw.\" That same transcript contains the Ronaldo passages: Trump says he met Ronaldo at the White House, later says he was \"not Ronaldo or Messi,\" and the note identifies Ronaldo among the people referenced. So DX-1 is not adverse to the defense because it confirms the word; it is decisive because it places the word in an exchange with reporters prior to the Draw.\n\nDX-2 supplies the timing anchor. The official FIFA Final Draw page states that the Draw at the Kennedy Center commenced at 12:00 local time on Friday, December 5, 2025. DX-1 states that the President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the Kennedy Center. A reporter exchange at 11:13, officially titled as prior to a 12:00 draw, is not more likely than not \"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\" It is before it.\n\nThat reading matches the governing PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION terms. PX-2 says the payout criterion is satisfied when the word is said by the entity during the specified time period. It recognizes event-based periods and permits the Exchange to specify what is included for an event. It also treats official presentation differently from adjacent material: pre-recorded content counts if presented as part of the official event presentation, while behind-the-scenes, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings do not count unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. The point is not that this reporter exchange was a rehearsal or sound check. The point is that the terms require a link to the time period itself. Plaintiff has supplied no market-specific language saying pre-event reporter availability, arrivals, or venue interviews count as part of the Draw.\n\nPlaintiff's new exhibits do not fill that gap. PX-3, the White House page capture, establishes that the White House had a page titled \"President Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing,\" but plaintiff's own capture says the embedded/full video was not captured. It does not prove that the Ronaldo words occurred inside the official draw program. PX-4 is weaker still: it is metadata from a nonofficial YouTube channel. It says the clip is about Trump talking Ronaldo at the FIFA Draw, but it is not a transcript, not an official source, and not an audio extraction. When a nonofficial clip description is weighed against GovInfo's official transcript title and FIFA's official start time, the official sources control.\n\nNor is this a burden-shifting problem. The proposition asks the council to overturn Kalshi's No because the market supposedly did not clearly exclude remarks immediately before the formal program. But the preponderance burden is on Yes. The record must show that the strike satisfied the payout criterion. The admitted terms do not say that ambiguous pre-event remarks count by default; they say the word must be said during the specified time period. Here, the best evidence identifies the remarks as prior to the Draw and before the official commencement time.\n\nProvenance also matters. DX-1 is an official government transcript with a correction note and an audio-incomplete caveat. That caveat affects stray inaudible portions, but it does not weaken the title, the 11:13 timing note, or the Ronaldo passages preserved in the transcript. DX-2 is an official FIFA timing source. Plaintiff's YouTube metadata may explain why the dispute arose, but it cannot outweigh those primary sources on timing and event classification.\n\nThe council should resolve the proposition against plaintiff. Trump said Ronaldo, but the record more likely shows he did so in a reporter exchange prior to the FIFA World Cup Draw, not during the countable Draw event. Kalshi's No resolution should be upheld.\n\nRebuttals:\n[plaintiff] Council members, defendant’s new evidence narrows the case but does not end it.\n\nPlaintiff accepts the important parts of DX-1 and DX-2. The GovInfo transcript is official; it labels the item an exchange with reporters \"Prior to\" the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw; it places the exchange at 11:13 a.m. at the Kennedy Center; and the FIFA capture states the draw commenced at 12:00 local time. Plaintiff should not pretend those facts are weak.\n\nBut defendant asks those facts to do more than they do. The market was not drafted as \"what will Trump say after the official 12:00 commencement,\" \"during the televised draw program,\" or \"during the ball-drawing segment.\" PX-1 says the public market title was \"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\" That is ordinary event language, and PX-2 recognizes event-based time periods while leaving room for the Exchange to specify what is included. The record still contains no market-specific exclusion for official venue press remarks immediately before the formal program.\n\nDX-1 also helps plaintiff on the facts defendant originally said were missing. It confirms the relevant spoken word. Trump said he met Ronaldo, that Ronaldo is great, and that he was not Ronaldo or Messi. It also places those remarks at the Kennedy Center in a FIFA World Cup Draw-centered exchange with reporters, not in an unrelated private dinner or stale campaign setting. The transcript’s own subject metadata includes the FIFA World Cup, the Kennedy Center, news media, presidential interviews, and soccer. That is event-linked public context.\n\nThe terms’ exclusions do not fit defendant’s leap. PX-2 excludes captions alone, rehearsals, sound checks, behind-the-scenes content, and unofficial recordings unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. DX-1 is not a rehearsal transcript. It is not a sound check. It is not merely a caption. It is an official presidential transcript of a public reporter exchange at the venue, released in the Compilation of Presidential Documents. If Kalshi meant to exclude that category because it occurred before a formal noon commencement, the market needed to say so clearly.\n\nSo the dispositive question remains one of market construction: does \"during the FIFA World Cup Draw\" clearly exclude public, official, event-site remarks immediately before the formal program? Defendant has proved \"prior to\" the formal draw start. Defendant has not proved a clear market rule that treats the broader Draw event as beginning only at 12:00 for mention purposes.\n\nUnder a preponderance standard, the record now confirms the Ronaldo utterance and confirms the FIFA Draw setting. The challenged No resolution should not be upheld by importing a narrow formal-program limitation that the market title and generic terms did not state.\n\nSurrebuttals:\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff's rebuttal usefully clarifies the remaining dispute: plaintiff accepts that DX-1 is official, that it labels the relevant item an exchange with reporters \"Prior to\" the FIFA World Cup Draw, that the exchange occurred at 11:13 a.m. at the Kennedy Center, and that DX-2 places the official Draw commencement at 12:00 local time. Those concessions should decide the case.\n\nPlaintiff's answer is that the market did not say \"after 12:00,\" \"during the televised program,\" or \"during the ball-drawing segment.\" But the market also did not say \"at the venue before the Draw,\" \"in pre-event reporter exchanges,\" or \"in any public remarks connected to the Draw.\" The phrase it chose was \"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\" Ordinary event language has a start, and the official FIFA source fixes that start at noon. Official GovInfo then fixes this exchange at 11:13 and titles it as prior to the Draw.\n\nThat is not a technicality. The terms require the word to be said during the specified time period. They recognize event-based periods and allow event-specific inclusions, but no admitted market-specific rule includes pre-event press access. Plaintiff's construction would turn any event-adjacent public remark into part of the event unless expressly excluded. That reverses the payout criterion. The claimant must show the word occurred during the time period; it is not enough to show the same venue, the same general topic, and official publication.\n\nPlaintiff says the exclusions do not fit because DX-1 is not a rehearsal, sound check, caption, or private backstage recording. Fair enough; the defense is not relying on those categories as labels. The defense relies on the affirmative timing requirement. A remark need not be a rehearsal to be outside the event. A reporter exchange officially described as prior to a noon event and occurring at 11:13 is outside because it is before the event began.\n\nThe record therefore proves the wrong fact for plaintiff. It proves Trump said Ronaldo, but in a pre-event reporter exchange. The proposition requires Yes only if those words count during the FIFA World Cup Draw. On this record, they do not. Kalshi's No resolution should be upheld.\n\nClosings:\n[plaintiff] Council members, the final record leaves one legal question.\n\nThe easy factual question is resolved in plaintiff’s favor: Trump said \"Ronaldo.\" The official GovInfo transcript confirms it twice in substance: he said he met Ronaldo, praised him, and later said he was not Ronaldo or Messi. That is a spoken standalone use of the strike word. The record also places the remarks at the Kennedy Center in a FIFA World Cup Draw-centered reporter exchange. This was not an unrelated dinner, a caption, an AI voice, or a social-media paraphrase.\n\nThe hard point is timing. Defendant has the strongest evidence on the formal program boundary: GovInfo titled the exchange as \"Prior to\" the Draw, notes 11:13 a.m., and FIFA states the Final Draw commenced at 12:00 local time. Plaintiff does not ask the council to ignore that. The question is what the Kalshi market actually required.\n\nPX-1 did not say \"after 12:00.\" It did not say \"during the televised draw program\" or \"during the ball-drawing segment.\" It asked, in public market wording, \"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\" PX-2’s generic terms recognize event-based periods and say the Exchange may specify what is included when a time period refers to an event. They also give specific exclusions: captions alone, rehearsals, sound checks, behind-the-scenes content, and unofficial recordings unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. None of those exclusions is this case. The GovInfo transcript is an official public presidential record of an event-site reporter exchange, not a rehearsal or sound check.\n\nDefendant’s best argument is that ordinary events have start times. True. But this market dispute is about public remarks at the venue immediately before the formal program, in the official context of the Draw, where the market and rules did not clearly define a noon-only boundary. If Kalshi wanted that narrower rule, it could have said so in the strike, the market title, or the event inclusion language. It did not.\n\nThe preponderance record therefore shows: Ronaldo was spoken; the remarks were public and officially documented; they were at the Kennedy Center in the FIFA World Cup Draw setting; and the governing market language did not clearly exclude that immediately-before-program event context. The challenged No resolution depends on importing a formal commencement limitation that is absent from the market packet.\n\nFor that reason, the Ronaldo strike should resolve Yes.\n\n[defendant] Council members, the closing record is narrow and concrete.\n\nEveryone now agrees on the easy fact: Trump said \"Ronaldo.\" The official GovInfo transcript proves that. But the proposition is not simply that Trump said the word somewhere near the FIFA World Cup Draw. The proposition asks you to overturn Kalshi's No because remarks immediately before the formal program should count under a market asking what Trump would say \"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\" Plaintiff has not carried that burden.\n\nThe two strongest sources are official and aligned. GovInfo, in DX-1, titles the relevant document \"Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw.\" It notes that the President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the Kennedy Center. FIFA, in DX-2, states that the Final Draw commenced at 12:00 local time. Those facts are not peripheral. They answer the timing question: the Ronaldo words were in a reporter exchange before the Draw began.\n\nPlaintiff's closing says the market did not specify \"after 12:00,\" \"during the televised draw program,\" or \"during the ball-drawing segment.\" True, but that does not prove Yes. The market did specify \"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\" The ordinary function of \"during\" is to define the event period, not to include anything public, official, and thematically related that happens beforehand. A 47-minute-before reporter exchange officially titled as prior to the Draw is outside that period unless the market or governing terms affirmatively include it. The record contains no such inclusion.\n\nThe governing terms reinforce that conclusion. They require the word to be said by the entity during the specified time period. They recognize event-based periods and allow the Exchange to specify event inclusions. They include official-presentation concepts for material presented as part of an event. But they do not say that pre-event press availability counts by default. Plaintiff's argument turns the absence of an exclusion into proof of inclusion. That is backwards under a preponderance standard.\n\nPlaintiff also leans on setting: Kennedy Center, FIFA World Cup subject matter, official transcript, public reporters. Those facts show why the issue is understandable. They do not move 11:13 into a 12:00 event. A source can be official and still describe something outside the event. Indeed, that is exactly what DX-1 does: it officially documents the remarks and officially labels them prior to the Draw.\n\nThe weaker evidence points the same way once weighed properly. The White House page capture does not include the video or transcript. The YouTube metadata is nonofficial and not an audio transcript. Neither overcomes GovInfo's title and timing note plus FIFA's commencement time.\n\nSo the final answer is simple: the word was spoken, but not during the countable event period shown by the best evidence. Plaintiff has not shown that Kalshi's No resolution was wrong. The council should reject the proposition and uphold No.\n\nExhibits:\n[plaintiff] PX-1 Market page packet: Ronaldo strike and challenged No resolution\nMarket URL: https://kalshi.com/markets/kxtrumpmentionb/trump-mention-b/kxtrumpmentionb-25dec06\n\nPublic market title: What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\n\nContract family: PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION\n\nStrike at issue: Ronaldo\n\nChallenged resolution: No\n\nRequested resolution: Yes\n\n\n[plaintiff] PX-2 Governing PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION terms\n                                         NEWMENTION\n\nScope: These rules shall apply to this contract.\n\nUnderlying: The Underlying for this Contract is words used by <entity> <time period>.\nRevisions to the Underlying made after Expiration will not be accounted for in determining the\nExpiration Value.\n\nSource Agency: The Source Agencies are <source>.\n\nType: The type of Contract is an Event Contract.\n\nIssuance: After the initial Contract, Contract iterations will be listed on an as-needed basis at\nthe discretion of the Exchange and corresponding to the risk management needs of Members.\n\n<entity>: <entity> refers to the speaker, writer, performer, or communicator specified by the\nExchange. This may include (but is not limited to): a specific named individual, multiple\nindividuals specified using AND/OR logic, an individual identified by position or title, a group,\nband, team or collective entity, a specified member or members of a group, an organization,\ncompany, or institutional entity, or any combination of the aforementioned.\n\nWhen <entity> is defined by a position or title, the Contract tracks whoever holds that position\nduring <time period>, even if the individual holding the position changes. When <entity> is a\nspecific named individual, the identity remains consistent throughout. Name changes (e.g.,\nstage names, married names) do not create a new entity. When <entity> is a group or\norganization and the Contract does not specify particular members, any official\ncommunication or statement by any member or designated spokesperson counts. When using\nAND logic, all specified entities must independently say <word> during <time period>. When\nusing OR logic, at least one of the specified entities must say <word> during <time period>.\nThe Exchange may specify additional conditions such as “at least X members of” a group or\n“the majority of” a group.\n\n<source>: <source> refers to a Source Agency or ordered collection of Source Agencies\nspecified by the Exchange at the time of Contract listing, which will be incorporated into the\nSource Agency hierarchy above and used to determine the occurrence of the Underlying.\n<source> may refer to a singular agency, multiple agencies, an agency by distinguishing\ncharacteristics, by category or type (e.g., “official government statistical body,” “primary wire\nservice”), or any combination thereof. When multiple agencies are specified, they may be\napplied in the hierarchical order designated by the Exchange if so specified, with the highest-\nranked available and responsive agency taking precedence for purposes of determining the\nExpiration Value. A lower-ranked agency shall only be consulted if all higher-ranked agencies\nare unavailable, unresponsive, have not reported on the Underlying by the Expiration time, or\nif the Exchange, in its sole discretion, determines that a higher-ranked agency’s reporting is\nincomplete, erroneous, or otherwise insufficient to determine the Expiration Value. If <source>\ndesignates multiple agencies without specifying a hierarchical order, the Exchange shall\nresolve any conflict between reporting agencies at its sole discretion.\n\n<word>: <word> refers to the particular word or phrase potentially to be mentioned by\n<entity>. It may refer to a word being said a minimum number of times. It may also refer to\none of multiple words/phrases, any of which are acceptable (e.g., “Doge/Dogecoin”).\n\f<time period>: <time period> refers to a specific range of time, event or discrete date and\ntime specified by the Exchange. This may be defined by, but is not limited to: a specific event\nor context (e.g., “during the State of the Union address”), exact dates or times, relative time\nmarkers (e.g., “before July 1, 2027,” “in Q1 2026”), event-based periods (e.g., “during any\ncampaign rally in October 2026,” “during the awards ceremony”), and broader intervals (e.g.,\n“Q1–Q2 2027,” “January–March 2026”).\n\nUnless stated otherwise, “Between” is inclusive of both endpoints, while “before” and “after”\nexclude the specified date. <time period> may also refer to “Any” or “None”, to multiple dates\n(even if non-consecutive), or to a singular and discrete date or time.\n\nWhen <time period> refers to a specific event (such as an address, speech, performance, or\nbroadcast), the Exchange may specify what is included, including whether it includes both live\nand pre-recorded segments (including whether advertisements are included). Where a\ntimezone is not specified, ET is assumed.\n\n\nPayout Criterion: The Payout Criterion for the Contract encompasses the Expiration Values that\n<word> is said by <entity> <time period>.\n\n\nThe word must appear as a distinct, standalone unit, not buried inside another word. Plural\nand possessive noun forms count. Other grammatical changes (tense, conjugation, derivation)\ndo not. If <word> appears separated from other words by a space or hyphen or in a\ncompound form with a space or hyphen, it counts. If <word> is fused into a single\nunhyphenated word, it does not count.\n\nIf <time period> refers to an event and that event is cancelled, and the market contains a\nstrike stating “Event does not qualify/occur”, such a strike shall resolve “Yes” and all others\n“No”. If <time period> refers to an event and that event is cancelled but such strikes are NOT\nlisted, the Contracts will resolve to the last fair price determined at the discretion of the\nExchange. If the event is postponed, and such a postponement is announced by the end of the\nfollowing calendar day to be rescheduled to a time within 14 calendar days, the markets shall\nremain open. If the event captured in <time period> is a live-stream or broadcast, the\nExchange may keep the market open for 24 hours for the release of an official recording.\nFurther granular details on conditions for these Contracts is available below.\n\nAdditional clarification(s):\n\n     Possessive noun forms of <word>, plurals, and possessive plural noun forms are\n     INCLUDED:\n          <word> is “Immigrant” → “Immigrants” counts\n          <word> is “Egg” → “eggs’ shells” counts\n          <word> is “Russia” → “Russia’s” counts, “Russian” does not\n     If <word> exists only in adjective form, no plural form exists:\n          <word> is “Economic” → “Economics” does not count (“Economic” is an adjective\n          for which “Economics” is not a plural)\n     Plural nouns occurring within proper nouns and noun phrases are included:\n          <word> is “Cat” → “Cats the musical” counts\n\f    Grammatical variations beyond plurals/possessives are NOT included:\n         <word> is “Immigrant” → “Immigration” does NOT count\n         <word> is “Run” → “Running” or “Ran” do NOT count\n    When <word> specifies a plural form, the singular does NOT count:\n         <word> is “Veterans” → “Veteran” does NOT count\n    Words that are spelled the same as the plural form of <word> (if such exists) but are\n    themselves not a plural noun are included:\n         <word> is “Wind” → “Winds up the clock” counts\n         <word> is “Border” → “The United States has strong borders” counts\n    Open compounds (words separated by spaces) count:\n         <word> is “fire” → “fire station” counts\n         <word> is “couch” → “couch potato” counts\n    Hyphenated compounds (words connected by hyphens) count:\n         <word> is “Palestine” → “pro-Palestine” counts\n         <word> is “fat” → “non-fat” counts\n    Closed compounds (single word, no spaces/hyphens) do not count:\n         <word> is “fire” → “wildfire” does not count\n         <word> is “fire” → “firefighter” does not count\n    Multi-word <word> in larger constructions: When <word> is a multi-word phrase\n    appearing within a hyphenated construction, it counts only if <word> appears as a\n    complete, unmodified element:\n         <word> is “New York” → “New York-based” counts (complete element)\n    Portmanteaus (words blended from two words where parts of each are combined) are\n    NOT included unless the portmanteau clearly contains <word> as a distinct, unaltered\n    element:\n         <word> is “MAGA” → “MAGA-nificent” counts (MAGA appears as distinct element)\n         <word> is “magnificent” → “MAGA-nificent” does NOT count (portmanteau blend)\n\nDictionary determination: Both the Merriam-Webster Dictionary (available online) AND the\nOxford English Dictionary shall be used to determine compound type and/or conventional\nspelling patterns. Inclusion in either dictionary as an open or hyphenated compound shall\nsatisfy the Payout Criterion. If neither provides clarity (or the word is not included),\ndetermination is based on whether written as single unit (closed/doesn’t count) vs. spaces or\nhyphens (open or hyphenated/counts) and/or context and previous usage.\n\nPHONETIC EQUIVALENCIES\n\n    Homophones (same sound, different spelling) do not count:\n        <word> is “write” → “right” does not count\n    Homonyms and homographs (same spelling) COUNT regardless of meaning or\n    pronunciation:\n        <word> is “bass” → both “bass guitar” and “bass fishing” count\n    Proper and common nouns are treated identically:\n        <word> is “Apple” → both “Apple Inc.” and “apple” (fruit) count\n        <word> is “Will” → both “Will Smith” and “I will go” count\n    Minor unintentional mispronunciations COUNT if context makes intent clear:\n        <word> is “Mamdani” → “Mandani” counts\n    Severe mispronunciations that make <word> unrecognizable do NOT count.\n    Trademarked spellings do not count, even when pronounced identically, unless the word\n\fitself is the same:\n      <word> is “lift” → “Lyft” (pronounced “lift”) does not count\n      <word> is “uber” → “Uber” counts\nWords with non-standard transliteration to English count within reason, provided they are\nphonetically equivalent:\n      <word> is “Zelensky” → any of “Zelenski,” “Zelenskii,” “Zelensky,” or “Zelenskiy”\n      count if pronounced equivalently\nContractions do not count for their constituent words unless otherwise explicitly specified\nby the Exchange:\n      <word> is “not” → “won’t,” “can’t,” “don’t,” “isn’t” do not count\nNumbers spoken as words COUNT, when spoken exactly (not part of a larger number):\n      <word> is “five” → saying “five” or reading “$5” aloud as “five dollars” counts,\n      saying “five hundred” does NOT count\n      <word> is “410” → “four hundred ten”, “four one zero” or “four ten” counts\nOrdinals COUNT when <word> is written numerically OR a phrase that includes a\nnumber:\n      <word> is “January 6” → “January 6th” counts\n      <word> is “3” (written numerically) → “3rd” (spoken as “third”) counts\n      <word> is “Eight War” → “8 Wars” and “Eighth War” will count\nCardinal and ordinal number words are distinct:\n      <word> is “one” → “first” does NOT count\n      <word> is “first” → “one” does NOT count\nAcronyms and abbreviations count when pronunciation or letter-by-letter spelling\nmatches <word>:\n      <word> is “NASA” → “NASA” (pronounced “NAH-suh”) counts\n      <word> is “NASA” → “N-A-S-A” (spelled out) counts\nAcronyms and abbreviations count as <word> when pronounced as the full word:\n      <word> is “Doctor” → “Dr.” (pronounced “Doctor”) counts\nExpanded forms of acronyms do NOT count:\n      <word> is “AI” → “artificial intelligence” does not count\nWords in foreign languages do NOT count unless they are perfect cognates with an\nEnglish word:\n      <word> is “fire” → “fuego” (Spanish) does NOT count\nEnglish words within foreign sentences count:\n      <word> is “policy” → “Nuestra policy es clara” counts\n<word> in organization/company names counts:\n      <word> is “Securities” → “Bank of America Securities” counts\nWords in URLs, emails, handles, and hashtags (exclusive of domain structure, email\nprovider or symbols) are treated as compounds when spoken as complete words, with the\ntype of compound subject to aforementioned rules:\n      <word> is “fire” → “firestation.com” pronounced “fire station dot com” counts\n      <word> is “fire” → “wildfire.com” pronounced “wildfire dot com” does NOT count\n      <word> is “apple” → “apple.com” pronounced “apple dot com” does count\n      When presented in URL, email, handle, or hashtag form, <word> shall be treated as\n      a compound, not a multi-word word\nSung, rapped, or poetic words COUNT if phonetically recognizable:\n      <word> is “money” → “moneyyy” (extended in rap) counts\n      Extreme distortion making <word> unrecognizable does NOT count.\nPhonetic alphabet spelling (“Foxtrot India Romeo Echo” for “FIRE”) does NOT count.\n\fCANCELLATIONS AND DELAYS\n\n   The Exchange may list an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike for any Contract. If listed,\n   such a strike refers to the structural conditions of the market, and is NOT adjudicated as a\n   <word> needing to be said by or validated by having been said by <entity>. If listed, this\n   strike resolves to “Yes” whenever the event fails to occur or qualify under the Payout\n   Criterion, or any other circumstance prevents normal resolution.\n   If no such strike is listed, and <time period> refers to a specific event, the following rules\n   apply if the event is cancelled, postponed, rescheduled, or materially altered (including\n   being closed to press) such that no video is released within one calendar day of the\n   original start time of the event:\n         If the event is cancelled, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price determined in\n         the sole discretion of the Exchange.\n         If the event is postponed or rescheduled, the outcome depends on whether a new\n         date is publicly announced within one calendar day (i.e. if the event was scheduled\n         to begin on Monday, any time up to 11:59PM on Tuesday falls within this period) of\n         the originally scheduled start time:\n               If no new date is announced within one calendar day, the Contract will resolve\n               to the last fair price determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\n               If a new date is announced within one calendar day, the outcome depends on\n               when the rescheduled event is set to occur:\n                     If the rescheduled date falls within fourteen (14) calendar days of the\n                     originally scheduled date, the Contract shall remain open and <word>\n                     stated during the rescheduled event will count.\n                           The fourteen-day window begins at 12:00 AM ET on the originally\n                           scheduled date and ends at 11:59 PM ET fourteen days later, unless\n                           an alternate timezone is explicitly specified.\n                           Example: <time period> is “during the State of the Union on January\n                           15, 2026” rescheduled to January 20, 2026 → words spoken during\n                           the rescheduled address count.\n                     If the rescheduled date falls more than fourteen (14) calendar days after\n                     the originally scheduled date, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price\n                     determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\n         Any Contract that cannot be resolved through the Source Agency hierarchy will\n         instead be settled at the Last Fair Price. The Exchange will disclose the methodology\n         used to determine the Last Fair Price (e.g., Last Traded Price, Time-Weighted\n         Average Price) at the time of Issuance.\n         If an event begins but is interrupted, abbreviated, or ends prematurely, words\n         stated by <entity> during the portion of the event that did occur will count and the\n         market will otherwise resolve.\n   If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window but the venue, format, or medium\n   changes (e.g., moved to a different location, changed from in-person to virtual (with the\n   exception of being closed to press)), words stated during the event will count.\n   Special condition: Across both cases, whether an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike is\n   listed or not, if the event specified as or in <time period> is a live-stream or broadcast (or\n   relayed as such) but the live stream/broadcast does not occur, the Exchange will instead\n   use an officially released recording as the Underlying, and may delay resolution by up to\n   one calendar day to allow for the release of such a recording.\n\f          If partial snippets are released, Contracts on words that do not appear will be\n          resolved to last fair price, and Contracts on those that do will be resolved to “Yes”.\n          If no recording is released, the relevant outcomes triggered by the\n          presence/absence of an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike shall occur as outlined\n          above.\n\nTECHNICAL DETAILS (UNLESS OTHERWISE SPECIFIED)\n\n     When <time period> refers to a specific event, pre-recorded content broadcast,\n     streamed, or published as part of that event is included if presented as part of the official\n     presentation.\n          Example: <time period> is “during the concert” with pre-recorded video interlude\n          where entity speaks → words from interlude count\n          Example: <time period> is “during the television appearance” with pre-taped\n          segment aired during broadcast → words from segment count\n     Behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are NOT\n     included unless officially broadcast or published as part of <time period>.\n     Subtitles and captions that display <word> on screen but are not spoken aloud by\n     <entity> do NOT count.\n     Sign language interpretation or usage by entity does NOT count as saying <word> unless\n     the Contract explicitly specifies that sign language counts.\n     Text that entity displays on screen (presentation slides, teleprompter visible to audience,\n     signatures) does NOT count unless entity reads it aloud.\n     Content generated by AI, deepfakes, or synthetic voice technology impersonating entity\n     does NOT count unless the synthetic content is officially commissioned, authorized, or\n     published by entity, OR the Contract explicitly specifies that AI-generated content counts.\n     If <word> is muted due to technical failure or censorship it shall not count unless\n     corroborating contextual evidence (including surrounding speech, or an official\n     uncensored recording or transcript) confirms that <entity> specifically uttered <word>\n     during the muted period.\n\nMinimum Tick: The Minimum Tick size for the Contract shall be $0.01.\n\nPosition Accountability Level: The Position Accountability Level for the Contract shall be\n$25,000 per strike, per Member.\n\nLast Trading Date: The Last Trading Date of the Contract will be the Expiration Date. The Last\nTrading Time will be the Expiration time.\n\nSettlement Date: The Settlement Date of the Contract shall be no later than the day after the\nExpiration Date, unless the Market Outcome is under review pursuant to Rule 7.1.\n\nExpiration Date: When <time period> refers to a specific event: The latest Expiration Date of\nthe Contract shall be fourteen (14) calendar days after the originally scheduled date of the\nevent. If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window, expiration will be moved to an\nearlier date and time in accordance with Rule 7.2. When <time period> is defined by specific\ndates: The latest Expiration Date of the Contract shall be two weeks after the end of <time\nperiod>. If an event described in the Payout Criterion occurs and a consensus has been\nreached on all terms, then expiration will be moved to an earlier date and time in accordance\nwith Rule 7.2.\n\fExpiration time: The Expiration time of the Contract shall be 10:00 AM ET.\n\nSettlement Value: The Settlement Value for this Contract is $1.00.\n\nExpiration Value: The Expiration Value is the value of the Underlying as documented by the\nSource Agency on the Expiration Date at the Expiration time.\n\nContingencies: Before Settlement, Kalshi may, at its sole discretion, initiate the Market\nOutcome Review Process pursuant to Rule 7.1 of the Rulebook. If an Expiration Value cannot\nbe determined on the Expiration Date, Kalshi has the right to determine payouts pursuant to\nRule 7.1 in the Rulebook.\n\f\n\n[plaintiff] PX-3 Official White House World Cup Drawing video page capture\nSource capture from official White House page https://www.whitehouse.gov/videos/president-trump-attends-the-fifa-world-cup-drawing/\nRetrieval: 2026-06-29T21:52:12Z via OpenClaw web_fetch and web.open.\n\nVisible page facts captured:\n- Page title: President Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing\n- Date shown on page: December 5, 2025\n- Page section: Videos\n- The page contains a link labeled View Full Video to Instagram.\n- Related video listed: FIFA World Cup 2026 Draw at The Kennedy Center, duration 00:45, dated December 6, 2025.\n- Related video listed: FIFA World Cup Drawing Announced to Take Place at The Kennedy Center, duration 00:56, dated August 23, 2025.\n- Related video listed: President Trump on the 2026 FIFA World Cup, duration 01:22, dated May 6, 2025.\n\nRelevant extracted lines from web.open capture:\nL142: Videos\nL143: # President Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing\nL145: December 5, 2025\nL133: ... View Full Video [instagram.com] ...\nL151: FIFA World Cup 2026 Draw at The Kennedy Center\nL153: December 6, 2025\nL167-L170: President Trump on the 2026 FIFA World Cup, May 6, 2025\n\nNotes on capture limits: readability extraction returned minimal content, so the above preserves visible lines from the page capture. The embedded/full video itself was not captured in this item.\n\n[plaintiff] PX-4 YouTube metadata capture for Ronaldo-at-FIFA-Draw clip\nSource capture: YouTube watch page https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Cb2yO0lLEnM\nVideo ID: Cb2yO0lLEnM\nRetrieval: 2026-06-29T21:53:00Z via web search and curl of the YouTube watch page.\n\nCaptured title / page metadata:\n- Title shown in search and page metadata: Trump Talks Cristiano Ronaldo at FIFA Draw — ‘He’s a Great Person’\n- Channel shown in page metadata: interestingText You / @InterestingTextYou\n- Subscriber count shown in page metadata at capture: about 10.3K subscribers\n\nCaptured description text from YouTube page metadata:\n\"Trump Talks Cristiano Ronaldo at FIFA Draw — ‘He’s a Great Person’\n\nAt the FIFA World Cup Draw Ceremony, Donald Trump shared a story about meeting Cristiano Ronaldo at the White House. Trump said Ronaldo was “a great person” and even mentioned that Ronaldo spoke with his son about soccer during the visit.\n\nThis unexpected crossover between world politics and one of the biggest global sports stars quickly caught viewers' attention.\n\nTrump FIFA Draw\nDonald Trump FIFA World Cup\nTrump Cristiano Ronaldo\nCristiano Ronaldo Trump meeting\nFIFA World Cup draw 2026\nRonaldo White House visit\nTrump soccer comments\nWorld Cup trending 2025\nsports politics crossover\nCristiano Ronaldo story\nDonald Trump viral moment\nFIFA draw ceremony Trump\nWorld Cup 2026 news\nRonaldo fan reaction\npolitical celebrity moments\nviral sports clips 2025\nFIFA draw highlights\nTrump speech FIFA\nglobal sports news\"\n\nCapture limits and provenance caveat: direct video/caption extraction was attempted but YouTube transcript/open paths were throttled or unavailable in this environment. This item preserves the public watch-page metadata and description, not an independently extracted audio transcript. It is not an official White House or FIFA source.\n\n[defendant] DX-1 GovInfo official transcript: remarks prior to FIFA World Cup Draw\nSource: GovInfo, Compilation of Presidential Documents, DCPD202501162\nURL retrieved: https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/DCPD-202501162/html/DCPD-202501162.htm\nRetrieval time: 2026-06-29T22:00:00Z\nLocal captured HTML size/hash: 51,571 bytes; SHA-256 eadbceeecf3e94f5bd423bcb8e8511165fdc7265dd8c1e025870c2e8f34dfd99\n\nMaterial captured text from official GovInfo HTML/web.open:\n\nAdministration of Donald J. Trump, 2025\n\nTitle: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\nDate: December 5, 2025\n\nOpening note: [The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\n\nExcerpt - The President's Interest in Soccer (web.open lines 196-203):\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\"football,\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\n\nExcerpt - The President's Interest in Soccer (web.open lines 322-329):\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\nThe President. But they have a little more speed. But no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\n\nTiming/context note (web.open lines 461-462):\nNOTE: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. In his remarks, he referred to Trey Yingst, chief foreign correspondent, Fox News Channel; Cristiano Ronaldo, forward for Saudi Pro League club Al-Nass and Portugal's national soccer team; and Lionel Messi, forward for Major League Soccer club Inter Miami and Argentina's national team. A reporter referred to New York State Attorney General Letitia James.\nThe transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\n\nDocument category/location/name/subject metadata (web.open lines 463-468):\nCategories: Interviews With the News Media: Exchanges with reporters, Washington, DC.\nLocations: Washington, DC.\nNames include: Cristiano Ronaldo and Lionel Messi.\nSubjects include: Federation Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) World Cup; John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts; News media, Presidential interviews; Soccer.\nDCPD Number: DCPD202501162.\n\nCapture limits: This item is a focused text capture of the material official transcript title, Ronaldo excerpts, timing/correction note, and metadata. It is not a full video or audio artifact. The official transcript itself notes some portions could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\n\n[defendant] DX-2 FIFA official Final Draw start-time capture\nSource: FIFA official page, FIFA World Cup 2026 Final Draw\nURL: https://www.fifa.com/en/tournaments/mens/worldcup/canadamexicousa2026/live-draw\nRetrieval time: 2026-06-29T22:01:00Z\n\nMaterial captured text from web search/open result:\n- Page title/source: FIFA World Cup 2026™ Final Draw\n- The draw takes place at the Kennedy Center in Washington DC, USA.\n- The draw commences at 12:00 local time (17:00 UTC) on Friday 5 December 2025.\n\nCapture limits: This is a focused text capture of the official FIFA page timing statement located by web search. It is not a video capture of the draw ceremony.\n\n[defendant] DX-3 Governing PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION terms\n                                         NEWMENTION\n\nScope: These rules shall apply to this contract.\n\nUnderlying: The Underlying for this Contract is words used by <entity> <time period>.\nRevisions to the Underlying made after Expiration will not be accounted for in determining the\nExpiration Value.\n\nSource Agency: The Source Agencies are <source>.\n\nType: The type of Contract is an Event Contract.\n\nIssuance: After the initial Contract, Contract iterations will be listed on an as-needed basis at\nthe discretion of the Exchange and corresponding to the risk management needs of Members.\n\n<entity>: <entity> refers to the speaker, writer, performer, or communicator specified by the\nExchange. This may include (but is not limited to): a specific named individual, multiple\nindividuals specified using AND/OR logic, an individual identified by position or title, a group,\nband, team or collective entity, a specified member or members of a group, an organization,\ncompany, or institutional entity, or any combination of the aforementioned.\n\nWhen <entity> is defined by a position or title, the Contract tracks whoever holds that position\nduring <time period>, even if the individual holding the position changes. When <entity> is a\nspecific named individual, the identity remains consistent throughout. Name changes (e.g.,\nstage names, married names) do not create a new entity. When <entity> is a group or\norganization and the Contract does not specify particular members, any official\ncommunication or statement by any member or designated spokesperson counts. When using\nAND logic, all specified entities must independently say <word> during <time period>. When\nusing OR logic, at least one of the specified entities must say <word> during <time period>.\nThe Exchange may specify additional conditions such as “at least X members of” a group or\n“the majority of” a group.\n\n<source>: <source> refers to a Source Agency or ordered collection of Source Agencies\nspecified by the Exchange at the time of Contract listing, which will be incorporated into the\nSource Agency hierarchy above and used to determine the occurrence of the Underlying.\n<source> may refer to a singular agency, multiple agencies, an agency by distinguishing\ncharacteristics, by category or type (e.g., “official government statistical body,” “primary wire\nservice”), or any combination thereof. When multiple agencies are specified, they may be\napplied in the hierarchical order designated by the Exchange if so specified, with the highest-\nranked available and responsive agency taking precedence for purposes of determining the\nExpiration Value. A lower-ranked agency shall only be consulted if all higher-ranked agencies\nare unavailable, unresponsive, have not reported on the Underlying by the Expiration time, or\nif the Exchange, in its sole discretion, determines that a higher-ranked agency’s reporting is\nincomplete, erroneous, or otherwise insufficient to determine the Expiration Value. If <source>\ndesignates multiple agencies without specifying a hierarchical order, the Exchange shall\nresolve any conflict between reporting agencies at its sole discretion.\n\n<word>: <word> refers to the particular word or phrase potentially to be mentioned by\n<entity>. It may refer to a word being said a minimum number of times. It may also refer to\none of multiple words/phrases, any of which are acceptable (e.g., “Doge/Dogecoin”).\n\f<time period>: <time period> refers to a specific range of time, event or discrete date and\ntime specified by the Exchange. This may be defined by, but is not limited to: a specific event\nor context (e.g., “during the State of the Union address”), exact dates or times, relative time\nmarkers (e.g., “before July 1, 2027,” “in Q1 2026”), event-based periods (e.g., “during any\ncampaign rally in October 2026,” “during the awards ceremony”), and broader intervals (e.g.,\n“Q1–Q2 2027,” “January–March 2026”).\n\nUnless stated otherwise, “Between” is inclusive of both endpoints, while “before” and “after”\nexclude the specified date. <time period> may also refer to “Any” or “None”, to multiple dates\n(even if non-consecutive), or to a singular and discrete date or time.\n\nWhen <time period> refers to a specific event (such as an address, speech, performance, or\nbroadcast), the Exchange may specify what is included, including whether it includes both live\nand pre-recorded segments (including whether advertisements are included). Where a\ntimezone is not specified, ET is assumed.\n\n\nPayout Criterion: The Payout Criterion for the Contract encompasses the Expiration Values that\n<word> is said by <entity> <time period>.\n\n\nThe word must appear as a distinct, standalone unit, not buried inside another word. Plural\nand possessive noun forms count. Other grammatical changes (tense, conjugation, derivation)\ndo not. If <word> appears separated from other words by a space or hyphen or in a\ncompound form with a space or hyphen, it counts. If <word> is fused into a single\nunhyphenated word, it does not count.\n\nIf <time period> refers to an event and that event is cancelled, and the market contains a\nstrike stating “Event does not qualify/occur”, such a strike shall resolve “Yes” and all others\n“No”. If <time period> refers to an event and that event is cancelled but such strikes are NOT\nlisted, the Contracts will resolve to the last fair price determined at the discretion of the\nExchange. If the event is postponed, and such a postponement is announced by the end of the\nfollowing calendar day to be rescheduled to a time within 14 calendar days, the markets shall\nremain open. If the event captured in <time period> is a live-stream or broadcast, the\nExchange may keep the market open for 24 hours for the release of an official recording.\nFurther granular details on conditions for these Contracts is available below.\n\nAdditional clarification(s):\n\n     Possessive noun forms of <word>, plurals, and possessive plural noun forms are\n     INCLUDED:\n          <word> is “Immigrant” → “Immigrants” counts\n          <word> is “Egg” → “eggs’ shells” counts\n          <word> is “Russia” → “Russia’s” counts, “Russian” does not\n     If <word> exists only in adjective form, no plural form exists:\n          <word> is “Economic” → “Economics” does not count (“Economic” is an adjective\n          for which “Economics” is not a plural)\n     Plural nouns occurring within proper nouns and noun phrases are included:\n          <word> is “Cat” → “Cats the musical” counts\n\f    Grammatical variations beyond plurals/possessives are NOT included:\n         <word> is “Immigrant” → “Immigration” does NOT count\n         <word> is “Run” → “Running” or “Ran” do NOT count\n    When <word> specifies a plural form, the singular does NOT count:\n         <word> is “Veterans” → “Veteran” does NOT count\n    Words that are spelled the same as the plural form of <word> (if such exists) but are\n    themselves not a plural noun are included:\n         <word> is “Wind” → “Winds up the clock” counts\n         <word> is “Border” → “The United States has strong borders” counts\n    Open compounds (words separated by spaces) count:\n         <word> is “fire” → “fire station” counts\n         <word> is “couch” → “couch potato” counts\n    Hyphenated compounds (words connected by hyphens) count:\n         <word> is “Palestine” → “pro-Palestine” counts\n         <word> is “fat” → “non-fat” counts\n    Closed compounds (single word, no spaces/hyphens) do not count:\n         <word> is “fire” → “wildfire” does not count\n         <word> is “fire” → “firefighter” does not count\n    Multi-word <word> in larger constructions: When <word> is a multi-word phrase\n    appearing within a hyphenated construction, it counts only if <word> appears as a\n    complete, unmodified element:\n         <word> is “New York” → “New York-based” counts (complete element)\n    Portmanteaus (words blended from two words where parts of each are combined) are\n    NOT included unless the portmanteau clearly contains <word> as a distinct, unaltered\n    element:\n         <word> is “MAGA” → “MAGA-nificent” counts (MAGA appears as distinct element)\n         <word> is “magnificent” → “MAGA-nificent” does NOT count (portmanteau blend)\n\nDictionary determination: Both the Merriam-Webster Dictionary (available online) AND the\nOxford English Dictionary shall be used to determine compound type and/or conventional\nspelling patterns. Inclusion in either dictionary as an open or hyphenated compound shall\nsatisfy the Payout Criterion. If neither provides clarity (or the word is not included),\ndetermination is based on whether written as single unit (closed/doesn’t count) vs. spaces or\nhyphens (open or hyphenated/counts) and/or context and previous usage.\n\nPHONETIC EQUIVALENCIES\n\n    Homophones (same sound, different spelling) do not count:\n        <word> is “write” → “right” does not count\n    Homonyms and homographs (same spelling) COUNT regardless of meaning or\n    pronunciation:\n        <word> is “bass” → both “bass guitar” and “bass fishing” count\n    Proper and common nouns are treated identically:\n        <word> is “Apple” → both “Apple Inc.” and “apple” (fruit) count\n        <word> is “Will” → both “Will Smith” and “I will go” count\n    Minor unintentional mispronunciations COUNT if context makes intent clear:\n        <word> is “Mamdani” → “Mandani” counts\n    Severe mispronunciations that make <word> unrecognizable do NOT count.\n    Trademarked spellings do not count, even when pronounced identically, unless the word\n\fitself is the same:\n      <word> is “lift” → “Lyft” (pronounced “lift”) does not count\n      <word> is “uber” → “Uber” counts\nWords with non-standard transliteration to English count within reason, provided they are\nphonetically equivalent:\n      <word> is “Zelensky” → any of “Zelenski,” “Zelenskii,” “Zelensky,” or “Zelenskiy”\n      count if pronounced equivalently\nContractions do not count for their constituent words unless otherwise explicitly specified\nby the Exchange:\n      <word> is “not” → “won’t,” “can’t,” “don’t,” “isn’t” do not count\nNumbers spoken as words COUNT, when spoken exactly (not part of a larger number):\n      <word> is “five” → saying “five” or reading “$5” aloud as “five dollars” counts,\n      saying “five hundred” does NOT count\n      <word> is “410” → “four hundred ten”, “four one zero” or “four ten” counts\nOrdinals COUNT when <word> is written numerically OR a phrase that includes a\nnumber:\n      <word> is “January 6” → “January 6th” counts\n      <word> is “3” (written numerically) → “3rd” (spoken as “third”) counts\n      <word> is “Eight War” → “8 Wars” and “Eighth War” will count\nCardinal and ordinal number words are distinct:\n      <word> is “one” → “first” does NOT count\n      <word> is “first” → “one” does NOT count\nAcronyms and abbreviations count when pronunciation or letter-by-letter spelling\nmatches <word>:\n      <word> is “NASA” → “NASA” (pronounced “NAH-suh”) counts\n      <word> is “NASA” → “N-A-S-A” (spelled out) counts\nAcronyms and abbreviations count as <word> when pronounced as the full word:\n      <word> is “Doctor” → “Dr.” (pronounced “Doctor”) counts\nExpanded forms of acronyms do NOT count:\n      <word> is “AI” → “artificial intelligence” does not count\nWords in foreign languages do NOT count unless they are perfect cognates with an\nEnglish word:\n      <word> is “fire” → “fuego” (Spanish) does NOT count\nEnglish words within foreign sentences count:\n      <word> is “policy” → “Nuestra policy es clara” counts\n<word> in organization/company names counts:\n      <word> is “Securities” → “Bank of America Securities” counts\nWords in URLs, emails, handles, and hashtags (exclusive of domain structure, email\nprovider or symbols) are treated as compounds when spoken as complete words, with the\ntype of compound subject to aforementioned rules:\n      <word> is “fire” → “firestation.com” pronounced “fire station dot com” counts\n      <word> is “fire” → “wildfire.com” pronounced “wildfire dot com” does NOT count\n      <word> is “apple” → “apple.com” pronounced “apple dot com” does count\n      When presented in URL, email, handle, or hashtag form, <word> shall be treated as\n      a compound, not a multi-word word\nSung, rapped, or poetic words COUNT if phonetically recognizable:\n      <word> is “money” → “moneyyy” (extended in rap) counts\n      Extreme distortion making <word> unrecognizable does NOT count.\nPhonetic alphabet spelling (“Foxtrot India Romeo Echo” for “FIRE”) does NOT count.\n\fCANCELLATIONS AND DELAYS\n\n   The Exchange may list an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike for any Contract. If listed,\n   such a strike refers to the structural conditions of the market, and is NOT adjudicated as a\n   <word> needing to be said by or validated by having been said by <entity>. If listed, this\n   strike resolves to “Yes” whenever the event fails to occur or qualify under the Payout\n   Criterion, or any other circumstance prevents normal resolution.\n   If no such strike is listed, and <time period> refers to a specific event, the following rules\n   apply if the event is cancelled, postponed, rescheduled, or materially altered (including\n   being closed to press) such that no video is released within one calendar day of the\n   original start time of the event:\n         If the event is cancelled, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price determined in\n         the sole discretion of the Exchange.\n         If the event is postponed or rescheduled, the outcome depends on whether a new\n         date is publicly announced within one calendar day (i.e. if the event was scheduled\n         to begin on Monday, any time up to 11:59PM on Tuesday falls within this period) of\n         the originally scheduled start time:\n               If no new date is announced within one calendar day, the Contract will resolve\n               to the last fair price determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\n               If a new date is announced within one calendar day, the outcome depends on\n               when the rescheduled event is set to occur:\n                     If the rescheduled date falls within fourteen (14) calendar days of the\n                     originally scheduled date, the Contract shall remain open and <word>\n                     stated during the rescheduled event will count.\n                           The fourteen-day window begins at 12:00 AM ET on the originally\n                           scheduled date and ends at 11:59 PM ET fourteen days later, unless\n                           an alternate timezone is explicitly specified.\n                           Example: <time period> is “during the State of the Union on January\n                           15, 2026” rescheduled to January 20, 2026 → words spoken during\n                           the rescheduled address count.\n                     If the rescheduled date falls more than fourteen (14) calendar days after\n                     the originally scheduled date, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price\n                     determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\n         Any Contract that cannot be resolved through the Source Agency hierarchy will\n         instead be settled at the Last Fair Price. The Exchange will disclose the methodology\n         used to determine the Last Fair Price (e.g., Last Traded Price, Time-Weighted\n         Average Price) at the time of Issuance.\n         If an event begins but is interrupted, abbreviated, or ends prematurely, words\n         stated by <entity> during the portion of the event that did occur will count and the\n         market will otherwise resolve.\n   If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window but the venue, format, or medium\n   changes (e.g., moved to a different location, changed from in-person to virtual (with the\n   exception of being closed to press)), words stated during the event will count.\n   Special condition: Across both cases, whether an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike is\n   listed or not, if the event specified as or in <time period> is a live-stream or broadcast (or\n   relayed as such) but the live stream/broadcast does not occur, the Exchange will instead\n   use an officially released recording as the Underlying, and may delay resolution by up to\n   one calendar day to allow for the release of such a recording.\n\f          If partial snippets are released, Contracts on words that do not appear will be\n          resolved to last fair price, and Contracts on those that do will be resolved to “Yes”.\n          If no recording is released, the relevant outcomes triggered by the\n          presence/absence of an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike shall occur as outlined\n          above.\n\nTECHNICAL DETAILS (UNLESS OTHERWISE SPECIFIED)\n\n     When <time period> refers to a specific event, pre-recorded content broadcast,\n     streamed, or published as part of that event is included if presented as part of the official\n     presentation.\n          Example: <time period> is “during the concert” with pre-recorded video interlude\n          where entity speaks → words from interlude count\n          Example: <time period> is “during the television appearance” with pre-taped\n          segment aired during broadcast → words from segment count\n     Behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are NOT\n     included unless officially broadcast or published as part of <time period>.\n     Subtitles and captions that display <word> on screen but are not spoken aloud by\n     <entity> do NOT count.\n     Sign language interpretation or usage by entity does NOT count as saying <word> unless\n     the Contract explicitly specifies that sign language counts.\n     Text that entity displays on screen (presentation slides, teleprompter visible to audience,\n     signatures) does NOT count unless entity reads it aloud.\n     Content generated by AI, deepfakes, or synthetic voice technology impersonating entity\n     does NOT count unless the synthetic content is officially commissioned, authorized, or\n     published by entity, OR the Contract explicitly specifies that AI-generated content counts.\n     If <word> is muted due to technical failure or censorship it shall not count unless\n     corroborating contextual evidence (including surrounding speech, or an official\n     uncensored recording or transcript) confirms that <entity> specifically uttered <word>\n     during the muted period.\n\nMinimum Tick: The Minimum Tick size for the Contract shall be $0.01.\n\nPosition Accountability Level: The Position Accountability Level for the Contract shall be\n$25,000 per strike, per Member.\n\nLast Trading Date: The Last Trading Date of the Contract will be the Expiration Date. The Last\nTrading Time will be the Expiration time.\n\nSettlement Date: The Settlement Date of the Contract shall be no later than the day after the\nExpiration Date, unless the Market Outcome is under review pursuant to Rule 7.1.\n\nExpiration Date: When <time period> refers to a specific event: The latest Expiration Date of\nthe Contract shall be fourteen (14) calendar days after the originally scheduled date of the\nevent. If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window, expiration will be moved to an\nearlier date and time in accordance with Rule 7.2. When <time period> is defined by specific\ndates: The latest Expiration Date of the Contract shall be two weeks after the end of <time\nperiod>. If an event described in the Payout Criterion occurs and a consensus has been\nreached on all terms, then expiration will be moved to an earlier date and time in accordance\nwith Rule 7.2.\n\fExpiration time: The Expiration time of the Contract shall be 10:00 AM ET.\n\nSettlement Value: The Settlement Value for this Contract is $1.00.\n\nExpiration Value: The Expiration Value is the value of the Underlying as documented by the\nSource Agency on the Expiration Date at the Expiration time.\n\nContingencies: Before Settlement, Kalshi may, at its sole discretion, initiate the Market\nOutcome Review Process pursuant to Rule 7.1 of the Rulebook. If an Expiration Value cannot\nbe determined on the Expiration Date, Kalshi has the right to determine payouts pursuant to\nRule 7.1 in the Rulebook.\n\f\n\n[defendant] DX-4 Market packet: Ronaldo strike and challenged No resolution\nMarket URL: https://kalshi.com/markets/kxtrumpmentionb/trump-mention-b/kxtrumpmentionb-25dec06\n\nPublic market title: What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\n\nContract family: PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION\n\nStrike at issue: Ronaldo\n\nChallenged resolution: No\n\nRequested resolution: Yes\n\n\n[plaintiff] PX-R1 GovInfo transcript confirming Ronaldo utterances and Kennedy Center/FIFA Draw context\nSource: GovInfo, Compilation of Presidential Documents, DCPD202501162\nURL retrieved: https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/DCPD-202501162/html/DCPD-202501162.htm\nRetrieval time: 2026-06-29T22:00:00Z\nLocal captured HTML size/hash: 51,571 bytes; SHA-256 eadbceeecf3e94f5bd423bcb8e8511165fdc7265dd8c1e025870c2e8f34dfd99\n\nMaterial captured text from official GovInfo HTML/web.open:\n\nAdministration of Donald J. Trump, 2025\n\nTitle: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\nDate: December 5, 2025\n\nOpening note: [The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\n\nExcerpt - The President's Interest in Soccer (web.open lines 196-203):\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\"football,\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\n\nExcerpt - The President's Interest in Soccer (web.open lines 322-329):\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\nThe President. But they have a little more speed. But no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\n\nTiming/context note (web.open lines 461-462):\nNOTE: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. In his remarks, he referred to Trey Yingst, chief foreign correspondent, Fox News Channel; Cristiano Ronaldo, forward for Saudi Pro League club Al-Nass and Portugal's national soccer team; and Lionel Messi, forward for Major League Soccer club Inter Miami and Argentina's national team. A reporter referred to New York State Attorney General Letitia James.\nThe transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\n\nDocument category/location/name/subject metadata (web.open lines 463-468):\nCategories: Interviews With the News Media: Exchanges with reporters, Washington, DC.\nLocations: Washington, DC.\nNames include: Cristiano Ronaldo and Lionel Messi.\nSubjects include: Federation Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) World Cup; John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts; News media, Presidential interviews; Soccer.\nDCPD Number: DCPD202501162.\n\nCapture limits: This item is a focused text capture of the material official transcript title, Ronaldo excerpts, timing/correction note, and metadata. It is not a full video or audio artifact. The official transcript itself notes some portions could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\n\n[plaintiff] PX-R2 FIFA timing capture showing formal commencement time but not market-specific exclusion\nSource: FIFA official page, FIFA World Cup 2026 Final Draw\nURL: https://www.fifa.com/en/tournaments/mens/worldcup/canadamexicousa2026/live-draw\nRetrieval time: 2026-06-29T22:01:00Z\n\nMaterial captured text from web search/open result:\n- Page title/source: FIFA World Cup 2026™ Final Draw\n- The draw takes place at the Kennedy Center in Washington DC, USA.\n- The draw commences at 12:00 local time (17:00 UTC) on Friday 5 December 2025.\n\nCapture limits: This is a focused text capture of the official FIFA page timing statement located by web search. It is not a video capture of the draw ceremony.\n\n[plaintiff] PX-R3 Event-period terms and exclusions\n                                         NEWMENTION\n\nScope: These rules shall apply to this contract.\n\nUnderlying: The Underlying for this Contract is words used by <entity> <time period>.\nRevisions to the Underlying made after Expiration will not be accounted for in determining the\nExpiration Value.\n\nSource Agency: The Source Agencies are <source>.\n\nType: The type of Contract is an Event Contract.\n\nIssuance: After the initial Contract, Contract iterations will be listed on an as-needed basis at\nthe discretion of the Exchange and corresponding to the risk management needs of Members.\n\n<entity>: <entity> refers to the speaker, writer, performer, or communicator specified by the\nExchange. This may include (but is not limited to): a specific named individual, multiple\nindividuals specified using AND/OR logic, an individual identified by position or title, a group,\nband, team or collective entity, a specified member or members of a group, an organization,\ncompany, or institutional entity, or any combination of the aforementioned.\n\nWhen <entity> is defined by a position or title, the Contract tracks whoever holds that position\nduring <time period>, even if the individual holding the position changes. When <entity> is a\nspecific named individual, the identity remains consistent throughout. Name changes (e.g.,\nstage names, married names) do not create a new entity. When <entity> is a group or\norganization and the Contract does not specify particular members, any official\ncommunication or statement by any member or designated spokesperson counts. When using\nAND logic, all specified entities must independently say <word> during <time period>. When\nusing OR logic, at least one of the specified entities must say <word> during <time period>.\nThe Exchange may specify additional conditions such as “at least X members of” a group or\n“the majority of” a group.\n\n<source>: <source> refers to a Source Agency or ordered collection of Source Agencies\nspecified by the Exchange at the time of Contract listing, which will be incorporated into the\nSource Agency hierarchy above and used to determine the occurrence of the Underlying.\n<source> may refer to a singular agency, multiple agencies, an agency by distinguishing\ncharacteristics, by category or type (e.g., “official government statistical body,” “primary wire\nservice”), or any combination thereof. When multiple agencies are specified, they may be\napplied in the hierarchical order designated by the Exchange if so specified, with the highest-\nranked available and responsive agency taking precedence for purposes of determining the\nExpiration Value. A lower-ranked agency shall only be consulted if all higher-ranked agencies\nare unavailable, unresponsive, have not reported on the Underlying by the Expiration time, or\nif the Exchange, in its sole discretion, determines that a higher-ranked agency’s reporting is\nincomplete, erroneous, or otherwise insufficient to determine the Expiration Value. If <source>\ndesignates multiple agencies without specifying a hierarchical order, the Exchange shall\nresolve any conflict between reporting agencies at its sole discretion.\n\n<word>: <word> refers to the particular word or phrase potentially to be mentioned by\n<entity>. It may refer to a word being said a minimum number of times. It may also refer to\none of multiple words/phrases, any of which are acceptable (e.g., “Doge/Dogecoin”).\n\f<time period>: <time period> refers to a specific range of time, event or discrete date and\ntime specified by the Exchange. This may be defined by, but is not limited to: a specific event\nor context (e.g., “during the State of the Union address”), exact dates or times, relative time\nmarkers (e.g., “before July 1, 2027,” “in Q1 2026”), event-based periods (e.g., “during any\ncampaign rally in October 2026,” “during the awards ceremony”), and broader intervals (e.g.,\n“Q1–Q2 2027,” “January–March 2026”).\n\nUnless stated otherwise, “Between” is inclusive of both endpoints, while “before” and “after”\nexclude the specified date. <time period> may also refer to “Any” or “None”, to multiple dates\n(even if non-consecutive), or to a singular and discrete date or time.\n\nWhen <time period> refers to a specific event (such as an address, speech, performance, or\nbroadcast), the Exchange may specify what is included, including whether it includes both live\nand pre-recorded segments (including whether advertisements are included). Where a\ntimezone is not specified, ET is assumed.\n\n\nPayout Criterion: The Payout Criterion for the Contract encompasses the Expiration Values that\n<word> is said by <entity> <time period>.\n\n\nThe word must appear as a distinct, standalone unit, not buried inside another word. Plural\nand possessive noun forms count. Other grammatical changes (tense, conjugation, derivation)\ndo not. If <word> appears separated from other words by a space or hyphen or in a\ncompound form with a space or hyphen, it counts. If <word> is fused into a single\nunhyphenated word, it does not count.\n\nIf <time period> refers to an event and that event is cancelled, and the market contains a\nstrike stating “Event does not qualify/occur”, such a strike shall resolve “Yes” and all others\n“No”. If <time period> refers to an event and that event is cancelled but such strikes are NOT\nlisted, the Contracts will resolve to the last fair price determined at the discretion of the\nExchange. If the event is postponed, and such a postponement is announced by the end of the\nfollowing calendar day to be rescheduled to a time within 14 calendar days, the markets shall\nremain open. If the event captured in <time period> is a live-stream or broadcast, the\nExchange may keep the market open for 24 hours for the release of an official recording.\nFurther granular details on conditions for these Contracts is available below.\n\nAdditional clarification(s):\n\n     Possessive noun forms of <word>, plurals, and possessive plural noun forms are\n     INCLUDED:\n          <word> is “Immigrant” → “Immigrants” counts\n          <word> is “Egg” → “eggs’ shells” counts\n          <word> is “Russia” → “Russia’s” counts, “Russian” does not\n     If <word> exists only in adjective form, no plural form exists:\n          <word> is “Economic” → “Economics” does not count (“Economic” is an adjective\n          for which “Economics” is not a plural)\n     Plural nouns occurring within proper nouns and noun phrases are included:\n          <word> is “Cat” → “Cats the musical” counts\n\f    Grammatical variations beyond plurals/possessives are NOT included:\n         <word> is “Immigrant” → “Immigration” does NOT count\n         <word> is “Run” → “Running” or “Ran” do NOT count\n    When <word> specifies a plural form, the singular does NOT count:\n         <word> is “Veterans” → “Veteran” does NOT count\n    Words that are spelled the same as the plural form of <word> (if such exists) but are\n    themselves not a plural noun are included:\n         <word> is “Wind” → “Winds up the clock” counts\n         <word> is “Border” → “The United States has strong borders” counts\n    Open compounds (words separated by spaces) count:\n         <word> is “fire” → “fire station” counts\n         <word> is “couch” → “couch potato” counts\n    Hyphenated compounds (words connected by hyphens) count:\n         <word> is “Palestine” → “pro-Palestine” counts\n         <word> is “fat” → “non-fat” counts\n    Closed compounds (single word, no spaces/hyphens) do not count:\n         <word> is “fire” → “wildfire” does not count\n         <word> is “fire” → “firefighter” does not count\n    Multi-word <word> in larger constructions: When <word> is a multi-word phrase\n    appearing within a hyphenated construction, it counts only if <word> appears as a\n    complete, unmodified element:\n         <word> is “New York” → “New York-based” counts (complete element)\n    Portmanteaus (words blended from two words where parts of each are combined) are\n    NOT included unless the portmanteau clearly contains <word> as a distinct, unaltered\n    element:\n         <word> is “MAGA” → “MAGA-nificent” counts (MAGA appears as distinct element)\n         <word> is “magnificent” → “MAGA-nificent” does NOT count (portmanteau blend)\n\nDictionary determination: Both the Merriam-Webster Dictionary (available online) AND the\nOxford English Dictionary shall be used to determine compound type and/or conventional\nspelling patterns. Inclusion in either dictionary as an open or hyphenated compound shall\nsatisfy the Payout Criterion. If neither provides clarity (or the word is not included),\ndetermination is based on whether written as single unit (closed/doesn’t count) vs. spaces or\nhyphens (open or hyphenated/counts) and/or context and previous usage.\n\nPHONETIC EQUIVALENCIES\n\n    Homophones (same sound, different spelling) do not count:\n        <word> is “write” → “right” does not count\n    Homonyms and homographs (same spelling) COUNT regardless of meaning or\n    pronunciation:\n        <word> is “bass” → both “bass guitar” and “bass fishing” count\n    Proper and common nouns are treated identically:\n        <word> is “Apple” → both “Apple Inc.” and “apple” (fruit) count\n        <word> is “Will” → both “Will Smith” and “I will go” count\n    Minor unintentional mispronunciations COUNT if context makes intent clear:\n        <word> is “Mamdani” → “Mandani” counts\n    Severe mispronunciations that make <word> unrecognizable do NOT count.\n    Trademarked spellings do not count, even when pronounced identically, unless the word\n\fitself is the same:\n      <word> is “lift” → “Lyft” (pronounced “lift”) does not count\n      <word> is “uber” → “Uber” counts\nWords with non-standard transliteration to English count within reason, provided they are\nphonetically equivalent:\n      <word> is “Zelensky” → any of “Zelenski,” “Zelenskii,” “Zelensky,” or “Zelenskiy”\n      count if pronounced equivalently\nContractions do not count for their constituent words unless otherwise explicitly specified\nby the Exchange:\n      <word> is “not” → “won’t,” “can’t,” “don’t,” “isn’t” do not count\nNumbers spoken as words COUNT, when spoken exactly (not part of a larger number):\n      <word> is “five” → saying “five” or reading “$5” aloud as “five dollars” counts,\n      saying “five hundred” does NOT count\n      <word> is “410” → “four hundred ten”, “four one zero” or “four ten” counts\nOrdinals COUNT when <word> is written numerically OR a phrase that includes a\nnumber:\n      <word> is “January 6” → “January 6th” counts\n      <word> is “3” (written numerically) → “3rd” (spoken as “third”) counts\n      <word> is “Eight War” → “8 Wars” and “Eighth War” will count\nCardinal and ordinal number words are distinct:\n      <word> is “one” → “first” does NOT count\n      <word> is “first” → “one” does NOT count\nAcronyms and abbreviations count when pronunciation or letter-by-letter spelling\nmatches <word>:\n      <word> is “NASA” → “NASA” (pronounced “NAH-suh”) counts\n      <word> is “NASA” → “N-A-S-A” (spelled out) counts\nAcronyms and abbreviations count as <word> when pronounced as the full word:\n      <word> is “Doctor” → “Dr.” (pronounced “Doctor”) counts\nExpanded forms of acronyms do NOT count:\n      <word> is “AI” → “artificial intelligence” does not count\nWords in foreign languages do NOT count unless they are perfect cognates with an\nEnglish word:\n      <word> is “fire” → “fuego” (Spanish) does NOT count\nEnglish words within foreign sentences count:\n      <word> is “policy” → “Nuestra policy es clara” counts\n<word> in organization/company names counts:\n      <word> is “Securities” → “Bank of America Securities” counts\nWords in URLs, emails, handles, and hashtags (exclusive of domain structure, email\nprovider or symbols) are treated as compounds when spoken as complete words, with the\ntype of compound subject to aforementioned rules:\n      <word> is “fire” → “firestation.com” pronounced “fire station dot com” counts\n      <word> is “fire” → “wildfire.com” pronounced “wildfire dot com” does NOT count\n      <word> is “apple” → “apple.com” pronounced “apple dot com” does count\n      When presented in URL, email, handle, or hashtag form, <word> shall be treated as\n      a compound, not a multi-word word\nSung, rapped, or poetic words COUNT if phonetically recognizable:\n      <word> is “money” → “moneyyy” (extended in rap) counts\n      Extreme distortion making <word> unrecognizable does NOT count.\nPhonetic alphabet spelling (“Foxtrot India Romeo Echo” for “FIRE”) does NOT count.\n\fCANCELLATIONS AND DELAYS\n\n   The Exchange may list an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike for any Contract. If listed,\n   such a strike refers to the structural conditions of the market, and is NOT adjudicated as a\n   <word> needing to be said by or validated by having been said by <entity>. If listed, this\n   strike resolves to “Yes” whenever the event fails to occur or qualify under the Payout\n   Criterion, or any other circumstance prevents normal resolution.\n   If no such strike is listed, and <time period> refers to a specific event, the following rules\n   apply if the event is cancelled, postponed, rescheduled, or materially altered (including\n   being closed to press) such that no video is released within one calendar day of the\n   original start time of the event:\n         If the event is cancelled, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price determined in\n         the sole discretion of the Exchange.\n         If the event is postponed or rescheduled, the outcome depends on whether a new\n         date is publicly announced within one calendar day (i.e. if the event was scheduled\n         to begin on Monday, any time up to 11:59PM on Tuesday falls within this period) of\n         the originally scheduled start time:\n               If no new date is announced within one calendar day, the Contract will resolve\n               to the last fair price determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\n               If a new date is announced within one calendar day, the outcome depends on\n               when the rescheduled event is set to occur:\n                     If the rescheduled date falls within fourteen (14) calendar days of the\n                     originally scheduled date, the Contract shall remain open and <word>\n                     stated during the rescheduled event will count.\n                           The fourteen-day window begins at 12:00 AM ET on the originally\n                           scheduled date and ends at 11:59 PM ET fourteen days later, unless\n                           an alternate timezone is explicitly specified.\n                           Example: <time period> is “during the State of the Union on January\n                           15, 2026” rescheduled to January 20, 2026 → words spoken during\n                           the rescheduled address count.\n                     If the rescheduled date falls more than fourteen (14) calendar days after\n                     the originally scheduled date, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price\n                     determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\n         Any Contract that cannot be resolved through the Source Agency hierarchy will\n         instead be settled at the Last Fair Price. The Exchange will disclose the methodology\n         used to determine the Last Fair Price (e.g., Last Traded Price, Time-Weighted\n         Average Price) at the time of Issuance.\n         If an event begins but is interrupted, abbreviated, or ends prematurely, words\n         stated by <entity> during the portion of the event that did occur will count and the\n         market will otherwise resolve.\n   If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window but the venue, format, or medium\n   changes (e.g., moved to a different location, changed from in-person to virtual (with the\n   exception of being closed to press)), words stated during the event will count.\n   Special condition: Across both cases, whether an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike is\n   listed or not, if the event specified as or in <time period> is a live-stream or broadcast (or\n   relayed as such) but the live stream/broadcast does not occur, the Exchange will instead\n   use an officially released recording as the Underlying, and may delay resolution by up to\n   one calendar day to allow for the release of such a recording.\n\f          If partial snippets are released, Contracts on words that do not appear will be\n          resolved to last fair price, and Contracts on those that do will be resolved to “Yes”.\n          If no recording is released, the relevant outcomes triggered by the\n          presence/absence of an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike shall occur as outlined\n          above.\n\nTECHNICAL DETAILS (UNLESS OTHERWISE SPECIFIED)\n\n     When <time period> refers to a specific event, pre-recorded content broadcast,\n     streamed, or published as part of that event is included if presented as part of the official\n     presentation.\n          Example: <time period> is “during the concert” with pre-recorded video interlude\n          where entity speaks → words from interlude count\n          Example: <time period> is “during the television appearance” with pre-taped\n          segment aired during broadcast → words from segment count\n     Behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are NOT\n     included unless officially broadcast or published as part of <time period>.\n     Subtitles and captions that display <word> on screen but are not spoken aloud by\n     <entity> do NOT count.\n     Sign language interpretation or usage by entity does NOT count as saying <word> unless\n     the Contract explicitly specifies that sign language counts.\n     Text that entity displays on screen (presentation slides, teleprompter visible to audience,\n     signatures) does NOT count unless entity reads it aloud.\n     Content generated by AI, deepfakes, or synthetic voice technology impersonating entity\n     does NOT count unless the synthetic content is officially commissioned, authorized, or\n     published by entity, OR the Contract explicitly specifies that AI-generated content counts.\n     If <word> is muted due to technical failure or censorship it shall not count unless\n     corroborating contextual evidence (including surrounding speech, or an official\n     uncensored recording or transcript) confirms that <entity> specifically uttered <word>\n     during the muted period.\n\nMinimum Tick: The Minimum Tick size for the Contract shall be $0.01.\n\nPosition Accountability Level: The Position Accountability Level for the Contract shall be\n$25,000 per strike, per Member.\n\nLast Trading Date: The Last Trading Date of the Contract will be the Expiration Date. The Last\nTrading Time will be the Expiration time.\n\nSettlement Date: The Settlement Date of the Contract shall be no later than the day after the\nExpiration Date, unless the Market Outcome is under review pursuant to Rule 7.1.\n\nExpiration Date: When <time period> refers to a specific event: The latest Expiration Date of\nthe Contract shall be fourteen (14) calendar days after the originally scheduled date of the\nevent. If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window, expiration will be moved to an\nearlier date and time in accordance with Rule 7.2. When <time period> is defined by specific\ndates: The latest Expiration Date of the Contract shall be two weeks after the end of <time\nperiod>. If an event described in the Payout Criterion occurs and a consensus has been\nreached on all terms, then expiration will be moved to an earlier date and time in accordance\nwith Rule 7.2.\n\fExpiration time: The Expiration time of the Contract shall be 10:00 AM ET.\n\nSettlement Value: The Settlement Value for this Contract is $1.00.\n\nExpiration Value: The Expiration Value is the value of the Underlying as documented by the\nSource Agency on the Expiration Date at the Expiration time.\n\nContingencies: Before Settlement, Kalshi may, at its sole discretion, initiate the Market\nOutcome Review Process pursuant to Rule 7.1 of the Rulebook. If an Expiration Value cannot\nbe determined on the Expiration Date, Kalshi has the right to determine payouts pursuant to\nRule 7.1 in the Rulebook.\n\f\n\n[defendant] DX-S1 GovInfo official transcript: prior reporter exchange\nSource: GovInfo, Compilation of Presidential Documents, DCPD202501162\nURL retrieved: https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/DCPD-202501162/html/DCPD-202501162.htm\nRetrieval time: 2026-06-29T22:00:00Z\nLocal captured HTML size/hash: 51,571 bytes; SHA-256 eadbceeecf3e94f5bd423bcb8e8511165fdc7265dd8c1e025870c2e8f34dfd99\n\nMaterial captured text from official GovInfo HTML/web.open:\n\nAdministration of Donald J. Trump, 2025\n\nTitle: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\nDate: December 5, 2025\n\nOpening note: [The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\n\nExcerpt - The President's Interest in Soccer (web.open lines 196-203):\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\"football,\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\n\nExcerpt - The President's Interest in Soccer (web.open lines 322-329):\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\nThe President. But they have a little more speed. But no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\n\nTiming/context note (web.open lines 461-462):\nNOTE: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. In his remarks, he referred to Trey Yingst, chief foreign correspondent, Fox News Channel; Cristiano Ronaldo, forward for Saudi Pro League club Al-Nass and Portugal's national soccer team; and Lionel Messi, forward for Major League Soccer club Inter Miami and Argentina's national team. A reporter referred to New York State Attorney General Letitia James.\nThe transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\n\nDocument category/location/name/subject metadata (web.open lines 463-468):\nCategories: Interviews With the News Media: Exchanges with reporters, Washington, DC.\nLocations: Washington, DC.\nNames include: Cristiano Ronaldo and Lionel Messi.\nSubjects include: Federation Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) World Cup; John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts; News media, Presidential interviews; Soccer.\nDCPD Number: DCPD202501162.\n\nCapture limits: This item is a focused text capture of the material official transcript title, Ronaldo excerpts, timing/correction note, and metadata. It is not a full video or audio artifact. The official transcript itself notes some portions could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\n\n[defendant] DX-S2 FIFA official draw commencement time\nSource: FIFA official page, FIFA World Cup 2026 Final Draw\nURL: https://www.fifa.com/en/tournaments/mens/worldcup/canadamexicousa2026/live-draw\nRetrieval time: 2026-06-29T22:01:00Z\n\nMaterial captured text from web search/open result:\n- Page title/source: FIFA World Cup 2026™ Final Draw\n- The draw takes place at the Kennedy Center in Washington DC, USA.\n- The draw commences at 12:00 local time (17:00 UTC) on Friday 5 December 2025.\n\nCapture limits: This is a focused text capture of the official FIFA page timing statement located by web search. It is not a video capture of the draw ceremony.\n\nSubmitted evidence:\n[plaintiff arguments] Official White House video page capture: President Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing (ev_db357d4e9407_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-db357d4e9407)\nSource: https://www.whitehouse.gov/videos/president-trump-attends-the-fifa-world-cup-drawing/\nSHA-256: `db357d4e940728d417ae4f7f3caac6b78d3fd3e4aba70d46fe10c6132d45997a`\nBytes: 1300\nRelevance: Establishes that the White House officially published a video page titled President Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing, dated December 5, 2025, with a full-video link and related World Cup Draw videos; relevant to source chain and event context.\n\n[plaintiff arguments] YouTube metadata capture: Trump Talks Cristiano Ronaldo at FIFA Draw (ev_4e1045905547_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-4e1045905547)\nSource: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Cb2yO0lLEnM\nSHA-256: `4e10459055477440085fe5e20d970eb2488e61d13a5e2b3133a3656bed7526d7`\nBytes: 1779\nRelevance: Provides a public clip source and page metadata asserting that at the FIFA World Cup Draw Ceremony Trump shared a story about meeting Cristiano Ronaldo and said Ronaldo was a great person; relevant to the alleged Ronaldo utterance, though weaker than an official full transcript or video.\n\n[defendant arguments] GovInfo official transcript capture: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the FIFA World Cup Draw (ev_a1b1f6b1b7bd_submitted-evidence-03-defendant-a1b1f6b1b7bd)\nSource: https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/DCPD-202501162/html/DCPD-202501162.htm\nSHA-256: `a1b1f6b1b7bd0b691c7fe8d97467dd0d085e2b22387ae4198270764de66e56e2`\nBytes: 3070\nRelevance: Official transcript identifies the relevant Trump remarks as an exchange with reporters prior to the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw; it includes the Ronaldo utterances and timing/correction notes, directly bearing on whether the utterances were during the countable event period.\n\n[defendant arguments] FIFA official page capture: 2026 World Cup Final Draw start time (ev_3973dc8f98c0_submitted-evidence-04-defendant-3973dc8f98c0)\nSource: https://www.fifa.com/en/tournaments/mens/worldcup/canadamexicousa2026/live-draw\nSHA-256: `3973dc8f98c01702174f61f5548eb1e80efe64dd72b44f21ed0fa7d944f93248`\nBytes: 598\nRelevance: Establishes the official Final Draw start time as 12:00 local time on December 5, 2025, which helps compare the draw event period against the GovInfo transcript note that the reporter exchange occurred at 11:13 a.m.\n\nTechnical reports:\n[plaintiff] Plaintiff source-search and capture ledger\nSearched exact market/strike phrases, White House domain, public video pages, YouTube video IDs, and Kalshi live market URL. Submitted official White House page capture and YouTube metadata capture. Kalshi live page returned a Vercel security checkpoint/429; local browser was unavailable; Python pip/ensurepip unavailable for yt-dlp; direct YouTube caption/open paths were throttled or unavailable. Remaining best evidence would be a full official video/transcript or Kalshi resolution rationale if later accessible.\n\n[defendant] Defendant source-search and capture ledger\nInspected current AAR evidence and exact contents of plaintiff's White House and YouTube captures. Retrieved GovInfo official HTML transcript with curl from DCPD-202501162; local full HTML was 51,571 bytes with SHA-256 eadbceeecf3e94f5bd423bcb8e8511165fdc7265dd8c1e025870c2e8f34dfd99, then submitted a focused material text capture as DX-1. Searched official draw timing and submitted the FIFA official page timing statement as DX-2. Remaining gaps: full Kalshi market source hierarchy/resolution rationale and full WH/FIFA video were not captured, but official GovInfo timing/title plus FIFA start time resolve the material timing issue.\n\nCall submit_council_vote with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated.\nKeep the rationale brief: no more than three sentences.\n\nCouncil API instructions:\nYou are a council member. Decide the proposition from the admitted record.\nYou may examine admitted evidence through read-only tools when exact bytes, metadata, or exhibit contents matter.\nDo not search the web, introduce new facts, create new evidence, or upload evidence.\nWhen ready, call submit_council_vote exactly once with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated and a concise rationale.\n","state":"ready","status":"ready","tools":[{"description":"Return the current visible arbitration record for this council member.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{},"type":"object"},"name":"get_case","read_only":true},{"description":"List visible immutable record evidence.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{},"type":"object"},"name":"list_evidence","read_only":true},{"description":"Return metadata and read limits for one visible evidence item.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"evidence_id":{"type":"string"}},"required":["evidence_id"],"type":"object"},"name":"stat_evidence","read_only":true},{"description":"Read a bounded byte range from one visible evidence item as base64.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"evidence_id":{"type":"string"},"length":{"minimum":1,"type":"integer"},"offset":{"minimum":0,"type":"integer"}},"required":["evidence_id","offset","length"],"type":"object"},"name":"read_evidence_range","read_only":true},{"description":"Submit one council vote for the current deliberation opportunity.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"rationale":{"type":"string"},"vote":{"enum":["demonstrated","not_demonstrated"],"type":"string"}},"required":["vote","rationale"],"type":"object"},"name":"submit_council_vote","read_only":false}],"turn":{"attempts_max":3,"attempts_remaining":3,"completed":false,"deadline":"2026-06-29T22:18:45.386037689Z","deliberation_round":1,"member_id":"C2","opportunity_id":"deliberation:1:C2","phase":"deliberation","remaining_ms":889046,"role_id":"council","turn_number":10},"wait":{"reason":"ready","state_version":14,"version":17}},"isError":false},"server":"aar","tool":"wait_for_opportunity"}},"isError":false}
{"type":"message_start","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_4OMctTF3Tl2BBcznCUaZhAHt","toolName":"mcp","content":[{"type":"text","text":"ok: true\nstatus: ready\nstate: ready\nmessage: An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\nafter_version: 17\nafter_opportunity_id: deliberation:1:C2\nmember_id: C2\ncase_id: arb-ex03a-20260629214245\nwait_reason: ready\nphase: deliberation\nopportunity_id: deliberation:1:C2\nremaining_ms: 889046\nattempts_remaining: 3\njson: {\"after_opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C2\",\"after_version\":17,\"case_id\":\"arb-ex03a-20260629214245\",\"limits\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"max_evidence_read_bytes\":65536,\"max_evidence_read_bytes_per_opportunity\":524288,\"max_evidence_reads_per_opportunity\":32,\"max_response_bytes\":131072,\"remaining_evidence_read_bytes_for_opportunity\":524288,\"remaining_evidence_reads_for_opportunity\":32},\"member_id\":\"C2\",\"message\":\"An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\",\"ok\":true,\"prompt\":\"Role: council member\\nMember ID: C2\\nDeliberation round: 1\\nProposition: For the Kalshi market \\\"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\\", the strike \\\"Ronaldo\\\" should resolve Yes because Trump said \\\"Ronaldo\\\" in public remarks at the World Cup Draw venue immediately before the formal program, and the market wording plus the governing mention-market terms did not clearly exclude those event-linked remarks.\\nStandard of evidence: Preponderance of the evidence.\\nPersona:\\nYou are a careful juror and council member.\\n\\nEvaluate the record faithfully. Decide only from the evidence, the stated rules, and the applicable burden of proof. Do not favor either side, fill gaps with speculation, or ignore uncertainty.\\n\\nGive weight to reliable sources, direct evidence, consistent reasoning, and clear admissions. Discount unsupported claims, rhetorical force, irrelevant facts, and conclusions that exceed the record.\\n\\nWhen the evidence supports one answer, state it plainly. When the evidence is incomplete or balanced, say so. Be concise, honest, and exact.\\n\\nRecord:\\nOpenings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, this case is not about whether the word \\\"Ronaldo\\\" would count if President Trump clearly said it. The current packet makes that part straightforward: the market is the Kalshi PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION market titled \\\"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\\"; the strike is \\\"Ronaldo\\\"; Kalshi’s challenged resolution is No; and plaintiff seeks Yes.\\n\\nThe real dispute is temporal and contextual. Did the market phrase \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw,\\\" read with the governing mention-market terms, include public event-linked remarks at the World Cup Draw venue immediately before the formal draw program? Or did it clearly confine countable words to a narrower formal broadcast segment? Plaintiff’s position is that a No resolution cannot stand unless the record shows that the counting window clearly excluded those event-linked remarks.\\n\\nThe admitted terms matter. They define the underlying as words used by the specified entity during the specified time period. They expressly recognize event-based time periods, and they say the payout criterion is satisfied when the word is said by the entity during that period. They also contain exclusions: behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings do not count unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period; captions or text alone do not count; and the word must appear as a distinct standalone unit. Those exclusions are important, but they do not by themselves answer this case. A public remark at the event venue, tied to the Draw and immediately before the formal program, is not automatically a rehearsal, sound check, or private behind-the-scenes moment.\\n\\nAt this opening stage, the record proves the market identity, the challenged resolution, the requested resolution, and the generic governing terms. It does not yet prove the utterance itself, the exact sequence of the venue remarks, the source-agency hierarchy or any market-specific time-period language beyond the packet, or Kalshi’s reason for treating the strike as No. Those are the factual links that should decide the case under a preponderance standard.\\n\\nPlaintiff expects the decisive proof to be the full official or otherwise reliable event video or transcript, with enough surrounding context to show whether Trump said \\\"Ronaldo\\\" aloud as a standalone word; when he said it relative to the Draw event; whether the remarks were public and event-linked rather than backstage or a sound check; and whether any market-specific rule clearly excluded that segment. Plaintiff also expects the market page, archived market details, and any resolution rationale to be important because ambiguity in the market’s own event wording should not be resolved against Yes after the fact.\\n\\nThe defense will likely argue that \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw\\\" means only the formal draw ceremony or broadcast, and that anything before the formal program is outside the counting period. That theory can win only if the evidence shows a clear exclusion or a source record that separates the alleged remarks from the event itself. If the evidence instead shows public remarks at the Draw venue, officially connected to the event, immediately before the formal program, and no clear rule excluding them, then the terms favor counting the word and resolving the Ronaldo strike Yes.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the defense position is straightforward: the admitted record does not yet prove that the Ronaldo strike should resolve Yes. It proves a market title, a generic mention-market rule set, and Kalshi's challenged No resolution. It does not prove that any qualifying utterance of \\\"Ronaldo\\\" occurred during the market's countable time period.\\n\\nThe plaintiff's opening usefully narrows the dispute. This is not primarily a word-boundary case. If President Trump said \\\"Ronaldo\\\" as a standalone spoken word during the countable FIFA World Cup Draw period, the generic terms would ordinarily treat that as the kind of word that can count. The real question is whether plaintiff can carry the burden of showing that alleged pre-program, venue-adjacent remarks were part of the market's specified time period: \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\\\"\\n\\nThe case-packet terms matter, but they cut both ways. They say the underlying is words used by the entity during the specified time period. They recognize that a time period can be an event, and they allow the Exchange to specify what is included when an event is involved. They also distinguish official event presentation from material outside the event: behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are not included unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period; text or captions alone do not count; and the relevant word must be spoken aloud by the entity. Those provisions do not support a rule that every public comment inside the same building, or every press exchange near the formal program, is automatically \\\"during\\\" the Draw.\\n\\nThat is the burden problem for plaintiff. The admitted market-page file identifies the public title, contract family, strike, challenged resolution, and requested resolution. It does not supply a full market-specific source hierarchy, a formal start time, a transcript, a video, a resolution rationale, or the alleged remarks. The terms file supplies the generic framework, but not the factual bridge from \\\"immediately before the formal program\\\" to \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\\\" Without that bridge, the No resolution is not shown to be wrong by a preponderance of the evidence.\\n\\nThe defense expects the decisive proof to be source-chain evidence, not characterization. The council should want the market's full rule page if available, the source agency hierarchy, the official draw program or broadcast, any official transcript or recording of the alleged exchange, and enough surrounding timestamps to separate the formal draw from pre-event reporter access, red-carpet exchanges, arrivals, or other ancillary material. If later evidence shows that the alleged Ronaldo comment was in a segment officially presented as part of the Draw itself, plaintiff's argument becomes stronger. If the evidence instead shows a separate exchange with reporters before the draw, or an event-linked but pre-program interaction not incorporated into the official presentation, the generic terms support Kalshi's No.\\n\\nSo the defense opening is not that the word Ronaldo could never count. It is that this record has not established the necessary time-period link. The proposition asks the council to overturn No because the market wording and terms did not clearly exclude pre-program remarks. That reverses the burden. Plaintiff must show that the remarks were included in the countable period. Ambiguity about the outer edge of an event is not the same as proof that a specific pre-event utterance satisfies the payout criterion.\\n\\nArguments:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, plaintiff has now supplied the record links that were missing at opening.\\n\\nFirst, the market packet fixes what this dispute is: the Kalshi market title is \\\"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\\"; the contract family is PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION; the strike is \\\"Ronaldo\\\"; Kalshi's challenged resolution is No; and plaintiff seeks Yes. That is PX-1.\\n\\nSecond, the governing terms make this an event-period mention question, not a narrow formal-program-only question. PX-2 says the underlying is words used by the entity during the time period, recognizes that a time period may be a specific event, and sets the payout criterion as the word being said by the entity during that period. It also tells us what does not count: text/captions alone, unofficial behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, and sound checks unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. Those exclusions matter, but none says that public event-linked remarks at the venue immediately before the formal program are categorically outside \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\\\"\\n\\nThird, the source-chain evidence now points to the disputed event and the Ronaldo utterance. PX-3 is an official White House page titled \\\"President Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing,\\\" dated December 5, 2025, with a full-video link and related World Cup Draw videos. That establishes an official White House event-video source for Trump's attendance at the World Cup Drawing. PX-4 is a public YouTube watch-page metadata capture for video ID Cb2yO0lLEnM, titled \\\"Trump Talks Cristiano Ronaldo at FIFA Draw -- 'He's a Great Person'.\\\" Its description states that at the FIFA World Cup Draw Ceremony, Trump shared a story about meeting Cristiano Ronaldo at the White House, said Ronaldo was a great person, and mentioned Ronaldo spoke with his son. PX-4 is not as strong as an official transcript, and plaintiff says that plainly. But it is admitted source content that directly links Trump, Cristiano Ronaldo, and the FIFA Draw ceremony.\\n\\nOn a preponderance standard, that is enough to defeat the challenged No resolution unless the defense can supply a clearer exclusion. The market did not ask only what Trump would say during the ball-pulling segment, during the televised main show, or after a particular formal start cue. It asked what he would say \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\\\" The terms recognize event-based periods and exclude particular non-event categories. A public remark at the Draw venue, tied to the Draw, is far closer to the event period than to a rehearsal, sound check, caption, or private backstage recording.\\n\\nThe defense's burden framing is too strict. Plaintiff must prove Yes by a preponderance; plaintiff need not prove that Kalshi drafted every boundary with perfect precision. Once the admitted sources show a Ronaldo mention in connection with the FIFA Draw ceremony, the remaining question is whether the rules clearly remove that event-linked remark from the counting period. They do not. Ambiguity in a mention market's event wording should not be converted into an unstated formal-program limitation after the fact.\\n\\nProvenance and gaps: plaintiff attempted to retrieve the live Kalshi page, official/full video, caption, and transcript. Kalshi returned a Vercel security checkpoint; the local browser tool was unavailable; Python pip/ensurepip was unavailable for yt-dlp; and direct YouTube caption/open paths were throttled or unavailable. That leaves PX-4 weaker than ideal, but not weightless. PX-3 supplies official event context, PX-4 supplies the Ronaldo-at-FIFA-Draw metadata, and PX-2 supplies the rule that event-linked spoken words count absent a clear exclusion.\\n\\nThe council should resolve the proposition Yes: the Ronaldo strike should have resolved Yes because the record more likely than not shows Trump said Ronaldo in public remarks tied to the FIFA World Cup Draw, and the market wording plus governing terms did not clearly exclude those remarks.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the merits record now shows why the challenged No resolution should stand.\\n\\nPlaintiff's best point is that Trump did say the word \\\"Ronaldo.\\\" The defense does not need to fight that. The question is whether he said it during the market's countable time period: \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\\\" On that decisive question, the strongest official sources favor No.\\n\\nThe admitted GovInfo transcript, DX-1, is an official Compilation of Presidential Documents capture. Its title is not merely \\\"World Cup Draw\\\" or \\\"FIFA ceremony.\\\" It is \\\"Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw.\\\" That same transcript contains the Ronaldo passages: Trump says he met Ronaldo at the White House, later says he was \\\"not Ronaldo or Messi,\\\" and the note identifies Ronaldo among the people referenced. So DX-1 is not adverse to the defense because it confirms the word; it is decisive because it places the word in an exchange with reporters prior to the Draw.\\n\\nDX-2 supplies the timing anchor. The official FIFA Final Draw page states that the Draw at the Kennedy Center commenced at 12:00 local time on Friday, December 5, 2025. DX-1 states that the President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the Kennedy Center. A reporter exchange at 11:13, officially titled as prior to a 12:00 draw, is not more likely than not \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\\\" It is before it.\\n\\nThat reading matches the governing PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION terms. PX-2 says the payout criterion is satisfied when the word is said by the entity during the specified time period. It recognizes event-based periods and permits the Exchange to specify what is included for an event. It also treats official presentation differently from adjacent material: pre-recorded content counts if presented as part of the official event presentation, while behind-the-scenes, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings do not count unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. The point is not that this reporter exchange was a rehearsal or sound check. The point is that the terms require a link to the time period itself. Plaintiff has supplied no market-specific language saying pre-event reporter availability, arrivals, or venue interviews count as part of the Draw.\\n\\nPlaintiff's new exhibits do not fill that gap. PX-3, the White House page capture, establishes that the White House had a page titled \\\"President Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing,\\\" but plaintiff's own capture says the embedded/full video was not captured. It does not prove that the Ronaldo words occurred inside the official draw program. PX-4 is weaker still: it is metadata from a nonofficial YouTube channel. It says the clip is about Trump talking Ronaldo at the FIFA Draw, but it is not a transcript, not an official source, and not an audio extraction. When a nonofficial clip description is weighed against GovInfo's official transcript title and FIFA's official start time, the official sources control.\\n\\nNor is this a burden-shifting problem. The proposition asks the council to overturn Kalshi's No because the market supposedly did not clearly exclude remarks immediately before the formal program. But the preponderance burden is on Yes. The record must show that the strike satisfied the payout criterion. The admitted terms do not say that ambiguous pre-event remarks count by default; they say the word must be said during the specified time period. Here, the best evidence identifies the remarks as prior to the Draw and before the official commencement time.\\n\\nProvenance also matters. DX-1 is an official government transcript with a correction note and an audio-incomplete caveat. That caveat affects stray inaudible portions, but it does not weaken the title, the 11:13 timing note, or the Ronaldo passages preserved in the transcript. DX-2 is an official FIFA timing source. Plaintiff's YouTube metadata may explain why the dispute arose, but it cannot outweigh those primary sources on timing and event classification.\\n\\nThe council should resolve the proposition against plaintiff. Trump said Ronaldo, but the record more likely shows he did so in a reporter exchange prior to the FIFA World Cup Draw, not during the countable Draw event. Kalshi's No resolution should be upheld.\\n\\nRebuttals:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, defendant’s new evidence narrows the case but does not end it.\\n\\nPlaintiff accepts the important parts of DX-1 and DX-2. The GovInfo transcript is official; it labels the item an exchange with reporters \\\"Prior to\\\" the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw; it places the exchange at 11:13 a.m. at the Kennedy Center; and the FIFA capture states the draw commenced at 12:00 local time. Plaintiff should not pretend those facts are weak.\\n\\nBut defendant asks those facts to do more than they do. The market was not drafted as \\\"what will Trump say after the official 12:00 commencement,\\\" \\\"during the televised draw program,\\\" or \\\"during the ball-drawing segment.\\\" PX-1 says the public market title was \\\"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\\" That is ordinary event language, and PX-2 recognizes event-based time periods while leaving room for the Exchange to specify what is included. The record still contains no market-specific exclusion for official venue press remarks immediately before the formal program.\\n\\nDX-1 also helps plaintiff on the facts defendant originally said were missing. It confirms the relevant spoken word. Trump said he met Ronaldo, that Ronaldo is great, and that he was not Ronaldo or Messi. It also places those remarks at the Kennedy Center in a FIFA World Cup Draw-centered exchange with reporters, not in an unrelated private dinner or stale campaign setting. The transcript’s own subject metadata includes the FIFA World Cup, the Kennedy Center, news media, presidential interviews, and soccer. That is event-linked public context.\\n\\nThe terms’ exclusions do not fit defendant’s leap. PX-2 excludes captions alone, rehearsals, sound checks, behind-the-scenes content, and unofficial recordings unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. DX-1 is not a rehearsal transcript. It is not a sound check. It is not merely a caption. It is an official presidential transcript of a public reporter exchange at the venue, released in the Compilation of Presidential Documents. If Kalshi meant to exclude that category because it occurred before a formal noon commencement, the market needed to say so clearly.\\n\\nSo the dispositive question remains one of market construction: does \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw\\\" clearly exclude public, official, event-site remarks immediately before the formal program? Defendant has proved \\\"prior to\\\" the formal draw start. Defendant has not proved a clear market rule that treats the broader Draw event as beginning only at 12:00 for mention purposes.\\n\\nUnder a preponderance standard, the record now confirms the Ronaldo utterance and confirms the FIFA Draw setting. The challenged No resolution should not be upheld by importing a narrow formal-program limitation that the market title and generic terms did not state.\\n\\nSurrebuttals:\\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff's rebuttal usefully clarifies the remaining dispute: plaintiff accepts that DX-1 is official, that it labels the relevant item an exchange with reporters \\\"Prior to\\\" the FIFA World Cup Draw, that the exchange occurred at 11:13 a.m. at the Kennedy Center, and that DX-2 places the official Draw commencement at 12:00 local time. Those concessions should decide the case.\\n\\nPlaintiff's answer is that the market did not say \\\"after 12:00,\\\" \\\"during the televised program,\\\" or \\\"during the ball-drawing segment.\\\" But the market also did not say \\\"at the venue before the Draw,\\\" \\\"in pre-event reporter exchanges,\\\" or \\\"in any public remarks connected to the Draw.\\\" The phrase it chose was \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\\\" Ordinary event language has a start, and the official FIFA source fixes that start at noon. Official GovInfo then fixes this exchange at 11:13 and titles it as prior to the Draw.\\n\\nThat is not a technicality. The terms require the word to be said during the specified time period. They recognize event-based periods and allow event-specific inclusions, but no admitted market-specific rule includes pre-event press access. Plaintiff's construction would turn any event-adjacent public remark into part of the event unless expressly excluded. That reverses the payout criterion. The claimant must show the word occurred during the time period; it is not enough to show the same venue, the same general topic, and official publication.\\n\\nPlaintiff says the exclusions do not fit because DX-1 is not a rehearsal, sound check, caption, or private backstage recording. Fair enough; the defense is not relying on those categories as labels. The defense relies on the affirmative timing requirement. A remark need not be a rehearsal to be outside the event. A reporter exchange officially described as prior to a noon event and occurring at 11:13 is outside because it is before the event began.\\n\\nThe record therefore proves the wrong fact for plaintiff. It proves Trump said Ronaldo, but in a pre-event reporter exchange. The proposition requires Yes only if those words count during the FIFA World Cup Draw. On this record, they do not. Kalshi's No resolution should be upheld.\\n\\nClosings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the final record leaves one legal question.\\n\\nThe easy factual question is resolved in plaintiff’s favor: Trump said \\\"Ronaldo.\\\" The official GovInfo transcript confirms it twice in substance: he said he met Ronaldo, praised him, and later said he was not Ronaldo or Messi. That is a spoken standalone use of the strike word. The record also places the remarks at the Kennedy Center in a FIFA World Cup Draw-centered reporter exchange. This was not an unrelated dinner, a caption, an AI voice, or a social-media paraphrase.\\n\\nThe hard point is timing. Defendant has the strongest evidence on the formal program boundary: GovInfo titled the exchange as \\\"Prior to\\\" the Draw, notes 11:13 a.m., and FIFA states the Final Draw commenced at 12:00 local time. Plaintiff does not ask the council to ignore that. The question is what the Kalshi market actually required.\\n\\nPX-1 did not say \\\"after 12:00.\\\" It did not say \\\"during the televised draw program\\\" or \\\"during the ball-drawing segment.\\\" It asked, in public market wording, \\\"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\\" PX-2’s generic terms recognize event-based periods and say the Exchange may specify what is included when a time period refers to an event. They also give specific exclusions: captions alone, rehearsals, sound checks, behind-the-scenes content, and unofficial recordings unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. None of those exclusions is this case. The GovInfo transcript is an official public presidential record of an event-site reporter exchange, not a rehearsal or sound check.\\n\\nDefendant’s best argument is that ordinary events have start times. True. But this market dispute is about public remarks at the venue immediately before the formal program, in the official context of the Draw, where the market and rules did not clearly define a noon-only boundary. If Kalshi wanted that narrower rule, it could have said so in the strike, the market title, or the event inclusion language. It did not.\\n\\nThe preponderance record therefore shows: Ronaldo was spoken; the remarks were public and officially documented; they were at the Kennedy Center in the FIFA World Cup Draw setting; and the governing market language did not clearly exclude that immediately-before-program event context. The challenged No resolution depends on importing a formal commencement limitation that is absent from the market packet.\\n\\nFor that reason, the Ronaldo strike should resolve Yes.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the closing record is narrow and concrete.\\n\\nEveryone now agrees on the easy fact: Trump said \\\"Ronaldo.\\\" The official GovInfo transcript proves that. But the proposition is not simply that Trump said the word somewhere near the FIFA World Cup Draw. The proposition asks you to overturn Kalshi's No because remarks immediately before the formal program should count under a market asking what Trump would say \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\\\" Plaintiff has not carried that burden.\\n\\nThe two strongest sources are official and aligned. GovInfo, in DX-1, titles the relevant document \\\"Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw.\\\" It notes that the President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the Kennedy Center. FIFA, in DX-2, states that the Final Draw commenced at 12:00 local time. Those facts are not peripheral. They answer the timing question: the Ronaldo words were in a reporter exchange before the Draw began.\\n\\nPlaintiff's closing says the market did not specify \\\"after 12:00,\\\" \\\"during the televised draw program,\\\" or \\\"during the ball-drawing segment.\\\" True, but that does not prove Yes. The market did specify \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\\\" The ordinary function of \\\"during\\\" is to define the event period, not to include anything public, official, and thematically related that happens beforehand. A 47-minute-before reporter exchange officially titled as prior to the Draw is outside that period unless the market or governing terms affirmatively include it. The record contains no such inclusion.\\n\\nThe governing terms reinforce that conclusion. They require the word to be said by the entity during the specified time period. They recognize event-based periods and allow the Exchange to specify event inclusions. They include official-presentation concepts for material presented as part of an event. But they do not say that pre-event press availability counts by default. Plaintiff's argument turns the absence of an exclusion into proof of inclusion. That is backwards under a preponderance standard.\\n\\nPlaintiff also leans on setting: Kennedy Center, FIFA World Cup subject matter, official transcript, public reporters. Those facts show why the issue is understandable. They do not move 11:13 into a 12:00 event. A source can be official and still describe something outside the event. Indeed, that is exactly what DX-1 does: it officially documents the remarks and officially labels them prior to the Draw.\\n\\nThe weaker evidence points the same way once weighed properly. The White House page capture does not include the video or transcript. The YouTube metadata is nonofficial and not an audio transcript. Neither overcomes GovInfo's title and timing note plus FIFA's commencement time.\\n\\nSo the final answer is simple: the word was spoken, but not during the countable event period shown by the best evidence. Plaintiff has not shown that Kalshi's No resolution was wrong. The council should reject the proposition and uphold No.\\n\\nExhibits:\\n[plaintiff] PX-1 Market page packet: Ronaldo strike and challenged No resolution\\nMarket URL: https://kalshi.com/markets/kxtrumpmentionb/trump-mention-b/kxtrumpmentionb-25dec06\\n\\nPublic market title: What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\n\\nContract family: PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION\\n\\nStrike at issue: Ronaldo\\n\\nChallenged resolution: No\\n\\nRequested resolution: Yes\\n\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-2 Governing PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION terms\\n                                         NEWMENTION\\n\\nScope: These rules shall apply to this contract.\\n\\nUnderlying: The Underlying for this Contract is words used by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nRevisions to the Underlying made after Expiration will not be accounted for in determining the\\nExpiration Value.\\n\\nSource Agency: The Source Agencies are \\u003csource\\u003e.\\n\\nType: The type of Contract is an Event Contract.\\n\\nIssuance: After the initial Contract, Contract iterations will be listed on an as-needed basis at\\nthe discretion of the Exchange and corresponding to the risk management needs of Members.\\n\\n\\u003centity\\u003e: \\u003centity\\u003e refers to the speaker, writer, performer, or communicator specified by the\\nExchange. This may include (but is not limited to): a specific named individual, multiple\\nindividuals specified using AND/OR logic, an individual identified by position or title, a group,\\nband, team or collective entity, a specified member or members of a group, an organization,\\ncompany, or institutional entity, or any combination of the aforementioned.\\n\\nWhen \\u003centity\\u003e is defined by a position or title, the Contract tracks whoever holds that position\\nduring \\u003ctime period\\u003e, even if the individual holding the position changes. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a\\nspecific named individual, the identity remains consistent throughout. Name changes (e.g.,\\nstage names, married names) do not create a new entity. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a group or\\norganization and the Contract does not specify particular members, any official\\ncommunication or statement by any member or designated spokesperson counts. When using\\nAND logic, all specified entities must independently say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e. When\\nusing OR logic, at least one of the specified entities must say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nThe Exchange may specify additional conditions such as “at least X members of” a group or\\n“the majority of” a group.\\n\\n\\u003csource\\u003e: \\u003csource\\u003e refers to a Source Agency or ordered collection of Source Agencies\\nspecified by the Exchange at the time of Contract listing, which will be incorporated into the\\nSource Agency hierarchy above and used to determine the occurrence of the Underlying.\\n\\u003csource\\u003e may refer to a singular agency, multiple agencies, an agency by distinguishing\\ncharacteristics, by category or type (e.g., “official government statistical body,” “primary wire\\nservice”), or any combination thereof. When multiple agencies are specified, they may be\\napplied in the hierarchical order designated by the Exchange if so specified, with the highest-\\nranked available and responsive agency taking precedence for purposes of determining the\\nExpiration Value. A lower-ranked agency shall only be consulted if all higher-ranked agencies\\nare unavailable, unresponsive, have not reported on the Underlying by the Expiration time, or\\nif the Exchange, in its sole discretion, determines that a higher-ranked agency’s reporting is\\nincomplete, erroneous, or otherwise insufficient to determine the Expiration Value. If \\u003csource\\u003e\\ndesignates multiple agencies without specifying a hierarchical order, the Exchange shall\\nresolve any conflict between reporting agencies at its sole discretion.\\n\\n\\u003cword\\u003e: \\u003cword\\u003e refers to the particular word or phrase potentially to be mentioned by\\n\\u003centity\\u003e. It may refer to a word being said a minimum number of times. It may also refer to\\none of multiple words/phrases, any of which are acceptable (e.g., “Doge/Dogecoin”).\\n\\f\\u003ctime period\\u003e: \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific range of time, event or discrete date and\\ntime specified by the Exchange. This may be defined by, but is not limited to: a specific event\\nor context (e.g., “during the State of the Union address”), exact dates or times, relative time\\nmarkers (e.g., “before July 1, 2027,” “in Q1 2026”), event-based periods (e.g., “during any\\ncampaign rally in October 2026,” “during the awards ceremony”), and broader intervals (e.g.,\\n“Q1–Q2 2027,” “January–March 2026”).\\n\\nUnless stated otherwise, “Between” is inclusive of both endpoints, while “before” and “after”\\nexclude the specified date. \\u003ctime period\\u003e may also refer to “Any” or “None”, to multiple dates\\n(even if non-consecutive), or to a singular and discrete date or time.\\n\\nWhen \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event (such as an address, speech, performance, or\\nbroadcast), the Exchange may specify what is included, including whether it includes both live\\nand pre-recorded segments (including whether advertisements are included). Where a\\ntimezone is not specified, ET is assumed.\\n\\n\\nPayout Criterion: The Payout Criterion for the Contract encompasses the Expiration Values that\\n\\u003cword\\u003e is said by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n\\n\\nThe word must appear as a distinct, standalone unit, not buried inside another word. Plural\\nand possessive noun forms count. Other grammatical changes (tense, conjugation, derivation)\\ndo not. If \\u003cword\\u003e appears separated from other words by a space or hyphen or in a\\ncompound form with a space or hyphen, it counts. If \\u003cword\\u003e is fused into a single\\nunhyphenated word, it does not count.\\n\\nIf \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled, and the market contains a\\nstrike stating “Event does not qualify/occur”, such a strike shall resolve “Yes” and all others\\n“No”. If \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled but such strikes are NOT\\nlisted, the Contracts will resolve to the last fair price determined at the discretion of the\\nExchange. If the event is postponed, and such a postponement is announced by the end of the\\nfollowing calendar day to be rescheduled to a time within 14 calendar days, the markets shall\\nremain open. If the event captured in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast, the\\nExchange may keep the market open for 24 hours for the release of an official recording.\\nFurther granular details on conditions for these Contracts is available below.\\n\\nAdditional clarification(s):\\n\\n     Possessive noun forms of \\u003cword\\u003e, plurals, and possessive plural noun forms are\\n     INCLUDED:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigrants” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Egg” → “eggs’ shells” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Russia” → “Russia’s” counts, “Russian” does not\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e exists only in adjective form, no plural form exists:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Economic” → “Economics” does not count (“Economic” is an adjective\\n          for which “Economics” is not a plural)\\n     Plural nouns occurring within proper nouns and noun phrases are included:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Cat” → “Cats the musical” counts\\n\\f    Grammatical variations beyond plurals/possessives are NOT included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigration” does NOT count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Run” → “Running” or “Ran” do NOT count\\n    When \\u003cword\\u003e specifies a plural form, the singular does NOT count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Veterans” → “Veteran” does NOT count\\n    Words that are spelled the same as the plural form of \\u003cword\\u003e (if such exists) but are\\n    themselves not a plural noun are included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Wind” → “Winds up the clock” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Border” → “The United States has strong borders” counts\\n    Open compounds (words separated by spaces) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fire station” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “couch” → “couch potato” counts\\n    Hyphenated compounds (words connected by hyphens) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Palestine” → “pro-Palestine” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fat” → “non-fat” counts\\n    Closed compounds (single word, no spaces/hyphens) do not count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire” does not count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firefighter” does not count\\n    Multi-word \\u003cword\\u003e in larger constructions: When \\u003cword\\u003e is a multi-word phrase\\n    appearing within a hyphenated construction, it counts only if \\u003cword\\u003e appears as a\\n    complete, unmodified element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “New York” → “New York-based” counts (complete element)\\n    Portmanteaus (words blended from two words where parts of each are combined) are\\n    NOT included unless the portmanteau clearly contains \\u003cword\\u003e as a distinct, unaltered\\n    element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “MAGA” → “MAGA-nificent” counts (MAGA appears as distinct element)\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “magnificent” → “MAGA-nificent” does NOT count (portmanteau blend)\\n\\nDictionary determination: Both the Merriam-Webster Dictionary (available online) AND the\\nOxford English Dictionary shall be used to determine compound type and/or conventional\\nspelling patterns. Inclusion in either dictionary as an open or hyphenated compound shall\\nsatisfy the Payout Criterion. If neither provides clarity (or the word is not included),\\ndetermination is based on whether written as single unit (closed/doesn’t count) vs. spaces or\\nhyphens (open or hyphenated/counts) and/or context and previous usage.\\n\\nPHONETIC EQUIVALENCIES\\n\\n    Homophones (same sound, different spelling) do not count:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “write” → “right” does not count\\n    Homonyms and homographs (same spelling) COUNT regardless of meaning or\\n    pronunciation:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “bass” → both “bass guitar” and “bass fishing” count\\n    Proper and common nouns are treated identically:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Apple” → both “Apple Inc.” and “apple” (fruit) count\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Will” → both “Will Smith” and “I will go” count\\n    Minor unintentional mispronunciations COUNT if context makes intent clear:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Mamdani” → “Mandani” counts\\n    Severe mispronunciations that make \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable do NOT count.\\n    Trademarked spellings do not count, even when pronounced identically, unless the word\\n\\fitself is the same:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “lift” → “Lyft” (pronounced “lift”) does not count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “uber” → “Uber” counts\\nWords with non-standard transliteration to English count within reason, provided they are\\nphonetically equivalent:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Zelensky” → any of “Zelenski,” “Zelenskii,” “Zelensky,” or “Zelenskiy”\\n      count if pronounced equivalently\\nContractions do not count for their constituent words unless otherwise explicitly specified\\nby the Exchange:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “not” → “won’t,” “can’t,” “don’t,” “isn’t” do not count\\nNumbers spoken as words COUNT, when spoken exactly (not part of a larger number):\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “five” → saying “five” or reading “$5” aloud as “five dollars” counts,\\n      saying “five hundred” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “410” → “four hundred ten”, “four one zero” or “four ten” counts\\nOrdinals COUNT when \\u003cword\\u003e is written numerically OR a phrase that includes a\\nnumber:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “January 6” → “January 6th” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “3” (written numerically) → “3rd” (spoken as “third”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Eight War” → “8 Wars” and “Eighth War” will count\\nCardinal and ordinal number words are distinct:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “one” → “first” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “first” → “one” does NOT count\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count when pronunciation or letter-by-letter spelling\\nmatches \\u003cword\\u003e:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “NASA” (pronounced “NAH-suh”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “N-A-S-A” (spelled out) counts\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count as \\u003cword\\u003e when pronounced as the full word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Doctor” → “Dr.” (pronounced “Doctor”) counts\\nExpanded forms of acronyms do NOT count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “AI” → “artificial intelligence” does not count\\nWords in foreign languages do NOT count unless they are perfect cognates with an\\nEnglish word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fuego” (Spanish) does NOT count\\nEnglish words within foreign sentences count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “policy” → “Nuestra policy es clara” counts\\n\\u003cword\\u003e in organization/company names counts:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Securities” → “Bank of America Securities” counts\\nWords in URLs, emails, handles, and hashtags (exclusive of domain structure, email\\nprovider or symbols) are treated as compounds when spoken as complete words, with the\\ntype of compound subject to aforementioned rules:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firestation.com” pronounced “fire station dot com” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire.com” pronounced “wildfire dot com” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “apple” → “apple.com” pronounced “apple dot com” does count\\n      When presented in URL, email, handle, or hashtag form, \\u003cword\\u003e shall be treated as\\n      a compound, not a multi-word word\\nSung, rapped, or poetic words COUNT if phonetically recognizable:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “money” → “moneyyy” (extended in rap) counts\\n      Extreme distortion making \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable does NOT count.\\nPhonetic alphabet spelling (“Foxtrot India Romeo Echo” for “FIRE”) does NOT count.\\n\\fCANCELLATIONS AND DELAYS\\n\\n   The Exchange may list an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike for any Contract. If listed,\\n   such a strike refers to the structural conditions of the market, and is NOT adjudicated as a\\n   \\u003cword\\u003e needing to be said by or validated by having been said by \\u003centity\\u003e. If listed, this\\n   strike resolves to “Yes” whenever the event fails to occur or qualify under the Payout\\n   Criterion, or any other circumstance prevents normal resolution.\\n   If no such strike is listed, and \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, the following rules\\n   apply if the event is cancelled, postponed, rescheduled, or materially altered (including\\n   being closed to press) such that no video is released within one calendar day of the\\n   original start time of the event:\\n         If the event is cancelled, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price determined in\\n         the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         If the event is postponed or rescheduled, the outcome depends on whether a new\\n         date is publicly announced within one calendar day (i.e. if the event was scheduled\\n         to begin on Monday, any time up to 11:59PM on Tuesday falls within this period) of\\n         the originally scheduled start time:\\n               If no new date is announced within one calendar day, the Contract will resolve\\n               to the last fair price determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n               If a new date is announced within one calendar day, the outcome depends on\\n               when the rescheduled event is set to occur:\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls within fourteen (14) calendar days of the\\n                     originally scheduled date, the Contract shall remain open and \\u003cword\\u003e\\n                     stated during the rescheduled event will count.\\n                           The fourteen-day window begins at 12:00 AM ET on the originally\\n                           scheduled date and ends at 11:59 PM ET fourteen days later, unless\\n                           an alternate timezone is explicitly specified.\\n                           Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the State of the Union on January\\n                           15, 2026” rescheduled to January 20, 2026 → words spoken during\\n                           the rescheduled address count.\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls more than fourteen (14) calendar days after\\n                     the originally scheduled date, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price\\n                     determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         Any Contract that cannot be resolved through the Source Agency hierarchy will\\n         instead be settled at the Last Fair Price. The Exchange will disclose the methodology\\n         used to determine the Last Fair Price (e.g., Last Traded Price, Time-Weighted\\n         Average Price) at the time of Issuance.\\n         If an event begins but is interrupted, abbreviated, or ends prematurely, words\\n         stated by \\u003centity\\u003e during the portion of the event that did occur will count and the\\n         market will otherwise resolve.\\n   If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window but the venue, format, or medium\\n   changes (e.g., moved to a different location, changed from in-person to virtual (with the\\n   exception of being closed to press)), words stated during the event will count.\\n   Special condition: Across both cases, whether an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike is\\n   listed or not, if the event specified as or in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast (or\\n   relayed as such) but the live stream/broadcast does not occur, the Exchange will instead\\n   use an officially released recording as the Underlying, and may delay resolution by up to\\n   one calendar day to allow for the release of such a recording.\\n\\f          If partial snippets are released, Contracts on words that do not appear will be\\n          resolved to last fair price, and Contracts on those that do will be resolved to “Yes”.\\n          If no recording is released, the relevant outcomes triggered by the\\n          presence/absence of an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike shall occur as outlined\\n          above.\\n\\nTECHNICAL DETAILS (UNLESS OTHERWISE SPECIFIED)\\n\\n     When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, pre-recorded content broadcast,\\n     streamed, or published as part of that event is included if presented as part of the official\\n     presentation.\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the concert” with pre-recorded video interlude\\n          where entity speaks → words from interlude count\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the television appearance” with pre-taped\\n          segment aired during broadcast → words from segment count\\n     Behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are NOT\\n     included unless officially broadcast or published as part of \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n     Subtitles and captions that display \\u003cword\\u003e on screen but are not spoken aloud by\\n     \\u003centity\\u003e do NOT count.\\n     Sign language interpretation or usage by entity does NOT count as saying \\u003cword\\u003e unless\\n     the Contract explicitly specifies that sign language counts.\\n     Text that entity displays on screen (presentation slides, teleprompter visible to audience,\\n     signatures) does NOT count unless entity reads it aloud.\\n     Content generated by AI, deepfakes, or synthetic voice technology impersonating entity\\n     does NOT count unless the synthetic content is officially commissioned, authorized, or\\n     published by entity, OR the Contract explicitly specifies that AI-generated content counts.\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e is muted due to technical failure or censorship it shall not count unless\\n     corroborating contextual evidence (including surrounding speech, or an official\\n     uncensored recording or transcript) confirms that \\u003centity\\u003e specifically uttered \\u003cword\\u003e\\n     during the muted period.\\n\\nMinimum Tick: The Minimum Tick size for the Contract shall be $0.01.\\n\\nPosition Accountability Level: The Position Accountability Level for the Contract shall be\\n$25,000 per strike, per Member.\\n\\nLast Trading Date: The Last Trading Date of the Contract will be the Expiration Date. The Last\\nTrading Time will be the Expiration time.\\n\\nSettlement Date: The Settlement Date of the Contract shall be no later than the day after the\\nExpiration Date, unless the Market Outcome is under review pursuant to Rule 7.1.\\n\\nExpiration Date: When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event: The latest Expiration Date of\\nthe Contract shall be fourteen (14) calendar days after the originally scheduled date of the\\nevent. If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window, expiration will be moved to an\\nearlier date and time in accordance with Rule 7.2. When \\u003ctime period\\u003e is defined by specific\\ndates: The latest Expiration Date of the Contract shall be two weeks after the end of \\u003ctime\\nperiod\\u003e. If an event described in the Payout Criterion occurs and a consensus has been\\nreached on all terms, then expiration will be moved to an earlier date and time in accordance\\nwith Rule 7.2.\\n\\fExpiration time: The Expiration time of the Contract shall be 10:00 AM ET.\\n\\nSettlement Value: The Settlement Value for this Contract is $1.00.\\n\\nExpiration Value: The Expiration Value is the value of the Underlying as documented by the\\nSource Agency on the Expiration Date at the Expiration time.\\n\\nContingencies: Before Settlement, Kalshi may, at its sole discretion, initiate the Market\\nOutcome Review Process pursuant to Rule 7.1 of the Rulebook. If an Expiration Value cannot\\nbe determined on the Expiration Date, Kalshi has the right to determine payouts pursuant to\\nRule 7.1 in the Rulebook.\\n\\f\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-3 Official White House World Cup Drawing video page capture\\nSource capture from official White House page https://www.whitehouse.gov/videos/president-trump-attends-the-fifa-world-cup-drawing/\\nRetrieval: 2026-06-29T21:52:12Z via OpenClaw web_fetch and web.open.\\n\\nVisible page facts captured:\\n- Page title: President Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing\\n- Date shown on page: December 5, 2025\\n- Page section: Videos\\n- The page contains a link labeled View Full Video to Instagram.\\n- Related video listed: FIFA World Cup 2026 Draw at The Kennedy Center, duration 00:45, dated December 6, 2025.\\n- Related video listed: FIFA World Cup Drawing Announced to Take Place at The Kennedy Center, duration 00:56, dated August 23, 2025.\\n- Related video listed: President Trump on the 2026 FIFA World Cup, duration 01:22, dated May 6, 2025.\\n\\nRelevant extracted lines from web.open capture:\\nL142: Videos\\nL143: # President Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing\\nL145: December 5, 2025\\nL133: ... View Full Video [instagram.com] ...\\nL151: FIFA World Cup 2026 Draw at The Kennedy Center\\nL153: December 6, 2025\\nL167-L170: President Trump on the 2026 FIFA World Cup, May 6, 2025\\n\\nNotes on capture limits: readability extraction returned minimal content, so the above preserves visible lines from the page capture. The embedded/full video itself was not captured in this item.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-4 YouTube metadata capture for Ronaldo-at-FIFA-Draw clip\\nSource capture: YouTube watch page https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Cb2yO0lLEnM\\nVideo ID: Cb2yO0lLEnM\\nRetrieval: 2026-06-29T21:53:00Z via web search and curl of the YouTube watch page.\\n\\nCaptured title / page metadata:\\n- Title shown in search and page metadata: Trump Talks Cristiano Ronaldo at FIFA Draw — ‘He’s a Great Person’\\n- Channel shown in page metadata: interestingText You / @InterestingTextYou\\n- Subscriber count shown in page metadata at capture: about 10.3K subscribers\\n\\nCaptured description text from YouTube page metadata:\\n\\\"Trump Talks Cristiano Ronaldo at FIFA Draw — ‘He’s a Great Person’\\n\\nAt the FIFA World Cup Draw Ceremony, Donald Trump shared a story about meeting Cristiano Ronaldo at the White House. Trump said Ronaldo was “a great person” and even mentioned that Ronaldo spoke with his son about soccer during the visit.\\n\\nThis unexpected crossover between world politics and one of the biggest global sports stars quickly caught viewers' attention.\\n\\nTrump FIFA Draw\\nDonald Trump FIFA World Cup\\nTrump Cristiano Ronaldo\\nCristiano Ronaldo Trump meeting\\nFIFA World Cup draw 2026\\nRonaldo White House visit\\nTrump soccer comments\\nWorld Cup trending 2025\\nsports politics crossover\\nCristiano Ronaldo story\\nDonald Trump viral moment\\nFIFA draw ceremony Trump\\nWorld Cup 2026 news\\nRonaldo fan reaction\\npolitical celebrity moments\\nviral sports clips 2025\\nFIFA draw highlights\\nTrump speech FIFA\\nglobal sports news\\\"\\n\\nCapture limits and provenance caveat: direct video/caption extraction was attempted but YouTube transcript/open paths were throttled or unavailable in this environment. This item preserves the public watch-page metadata and description, not an independently extracted audio transcript. It is not an official White House or FIFA source.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-1 GovInfo official transcript: remarks prior to FIFA World Cup Draw\\nSource: GovInfo, Compilation of Presidential Documents, DCPD202501162\\nURL retrieved: https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/DCPD-202501162/html/DCPD-202501162.htm\\nRetrieval time: 2026-06-29T22:00:00Z\\nLocal captured HTML size/hash: 51,571 bytes; SHA-256 eadbceeecf3e94f5bd423bcb8e8511165fdc7265dd8c1e025870c2e8f34dfd99\\n\\nMaterial captured text from official GovInfo HTML/web.open:\\n\\nAdministration of Donald J. Trump, 2025\\n\\nTitle: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\nDate: December 5, 2025\\n\\nOpening note: [The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\\n\\nExcerpt - The President's Interest in Soccer (web.open lines 196-203):\\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\\\"football,\\\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\\n\\nExcerpt - The President's Interest in Soccer (web.open lines 322-329):\\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\\nThe President. But they have a little more speed. But no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\\n\\nTiming/context note (web.open lines 461-462):\\nNOTE: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. In his remarks, he referred to Trey Yingst, chief foreign correspondent, Fox News Channel; Cristiano Ronaldo, forward for Saudi Pro League club Al-Nass and Portugal's national soccer team; and Lionel Messi, forward for Major League Soccer club Inter Miami and Argentina's national team. A reporter referred to New York State Attorney General Letitia James.\\nThe transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\n\\nDocument category/location/name/subject metadata (web.open lines 463-468):\\nCategories: Interviews With the News Media: Exchanges with reporters, Washington, DC.\\nLocations: Washington, DC.\\nNames include: Cristiano Ronaldo and Lionel Messi.\\nSubjects include: Federation Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) World Cup; John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts; News media, Presidential interviews; Soccer.\\nDCPD Number: DCPD202501162.\\n\\nCapture limits: This item is a focused text capture of the material official transcript title, Ronaldo excerpts, timing/correction note, and metadata. It is not a full video or audio artifact. The official transcript itself notes some portions could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-2 FIFA official Final Draw start-time capture\\nSource: FIFA official page, FIFA World Cup 2026 Final Draw\\nURL: https://www.fifa.com/en/tournaments/mens/worldcup/canadamexicousa2026/live-draw\\nRetrieval time: 2026-06-29T22:01:00Z\\n\\nMaterial captured text from web search/open result:\\n- Page title/source: FIFA World Cup 2026™ Final Draw\\n- The draw takes place at the Kennedy Center in Washington DC, USA.\\n- The draw commences at 12:00 local time (17:00 UTC) on Friday 5 December 2025.\\n\\nCapture limits: This is a focused text capture of the official FIFA page timing statement located by web search. It is not a video capture of the draw ceremony.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-3 Governing PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION terms\\n                                         NEWMENTION\\n\\nScope: These rules shall apply to this contract.\\n\\nUnderlying: The Underlying for this Contract is words used by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nRevisions to the Underlying made after Expiration will not be accounted for in determining the\\nExpiration Value.\\n\\nSource Agency: The Source Agencies are \\u003csource\\u003e.\\n\\nType: The type of Contract is an Event Contract.\\n\\nIssuance: After the initial Contract, Contract iterations will be listed on an as-needed basis at\\nthe discretion of the Exchange and corresponding to the risk management needs of Members.\\n\\n\\u003centity\\u003e: \\u003centity\\u003e refers to the speaker, writer, performer, or communicator specified by the\\nExchange. This may include (but is not limited to): a specific named individual, multiple\\nindividuals specified using AND/OR logic, an individual identified by position or title, a group,\\nband, team or collective entity, a specified member or members of a group, an organization,\\ncompany, or institutional entity, or any combination of the aforementioned.\\n\\nWhen \\u003centity\\u003e is defined by a position or title, the Contract tracks whoever holds that position\\nduring \\u003ctime period\\u003e, even if the individual holding the position changes. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a\\nspecific named individual, the identity remains consistent throughout. Name changes (e.g.,\\nstage names, married names) do not create a new entity. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a group or\\norganization and the Contract does not specify particular members, any official\\ncommunication or statement by any member or designated spokesperson counts. When using\\nAND logic, all specified entities must independently say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e. When\\nusing OR logic, at least one of the specified entities must say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nThe Exchange may specify additional conditions such as “at least X members of” a group or\\n“the majority of” a group.\\n\\n\\u003csource\\u003e: \\u003csource\\u003e refers to a Source Agency or ordered collection of Source Agencies\\nspecified by the Exchange at the time of Contract listing, which will be incorporated into the\\nSource Agency hierarchy above and used to determine the occurrence of the Underlying.\\n\\u003csource\\u003e may refer to a singular agency, multiple agencies, an agency by distinguishing\\ncharacteristics, by category or type (e.g., “official government statistical body,” “primary wire\\nservice”), or any combination thereof. When multiple agencies are specified, they may be\\napplied in the hierarchical order designated by the Exchange if so specified, with the highest-\\nranked available and responsive agency taking precedence for purposes of determining the\\nExpiration Value. A lower-ranked agency shall only be consulted if all higher-ranked agencies\\nare unavailable, unresponsive, have not reported on the Underlying by the Expiration time, or\\nif the Exchange, in its sole discretion, determines that a higher-ranked agency’s reporting is\\nincomplete, erroneous, or otherwise insufficient to determine the Expiration Value. If \\u003csource\\u003e\\ndesignates multiple agencies without specifying a hierarchical order, the Exchange shall\\nresolve any conflict between reporting agencies at its sole discretion.\\n\\n\\u003cword\\u003e: \\u003cword\\u003e refers to the particular word or phrase potentially to be mentioned by\\n\\u003centity\\u003e. It may refer to a word being said a minimum number of times. It may also refer to\\none of multiple words/phrases, any of which are acceptable (e.g., “Doge/Dogecoin”).\\n\\f\\u003ctime period\\u003e: \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific range of time, event or discrete date and\\ntime specified by the Exchange. This may be defined by, but is not limited to: a specific event\\nor context (e.g., “during the State of the Union address”), exact dates or times, relative time\\nmarkers (e.g., “before July 1, 2027,” “in Q1 2026”), event-based periods (e.g., “during any\\ncampaign rally in October 2026,” “during the awards ceremony”), and broader intervals (e.g.,\\n“Q1–Q2 2027,” “January–March 2026”).\\n\\nUnless stated otherwise, “Between” is inclusive of both endpoints, while “before” and “after”\\nexclude the specified date. \\u003ctime period\\u003e may also refer to “Any” or “None”, to multiple dates\\n(even if non-consecutive), or to a singular and discrete date or time.\\n\\nWhen \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event (such as an address, speech, performance, or\\nbroadcast), the Exchange may specify what is included, including whether it includes both live\\nand pre-recorded segments (including whether advertisements are included). Where a\\ntimezone is not specified, ET is assumed.\\n\\n\\nPayout Criterion: The Payout Criterion for the Contract encompasses the Expiration Values that\\n\\u003cword\\u003e is said by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n\\n\\nThe word must appear as a distinct, standalone unit, not buried inside another word. Plural\\nand possessive noun forms count. Other grammatical changes (tense, conjugation, derivation)\\ndo not. If \\u003cword\\u003e appears separated from other words by a space or hyphen or in a\\ncompound form with a space or hyphen, it counts. If \\u003cword\\u003e is fused into a single\\nunhyphenated word, it does not count.\\n\\nIf \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled, and the market contains a\\nstrike stating “Event does not qualify/occur”, such a strike shall resolve “Yes” and all others\\n“No”. If \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled but such strikes are NOT\\nlisted, the Contracts will resolve to the last fair price determined at the discretion of the\\nExchange. If the event is postponed, and such a postponement is announced by the end of the\\nfollowing calendar day to be rescheduled to a time within 14 calendar days, the markets shall\\nremain open. If the event captured in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast, the\\nExchange may keep the market open for 24 hours for the release of an official recording.\\nFurther granular details on conditions for these Contracts is available below.\\n\\nAdditional clarification(s):\\n\\n     Possessive noun forms of \\u003cword\\u003e, plurals, and possessive plural noun forms are\\n     INCLUDED:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigrants” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Egg” → “eggs’ shells” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Russia” → “Russia’s” counts, “Russian” does not\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e exists only in adjective form, no plural form exists:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Economic” → “Economics” does not count (“Economic” is an adjective\\n          for which “Economics” is not a plural)\\n     Plural nouns occurring within proper nouns and noun phrases are included:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Cat” → “Cats the musical” counts\\n\\f    Grammatical variations beyond plurals/possessives are NOT included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigration” does NOT count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Run” → “Running” or “Ran” do NOT count\\n    When \\u003cword\\u003e specifies a plural form, the singular does NOT count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Veterans” → “Veteran” does NOT count\\n    Words that are spelled the same as the plural form of \\u003cword\\u003e (if such exists) but are\\n    themselves not a plural noun are included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Wind” → “Winds up the clock” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Border” → “The United States has strong borders” counts\\n    Open compounds (words separated by spaces) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fire station” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “couch” → “couch potato” counts\\n    Hyphenated compounds (words connected by hyphens) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Palestine” → “pro-Palestine” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fat” → “non-fat” counts\\n    Closed compounds (single word, no spaces/hyphens) do not count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire” does not count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firefighter” does not count\\n    Multi-word \\u003cword\\u003e in larger constructions: When \\u003cword\\u003e is a multi-word phrase\\n    appearing within a hyphenated construction, it counts only if \\u003cword\\u003e appears as a\\n    complete, unmodified element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “New York” → “New York-based” counts (complete element)\\n    Portmanteaus (words blended from two words where parts of each are combined) are\\n    NOT included unless the portmanteau clearly contains \\u003cword\\u003e as a distinct, unaltered\\n    element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “MAGA” → “MAGA-nificent” counts (MAGA appears as distinct element)\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “magnificent” → “MAGA-nificent” does NOT count (portmanteau blend)\\n\\nDictionary determination: Both the Merriam-Webster Dictionary (available online) AND the\\nOxford English Dictionary shall be used to determine compound type and/or conventional\\nspelling patterns. Inclusion in either dictionary as an open or hyphenated compound shall\\nsatisfy the Payout Criterion. If neither provides clarity (or the word is not included),\\ndetermination is based on whether written as single unit (closed/doesn’t count) vs. spaces or\\nhyphens (open or hyphenated/counts) and/or context and previous usage.\\n\\nPHONETIC EQUIVALENCIES\\n\\n    Homophones (same sound, different spelling) do not count:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “write” → “right” does not count\\n    Homonyms and homographs (same spelling) COUNT regardless of meaning or\\n    pronunciation:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “bass” → both “bass guitar” and “bass fishing” count\\n    Proper and common nouns are treated identically:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Apple” → both “Apple Inc.” and “apple” (fruit) count\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Will” → both “Will Smith” and “I will go” count\\n    Minor unintentional mispronunciations COUNT if context makes intent clear:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Mamdani” → “Mandani” counts\\n    Severe mispronunciations that make \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable do NOT count.\\n    Trademarked spellings do not count, even when pronounced identically, unless the word\\n\\fitself is the same:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “lift” → “Lyft” (pronounced “lift”) does not count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “uber” → “Uber” counts\\nWords with non-standard transliteration to English count within reason, provided they are\\nphonetically equivalent:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Zelensky” → any of “Zelenski,” “Zelenskii,” “Zelensky,” or “Zelenskiy”\\n      count if pronounced equivalently\\nContractions do not count for their constituent words unless otherwise explicitly specified\\nby the Exchange:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “not” → “won’t,” “can’t,” “don’t,” “isn’t” do not count\\nNumbers spoken as words COUNT, when spoken exactly (not part of a larger number):\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “five” → saying “five” or reading “$5” aloud as “five dollars” counts,\\n      saying “five hundred” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “410” → “four hundred ten”, “four one zero” or “four ten” counts\\nOrdinals COUNT when \\u003cword\\u003e is written numerically OR a phrase that includes a\\nnumber:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “January 6” → “January 6th” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “3” (written numerically) → “3rd” (spoken as “third”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Eight War” → “8 Wars” and “Eighth War” will count\\nCardinal and ordinal number words are distinct:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “one” → “first” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “first” → “one” does NOT count\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count when pronunciation or letter-by-letter spelling\\nmatches \\u003cword\\u003e:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “NASA” (pronounced “NAH-suh”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “N-A-S-A” (spelled out) counts\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count as \\u003cword\\u003e when pronounced as the full word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Doctor” → “Dr.” (pronounced “Doctor”) counts\\nExpanded forms of acronyms do NOT count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “AI” → “artificial intelligence” does not count\\nWords in foreign languages do NOT count unless they are perfect cognates with an\\nEnglish word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fuego” (Spanish) does NOT count\\nEnglish words within foreign sentences count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “policy” → “Nuestra policy es clara” counts\\n\\u003cword\\u003e in organization/company names counts:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Securities” → “Bank of America Securities” counts\\nWords in URLs, emails, handles, and hashtags (exclusive of domain structure, email\\nprovider or symbols) are treated as compounds when spoken as complete words, with the\\ntype of compound subject to aforementioned rules:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firestation.com” pronounced “fire station dot com” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire.com” pronounced “wildfire dot com” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “apple” → “apple.com” pronounced “apple dot com” does count\\n      When presented in URL, email, handle, or hashtag form, \\u003cword\\u003e shall be treated as\\n      a compound, not a multi-word word\\nSung, rapped, or poetic words COUNT if phonetically recognizable:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “money” → “moneyyy” (extended in rap) counts\\n      Extreme distortion making \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable does NOT count.\\nPhonetic alphabet spelling (“Foxtrot India Romeo Echo” for “FIRE”) does NOT count.\\n\\fCANCELLATIONS AND DELAYS\\n\\n   The Exchange may list an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike for any Contract. If listed,\\n   such a strike refers to the structural conditions of the market, and is NOT adjudicated as a\\n   \\u003cword\\u003e needing to be said by or validated by having been said by \\u003centity\\u003e. If listed, this\\n   strike resolves to “Yes” whenever the event fails to occur or qualify under the Payout\\n   Criterion, or any other circumstance prevents normal resolution.\\n   If no such strike is listed, and \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, the following rules\\n   apply if the event is cancelled, postponed, rescheduled, or materially altered (including\\n   being closed to press) such that no video is released within one calendar day of the\\n   original start time of the event:\\n         If the event is cancelled, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price determined in\\n         the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         If the event is postponed or rescheduled, the outcome depends on whether a new\\n         date is publicly announced within one calendar day (i.e. if the event was scheduled\\n         to begin on Monday, any time up to 11:59PM on Tuesday falls within this period) of\\n         the originally scheduled start time:\\n               If no new date is announced within one calendar day, the Contract will resolve\\n               to the last fair price determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n               If a new date is announced within one calendar day, the outcome depends on\\n               when the rescheduled event is set to occur:\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls within fourteen (14) calendar days of the\\n                     originally scheduled date, the Contract shall remain open and \\u003cword\\u003e\\n                     stated during the rescheduled event will count.\\n                           The fourteen-day window begins at 12:00 AM ET on the originally\\n                           scheduled date and ends at 11:59 PM ET fourteen days later, unless\\n                           an alternate timezone is explicitly specified.\\n                           Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the State of the Union on January\\n                           15, 2026” rescheduled to January 20, 2026 → words spoken during\\n                           the rescheduled address count.\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls more than fourteen (14) calendar days after\\n                     the originally scheduled date, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price\\n                     determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         Any Contract that cannot be resolved through the Source Agency hierarchy will\\n         instead be settled at the Last Fair Price. The Exchange will disclose the methodology\\n         used to determine the Last Fair Price (e.g., Last Traded Price, Time-Weighted\\n         Average Price) at the time of Issuance.\\n         If an event begins but is interrupted, abbreviated, or ends prematurely, words\\n         stated by \\u003centity\\u003e during the portion of the event that did occur will count and the\\n         market will otherwise resolve.\\n   If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window but the venue, format, or medium\\n   changes (e.g., moved to a different location, changed from in-person to virtual (with the\\n   exception of being closed to press)), words stated during the event will count.\\n   Special condition: Across both cases, whether an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike is\\n   listed or not, if the event specified as or in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast (or\\n   relayed as such) but the live stream/broadcast does not occur, the Exchange will instead\\n   use an officially released recording as the Underlying, and may delay resolution by up to\\n   one calendar day to allow for the release of such a recording.\\n\\f          If partial snippets are released, Contracts on words that do not appear will be\\n          resolved to last fair price, and Contracts on those that do will be resolved to “Yes”.\\n          If no recording is released, the relevant outcomes triggered by the\\n          presence/absence of an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike shall occur as outlined\\n          above.\\n\\nTECHNICAL DETAILS (UNLESS OTHERWISE SPECIFIED)\\n\\n     When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, pre-recorded content broadcast,\\n     streamed, or published as part of that event is included if presented as part of the official\\n     presentation.\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the concert” with pre-recorded video interlude\\n          where entity speaks → words from interlude count\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the television appearance” with pre-taped\\n          segment aired during broadcast → words from segment count\\n     Behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are NOT\\n     included unless officially broadcast or published as part of \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n     Subtitles and captions that display \\u003cword\\u003e on screen but are not spoken aloud by\\n     \\u003centity\\u003e do NOT count.\\n     Sign language interpretation or usage by entity does NOT count as saying \\u003cword\\u003e unless\\n     the Contract explicitly specifies that sign language counts.\\n     Text that entity displays on screen (presentation slides, teleprompter visible to audience,\\n     signatures) does NOT count unless entity reads it aloud.\\n     Content generated by AI, deepfakes, or synthetic voice technology impersonating entity\\n     does NOT count unless the synthetic content is officially commissioned, authorized, or\\n     published by entity, OR the Contract explicitly specifies that AI-generated content counts.\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e is muted due to technical failure or censorship it shall not count unless\\n     corroborating contextual evidence (including surrounding speech, or an official\\n     uncensored recording or transcript) confirms that \\u003centity\\u003e specifically uttered \\u003cword\\u003e\\n     during the muted period.\\n\\nMinimum Tick: The Minimum Tick size for the Contract shall be $0.01.\\n\\nPosition Accountability Level: The Position Accountability Level for the Contract shall be\\n$25,000 per strike, per Member.\\n\\nLast Trading Date: The Last Trading Date of the Contract will be the Expiration Date. The Last\\nTrading Time will be the Expiration time.\\n\\nSettlement Date: The Settlement Date of the Contract shall be no later than the day after the\\nExpiration Date, unless the Market Outcome is under review pursuant to Rule 7.1.\\n\\nExpiration Date: When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event: The latest Expiration Date of\\nthe Contract shall be fourteen (14) calendar days after the originally scheduled date of the\\nevent. If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window, expiration will be moved to an\\nearlier date and time in accordance with Rule 7.2. When \\u003ctime period\\u003e is defined by specific\\ndates: The latest Expiration Date of the Contract shall be two weeks after the end of \\u003ctime\\nperiod\\u003e. If an event described in the Payout Criterion occurs and a consensus has been\\nreached on all terms, then expiration will be moved to an earlier date and time in accordance\\nwith Rule 7.2.\\n\\fExpiration time: The Expiration time of the Contract shall be 10:00 AM ET.\\n\\nSettlement Value: The Settlement Value for this Contract is $1.00.\\n\\nExpiration Value: The Expiration Value is the value of the Underlying as documented by the\\nSource Agency on the Expiration Date at the Expiration time.\\n\\nContingencies: Before Settlement, Kalshi may, at its sole discretion, initiate the Market\\nOutcome Review Process pursuant to Rule 7.1 of the Rulebook. If an Expiration Value cannot\\nbe determined on the Expiration Date, Kalshi has the right to determine payouts pursuant to\\nRule 7.1 in the Rulebook.\\n\\f\\n\\n[defendant] DX-4 Market packet: Ronaldo strike and challenged No resolution\\nMarket URL: https://kalshi.com/markets/kxtrumpmentionb/trump-mention-b/kxtrumpmentionb-25dec06\\n\\nPublic market title: What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\n\\nContract family: PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION\\n\\nStrike at issue: Ronaldo\\n\\nChallenged resolution: No\\n\\nRequested resolution: Yes\\n\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R1 GovInfo transcript confirming Ronaldo utterances and Kennedy Center/FIFA Draw context\\nSource: GovInfo, Compilation of Presidential Documents, DCPD202501162\\nURL retrieved: https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/DCPD-202501162/html/DCPD-202501162.htm\\nRetrieval time: 2026-06-29T22:00:00Z\\nLocal captured HTML size/hash: 51,571 bytes; SHA-256 eadbceeecf3e94f5bd423bcb8e8511165fdc7265dd8c1e025870c2e8f34dfd99\\n\\nMaterial captured text from official GovInfo HTML/web.open:\\n\\nAdministration of Donald J. Trump, 2025\\n\\nTitle: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\nDate: December 5, 2025\\n\\nOpening note: [The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\\n\\nExcerpt - The President's Interest in Soccer (web.open lines 196-203):\\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\\\"football,\\\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\\n\\nExcerpt - The President's Interest in Soccer (web.open lines 322-329):\\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\\nThe President. But they have a little more speed. But no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\\n\\nTiming/context note (web.open lines 461-462):\\nNOTE: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. In his remarks, he referred to Trey Yingst, chief foreign correspondent, Fox News Channel; Cristiano Ronaldo, forward for Saudi Pro League club Al-Nass and Portugal's national soccer team; and Lionel Messi, forward for Major League Soccer club Inter Miami and Argentina's national team. A reporter referred to New York State Attorney General Letitia James.\\nThe transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\n\\nDocument category/location/name/subject metadata (web.open lines 463-468):\\nCategories: Interviews With the News Media: Exchanges with reporters, Washington, DC.\\nLocations: Washington, DC.\\nNames include: Cristiano Ronaldo and Lionel Messi.\\nSubjects include: Federation Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) World Cup; John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts; News media, Presidential interviews; Soccer.\\nDCPD Number: DCPD202501162.\\n\\nCapture limits: This item is a focused text capture of the material official transcript title, Ronaldo excerpts, timing/correction note, and metadata. It is not a full video or audio artifact. The official transcript itself notes some portions could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R2 FIFA timing capture showing formal commencement time but not market-specific exclusion\\nSource: FIFA official page, FIFA World Cup 2026 Final Draw\\nURL: https://www.fifa.com/en/tournaments/mens/worldcup/canadamexicousa2026/live-draw\\nRetrieval time: 2026-06-29T22:01:00Z\\n\\nMaterial captured text from web search/open result:\\n- Page title/source: FIFA World Cup 2026™ Final Draw\\n- The draw takes place at the Kennedy Center in Washington DC, USA.\\n- The draw commences at 12:00 local time (17:00 UTC) on Friday 5 December 2025.\\n\\nCapture limits: This is a focused text capture of the official FIFA page timing statement located by web search. It is not a video capture of the draw ceremony.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R3 Event-period terms and exclusions\\n                                         NEWMENTION\\n\\nScope: These rules shall apply to this contract.\\n\\nUnderlying: The Underlying for this Contract is words used by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nRevisions to the Underlying made after Expiration will not be accounted for in determining the\\nExpiration Value.\\n\\nSource Agency: The Source Agencies are \\u003csource\\u003e.\\n\\nType: The type of Contract is an Event Contract.\\n\\nIssuance: After the initial Contract, Contract iterations will be listed on an as-needed basis at\\nthe discretion of the Exchange and corresponding to the risk management needs of Members.\\n\\n\\u003centity\\u003e: \\u003centity\\u003e refers to the speaker, writer, performer, or communicator specified by the\\nExchange. This may include (but is not limited to): a specific named individual, multiple\\nindividuals specified using AND/OR logic, an individual identified by position or title, a group,\\nband, team or collective entity, a specified member or members of a group, an organization,\\ncompany, or institutional entity, or any combination of the aforementioned.\\n\\nWhen \\u003centity\\u003e is defined by a position or title, the Contract tracks whoever holds that position\\nduring \\u003ctime period\\u003e, even if the individual holding the position changes. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a\\nspecific named individual, the identity remains consistent throughout. Name changes (e.g.,\\nstage names, married names) do not create a new entity. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a group or\\norganization and the Contract does not specify particular members, any official\\ncommunication or statement by any member or designated spokesperson counts. When using\\nAND logic, all specified entities must independently say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e. When\\nusing OR logic, at least one of the specified entities must say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nThe Exchange may specify additional conditions such as “at least X members of” a group or\\n“the majority of” a group.\\n\\n\\u003csource\\u003e: \\u003csource\\u003e refers to a Source Agency or ordered collection of Source Agencies\\nspecified by the Exchange at the time of Contract listing, which will be incorporated into the\\nSource Agency hierarchy above and used to determine the occurrence of the Underlying.\\n\\u003csource\\u003e may refer to a singular agency, multiple agencies, an agency by distinguishing\\ncharacteristics, by category or type (e.g., “official government statistical body,” “primary wire\\nservice”), or any combination thereof. When multiple agencies are specified, they may be\\napplied in the hierarchical order designated by the Exchange if so specified, with the highest-\\nranked available and responsive agency taking precedence for purposes of determining the\\nExpiration Value. A lower-ranked agency shall only be consulted if all higher-ranked agencies\\nare unavailable, unresponsive, have not reported on the Underlying by the Expiration time, or\\nif the Exchange, in its sole discretion, determines that a higher-ranked agency’s reporting is\\nincomplete, erroneous, or otherwise insufficient to determine the Expiration Value. If \\u003csource\\u003e\\ndesignates multiple agencies without specifying a hierarchical order, the Exchange shall\\nresolve any conflict between reporting agencies at its sole discretion.\\n\\n\\u003cword\\u003e: \\u003cword\\u003e refers to the particular word or phrase potentially to be mentioned by\\n\\u003centity\\u003e. It may refer to a word being said a minimum number of times. It may also refer to\\none of multiple words/phrases, any of which are acceptable (e.g., “Doge/Dogecoin”).\\n\\f\\u003ctime period\\u003e: \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific range of time, event or discrete date and\\ntime specified by the Exchange. This may be defined by, but is not limited to: a specific event\\nor context (e.g., “during the State of the Union address”), exact dates or times, relative time\\nmarkers (e.g., “before July 1, 2027,” “in Q1 2026”), event-based periods (e.g., “during any\\ncampaign rally in October 2026,” “during the awards ceremony”), and broader intervals (e.g.,\\n“Q1–Q2 2027,” “January–March 2026”).\\n\\nUnless stated otherwise, “Between” is inclusive of both endpoints, while “before” and “after”\\nexclude the specified date. \\u003ctime period\\u003e may also refer to “Any” or “None”, to multiple dates\\n(even if non-consecutive), or to a singular and discrete date or time.\\n\\nWhen \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event (such as an address, speech, performance, or\\nbroadcast), the Exchange may specify what is included, including whether it includes both live\\nand pre-recorded segments (including whether advertisements are included). Where a\\ntimezone is not specified, ET is assumed.\\n\\n\\nPayout Criterion: The Payout Criterion for the Contract encompasses the Expiration Values that\\n\\u003cword\\u003e is said by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n\\n\\nThe word must appear as a distinct, standalone unit, not buried inside another word. Plural\\nand possessive noun forms count. Other grammatical changes (tense, conjugation, derivation)\\ndo not. If \\u003cword\\u003e appears separated from other words by a space or hyphen or in a\\ncompound form with a space or hyphen, it counts. If \\u003cword\\u003e is fused into a single\\nunhyphenated word, it does not count.\\n\\nIf \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled, and the market contains a\\nstrike stating “Event does not qualify/occur”, such a strike shall resolve “Yes” and all others\\n“No”. If \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled but such strikes are NOT\\nlisted, the Contracts will resolve to the last fair price determined at the discretion of the\\nExchange. If the event is postponed, and such a postponement is announced by the end of the\\nfollowing calendar day to be rescheduled to a time within 14 calendar days, the markets shall\\nremain open. If the event captured in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast, the\\nExchange may keep the market open for 24 hours for the release of an official recording.\\nFurther granular details on conditions for these Contracts is available below.\\n\\nAdditional clarification(s):\\n\\n     Possessive noun forms of \\u003cword\\u003e, plurals, and possessive plural noun forms are\\n     INCLUDED:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigrants” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Egg” → “eggs’ shells” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Russia” → “Russia’s” counts, “Russian” does not\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e exists only in adjective form, no plural form exists:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Economic” → “Economics” does not count (“Economic” is an adjective\\n          for which “Economics” is not a plural)\\n     Plural nouns occurring within proper nouns and noun phrases are included:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Cat” → “Cats the musical” counts\\n\\f    Grammatical variations beyond plurals/possessives are NOT included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigration” does NOT count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Run” → “Running” or “Ran” do NOT count\\n    When \\u003cword\\u003e specifies a plural form, the singular does NOT count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Veterans” → “Veteran” does NOT count\\n    Words that are spelled the same as the plural form of \\u003cword\\u003e (if such exists) but are\\n    themselves not a plural noun are included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Wind” → “Winds up the clock” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Border” → “The United States has strong borders” counts\\n    Open compounds (words separated by spaces) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fire station” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “couch” → “couch potato” counts\\n    Hyphenated compounds (words connected by hyphens) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Palestine” → “pro-Palestine” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fat” → “non-fat” counts\\n    Closed compounds (single word, no spaces/hyphens) do not count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire” does not count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firefighter” does not count\\n    Multi-word \\u003cword\\u003e in larger constructions: When \\u003cword\\u003e is a multi-word phrase\\n    appearing within a hyphenated construction, it counts only if \\u003cword\\u003e appears as a\\n    complete, unmodified element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “New York” → “New York-based” counts (complete element)\\n    Portmanteaus (words blended from two words where parts of each are combined) are\\n    NOT included unless the portmanteau clearly contains \\u003cword\\u003e as a distinct, unaltered\\n    element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “MAGA” → “MAGA-nificent” counts (MAGA appears as distinct element)\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “magnificent” → “MAGA-nificent” does NOT count (portmanteau blend)\\n\\nDictionary determination: Both the Merriam-Webster Dictionary (available online) AND the\\nOxford English Dictionary shall be used to determine compound type and/or conventional\\nspelling patterns. Inclusion in either dictionary as an open or hyphenated compound shall\\nsatisfy the Payout Criterion. If neither provides clarity (or the word is not included),\\ndetermination is based on whether written as single unit (closed/doesn’t count) vs. spaces or\\nhyphens (open or hyphenated/counts) and/or context and previous usage.\\n\\nPHONETIC EQUIVALENCIES\\n\\n    Homophones (same sound, different spelling) do not count:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “write” → “right” does not count\\n    Homonyms and homographs (same spelling) COUNT regardless of meaning or\\n    pronunciation:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “bass” → both “bass guitar” and “bass fishing” count\\n    Proper and common nouns are treated identically:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Apple” → both “Apple Inc.” and “apple” (fruit) count\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Will” → both “Will Smith” and “I will go” count\\n    Minor unintentional mispronunciations COUNT if context makes intent clear:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Mamdani” → “Mandani” counts\\n    Severe mispronunciations that make \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable do NOT count.\\n    Trademarked spellings do not count, even when pronounced identically, unless the word\\n\\fitself is the same:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “lift” → “Lyft” (pronounced “lift”) does not count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “uber” → “Uber” counts\\nWords with non-standard transliteration to English count within reason, provided they are\\nphonetically equivalent:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Zelensky” → any of “Zelenski,” “Zelenskii,” “Zelensky,” or “Zelenskiy”\\n      count if pronounced equivalently\\nContractions do not count for their constituent words unless otherwise explicitly specified\\nby the Exchange:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “not” → “won’t,” “can’t,” “don’t,” “isn’t” do not count\\nNumbers spoken as words COUNT, when spoken exactly (not part of a larger number):\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “five” → saying “five” or reading “$5” aloud as “five dollars” counts,\\n      saying “five hundred” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “410” → “four hundred ten”, “four one zero” or “four ten” counts\\nOrdinals COUNT when \\u003cword\\u003e is written numerically OR a phrase that includes a\\nnumber:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “January 6” → “January 6th” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “3” (written numerically) → “3rd” (spoken as “third”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Eight War” → “8 Wars” and “Eighth War” will count\\nCardinal and ordinal number words are distinct:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “one” → “first” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “first” → “one” does NOT count\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count when pronunciation or letter-by-letter spelling\\nmatches \\u003cword\\u003e:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “NASA” (pronounced “NAH-suh”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “N-A-S-A” (spelled out) counts\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count as \\u003cword\\u003e when pronounced as the full word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Doctor” → “Dr.” (pronounced “Doctor”) counts\\nExpanded forms of acronyms do NOT count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “AI” → “artificial intelligence” does not count\\nWords in foreign languages do NOT count unless they are perfect cognates with an\\nEnglish word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fuego” (Spanish) does NOT count\\nEnglish words within foreign sentences count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “policy” → “Nuestra policy es clara” counts\\n\\u003cword\\u003e in organization/company names counts:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Securities” → “Bank of America Securities” counts\\nWords in URLs, emails, handles, and hashtags (exclusive of domain structure, email\\nprovider or symbols) are treated as compounds when spoken as complete words, with the\\ntype of compound subject to aforementioned rules:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firestation.com” pronounced “fire station dot com” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire.com” pronounced “wildfire dot com” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “apple” → “apple.com” pronounced “apple dot com” does count\\n      When presented in URL, email, handle, or hashtag form, \\u003cword\\u003e shall be treated as\\n      a compound, not a multi-word word\\nSung, rapped, or poetic words COUNT if phonetically recognizable:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “money” → “moneyyy” (extended in rap) counts\\n      Extreme distortion making \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable does NOT count.\\nPhonetic alphabet spelling (“Foxtrot India Romeo Echo” for “FIRE”) does NOT count.\\n\\fCANCELLATIONS AND DELAYS\\n\\n   The Exchange may list an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike for any Contract. If listed,\\n   such a strike refers to the structural conditions of the market, and is NOT adjudicated as a\\n   \\u003cword\\u003e needing to be said by or validated by having been said by \\u003centity\\u003e. If listed, this\\n   strike resolves to “Yes” whenever the event fails to occur or qualify under the Payout\\n   Criterion, or any other circumstance prevents normal resolution.\\n   If no such strike is listed, and \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, the following rules\\n   apply if the event is cancelled, postponed, rescheduled, or materially altered (including\\n   being closed to press) such that no video is released within one calendar day of the\\n   original start time of the event:\\n         If the event is cancelled, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price determined in\\n         the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         If the event is postponed or rescheduled, the outcome depends on whether a new\\n         date is publicly announced within one calendar day (i.e. if the event was scheduled\\n         to begin on Monday, any time up to 11:59PM on Tuesday falls within this period) of\\n         the originally scheduled start time:\\n               If no new date is announced within one calendar day, the Contract will resolve\\n               to the last fair price determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n               If a new date is announced within one calendar day, the outcome depends on\\n               when the rescheduled event is set to occur:\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls within fourteen (14) calendar days of the\\n                     originally scheduled date, the Contract shall remain open and \\u003cword\\u003e\\n                     stated during the rescheduled event will count.\\n                           The fourteen-day window begins at 12:00 AM ET on the originally\\n                           scheduled date and ends at 11:59 PM ET fourteen days later, unless\\n                           an alternate timezone is explicitly specified.\\n                           Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the State of the Union on January\\n                           15, 2026” rescheduled to January 20, 2026 → words spoken during\\n                           the rescheduled address count.\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls more than fourteen (14) calendar days after\\n                     the originally scheduled date, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price\\n                     determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         Any Contract that cannot be resolved through the Source Agency hierarchy will\\n         instead be settled at the Last Fair Price. The Exchange will disclose the methodology\\n         used to determine the Last Fair Price (e.g., Last Traded Price, Time-Weighted\\n         Average Price) at the time of Issuance.\\n         If an event begins but is interrupted, abbreviated, or ends prematurely, words\\n         stated by \\u003centity\\u003e during the portion of the event that did occur will count and the\\n         market will otherwise resolve.\\n   If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window but the venue, format, or medium\\n   changes (e.g., moved to a different location, changed from in-person to virtual (with the\\n   exception of being closed to press)), words stated during the event will count.\\n   Special condition: Across both cases, whether an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike is\\n   listed or not, if the event specified as or in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast (or\\n   relayed as such) but the live stream/broadcast does not occur, the Exchange will instead\\n   use an officially released recording as the Underlying, and may delay resolution by up to\\n   one calendar day to allow for the release of such a recording.\\n\\f          If partial snippets are released, Contracts on words that do not appear will be\\n          resolved to last fair price, and Contracts on those that do will be resolved to “Yes”.\\n          If no recording is released, the relevant outcomes triggered by the\\n          presence/absence of an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike shall occur as outlined\\n          above.\\n\\nTECHNICAL DETAILS (UNLESS OTHERWISE SPECIFIED)\\n\\n     When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, pre-recorded content broadcast,\\n     streamed, or published as part of that event is included if presented as part of the official\\n     presentation.\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the concert” with pre-recorded video interlude\\n          where entity speaks → words from interlude count\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the television appearance” with pre-taped\\n          segment aired during broadcast → words from segment count\\n     Behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are NOT\\n     included unless officially broadcast or published as part of \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n     Subtitles and captions that display \\u003cword\\u003e on screen but are not spoken aloud by\\n     \\u003centity\\u003e do NOT count.\\n     Sign language interpretation or usage by entity does NOT count as saying \\u003cword\\u003e unless\\n     the Contract explicitly specifies that sign language counts.\\n     Text that entity displays on screen (presentation slides, teleprompter visible to audience,\\n     signatures) does NOT count unless entity reads it aloud.\\n     Content generated by AI, deepfakes, or synthetic voice technology impersonating entity\\n     does NOT count unless the synthetic content is officially commissioned, authorized, or\\n     published by entity, OR the Contract explicitly specifies that AI-generated content counts.\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e is muted due to technical failure or censorship it shall not count unless\\n     corroborating contextual evidence (including surrounding speech, or an official\\n     uncensored recording or transcript) confirms that \\u003centity\\u003e specifically uttered \\u003cword\\u003e\\n     during the muted period.\\n\\nMinimum Tick: The Minimum Tick size for the Contract shall be $0.01.\\n\\nPosition Accountability Level: The Position Accountability Level for the Contract shall be\\n$25,000 per strike, per Member.\\n\\nLast Trading Date: The Last Trading Date of the Contract will be the Expiration Date. The Last\\nTrading Time will be the Expiration time.\\n\\nSettlement Date: The Settlement Date of the Contract shall be no later than the day after the\\nExpiration Date, unless the Market Outcome is under review pursuant to Rule 7.1.\\n\\nExpiration Date: When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event: The latest Expiration Date of\\nthe Contract shall be fourteen (14) calendar days after the originally scheduled date of the\\nevent. If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window, expiration will be moved to an\\nearlier date and time in accordance with Rule 7.2. When \\u003ctime period\\u003e is defined by specific\\ndates: The latest Expiration Date of the Contract shall be two weeks after the end of \\u003ctime\\nperiod\\u003e. If an event described in the Payout Criterion occurs and a consensus has been\\nreached on all terms, then expiration will be moved to an earlier date and time in accordance\\nwith Rule 7.2.\\n\\fExpiration time: The Expiration time of the Contract shall be 10:00 AM ET.\\n\\nSettlement Value: The Settlement Value for this Contract is $1.00.\\n\\nExpiration Value: The Expiration Value is the value of the Underlying as documented by the\\nSource Agency on the Expiration Date at the Expiration time.\\n\\nContingencies: Before Settlement, Kalshi may, at its sole discretion, initiate the Market\\nOutcome Review Process pursuant to Rule 7.1 of the Rulebook. If an Expiration Value cannot\\nbe determined on the Expiration Date, Kalshi has the right to determine payouts pursuant to\\nRule 7.1 in the Rulebook.\\n\\f\\n\\n[defendant] DX-S1 GovInfo official transcript: prior reporter exchange\\nSource: GovInfo, Compilation of Presidential Documents, DCPD202501162\\nURL retrieved: https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/DCPD-202501162/html/DCPD-202501162.htm\\nRetrieval time: 2026-06-29T22:00:00Z\\nLocal captured HTML size/hash: 51,571 bytes; SHA-256 eadbceeecf3e94f5bd423bcb8e8511165fdc7265dd8c1e025870c2e8f34dfd99\\n\\nMaterial captured text from official GovInfo HTML/web.open:\\n\\nAdministration of Donald J. Trump, 2025\\n\\nTitle: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\nDate: December 5, 2025\\n\\nOpening note: [The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\\n\\nExcerpt - The President's Interest in Soccer (web.open lines 196-203):\\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\\\"football,\\\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\\n\\nExcerpt - The President's Interest in Soccer (web.open lines 322-329):\\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\\nThe President. But they have a little more speed. But no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\\n\\nTiming/context note (web.open lines 461-462):\\nNOTE: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. In his remarks, he referred to Trey Yingst, chief foreign correspondent, Fox News Channel; Cristiano Ronaldo, forward for Saudi Pro League club Al-Nass and Portugal's national soccer team; and Lionel Messi, forward for Major League Soccer club Inter Miami and Argentina's national team. A reporter referred to New York State Attorney General Letitia James.\\nThe transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\n\\nDocument category/location/name/subject metadata (web.open lines 463-468):\\nCategories: Interviews With the News Media: Exchanges with reporters, Washington, DC.\\nLocations: Washington, DC.\\nNames include: Cristiano Ronaldo and Lionel Messi.\\nSubjects include: Federation Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) World Cup; John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts; News media, Presidential interviews; Soccer.\\nDCPD Number: DCPD202501162.\\n\\nCapture limits: This item is a focused text capture of the material official transcript title, Ronaldo excerpts, timing/correction note, and metadata. It is not a full video or audio artifact. The official transcript itself notes some portions could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-S2 FIFA official draw commencement time\\nSource: FIFA official page, FIFA World Cup 2026 Final Draw\\nURL: https://www.fifa.com/en/tournaments/mens/worldcup/canadamexicousa2026/live-draw\\nRetrieval time: 2026-06-29T22:01:00Z\\n\\nMaterial captured text from web search/open result:\\n- Page title/source: FIFA World Cup 2026™ Final Draw\\n- The draw takes place at the Kennedy Center in Washington DC, USA.\\n- The draw commences at 12:00 local time (17:00 UTC) on Friday 5 December 2025.\\n\\nCapture limits: This is a focused text capture of the official FIFA page timing statement located by web search. It is not a video capture of the draw ceremony.\\n\\nSubmitted evidence:\\n[plaintiff arguments] Official White House video page capture: President Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing (ev_db357d4e9407_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-db357d4e9407)\\nSource: https://www.whitehouse.gov/videos/president-trump-attends-the-fifa-world-cup-drawing/\\nSHA-256: `db357d4e940728d417ae4f7f3caac6b78d3fd3e4aba70d46fe10c6132d45997a`\\nBytes: 1300\\nRelevance: Establishes that the White House officially published a video page titled President Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing, dated December 5, 2025, with a full-video link and related World Cup Draw videos; relevant to source chain and event context.\\n\\n[plaintiff arguments] YouTube metadata capture: Trump Talks Cristiano Ronaldo at FIFA Draw (ev_4e1045905547_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-4e1045905547)\\nSource: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Cb2yO0lLEnM\\nSHA-256: `4e10459055477440085fe5e20d970eb2488e61d13a5e2b3133a3656bed7526d7`\\nBytes: 1779\\nRelevance: Provides a public clip source and page metadata asserting that at the FIFA World Cup Draw Ceremony Trump shared a story about meeting Cristiano Ronaldo and said Ronaldo was a great person; relevant to the alleged Ronaldo utterance, though weaker than an official full transcript or video.\\n\\n[defendant arguments] GovInfo official transcript capture: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the FIFA World Cup Draw (ev_a1b1f6b1b7bd_submitted-evidence-03-defendant-a1b1f6b1b7bd)\\nSource: https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/DCPD-202501162/html/DCPD-202501162.htm\\nSHA-256: `a1b1f6b1b7bd0b691c7fe8d97467dd0d085e2b22387ae4198270764de66e56e2`\\nBytes: 3070\\nRelevance: Official transcript identifies the relevant Trump remarks as an exchange with reporters prior to the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw; it includes the Ronaldo utterances and timing/correction notes, directly bearing on whether the utterances were during the countable event period.\\n\\n[defendant arguments] FIFA official page capture: 2026 World Cup Final Draw start time (ev_3973dc8f98c0_submitted-evidence-04-defendant-3973dc8f98c0)\\nSource: https://www.fifa.com/en/tournaments/mens/worldcup/canadamexicousa2026/live-draw\\nSHA-256: `3973dc8f98c01702174f61f5548eb1e80efe64dd72b44f21ed0fa7d944f93248`\\nBytes: 598\\nRelevance: Establishes the official Final Draw start time as 12:00 local time on December 5, 2025, which helps compare the draw event period against the GovInfo transcript note that the reporter exchange occurred at 11:13 a.m.\\n\\nTechnical reports:\\n[plaintiff] Plaintiff source-search and capture ledger\\nSearched exact market/strike phrases, White House domain, public video pages, YouTube video IDs, and Kalshi live market URL. Submitted official White House page capture and YouTube metadata capture. Kalshi live page returned a Vercel security checkpoint/429; local browser was unavailable; Python pip/ensurepip unavailable for yt-dlp; direct YouTube caption/open paths were throttled or unavailable. Remaining best evidence would be a full official video/transcript or Kalshi resolution rationale if later accessible.\\n\\n[defendant] Defendant source-search and capture ledger\\nInspected current AAR evidence and exact contents of plaintiff's White House and YouTube captures. Retrieved GovInfo official HTML transcript with curl from DCPD-202501162; local full HTML was 51,571 bytes with SHA-256 eadbceeecf3e94f5bd423bcb8e8511165fdc7265dd8c1e025870c2e8f34dfd99, then submitted a focused material text capture as DX-1. Searched official draw timing and submitted the FIFA official page timing statement as DX-2. Remaining gaps: full Kalshi market source hierarchy/resolution rationale and full WH/FIFA video were not captured, but official GovInfo timing/title plus FIFA start time resolve the material timing issue.\\n\\nCall submit_council_vote with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated.\\nKeep the rationale brief: no more than three sentences.\\n\\nCouncil API instructions:\\nYou are a council member. Decide the proposition from the admitted record.\\nYou may examine admitted evidence through read-only tools when exact bytes, metadata, or exhibit contents matter.\\nDo not search the web, introduce new facts, create new evidence, or upload evidence.\\nWhen ready, call submit_council_vote exactly once with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated and a concise rationale.\\n\",\"state\":\"ready\",\"status\":\"ready\",\"tools\":[{\"description\":\"Return the current visible arbitration record for this council member.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"get_case\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"List visible immutable record evidence.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"list_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Return metadata and read limits for one visible evidence item.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"stat_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Read a bounded byte range from one visible evidence item as base64.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"length\":{\"minimum\":1,\"type\":\"integer\"},\"offset\":{\"minimum\":0,\"type\":\"integer\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\",\"offset\",\"length\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"read_evidence_range\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Submit one council vote for the current deliberation opportunity.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"rationale\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"vote\":{\"enum\":[\"demonstrated\",\"not_demonstrated\"],\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"vote\",\"rationale\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"submit_council_vote\",\"read_only\":false}],\"turn\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"completed\":false,\"deadline\":\"2026-06-29T22:18:45.386037689Z\",\"deliberation_round\":1,\"member_id\":\"C2\",\"opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C2\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"remaining_ms\":889046,\"role_id\":\"council\",\"turn_number\":10},\"wait\":{\"reason\":\"ready\",\"state_version\":14,\"version\":17}}"}],"details":{"mode":"call","mcpResult":{"content":[{"type":"text","text":"ok: true\nstatus: ready\nstate: ready\nmessage: An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\nafter_version: 17\nafter_opportunity_id: deliberation:1:C2\nmember_id: C2\ncase_id: arb-ex03a-20260629214245\nwait_reason: ready\nphase: deliberation\nopportunity_id: deliberation:1:C2\nremaining_ms: 889046\nattempts_remaining: 3\njson: {\"after_opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C2\",\"after_version\":17,\"case_id\":\"arb-ex03a-20260629214245\",\"limits\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"max_evidence_read_bytes\":65536,\"max_evidence_read_bytes_per_opportunity\":524288,\"max_evidence_reads_per_opportunity\":32,\"max_response_bytes\":131072,\"remaining_evidence_read_bytes_for_opportunity\":524288,\"remaining_evidence_reads_for_opportunity\":32},\"member_id\":\"C2\",\"message\":\"An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\",\"ok\":true,\"prompt\":\"Role: council member\\nMember ID: C2\\nDeliberation round: 1\\nProposition: For the Kalshi market \\\"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\\", the strike \\\"Ronaldo\\\" should resolve Yes because Trump said \\\"Ronaldo\\\" in public remarks at the World Cup Draw venue immediately before the formal program, and the market wording plus the governing mention-market terms did not clearly exclude those event-linked remarks.\\nStandard of evidence: Preponderance of the evidence.\\nPersona:\\nYou are a careful juror and council member.\\n\\nEvaluate the record faithfully. Decide only from the evidence, the stated rules, and the applicable burden of proof. Do not favor either side, fill gaps with speculation, or ignore uncertainty.\\n\\nGive weight to reliable sources, direct evidence, consistent reasoning, and clear admissions. Discount unsupported claims, rhetorical force, irrelevant facts, and conclusions that exceed the record.\\n\\nWhen the evidence supports one answer, state it plainly. When the evidence is incomplete or balanced, say so. Be concise, honest, and exact.\\n\\nRecord:\\nOpenings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, this case is not about whether the word \\\"Ronaldo\\\" would count if President Trump clearly said it. The current packet makes that part straightforward: the market is the Kalshi PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION market titled \\\"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\\"; the strike is \\\"Ronaldo\\\"; Kalshi’s challenged resolution is No; and plaintiff seeks Yes.\\n\\nThe real dispute is temporal and contextual. Did the market phrase \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw,\\\" read with the governing mention-market terms, include public event-linked remarks at the World Cup Draw venue immediately before the formal draw program? Or did it clearly confine countable words to a narrower formal broadcast segment? Plaintiff’s position is that a No resolution cannot stand unless the record shows that the counting window clearly excluded those event-linked remarks.\\n\\nThe admitted terms matter. They define the underlying as words used by the specified entity during the specified time period. They expressly recognize event-based time periods, and they say the payout criterion is satisfied when the word is said by the entity during that period. They also contain exclusions: behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings do not count unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period; captions or text alone do not count; and the word must appear as a distinct standalone unit. Those exclusions are important, but they do not by themselves answer this case. A public remark at the event venue, tied to the Draw and immediately before the formal program, is not automatically a rehearsal, sound check, or private behind-the-scenes moment.\\n\\nAt this opening stage, the record proves the market identity, the challenged resolution, the requested resolution, and the generic governing terms. It does not yet prove the utterance itself, the exact sequence of the venue remarks, the source-agency hierarchy or any market-specific time-period language beyond the packet, or Kalshi’s reason for treating the strike as No. Those are the factual links that should decide the case under a preponderance standard.\\n\\nPlaintiff expects the decisive proof to be the full official or otherwise reliable event video or transcript, with enough surrounding context to show whether Trump said \\\"Ronaldo\\\" aloud as a standalone word; when he said it relative to the Draw event; whether the remarks were public and event-linked rather than backstage or a sound check; and whether any market-specific rule clearly excluded that segment. Plaintiff also expects the market page, archived market details, and any resolution rationale to be important because ambiguity in the market’s own event wording should not be resolved against Yes after the fact.\\n\\nThe defense will likely argue that \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw\\\" means only the formal draw ceremony or broadcast, and that anything before the formal program is outside the counting period. That theory can win only if the evidence shows a clear exclusion or a source record that separates the alleged remarks from the event itself. If the evidence instead shows public remarks at the Draw venue, officially connected to the event, immediately before the formal program, and no clear rule excluding them, then the terms favor counting the word and resolving the Ronaldo strike Yes.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the defense position is straightforward: the admitted record does not yet prove that the Ronaldo strike should resolve Yes. It proves a market title, a generic mention-market rule set, and Kalshi's challenged No resolution. It does not prove that any qualifying utterance of \\\"Ronaldo\\\" occurred during the market's countable time period.\\n\\nThe plaintiff's opening usefully narrows the dispute. This is not primarily a word-boundary case. If President Trump said \\\"Ronaldo\\\" as a standalone spoken word during the countable FIFA World Cup Draw period, the generic terms would ordinarily treat that as the kind of word that can count. The real question is whether plaintiff can carry the burden of showing that alleged pre-program, venue-adjacent remarks were part of the market's specified time period: \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\\\"\\n\\nThe case-packet terms matter, but they cut both ways. They say the underlying is words used by the entity during the specified time period. They recognize that a time period can be an event, and they allow the Exchange to specify what is included when an event is involved. They also distinguish official event presentation from material outside the event: behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are not included unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period; text or captions alone do not count; and the relevant word must be spoken aloud by the entity. Those provisions do not support a rule that every public comment inside the same building, or every press exchange near the formal program, is automatically \\\"during\\\" the Draw.\\n\\nThat is the burden problem for plaintiff. The admitted market-page file identifies the public title, contract family, strike, challenged resolution, and requested resolution. It does not supply a full market-specific source hierarchy, a formal start time, a transcript, a video, a resolution rationale, or the alleged remarks. The terms file supplies the generic framework, but not the factual bridge from \\\"immediately before the formal program\\\" to \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\\\" Without that bridge, the No resolution is not shown to be wrong by a preponderance of the evidence.\\n\\nThe defense expects the decisive proof to be source-chain evidence, not characterization. The council should want the market's full rule page if available, the source agency hierarchy, the official draw program or broadcast, any official transcript or recording of the alleged exchange, and enough surrounding timestamps to separate the formal draw from pre-event reporter access, red-carpet exchanges, arrivals, or other ancillary material. If later evidence shows that the alleged Ronaldo comment was in a segment officially presented as part of the Draw itself, plaintiff's argument becomes stronger. If the evidence instead shows a separate exchange with reporters before the draw, or an event-linked but pre-program interaction not incorporated into the official presentation, the generic terms support Kalshi's No.\\n\\nSo the defense opening is not that the word Ronaldo could never count. It is that this record has not established the necessary time-period link. The proposition asks the council to overturn No because the market wording and terms did not clearly exclude pre-program remarks. That reverses the burden. Plaintiff must show that the remarks were included in the countable period. Ambiguity about the outer edge of an event is not the same as proof that a specific pre-event utterance satisfies the payout criterion.\\n\\nArguments:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, plaintiff has now supplied the record links that were missing at opening.\\n\\nFirst, the market packet fixes what this dispute is: the Kalshi market title is \\\"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\\"; the contract family is PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION; the strike is \\\"Ronaldo\\\"; Kalshi's challenged resolution is No; and plaintiff seeks Yes. That is PX-1.\\n\\nSecond, the governing terms make this an event-period mention question, not a narrow formal-program-only question. PX-2 says the underlying is words used by the entity during the time period, recognizes that a time period may be a specific event, and sets the payout criterion as the word being said by the entity during that period. It also tells us what does not count: text/captions alone, unofficial behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, and sound checks unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. Those exclusions matter, but none says that public event-linked remarks at the venue immediately before the formal program are categorically outside \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\\\"\\n\\nThird, the source-chain evidence now points to the disputed event and the Ronaldo utterance. PX-3 is an official White House page titled \\\"President Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing,\\\" dated December 5, 2025, with a full-video link and related World Cup Draw videos. That establishes an official White House event-video source for Trump's attendance at the World Cup Drawing. PX-4 is a public YouTube watch-page metadata capture for video ID Cb2yO0lLEnM, titled \\\"Trump Talks Cristiano Ronaldo at FIFA Draw -- 'He's a Great Person'.\\\" Its description states that at the FIFA World Cup Draw Ceremony, Trump shared a story about meeting Cristiano Ronaldo at the White House, said Ronaldo was a great person, and mentioned Ronaldo spoke with his son. PX-4 is not as strong as an official transcript, and plaintiff says that plainly. But it is admitted source content that directly links Trump, Cristiano Ronaldo, and the FIFA Draw ceremony.\\n\\nOn a preponderance standard, that is enough to defeat the challenged No resolution unless the defense can supply a clearer exclusion. The market did not ask only what Trump would say during the ball-pulling segment, during the televised main show, or after a particular formal start cue. It asked what he would say \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\\\" The terms recognize event-based periods and exclude particular non-event categories. A public remark at the Draw venue, tied to the Draw, is far closer to the event period than to a rehearsal, sound check, caption, or private backstage recording.\\n\\nThe defense's burden framing is too strict. Plaintiff must prove Yes by a preponderance; plaintiff need not prove that Kalshi drafted every boundary with perfect precision. Once the admitted sources show a Ronaldo mention in connection with the FIFA Draw ceremony, the remaining question is whether the rules clearly remove that event-linked remark from the counting period. They do not. Ambiguity in a mention market's event wording should not be converted into an unstated formal-program limitation after the fact.\\n\\nProvenance and gaps: plaintiff attempted to retrieve the live Kalshi page, official/full video, caption, and transcript. Kalshi returned a Vercel security checkpoint; the local browser tool was unavailable; Python pip/ensurepip was unavailable for yt-dlp; and direct YouTube caption/open paths were throttled or unavailable. That leaves PX-4 weaker than ideal, but not weightless. PX-3 supplies official event context, PX-4 supplies the Ronaldo-at-FIFA-Draw metadata, and PX-2 supplies the rule that event-linked spoken words count absent a clear exclusion.\\n\\nThe council should resolve the proposition Yes: the Ronaldo strike should have resolved Yes because the record more likely than not shows Trump said Ronaldo in public remarks tied to the FIFA World Cup Draw, and the market wording plus governing terms did not clearly exclude those remarks.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the merits record now shows why the challenged No resolution should stand.\\n\\nPlaintiff's best point is that Trump did say the word \\\"Ronaldo.\\\" The defense does not need to fight that. The question is whether he said it during the market's countable time period: \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\\\" On that decisive question, the strongest official sources favor No.\\n\\nThe admitted GovInfo transcript, DX-1, is an official Compilation of Presidential Documents capture. Its title is not merely \\\"World Cup Draw\\\" or \\\"FIFA ceremony.\\\" It is \\\"Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw.\\\" That same transcript contains the Ronaldo passages: Trump says he met Ronaldo at the White House, later says he was \\\"not Ronaldo or Messi,\\\" and the note identifies Ronaldo among the people referenced. So DX-1 is not adverse to the defense because it confirms the word; it is decisive because it places the word in an exchange with reporters prior to the Draw.\\n\\nDX-2 supplies the timing anchor. The official FIFA Final Draw page states that the Draw at the Kennedy Center commenced at 12:00 local time on Friday, December 5, 2025. DX-1 states that the President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the Kennedy Center. A reporter exchange at 11:13, officially titled as prior to a 12:00 draw, is not more likely than not \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\\\" It is before it.\\n\\nThat reading matches the governing PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION terms. PX-2 says the payout criterion is satisfied when the word is said by the entity during the specified time period. It recognizes event-based periods and permits the Exchange to specify what is included for an event. It also treats official presentation differently from adjacent material: pre-recorded content counts if presented as part of the official event presentation, while behind-the-scenes, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings do not count unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. The point is not that this reporter exchange was a rehearsal or sound check. The point is that the terms require a link to the time period itself. Plaintiff has supplied no market-specific language saying pre-event reporter availability, arrivals, or venue interviews count as part of the Draw.\\n\\nPlaintiff's new exhibits do not fill that gap. PX-3, the White House page capture, establishes that the White House had a page titled \\\"President Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing,\\\" but plaintiff's own capture says the embedded/full video was not captured. It does not prove that the Ronaldo words occurred inside the official draw program. PX-4 is weaker still: it is metadata from a nonofficial YouTube channel. It says the clip is about Trump talking Ronaldo at the FIFA Draw, but it is not a transcript, not an official source, and not an audio extraction. When a nonofficial clip description is weighed against GovInfo's official transcript title and FIFA's official start time, the official sources control.\\n\\nNor is this a burden-shifting problem. The proposition asks the council to overturn Kalshi's No because the market supposedly did not clearly exclude remarks immediately before the formal program. But the preponderance burden is on Yes. The record must show that the strike satisfied the payout criterion. The admitted terms do not say that ambiguous pre-event remarks count by default; they say the word must be said during the specified time period. Here, the best evidence identifies the remarks as prior to the Draw and before the official commencement time.\\n\\nProvenance also matters. DX-1 is an official government transcript with a correction note and an audio-incomplete caveat. That caveat affects stray inaudible portions, but it does not weaken the title, the 11:13 timing note, or the Ronaldo passages preserved in the transcript. DX-2 is an official FIFA timing source. Plaintiff's YouTube metadata may explain why the dispute arose, but it cannot outweigh those primary sources on timing and event classification.\\n\\nThe council should resolve the proposition against plaintiff. Trump said Ronaldo, but the record more likely shows he did so in a reporter exchange prior to the FIFA World Cup Draw, not during the countable Draw event. Kalshi's No resolution should be upheld.\\n\\nRebuttals:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, defendant’s new evidence narrows the case but does not end it.\\n\\nPlaintiff accepts the important parts of DX-1 and DX-2. The GovInfo transcript is official; it labels the item an exchange with reporters \\\"Prior to\\\" the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw; it places the exchange at 11:13 a.m. at the Kennedy Center; and the FIFA capture states the draw commenced at 12:00 local time. Plaintiff should not pretend those facts are weak.\\n\\nBut defendant asks those facts to do more than they do. The market was not drafted as \\\"what will Trump say after the official 12:00 commencement,\\\" \\\"during the televised draw program,\\\" or \\\"during the ball-drawing segment.\\\" PX-1 says the public market title was \\\"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\\" That is ordinary event language, and PX-2 recognizes event-based time periods while leaving room for the Exchange to specify what is included. The record still contains no market-specific exclusion for official venue press remarks immediately before the formal program.\\n\\nDX-1 also helps plaintiff on the facts defendant originally said were missing. It confirms the relevant spoken word. Trump said he met Ronaldo, that Ronaldo is great, and that he was not Ronaldo or Messi. It also places those remarks at the Kennedy Center in a FIFA World Cup Draw-centered exchange with reporters, not in an unrelated private dinner or stale campaign setting. The transcript’s own subject metadata includes the FIFA World Cup, the Kennedy Center, news media, presidential interviews, and soccer. That is event-linked public context.\\n\\nThe terms’ exclusions do not fit defendant’s leap. PX-2 excludes captions alone, rehearsals, sound checks, behind-the-scenes content, and unofficial recordings unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. DX-1 is not a rehearsal transcript. It is not a sound check. It is not merely a caption. It is an official presidential transcript of a public reporter exchange at the venue, released in the Compilation of Presidential Documents. If Kalshi meant to exclude that category because it occurred before a formal noon commencement, the market needed to say so clearly.\\n\\nSo the dispositive question remains one of market construction: does \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw\\\" clearly exclude public, official, event-site remarks immediately before the formal program? Defendant has proved \\\"prior to\\\" the formal draw start. Defendant has not proved a clear market rule that treats the broader Draw event as beginning only at 12:00 for mention purposes.\\n\\nUnder a preponderance standard, the record now confirms the Ronaldo utterance and confirms the FIFA Draw setting. The challenged No resolution should not be upheld by importing a narrow formal-program limitation that the market title and generic terms did not state.\\n\\nSurrebuttals:\\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff's rebuttal usefully clarifies the remaining dispute: plaintiff accepts that DX-1 is official, that it labels the relevant item an exchange with reporters \\\"Prior to\\\" the FIFA World Cup Draw, that the exchange occurred at 11:13 a.m. at the Kennedy Center, and that DX-2 places the official Draw commencement at 12:00 local time. Those concessions should decide the case.\\n\\nPlaintiff's answer is that the market did not say \\\"after 12:00,\\\" \\\"during the televised program,\\\" or \\\"during the ball-drawing segment.\\\" But the market also did not say \\\"at the venue before the Draw,\\\" \\\"in pre-event reporter exchanges,\\\" or \\\"in any public remarks connected to the Draw.\\\" The phrase it chose was \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\\\" Ordinary event language has a start, and the official FIFA source fixes that start at noon. Official GovInfo then fixes this exchange at 11:13 and titles it as prior to the Draw.\\n\\nThat is not a technicality. The terms require the word to be said during the specified time period. They recognize event-based periods and allow event-specific inclusions, but no admitted market-specific rule includes pre-event press access. Plaintiff's construction would turn any event-adjacent public remark into part of the event unless expressly excluded. That reverses the payout criterion. The claimant must show the word occurred during the time period; it is not enough to show the same venue, the same general topic, and official publication.\\n\\nPlaintiff says the exclusions do not fit because DX-1 is not a rehearsal, sound check, caption, or private backstage recording. Fair enough; the defense is not relying on those categories as labels. The defense relies on the affirmative timing requirement. A remark need not be a rehearsal to be outside the event. A reporter exchange officially described as prior to a noon event and occurring at 11:13 is outside because it is before the event began.\\n\\nThe record therefore proves the wrong fact for plaintiff. It proves Trump said Ronaldo, but in a pre-event reporter exchange. The proposition requires Yes only if those words count during the FIFA World Cup Draw. On this record, they do not. Kalshi's No resolution should be upheld.\\n\\nClosings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the final record leaves one legal question.\\n\\nThe easy factual question is resolved in plaintiff’s favor: Trump said \\\"Ronaldo.\\\" The official GovInfo transcript confirms it twice in substance: he said he met Ronaldo, praised him, and later said he was not Ronaldo or Messi. That is a spoken standalone use of the strike word. The record also places the remarks at the Kennedy Center in a FIFA World Cup Draw-centered reporter exchange. This was not an unrelated dinner, a caption, an AI voice, or a social-media paraphrase.\\n\\nThe hard point is timing. Defendant has the strongest evidence on the formal program boundary: GovInfo titled the exchange as \\\"Prior to\\\" the Draw, notes 11:13 a.m., and FIFA states the Final Draw commenced at 12:00 local time. Plaintiff does not ask the council to ignore that. The question is what the Kalshi market actually required.\\n\\nPX-1 did not say \\\"after 12:00.\\\" It did not say \\\"during the televised draw program\\\" or \\\"during the ball-drawing segment.\\\" It asked, in public market wording, \\\"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\\" PX-2’s generic terms recognize event-based periods and say the Exchange may specify what is included when a time period refers to an event. They also give specific exclusions: captions alone, rehearsals, sound checks, behind-the-scenes content, and unofficial recordings unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. None of those exclusions is this case. The GovInfo transcript is an official public presidential record of an event-site reporter exchange, not a rehearsal or sound check.\\n\\nDefendant’s best argument is that ordinary events have start times. True. But this market dispute is about public remarks at the venue immediately before the formal program, in the official context of the Draw, where the market and rules did not clearly define a noon-only boundary. If Kalshi wanted that narrower rule, it could have said so in the strike, the market title, or the event inclusion language. It did not.\\n\\nThe preponderance record therefore shows: Ronaldo was spoken; the remarks were public and officially documented; they were at the Kennedy Center in the FIFA World Cup Draw setting; and the governing market language did not clearly exclude that immediately-before-program event context. The challenged No resolution depends on importing a formal commencement limitation that is absent from the market packet.\\n\\nFor that reason, the Ronaldo strike should resolve Yes.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the closing record is narrow and concrete.\\n\\nEveryone now agrees on the easy fact: Trump said \\\"Ronaldo.\\\" The official GovInfo transcript proves that. But the proposition is not simply that Trump said the word somewhere near the FIFA World Cup Draw. The proposition asks you to overturn Kalshi's No because remarks immediately before the formal program should count under a market asking what Trump would say \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\\\" Plaintiff has not carried that burden.\\n\\nThe two strongest sources are official and aligned. GovInfo, in DX-1, titles the relevant document \\\"Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw.\\\" It notes that the President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the Kennedy Center. FIFA, in DX-2, states that the Final Draw commenced at 12:00 local time. Those facts are not peripheral. They answer the timing question: the Ronaldo words were in a reporter exchange before the Draw began.\\n\\nPlaintiff's closing says the market did not specify \\\"after 12:00,\\\" \\\"during the televised draw program,\\\" or \\\"during the ball-drawing segment.\\\" True, but that does not prove Yes. The market did specify \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\\\" The ordinary function of \\\"during\\\" is to define the event period, not to include anything public, official, and thematically related that happens beforehand. A 47-minute-before reporter exchange officially titled as prior to the Draw is outside that period unless the market or governing terms affirmatively include it. The record contains no such inclusion.\\n\\nThe governing terms reinforce that conclusion. They require the word to be said by the entity during the specified time period. They recognize event-based periods and allow the Exchange to specify event inclusions. They include official-presentation concepts for material presented as part of an event. But they do not say that pre-event press availability counts by default. Plaintiff's argument turns the absence of an exclusion into proof of inclusion. That is backwards under a preponderance standard.\\n\\nPlaintiff also leans on setting: Kennedy Center, FIFA World Cup subject matter, official transcript, public reporters. Those facts show why the issue is understandable. They do not move 11:13 into a 12:00 event. A source can be official and still describe something outside the event. Indeed, that is exactly what DX-1 does: it officially documents the remarks and officially labels them prior to the Draw.\\n\\nThe weaker evidence points the same way once weighed properly. The White House page capture does not include the video or transcript. The YouTube metadata is nonofficial and not an audio transcript. Neither overcomes GovInfo's title and timing note plus FIFA's commencement time.\\n\\nSo the final answer is simple: the word was spoken, but not during the countable event period shown by the best evidence. Plaintiff has not shown that Kalshi's No resolution was wrong. The council should reject the proposition and uphold No.\\n\\nExhibits:\\n[plaintiff] PX-1 Market page packet: Ronaldo strike and challenged No resolution\\nMarket URL: https://kalshi.com/markets/kxtrumpmentionb/trump-mention-b/kxtrumpmentionb-25dec06\\n\\nPublic market title: What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\n\\nContract family: PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION\\n\\nStrike at issue: Ronaldo\\n\\nChallenged resolution: No\\n\\nRequested resolution: Yes\\n\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-2 Governing PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION terms\\n                                         NEWMENTION\\n\\nScope: These rules shall apply to this contract.\\n\\nUnderlying: The Underlying for this Contract is words used by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nRevisions to the Underlying made after Expiration will not be accounted for in determining the\\nExpiration Value.\\n\\nSource Agency: The Source Agencies are \\u003csource\\u003e.\\n\\nType: The type of Contract is an Event Contract.\\n\\nIssuance: After the initial Contract, Contract iterations will be listed on an as-needed basis at\\nthe discretion of the Exchange and corresponding to the risk management needs of Members.\\n\\n\\u003centity\\u003e: \\u003centity\\u003e refers to the speaker, writer, performer, or communicator specified by the\\nExchange. This may include (but is not limited to): a specific named individual, multiple\\nindividuals specified using AND/OR logic, an individual identified by position or title, a group,\\nband, team or collective entity, a specified member or members of a group, an organization,\\ncompany, or institutional entity, or any combination of the aforementioned.\\n\\nWhen \\u003centity\\u003e is defined by a position or title, the Contract tracks whoever holds that position\\nduring \\u003ctime period\\u003e, even if the individual holding the position changes. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a\\nspecific named individual, the identity remains consistent throughout. Name changes (e.g.,\\nstage names, married names) do not create a new entity. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a group or\\norganization and the Contract does not specify particular members, any official\\ncommunication or statement by any member or designated spokesperson counts. When using\\nAND logic, all specified entities must independently say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e. When\\nusing OR logic, at least one of the specified entities must say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nThe Exchange may specify additional conditions such as “at least X members of” a group or\\n“the majority of” a group.\\n\\n\\u003csource\\u003e: \\u003csource\\u003e refers to a Source Agency or ordered collection of Source Agencies\\nspecified by the Exchange at the time of Contract listing, which will be incorporated into the\\nSource Agency hierarchy above and used to determine the occurrence of the Underlying.\\n\\u003csource\\u003e may refer to a singular agency, multiple agencies, an agency by distinguishing\\ncharacteristics, by category or type (e.g., “official government statistical body,” “primary wire\\nservice”), or any combination thereof. When multiple agencies are specified, they may be\\napplied in the hierarchical order designated by the Exchange if so specified, with the highest-\\nranked available and responsive agency taking precedence for purposes of determining the\\nExpiration Value. A lower-ranked agency shall only be consulted if all higher-ranked agencies\\nare unavailable, unresponsive, have not reported on the Underlying by the Expiration time, or\\nif the Exchange, in its sole discretion, determines that a higher-ranked agency’s reporting is\\nincomplete, erroneous, or otherwise insufficient to determine the Expiration Value. If \\u003csource\\u003e\\ndesignates multiple agencies without specifying a hierarchical order, the Exchange shall\\nresolve any conflict between reporting agencies at its sole discretion.\\n\\n\\u003cword\\u003e: \\u003cword\\u003e refers to the particular word or phrase potentially to be mentioned by\\n\\u003centity\\u003e. It may refer to a word being said a minimum number of times. It may also refer to\\none of multiple words/phrases, any of which are acceptable (e.g., “Doge/Dogecoin”).\\n\\f\\u003ctime period\\u003e: \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific range of time, event or discrete date and\\ntime specified by the Exchange. This may be defined by, but is not limited to: a specific event\\nor context (e.g., “during the State of the Union address”), exact dates or times, relative time\\nmarkers (e.g., “before July 1, 2027,” “in Q1 2026”), event-based periods (e.g., “during any\\ncampaign rally in October 2026,” “during the awards ceremony”), and broader intervals (e.g.,\\n“Q1–Q2 2027,” “January–March 2026”).\\n\\nUnless stated otherwise, “Between” is inclusive of both endpoints, while “before” and “after”\\nexclude the specified date. \\u003ctime period\\u003e may also refer to “Any” or “None”, to multiple dates\\n(even if non-consecutive), or to a singular and discrete date or time.\\n\\nWhen \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event (such as an address, speech, performance, or\\nbroadcast), the Exchange may specify what is included, including whether it includes both live\\nand pre-recorded segments (including whether advertisements are included). Where a\\ntimezone is not specified, ET is assumed.\\n\\n\\nPayout Criterion: The Payout Criterion for the Contract encompasses the Expiration Values that\\n\\u003cword\\u003e is said by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n\\n\\nThe word must appear as a distinct, standalone unit, not buried inside another word. Plural\\nand possessive noun forms count. Other grammatical changes (tense, conjugation, derivation)\\ndo not. If \\u003cword\\u003e appears separated from other words by a space or hyphen or in a\\ncompound form with a space or hyphen, it counts. If \\u003cword\\u003e is fused into a single\\nunhyphenated word, it does not count.\\n\\nIf \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled, and the market contains a\\nstrike stating “Event does not qualify/occur”, such a strike shall resolve “Yes” and all others\\n“No”. If \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled but such strikes are NOT\\nlisted, the Contracts will resolve to the last fair price determined at the discretion of the\\nExchange. If the event is postponed, and such a postponement is announced by the end of the\\nfollowing calendar day to be rescheduled to a time within 14 calendar days, the markets shall\\nremain open. If the event captured in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast, the\\nExchange may keep the market open for 24 hours for the release of an official recording.\\nFurther granular details on conditions for these Contracts is available below.\\n\\nAdditional clarification(s):\\n\\n     Possessive noun forms of \\u003cword\\u003e, plurals, and possessive plural noun forms are\\n     INCLUDED:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigrants” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Egg” → “eggs’ shells” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Russia” → “Russia’s” counts, “Russian” does not\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e exists only in adjective form, no plural form exists:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Economic” → “Economics” does not count (“Economic” is an adjective\\n          for which “Economics” is not a plural)\\n     Plural nouns occurring within proper nouns and noun phrases are included:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Cat” → “Cats the musical” counts\\n\\f    Grammatical variations beyond plurals/possessives are NOT included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigration” does NOT count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Run” → “Running” or “Ran” do NOT count\\n    When \\u003cword\\u003e specifies a plural form, the singular does NOT count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Veterans” → “Veteran” does NOT count\\n    Words that are spelled the same as the plural form of \\u003cword\\u003e (if such exists) but are\\n    themselves not a plural noun are included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Wind” → “Winds up the clock” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Border” → “The United States has strong borders” counts\\n    Open compounds (words separated by spaces) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fire station” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “couch” → “couch potato” counts\\n    Hyphenated compounds (words connected by hyphens) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Palestine” → “pro-Palestine” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fat” → “non-fat” counts\\n    Closed compounds (single word, no spaces/hyphens) do not count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire” does not count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firefighter” does not count\\n    Multi-word \\u003cword\\u003e in larger constructions: When \\u003cword\\u003e is a multi-word phrase\\n    appearing within a hyphenated construction, it counts only if \\u003cword\\u003e appears as a\\n    complete, unmodified element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “New York” → “New York-based” counts (complete element)\\n    Portmanteaus (words blended from two words where parts of each are combined) are\\n    NOT included unless the portmanteau clearly contains \\u003cword\\u003e as a distinct, unaltered\\n    element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “MAGA” → “MAGA-nificent” counts (MAGA appears as distinct element)\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “magnificent” → “MAGA-nificent” does NOT count (portmanteau blend)\\n\\nDictionary determination: Both the Merriam-Webster Dictionary (available online) AND the\\nOxford English Dictionary shall be used to determine compound type and/or conventional\\nspelling patterns. Inclusion in either dictionary as an open or hyphenated compound shall\\nsatisfy the Payout Criterion. If neither provides clarity (or the word is not included),\\ndetermination is based on whether written as single unit (closed/doesn’t count) vs. spaces or\\nhyphens (open or hyphenated/counts) and/or context and previous usage.\\n\\nPHONETIC EQUIVALENCIES\\n\\n    Homophones (same sound, different spelling) do not count:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “write” → “right” does not count\\n    Homonyms and homographs (same spelling) COUNT regardless of meaning or\\n    pronunciation:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “bass” → both “bass guitar” and “bass fishing” count\\n    Proper and common nouns are treated identically:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Apple” → both “Apple Inc.” and “apple” (fruit) count\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Will” → both “Will Smith” and “I will go” count\\n    Minor unintentional mispronunciations COUNT if context makes intent clear:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Mamdani” → “Mandani” counts\\n    Severe mispronunciations that make \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable do NOT count.\\n    Trademarked spellings do not count, even when pronounced identically, unless the word\\n\\fitself is the same:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “lift” → “Lyft” (pronounced “lift”) does not count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “uber” → “Uber” counts\\nWords with non-standard transliteration to English count within reason, provided they are\\nphonetically equivalent:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Zelensky” → any of “Zelenski,” “Zelenskii,” “Zelensky,” or “Zelenskiy”\\n      count if pronounced equivalently\\nContractions do not count for their constituent words unless otherwise explicitly specified\\nby the Exchange:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “not” → “won’t,” “can’t,” “don’t,” “isn’t” do not count\\nNumbers spoken as words COUNT, when spoken exactly (not part of a larger number):\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “five” → saying “five” or reading “$5” aloud as “five dollars” counts,\\n      saying “five hundred” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “410” → “four hundred ten”, “four one zero” or “four ten” counts\\nOrdinals COUNT when \\u003cword\\u003e is written numerically OR a phrase that includes a\\nnumber:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “January 6” → “January 6th” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “3” (written numerically) → “3rd” (spoken as “third”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Eight War” → “8 Wars” and “Eighth War” will count\\nCardinal and ordinal number words are distinct:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “one” → “first” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “first” → “one” does NOT count\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count when pronunciation or letter-by-letter spelling\\nmatches \\u003cword\\u003e:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “NASA” (pronounced “NAH-suh”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “N-A-S-A” (spelled out) counts\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count as \\u003cword\\u003e when pronounced as the full word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Doctor” → “Dr.” (pronounced “Doctor”) counts\\nExpanded forms of acronyms do NOT count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “AI” → “artificial intelligence” does not count\\nWords in foreign languages do NOT count unless they are perfect cognates with an\\nEnglish word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fuego” (Spanish) does NOT count\\nEnglish words within foreign sentences count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “policy” → “Nuestra policy es clara” counts\\n\\u003cword\\u003e in organization/company names counts:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Securities” → “Bank of America Securities” counts\\nWords in URLs, emails, handles, and hashtags (exclusive of domain structure, email\\nprovider or symbols) are treated as compounds when spoken as complete words, with the\\ntype of compound subject to aforementioned rules:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firestation.com” pronounced “fire station dot com” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire.com” pronounced “wildfire dot com” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “apple” → “apple.com” pronounced “apple dot com” does count\\n      When presented in URL, email, handle, or hashtag form, \\u003cword\\u003e shall be treated as\\n      a compound, not a multi-word word\\nSung, rapped, or poetic words COUNT if phonetically recognizable:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “money” → “moneyyy” (extended in rap) counts\\n      Extreme distortion making \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable does NOT count.\\nPhonetic alphabet spelling (“Foxtrot India Romeo Echo” for “FIRE”) does NOT count.\\n\\fCANCELLATIONS AND DELAYS\\n\\n   The Exchange may list an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike for any Contract. If listed,\\n   such a strike refers to the structural conditions of the market, and is NOT adjudicated as a\\n   \\u003cword\\u003e needing to be said by or validated by having been said by \\u003centity\\u003e. If listed, this\\n   strike resolves to “Yes” whenever the event fails to occur or qualify under the Payout\\n   Criterion, or any other circumstance prevents normal resolution.\\n   If no such strike is listed, and \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, the following rules\\n   apply if the event is cancelled, postponed, rescheduled, or materially altered (including\\n   being closed to press) such that no video is released within one calendar day of the\\n   original start time of the event:\\n         If the event is cancelled, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price determined in\\n         the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         If the event is postponed or rescheduled, the outcome depends on whether a new\\n         date is publicly announced within one calendar day (i.e. if the event was scheduled\\n         to begin on Monday, any time up to 11:59PM on Tuesday falls within this period) of\\n         the originally scheduled start time:\\n               If no new date is announced within one calendar day, the Contract will resolve\\n               to the last fair price determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n               If a new date is announced within one calendar day, the outcome depends on\\n               when the rescheduled event is set to occur:\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls within fourteen (14) calendar days of the\\n                     originally scheduled date, the Contract shall remain open and \\u003cword\\u003e\\n                     stated during the rescheduled event will count.\\n                           The fourteen-day window begins at 12:00 AM ET on the originally\\n                           scheduled date and ends at 11:59 PM ET fourteen days later, unless\\n                           an alternate timezone is explicitly specified.\\n                           Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the State of the Union on January\\n                           15, 2026” rescheduled to January 20, 2026 → words spoken during\\n                           the rescheduled address count.\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls more than fourteen (14) calendar days after\\n                     the originally scheduled date, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price\\n                     determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         Any Contract that cannot be resolved through the Source Agency hierarchy will\\n         instead be settled at the Last Fair Price. The Exchange will disclose the methodology\\n         used to determine the Last Fair Price (e.g., Last Traded Price, Time-Weighted\\n         Average Price) at the time of Issuance.\\n         If an event begins but is interrupted, abbreviated, or ends prematurely, words\\n         stated by \\u003centity\\u003e during the portion of the event that did occur will count and the\\n         market will otherwise resolve.\\n   If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window but the venue, format, or medium\\n   changes (e.g., moved to a different location, changed from in-person to virtual (with the\\n   exception of being closed to press)), words stated during the event will count.\\n   Special condition: Across both cases, whether an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike is\\n   listed or not, if the event specified as or in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast (or\\n   relayed as such) but the live stream/broadcast does not occur, the Exchange will instead\\n   use an officially released recording as the Underlying, and may delay resolution by up to\\n   one calendar day to allow for the release of such a recording.\\n\\f          If partial snippets are released, Contracts on words that do not appear will be\\n          resolved to last fair price, and Contracts on those that do will be resolved to “Yes”.\\n          If no recording is released, the relevant outcomes triggered by the\\n          presence/absence of an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike shall occur as outlined\\n          above.\\n\\nTECHNICAL DETAILS (UNLESS OTHERWISE SPECIFIED)\\n\\n     When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, pre-recorded content broadcast,\\n     streamed, or published as part of that event is included if presented as part of the official\\n     presentation.\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the concert” with pre-recorded video interlude\\n          where entity speaks → words from interlude count\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the television appearance” with pre-taped\\n          segment aired during broadcast → words from segment count\\n     Behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are NOT\\n     included unless officially broadcast or published as part of \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n     Subtitles and captions that display \\u003cword\\u003e on screen but are not spoken aloud by\\n     \\u003centity\\u003e do NOT count.\\n     Sign language interpretation or usage by entity does NOT count as saying \\u003cword\\u003e unless\\n     the Contract explicitly specifies that sign language counts.\\n     Text that entity displays on screen (presentation slides, teleprompter visible to audience,\\n     signatures) does NOT count unless entity reads it aloud.\\n     Content generated by AI, deepfakes, or synthetic voice technology impersonating entity\\n     does NOT count unless the synthetic content is officially commissioned, authorized, or\\n     published by entity, OR the Contract explicitly specifies that AI-generated content counts.\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e is muted due to technical failure or censorship it shall not count unless\\n     corroborating contextual evidence (including surrounding speech, or an official\\n     uncensored recording or transcript) confirms that \\u003centity\\u003e specifically uttered \\u003cword\\u003e\\n     during the muted period.\\n\\nMinimum Tick: The Minimum Tick size for the Contract shall be $0.01.\\n\\nPosition Accountability Level: The Position Accountability Level for the Contract shall be\\n$25,000 per strike, per Member.\\n\\nLast Trading Date: The Last Trading Date of the Contract will be the Expiration Date. The Last\\nTrading Time will be the Expiration time.\\n\\nSettlement Date: The Settlement Date of the Contract shall be no later than the day after the\\nExpiration Date, unless the Market Outcome is under review pursuant to Rule 7.1.\\n\\nExpiration Date: When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event: The latest Expiration Date of\\nthe Contract shall be fourteen (14) calendar days after the originally scheduled date of the\\nevent. If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window, expiration will be moved to an\\nearlier date and time in accordance with Rule 7.2. When \\u003ctime period\\u003e is defined by specific\\ndates: The latest Expiration Date of the Contract shall be two weeks after the end of \\u003ctime\\nperiod\\u003e. If an event described in the Payout Criterion occurs and a consensus has been\\nreached on all terms, then expiration will be moved to an earlier date and time in accordance\\nwith Rule 7.2.\\n\\fExpiration time: The Expiration time of the Contract shall be 10:00 AM ET.\\n\\nSettlement Value: The Settlement Value for this Contract is $1.00.\\n\\nExpiration Value: The Expiration Value is the value of the Underlying as documented by the\\nSource Agency on the Expiration Date at the Expiration time.\\n\\nContingencies: Before Settlement, Kalshi may, at its sole discretion, initiate the Market\\nOutcome Review Process pursuant to Rule 7.1 of the Rulebook. If an Expiration Value cannot\\nbe determined on the Expiration Date, Kalshi has the right to determine payouts pursuant to\\nRule 7.1 in the Rulebook.\\n\\f\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-3 Official White House World Cup Drawing video page capture\\nSource capture from official White House page https://www.whitehouse.gov/videos/president-trump-attends-the-fifa-world-cup-drawing/\\nRetrieval: 2026-06-29T21:52:12Z via OpenClaw web_fetch and web.open.\\n\\nVisible page facts captured:\\n- Page title: President Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing\\n- Date shown on page: December 5, 2025\\n- Page section: Videos\\n- The page contains a link labeled View Full Video to Instagram.\\n- Related video listed: FIFA World Cup 2026 Draw at The Kennedy Center, duration 00:45, dated December 6, 2025.\\n- Related video listed: FIFA World Cup Drawing Announced to Take Place at The Kennedy Center, duration 00:56, dated August 23, 2025.\\n- Related video listed: President Trump on the 2026 FIFA World Cup, duration 01:22, dated May 6, 2025.\\n\\nRelevant extracted lines from web.open capture:\\nL142: Videos\\nL143: # President Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing\\nL145: December 5, 2025\\nL133: ... View Full Video [instagram.com] ...\\nL151: FIFA World Cup 2026 Draw at The Kennedy Center\\nL153: December 6, 2025\\nL167-L170: President Trump on the 2026 FIFA World Cup, May 6, 2025\\n\\nNotes on capture limits: readability extraction returned minimal content, so the above preserves visible lines from the page capture. The embedded/full video itself was not captured in this item.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-4 YouTube metadata capture for Ronaldo-at-FIFA-Draw clip\\nSource capture: YouTube watch page https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Cb2yO0lLEnM\\nVideo ID: Cb2yO0lLEnM\\nRetrieval: 2026-06-29T21:53:00Z via web search and curl of the YouTube watch page.\\n\\nCaptured title / page metadata:\\n- Title shown in search and page metadata: Trump Talks Cristiano Ronaldo at FIFA Draw — ‘He’s a Great Person’\\n- Channel shown in page metadata: interestingText You / @InterestingTextYou\\n- Subscriber count shown in page metadata at capture: about 10.3K subscribers\\n\\nCaptured description text from YouTube page metadata:\\n\\\"Trump Talks Cristiano Ronaldo at FIFA Draw — ‘He’s a Great Person’\\n\\nAt the FIFA World Cup Draw Ceremony, Donald Trump shared a story about meeting Cristiano Ronaldo at the White House. Trump said Ronaldo was “a great person” and even mentioned that Ronaldo spoke with his son about soccer during the visit.\\n\\nThis unexpected crossover between world politics and one of the biggest global sports stars quickly caught viewers' attention.\\n\\nTrump FIFA Draw\\nDonald Trump FIFA World Cup\\nTrump Cristiano Ronaldo\\nCristiano Ronaldo Trump meeting\\nFIFA World Cup draw 2026\\nRonaldo White House visit\\nTrump soccer comments\\nWorld Cup trending 2025\\nsports politics crossover\\nCristiano Ronaldo story\\nDonald Trump viral moment\\nFIFA draw ceremony Trump\\nWorld Cup 2026 news\\nRonaldo fan reaction\\npolitical celebrity moments\\nviral sports clips 2025\\nFIFA draw highlights\\nTrump speech FIFA\\nglobal sports news\\\"\\n\\nCapture limits and provenance caveat: direct video/caption extraction was attempted but YouTube transcript/open paths were throttled or unavailable in this environment. This item preserves the public watch-page metadata and description, not an independently extracted audio transcript. It is not an official White House or FIFA source.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-1 GovInfo official transcript: remarks prior to FIFA World Cup Draw\\nSource: GovInfo, Compilation of Presidential Documents, DCPD202501162\\nURL retrieved: https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/DCPD-202501162/html/DCPD-202501162.htm\\nRetrieval time: 2026-06-29T22:00:00Z\\nLocal captured HTML size/hash: 51,571 bytes; SHA-256 eadbceeecf3e94f5bd423bcb8e8511165fdc7265dd8c1e025870c2e8f34dfd99\\n\\nMaterial captured text from official GovInfo HTML/web.open:\\n\\nAdministration of Donald J. Trump, 2025\\n\\nTitle: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\nDate: December 5, 2025\\n\\nOpening note: [The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\\n\\nExcerpt - The President's Interest in Soccer (web.open lines 196-203):\\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\\\"football,\\\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\\n\\nExcerpt - The President's Interest in Soccer (web.open lines 322-329):\\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\\nThe President. But they have a little more speed. But no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\\n\\nTiming/context note (web.open lines 461-462):\\nNOTE: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. In his remarks, he referred to Trey Yingst, chief foreign correspondent, Fox News Channel; Cristiano Ronaldo, forward for Saudi Pro League club Al-Nass and Portugal's national soccer team; and Lionel Messi, forward for Major League Soccer club Inter Miami and Argentina's national team. A reporter referred to New York State Attorney General Letitia James.\\nThe transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\n\\nDocument category/location/name/subject metadata (web.open lines 463-468):\\nCategories: Interviews With the News Media: Exchanges with reporters, Washington, DC.\\nLocations: Washington, DC.\\nNames include: Cristiano Ronaldo and Lionel Messi.\\nSubjects include: Federation Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) World Cup; John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts; News media, Presidential interviews; Soccer.\\nDCPD Number: DCPD202501162.\\n\\nCapture limits: This item is a focused text capture of the material official transcript title, Ronaldo excerpts, timing/correction note, and metadata. It is not a full video or audio artifact. The official transcript itself notes some portions could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-2 FIFA official Final Draw start-time capture\\nSource: FIFA official page, FIFA World Cup 2026 Final Draw\\nURL: https://www.fifa.com/en/tournaments/mens/worldcup/canadamexicousa2026/live-draw\\nRetrieval time: 2026-06-29T22:01:00Z\\n\\nMaterial captured text from web search/open result:\\n- Page title/source: FIFA World Cup 2026™ Final Draw\\n- The draw takes place at the Kennedy Center in Washington DC, USA.\\n- The draw commences at 12:00 local time (17:00 UTC) on Friday 5 December 2025.\\n\\nCapture limits: This is a focused text capture of the official FIFA page timing statement located by web search. It is not a video capture of the draw ceremony.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-3 Governing PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION terms\\n                                         NEWMENTION\\n\\nScope: These rules shall apply to this contract.\\n\\nUnderlying: The Underlying for this Contract is words used by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nRevisions to the Underlying made after Expiration will not be accounted for in determining the\\nExpiration Value.\\n\\nSource Agency: The Source Agencies are \\u003csource\\u003e.\\n\\nType: The type of Contract is an Event Contract.\\n\\nIssuance: After the initial Contract, Contract iterations will be listed on an as-needed basis at\\nthe discretion of the Exchange and corresponding to the risk management needs of Members.\\n\\n\\u003centity\\u003e: \\u003centity\\u003e refers to the speaker, writer, performer, or communicator specified by the\\nExchange. This may include (but is not limited to): a specific named individual, multiple\\nindividuals specified using AND/OR logic, an individual identified by position or title, a group,\\nband, team or collective entity, a specified member or members of a group, an organization,\\ncompany, or institutional entity, or any combination of the aforementioned.\\n\\nWhen \\u003centity\\u003e is defined by a position or title, the Contract tracks whoever holds that position\\nduring \\u003ctime period\\u003e, even if the individual holding the position changes. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a\\nspecific named individual, the identity remains consistent throughout. Name changes (e.g.,\\nstage names, married names) do not create a new entity. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a group or\\norganization and the Contract does not specify particular members, any official\\ncommunication or statement by any member or designated spokesperson counts. When using\\nAND logic, all specified entities must independently say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e. When\\nusing OR logic, at least one of the specified entities must say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nThe Exchange may specify additional conditions such as “at least X members of” a group or\\n“the majority of” a group.\\n\\n\\u003csource\\u003e: \\u003csource\\u003e refers to a Source Agency or ordered collection of Source Agencies\\nspecified by the Exchange at the time of Contract listing, which will be incorporated into the\\nSource Agency hierarchy above and used to determine the occurrence of the Underlying.\\n\\u003csource\\u003e may refer to a singular agency, multiple agencies, an agency by distinguishing\\ncharacteristics, by category or type (e.g., “official government statistical body,” “primary wire\\nservice”), or any combination thereof. When multiple agencies are specified, they may be\\napplied in the hierarchical order designated by the Exchange if so specified, with the highest-\\nranked available and responsive agency taking precedence for purposes of determining the\\nExpiration Value. A lower-ranked agency shall only be consulted if all higher-ranked agencies\\nare unavailable, unresponsive, have not reported on the Underlying by the Expiration time, or\\nif the Exchange, in its sole discretion, determines that a higher-ranked agency’s reporting is\\nincomplete, erroneous, or otherwise insufficient to determine the Expiration Value. If \\u003csource\\u003e\\ndesignates multiple agencies without specifying a hierarchical order, the Exchange shall\\nresolve any conflict between reporting agencies at its sole discretion.\\n\\n\\u003cword\\u003e: \\u003cword\\u003e refers to the particular word or phrase potentially to be mentioned by\\n\\u003centity\\u003e. It may refer to a word being said a minimum number of times. It may also refer to\\none of multiple words/phrases, any of which are acceptable (e.g., “Doge/Dogecoin”).\\n\\f\\u003ctime period\\u003e: \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific range of time, event or discrete date and\\ntime specified by the Exchange. This may be defined by, but is not limited to: a specific event\\nor context (e.g., “during the State of the Union address”), exact dates or times, relative time\\nmarkers (e.g., “before July 1, 2027,” “in Q1 2026”), event-based periods (e.g., “during any\\ncampaign rally in October 2026,” “during the awards ceremony”), and broader intervals (e.g.,\\n“Q1–Q2 2027,” “January–March 2026”).\\n\\nUnless stated otherwise, “Between” is inclusive of both endpoints, while “before” and “after”\\nexclude the specified date. \\u003ctime period\\u003e may also refer to “Any” or “None”, to multiple dates\\n(even if non-consecutive), or to a singular and discrete date or time.\\n\\nWhen \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event (such as an address, speech, performance, or\\nbroadcast), the Exchange may specify what is included, including whether it includes both live\\nand pre-recorded segments (including whether advertisements are included). Where a\\ntimezone is not specified, ET is assumed.\\n\\n\\nPayout Criterion: The Payout Criterion for the Contract encompasses the Expiration Values that\\n\\u003cword\\u003e is said by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n\\n\\nThe word must appear as a distinct, standalone unit, not buried inside another word. Plural\\nand possessive noun forms count. Other grammatical changes (tense, conjugation, derivation)\\ndo not. If \\u003cword\\u003e appears separated from other words by a space or hyphen or in a\\ncompound form with a space or hyphen, it counts. If \\u003cword\\u003e is fused into a single\\nunhyphenated word, it does not count.\\n\\nIf \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled, and the market contains a\\nstrike stating “Event does not qualify/occur”, such a strike shall resolve “Yes” and all others\\n“No”. If \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled but such strikes are NOT\\nlisted, the Contracts will resolve to the last fair price determined at the discretion of the\\nExchange. If the event is postponed, and such a postponement is announced by the end of the\\nfollowing calendar day to be rescheduled to a time within 14 calendar days, the markets shall\\nremain open. If the event captured in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast, the\\nExchange may keep the market open for 24 hours for the release of an official recording.\\nFurther granular details on conditions for these Contracts is available below.\\n\\nAdditional clarification(s):\\n\\n     Possessive noun forms of \\u003cword\\u003e, plurals, and possessive plural noun forms are\\n     INCLUDED:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigrants” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Egg” → “eggs’ shells” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Russia” → “Russia’s” counts, “Russian” does not\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e exists only in adjective form, no plural form exists:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Economic” → “Economics” does not count (“Economic” is an adjective\\n          for which “Economics” is not a plural)\\n     Plural nouns occurring within proper nouns and noun phrases are included:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Cat” → “Cats the musical” counts\\n\\f    Grammatical variations beyond plurals/possessives are NOT included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigration” does NOT count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Run” → “Running” or “Ran” do NOT count\\n    When \\u003cword\\u003e specifies a plural form, the singular does NOT count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Veterans” → “Veteran” does NOT count\\n    Words that are spelled the same as the plural form of \\u003cword\\u003e (if such exists) but are\\n    themselves not a plural noun are included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Wind” → “Winds up the clock” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Border” → “The United States has strong borders” counts\\n    Open compounds (words separated by spaces) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fire station” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “couch” → “couch potato” counts\\n    Hyphenated compounds (words connected by hyphens) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Palestine” → “pro-Palestine” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fat” → “non-fat” counts\\n    Closed compounds (single word, no spaces/hyphens) do not count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire” does not count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firefighter” does not count\\n    Multi-word \\u003cword\\u003e in larger constructions: When \\u003cword\\u003e is a multi-word phrase\\n    appearing within a hyphenated construction, it counts only if \\u003cword\\u003e appears as a\\n    complete, unmodified element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “New York” → “New York-based” counts (complete element)\\n    Portmanteaus (words blended from two words where parts of each are combined) are\\n    NOT included unless the portmanteau clearly contains \\u003cword\\u003e as a distinct, unaltered\\n    element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “MAGA” → “MAGA-nificent” counts (MAGA appears as distinct element)\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “magnificent” → “MAGA-nificent” does NOT count (portmanteau blend)\\n\\nDictionary determination: Both the Merriam-Webster Dictionary (available online) AND the\\nOxford English Dictionary shall be used to determine compound type and/or conventional\\nspelling patterns. Inclusion in either dictionary as an open or hyphenated compound shall\\nsatisfy the Payout Criterion. If neither provides clarity (or the word is not included),\\ndetermination is based on whether written as single unit (closed/doesn’t count) vs. spaces or\\nhyphens (open or hyphenated/counts) and/or context and previous usage.\\n\\nPHONETIC EQUIVALENCIES\\n\\n    Homophones (same sound, different spelling) do not count:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “write” → “right” does not count\\n    Homonyms and homographs (same spelling) COUNT regardless of meaning or\\n    pronunciation:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “bass” → both “bass guitar” and “bass fishing” count\\n    Proper and common nouns are treated identically:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Apple” → both “Apple Inc.” and “apple” (fruit) count\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Will” → both “Will Smith” and “I will go” count\\n    Minor unintentional mispronunciations COUNT if context makes intent clear:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Mamdani” → “Mandani” counts\\n    Severe mispronunciations that make \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable do NOT count.\\n    Trademarked spellings do not count, even when pronounced identically, unless the word\\n\\fitself is the same:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “lift” → “Lyft” (pronounced “lift”) does not count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “uber” → “Uber” counts\\nWords with non-standard transliteration to English count within reason, provided they are\\nphonetically equivalent:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Zelensky” → any of “Zelenski,” “Zelenskii,” “Zelensky,” or “Zelenskiy”\\n      count if pronounced equivalently\\nContractions do not count for their constituent words unless otherwise explicitly specified\\nby the Exchange:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “not” → “won’t,” “can’t,” “don’t,” “isn’t” do not count\\nNumbers spoken as words COUNT, when spoken exactly (not part of a larger number):\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “five” → saying “five” or reading “$5” aloud as “five dollars” counts,\\n      saying “five hundred” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “410” → “four hundred ten”, “four one zero” or “four ten” counts\\nOrdinals COUNT when \\u003cword\\u003e is written numerically OR a phrase that includes a\\nnumber:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “January 6” → “January 6th” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “3” (written numerically) → “3rd” (spoken as “third”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Eight War” → “8 Wars” and “Eighth War” will count\\nCardinal and ordinal number words are distinct:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “one” → “first” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “first” → “one” does NOT count\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count when pronunciation or letter-by-letter spelling\\nmatches \\u003cword\\u003e:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “NASA” (pronounced “NAH-suh”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “N-A-S-A” (spelled out) counts\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count as \\u003cword\\u003e when pronounced as the full word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Doctor” → “Dr.” (pronounced “Doctor”) counts\\nExpanded forms of acronyms do NOT count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “AI” → “artificial intelligence” does not count\\nWords in foreign languages do NOT count unless they are perfect cognates with an\\nEnglish word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fuego” (Spanish) does NOT count\\nEnglish words within foreign sentences count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “policy” → “Nuestra policy es clara” counts\\n\\u003cword\\u003e in organization/company names counts:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Securities” → “Bank of America Securities” counts\\nWords in URLs, emails, handles, and hashtags (exclusive of domain structure, email\\nprovider or symbols) are treated as compounds when spoken as complete words, with the\\ntype of compound subject to aforementioned rules:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firestation.com” pronounced “fire station dot com” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire.com” pronounced “wildfire dot com” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “apple” → “apple.com” pronounced “apple dot com” does count\\n      When presented in URL, email, handle, or hashtag form, \\u003cword\\u003e shall be treated as\\n      a compound, not a multi-word word\\nSung, rapped, or poetic words COUNT if phonetically recognizable:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “money” → “moneyyy” (extended in rap) counts\\n      Extreme distortion making \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable does NOT count.\\nPhonetic alphabet spelling (“Foxtrot India Romeo Echo” for “FIRE”) does NOT count.\\n\\fCANCELLATIONS AND DELAYS\\n\\n   The Exchange may list an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike for any Contract. If listed,\\n   such a strike refers to the structural conditions of the market, and is NOT adjudicated as a\\n   \\u003cword\\u003e needing to be said by or validated by having been said by \\u003centity\\u003e. If listed, this\\n   strike resolves to “Yes” whenever the event fails to occur or qualify under the Payout\\n   Criterion, or any other circumstance prevents normal resolution.\\n   If no such strike is listed, and \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, the following rules\\n   apply if the event is cancelled, postponed, rescheduled, or materially altered (including\\n   being closed to press) such that no video is released within one calendar day of the\\n   original start time of the event:\\n         If the event is cancelled, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price determined in\\n         the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         If the event is postponed or rescheduled, the outcome depends on whether a new\\n         date is publicly announced within one calendar day (i.e. if the event was scheduled\\n         to begin on Monday, any time up to 11:59PM on Tuesday falls within this period) of\\n         the originally scheduled start time:\\n               If no new date is announced within one calendar day, the Contract will resolve\\n               to the last fair price determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n               If a new date is announced within one calendar day, the outcome depends on\\n               when the rescheduled event is set to occur:\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls within fourteen (14) calendar days of the\\n                     originally scheduled date, the Contract shall remain open and \\u003cword\\u003e\\n                     stated during the rescheduled event will count.\\n                           The fourteen-day window begins at 12:00 AM ET on the originally\\n                           scheduled date and ends at 11:59 PM ET fourteen days later, unless\\n                           an alternate timezone is explicitly specified.\\n                           Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the State of the Union on January\\n                           15, 2026” rescheduled to January 20, 2026 → words spoken during\\n                           the rescheduled address count.\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls more than fourteen (14) calendar days after\\n                     the originally scheduled date, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price\\n                     determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         Any Contract that cannot be resolved through the Source Agency hierarchy will\\n         instead be settled at the Last Fair Price. The Exchange will disclose the methodology\\n         used to determine the Last Fair Price (e.g., Last Traded Price, Time-Weighted\\n         Average Price) at the time of Issuance.\\n         If an event begins but is interrupted, abbreviated, or ends prematurely, words\\n         stated by \\u003centity\\u003e during the portion of the event that did occur will count and the\\n         market will otherwise resolve.\\n   If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window but the venue, format, or medium\\n   changes (e.g., moved to a different location, changed from in-person to virtual (with the\\n   exception of being closed to press)), words stated during the event will count.\\n   Special condition: Across both cases, whether an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike is\\n   listed or not, if the event specified as or in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast (or\\n   relayed as such) but the live stream/broadcast does not occur, the Exchange will instead\\n   use an officially released recording as the Underlying, and may delay resolution by up to\\n   one calendar day to allow for the release of such a recording.\\n\\f          If partial snippets are released, Contracts on words that do not appear will be\\n          resolved to last fair price, and Contracts on those that do will be resolved to “Yes”.\\n          If no recording is released, the relevant outcomes triggered by the\\n          presence/absence of an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike shall occur as outlined\\n          above.\\n\\nTECHNICAL DETAILS (UNLESS OTHERWISE SPECIFIED)\\n\\n     When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, pre-recorded content broadcast,\\n     streamed, or published as part of that event is included if presented as part of the official\\n     presentation.\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the concert” with pre-recorded video interlude\\n          where entity speaks → words from interlude count\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the television appearance” with pre-taped\\n          segment aired during broadcast → words from segment count\\n     Behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are NOT\\n     included unless officially broadcast or published as part of \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n     Subtitles and captions that display \\u003cword\\u003e on screen but are not spoken aloud by\\n     \\u003centity\\u003e do NOT count.\\n     Sign language interpretation or usage by entity does NOT count as saying \\u003cword\\u003e unless\\n     the Contract explicitly specifies that sign language counts.\\n     Text that entity displays on screen (presentation slides, teleprompter visible to audience,\\n     signatures) does NOT count unless entity reads it aloud.\\n     Content generated by AI, deepfakes, or synthetic voice technology impersonating entity\\n     does NOT count unless the synthetic content is officially commissioned, authorized, or\\n     published by entity, OR the Contract explicitly specifies that AI-generated content counts.\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e is muted due to technical failure or censorship it shall not count unless\\n     corroborating contextual evidence (including surrounding speech, or an official\\n     uncensored recording or transcript) confirms that \\u003centity\\u003e specifically uttered \\u003cword\\u003e\\n     during the muted period.\\n\\nMinimum Tick: The Minimum Tick size for the Contract shall be $0.01.\\n\\nPosition Accountability Level: The Position Accountability Level for the Contract shall be\\n$25,000 per strike, per Member.\\n\\nLast Trading Date: The Last Trading Date of the Contract will be the Expiration Date. The Last\\nTrading Time will be the Expiration time.\\n\\nSettlement Date: The Settlement Date of the Contract shall be no later than the day after the\\nExpiration Date, unless the Market Outcome is under review pursuant to Rule 7.1.\\n\\nExpiration Date: When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event: The latest Expiration Date of\\nthe Contract shall be fourteen (14) calendar days after the originally scheduled date of the\\nevent. If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window, expiration will be moved to an\\nearlier date and time in accordance with Rule 7.2. When \\u003ctime period\\u003e is defined by specific\\ndates: The latest Expiration Date of the Contract shall be two weeks after the end of \\u003ctime\\nperiod\\u003e. If an event described in the Payout Criterion occurs and a consensus has been\\nreached on all terms, then expiration will be moved to an earlier date and time in accordance\\nwith Rule 7.2.\\n\\fExpiration time: The Expiration time of the Contract shall be 10:00 AM ET.\\n\\nSettlement Value: The Settlement Value for this Contract is $1.00.\\n\\nExpiration Value: The Expiration Value is the value of the Underlying as documented by the\\nSource Agency on the Expiration Date at the Expiration time.\\n\\nContingencies: Before Settlement, Kalshi may, at its sole discretion, initiate the Market\\nOutcome Review Process pursuant to Rule 7.1 of the Rulebook. If an Expiration Value cannot\\nbe determined on the Expiration Date, Kalshi has the right to determine payouts pursuant to\\nRule 7.1 in the Rulebook.\\n\\f\\n\\n[defendant] DX-4 Market packet: Ronaldo strike and challenged No resolution\\nMarket URL: https://kalshi.com/markets/kxtrumpmentionb/trump-mention-b/kxtrumpmentionb-25dec06\\n\\nPublic market title: What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\n\\nContract family: PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION\\n\\nStrike at issue: Ronaldo\\n\\nChallenged resolution: No\\n\\nRequested resolution: Yes\\n\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R1 GovInfo transcript confirming Ronaldo utterances and Kennedy Center/FIFA Draw context\\nSource: GovInfo, Compilation of Presidential Documents, DCPD202501162\\nURL retrieved: https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/DCPD-202501162/html/DCPD-202501162.htm\\nRetrieval time: 2026-06-29T22:00:00Z\\nLocal captured HTML size/hash: 51,571 bytes; SHA-256 eadbceeecf3e94f5bd423bcb8e8511165fdc7265dd8c1e025870c2e8f34dfd99\\n\\nMaterial captured text from official GovInfo HTML/web.open:\\n\\nAdministration of Donald J. Trump, 2025\\n\\nTitle: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\nDate: December 5, 2025\\n\\nOpening note: [The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\\n\\nExcerpt - The President's Interest in Soccer (web.open lines 196-203):\\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\\\"football,\\\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\\n\\nExcerpt - The President's Interest in Soccer (web.open lines 322-329):\\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\\nThe President. But they have a little more speed. But no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\\n\\nTiming/context note (web.open lines 461-462):\\nNOTE: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. In his remarks, he referred to Trey Yingst, chief foreign correspondent, Fox News Channel; Cristiano Ronaldo, forward for Saudi Pro League club Al-Nass and Portugal's national soccer team; and Lionel Messi, forward for Major League Soccer club Inter Miami and Argentina's national team. A reporter referred to New York State Attorney General Letitia James.\\nThe transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\n\\nDocument category/location/name/subject metadata (web.open lines 463-468):\\nCategories: Interviews With the News Media: Exchanges with reporters, Washington, DC.\\nLocations: Washington, DC.\\nNames include: Cristiano Ronaldo and Lionel Messi.\\nSubjects include: Federation Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) World Cup; John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts; News media, Presidential interviews; Soccer.\\nDCPD Number: DCPD202501162.\\n\\nCapture limits: This item is a focused text capture of the material official transcript title, Ronaldo excerpts, timing/correction note, and metadata. It is not a full video or audio artifact. The official transcript itself notes some portions could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R2 FIFA timing capture showing formal commencement time but not market-specific exclusion\\nSource: FIFA official page, FIFA World Cup 2026 Final Draw\\nURL: https://www.fifa.com/en/tournaments/mens/worldcup/canadamexicousa2026/live-draw\\nRetrieval time: 2026-06-29T22:01:00Z\\n\\nMaterial captured text from web search/open result:\\n- Page title/source: FIFA World Cup 2026™ Final Draw\\n- The draw takes place at the Kennedy Center in Washington DC, USA.\\n- The draw commences at 12:00 local time (17:00 UTC) on Friday 5 December 2025.\\n\\nCapture limits: This is a focused text capture of the official FIFA page timing statement located by web search. It is not a video capture of the draw ceremony.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R3 Event-period terms and exclusions\\n                                         NEWMENTION\\n\\nScope: These rules shall apply to this contract.\\n\\nUnderlying: The Underlying for this Contract is words used by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nRevisions to the Underlying made after Expiration will not be accounted for in determining the\\nExpiration Value.\\n\\nSource Agency: The Source Agencies are \\u003csource\\u003e.\\n\\nType: The type of Contract is an Event Contract.\\n\\nIssuance: After the initial Contract, Contract iterations will be listed on an as-needed basis at\\nthe discretion of the Exchange and corresponding to the risk management needs of Members.\\n\\n\\u003centity\\u003e: \\u003centity\\u003e refers to the speaker, writer, performer, or communicator specified by the\\nExchange. This may include (but is not limited to): a specific named individual, multiple\\nindividuals specified using AND/OR logic, an individual identified by position or title, a group,\\nband, team or collective entity, a specified member or members of a group, an organization,\\ncompany, or institutional entity, or any combination of the aforementioned.\\n\\nWhen \\u003centity\\u003e is defined by a position or title, the Contract tracks whoever holds that position\\nduring \\u003ctime period\\u003e, even if the individual holding the position changes. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a\\nspecific named individual, the identity remains consistent throughout. Name changes (e.g.,\\nstage names, married names) do not create a new entity. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a group or\\norganization and the Contract does not specify particular members, any official\\ncommunication or statement by any member or designated spokesperson counts. When using\\nAND logic, all specified entities must independently say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e. When\\nusing OR logic, at least one of the specified entities must say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nThe Exchange may specify additional conditions such as “at least X members of” a group or\\n“the majority of” a group.\\n\\n\\u003csource\\u003e: \\u003csource\\u003e refers to a Source Agency or ordered collection of Source Agencies\\nspecified by the Exchange at the time of Contract listing, which will be incorporated into the\\nSource Agency hierarchy above and used to determine the occurrence of the Underlying.\\n\\u003csource\\u003e may refer to a singular agency, multiple agencies, an agency by distinguishing\\ncharacteristics, by category or type (e.g., “official government statistical body,” “primary wire\\nservice”), or any combination thereof. When multiple agencies are specified, they may be\\napplied in the hierarchical order designated by the Exchange if so specified, with the highest-\\nranked available and responsive agency taking precedence for purposes of determining the\\nExpiration Value. A lower-ranked agency shall only be consulted if all higher-ranked agencies\\nare unavailable, unresponsive, have not reported on the Underlying by the Expiration time, or\\nif the Exchange, in its sole discretion, determines that a higher-ranked agency’s reporting is\\nincomplete, erroneous, or otherwise insufficient to determine the Expiration Value. If \\u003csource\\u003e\\ndesignates multiple agencies without specifying a hierarchical order, the Exchange shall\\nresolve any conflict between reporting agencies at its sole discretion.\\n\\n\\u003cword\\u003e: \\u003cword\\u003e refers to the particular word or phrase potentially to be mentioned by\\n\\u003centity\\u003e. It may refer to a word being said a minimum number of times. It may also refer to\\none of multiple words/phrases, any of which are acceptable (e.g., “Doge/Dogecoin”).\\n\\f\\u003ctime period\\u003e: \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific range of time, event or discrete date and\\ntime specified by the Exchange. This may be defined by, but is not limited to: a specific event\\nor context (e.g., “during the State of the Union address”), exact dates or times, relative time\\nmarkers (e.g., “before July 1, 2027,” “in Q1 2026”), event-based periods (e.g., “during any\\ncampaign rally in October 2026,” “during the awards ceremony”), and broader intervals (e.g.,\\n“Q1–Q2 2027,” “January–March 2026”).\\n\\nUnless stated otherwise, “Between” is inclusive of both endpoints, while “before” and “after”\\nexclude the specified date. \\u003ctime period\\u003e may also refer to “Any” or “None”, to multiple dates\\n(even if non-consecutive), or to a singular and discrete date or time.\\n\\nWhen \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event (such as an address, speech, performance, or\\nbroadcast), the Exchange may specify what is included, including whether it includes both live\\nand pre-recorded segments (including whether advertisements are included). Where a\\ntimezone is not specified, ET is assumed.\\n\\n\\nPayout Criterion: The Payout Criterion for the Contract encompasses the Expiration Values that\\n\\u003cword\\u003e is said by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n\\n\\nThe word must appear as a distinct, standalone unit, not buried inside another word. Plural\\nand possessive noun forms count. Other grammatical changes (tense, conjugation, derivation)\\ndo not. If \\u003cword\\u003e appears separated from other words by a space or hyphen or in a\\ncompound form with a space or hyphen, it counts. If \\u003cword\\u003e is fused into a single\\nunhyphenated word, it does not count.\\n\\nIf \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled, and the market contains a\\nstrike stating “Event does not qualify/occur”, such a strike shall resolve “Yes” and all others\\n“No”. If \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled but such strikes are NOT\\nlisted, the Contracts will resolve to the last fair price determined at the discretion of the\\nExchange. If the event is postponed, and such a postponement is announced by the end of the\\nfollowing calendar day to be rescheduled to a time within 14 calendar days, the markets shall\\nremain open. If the event captured in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast, the\\nExchange may keep the market open for 24 hours for the release of an official recording.\\nFurther granular details on conditions for these Contracts is available below.\\n\\nAdditional clarification(s):\\n\\n     Possessive noun forms of \\u003cword\\u003e, plurals, and possessive plural noun forms are\\n     INCLUDED:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigrants” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Egg” → “eggs’ shells” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Russia” → “Russia’s” counts, “Russian” does not\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e exists only in adjective form, no plural form exists:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Economic” → “Economics” does not count (“Economic” is an adjective\\n          for which “Economics” is not a plural)\\n     Plural nouns occurring within proper nouns and noun phrases are included:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Cat” → “Cats the musical” counts\\n\\f    Grammatical variations beyond plurals/possessives are NOT included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigration” does NOT count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Run” → “Running” or “Ran” do NOT count\\n    When \\u003cword\\u003e specifies a plural form, the singular does NOT count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Veterans” → “Veteran” does NOT count\\n    Words that are spelled the same as the plural form of \\u003cword\\u003e (if such exists) but are\\n    themselves not a plural noun are included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Wind” → “Winds up the clock” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Border” → “The United States has strong borders” counts\\n    Open compounds (words separated by spaces) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fire station” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “couch” → “couch potato” counts\\n    Hyphenated compounds (words connected by hyphens) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Palestine” → “pro-Palestine” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fat” → “non-fat” counts\\n    Closed compounds (single word, no spaces/hyphens) do not count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire” does not count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firefighter” does not count\\n    Multi-word \\u003cword\\u003e in larger constructions: When \\u003cword\\u003e is a multi-word phrase\\n    appearing within a hyphenated construction, it counts only if \\u003cword\\u003e appears as a\\n    complete, unmodified element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “New York” → “New York-based” counts (complete element)\\n    Portmanteaus (words blended from two words where parts of each are combined) are\\n    NOT included unless the portmanteau clearly contains \\u003cword\\u003e as a distinct, unaltered\\n    element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “MAGA” → “MAGA-nificent” counts (MAGA appears as distinct element)\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “magnificent” → “MAGA-nificent” does NOT count (portmanteau blend)\\n\\nDictionary determination: Both the Merriam-Webster Dictionary (available online) AND the\\nOxford English Dictionary shall be used to determine compound type and/or conventional\\nspelling patterns. Inclusion in either dictionary as an open or hyphenated compound shall\\nsatisfy the Payout Criterion. If neither provides clarity (or the word is not included),\\ndetermination is based on whether written as single unit (closed/doesn’t count) vs. spaces or\\nhyphens (open or hyphenated/counts) and/or context and previous usage.\\n\\nPHONETIC EQUIVALENCIES\\n\\n    Homophones (same sound, different spelling) do not count:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “write” → “right” does not count\\n    Homonyms and homographs (same spelling) COUNT regardless of meaning or\\n    pronunciation:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “bass” → both “bass guitar” and “bass fishing” count\\n    Proper and common nouns are treated identically:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Apple” → both “Apple Inc.” and “apple” (fruit) count\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Will” → both “Will Smith” and “I will go” count\\n    Minor unintentional mispronunciations COUNT if context makes intent clear:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Mamdani” → “Mandani” counts\\n    Severe mispronunciations that make \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable do NOT count.\\n    Trademarked spellings do not count, even when pronounced identically, unless the word\\n\\fitself is the same:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “lift” → “Lyft” (pronounced “lift”) does not count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “uber” → “Uber” counts\\nWords with non-standard transliteration to English count within reason, provided they are\\nphonetically equivalent:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Zelensky” → any of “Zelenski,” “Zelenskii,” “Zelensky,” or “Zelenskiy”\\n      count if pronounced equivalently\\nContractions do not count for their constituent words unless otherwise explicitly specified\\nby the Exchange:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “not” → “won’t,” “can’t,” “don’t,” “isn’t” do not count\\nNumbers spoken as words COUNT, when spoken exactly (not part of a larger number):\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “five” → saying “five” or reading “$5” aloud as “five dollars” counts,\\n      saying “five hundred” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “410” → “four hundred ten”, “four one zero” or “four ten” counts\\nOrdinals COUNT when \\u003cword\\u003e is written numerically OR a phrase that includes a\\nnumber:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “January 6” → “January 6th” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “3” (written numerically) → “3rd” (spoken as “third”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Eight War” → “8 Wars” and “Eighth War” will count\\nCardinal and ordinal number words are distinct:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “one” → “first” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “first” → “one” does NOT count\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count when pronunciation or letter-by-letter spelling\\nmatches \\u003cword\\u003e:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “NASA” (pronounced “NAH-suh”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “N-A-S-A” (spelled out) counts\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count as \\u003cword\\u003e when pronounced as the full word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Doctor” → “Dr.” (pronounced “Doctor”) counts\\nExpanded forms of acronyms do NOT count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “AI” → “artificial intelligence” does not count\\nWords in foreign languages do NOT count unless they are perfect cognates with an\\nEnglish word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fuego” (Spanish) does NOT count\\nEnglish words within foreign sentences count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “policy” → “Nuestra policy es clara” counts\\n\\u003cword\\u003e in organization/company names counts:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Securities” → “Bank of America Securities” counts\\nWords in URLs, emails, handles, and hashtags (exclusive of domain structure, email\\nprovider or symbols) are treated as compounds when spoken as complete words, with the\\ntype of compound subject to aforementioned rules:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firestation.com” pronounced “fire station dot com” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire.com” pronounced “wildfire dot com” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “apple” → “apple.com” pronounced “apple dot com” does count\\n      When presented in URL, email, handle, or hashtag form, \\u003cword\\u003e shall be treated as\\n      a compound, not a multi-word word\\nSung, rapped, or poetic words COUNT if phonetically recognizable:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “money” → “moneyyy” (extended in rap) counts\\n      Extreme distortion making \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable does NOT count.\\nPhonetic alphabet spelling (“Foxtrot India Romeo Echo” for “FIRE”) does NOT count.\\n\\fCANCELLATIONS AND DELAYS\\n\\n   The Exchange may list an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike for any Contract. If listed,\\n   such a strike refers to the structural conditions of the market, and is NOT adjudicated as a\\n   \\u003cword\\u003e needing to be said by or validated by having been said by \\u003centity\\u003e. If listed, this\\n   strike resolves to “Yes” whenever the event fails to occur or qualify under the Payout\\n   Criterion, or any other circumstance prevents normal resolution.\\n   If no such strike is listed, and \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, the following rules\\n   apply if the event is cancelled, postponed, rescheduled, or materially altered (including\\n   being closed to press) such that no video is released within one calendar day of the\\n   original start time of the event:\\n         If the event is cancelled, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price determined in\\n         the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         If the event is postponed or rescheduled, the outcome depends on whether a new\\n         date is publicly announced within one calendar day (i.e. if the event was scheduled\\n         to begin on Monday, any time up to 11:59PM on Tuesday falls within this period) of\\n         the originally scheduled start time:\\n               If no new date is announced within one calendar day, the Contract will resolve\\n               to the last fair price determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n               If a new date is announced within one calendar day, the outcome depends on\\n               when the rescheduled event is set to occur:\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls within fourteen (14) calendar days of the\\n                     originally scheduled date, the Contract shall remain open and \\u003cword\\u003e\\n                     stated during the rescheduled event will count.\\n                           The fourteen-day window begins at 12:00 AM ET on the originally\\n                           scheduled date and ends at 11:59 PM ET fourteen days later, unless\\n                           an alternate timezone is explicitly specified.\\n                           Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the State of the Union on January\\n                           15, 2026” rescheduled to January 20, 2026 → words spoken during\\n                           the rescheduled address count.\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls more than fourteen (14) calendar days after\\n                     the originally scheduled date, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price\\n                     determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         Any Contract that cannot be resolved through the Source Agency hierarchy will\\n         instead be settled at the Last Fair Price. The Exchange will disclose the methodology\\n         used to determine the Last Fair Price (e.g., Last Traded Price, Time-Weighted\\n         Average Price) at the time of Issuance.\\n         If an event begins but is interrupted, abbreviated, or ends prematurely, words\\n         stated by \\u003centity\\u003e during the portion of the event that did occur will count and the\\n         market will otherwise resolve.\\n   If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window but the venue, format, or medium\\n   changes (e.g., moved to a different location, changed from in-person to virtual (with the\\n   exception of being closed to press)), words stated during the event will count.\\n   Special condition: Across both cases, whether an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike is\\n   listed or not, if the event specified as or in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast (or\\n   relayed as such) but the live stream/broadcast does not occur, the Exchange will instead\\n   use an officially released recording as the Underlying, and may delay resolution by up to\\n   one calendar day to allow for the release of such a recording.\\n\\f          If partial snippets are released, Contracts on words that do not appear will be\\n          resolved to last fair price, and Contracts on those that do will be resolved to “Yes”.\\n          If no recording is released, the relevant outcomes triggered by the\\n          presence/absence of an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike shall occur as outlined\\n          above.\\n\\nTECHNICAL DETAILS (UNLESS OTHERWISE SPECIFIED)\\n\\n     When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, pre-recorded content broadcast,\\n     streamed, or published as part of that event is included if presented as part of the official\\n     presentation.\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the concert” with pre-recorded video interlude\\n          where entity speaks → words from interlude count\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the television appearance” with pre-taped\\n          segment aired during broadcast → words from segment count\\n     Behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are NOT\\n     included unless officially broadcast or published as part of \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n     Subtitles and captions that display \\u003cword\\u003e on screen but are not spoken aloud by\\n     \\u003centity\\u003e do NOT count.\\n     Sign language interpretation or usage by entity does NOT count as saying \\u003cword\\u003e unless\\n     the Contract explicitly specifies that sign language counts.\\n     Text that entity displays on screen (presentation slides, teleprompter visible to audience,\\n     signatures) does NOT count unless entity reads it aloud.\\n     Content generated by AI, deepfakes, or synthetic voice technology impersonating entity\\n     does NOT count unless the synthetic content is officially commissioned, authorized, or\\n     published by entity, OR the Contract explicitly specifies that AI-generated content counts.\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e is muted due to technical failure or censorship it shall not count unless\\n     corroborating contextual evidence (including surrounding speech, or an official\\n     uncensored recording or transcript) confirms that \\u003centity\\u003e specifically uttered \\u003cword\\u003e\\n     during the muted period.\\n\\nMinimum Tick: The Minimum Tick size for the Contract shall be $0.01.\\n\\nPosition Accountability Level: The Position Accountability Level for the Contract shall be\\n$25,000 per strike, per Member.\\n\\nLast Trading Date: The Last Trading Date of the Contract will be the Expiration Date. The Last\\nTrading Time will be the Expiration time.\\n\\nSettlement Date: The Settlement Date of the Contract shall be no later than the day after the\\nExpiration Date, unless the Market Outcome is under review pursuant to Rule 7.1.\\n\\nExpiration Date: When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event: The latest Expiration Date of\\nthe Contract shall be fourteen (14) calendar days after the originally scheduled date of the\\nevent. If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window, expiration will be moved to an\\nearlier date and time in accordance with Rule 7.2. When \\u003ctime period\\u003e is defined by specific\\ndates: The latest Expiration Date of the Contract shall be two weeks after the end of \\u003ctime\\nperiod\\u003e. If an event described in the Payout Criterion occurs and a consensus has been\\nreached on all terms, then expiration will be moved to an earlier date and time in accordance\\nwith Rule 7.2.\\n\\fExpiration time: The Expiration time of the Contract shall be 10:00 AM ET.\\n\\nSettlement Value: The Settlement Value for this Contract is $1.00.\\n\\nExpiration Value: The Expiration Value is the value of the Underlying as documented by the\\nSource Agency on the Expiration Date at the Expiration time.\\n\\nContingencies: Before Settlement, Kalshi may, at its sole discretion, initiate the Market\\nOutcome Review Process pursuant to Rule 7.1 of the Rulebook. If an Expiration Value cannot\\nbe determined on the Expiration Date, Kalshi has the right to determine payouts pursuant to\\nRule 7.1 in the Rulebook.\\n\\f\\n\\n[defendant] DX-S1 GovInfo official transcript: prior reporter exchange\\nSource: GovInfo, Compilation of Presidential Documents, DCPD202501162\\nURL retrieved: https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/DCPD-202501162/html/DCPD-202501162.htm\\nRetrieval time: 2026-06-29T22:00:00Z\\nLocal captured HTML size/hash: 51,571 bytes; SHA-256 eadbceeecf3e94f5bd423bcb8e8511165fdc7265dd8c1e025870c2e8f34dfd99\\n\\nMaterial captured text from official GovInfo HTML/web.open:\\n\\nAdministration of Donald J. Trump, 2025\\n\\nTitle: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\nDate: December 5, 2025\\n\\nOpening note: [The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\\n\\nExcerpt - The President's Interest in Soccer (web.open lines 196-203):\\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\\\"football,\\\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\\n\\nExcerpt - The President's Interest in Soccer (web.open lines 322-329):\\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\\nThe President. But they have a little more speed. But no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\\n\\nTiming/context note (web.open lines 461-462):\\nNOTE: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. In his remarks, he referred to Trey Yingst, chief foreign correspondent, Fox News Channel; Cristiano Ronaldo, forward for Saudi Pro League club Al-Nass and Portugal's national soccer team; and Lionel Messi, forward for Major League Soccer club Inter Miami and Argentina's national team. A reporter referred to New York State Attorney General Letitia James.\\nThe transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\n\\nDocument category/location/name/subject metadata (web.open lines 463-468):\\nCategories: Interviews With the News Media: Exchanges with reporters, Washington, DC.\\nLocations: Washington, DC.\\nNames include: Cristiano Ronaldo and Lionel Messi.\\nSubjects include: Federation Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) World Cup; John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts; News media, Presidential interviews; Soccer.\\nDCPD Number: DCPD202501162.\\n\\nCapture limits: This item is a focused text capture of the material official transcript title, Ronaldo excerpts, timing/correction note, and metadata. It is not a full video or audio artifact. The official transcript itself notes some portions could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-S2 FIFA official draw commencement time\\nSource: FIFA official page, FIFA World Cup 2026 Final Draw\\nURL: https://www.fifa.com/en/tournaments/mens/worldcup/canadamexicousa2026/live-draw\\nRetrieval time: 2026-06-29T22:01:00Z\\n\\nMaterial captured text from web search/open result:\\n- Page title/source: FIFA World Cup 2026™ Final Draw\\n- The draw takes place at the Kennedy Center in Washington DC, USA.\\n- The draw commences at 12:00 local time (17:00 UTC) on Friday 5 December 2025.\\n\\nCapture limits: This is a focused text capture of the official FIFA page timing statement located by web search. It is not a video capture of the draw ceremony.\\n\\nSubmitted evidence:\\n[plaintiff arguments] Official White House video page capture: President Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing (ev_db357d4e9407_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-db357d4e9407)\\nSource: https://www.whitehouse.gov/videos/president-trump-attends-the-fifa-world-cup-drawing/\\nSHA-256: `db357d4e940728d417ae4f7f3caac6b78d3fd3e4aba70d46fe10c6132d45997a`\\nBytes: 1300\\nRelevance: Establishes that the White House officially published a video page titled President Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing, dated December 5, 2025, with a full-video link and related World Cup Draw videos; relevant to source chain and event context.\\n\\n[plaintiff arguments] YouTube metadata capture: Trump Talks Cristiano Ronaldo at FIFA Draw (ev_4e1045905547_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-4e1045905547)\\nSource: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Cb2yO0lLEnM\\nSHA-256: `4e10459055477440085fe5e20d970eb2488e61d13a5e2b3133a3656bed7526d7`\\nBytes: 1779\\nRelevance: Provides a public clip source and page metadata asserting that at the FIFA World Cup Draw Ceremony Trump shared a story about meeting Cristiano Ronaldo and said Ronaldo was a great person; relevant to the alleged Ronaldo utterance, though weaker than an official full transcript or video.\\n\\n[defendant arguments] GovInfo official transcript capture: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the FIFA World Cup Draw (ev_a1b1f6b1b7bd_submitted-evidence-03-defendant-a1b1f6b1b7bd)\\nSource: https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/DCPD-202501162/html/DCPD-202501162.htm\\nSHA-256: `a1b1f6b1b7bd0b691c7fe8d97467dd0d085e2b22387ae4198270764de66e56e2`\\nBytes: 3070\\nRelevance: Official transcript identifies the relevant Trump remarks as an exchange with reporters prior to the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw; it includes the Ronaldo utterances and timing/correction notes, directly bearing on whether the utterances were during the countable event period.\\n\\n[defendant arguments] FIFA official page capture: 2026 World Cup Final Draw start time (ev_3973dc8f98c0_submitted-evidence-04-defendant-3973dc8f98c0)\\nSource: https://www.fifa.com/en/tournaments/mens/worldcup/canadamexicousa2026/live-draw\\nSHA-256: `3973dc8f98c01702174f61f5548eb1e80efe64dd72b44f21ed0fa7d944f93248`\\nBytes: 598\\nRelevance: Establishes the official Final Draw start time as 12:00 local time on December 5, 2025, which helps compare the draw event period against the GovInfo transcript note that the reporter exchange occurred at 11:13 a.m.\\n\\nTechnical reports:\\n[plaintiff] Plaintiff source-search and capture ledger\\nSearched exact market/strike phrases, White House domain, public video pages, YouTube video IDs, and Kalshi live market URL. Submitted official White House page capture and YouTube metadata capture. Kalshi live page returned a Vercel security checkpoint/429; local browser was unavailable; Python pip/ensurepip unavailable for yt-dlp; direct YouTube caption/open paths were throttled or unavailable. Remaining best evidence would be a full official video/transcript or Kalshi resolution rationale if later accessible.\\n\\n[defendant] Defendant source-search and capture ledger\\nInspected current AAR evidence and exact contents of plaintiff's White House and YouTube captures. Retrieved GovInfo official HTML transcript with curl from DCPD-202501162; local full HTML was 51,571 bytes with SHA-256 eadbceeecf3e94f5bd423bcb8e8511165fdc7265dd8c1e025870c2e8f34dfd99, then submitted a focused material text capture as DX-1. Searched official draw timing and submitted the FIFA official page timing statement as DX-2. Remaining gaps: full Kalshi market source hierarchy/resolution rationale and full WH/FIFA video were not captured, but official GovInfo timing/title plus FIFA start time resolve the material timing issue.\\n\\nCall submit_council_vote with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated.\\nKeep the rationale brief: no more than three sentences.\\n\\nCouncil API instructions:\\nYou are a council member. Decide the proposition from the admitted record.\\nYou may examine admitted evidence through read-only tools when exact bytes, metadata, or exhibit contents matter.\\nDo not search the web, introduce new facts, create new evidence, or upload evidence.\\nWhen ready, call submit_council_vote exactly once with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated and a concise rationale.\\n\",\"state\":\"ready\",\"status\":\"ready\",\"tools\":[{\"description\":\"Return the current visible arbitration record for this council member.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"get_case\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"List visible immutable record evidence.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"list_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Return metadata and read limits for one visible evidence item.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"stat_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Read a bounded byte range from one visible evidence item as base64.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"length\":{\"minimum\":1,\"type\":\"integer\"},\"offset\":{\"minimum\":0,\"type\":\"integer\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\",\"offset\",\"length\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"read_evidence_range\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Submit one council vote for the current deliberation opportunity.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"rationale\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"vote\":{\"enum\":[\"demonstrated\",\"not_demonstrated\"],\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"vote\",\"rationale\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"submit_council_vote\",\"read_only\":false}],\"turn\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"completed\":false,\"deadline\":\"2026-06-29T22:18:45.386037689Z\",\"deliberation_round\":1,\"member_id\":\"C2\",\"opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C2\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"remaining_ms\":889046,\"role_id\":\"council\",\"turn_number\":10},\"wait\":{\"reason\":\"ready\",\"state_version\":14,\"version\":17}}"}],"structuredContent":{"after_opportunity_id":"deliberation:1:C2","after_version":17,"case_id":"arb-ex03a-20260629214245","limits":{"attempts_max":3,"attempts_remaining":3,"max_evidence_read_bytes":65536,"max_evidence_read_bytes_per_opportunity":524288,"max_evidence_reads_per_opportunity":32,"max_response_bytes":131072,"remaining_evidence_read_bytes_for_opportunity":524288,"remaining_evidence_reads_for_opportunity":32},"member_id":"C2","message":"An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.","ok":true,"prompt":"Role: council member\nMember ID: C2\nDeliberation round: 1\nProposition: For the Kalshi market \"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\", the strike \"Ronaldo\" should resolve Yes because Trump said \"Ronaldo\" in public remarks at the World Cup Draw venue immediately before the formal program, and the market wording plus the governing mention-market terms did not clearly exclude those event-linked remarks.\nStandard of evidence: Preponderance of the evidence.\nPersona:\nYou are a careful juror and council member.\n\nEvaluate the record faithfully. Decide only from the evidence, the stated rules, and the applicable burden of proof. Do not favor either side, fill gaps with speculation, or ignore uncertainty.\n\nGive weight to reliable sources, direct evidence, consistent reasoning, and clear admissions. Discount unsupported claims, rhetorical force, irrelevant facts, and conclusions that exceed the record.\n\nWhen the evidence supports one answer, state it plainly. When the evidence is incomplete or balanced, say so. Be concise, honest, and exact.\n\nRecord:\nOpenings:\n[plaintiff] Council members, this case is not about whether the word \"Ronaldo\" would count if President Trump clearly said it. The current packet makes that part straightforward: the market is the Kalshi PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION market titled \"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\"; the strike is \"Ronaldo\"; Kalshi’s challenged resolution is No; and plaintiff seeks Yes.\n\nThe real dispute is temporal and contextual. Did the market phrase \"during the FIFA World Cup Draw,\" read with the governing mention-market terms, include public event-linked remarks at the World Cup Draw venue immediately before the formal draw program? Or did it clearly confine countable words to a narrower formal broadcast segment? Plaintiff’s position is that a No resolution cannot stand unless the record shows that the counting window clearly excluded those event-linked remarks.\n\nThe admitted terms matter. They define the underlying as words used by the specified entity during the specified time period. They expressly recognize event-based time periods, and they say the payout criterion is satisfied when the word is said by the entity during that period. They also contain exclusions: behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings do not count unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period; captions or text alone do not count; and the word must appear as a distinct standalone unit. Those exclusions are important, but they do not by themselves answer this case. A public remark at the event venue, tied to the Draw and immediately before the formal program, is not automatically a rehearsal, sound check, or private behind-the-scenes moment.\n\nAt this opening stage, the record proves the market identity, the challenged resolution, the requested resolution, and the generic governing terms. It does not yet prove the utterance itself, the exact sequence of the venue remarks, the source-agency hierarchy or any market-specific time-period language beyond the packet, or Kalshi’s reason for treating the strike as No. Those are the factual links that should decide the case under a preponderance standard.\n\nPlaintiff expects the decisive proof to be the full official or otherwise reliable event video or transcript, with enough surrounding context to show whether Trump said \"Ronaldo\" aloud as a standalone word; when he said it relative to the Draw event; whether the remarks were public and event-linked rather than backstage or a sound check; and whether any market-specific rule clearly excluded that segment. Plaintiff also expects the market page, archived market details, and any resolution rationale to be important because ambiguity in the market’s own event wording should not be resolved against Yes after the fact.\n\nThe defense will likely argue that \"during the FIFA World Cup Draw\" means only the formal draw ceremony or broadcast, and that anything before the formal program is outside the counting period. That theory can win only if the evidence shows a clear exclusion or a source record that separates the alleged remarks from the event itself. If the evidence instead shows public remarks at the Draw venue, officially connected to the event, immediately before the formal program, and no clear rule excluding them, then the terms favor counting the word and resolving the Ronaldo strike Yes.\n\n[defendant] Council members, the defense position is straightforward: the admitted record does not yet prove that the Ronaldo strike should resolve Yes. It proves a market title, a generic mention-market rule set, and Kalshi's challenged No resolution. It does not prove that any qualifying utterance of \"Ronaldo\" occurred during the market's countable time period.\n\nThe plaintiff's opening usefully narrows the dispute. This is not primarily a word-boundary case. If President Trump said \"Ronaldo\" as a standalone spoken word during the countable FIFA World Cup Draw period, the generic terms would ordinarily treat that as the kind of word that can count. The real question is whether plaintiff can carry the burden of showing that alleged pre-program, venue-adjacent remarks were part of the market's specified time period: \"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\"\n\nThe case-packet terms matter, but they cut both ways. They say the underlying is words used by the entity during the specified time period. They recognize that a time period can be an event, and they allow the Exchange to specify what is included when an event is involved. They also distinguish official event presentation from material outside the event: behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are not included unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period; text or captions alone do not count; and the relevant word must be spoken aloud by the entity. Those provisions do not support a rule that every public comment inside the same building, or every press exchange near the formal program, is automatically \"during\" the Draw.\n\nThat is the burden problem for plaintiff. The admitted market-page file identifies the public title, contract family, strike, challenged resolution, and requested resolution. It does not supply a full market-specific source hierarchy, a formal start time, a transcript, a video, a resolution rationale, or the alleged remarks. The terms file supplies the generic framework, but not the factual bridge from \"immediately before the formal program\" to \"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\" Without that bridge, the No resolution is not shown to be wrong by a preponderance of the evidence.\n\nThe defense expects the decisive proof to be source-chain evidence, not characterization. The council should want the market's full rule page if available, the source agency hierarchy, the official draw program or broadcast, any official transcript or recording of the alleged exchange, and enough surrounding timestamps to separate the formal draw from pre-event reporter access, red-carpet exchanges, arrivals, or other ancillary material. If later evidence shows that the alleged Ronaldo comment was in a segment officially presented as part of the Draw itself, plaintiff's argument becomes stronger. If the evidence instead shows a separate exchange with reporters before the draw, or an event-linked but pre-program interaction not incorporated into the official presentation, the generic terms support Kalshi's No.\n\nSo the defense opening is not that the word Ronaldo could never count. It is that this record has not established the necessary time-period link. The proposition asks the council to overturn No because the market wording and terms did not clearly exclude pre-program remarks. That reverses the burden. Plaintiff must show that the remarks were included in the countable period. Ambiguity about the outer edge of an event is not the same as proof that a specific pre-event utterance satisfies the payout criterion.\n\nArguments:\n[plaintiff] Council members, plaintiff has now supplied the record links that were missing at opening.\n\nFirst, the market packet fixes what this dispute is: the Kalshi market title is \"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\"; the contract family is PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION; the strike is \"Ronaldo\"; Kalshi's challenged resolution is No; and plaintiff seeks Yes. That is PX-1.\n\nSecond, the governing terms make this an event-period mention question, not a narrow formal-program-only question. PX-2 says the underlying is words used by the entity during the time period, recognizes that a time period may be a specific event, and sets the payout criterion as the word being said by the entity during that period. It also tells us what does not count: text/captions alone, unofficial behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, and sound checks unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. Those exclusions matter, but none says that public event-linked remarks at the venue immediately before the formal program are categorically outside \"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\"\n\nThird, the source-chain evidence now points to the disputed event and the Ronaldo utterance. PX-3 is an official White House page titled \"President Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing,\" dated December 5, 2025, with a full-video link and related World Cup Draw videos. That establishes an official White House event-video source for Trump's attendance at the World Cup Drawing. PX-4 is a public YouTube watch-page metadata capture for video ID Cb2yO0lLEnM, titled \"Trump Talks Cristiano Ronaldo at FIFA Draw -- 'He's a Great Person'.\" Its description states that at the FIFA World Cup Draw Ceremony, Trump shared a story about meeting Cristiano Ronaldo at the White House, said Ronaldo was a great person, and mentioned Ronaldo spoke with his son. PX-4 is not as strong as an official transcript, and plaintiff says that plainly. But it is admitted source content that directly links Trump, Cristiano Ronaldo, and the FIFA Draw ceremony.\n\nOn a preponderance standard, that is enough to defeat the challenged No resolution unless the defense can supply a clearer exclusion. The market did not ask only what Trump would say during the ball-pulling segment, during the televised main show, or after a particular formal start cue. It asked what he would say \"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\" The terms recognize event-based periods and exclude particular non-event categories. A public remark at the Draw venue, tied to the Draw, is far closer to the event period than to a rehearsal, sound check, caption, or private backstage recording.\n\nThe defense's burden framing is too strict. Plaintiff must prove Yes by a preponderance; plaintiff need not prove that Kalshi drafted every boundary with perfect precision. Once the admitted sources show a Ronaldo mention in connection with the FIFA Draw ceremony, the remaining question is whether the rules clearly remove that event-linked remark from the counting period. They do not. Ambiguity in a mention market's event wording should not be converted into an unstated formal-program limitation after the fact.\n\nProvenance and gaps: plaintiff attempted to retrieve the live Kalshi page, official/full video, caption, and transcript. Kalshi returned a Vercel security checkpoint; the local browser tool was unavailable; Python pip/ensurepip was unavailable for yt-dlp; and direct YouTube caption/open paths were throttled or unavailable. That leaves PX-4 weaker than ideal, but not weightless. PX-3 supplies official event context, PX-4 supplies the Ronaldo-at-FIFA-Draw metadata, and PX-2 supplies the rule that event-linked spoken words count absent a clear exclusion.\n\nThe council should resolve the proposition Yes: the Ronaldo strike should have resolved Yes because the record more likely than not shows Trump said Ronaldo in public remarks tied to the FIFA World Cup Draw, and the market wording plus governing terms did not clearly exclude those remarks.\n\n[defendant] Council members, the merits record now shows why the challenged No resolution should stand.\n\nPlaintiff's best point is that Trump did say the word \"Ronaldo.\" The defense does not need to fight that. The question is whether he said it during the market's countable time period: \"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\" On that decisive question, the strongest official sources favor No.\n\nThe admitted GovInfo transcript, DX-1, is an official Compilation of Presidential Documents capture. Its title is not merely \"World Cup Draw\" or \"FIFA ceremony.\" It is \"Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw.\" That same transcript contains the Ronaldo passages: Trump says he met Ronaldo at the White House, later says he was \"not Ronaldo or Messi,\" and the note identifies Ronaldo among the people referenced. So DX-1 is not adverse to the defense because it confirms the word; it is decisive because it places the word in an exchange with reporters prior to the Draw.\n\nDX-2 supplies the timing anchor. The official FIFA Final Draw page states that the Draw at the Kennedy Center commenced at 12:00 local time on Friday, December 5, 2025. DX-1 states that the President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the Kennedy Center. A reporter exchange at 11:13, officially titled as prior to a 12:00 draw, is not more likely than not \"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\" It is before it.\n\nThat reading matches the governing PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION terms. PX-2 says the payout criterion is satisfied when the word is said by the entity during the specified time period. It recognizes event-based periods and permits the Exchange to specify what is included for an event. It also treats official presentation differently from adjacent material: pre-recorded content counts if presented as part of the official event presentation, while behind-the-scenes, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings do not count unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. The point is not that this reporter exchange was a rehearsal or sound check. The point is that the terms require a link to the time period itself. Plaintiff has supplied no market-specific language saying pre-event reporter availability, arrivals, or venue interviews count as part of the Draw.\n\nPlaintiff's new exhibits do not fill that gap. PX-3, the White House page capture, establishes that the White House had a page titled \"President Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing,\" but plaintiff's own capture says the embedded/full video was not captured. It does not prove that the Ronaldo words occurred inside the official draw program. PX-4 is weaker still: it is metadata from a nonofficial YouTube channel. It says the clip is about Trump talking Ronaldo at the FIFA Draw, but it is not a transcript, not an official source, and not an audio extraction. When a nonofficial clip description is weighed against GovInfo's official transcript title and FIFA's official start time, the official sources control.\n\nNor is this a burden-shifting problem. The proposition asks the council to overturn Kalshi's No because the market supposedly did not clearly exclude remarks immediately before the formal program. But the preponderance burden is on Yes. The record must show that the strike satisfied the payout criterion. The admitted terms do not say that ambiguous pre-event remarks count by default; they say the word must be said during the specified time period. Here, the best evidence identifies the remarks as prior to the Draw and before the official commencement time.\n\nProvenance also matters. DX-1 is an official government transcript with a correction note and an audio-incomplete caveat. That caveat affects stray inaudible portions, but it does not weaken the title, the 11:13 timing note, or the Ronaldo passages preserved in the transcript. DX-2 is an official FIFA timing source. Plaintiff's YouTube metadata may explain why the dispute arose, but it cannot outweigh those primary sources on timing and event classification.\n\nThe council should resolve the proposition against plaintiff. Trump said Ronaldo, but the record more likely shows he did so in a reporter exchange prior to the FIFA World Cup Draw, not during the countable Draw event. Kalshi's No resolution should be upheld.\n\nRebuttals:\n[plaintiff] Council members, defendant’s new evidence narrows the case but does not end it.\n\nPlaintiff accepts the important parts of DX-1 and DX-2. The GovInfo transcript is official; it labels the item an exchange with reporters \"Prior to\" the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw; it places the exchange at 11:13 a.m. at the Kennedy Center; and the FIFA capture states the draw commenced at 12:00 local time. Plaintiff should not pretend those facts are weak.\n\nBut defendant asks those facts to do more than they do. The market was not drafted as \"what will Trump say after the official 12:00 commencement,\" \"during the televised draw program,\" or \"during the ball-drawing segment.\" PX-1 says the public market title was \"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\" That is ordinary event language, and PX-2 recognizes event-based time periods while leaving room for the Exchange to specify what is included. The record still contains no market-specific exclusion for official venue press remarks immediately before the formal program.\n\nDX-1 also helps plaintiff on the facts defendant originally said were missing. It confirms the relevant spoken word. Trump said he met Ronaldo, that Ronaldo is great, and that he was not Ronaldo or Messi. It also places those remarks at the Kennedy Center in a FIFA World Cup Draw-centered exchange with reporters, not in an unrelated private dinner or stale campaign setting. The transcript’s own subject metadata includes the FIFA World Cup, the Kennedy Center, news media, presidential interviews, and soccer. That is event-linked public context.\n\nThe terms’ exclusions do not fit defendant’s leap. PX-2 excludes captions alone, rehearsals, sound checks, behind-the-scenes content, and unofficial recordings unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. DX-1 is not a rehearsal transcript. It is not a sound check. It is not merely a caption. It is an official presidential transcript of a public reporter exchange at the venue, released in the Compilation of Presidential Documents. If Kalshi meant to exclude that category because it occurred before a formal noon commencement, the market needed to say so clearly.\n\nSo the dispositive question remains one of market construction: does \"during the FIFA World Cup Draw\" clearly exclude public, official, event-site remarks immediately before the formal program? Defendant has proved \"prior to\" the formal draw start. Defendant has not proved a clear market rule that treats the broader Draw event as beginning only at 12:00 for mention purposes.\n\nUnder a preponderance standard, the record now confirms the Ronaldo utterance and confirms the FIFA Draw setting. The challenged No resolution should not be upheld by importing a narrow formal-program limitation that the market title and generic terms did not state.\n\nSurrebuttals:\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff's rebuttal usefully clarifies the remaining dispute: plaintiff accepts that DX-1 is official, that it labels the relevant item an exchange with reporters \"Prior to\" the FIFA World Cup Draw, that the exchange occurred at 11:13 a.m. at the Kennedy Center, and that DX-2 places the official Draw commencement at 12:00 local time. Those concessions should decide the case.\n\nPlaintiff's answer is that the market did not say \"after 12:00,\" \"during the televised program,\" or \"during the ball-drawing segment.\" But the market also did not say \"at the venue before the Draw,\" \"in pre-event reporter exchanges,\" or \"in any public remarks connected to the Draw.\" The phrase it chose was \"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\" Ordinary event language has a start, and the official FIFA source fixes that start at noon. Official GovInfo then fixes this exchange at 11:13 and titles it as prior to the Draw.\n\nThat is not a technicality. The terms require the word to be said during the specified time period. They recognize event-based periods and allow event-specific inclusions, but no admitted market-specific rule includes pre-event press access. Plaintiff's construction would turn any event-adjacent public remark into part of the event unless expressly excluded. That reverses the payout criterion. The claimant must show the word occurred during the time period; it is not enough to show the same venue, the same general topic, and official publication.\n\nPlaintiff says the exclusions do not fit because DX-1 is not a rehearsal, sound check, caption, or private backstage recording. Fair enough; the defense is not relying on those categories as labels. The defense relies on the affirmative timing requirement. A remark need not be a rehearsal to be outside the event. A reporter exchange officially described as prior to a noon event and occurring at 11:13 is outside because it is before the event began.\n\nThe record therefore proves the wrong fact for plaintiff. It proves Trump said Ronaldo, but in a pre-event reporter exchange. The proposition requires Yes only if those words count during the FIFA World Cup Draw. On this record, they do not. Kalshi's No resolution should be upheld.\n\nClosings:\n[plaintiff] Council members, the final record leaves one legal question.\n\nThe easy factual question is resolved in plaintiff’s favor: Trump said \"Ronaldo.\" The official GovInfo transcript confirms it twice in substance: he said he met Ronaldo, praised him, and later said he was not Ronaldo or Messi. That is a spoken standalone use of the strike word. The record also places the remarks at the Kennedy Center in a FIFA World Cup Draw-centered reporter exchange. This was not an unrelated dinner, a caption, an AI voice, or a social-media paraphrase.\n\nThe hard point is timing. Defendant has the strongest evidence on the formal program boundary: GovInfo titled the exchange as \"Prior to\" the Draw, notes 11:13 a.m., and FIFA states the Final Draw commenced at 12:00 local time. Plaintiff does not ask the council to ignore that. The question is what the Kalshi market actually required.\n\nPX-1 did not say \"after 12:00.\" It did not say \"during the televised draw program\" or \"during the ball-drawing segment.\" It asked, in public market wording, \"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\" PX-2’s generic terms recognize event-based periods and say the Exchange may specify what is included when a time period refers to an event. They also give specific exclusions: captions alone, rehearsals, sound checks, behind-the-scenes content, and unofficial recordings unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. None of those exclusions is this case. The GovInfo transcript is an official public presidential record of an event-site reporter exchange, not a rehearsal or sound check.\n\nDefendant’s best argument is that ordinary events have start times. True. But this market dispute is about public remarks at the venue immediately before the formal program, in the official context of the Draw, where the market and rules did not clearly define a noon-only boundary. If Kalshi wanted that narrower rule, it could have said so in the strike, the market title, or the event inclusion language. It did not.\n\nThe preponderance record therefore shows: Ronaldo was spoken; the remarks were public and officially documented; they were at the Kennedy Center in the FIFA World Cup Draw setting; and the governing market language did not clearly exclude that immediately-before-program event context. The challenged No resolution depends on importing a formal commencement limitation that is absent from the market packet.\n\nFor that reason, the Ronaldo strike should resolve Yes.\n\n[defendant] Council members, the closing record is narrow and concrete.\n\nEveryone now agrees on the easy fact: Trump said \"Ronaldo.\" The official GovInfo transcript proves that. But the proposition is not simply that Trump said the word somewhere near the FIFA World Cup Draw. The proposition asks you to overturn Kalshi's No because remarks immediately before the formal program should count under a market asking what Trump would say \"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\" Plaintiff has not carried that burden.\n\nThe two strongest sources are official and aligned. GovInfo, in DX-1, titles the relevant document \"Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw.\" It notes that the President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the Kennedy Center. FIFA, in DX-2, states that the Final Draw commenced at 12:00 local time. Those facts are not peripheral. They answer the timing question: the Ronaldo words were in a reporter exchange before the Draw began.\n\nPlaintiff's closing says the market did not specify \"after 12:00,\" \"during the televised draw program,\" or \"during the ball-drawing segment.\" True, but that does not prove Yes. The market did specify \"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\" The ordinary function of \"during\" is to define the event period, not to include anything public, official, and thematically related that happens beforehand. A 47-minute-before reporter exchange officially titled as prior to the Draw is outside that period unless the market or governing terms affirmatively include it. The record contains no such inclusion.\n\nThe governing terms reinforce that conclusion. They require the word to be said by the entity during the specified time period. They recognize event-based periods and allow the Exchange to specify event inclusions. They include official-presentation concepts for material presented as part of an event. But they do not say that pre-event press availability counts by default. Plaintiff's argument turns the absence of an exclusion into proof of inclusion. That is backwards under a preponderance standard.\n\nPlaintiff also leans on setting: Kennedy Center, FIFA World Cup subject matter, official transcript, public reporters. Those facts show why the issue is understandable. They do not move 11:13 into a 12:00 event. A source can be official and still describe something outside the event. Indeed, that is exactly what DX-1 does: it officially documents the remarks and officially labels them prior to the Draw.\n\nThe weaker evidence points the same way once weighed properly. The White House page capture does not include the video or transcript. The YouTube metadata is nonofficial and not an audio transcript. Neither overcomes GovInfo's title and timing note plus FIFA's commencement time.\n\nSo the final answer is simple: the word was spoken, but not during the countable event period shown by the best evidence. Plaintiff has not shown that Kalshi's No resolution was wrong. The council should reject the proposition and uphold No.\n\nExhibits:\n[plaintiff] PX-1 Market page packet: Ronaldo strike and challenged No resolution\nMarket URL: https://kalshi.com/markets/kxtrumpmentionb/trump-mention-b/kxtrumpmentionb-25dec06\n\nPublic market title: What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\n\nContract family: PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION\n\nStrike at issue: Ronaldo\n\nChallenged resolution: No\n\nRequested resolution: Yes\n\n\n[plaintiff] PX-2 Governing PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION terms\n                                         NEWMENTION\n\nScope: These rules shall apply to this contract.\n\nUnderlying: The Underlying for this Contract is words used by <entity> <time period>.\nRevisions to the Underlying made after Expiration will not be accounted for in determining the\nExpiration Value.\n\nSource Agency: The Source Agencies are <source>.\n\nType: The type of Contract is an Event Contract.\n\nIssuance: After the initial Contract, Contract iterations will be listed on an as-needed basis at\nthe discretion of the Exchange and corresponding to the risk management needs of Members.\n\n<entity>: <entity> refers to the speaker, writer, performer, or communicator specified by the\nExchange. This may include (but is not limited to): a specific named individual, multiple\nindividuals specified using AND/OR logic, an individual identified by position or title, a group,\nband, team or collective entity, a specified member or members of a group, an organization,\ncompany, or institutional entity, or any combination of the aforementioned.\n\nWhen <entity> is defined by a position or title, the Contract tracks whoever holds that position\nduring <time period>, even if the individual holding the position changes. When <entity> is a\nspecific named individual, the identity remains consistent throughout. Name changes (e.g.,\nstage names, married names) do not create a new entity. When <entity> is a group or\norganization and the Contract does not specify particular members, any official\ncommunication or statement by any member or designated spokesperson counts. When using\nAND logic, all specified entities must independently say <word> during <time period>. When\nusing OR logic, at least one of the specified entities must say <word> during <time period>.\nThe Exchange may specify additional conditions such as “at least X members of” a group or\n“the majority of” a group.\n\n<source>: <source> refers to a Source Agency or ordered collection of Source Agencies\nspecified by the Exchange at the time of Contract listing, which will be incorporated into the\nSource Agency hierarchy above and used to determine the occurrence of the Underlying.\n<source> may refer to a singular agency, multiple agencies, an agency by distinguishing\ncharacteristics, by category or type (e.g., “official government statistical body,” “primary wire\nservice”), or any combination thereof. When multiple agencies are specified, they may be\napplied in the hierarchical order designated by the Exchange if so specified, with the highest-\nranked available and responsive agency taking precedence for purposes of determining the\nExpiration Value. A lower-ranked agency shall only be consulted if all higher-ranked agencies\nare unavailable, unresponsive, have not reported on the Underlying by the Expiration time, or\nif the Exchange, in its sole discretion, determines that a higher-ranked agency’s reporting is\nincomplete, erroneous, or otherwise insufficient to determine the Expiration Value. If <source>\ndesignates multiple agencies without specifying a hierarchical order, the Exchange shall\nresolve any conflict between reporting agencies at its sole discretion.\n\n<word>: <word> refers to the particular word or phrase potentially to be mentioned by\n<entity>. It may refer to a word being said a minimum number of times. It may also refer to\none of multiple words/phrases, any of which are acceptable (e.g., “Doge/Dogecoin”).\n\f<time period>: <time period> refers to a specific range of time, event or discrete date and\ntime specified by the Exchange. This may be defined by, but is not limited to: a specific event\nor context (e.g., “during the State of the Union address”), exact dates or times, relative time\nmarkers (e.g., “before July 1, 2027,” “in Q1 2026”), event-based periods (e.g., “during any\ncampaign rally in October 2026,” “during the awards ceremony”), and broader intervals (e.g.,\n“Q1–Q2 2027,” “January–March 2026”).\n\nUnless stated otherwise, “Between” is inclusive of both endpoints, while “before” and “after”\nexclude the specified date. <time period> may also refer to “Any” or “None”, to multiple dates\n(even if non-consecutive), or to a singular and discrete date or time.\n\nWhen <time period> refers to a specific event (such as an address, speech, performance, or\nbroadcast), the Exchange may specify what is included, including whether it includes both live\nand pre-recorded segments (including whether advertisements are included). Where a\ntimezone is not specified, ET is assumed.\n\n\nPayout Criterion: The Payout Criterion for the Contract encompasses the Expiration Values that\n<word> is said by <entity> <time period>.\n\n\nThe word must appear as a distinct, standalone unit, not buried inside another word. Plural\nand possessive noun forms count. Other grammatical changes (tense, conjugation, derivation)\ndo not. If <word> appears separated from other words by a space or hyphen or in a\ncompound form with a space or hyphen, it counts. If <word> is fused into a single\nunhyphenated word, it does not count.\n\nIf <time period> refers to an event and that event is cancelled, and the market contains a\nstrike stating “Event does not qualify/occur”, such a strike shall resolve “Yes” and all others\n“No”. If <time period> refers to an event and that event is cancelled but such strikes are NOT\nlisted, the Contracts will resolve to the last fair price determined at the discretion of the\nExchange. If the event is postponed, and such a postponement is announced by the end of the\nfollowing calendar day to be rescheduled to a time within 14 calendar days, the markets shall\nremain open. If the event captured in <time period> is a live-stream or broadcast, the\nExchange may keep the market open for 24 hours for the release of an official recording.\nFurther granular details on conditions for these Contracts is available below.\n\nAdditional clarification(s):\n\n     Possessive noun forms of <word>, plurals, and possessive plural noun forms are\n     INCLUDED:\n          <word> is “Immigrant” → “Immigrants” counts\n          <word> is “Egg” → “eggs’ shells” counts\n          <word> is “Russia” → “Russia’s” counts, “Russian” does not\n     If <word> exists only in adjective form, no plural form exists:\n          <word> is “Economic” → “Economics” does not count (“Economic” is an adjective\n          for which “Economics” is not a plural)\n     Plural nouns occurring within proper nouns and noun phrases are included:\n          <word> is “Cat” → “Cats the musical” counts\n\f    Grammatical variations beyond plurals/possessives are NOT included:\n         <word> is “Immigrant” → “Immigration” does NOT count\n         <word> is “Run” → “Running” or “Ran” do NOT count\n    When <word> specifies a plural form, the singular does NOT count:\n         <word> is “Veterans” → “Veteran” does NOT count\n    Words that are spelled the same as the plural form of <word> (if such exists) but are\n    themselves not a plural noun are included:\n         <word> is “Wind” → “Winds up the clock” counts\n         <word> is “Border” → “The United States has strong borders” counts\n    Open compounds (words separated by spaces) count:\n         <word> is “fire” → “fire station” counts\n         <word> is “couch” → “couch potato” counts\n    Hyphenated compounds (words connected by hyphens) count:\n         <word> is “Palestine” → “pro-Palestine” counts\n         <word> is “fat” → “non-fat” counts\n    Closed compounds (single word, no spaces/hyphens) do not count:\n         <word> is “fire” → “wildfire” does not count\n         <word> is “fire” → “firefighter” does not count\n    Multi-word <word> in larger constructions: When <word> is a multi-word phrase\n    appearing within a hyphenated construction, it counts only if <word> appears as a\n    complete, unmodified element:\n         <word> is “New York” → “New York-based” counts (complete element)\n    Portmanteaus (words blended from two words where parts of each are combined) are\n    NOT included unless the portmanteau clearly contains <word> as a distinct, unaltered\n    element:\n         <word> is “MAGA” → “MAGA-nificent” counts (MAGA appears as distinct element)\n         <word> is “magnificent” → “MAGA-nificent” does NOT count (portmanteau blend)\n\nDictionary determination: Both the Merriam-Webster Dictionary (available online) AND the\nOxford English Dictionary shall be used to determine compound type and/or conventional\nspelling patterns. Inclusion in either dictionary as an open or hyphenated compound shall\nsatisfy the Payout Criterion. If neither provides clarity (or the word is not included),\ndetermination is based on whether written as single unit (closed/doesn’t count) vs. spaces or\nhyphens (open or hyphenated/counts) and/or context and previous usage.\n\nPHONETIC EQUIVALENCIES\n\n    Homophones (same sound, different spelling) do not count:\n        <word> is “write” → “right” does not count\n    Homonyms and homographs (same spelling) COUNT regardless of meaning or\n    pronunciation:\n        <word> is “bass” → both “bass guitar” and “bass fishing” count\n    Proper and common nouns are treated identically:\n        <word> is “Apple” → both “Apple Inc.” and “apple” (fruit) count\n        <word> is “Will” → both “Will Smith” and “I will go” count\n    Minor unintentional mispronunciations COUNT if context makes intent clear:\n        <word> is “Mamdani” → “Mandani” counts\n    Severe mispronunciations that make <word> unrecognizable do NOT count.\n    Trademarked spellings do not count, even when pronounced identically, unless the word\n\fitself is the same:\n      <word> is “lift” → “Lyft” (pronounced “lift”) does not count\n      <word> is “uber” → “Uber” counts\nWords with non-standard transliteration to English count within reason, provided they are\nphonetically equivalent:\n      <word> is “Zelensky” → any of “Zelenski,” “Zelenskii,” “Zelensky,” or “Zelenskiy”\n      count if pronounced equivalently\nContractions do not count for their constituent words unless otherwise explicitly specified\nby the Exchange:\n      <word> is “not” → “won’t,” “can’t,” “don’t,” “isn’t” do not count\nNumbers spoken as words COUNT, when spoken exactly (not part of a larger number):\n      <word> is “five” → saying “five” or reading “$5” aloud as “five dollars” counts,\n      saying “five hundred” does NOT count\n      <word> is “410” → “four hundred ten”, “four one zero” or “four ten” counts\nOrdinals COUNT when <word> is written numerically OR a phrase that includes a\nnumber:\n      <word> is “January 6” → “January 6th” counts\n      <word> is “3” (written numerically) → “3rd” (spoken as “third”) counts\n      <word> is “Eight War” → “8 Wars” and “Eighth War” will count\nCardinal and ordinal number words are distinct:\n      <word> is “one” → “first” does NOT count\n      <word> is “first” → “one” does NOT count\nAcronyms and abbreviations count when pronunciation or letter-by-letter spelling\nmatches <word>:\n      <word> is “NASA” → “NASA” (pronounced “NAH-suh”) counts\n      <word> is “NASA” → “N-A-S-A” (spelled out) counts\nAcronyms and abbreviations count as <word> when pronounced as the full word:\n      <word> is “Doctor” → “Dr.” (pronounced “Doctor”) counts\nExpanded forms of acronyms do NOT count:\n      <word> is “AI” → “artificial intelligence” does not count\nWords in foreign languages do NOT count unless they are perfect cognates with an\nEnglish word:\n      <word> is “fire” → “fuego” (Spanish) does NOT count\nEnglish words within foreign sentences count:\n      <word> is “policy” → “Nuestra policy es clara” counts\n<word> in organization/company names counts:\n      <word> is “Securities” → “Bank of America Securities” counts\nWords in URLs, emails, handles, and hashtags (exclusive of domain structure, email\nprovider or symbols) are treated as compounds when spoken as complete words, with the\ntype of compound subject to aforementioned rules:\n      <word> is “fire” → “firestation.com” pronounced “fire station dot com” counts\n      <word> is “fire” → “wildfire.com” pronounced “wildfire dot com” does NOT count\n      <word> is “apple” → “apple.com” pronounced “apple dot com” does count\n      When presented in URL, email, handle, or hashtag form, <word> shall be treated as\n      a compound, not a multi-word word\nSung, rapped, or poetic words COUNT if phonetically recognizable:\n      <word> is “money” → “moneyyy” (extended in rap) counts\n      Extreme distortion making <word> unrecognizable does NOT count.\nPhonetic alphabet spelling (“Foxtrot India Romeo Echo” for “FIRE”) does NOT count.\n\fCANCELLATIONS AND DELAYS\n\n   The Exchange may list an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike for any Contract. If listed,\n   such a strike refers to the structural conditions of the market, and is NOT adjudicated as a\n   <word> needing to be said by or validated by having been said by <entity>. If listed, this\n   strike resolves to “Yes” whenever the event fails to occur or qualify under the Payout\n   Criterion, or any other circumstance prevents normal resolution.\n   If no such strike is listed, and <time period> refers to a specific event, the following rules\n   apply if the event is cancelled, postponed, rescheduled, or materially altered (including\n   being closed to press) such that no video is released within one calendar day of the\n   original start time of the event:\n         If the event is cancelled, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price determined in\n         the sole discretion of the Exchange.\n         If the event is postponed or rescheduled, the outcome depends on whether a new\n         date is publicly announced within one calendar day (i.e. if the event was scheduled\n         to begin on Monday, any time up to 11:59PM on Tuesday falls within this period) of\n         the originally scheduled start time:\n               If no new date is announced within one calendar day, the Contract will resolve\n               to the last fair price determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\n               If a new date is announced within one calendar day, the outcome depends on\n               when the rescheduled event is set to occur:\n                     If the rescheduled date falls within fourteen (14) calendar days of the\n                     originally scheduled date, the Contract shall remain open and <word>\n                     stated during the rescheduled event will count.\n                           The fourteen-day window begins at 12:00 AM ET on the originally\n                           scheduled date and ends at 11:59 PM ET fourteen days later, unless\n                           an alternate timezone is explicitly specified.\n                           Example: <time period> is “during the State of the Union on January\n                           15, 2026” rescheduled to January 20, 2026 → words spoken during\n                           the rescheduled address count.\n                     If the rescheduled date falls more than fourteen (14) calendar days after\n                     the originally scheduled date, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price\n                     determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\n         Any Contract that cannot be resolved through the Source Agency hierarchy will\n         instead be settled at the Last Fair Price. The Exchange will disclose the methodology\n         used to determine the Last Fair Price (e.g., Last Traded Price, Time-Weighted\n         Average Price) at the time of Issuance.\n         If an event begins but is interrupted, abbreviated, or ends prematurely, words\n         stated by <entity> during the portion of the event that did occur will count and the\n         market will otherwise resolve.\n   If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window but the venue, format, or medium\n   changes (e.g., moved to a different location, changed from in-person to virtual (with the\n   exception of being closed to press)), words stated during the event will count.\n   Special condition: Across both cases, whether an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike is\n   listed or not, if the event specified as or in <time period> is a live-stream or broadcast (or\n   relayed as such) but the live stream/broadcast does not occur, the Exchange will instead\n   use an officially released recording as the Underlying, and may delay resolution by up to\n   one calendar day to allow for the release of such a recording.\n\f          If partial snippets are released, Contracts on words that do not appear will be\n          resolved to last fair price, and Contracts on those that do will be resolved to “Yes”.\n          If no recording is released, the relevant outcomes triggered by the\n          presence/absence of an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike shall occur as outlined\n          above.\n\nTECHNICAL DETAILS (UNLESS OTHERWISE SPECIFIED)\n\n     When <time period> refers to a specific event, pre-recorded content broadcast,\n     streamed, or published as part of that event is included if presented as part of the official\n     presentation.\n          Example: <time period> is “during the concert” with pre-recorded video interlude\n          where entity speaks → words from interlude count\n          Example: <time period> is “during the television appearance” with pre-taped\n          segment aired during broadcast → words from segment count\n     Behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are NOT\n     included unless officially broadcast or published as part of <time period>.\n     Subtitles and captions that display <word> on screen but are not spoken aloud by\n     <entity> do NOT count.\n     Sign language interpretation or usage by entity does NOT count as saying <word> unless\n     the Contract explicitly specifies that sign language counts.\n     Text that entity displays on screen (presentation slides, teleprompter visible to audience,\n     signatures) does NOT count unless entity reads it aloud.\n     Content generated by AI, deepfakes, or synthetic voice technology impersonating entity\n     does NOT count unless the synthetic content is officially commissioned, authorized, or\n     published by entity, OR the Contract explicitly specifies that AI-generated content counts.\n     If <word> is muted due to technical failure or censorship it shall not count unless\n     corroborating contextual evidence (including surrounding speech, or an official\n     uncensored recording or transcript) confirms that <entity> specifically uttered <word>\n     during the muted period.\n\nMinimum Tick: The Minimum Tick size for the Contract shall be $0.01.\n\nPosition Accountability Level: The Position Accountability Level for the Contract shall be\n$25,000 per strike, per Member.\n\nLast Trading Date: The Last Trading Date of the Contract will be the Expiration Date. The Last\nTrading Time will be the Expiration time.\n\nSettlement Date: The Settlement Date of the Contract shall be no later than the day after the\nExpiration Date, unless the Market Outcome is under review pursuant to Rule 7.1.\n\nExpiration Date: When <time period> refers to a specific event: The latest Expiration Date of\nthe Contract shall be fourteen (14) calendar days after the originally scheduled date of the\nevent. If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window, expiration will be moved to an\nearlier date and time in accordance with Rule 7.2. When <time period> is defined by specific\ndates: The latest Expiration Date of the Contract shall be two weeks after the end of <time\nperiod>. If an event described in the Payout Criterion occurs and a consensus has been\nreached on all terms, then expiration will be moved to an earlier date and time in accordance\nwith Rule 7.2.\n\fExpiration time: The Expiration time of the Contract shall be 10:00 AM ET.\n\nSettlement Value: The Settlement Value for this Contract is $1.00.\n\nExpiration Value: The Expiration Value is the value of the Underlying as documented by the\nSource Agency on the Expiration Date at the Expiration time.\n\nContingencies: Before Settlement, Kalshi may, at its sole discretion, initiate the Market\nOutcome Review Process pursuant to Rule 7.1 of the Rulebook. If an Expiration Value cannot\nbe determined on the Expiration Date, Kalshi has the right to determine payouts pursuant to\nRule 7.1 in the Rulebook.\n\f\n\n[plaintiff] PX-3 Official White House World Cup Drawing video page capture\nSource capture from official White House page https://www.whitehouse.gov/videos/president-trump-attends-the-fifa-world-cup-drawing/\nRetrieval: 2026-06-29T21:52:12Z via OpenClaw web_fetch and web.open.\n\nVisible page facts captured:\n- Page title: President Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing\n- Date shown on page: December 5, 2025\n- Page section: Videos\n- The page contains a link labeled View Full Video to Instagram.\n- Related video listed: FIFA World Cup 2026 Draw at The Kennedy Center, duration 00:45, dated December 6, 2025.\n- Related video listed: FIFA World Cup Drawing Announced to Take Place at The Kennedy Center, duration 00:56, dated August 23, 2025.\n- Related video listed: President Trump on the 2026 FIFA World Cup, duration 01:22, dated May 6, 2025.\n\nRelevant extracted lines from web.open capture:\nL142: Videos\nL143: # President Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing\nL145: December 5, 2025\nL133: ... View Full Video [instagram.com] ...\nL151: FIFA World Cup 2026 Draw at The Kennedy Center\nL153: December 6, 2025\nL167-L170: President Trump on the 2026 FIFA World Cup, May 6, 2025\n\nNotes on capture limits: readability extraction returned minimal content, so the above preserves visible lines from the page capture. The embedded/full video itself was not captured in this item.\n\n[plaintiff] PX-4 YouTube metadata capture for Ronaldo-at-FIFA-Draw clip\nSource capture: YouTube watch page https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Cb2yO0lLEnM\nVideo ID: Cb2yO0lLEnM\nRetrieval: 2026-06-29T21:53:00Z via web search and curl of the YouTube watch page.\n\nCaptured title / page metadata:\n- Title shown in search and page metadata: Trump Talks Cristiano Ronaldo at FIFA Draw — ‘He’s a Great Person’\n- Channel shown in page metadata: interestingText You / @InterestingTextYou\n- Subscriber count shown in page metadata at capture: about 10.3K subscribers\n\nCaptured description text from YouTube page metadata:\n\"Trump Talks Cristiano Ronaldo at FIFA Draw — ‘He’s a Great Person’\n\nAt the FIFA World Cup Draw Ceremony, Donald Trump shared a story about meeting Cristiano Ronaldo at the White House. Trump said Ronaldo was “a great person” and even mentioned that Ronaldo spoke with his son about soccer during the visit.\n\nThis unexpected crossover between world politics and one of the biggest global sports stars quickly caught viewers' attention.\n\nTrump FIFA Draw\nDonald Trump FIFA World Cup\nTrump Cristiano Ronaldo\nCristiano Ronaldo Trump meeting\nFIFA World Cup draw 2026\nRonaldo White House visit\nTrump soccer comments\nWorld Cup trending 2025\nsports politics crossover\nCristiano Ronaldo story\nDonald Trump viral moment\nFIFA draw ceremony Trump\nWorld Cup 2026 news\nRonaldo fan reaction\npolitical celebrity moments\nviral sports clips 2025\nFIFA draw highlights\nTrump speech FIFA\nglobal sports news\"\n\nCapture limits and provenance caveat: direct video/caption extraction was attempted but YouTube transcript/open paths were throttled or unavailable in this environment. This item preserves the public watch-page metadata and description, not an independently extracted audio transcript. It is not an official White House or FIFA source.\n\n[defendant] DX-1 GovInfo official transcript: remarks prior to FIFA World Cup Draw\nSource: GovInfo, Compilation of Presidential Documents, DCPD202501162\nURL retrieved: https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/DCPD-202501162/html/DCPD-202501162.htm\nRetrieval time: 2026-06-29T22:00:00Z\nLocal captured HTML size/hash: 51,571 bytes; SHA-256 eadbceeecf3e94f5bd423bcb8e8511165fdc7265dd8c1e025870c2e8f34dfd99\n\nMaterial captured text from official GovInfo HTML/web.open:\n\nAdministration of Donald J. Trump, 2025\n\nTitle: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\nDate: December 5, 2025\n\nOpening note: [The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\n\nExcerpt - The President's Interest in Soccer (web.open lines 196-203):\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\"football,\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\n\nExcerpt - The President's Interest in Soccer (web.open lines 322-329):\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\nThe President. But they have a little more speed. But no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\n\nTiming/context note (web.open lines 461-462):\nNOTE: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. In his remarks, he referred to Trey Yingst, chief foreign correspondent, Fox News Channel; Cristiano Ronaldo, forward for Saudi Pro League club Al-Nass and Portugal's national soccer team; and Lionel Messi, forward for Major League Soccer club Inter Miami and Argentina's national team. A reporter referred to New York State Attorney General Letitia James.\nThe transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\n\nDocument category/location/name/subject metadata (web.open lines 463-468):\nCategories: Interviews With the News Media: Exchanges with reporters, Washington, DC.\nLocations: Washington, DC.\nNames include: Cristiano Ronaldo and Lionel Messi.\nSubjects include: Federation Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) World Cup; John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts; News media, Presidential interviews; Soccer.\nDCPD Number: DCPD202501162.\n\nCapture limits: This item is a focused text capture of the material official transcript title, Ronaldo excerpts, timing/correction note, and metadata. It is not a full video or audio artifact. The official transcript itself notes some portions could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\n\n[defendant] DX-2 FIFA official Final Draw start-time capture\nSource: FIFA official page, FIFA World Cup 2026 Final Draw\nURL: https://www.fifa.com/en/tournaments/mens/worldcup/canadamexicousa2026/live-draw\nRetrieval time: 2026-06-29T22:01:00Z\n\nMaterial captured text from web search/open result:\n- Page title/source: FIFA World Cup 2026™ Final Draw\n- The draw takes place at the Kennedy Center in Washington DC, USA.\n- The draw commences at 12:00 local time (17:00 UTC) on Friday 5 December 2025.\n\nCapture limits: This is a focused text capture of the official FIFA page timing statement located by web search. It is not a video capture of the draw ceremony.\n\n[defendant] DX-3 Governing PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION terms\n                                         NEWMENTION\n\nScope: These rules shall apply to this contract.\n\nUnderlying: The Underlying for this Contract is words used by <entity> <time period>.\nRevisions to the Underlying made after Expiration will not be accounted for in determining the\nExpiration Value.\n\nSource Agency: The Source Agencies are <source>.\n\nType: The type of Contract is an Event Contract.\n\nIssuance: After the initial Contract, Contract iterations will be listed on an as-needed basis at\nthe discretion of the Exchange and corresponding to the risk management needs of Members.\n\n<entity>: <entity> refers to the speaker, writer, performer, or communicator specified by the\nExchange. This may include (but is not limited to): a specific named individual, multiple\nindividuals specified using AND/OR logic, an individual identified by position or title, a group,\nband, team or collective entity, a specified member or members of a group, an organization,\ncompany, or institutional entity, or any combination of the aforementioned.\n\nWhen <entity> is defined by a position or title, the Contract tracks whoever holds that position\nduring <time period>, even if the individual holding the position changes. When <entity> is a\nspecific named individual, the identity remains consistent throughout. Name changes (e.g.,\nstage names, married names) do not create a new entity. When <entity> is a group or\norganization and the Contract does not specify particular members, any official\ncommunication or statement by any member or designated spokesperson counts. When using\nAND logic, all specified entities must independently say <word> during <time period>. When\nusing OR logic, at least one of the specified entities must say <word> during <time period>.\nThe Exchange may specify additional conditions such as “at least X members of” a group or\n“the majority of” a group.\n\n<source>: <source> refers to a Source Agency or ordered collection of Source Agencies\nspecified by the Exchange at the time of Contract listing, which will be incorporated into the\nSource Agency hierarchy above and used to determine the occurrence of the Underlying.\n<source> may refer to a singular agency, multiple agencies, an agency by distinguishing\ncharacteristics, by category or type (e.g., “official government statistical body,” “primary wire\nservice”), or any combination thereof. When multiple agencies are specified, they may be\napplied in the hierarchical order designated by the Exchange if so specified, with the highest-\nranked available and responsive agency taking precedence for purposes of determining the\nExpiration Value. A lower-ranked agency shall only be consulted if all higher-ranked agencies\nare unavailable, unresponsive, have not reported on the Underlying by the Expiration time, or\nif the Exchange, in its sole discretion, determines that a higher-ranked agency’s reporting is\nincomplete, erroneous, or otherwise insufficient to determine the Expiration Value. If <source>\ndesignates multiple agencies without specifying a hierarchical order, the Exchange shall\nresolve any conflict between reporting agencies at its sole discretion.\n\n<word>: <word> refers to the particular word or phrase potentially to be mentioned by\n<entity>. It may refer to a word being said a minimum number of times. It may also refer to\none of multiple words/phrases, any of which are acceptable (e.g., “Doge/Dogecoin”).\n\f<time period>: <time period> refers to a specific range of time, event or discrete date and\ntime specified by the Exchange. This may be defined by, but is not limited to: a specific event\nor context (e.g., “during the State of the Union address”), exact dates or times, relative time\nmarkers (e.g., “before July 1, 2027,” “in Q1 2026”), event-based periods (e.g., “during any\ncampaign rally in October 2026,” “during the awards ceremony”), and broader intervals (e.g.,\n“Q1–Q2 2027,” “January–March 2026”).\n\nUnless stated otherwise, “Between” is inclusive of both endpoints, while “before” and “after”\nexclude the specified date. <time period> may also refer to “Any” or “None”, to multiple dates\n(even if non-consecutive), or to a singular and discrete date or time.\n\nWhen <time period> refers to a specific event (such as an address, speech, performance, or\nbroadcast), the Exchange may specify what is included, including whether it includes both live\nand pre-recorded segments (including whether advertisements are included). Where a\ntimezone is not specified, ET is assumed.\n\n\nPayout Criterion: The Payout Criterion for the Contract encompasses the Expiration Values that\n<word> is said by <entity> <time period>.\n\n\nThe word must appear as a distinct, standalone unit, not buried inside another word. Plural\nand possessive noun forms count. Other grammatical changes (tense, conjugation, derivation)\ndo not. If <word> appears separated from other words by a space or hyphen or in a\ncompound form with a space or hyphen, it counts. If <word> is fused into a single\nunhyphenated word, it does not count.\n\nIf <time period> refers to an event and that event is cancelled, and the market contains a\nstrike stating “Event does not qualify/occur”, such a strike shall resolve “Yes” and all others\n“No”. If <time period> refers to an event and that event is cancelled but such strikes are NOT\nlisted, the Contracts will resolve to the last fair price determined at the discretion of the\nExchange. If the event is postponed, and such a postponement is announced by the end of the\nfollowing calendar day to be rescheduled to a time within 14 calendar days, the markets shall\nremain open. If the event captured in <time period> is a live-stream or broadcast, the\nExchange may keep the market open for 24 hours for the release of an official recording.\nFurther granular details on conditions for these Contracts is available below.\n\nAdditional clarification(s):\n\n     Possessive noun forms of <word>, plurals, and possessive plural noun forms are\n     INCLUDED:\n          <word> is “Immigrant” → “Immigrants” counts\n          <word> is “Egg” → “eggs’ shells” counts\n          <word> is “Russia” → “Russia’s” counts, “Russian” does not\n     If <word> exists only in adjective form, no plural form exists:\n          <word> is “Economic” → “Economics” does not count (“Economic” is an adjective\n          for which “Economics” is not a plural)\n     Plural nouns occurring within proper nouns and noun phrases are included:\n          <word> is “Cat” → “Cats the musical” counts\n\f    Grammatical variations beyond plurals/possessives are NOT included:\n         <word> is “Immigrant” → “Immigration” does NOT count\n         <word> is “Run” → “Running” or “Ran” do NOT count\n    When <word> specifies a plural form, the singular does NOT count:\n         <word> is “Veterans” → “Veteran” does NOT count\n    Words that are spelled the same as the plural form of <word> (if such exists) but are\n    themselves not a plural noun are included:\n         <word> is “Wind” → “Winds up the clock” counts\n         <word> is “Border” → “The United States has strong borders” counts\n    Open compounds (words separated by spaces) count:\n         <word> is “fire” → “fire station” counts\n         <word> is “couch” → “couch potato” counts\n    Hyphenated compounds (words connected by hyphens) count:\n         <word> is “Palestine” → “pro-Palestine” counts\n         <word> is “fat” → “non-fat” counts\n    Closed compounds (single word, no spaces/hyphens) do not count:\n         <word> is “fire” → “wildfire” does not count\n         <word> is “fire” → “firefighter” does not count\n    Multi-word <word> in larger constructions: When <word> is a multi-word phrase\n    appearing within a hyphenated construction, it counts only if <word> appears as a\n    complete, unmodified element:\n         <word> is “New York” → “New York-based” counts (complete element)\n    Portmanteaus (words blended from two words where parts of each are combined) are\n    NOT included unless the portmanteau clearly contains <word> as a distinct, unaltered\n    element:\n         <word> is “MAGA” → “MAGA-nificent” counts (MAGA appears as distinct element)\n         <word> is “magnificent” → “MAGA-nificent” does NOT count (portmanteau blend)\n\nDictionary determination: Both the Merriam-Webster Dictionary (available online) AND the\nOxford English Dictionary shall be used to determine compound type and/or conventional\nspelling patterns. Inclusion in either dictionary as an open or hyphenated compound shall\nsatisfy the Payout Criterion. If neither provides clarity (or the word is not included),\ndetermination is based on whether written as single unit (closed/doesn’t count) vs. spaces or\nhyphens (open or hyphenated/counts) and/or context and previous usage.\n\nPHONETIC EQUIVALENCIES\n\n    Homophones (same sound, different spelling) do not count:\n        <word> is “write” → “right” does not count\n    Homonyms and homographs (same spelling) COUNT regardless of meaning or\n    pronunciation:\n        <word> is “bass” → both “bass guitar” and “bass fishing” count\n    Proper and common nouns are treated identically:\n        <word> is “Apple” → both “Apple Inc.” and “apple” (fruit) count\n        <word> is “Will” → both “Will Smith” and “I will go” count\n    Minor unintentional mispronunciations COUNT if context makes intent clear:\n        <word> is “Mamdani” → “Mandani” counts\n    Severe mispronunciations that make <word> unrecognizable do NOT count.\n    Trademarked spellings do not count, even when pronounced identically, unless the word\n\fitself is the same:\n      <word> is “lift” → “Lyft” (pronounced “lift”) does not count\n      <word> is “uber” → “Uber” counts\nWords with non-standard transliteration to English count within reason, provided they are\nphonetically equivalent:\n      <word> is “Zelensky” → any of “Zelenski,” “Zelenskii,” “Zelensky,” or “Zelenskiy”\n      count if pronounced equivalently\nContractions do not count for their constituent words unless otherwise explicitly specified\nby the Exchange:\n      <word> is “not” → “won’t,” “can’t,” “don’t,” “isn’t” do not count\nNumbers spoken as words COUNT, when spoken exactly (not part of a larger number):\n      <word> is “five” → saying “five” or reading “$5” aloud as “five dollars” counts,\n      saying “five hundred” does NOT count\n      <word> is “410” → “four hundred ten”, “four one zero” or “four ten” counts\nOrdinals COUNT when <word> is written numerically OR a phrase that includes a\nnumber:\n      <word> is “January 6” → “January 6th” counts\n      <word> is “3” (written numerically) → “3rd” (spoken as “third”) counts\n      <word> is “Eight War” → “8 Wars” and “Eighth War” will count\nCardinal and ordinal number words are distinct:\n      <word> is “one” → “first” does NOT count\n      <word> is “first” → “one” does NOT count\nAcronyms and abbreviations count when pronunciation or letter-by-letter spelling\nmatches <word>:\n      <word> is “NASA” → “NASA” (pronounced “NAH-suh”) counts\n      <word> is “NASA” → “N-A-S-A” (spelled out) counts\nAcronyms and abbreviations count as <word> when pronounced as the full word:\n      <word> is “Doctor” → “Dr.” (pronounced “Doctor”) counts\nExpanded forms of acronyms do NOT count:\n      <word> is “AI” → “artificial intelligence” does not count\nWords in foreign languages do NOT count unless they are perfect cognates with an\nEnglish word:\n      <word> is “fire” → “fuego” (Spanish) does NOT count\nEnglish words within foreign sentences count:\n      <word> is “policy” → “Nuestra policy es clara” counts\n<word> in organization/company names counts:\n      <word> is “Securities” → “Bank of America Securities” counts\nWords in URLs, emails, handles, and hashtags (exclusive of domain structure, email\nprovider or symbols) are treated as compounds when spoken as complete words, with the\ntype of compound subject to aforementioned rules:\n      <word> is “fire” → “firestation.com” pronounced “fire station dot com” counts\n      <word> is “fire” → “wildfire.com” pronounced “wildfire dot com” does NOT count\n      <word> is “apple” → “apple.com” pronounced “apple dot com” does count\n      When presented in URL, email, handle, or hashtag form, <word> shall be treated as\n      a compound, not a multi-word word\nSung, rapped, or poetic words COUNT if phonetically recognizable:\n      <word> is “money” → “moneyyy” (extended in rap) counts\n      Extreme distortion making <word> unrecognizable does NOT count.\nPhonetic alphabet spelling (“Foxtrot India Romeo Echo” for “FIRE”) does NOT count.\n\fCANCELLATIONS AND DELAYS\n\n   The Exchange may list an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike for any Contract. If listed,\n   such a strike refers to the structural conditions of the market, and is NOT adjudicated as a\n   <word> needing to be said by or validated by having been said by <entity>. If listed, this\n   strike resolves to “Yes” whenever the event fails to occur or qualify under the Payout\n   Criterion, or any other circumstance prevents normal resolution.\n   If no such strike is listed, and <time period> refers to a specific event, the following rules\n   apply if the event is cancelled, postponed, rescheduled, or materially altered (including\n   being closed to press) such that no video is released within one calendar day of the\n   original start time of the event:\n         If the event is cancelled, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price determined in\n         the sole discretion of the Exchange.\n         If the event is postponed or rescheduled, the outcome depends on whether a new\n         date is publicly announced within one calendar day (i.e. if the event was scheduled\n         to begin on Monday, any time up to 11:59PM on Tuesday falls within this period) of\n         the originally scheduled start time:\n               If no new date is announced within one calendar day, the Contract will resolve\n               to the last fair price determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\n               If a new date is announced within one calendar day, the outcome depends on\n               when the rescheduled event is set to occur:\n                     If the rescheduled date falls within fourteen (14) calendar days of the\n                     originally scheduled date, the Contract shall remain open and <word>\n                     stated during the rescheduled event will count.\n                           The fourteen-day window begins at 12:00 AM ET on the originally\n                           scheduled date and ends at 11:59 PM ET fourteen days later, unless\n                           an alternate timezone is explicitly specified.\n                           Example: <time period> is “during the State of the Union on January\n                           15, 2026” rescheduled to January 20, 2026 → words spoken during\n                           the rescheduled address count.\n                     If the rescheduled date falls more than fourteen (14) calendar days after\n                     the originally scheduled date, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price\n                     determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\n         Any Contract that cannot be resolved through the Source Agency hierarchy will\n         instead be settled at the Last Fair Price. The Exchange will disclose the methodology\n         used to determine the Last Fair Price (e.g., Last Traded Price, Time-Weighted\n         Average Price) at the time of Issuance.\n         If an event begins but is interrupted, abbreviated, or ends prematurely, words\n         stated by <entity> during the portion of the event that did occur will count and the\n         market will otherwise resolve.\n   If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window but the venue, format, or medium\n   changes (e.g., moved to a different location, changed from in-person to virtual (with the\n   exception of being closed to press)), words stated during the event will count.\n   Special condition: Across both cases, whether an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike is\n   listed or not, if the event specified as or in <time period> is a live-stream or broadcast (or\n   relayed as such) but the live stream/broadcast does not occur, the Exchange will instead\n   use an officially released recording as the Underlying, and may delay resolution by up to\n   one calendar day to allow for the release of such a recording.\n\f          If partial snippets are released, Contracts on words that do not appear will be\n          resolved to last fair price, and Contracts on those that do will be resolved to “Yes”.\n          If no recording is released, the relevant outcomes triggered by the\n          presence/absence of an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike shall occur as outlined\n          above.\n\nTECHNICAL DETAILS (UNLESS OTHERWISE SPECIFIED)\n\n     When <time period> refers to a specific event, pre-recorded content broadcast,\n     streamed, or published as part of that event is included if presented as part of the official\n     presentation.\n          Example: <time period> is “during the concert” with pre-recorded video interlude\n          where entity speaks → words from interlude count\n          Example: <time period> is “during the television appearance” with pre-taped\n          segment aired during broadcast → words from segment count\n     Behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are NOT\n     included unless officially broadcast or published as part of <time period>.\n     Subtitles and captions that display <word> on screen but are not spoken aloud by\n     <entity> do NOT count.\n     Sign language interpretation or usage by entity does NOT count as saying <word> unless\n     the Contract explicitly specifies that sign language counts.\n     Text that entity displays on screen (presentation slides, teleprompter visible to audience,\n     signatures) does NOT count unless entity reads it aloud.\n     Content generated by AI, deepfakes, or synthetic voice technology impersonating entity\n     does NOT count unless the synthetic content is officially commissioned, authorized, or\n     published by entity, OR the Contract explicitly specifies that AI-generated content counts.\n     If <word> is muted due to technical failure or censorship it shall not count unless\n     corroborating contextual evidence (including surrounding speech, or an official\n     uncensored recording or transcript) confirms that <entity> specifically uttered <word>\n     during the muted period.\n\nMinimum Tick: The Minimum Tick size for the Contract shall be $0.01.\n\nPosition Accountability Level: The Position Accountability Level for the Contract shall be\n$25,000 per strike, per Member.\n\nLast Trading Date: The Last Trading Date of the Contract will be the Expiration Date. The Last\nTrading Time will be the Expiration time.\n\nSettlement Date: The Settlement Date of the Contract shall be no later than the day after the\nExpiration Date, unless the Market Outcome is under review pursuant to Rule 7.1.\n\nExpiration Date: When <time period> refers to a specific event: The latest Expiration Date of\nthe Contract shall be fourteen (14) calendar days after the originally scheduled date of the\nevent. If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window, expiration will be moved to an\nearlier date and time in accordance with Rule 7.2. When <time period> is defined by specific\ndates: The latest Expiration Date of the Contract shall be two weeks after the end of <time\nperiod>. If an event described in the Payout Criterion occurs and a consensus has been\nreached on all terms, then expiration will be moved to an earlier date and time in accordance\nwith Rule 7.2.\n\fExpiration time: The Expiration time of the Contract shall be 10:00 AM ET.\n\nSettlement Value: The Settlement Value for this Contract is $1.00.\n\nExpiration Value: The Expiration Value is the value of the Underlying as documented by the\nSource Agency on the Expiration Date at the Expiration time.\n\nContingencies: Before Settlement, Kalshi may, at its sole discretion, initiate the Market\nOutcome Review Process pursuant to Rule 7.1 of the Rulebook. If an Expiration Value cannot\nbe determined on the Expiration Date, Kalshi has the right to determine payouts pursuant to\nRule 7.1 in the Rulebook.\n\f\n\n[defendant] DX-4 Market packet: Ronaldo strike and challenged No resolution\nMarket URL: https://kalshi.com/markets/kxtrumpmentionb/trump-mention-b/kxtrumpmentionb-25dec06\n\nPublic market title: What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\n\nContract family: PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION\n\nStrike at issue: Ronaldo\n\nChallenged resolution: No\n\nRequested resolution: Yes\n\n\n[plaintiff] PX-R1 GovInfo transcript confirming Ronaldo utterances and Kennedy Center/FIFA Draw context\nSource: GovInfo, Compilation of Presidential Documents, DCPD202501162\nURL retrieved: https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/DCPD-202501162/html/DCPD-202501162.htm\nRetrieval time: 2026-06-29T22:00:00Z\nLocal captured HTML size/hash: 51,571 bytes; SHA-256 eadbceeecf3e94f5bd423bcb8e8511165fdc7265dd8c1e025870c2e8f34dfd99\n\nMaterial captured text from official GovInfo HTML/web.open:\n\nAdministration of Donald J. Trump, 2025\n\nTitle: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\nDate: December 5, 2025\n\nOpening note: [The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\n\nExcerpt - The President's Interest in Soccer (web.open lines 196-203):\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\"football,\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\n\nExcerpt - The President's Interest in Soccer (web.open lines 322-329):\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\nThe President. But they have a little more speed. But no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\n\nTiming/context note (web.open lines 461-462):\nNOTE: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. In his remarks, he referred to Trey Yingst, chief foreign correspondent, Fox News Channel; Cristiano Ronaldo, forward for Saudi Pro League club Al-Nass and Portugal's national soccer team; and Lionel Messi, forward for Major League Soccer club Inter Miami and Argentina's national team. A reporter referred to New York State Attorney General Letitia James.\nThe transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\n\nDocument category/location/name/subject metadata (web.open lines 463-468):\nCategories: Interviews With the News Media: Exchanges with reporters, Washington, DC.\nLocations: Washington, DC.\nNames include: Cristiano Ronaldo and Lionel Messi.\nSubjects include: Federation Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) World Cup; John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts; News media, Presidential interviews; Soccer.\nDCPD Number: DCPD202501162.\n\nCapture limits: This item is a focused text capture of the material official transcript title, Ronaldo excerpts, timing/correction note, and metadata. It is not a full video or audio artifact. The official transcript itself notes some portions could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\n\n[plaintiff] PX-R2 FIFA timing capture showing formal commencement time but not market-specific exclusion\nSource: FIFA official page, FIFA World Cup 2026 Final Draw\nURL: https://www.fifa.com/en/tournaments/mens/worldcup/canadamexicousa2026/live-draw\nRetrieval time: 2026-06-29T22:01:00Z\n\nMaterial captured text from web search/open result:\n- Page title/source: FIFA World Cup 2026™ Final Draw\n- The draw takes place at the Kennedy Center in Washington DC, USA.\n- The draw commences at 12:00 local time (17:00 UTC) on Friday 5 December 2025.\n\nCapture limits: This is a focused text capture of the official FIFA page timing statement located by web search. It is not a video capture of the draw ceremony.\n\n[plaintiff] PX-R3 Event-period terms and exclusions\n                                         NEWMENTION\n\nScope: These rules shall apply to this contract.\n\nUnderlying: The Underlying for this Contract is words used by <entity> <time period>.\nRevisions to the Underlying made after Expiration will not be accounted for in determining the\nExpiration Value.\n\nSource Agency: The Source Agencies are <source>.\n\nType: The type of Contract is an Event Contract.\n\nIssuance: After the initial Contract, Contract iterations will be listed on an as-needed basis at\nthe discretion of the Exchange and corresponding to the risk management needs of Members.\n\n<entity>: <entity> refers to the speaker, writer, performer, or communicator specified by the\nExchange. This may include (but is not limited to): a specific named individual, multiple\nindividuals specified using AND/OR logic, an individual identified by position or title, a group,\nband, team or collective entity, a specified member or members of a group, an organization,\ncompany, or institutional entity, or any combination of the aforementioned.\n\nWhen <entity> is defined by a position or title, the Contract tracks whoever holds that position\nduring <time period>, even if the individual holding the position changes. When <entity> is a\nspecific named individual, the identity remains consistent throughout. Name changes (e.g.,\nstage names, married names) do not create a new entity. When <entity> is a group or\norganization and the Contract does not specify particular members, any official\ncommunication or statement by any member or designated spokesperson counts. When using\nAND logic, all specified entities must independently say <word> during <time period>. When\nusing OR logic, at least one of the specified entities must say <word> during <time period>.\nThe Exchange may specify additional conditions such as “at least X members of” a group or\n“the majority of” a group.\n\n<source>: <source> refers to a Source Agency or ordered collection of Source Agencies\nspecified by the Exchange at the time of Contract listing, which will be incorporated into the\nSource Agency hierarchy above and used to determine the occurrence of the Underlying.\n<source> may refer to a singular agency, multiple agencies, an agency by distinguishing\ncharacteristics, by category or type (e.g., “official government statistical body,” “primary wire\nservice”), or any combination thereof. When multiple agencies are specified, they may be\napplied in the hierarchical order designated by the Exchange if so specified, with the highest-\nranked available and responsive agency taking precedence for purposes of determining the\nExpiration Value. A lower-ranked agency shall only be consulted if all higher-ranked agencies\nare unavailable, unresponsive, have not reported on the Underlying by the Expiration time, or\nif the Exchange, in its sole discretion, determines that a higher-ranked agency’s reporting is\nincomplete, erroneous, or otherwise insufficient to determine the Expiration Value. If <source>\ndesignates multiple agencies without specifying a hierarchical order, the Exchange shall\nresolve any conflict between reporting agencies at its sole discretion.\n\n<word>: <word> refers to the particular word or phrase potentially to be mentioned by\n<entity>. It may refer to a word being said a minimum number of times. It may also refer to\none of multiple words/phrases, any of which are acceptable (e.g., “Doge/Dogecoin”).\n\f<time period>: <time period> refers to a specific range of time, event or discrete date and\ntime specified by the Exchange. This may be defined by, but is not limited to: a specific event\nor context (e.g., “during the State of the Union address”), exact dates or times, relative time\nmarkers (e.g., “before July 1, 2027,” “in Q1 2026”), event-based periods (e.g., “during any\ncampaign rally in October 2026,” “during the awards ceremony”), and broader intervals (e.g.,\n“Q1–Q2 2027,” “January–March 2026”).\n\nUnless stated otherwise, “Between” is inclusive of both endpoints, while “before” and “after”\nexclude the specified date. <time period> may also refer to “Any” or “None”, to multiple dates\n(even if non-consecutive), or to a singular and discrete date or time.\n\nWhen <time period> refers to a specific event (such as an address, speech, performance, or\nbroadcast), the Exchange may specify what is included, including whether it includes both live\nand pre-recorded segments (including whether advertisements are included). Where a\ntimezone is not specified, ET is assumed.\n\n\nPayout Criterion: The Payout Criterion for the Contract encompasses the Expiration Values that\n<word> is said by <entity> <time period>.\n\n\nThe word must appear as a distinct, standalone unit, not buried inside another word. Plural\nand possessive noun forms count. Other grammatical changes (tense, conjugation, derivation)\ndo not. If <word> appears separated from other words by a space or hyphen or in a\ncompound form with a space or hyphen, it counts. If <word> is fused into a single\nunhyphenated word, it does not count.\n\nIf <time period> refers to an event and that event is cancelled, and the market contains a\nstrike stating “Event does not qualify/occur”, such a strike shall resolve “Yes” and all others\n“No”. If <time period> refers to an event and that event is cancelled but such strikes are NOT\nlisted, the Contracts will resolve to the last fair price determined at the discretion of the\nExchange. If the event is postponed, and such a postponement is announced by the end of the\nfollowing calendar day to be rescheduled to a time within 14 calendar days, the markets shall\nremain open. If the event captured in <time period> is a live-stream or broadcast, the\nExchange may keep the market open for 24 hours for the release of an official recording.\nFurther granular details on conditions for these Contracts is available below.\n\nAdditional clarification(s):\n\n     Possessive noun forms of <word>, plurals, and possessive plural noun forms are\n     INCLUDED:\n          <word> is “Immigrant” → “Immigrants” counts\n          <word> is “Egg” → “eggs’ shells” counts\n          <word> is “Russia” → “Russia’s” counts, “Russian” does not\n     If <word> exists only in adjective form, no plural form exists:\n          <word> is “Economic” → “Economics” does not count (“Economic” is an adjective\n          for which “Economics” is not a plural)\n     Plural nouns occurring within proper nouns and noun phrases are included:\n          <word> is “Cat” → “Cats the musical” counts\n\f    Grammatical variations beyond plurals/possessives are NOT included:\n         <word> is “Immigrant” → “Immigration” does NOT count\n         <word> is “Run” → “Running” or “Ran” do NOT count\n    When <word> specifies a plural form, the singular does NOT count:\n         <word> is “Veterans” → “Veteran” does NOT count\n    Words that are spelled the same as the plural form of <word> (if such exists) but are\n    themselves not a plural noun are included:\n         <word> is “Wind” → “Winds up the clock” counts\n         <word> is “Border” → “The United States has strong borders” counts\n    Open compounds (words separated by spaces) count:\n         <word> is “fire” → “fire station” counts\n         <word> is “couch” → “couch potato” counts\n    Hyphenated compounds (words connected by hyphens) count:\n         <word> is “Palestine” → “pro-Palestine” counts\n         <word> is “fat” → “non-fat” counts\n    Closed compounds (single word, no spaces/hyphens) do not count:\n         <word> is “fire” → “wildfire” does not count\n         <word> is “fire” → “firefighter” does not count\n    Multi-word <word> in larger constructions: When <word> is a multi-word phrase\n    appearing within a hyphenated construction, it counts only if <word> appears as a\n    complete, unmodified element:\n         <word> is “New York” → “New York-based” counts (complete element)\n    Portmanteaus (words blended from two words where parts of each are combined) are\n    NOT included unless the portmanteau clearly contains <word> as a distinct, unaltered\n    element:\n         <word> is “MAGA” → “MAGA-nificent” counts (MAGA appears as distinct element)\n         <word> is “magnificent” → “MAGA-nificent” does NOT count (portmanteau blend)\n\nDictionary determination: Both the Merriam-Webster Dictionary (available online) AND the\nOxford English Dictionary shall be used to determine compound type and/or conventional\nspelling patterns. Inclusion in either dictionary as an open or hyphenated compound shall\nsatisfy the Payout Criterion. If neither provides clarity (or the word is not included),\ndetermination is based on whether written as single unit (closed/doesn’t count) vs. spaces or\nhyphens (open or hyphenated/counts) and/or context and previous usage.\n\nPHONETIC EQUIVALENCIES\n\n    Homophones (same sound, different spelling) do not count:\n        <word> is “write” → “right” does not count\n    Homonyms and homographs (same spelling) COUNT regardless of meaning or\n    pronunciation:\n        <word> is “bass” → both “bass guitar” and “bass fishing” count\n    Proper and common nouns are treated identically:\n        <word> is “Apple” → both “Apple Inc.” and “apple” (fruit) count\n        <word> is “Will” → both “Will Smith” and “I will go” count\n    Minor unintentional mispronunciations COUNT if context makes intent clear:\n        <word> is “Mamdani” → “Mandani” counts\n    Severe mispronunciations that make <word> unrecognizable do NOT count.\n    Trademarked spellings do not count, even when pronounced identically, unless the word\n\fitself is the same:\n      <word> is “lift” → “Lyft” (pronounced “lift”) does not count\n      <word> is “uber” → “Uber” counts\nWords with non-standard transliteration to English count within reason, provided they are\nphonetically equivalent:\n      <word> is “Zelensky” → any of “Zelenski,” “Zelenskii,” “Zelensky,” or “Zelenskiy”\n      count if pronounced equivalently\nContractions do not count for their constituent words unless otherwise explicitly specified\nby the Exchange:\n      <word> is “not” → “won’t,” “can’t,” “don’t,” “isn’t” do not count\nNumbers spoken as words COUNT, when spoken exactly (not part of a larger number):\n      <word> is “five” → saying “five” or reading “$5” aloud as “five dollars” counts,\n      saying “five hundred” does NOT count\n      <word> is “410” → “four hundred ten”, “four one zero” or “four ten” counts\nOrdinals COUNT when <word> is written numerically OR a phrase that includes a\nnumber:\n      <word> is “January 6” → “January 6th” counts\n      <word> is “3” (written numerically) → “3rd” (spoken as “third”) counts\n      <word> is “Eight War” → “8 Wars” and “Eighth War” will count\nCardinal and ordinal number words are distinct:\n      <word> is “one” → “first” does NOT count\n      <word> is “first” → “one” does NOT count\nAcronyms and abbreviations count when pronunciation or letter-by-letter spelling\nmatches <word>:\n      <word> is “NASA” → “NASA” (pronounced “NAH-suh”) counts\n      <word> is “NASA” → “N-A-S-A” (spelled out) counts\nAcronyms and abbreviations count as <word> when pronounced as the full word:\n      <word> is “Doctor” → “Dr.” (pronounced “Doctor”) counts\nExpanded forms of acronyms do NOT count:\n      <word> is “AI” → “artificial intelligence” does not count\nWords in foreign languages do NOT count unless they are perfect cognates with an\nEnglish word:\n      <word> is “fire” → “fuego” (Spanish) does NOT count\nEnglish words within foreign sentences count:\n      <word> is “policy” → “Nuestra policy es clara” counts\n<word> in organization/company names counts:\n      <word> is “Securities” → “Bank of America Securities” counts\nWords in URLs, emails, handles, and hashtags (exclusive of domain structure, email\nprovider or symbols) are treated as compounds when spoken as complete words, with the\ntype of compound subject to aforementioned rules:\n      <word> is “fire” → “firestation.com” pronounced “fire station dot com” counts\n      <word> is “fire” → “wildfire.com” pronounced “wildfire dot com” does NOT count\n      <word> is “apple” → “apple.com” pronounced “apple dot com” does count\n      When presented in URL, email, handle, or hashtag form, <word> shall be treated as\n      a compound, not a multi-word word\nSung, rapped, or poetic words COUNT if phonetically recognizable:\n      <word> is “money” → “moneyyy” (extended in rap) counts\n      Extreme distortion making <word> unrecognizable does NOT count.\nPhonetic alphabet spelling (“Foxtrot India Romeo Echo” for “FIRE”) does NOT count.\n\fCANCELLATIONS AND DELAYS\n\n   The Exchange may list an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike for any Contract. If listed,\n   such a strike refers to the structural conditions of the market, and is NOT adjudicated as a\n   <word> needing to be said by or validated by having been said by <entity>. If listed, this\n   strike resolves to “Yes” whenever the event fails to occur or qualify under the Payout\n   Criterion, or any other circumstance prevents normal resolution.\n   If no such strike is listed, and <time period> refers to a specific event, the following rules\n   apply if the event is cancelled, postponed, rescheduled, or materially altered (including\n   being closed to press) such that no video is released within one calendar day of the\n   original start time of the event:\n         If the event is cancelled, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price determined in\n         the sole discretion of the Exchange.\n         If the event is postponed or rescheduled, the outcome depends on whether a new\n         date is publicly announced within one calendar day (i.e. if the event was scheduled\n         to begin on Monday, any time up to 11:59PM on Tuesday falls within this period) of\n         the originally scheduled start time:\n               If no new date is announced within one calendar day, the Contract will resolve\n               to the last fair price determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\n               If a new date is announced within one calendar day, the outcome depends on\n               when the rescheduled event is set to occur:\n                     If the rescheduled date falls within fourteen (14) calendar days of the\n                     originally scheduled date, the Contract shall remain open and <word>\n                     stated during the rescheduled event will count.\n                           The fourteen-day window begins at 12:00 AM ET on the originally\n                           scheduled date and ends at 11:59 PM ET fourteen days later, unless\n                           an alternate timezone is explicitly specified.\n                           Example: <time period> is “during the State of the Union on January\n                           15, 2026” rescheduled to January 20, 2026 → words spoken during\n                           the rescheduled address count.\n                     If the rescheduled date falls more than fourteen (14) calendar days after\n                     the originally scheduled date, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price\n                     determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\n         Any Contract that cannot be resolved through the Source Agency hierarchy will\n         instead be settled at the Last Fair Price. The Exchange will disclose the methodology\n         used to determine the Last Fair Price (e.g., Last Traded Price, Time-Weighted\n         Average Price) at the time of Issuance.\n         If an event begins but is interrupted, abbreviated, or ends prematurely, words\n         stated by <entity> during the portion of the event that did occur will count and the\n         market will otherwise resolve.\n   If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window but the venue, format, or medium\n   changes (e.g., moved to a different location, changed from in-person to virtual (with the\n   exception of being closed to press)), words stated during the event will count.\n   Special condition: Across both cases, whether an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike is\n   listed or not, if the event specified as or in <time period> is a live-stream or broadcast (or\n   relayed as such) but the live stream/broadcast does not occur, the Exchange will instead\n   use an officially released recording as the Underlying, and may delay resolution by up to\n   one calendar day to allow for the release of such a recording.\n\f          If partial snippets are released, Contracts on words that do not appear will be\n          resolved to last fair price, and Contracts on those that do will be resolved to “Yes”.\n          If no recording is released, the relevant outcomes triggered by the\n          presence/absence of an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike shall occur as outlined\n          above.\n\nTECHNICAL DETAILS (UNLESS OTHERWISE SPECIFIED)\n\n     When <time period> refers to a specific event, pre-recorded content broadcast,\n     streamed, or published as part of that event is included if presented as part of the official\n     presentation.\n          Example: <time period> is “during the concert” with pre-recorded video interlude\n          where entity speaks → words from interlude count\n          Example: <time period> is “during the television appearance” with pre-taped\n          segment aired during broadcast → words from segment count\n     Behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are NOT\n     included unless officially broadcast or published as part of <time period>.\n     Subtitles and captions that display <word> on screen but are not spoken aloud by\n     <entity> do NOT count.\n     Sign language interpretation or usage by entity does NOT count as saying <word> unless\n     the Contract explicitly specifies that sign language counts.\n     Text that entity displays on screen (presentation slides, teleprompter visible to audience,\n     signatures) does NOT count unless entity reads it aloud.\n     Content generated by AI, deepfakes, or synthetic voice technology impersonating entity\n     does NOT count unless the synthetic content is officially commissioned, authorized, or\n     published by entity, OR the Contract explicitly specifies that AI-generated content counts.\n     If <word> is muted due to technical failure or censorship it shall not count unless\n     corroborating contextual evidence (including surrounding speech, or an official\n     uncensored recording or transcript) confirms that <entity> specifically uttered <word>\n     during the muted period.\n\nMinimum Tick: The Minimum Tick size for the Contract shall be $0.01.\n\nPosition Accountability Level: The Position Accountability Level for the Contract shall be\n$25,000 per strike, per Member.\n\nLast Trading Date: The Last Trading Date of the Contract will be the Expiration Date. The Last\nTrading Time will be the Expiration time.\n\nSettlement Date: The Settlement Date of the Contract shall be no later than the day after the\nExpiration Date, unless the Market Outcome is under review pursuant to Rule 7.1.\n\nExpiration Date: When <time period> refers to a specific event: The latest Expiration Date of\nthe Contract shall be fourteen (14) calendar days after the originally scheduled date of the\nevent. If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window, expiration will be moved to an\nearlier date and time in accordance with Rule 7.2. When <time period> is defined by specific\ndates: The latest Expiration Date of the Contract shall be two weeks after the end of <time\nperiod>. If an event described in the Payout Criterion occurs and a consensus has been\nreached on all terms, then expiration will be moved to an earlier date and time in accordance\nwith Rule 7.2.\n\fExpiration time: The Expiration time of the Contract shall be 10:00 AM ET.\n\nSettlement Value: The Settlement Value for this Contract is $1.00.\n\nExpiration Value: The Expiration Value is the value of the Underlying as documented by the\nSource Agency on the Expiration Date at the Expiration time.\n\nContingencies: Before Settlement, Kalshi may, at its sole discretion, initiate the Market\nOutcome Review Process pursuant to Rule 7.1 of the Rulebook. If an Expiration Value cannot\nbe determined on the Expiration Date, Kalshi has the right to determine payouts pursuant to\nRule 7.1 in the Rulebook.\n\f\n\n[defendant] DX-S1 GovInfo official transcript: prior reporter exchange\nSource: GovInfo, Compilation of Presidential Documents, DCPD202501162\nURL retrieved: https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/DCPD-202501162/html/DCPD-202501162.htm\nRetrieval time: 2026-06-29T22:00:00Z\nLocal captured HTML size/hash: 51,571 bytes; SHA-256 eadbceeecf3e94f5bd423bcb8e8511165fdc7265dd8c1e025870c2e8f34dfd99\n\nMaterial captured text from official GovInfo HTML/web.open:\n\nAdministration of Donald J. Trump, 2025\n\nTitle: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\nDate: December 5, 2025\n\nOpening note: [The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\n\nExcerpt - The President's Interest in Soccer (web.open lines 196-203):\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\"football,\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\n\nExcerpt - The President's Interest in Soccer (web.open lines 322-329):\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\nThe President. But they have a little more speed. But no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\n\nTiming/context note (web.open lines 461-462):\nNOTE: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. In his remarks, he referred to Trey Yingst, chief foreign correspondent, Fox News Channel; Cristiano Ronaldo, forward for Saudi Pro League club Al-Nass and Portugal's national soccer team; and Lionel Messi, forward for Major League Soccer club Inter Miami and Argentina's national team. A reporter referred to New York State Attorney General Letitia James.\nThe transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\n\nDocument category/location/name/subject metadata (web.open lines 463-468):\nCategories: Interviews With the News Media: Exchanges with reporters, Washington, DC.\nLocations: Washington, DC.\nNames include: Cristiano Ronaldo and Lionel Messi.\nSubjects include: Federation Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) World Cup; John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts; News media, Presidential interviews; Soccer.\nDCPD Number: DCPD202501162.\n\nCapture limits: This item is a focused text capture of the material official transcript title, Ronaldo excerpts, timing/correction note, and metadata. It is not a full video or audio artifact. The official transcript itself notes some portions could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\n\n[defendant] DX-S2 FIFA official draw commencement time\nSource: FIFA official page, FIFA World Cup 2026 Final Draw\nURL: https://www.fifa.com/en/tournaments/mens/worldcup/canadamexicousa2026/live-draw\nRetrieval time: 2026-06-29T22:01:00Z\n\nMaterial captured text from web search/open result:\n- Page title/source: FIFA World Cup 2026™ Final Draw\n- The draw takes place at the Kennedy Center in Washington DC, USA.\n- The draw commences at 12:00 local time (17:00 UTC) on Friday 5 December 2025.\n\nCapture limits: This is a focused text capture of the official FIFA page timing statement located by web search. It is not a video capture of the draw ceremony.\n\nSubmitted evidence:\n[plaintiff arguments] Official White House video page capture: President Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing (ev_db357d4e9407_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-db357d4e9407)\nSource: https://www.whitehouse.gov/videos/president-trump-attends-the-fifa-world-cup-drawing/\nSHA-256: `db357d4e940728d417ae4f7f3caac6b78d3fd3e4aba70d46fe10c6132d45997a`\nBytes: 1300\nRelevance: Establishes that the White House officially published a video page titled President Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing, dated December 5, 2025, with a full-video link and related World Cup Draw videos; relevant to source chain and event context.\n\n[plaintiff arguments] YouTube metadata capture: Trump Talks Cristiano Ronaldo at FIFA Draw (ev_4e1045905547_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-4e1045905547)\nSource: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Cb2yO0lLEnM\nSHA-256: `4e10459055477440085fe5e20d970eb2488e61d13a5e2b3133a3656bed7526d7`\nBytes: 1779\nRelevance: Provides a public clip source and page metadata asserting that at the FIFA World Cup Draw Ceremony Trump shared a story about meeting Cristiano Ronaldo and said Ronaldo was a great person; relevant to the alleged Ronaldo utterance, though weaker than an official full transcript or video.\n\n[defendant arguments] GovInfo official transcript capture: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the FIFA World Cup Draw (ev_a1b1f6b1b7bd_submitted-evidence-03-defendant-a1b1f6b1b7bd)\nSource: https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/DCPD-202501162/html/DCPD-202501162.htm\nSHA-256: `a1b1f6b1b7bd0b691c7fe8d97467dd0d085e2b22387ae4198270764de66e56e2`\nBytes: 3070\nRelevance: Official transcript identifies the relevant Trump remarks as an exchange with reporters prior to the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw; it includes the Ronaldo utterances and timing/correction notes, directly bearing on whether the utterances were during the countable event period.\n\n[defendant arguments] FIFA official page capture: 2026 World Cup Final Draw start time (ev_3973dc8f98c0_submitted-evidence-04-defendant-3973dc8f98c0)\nSource: https://www.fifa.com/en/tournaments/mens/worldcup/canadamexicousa2026/live-draw\nSHA-256: `3973dc8f98c01702174f61f5548eb1e80efe64dd72b44f21ed0fa7d944f93248`\nBytes: 598\nRelevance: Establishes the official Final Draw start time as 12:00 local time on December 5, 2025, which helps compare the draw event period against the GovInfo transcript note that the reporter exchange occurred at 11:13 a.m.\n\nTechnical reports:\n[plaintiff] Plaintiff source-search and capture ledger\nSearched exact market/strike phrases, White House domain, public video pages, YouTube video IDs, and Kalshi live market URL. Submitted official White House page capture and YouTube metadata capture. Kalshi live page returned a Vercel security checkpoint/429; local browser was unavailable; Python pip/ensurepip unavailable for yt-dlp; direct YouTube caption/open paths were throttled or unavailable. Remaining best evidence would be a full official video/transcript or Kalshi resolution rationale if later accessible.\n\n[defendant] Defendant source-search and capture ledger\nInspected current AAR evidence and exact contents of plaintiff's White House and YouTube captures. Retrieved GovInfo official HTML transcript with curl from DCPD-202501162; local full HTML was 51,571 bytes with SHA-256 eadbceeecf3e94f5bd423bcb8e8511165fdc7265dd8c1e025870c2e8f34dfd99, then submitted a focused material text capture as DX-1. Searched official draw timing and submitted the FIFA official page timing statement as DX-2. Remaining gaps: full Kalshi market source hierarchy/resolution rationale and full WH/FIFA video were not captured, but official GovInfo timing/title plus FIFA start time resolve the material timing issue.\n\nCall submit_council_vote with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated.\nKeep the rationale brief: no more than three sentences.\n\nCouncil API instructions:\nYou are a council member. Decide the proposition from the admitted record.\nYou may examine admitted evidence through read-only tools when exact bytes, metadata, or exhibit contents matter.\nDo not search the web, introduce new facts, create new evidence, or upload evidence.\nWhen ready, call submit_council_vote exactly once with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated and a concise rationale.\n","state":"ready","status":"ready","tools":[{"description":"Return the current visible arbitration record for this council member.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{},"type":"object"},"name":"get_case","read_only":true},{"description":"List visible immutable record evidence.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{},"type":"object"},"name":"list_evidence","read_only":true},{"description":"Return metadata and read limits for one visible evidence item.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"evidence_id":{"type":"string"}},"required":["evidence_id"],"type":"object"},"name":"stat_evidence","read_only":true},{"description":"Read a bounded byte range from one visible evidence item as base64.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"evidence_id":{"type":"string"},"length":{"minimum":1,"type":"integer"},"offset":{"minimum":0,"type":"integer"}},"required":["evidence_id","offset","length"],"type":"object"},"name":"read_evidence_range","read_only":true},{"description":"Submit one council vote for the current deliberation opportunity.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"rationale":{"type":"string"},"vote":{"enum":["demonstrated","not_demonstrated"],"type":"string"}},"required":["vote","rationale"],"type":"object"},"name":"submit_council_vote","read_only":false}],"turn":{"attempts_max":3,"attempts_remaining":3,"completed":false,"deadline":"2026-06-29T22:18:45.386037689Z","deliberation_round":1,"member_id":"C2","opportunity_id":"deliberation:1:C2","phase":"deliberation","remaining_ms":889046,"role_id":"council","turn_number":10},"wait":{"reason":"ready","state_version":14,"version":17}},"isError":false},"server":"aar","tool":"wait_for_opportunity"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1782770636345}}
{"type":"message_end","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_4OMctTF3Tl2BBcznCUaZhAHt","toolName":"mcp","content":[{"type":"text","text":"ok: true\nstatus: ready\nstate: ready\nmessage: An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\nafter_version: 17\nafter_opportunity_id: deliberation:1:C2\nmember_id: C2\ncase_id: arb-ex03a-20260629214245\nwait_reason: ready\nphase: deliberation\nopportunity_id: deliberation:1:C2\nremaining_ms: 889046\nattempts_remaining: 3\njson: {\"after_opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C2\",\"after_version\":17,\"case_id\":\"arb-ex03a-20260629214245\",\"limits\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"max_evidence_read_bytes\":65536,\"max_evidence_read_bytes_per_opportunity\":524288,\"max_evidence_reads_per_opportunity\":32,\"max_response_bytes\":131072,\"remaining_evidence_read_bytes_for_opportunity\":524288,\"remaining_evidence_reads_for_opportunity\":32},\"member_id\":\"C2\",\"message\":\"An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\",\"ok\":true,\"prompt\":\"Role: council member\\nMember ID: C2\\nDeliberation round: 1\\nProposition: For the Kalshi market \\\"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\\", the strike \\\"Ronaldo\\\" should resolve Yes because Trump said \\\"Ronaldo\\\" in public remarks at the World Cup Draw venue immediately before the formal program, and the market wording plus the governing mention-market terms did not clearly exclude those event-linked remarks.\\nStandard of evidence: Preponderance of the evidence.\\nPersona:\\nYou are a careful juror and council member.\\n\\nEvaluate the record faithfully. Decide only from the evidence, the stated rules, and the applicable burden of proof. Do not favor either side, fill gaps with speculation, or ignore uncertainty.\\n\\nGive weight to reliable sources, direct evidence, consistent reasoning, and clear admissions. Discount unsupported claims, rhetorical force, irrelevant facts, and conclusions that exceed the record.\\n\\nWhen the evidence supports one answer, state it plainly. When the evidence is incomplete or balanced, say so. Be concise, honest, and exact.\\n\\nRecord:\\nOpenings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, this case is not about whether the word \\\"Ronaldo\\\" would count if President Trump clearly said it. The current packet makes that part straightforward: the market is the Kalshi PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION market titled \\\"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\\"; the strike is \\\"Ronaldo\\\"; Kalshi’s challenged resolution is No; and plaintiff seeks Yes.\\n\\nThe real dispute is temporal and contextual. Did the market phrase \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw,\\\" read with the governing mention-market terms, include public event-linked remarks at the World Cup Draw venue immediately before the formal draw program? Or did it clearly confine countable words to a narrower formal broadcast segment? Plaintiff’s position is that a No resolution cannot stand unless the record shows that the counting window clearly excluded those event-linked remarks.\\n\\nThe admitted terms matter. They define the underlying as words used by the specified entity during the specified time period. They expressly recognize event-based time periods, and they say the payout criterion is satisfied when the word is said by the entity during that period. They also contain exclusions: behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings do not count unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period; captions or text alone do not count; and the word must appear as a distinct standalone unit. Those exclusions are important, but they do not by themselves answer this case. A public remark at the event venue, tied to the Draw and immediately before the formal program, is not automatically a rehearsal, sound check, or private behind-the-scenes moment.\\n\\nAt this opening stage, the record proves the market identity, the challenged resolution, the requested resolution, and the generic governing terms. It does not yet prove the utterance itself, the exact sequence of the venue remarks, the source-agency hierarchy or any market-specific time-period language beyond the packet, or Kalshi’s reason for treating the strike as No. Those are the factual links that should decide the case under a preponderance standard.\\n\\nPlaintiff expects the decisive proof to be the full official or otherwise reliable event video or transcript, with enough surrounding context to show whether Trump said \\\"Ronaldo\\\" aloud as a standalone word; when he said it relative to the Draw event; whether the remarks were public and event-linked rather than backstage or a sound check; and whether any market-specific rule clearly excluded that segment. Plaintiff also expects the market page, archived market details, and any resolution rationale to be important because ambiguity in the market’s own event wording should not be resolved against Yes after the fact.\\n\\nThe defense will likely argue that \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw\\\" means only the formal draw ceremony or broadcast, and that anything before the formal program is outside the counting period. That theory can win only if the evidence shows a clear exclusion or a source record that separates the alleged remarks from the event itself. If the evidence instead shows public remarks at the Draw venue, officially connected to the event, immediately before the formal program, and no clear rule excluding them, then the terms favor counting the word and resolving the Ronaldo strike Yes.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the defense position is straightforward: the admitted record does not yet prove that the Ronaldo strike should resolve Yes. It proves a market title, a generic mention-market rule set, and Kalshi's challenged No resolution. It does not prove that any qualifying utterance of \\\"Ronaldo\\\" occurred during the market's countable time period.\\n\\nThe plaintiff's opening usefully narrows the dispute. This is not primarily a word-boundary case. If President Trump said \\\"Ronaldo\\\" as a standalone spoken word during the countable FIFA World Cup Draw period, the generic terms would ordinarily treat that as the kind of word that can count. The real question is whether plaintiff can carry the burden of showing that alleged pre-program, venue-adjacent remarks were part of the market's specified time period: \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\\\"\\n\\nThe case-packet terms matter, but they cut both ways. They say the underlying is words used by the entity during the specified time period. They recognize that a time period can be an event, and they allow the Exchange to specify what is included when an event is involved. They also distinguish official event presentation from material outside the event: behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are not included unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period; text or captions alone do not count; and the relevant word must be spoken aloud by the entity. Those provisions do not support a rule that every public comment inside the same building, or every press exchange near the formal program, is automatically \\\"during\\\" the Draw.\\n\\nThat is the burden problem for plaintiff. The admitted market-page file identifies the public title, contract family, strike, challenged resolution, and requested resolution. It does not supply a full market-specific source hierarchy, a formal start time, a transcript, a video, a resolution rationale, or the alleged remarks. The terms file supplies the generic framework, but not the factual bridge from \\\"immediately before the formal program\\\" to \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\\\" Without that bridge, the No resolution is not shown to be wrong by a preponderance of the evidence.\\n\\nThe defense expects the decisive proof to be source-chain evidence, not characterization. The council should want the market's full rule page if available, the source agency hierarchy, the official draw program or broadcast, any official transcript or recording of the alleged exchange, and enough surrounding timestamps to separate the formal draw from pre-event reporter access, red-carpet exchanges, arrivals, or other ancillary material. If later evidence shows that the alleged Ronaldo comment was in a segment officially presented as part of the Draw itself, plaintiff's argument becomes stronger. If the evidence instead shows a separate exchange with reporters before the draw, or an event-linked but pre-program interaction not incorporated into the official presentation, the generic terms support Kalshi's No.\\n\\nSo the defense opening is not that the word Ronaldo could never count. It is that this record has not established the necessary time-period link. The proposition asks the council to overturn No because the market wording and terms did not clearly exclude pre-program remarks. That reverses the burden. Plaintiff must show that the remarks were included in the countable period. Ambiguity about the outer edge of an event is not the same as proof that a specific pre-event utterance satisfies the payout criterion.\\n\\nArguments:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, plaintiff has now supplied the record links that were missing at opening.\\n\\nFirst, the market packet fixes what this dispute is: the Kalshi market title is \\\"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\\"; the contract family is PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION; the strike is \\\"Ronaldo\\\"; Kalshi's challenged resolution is No; and plaintiff seeks Yes. That is PX-1.\\n\\nSecond, the governing terms make this an event-period mention question, not a narrow formal-program-only question. PX-2 says the underlying is words used by the entity during the time period, recognizes that a time period may be a specific event, and sets the payout criterion as the word being said by the entity during that period. It also tells us what does not count: text/captions alone, unofficial behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, and sound checks unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. Those exclusions matter, but none says that public event-linked remarks at the venue immediately before the formal program are categorically outside \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\\\"\\n\\nThird, the source-chain evidence now points to the disputed event and the Ronaldo utterance. PX-3 is an official White House page titled \\\"President Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing,\\\" dated December 5, 2025, with a full-video link and related World Cup Draw videos. That establishes an official White House event-video source for Trump's attendance at the World Cup Drawing. PX-4 is a public YouTube watch-page metadata capture for video ID Cb2yO0lLEnM, titled \\\"Trump Talks Cristiano Ronaldo at FIFA Draw -- 'He's a Great Person'.\\\" Its description states that at the FIFA World Cup Draw Ceremony, Trump shared a story about meeting Cristiano Ronaldo at the White House, said Ronaldo was a great person, and mentioned Ronaldo spoke with his son. PX-4 is not as strong as an official transcript, and plaintiff says that plainly. But it is admitted source content that directly links Trump, Cristiano Ronaldo, and the FIFA Draw ceremony.\\n\\nOn a preponderance standard, that is enough to defeat the challenged No resolution unless the defense can supply a clearer exclusion. The market did not ask only what Trump would say during the ball-pulling segment, during the televised main show, or after a particular formal start cue. It asked what he would say \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\\\" The terms recognize event-based periods and exclude particular non-event categories. A public remark at the Draw venue, tied to the Draw, is far closer to the event period than to a rehearsal, sound check, caption, or private backstage recording.\\n\\nThe defense's burden framing is too strict. Plaintiff must prove Yes by a preponderance; plaintiff need not prove that Kalshi drafted every boundary with perfect precision. Once the admitted sources show a Ronaldo mention in connection with the FIFA Draw ceremony, the remaining question is whether the rules clearly remove that event-linked remark from the counting period. They do not. Ambiguity in a mention market's event wording should not be converted into an unstated formal-program limitation after the fact.\\n\\nProvenance and gaps: plaintiff attempted to retrieve the live Kalshi page, official/full video, caption, and transcript. Kalshi returned a Vercel security checkpoint; the local browser tool was unavailable; Python pip/ensurepip was unavailable for yt-dlp; and direct YouTube caption/open paths were throttled or unavailable. That leaves PX-4 weaker than ideal, but not weightless. PX-3 supplies official event context, PX-4 supplies the Ronaldo-at-FIFA-Draw metadata, and PX-2 supplies the rule that event-linked spoken words count absent a clear exclusion.\\n\\nThe council should resolve the proposition Yes: the Ronaldo strike should have resolved Yes because the record more likely than not shows Trump said Ronaldo in public remarks tied to the FIFA World Cup Draw, and the market wording plus governing terms did not clearly exclude those remarks.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the merits record now shows why the challenged No resolution should stand.\\n\\nPlaintiff's best point is that Trump did say the word \\\"Ronaldo.\\\" The defense does not need to fight that. The question is whether he said it during the market's countable time period: \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\\\" On that decisive question, the strongest official sources favor No.\\n\\nThe admitted GovInfo transcript, DX-1, is an official Compilation of Presidential Documents capture. Its title is not merely \\\"World Cup Draw\\\" or \\\"FIFA ceremony.\\\" It is \\\"Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw.\\\" That same transcript contains the Ronaldo passages: Trump says he met Ronaldo at the White House, later says he was \\\"not Ronaldo or Messi,\\\" and the note identifies Ronaldo among the people referenced. So DX-1 is not adverse to the defense because it confirms the word; it is decisive because it places the word in an exchange with reporters prior to the Draw.\\n\\nDX-2 supplies the timing anchor. The official FIFA Final Draw page states that the Draw at the Kennedy Center commenced at 12:00 local time on Friday, December 5, 2025. DX-1 states that the President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the Kennedy Center. A reporter exchange at 11:13, officially titled as prior to a 12:00 draw, is not more likely than not \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\\\" It is before it.\\n\\nThat reading matches the governing PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION terms. PX-2 says the payout criterion is satisfied when the word is said by the entity during the specified time period. It recognizes event-based periods and permits the Exchange to specify what is included for an event. It also treats official presentation differently from adjacent material: pre-recorded content counts if presented as part of the official event presentation, while behind-the-scenes, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings do not count unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. The point is not that this reporter exchange was a rehearsal or sound check. The point is that the terms require a link to the time period itself. Plaintiff has supplied no market-specific language saying pre-event reporter availability, arrivals, or venue interviews count as part of the Draw.\\n\\nPlaintiff's new exhibits do not fill that gap. PX-3, the White House page capture, establishes that the White House had a page titled \\\"President Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing,\\\" but plaintiff's own capture says the embedded/full video was not captured. It does not prove that the Ronaldo words occurred inside the official draw program. PX-4 is weaker still: it is metadata from a nonofficial YouTube channel. It says the clip is about Trump talking Ronaldo at the FIFA Draw, but it is not a transcript, not an official source, and not an audio extraction. When a nonofficial clip description is weighed against GovInfo's official transcript title and FIFA's official start time, the official sources control.\\n\\nNor is this a burden-shifting problem. The proposition asks the council to overturn Kalshi's No because the market supposedly did not clearly exclude remarks immediately before the formal program. But the preponderance burden is on Yes. The record must show that the strike satisfied the payout criterion. The admitted terms do not say that ambiguous pre-event remarks count by default; they say the word must be said during the specified time period. Here, the best evidence identifies the remarks as prior to the Draw and before the official commencement time.\\n\\nProvenance also matters. DX-1 is an official government transcript with a correction note and an audio-incomplete caveat. That caveat affects stray inaudible portions, but it does not weaken the title, the 11:13 timing note, or the Ronaldo passages preserved in the transcript. DX-2 is an official FIFA timing source. Plaintiff's YouTube metadata may explain why the dispute arose, but it cannot outweigh those primary sources on timing and event classification.\\n\\nThe council should resolve the proposition against plaintiff. Trump said Ronaldo, but the record more likely shows he did so in a reporter exchange prior to the FIFA World Cup Draw, not during the countable Draw event. Kalshi's No resolution should be upheld.\\n\\nRebuttals:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, defendant’s new evidence narrows the case but does not end it.\\n\\nPlaintiff accepts the important parts of DX-1 and DX-2. The GovInfo transcript is official; it labels the item an exchange with reporters \\\"Prior to\\\" the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw; it places the exchange at 11:13 a.m. at the Kennedy Center; and the FIFA capture states the draw commenced at 12:00 local time. Plaintiff should not pretend those facts are weak.\\n\\nBut defendant asks those facts to do more than they do. The market was not drafted as \\\"what will Trump say after the official 12:00 commencement,\\\" \\\"during the televised draw program,\\\" or \\\"during the ball-drawing segment.\\\" PX-1 says the public market title was \\\"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\\" That is ordinary event language, and PX-2 recognizes event-based time periods while leaving room for the Exchange to specify what is included. The record still contains no market-specific exclusion for official venue press remarks immediately before the formal program.\\n\\nDX-1 also helps plaintiff on the facts defendant originally said were missing. It confirms the relevant spoken word. Trump said he met Ronaldo, that Ronaldo is great, and that he was not Ronaldo or Messi. It also places those remarks at the Kennedy Center in a FIFA World Cup Draw-centered exchange with reporters, not in an unrelated private dinner or stale campaign setting. The transcript’s own subject metadata includes the FIFA World Cup, the Kennedy Center, news media, presidential interviews, and soccer. That is event-linked public context.\\n\\nThe terms’ exclusions do not fit defendant’s leap. PX-2 excludes captions alone, rehearsals, sound checks, behind-the-scenes content, and unofficial recordings unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. DX-1 is not a rehearsal transcript. It is not a sound check. It is not merely a caption. It is an official presidential transcript of a public reporter exchange at the venue, released in the Compilation of Presidential Documents. If Kalshi meant to exclude that category because it occurred before a formal noon commencement, the market needed to say so clearly.\\n\\nSo the dispositive question remains one of market construction: does \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw\\\" clearly exclude public, official, event-site remarks immediately before the formal program? Defendant has proved \\\"prior to\\\" the formal draw start. Defendant has not proved a clear market rule that treats the broader Draw event as beginning only at 12:00 for mention purposes.\\n\\nUnder a preponderance standard, the record now confirms the Ronaldo utterance and confirms the FIFA Draw setting. The challenged No resolution should not be upheld by importing a narrow formal-program limitation that the market title and generic terms did not state.\\n\\nSurrebuttals:\\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff's rebuttal usefully clarifies the remaining dispute: plaintiff accepts that DX-1 is official, that it labels the relevant item an exchange with reporters \\\"Prior to\\\" the FIFA World Cup Draw, that the exchange occurred at 11:13 a.m. at the Kennedy Center, and that DX-2 places the official Draw commencement at 12:00 local time. Those concessions should decide the case.\\n\\nPlaintiff's answer is that the market did not say \\\"after 12:00,\\\" \\\"during the televised program,\\\" or \\\"during the ball-drawing segment.\\\" But the market also did not say \\\"at the venue before the Draw,\\\" \\\"in pre-event reporter exchanges,\\\" or \\\"in any public remarks connected to the Draw.\\\" The phrase it chose was \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\\\" Ordinary event language has a start, and the official FIFA source fixes that start at noon. Official GovInfo then fixes this exchange at 11:13 and titles it as prior to the Draw.\\n\\nThat is not a technicality. The terms require the word to be said during the specified time period. They recognize event-based periods and allow event-specific inclusions, but no admitted market-specific rule includes pre-event press access. Plaintiff's construction would turn any event-adjacent public remark into part of the event unless expressly excluded. That reverses the payout criterion. The claimant must show the word occurred during the time period; it is not enough to show the same venue, the same general topic, and official publication.\\n\\nPlaintiff says the exclusions do not fit because DX-1 is not a rehearsal, sound check, caption, or private backstage recording. Fair enough; the defense is not relying on those categories as labels. The defense relies on the affirmative timing requirement. A remark need not be a rehearsal to be outside the event. A reporter exchange officially described as prior to a noon event and occurring at 11:13 is outside because it is before the event began.\\n\\nThe record therefore proves the wrong fact for plaintiff. It proves Trump said Ronaldo, but in a pre-event reporter exchange. The proposition requires Yes only if those words count during the FIFA World Cup Draw. On this record, they do not. Kalshi's No resolution should be upheld.\\n\\nClosings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the final record leaves one legal question.\\n\\nThe easy factual question is resolved in plaintiff’s favor: Trump said \\\"Ronaldo.\\\" The official GovInfo transcript confirms it twice in substance: he said he met Ronaldo, praised him, and later said he was not Ronaldo or Messi. That is a spoken standalone use of the strike word. The record also places the remarks at the Kennedy Center in a FIFA World Cup Draw-centered reporter exchange. This was not an unrelated dinner, a caption, an AI voice, or a social-media paraphrase.\\n\\nThe hard point is timing. Defendant has the strongest evidence on the formal program boundary: GovInfo titled the exchange as \\\"Prior to\\\" the Draw, notes 11:13 a.m., and FIFA states the Final Draw commenced at 12:00 local time. Plaintiff does not ask the council to ignore that. The question is what the Kalshi market actually required.\\n\\nPX-1 did not say \\\"after 12:00.\\\" It did not say \\\"during the televised draw program\\\" or \\\"during the ball-drawing segment.\\\" It asked, in public market wording, \\\"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\\" PX-2’s generic terms recognize event-based periods and say the Exchange may specify what is included when a time period refers to an event. They also give specific exclusions: captions alone, rehearsals, sound checks, behind-the-scenes content, and unofficial recordings unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. None of those exclusions is this case. The GovInfo transcript is an official public presidential record of an event-site reporter exchange, not a rehearsal or sound check.\\n\\nDefendant’s best argument is that ordinary events have start times. True. But this market dispute is about public remarks at the venue immediately before the formal program, in the official context of the Draw, where the market and rules did not clearly define a noon-only boundary. If Kalshi wanted that narrower rule, it could have said so in the strike, the market title, or the event inclusion language. It did not.\\n\\nThe preponderance record therefore shows: Ronaldo was spoken; the remarks were public and officially documented; they were at the Kennedy Center in the FIFA World Cup Draw setting; and the governing market language did not clearly exclude that immediately-before-program event context. The challenged No resolution depends on importing a formal commencement limitation that is absent from the market packet.\\n\\nFor that reason, the Ronaldo strike should resolve Yes.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the closing record is narrow and concrete.\\n\\nEveryone now agrees on the easy fact: Trump said \\\"Ronaldo.\\\" The official GovInfo transcript proves that. But the proposition is not simply that Trump said the word somewhere near the FIFA World Cup Draw. The proposition asks you to overturn Kalshi's No because remarks immediately before the formal program should count under a market asking what Trump would say \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\\\" Plaintiff has not carried that burden.\\n\\nThe two strongest sources are official and aligned. GovInfo, in DX-1, titles the relevant document \\\"Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw.\\\" It notes that the President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the Kennedy Center. FIFA, in DX-2, states that the Final Draw commenced at 12:00 local time. Those facts are not peripheral. They answer the timing question: the Ronaldo words were in a reporter exchange before the Draw began.\\n\\nPlaintiff's closing says the market did not specify \\\"after 12:00,\\\" \\\"during the televised draw program,\\\" or \\\"during the ball-drawing segment.\\\" True, but that does not prove Yes. The market did specify \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\\\" The ordinary function of \\\"during\\\" is to define the event period, not to include anything public, official, and thematically related that happens beforehand. A 47-minute-before reporter exchange officially titled as prior to the Draw is outside that period unless the market or governing terms affirmatively include it. The record contains no such inclusion.\\n\\nThe governing terms reinforce that conclusion. They require the word to be said by the entity during the specified time period. They recognize event-based periods and allow the Exchange to specify event inclusions. They include official-presentation concepts for material presented as part of an event. But they do not say that pre-event press availability counts by default. Plaintiff's argument turns the absence of an exclusion into proof of inclusion. That is backwards under a preponderance standard.\\n\\nPlaintiff also leans on setting: Kennedy Center, FIFA World Cup subject matter, official transcript, public reporters. Those facts show why the issue is understandable. They do not move 11:13 into a 12:00 event. A source can be official and still describe something outside the event. Indeed, that is exactly what DX-1 does: it officially documents the remarks and officially labels them prior to the Draw.\\n\\nThe weaker evidence points the same way once weighed properly. The White House page capture does not include the video or transcript. The YouTube metadata is nonofficial and not an audio transcript. Neither overcomes GovInfo's title and timing note plus FIFA's commencement time.\\n\\nSo the final answer is simple: the word was spoken, but not during the countable event period shown by the best evidence. Plaintiff has not shown that Kalshi's No resolution was wrong. The council should reject the proposition and uphold No.\\n\\nExhibits:\\n[plaintiff] PX-1 Market page packet: Ronaldo strike and challenged No resolution\\nMarket URL: https://kalshi.com/markets/kxtrumpmentionb/trump-mention-b/kxtrumpmentionb-25dec06\\n\\nPublic market title: What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\n\\nContract family: PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION\\n\\nStrike at issue: Ronaldo\\n\\nChallenged resolution: No\\n\\nRequested resolution: Yes\\n\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-2 Governing PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION terms\\n                                         NEWMENTION\\n\\nScope: These rules shall apply to this contract.\\n\\nUnderlying: The Underlying for this Contract is words used by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nRevisions to the Underlying made after Expiration will not be accounted for in determining the\\nExpiration Value.\\n\\nSource Agency: The Source Agencies are \\u003csource\\u003e.\\n\\nType: The type of Contract is an Event Contract.\\n\\nIssuance: After the initial Contract, Contract iterations will be listed on an as-needed basis at\\nthe discretion of the Exchange and corresponding to the risk management needs of Members.\\n\\n\\u003centity\\u003e: \\u003centity\\u003e refers to the speaker, writer, performer, or communicator specified by the\\nExchange. This may include (but is not limited to): a specific named individual, multiple\\nindividuals specified using AND/OR logic, an individual identified by position or title, a group,\\nband, team or collective entity, a specified member or members of a group, an organization,\\ncompany, or institutional entity, or any combination of the aforementioned.\\n\\nWhen \\u003centity\\u003e is defined by a position or title, the Contract tracks whoever holds that position\\nduring \\u003ctime period\\u003e, even if the individual holding the position changes. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a\\nspecific named individual, the identity remains consistent throughout. Name changes (e.g.,\\nstage names, married names) do not create a new entity. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a group or\\norganization and the Contract does not specify particular members, any official\\ncommunication or statement by any member or designated spokesperson counts. When using\\nAND logic, all specified entities must independently say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e. When\\nusing OR logic, at least one of the specified entities must say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nThe Exchange may specify additional conditions such as “at least X members of” a group or\\n“the majority of” a group.\\n\\n\\u003csource\\u003e: \\u003csource\\u003e refers to a Source Agency or ordered collection of Source Agencies\\nspecified by the Exchange at the time of Contract listing, which will be incorporated into the\\nSource Agency hierarchy above and used to determine the occurrence of the Underlying.\\n\\u003csource\\u003e may refer to a singular agency, multiple agencies, an agency by distinguishing\\ncharacteristics, by category or type (e.g., “official government statistical body,” “primary wire\\nservice”), or any combination thereof. When multiple agencies are specified, they may be\\napplied in the hierarchical order designated by the Exchange if so specified, with the highest-\\nranked available and responsive agency taking precedence for purposes of determining the\\nExpiration Value. A lower-ranked agency shall only be consulted if all higher-ranked agencies\\nare unavailable, unresponsive, have not reported on the Underlying by the Expiration time, or\\nif the Exchange, in its sole discretion, determines that a higher-ranked agency’s reporting is\\nincomplete, erroneous, or otherwise insufficient to determine the Expiration Value. If \\u003csource\\u003e\\ndesignates multiple agencies without specifying a hierarchical order, the Exchange shall\\nresolve any conflict between reporting agencies at its sole discretion.\\n\\n\\u003cword\\u003e: \\u003cword\\u003e refers to the particular word or phrase potentially to be mentioned by\\n\\u003centity\\u003e. It may refer to a word being said a minimum number of times. It may also refer to\\none of multiple words/phrases, any of which are acceptable (e.g., “Doge/Dogecoin”).\\n\\f\\u003ctime period\\u003e: \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific range of time, event or discrete date and\\ntime specified by the Exchange. This may be defined by, but is not limited to: a specific event\\nor context (e.g., “during the State of the Union address”), exact dates or times, relative time\\nmarkers (e.g., “before July 1, 2027,” “in Q1 2026”), event-based periods (e.g., “during any\\ncampaign rally in October 2026,” “during the awards ceremony”), and broader intervals (e.g.,\\n“Q1–Q2 2027,” “January–March 2026”).\\n\\nUnless stated otherwise, “Between” is inclusive of both endpoints, while “before” and “after”\\nexclude the specified date. \\u003ctime period\\u003e may also refer to “Any” or “None”, to multiple dates\\n(even if non-consecutive), or to a singular and discrete date or time.\\n\\nWhen \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event (such as an address, speech, performance, or\\nbroadcast), the Exchange may specify what is included, including whether it includes both live\\nand pre-recorded segments (including whether advertisements are included). Where a\\ntimezone is not specified, ET is assumed.\\n\\n\\nPayout Criterion: The Payout Criterion for the Contract encompasses the Expiration Values that\\n\\u003cword\\u003e is said by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n\\n\\nThe word must appear as a distinct, standalone unit, not buried inside another word. Plural\\nand possessive noun forms count. Other grammatical changes (tense, conjugation, derivation)\\ndo not. If \\u003cword\\u003e appears separated from other words by a space or hyphen or in a\\ncompound form with a space or hyphen, it counts. If \\u003cword\\u003e is fused into a single\\nunhyphenated word, it does not count.\\n\\nIf \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled, and the market contains a\\nstrike stating “Event does not qualify/occur”, such a strike shall resolve “Yes” and all others\\n“No”. If \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled but such strikes are NOT\\nlisted, the Contracts will resolve to the last fair price determined at the discretion of the\\nExchange. If the event is postponed, and such a postponement is announced by the end of the\\nfollowing calendar day to be rescheduled to a time within 14 calendar days, the markets shall\\nremain open. If the event captured in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast, the\\nExchange may keep the market open for 24 hours for the release of an official recording.\\nFurther granular details on conditions for these Contracts is available below.\\n\\nAdditional clarification(s):\\n\\n     Possessive noun forms of \\u003cword\\u003e, plurals, and possessive plural noun forms are\\n     INCLUDED:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigrants” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Egg” → “eggs’ shells” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Russia” → “Russia’s” counts, “Russian” does not\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e exists only in adjective form, no plural form exists:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Economic” → “Economics” does not count (“Economic” is an adjective\\n          for which “Economics” is not a plural)\\n     Plural nouns occurring within proper nouns and noun phrases are included:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Cat” → “Cats the musical” counts\\n\\f    Grammatical variations beyond plurals/possessives are NOT included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigration” does NOT count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Run” → “Running” or “Ran” do NOT count\\n    When \\u003cword\\u003e specifies a plural form, the singular does NOT count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Veterans” → “Veteran” does NOT count\\n    Words that are spelled the same as the plural form of \\u003cword\\u003e (if such exists) but are\\n    themselves not a plural noun are included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Wind” → “Winds up the clock” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Border” → “The United States has strong borders” counts\\n    Open compounds (words separated by spaces) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fire station” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “couch” → “couch potato” counts\\n    Hyphenated compounds (words connected by hyphens) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Palestine” → “pro-Palestine” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fat” → “non-fat” counts\\n    Closed compounds (single word, no spaces/hyphens) do not count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire” does not count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firefighter” does not count\\n    Multi-word \\u003cword\\u003e in larger constructions: When \\u003cword\\u003e is a multi-word phrase\\n    appearing within a hyphenated construction, it counts only if \\u003cword\\u003e appears as a\\n    complete, unmodified element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “New York” → “New York-based” counts (complete element)\\n    Portmanteaus (words blended from two words where parts of each are combined) are\\n    NOT included unless the portmanteau clearly contains \\u003cword\\u003e as a distinct, unaltered\\n    element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “MAGA” → “MAGA-nificent” counts (MAGA appears as distinct element)\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “magnificent” → “MAGA-nificent” does NOT count (portmanteau blend)\\n\\nDictionary determination: Both the Merriam-Webster Dictionary (available online) AND the\\nOxford English Dictionary shall be used to determine compound type and/or conventional\\nspelling patterns. Inclusion in either dictionary as an open or hyphenated compound shall\\nsatisfy the Payout Criterion. If neither provides clarity (or the word is not included),\\ndetermination is based on whether written as single unit (closed/doesn’t count) vs. spaces or\\nhyphens (open or hyphenated/counts) and/or context and previous usage.\\n\\nPHONETIC EQUIVALENCIES\\n\\n    Homophones (same sound, different spelling) do not count:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “write” → “right” does not count\\n    Homonyms and homographs (same spelling) COUNT regardless of meaning or\\n    pronunciation:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “bass” → both “bass guitar” and “bass fishing” count\\n    Proper and common nouns are treated identically:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Apple” → both “Apple Inc.” and “apple” (fruit) count\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Will” → both “Will Smith” and “I will go” count\\n    Minor unintentional mispronunciations COUNT if context makes intent clear:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Mamdani” → “Mandani” counts\\n    Severe mispronunciations that make \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable do NOT count.\\n    Trademarked spellings do not count, even when pronounced identically, unless the word\\n\\fitself is the same:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “lift” → “Lyft” (pronounced “lift”) does not count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “uber” → “Uber” counts\\nWords with non-standard transliteration to English count within reason, provided they are\\nphonetically equivalent:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Zelensky” → any of “Zelenski,” “Zelenskii,” “Zelensky,” or “Zelenskiy”\\n      count if pronounced equivalently\\nContractions do not count for their constituent words unless otherwise explicitly specified\\nby the Exchange:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “not” → “won’t,” “can’t,” “don’t,” “isn’t” do not count\\nNumbers spoken as words COUNT, when spoken exactly (not part of a larger number):\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “five” → saying “five” or reading “$5” aloud as “five dollars” counts,\\n      saying “five hundred” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “410” → “four hundred ten”, “four one zero” or “four ten” counts\\nOrdinals COUNT when \\u003cword\\u003e is written numerically OR a phrase that includes a\\nnumber:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “January 6” → “January 6th” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “3” (written numerically) → “3rd” (spoken as “third”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Eight War” → “8 Wars” and “Eighth War” will count\\nCardinal and ordinal number words are distinct:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “one” → “first” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “first” → “one” does NOT count\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count when pronunciation or letter-by-letter spelling\\nmatches \\u003cword\\u003e:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “NASA” (pronounced “NAH-suh”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “N-A-S-A” (spelled out) counts\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count as \\u003cword\\u003e when pronounced as the full word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Doctor” → “Dr.” (pronounced “Doctor”) counts\\nExpanded forms of acronyms do NOT count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “AI” → “artificial intelligence” does not count\\nWords in foreign languages do NOT count unless they are perfect cognates with an\\nEnglish word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fuego” (Spanish) does NOT count\\nEnglish words within foreign sentences count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “policy” → “Nuestra policy es clara” counts\\n\\u003cword\\u003e in organization/company names counts:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Securities” → “Bank of America Securities” counts\\nWords in URLs, emails, handles, and hashtags (exclusive of domain structure, email\\nprovider or symbols) are treated as compounds when spoken as complete words, with the\\ntype of compound subject to aforementioned rules:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firestation.com” pronounced “fire station dot com” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire.com” pronounced “wildfire dot com” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “apple” → “apple.com” pronounced “apple dot com” does count\\n      When presented in URL, email, handle, or hashtag form, \\u003cword\\u003e shall be treated as\\n      a compound, not a multi-word word\\nSung, rapped, or poetic words COUNT if phonetically recognizable:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “money” → “moneyyy” (extended in rap) counts\\n      Extreme distortion making \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable does NOT count.\\nPhonetic alphabet spelling (“Foxtrot India Romeo Echo” for “FIRE”) does NOT count.\\n\\fCANCELLATIONS AND DELAYS\\n\\n   The Exchange may list an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike for any Contract. If listed,\\n   such a strike refers to the structural conditions of the market, and is NOT adjudicated as a\\n   \\u003cword\\u003e needing to be said by or validated by having been said by \\u003centity\\u003e. If listed, this\\n   strike resolves to “Yes” whenever the event fails to occur or qualify under the Payout\\n   Criterion, or any other circumstance prevents normal resolution.\\n   If no such strike is listed, and \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, the following rules\\n   apply if the event is cancelled, postponed, rescheduled, or materially altered (including\\n   being closed to press) such that no video is released within one calendar day of the\\n   original start time of the event:\\n         If the event is cancelled, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price determined in\\n         the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         If the event is postponed or rescheduled, the outcome depends on whether a new\\n         date is publicly announced within one calendar day (i.e. if the event was scheduled\\n         to begin on Monday, any time up to 11:59PM on Tuesday falls within this period) of\\n         the originally scheduled start time:\\n               If no new date is announced within one calendar day, the Contract will resolve\\n               to the last fair price determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n               If a new date is announced within one calendar day, the outcome depends on\\n               when the rescheduled event is set to occur:\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls within fourteen (14) calendar days of the\\n                     originally scheduled date, the Contract shall remain open and \\u003cword\\u003e\\n                     stated during the rescheduled event will count.\\n                           The fourteen-day window begins at 12:00 AM ET on the originally\\n                           scheduled date and ends at 11:59 PM ET fourteen days later, unless\\n                           an alternate timezone is explicitly specified.\\n                           Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the State of the Union on January\\n                           15, 2026” rescheduled to January 20, 2026 → words spoken during\\n                           the rescheduled address count.\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls more than fourteen (14) calendar days after\\n                     the originally scheduled date, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price\\n                     determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         Any Contract that cannot be resolved through the Source Agency hierarchy will\\n         instead be settled at the Last Fair Price. The Exchange will disclose the methodology\\n         used to determine the Last Fair Price (e.g., Last Traded Price, Time-Weighted\\n         Average Price) at the time of Issuance.\\n         If an event begins but is interrupted, abbreviated, or ends prematurely, words\\n         stated by \\u003centity\\u003e during the portion of the event that did occur will count and the\\n         market will otherwise resolve.\\n   If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window but the venue, format, or medium\\n   changes (e.g., moved to a different location, changed from in-person to virtual (with the\\n   exception of being closed to press)), words stated during the event will count.\\n   Special condition: Across both cases, whether an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike is\\n   listed or not, if the event specified as or in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast (or\\n   relayed as such) but the live stream/broadcast does not occur, the Exchange will instead\\n   use an officially released recording as the Underlying, and may delay resolution by up to\\n   one calendar day to allow for the release of such a recording.\\n\\f          If partial snippets are released, Contracts on words that do not appear will be\\n          resolved to last fair price, and Contracts on those that do will be resolved to “Yes”.\\n          If no recording is released, the relevant outcomes triggered by the\\n          presence/absence of an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike shall occur as outlined\\n          above.\\n\\nTECHNICAL DETAILS (UNLESS OTHERWISE SPECIFIED)\\n\\n     When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, pre-recorded content broadcast,\\n     streamed, or published as part of that event is included if presented as part of the official\\n     presentation.\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the concert” with pre-recorded video interlude\\n          where entity speaks → words from interlude count\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the television appearance” with pre-taped\\n          segment aired during broadcast → words from segment count\\n     Behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are NOT\\n     included unless officially broadcast or published as part of \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n     Subtitles and captions that display \\u003cword\\u003e on screen but are not spoken aloud by\\n     \\u003centity\\u003e do NOT count.\\n     Sign language interpretation or usage by entity does NOT count as saying \\u003cword\\u003e unless\\n     the Contract explicitly specifies that sign language counts.\\n     Text that entity displays on screen (presentation slides, teleprompter visible to audience,\\n     signatures) does NOT count unless entity reads it aloud.\\n     Content generated by AI, deepfakes, or synthetic voice technology impersonating entity\\n     does NOT count unless the synthetic content is officially commissioned, authorized, or\\n     published by entity, OR the Contract explicitly specifies that AI-generated content counts.\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e is muted due to technical failure or censorship it shall not count unless\\n     corroborating contextual evidence (including surrounding speech, or an official\\n     uncensored recording or transcript) confirms that \\u003centity\\u003e specifically uttered \\u003cword\\u003e\\n     during the muted period.\\n\\nMinimum Tick: The Minimum Tick size for the Contract shall be $0.01.\\n\\nPosition Accountability Level: The Position Accountability Level for the Contract shall be\\n$25,000 per strike, per Member.\\n\\nLast Trading Date: The Last Trading Date of the Contract will be the Expiration Date. The Last\\nTrading Time will be the Expiration time.\\n\\nSettlement Date: The Settlement Date of the Contract shall be no later than the day after the\\nExpiration Date, unless the Market Outcome is under review pursuant to Rule 7.1.\\n\\nExpiration Date: When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event: The latest Expiration Date of\\nthe Contract shall be fourteen (14) calendar days after the originally scheduled date of the\\nevent. If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window, expiration will be moved to an\\nearlier date and time in accordance with Rule 7.2. When \\u003ctime period\\u003e is defined by specific\\ndates: The latest Expiration Date of the Contract shall be two weeks after the end of \\u003ctime\\nperiod\\u003e. If an event described in the Payout Criterion occurs and a consensus has been\\nreached on all terms, then expiration will be moved to an earlier date and time in accordance\\nwith Rule 7.2.\\n\\fExpiration time: The Expiration time of the Contract shall be 10:00 AM ET.\\n\\nSettlement Value: The Settlement Value for this Contract is $1.00.\\n\\nExpiration Value: The Expiration Value is the value of the Underlying as documented by the\\nSource Agency on the Expiration Date at the Expiration time.\\n\\nContingencies: Before Settlement, Kalshi may, at its sole discretion, initiate the Market\\nOutcome Review Process pursuant to Rule 7.1 of the Rulebook. If an Expiration Value cannot\\nbe determined on the Expiration Date, Kalshi has the right to determine payouts pursuant to\\nRule 7.1 in the Rulebook.\\n\\f\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-3 Official White House World Cup Drawing video page capture\\nSource capture from official White House page https://www.whitehouse.gov/videos/president-trump-attends-the-fifa-world-cup-drawing/\\nRetrieval: 2026-06-29T21:52:12Z via OpenClaw web_fetch and web.open.\\n\\nVisible page facts captured:\\n- Page title: President Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing\\n- Date shown on page: December 5, 2025\\n- Page section: Videos\\n- The page contains a link labeled View Full Video to Instagram.\\n- Related video listed: FIFA World Cup 2026 Draw at The Kennedy Center, duration 00:45, dated December 6, 2025.\\n- Related video listed: FIFA World Cup Drawing Announced to Take Place at The Kennedy Center, duration 00:56, dated August 23, 2025.\\n- Related video listed: President Trump on the 2026 FIFA World Cup, duration 01:22, dated May 6, 2025.\\n\\nRelevant extracted lines from web.open capture:\\nL142: Videos\\nL143: # President Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing\\nL145: December 5, 2025\\nL133: ... View Full Video [instagram.com] ...\\nL151: FIFA World Cup 2026 Draw at The Kennedy Center\\nL153: December 6, 2025\\nL167-L170: President Trump on the 2026 FIFA World Cup, May 6, 2025\\n\\nNotes on capture limits: readability extraction returned minimal content, so the above preserves visible lines from the page capture. The embedded/full video itself was not captured in this item.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-4 YouTube metadata capture for Ronaldo-at-FIFA-Draw clip\\nSource capture: YouTube watch page https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Cb2yO0lLEnM\\nVideo ID: Cb2yO0lLEnM\\nRetrieval: 2026-06-29T21:53:00Z via web search and curl of the YouTube watch page.\\n\\nCaptured title / page metadata:\\n- Title shown in search and page metadata: Trump Talks Cristiano Ronaldo at FIFA Draw — ‘He’s a Great Person’\\n- Channel shown in page metadata: interestingText You / @InterestingTextYou\\n- Subscriber count shown in page metadata at capture: about 10.3K subscribers\\n\\nCaptured description text from YouTube page metadata:\\n\\\"Trump Talks Cristiano Ronaldo at FIFA Draw — ‘He’s a Great Person’\\n\\nAt the FIFA World Cup Draw Ceremony, Donald Trump shared a story about meeting Cristiano Ronaldo at the White House. Trump said Ronaldo was “a great person” and even mentioned that Ronaldo spoke with his son about soccer during the visit.\\n\\nThis unexpected crossover between world politics and one of the biggest global sports stars quickly caught viewers' attention.\\n\\nTrump FIFA Draw\\nDonald Trump FIFA World Cup\\nTrump Cristiano Ronaldo\\nCristiano Ronaldo Trump meeting\\nFIFA World Cup draw 2026\\nRonaldo White House visit\\nTrump soccer comments\\nWorld Cup trending 2025\\nsports politics crossover\\nCristiano Ronaldo story\\nDonald Trump viral moment\\nFIFA draw ceremony Trump\\nWorld Cup 2026 news\\nRonaldo fan reaction\\npolitical celebrity moments\\nviral sports clips 2025\\nFIFA draw highlights\\nTrump speech FIFA\\nglobal sports news\\\"\\n\\nCapture limits and provenance caveat: direct video/caption extraction was attempted but YouTube transcript/open paths were throttled or unavailable in this environment. This item preserves the public watch-page metadata and description, not an independently extracted audio transcript. It is not an official White House or FIFA source.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-1 GovInfo official transcript: remarks prior to FIFA World Cup Draw\\nSource: GovInfo, Compilation of Presidential Documents, DCPD202501162\\nURL retrieved: https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/DCPD-202501162/html/DCPD-202501162.htm\\nRetrieval time: 2026-06-29T22:00:00Z\\nLocal captured HTML size/hash: 51,571 bytes; SHA-256 eadbceeecf3e94f5bd423bcb8e8511165fdc7265dd8c1e025870c2e8f34dfd99\\n\\nMaterial captured text from official GovInfo HTML/web.open:\\n\\nAdministration of Donald J. Trump, 2025\\n\\nTitle: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\nDate: December 5, 2025\\n\\nOpening note: [The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\\n\\nExcerpt - The President's Interest in Soccer (web.open lines 196-203):\\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\\\"football,\\\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\\n\\nExcerpt - The President's Interest in Soccer (web.open lines 322-329):\\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\\nThe President. But they have a little more speed. But no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\\n\\nTiming/context note (web.open lines 461-462):\\nNOTE: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. In his remarks, he referred to Trey Yingst, chief foreign correspondent, Fox News Channel; Cristiano Ronaldo, forward for Saudi Pro League club Al-Nass and Portugal's national soccer team; and Lionel Messi, forward for Major League Soccer club Inter Miami and Argentina's national team. A reporter referred to New York State Attorney General Letitia James.\\nThe transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\n\\nDocument category/location/name/subject metadata (web.open lines 463-468):\\nCategories: Interviews With the News Media: Exchanges with reporters, Washington, DC.\\nLocations: Washington, DC.\\nNames include: Cristiano Ronaldo and Lionel Messi.\\nSubjects include: Federation Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) World Cup; John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts; News media, Presidential interviews; Soccer.\\nDCPD Number: DCPD202501162.\\n\\nCapture limits: This item is a focused text capture of the material official transcript title, Ronaldo excerpts, timing/correction note, and metadata. It is not a full video or audio artifact. The official transcript itself notes some portions could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-2 FIFA official Final Draw start-time capture\\nSource: FIFA official page, FIFA World Cup 2026 Final Draw\\nURL: https://www.fifa.com/en/tournaments/mens/worldcup/canadamexicousa2026/live-draw\\nRetrieval time: 2026-06-29T22:01:00Z\\n\\nMaterial captured text from web search/open result:\\n- Page title/source: FIFA World Cup 2026™ Final Draw\\n- The draw takes place at the Kennedy Center in Washington DC, USA.\\n- The draw commences at 12:00 local time (17:00 UTC) on Friday 5 December 2025.\\n\\nCapture limits: This is a focused text capture of the official FIFA page timing statement located by web search. It is not a video capture of the draw ceremony.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-3 Governing PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION terms\\n                                         NEWMENTION\\n\\nScope: These rules shall apply to this contract.\\n\\nUnderlying: The Underlying for this Contract is words used by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nRevisions to the Underlying made after Expiration will not be accounted for in determining the\\nExpiration Value.\\n\\nSource Agency: The Source Agencies are \\u003csource\\u003e.\\n\\nType: The type of Contract is an Event Contract.\\n\\nIssuance: After the initial Contract, Contract iterations will be listed on an as-needed basis at\\nthe discretion of the Exchange and corresponding to the risk management needs of Members.\\n\\n\\u003centity\\u003e: \\u003centity\\u003e refers to the speaker, writer, performer, or communicator specified by the\\nExchange. This may include (but is not limited to): a specific named individual, multiple\\nindividuals specified using AND/OR logic, an individual identified by position or title, a group,\\nband, team or collective entity, a specified member or members of a group, an organization,\\ncompany, or institutional entity, or any combination of the aforementioned.\\n\\nWhen \\u003centity\\u003e is defined by a position or title, the Contract tracks whoever holds that position\\nduring \\u003ctime period\\u003e, even if the individual holding the position changes. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a\\nspecific named individual, the identity remains consistent throughout. Name changes (e.g.,\\nstage names, married names) do not create a new entity. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a group or\\norganization and the Contract does not specify particular members, any official\\ncommunication or statement by any member or designated spokesperson counts. When using\\nAND logic, all specified entities must independently say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e. When\\nusing OR logic, at least one of the specified entities must say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nThe Exchange may specify additional conditions such as “at least X members of” a group or\\n“the majority of” a group.\\n\\n\\u003csource\\u003e: \\u003csource\\u003e refers to a Source Agency or ordered collection of Source Agencies\\nspecified by the Exchange at the time of Contract listing, which will be incorporated into the\\nSource Agency hierarchy above and used to determine the occurrence of the Underlying.\\n\\u003csource\\u003e may refer to a singular agency, multiple agencies, an agency by distinguishing\\ncharacteristics, by category or type (e.g., “official government statistical body,” “primary wire\\nservice”), or any combination thereof. When multiple agencies are specified, they may be\\napplied in the hierarchical order designated by the Exchange if so specified, with the highest-\\nranked available and responsive agency taking precedence for purposes of determining the\\nExpiration Value. A lower-ranked agency shall only be consulted if all higher-ranked agencies\\nare unavailable, unresponsive, have not reported on the Underlying by the Expiration time, or\\nif the Exchange, in its sole discretion, determines that a higher-ranked agency’s reporting is\\nincomplete, erroneous, or otherwise insufficient to determine the Expiration Value. If \\u003csource\\u003e\\ndesignates multiple agencies without specifying a hierarchical order, the Exchange shall\\nresolve any conflict between reporting agencies at its sole discretion.\\n\\n\\u003cword\\u003e: \\u003cword\\u003e refers to the particular word or phrase potentially to be mentioned by\\n\\u003centity\\u003e. It may refer to a word being said a minimum number of times. It may also refer to\\none of multiple words/phrases, any of which are acceptable (e.g., “Doge/Dogecoin”).\\n\\f\\u003ctime period\\u003e: \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific range of time, event or discrete date and\\ntime specified by the Exchange. This may be defined by, but is not limited to: a specific event\\nor context (e.g., “during the State of the Union address”), exact dates or times, relative time\\nmarkers (e.g., “before July 1, 2027,” “in Q1 2026”), event-based periods (e.g., “during any\\ncampaign rally in October 2026,” “during the awards ceremony”), and broader intervals (e.g.,\\n“Q1–Q2 2027,” “January–March 2026”).\\n\\nUnless stated otherwise, “Between” is inclusive of both endpoints, while “before” and “after”\\nexclude the specified date. \\u003ctime period\\u003e may also refer to “Any” or “None”, to multiple dates\\n(even if non-consecutive), or to a singular and discrete date or time.\\n\\nWhen \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event (such as an address, speech, performance, or\\nbroadcast), the Exchange may specify what is included, including whether it includes both live\\nand pre-recorded segments (including whether advertisements are included). Where a\\ntimezone is not specified, ET is assumed.\\n\\n\\nPayout Criterion: The Payout Criterion for the Contract encompasses the Expiration Values that\\n\\u003cword\\u003e is said by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n\\n\\nThe word must appear as a distinct, standalone unit, not buried inside another word. Plural\\nand possessive noun forms count. Other grammatical changes (tense, conjugation, derivation)\\ndo not. If \\u003cword\\u003e appears separated from other words by a space or hyphen or in a\\ncompound form with a space or hyphen, it counts. If \\u003cword\\u003e is fused into a single\\nunhyphenated word, it does not count.\\n\\nIf \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled, and the market contains a\\nstrike stating “Event does not qualify/occur”, such a strike shall resolve “Yes” and all others\\n“No”. If \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled but such strikes are NOT\\nlisted, the Contracts will resolve to the last fair price determined at the discretion of the\\nExchange. If the event is postponed, and such a postponement is announced by the end of the\\nfollowing calendar day to be rescheduled to a time within 14 calendar days, the markets shall\\nremain open. If the event captured in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast, the\\nExchange may keep the market open for 24 hours for the release of an official recording.\\nFurther granular details on conditions for these Contracts is available below.\\n\\nAdditional clarification(s):\\n\\n     Possessive noun forms of \\u003cword\\u003e, plurals, and possessive plural noun forms are\\n     INCLUDED:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigrants” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Egg” → “eggs’ shells” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Russia” → “Russia’s” counts, “Russian” does not\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e exists only in adjective form, no plural form exists:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Economic” → “Economics” does not count (“Economic” is an adjective\\n          for which “Economics” is not a plural)\\n     Plural nouns occurring within proper nouns and noun phrases are included:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Cat” → “Cats the musical” counts\\n\\f    Grammatical variations beyond plurals/possessives are NOT included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigration” does NOT count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Run” → “Running” or “Ran” do NOT count\\n    When \\u003cword\\u003e specifies a plural form, the singular does NOT count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Veterans” → “Veteran” does NOT count\\n    Words that are spelled the same as the plural form of \\u003cword\\u003e (if such exists) but are\\n    themselves not a plural noun are included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Wind” → “Winds up the clock” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Border” → “The United States has strong borders” counts\\n    Open compounds (words separated by spaces) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fire station” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “couch” → “couch potato” counts\\n    Hyphenated compounds (words connected by hyphens) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Palestine” → “pro-Palestine” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fat” → “non-fat” counts\\n    Closed compounds (single word, no spaces/hyphens) do not count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire” does not count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firefighter” does not count\\n    Multi-word \\u003cword\\u003e in larger constructions: When \\u003cword\\u003e is a multi-word phrase\\n    appearing within a hyphenated construction, it counts only if \\u003cword\\u003e appears as a\\n    complete, unmodified element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “New York” → “New York-based” counts (complete element)\\n    Portmanteaus (words blended from two words where parts of each are combined) are\\n    NOT included unless the portmanteau clearly contains \\u003cword\\u003e as a distinct, unaltered\\n    element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “MAGA” → “MAGA-nificent” counts (MAGA appears as distinct element)\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “magnificent” → “MAGA-nificent” does NOT count (portmanteau blend)\\n\\nDictionary determination: Both the Merriam-Webster Dictionary (available online) AND the\\nOxford English Dictionary shall be used to determine compound type and/or conventional\\nspelling patterns. Inclusion in either dictionary as an open or hyphenated compound shall\\nsatisfy the Payout Criterion. If neither provides clarity (or the word is not included),\\ndetermination is based on whether written as single unit (closed/doesn’t count) vs. spaces or\\nhyphens (open or hyphenated/counts) and/or context and previous usage.\\n\\nPHONETIC EQUIVALENCIES\\n\\n    Homophones (same sound, different spelling) do not count:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “write” → “right” does not count\\n    Homonyms and homographs (same spelling) COUNT regardless of meaning or\\n    pronunciation:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “bass” → both “bass guitar” and “bass fishing” count\\n    Proper and common nouns are treated identically:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Apple” → both “Apple Inc.” and “apple” (fruit) count\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Will” → both “Will Smith” and “I will go” count\\n    Minor unintentional mispronunciations COUNT if context makes intent clear:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Mamdani” → “Mandani” counts\\n    Severe mispronunciations that make \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable do NOT count.\\n    Trademarked spellings do not count, even when pronounced identically, unless the word\\n\\fitself is the same:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “lift” → “Lyft” (pronounced “lift”) does not count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “uber” → “Uber” counts\\nWords with non-standard transliteration to English count within reason, provided they are\\nphonetically equivalent:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Zelensky” → any of “Zelenski,” “Zelenskii,” “Zelensky,” or “Zelenskiy”\\n      count if pronounced equivalently\\nContractions do not count for their constituent words unless otherwise explicitly specified\\nby the Exchange:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “not” → “won’t,” “can’t,” “don’t,” “isn’t” do not count\\nNumbers spoken as words COUNT, when spoken exactly (not part of a larger number):\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “five” → saying “five” or reading “$5” aloud as “five dollars” counts,\\n      saying “five hundred” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “410” → “four hundred ten”, “four one zero” or “four ten” counts\\nOrdinals COUNT when \\u003cword\\u003e is written numerically OR a phrase that includes a\\nnumber:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “January 6” → “January 6th” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “3” (written numerically) → “3rd” (spoken as “third”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Eight War” → “8 Wars” and “Eighth War” will count\\nCardinal and ordinal number words are distinct:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “one” → “first” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “first” → “one” does NOT count\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count when pronunciation or letter-by-letter spelling\\nmatches \\u003cword\\u003e:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “NASA” (pronounced “NAH-suh”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “N-A-S-A” (spelled out) counts\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count as \\u003cword\\u003e when pronounced as the full word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Doctor” → “Dr.” (pronounced “Doctor”) counts\\nExpanded forms of acronyms do NOT count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “AI” → “artificial intelligence” does not count\\nWords in foreign languages do NOT count unless they are perfect cognates with an\\nEnglish word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fuego” (Spanish) does NOT count\\nEnglish words within foreign sentences count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “policy” → “Nuestra policy es clara” counts\\n\\u003cword\\u003e in organization/company names counts:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Securities” → “Bank of America Securities” counts\\nWords in URLs, emails, handles, and hashtags (exclusive of domain structure, email\\nprovider or symbols) are treated as compounds when spoken as complete words, with the\\ntype of compound subject to aforementioned rules:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firestation.com” pronounced “fire station dot com” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire.com” pronounced “wildfire dot com” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “apple” → “apple.com” pronounced “apple dot com” does count\\n      When presented in URL, email, handle, or hashtag form, \\u003cword\\u003e shall be treated as\\n      a compound, not a multi-word word\\nSung, rapped, or poetic words COUNT if phonetically recognizable:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “money” → “moneyyy” (extended in rap) counts\\n      Extreme distortion making \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable does NOT count.\\nPhonetic alphabet spelling (“Foxtrot India Romeo Echo” for “FIRE”) does NOT count.\\n\\fCANCELLATIONS AND DELAYS\\n\\n   The Exchange may list an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike for any Contract. If listed,\\n   such a strike refers to the structural conditions of the market, and is NOT adjudicated as a\\n   \\u003cword\\u003e needing to be said by or validated by having been said by \\u003centity\\u003e. If listed, this\\n   strike resolves to “Yes” whenever the event fails to occur or qualify under the Payout\\n   Criterion, or any other circumstance prevents normal resolution.\\n   If no such strike is listed, and \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, the following rules\\n   apply if the event is cancelled, postponed, rescheduled, or materially altered (including\\n   being closed to press) such that no video is released within one calendar day of the\\n   original start time of the event:\\n         If the event is cancelled, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price determined in\\n         the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         If the event is postponed or rescheduled, the outcome depends on whether a new\\n         date is publicly announced within one calendar day (i.e. if the event was scheduled\\n         to begin on Monday, any time up to 11:59PM on Tuesday falls within this period) of\\n         the originally scheduled start time:\\n               If no new date is announced within one calendar day, the Contract will resolve\\n               to the last fair price determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n               If a new date is announced within one calendar day, the outcome depends on\\n               when the rescheduled event is set to occur:\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls within fourteen (14) calendar days of the\\n                     originally scheduled date, the Contract shall remain open and \\u003cword\\u003e\\n                     stated during the rescheduled event will count.\\n                           The fourteen-day window begins at 12:00 AM ET on the originally\\n                           scheduled date and ends at 11:59 PM ET fourteen days later, unless\\n                           an alternate timezone is explicitly specified.\\n                           Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the State of the Union on January\\n                           15, 2026” rescheduled to January 20, 2026 → words spoken during\\n                           the rescheduled address count.\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls more than fourteen (14) calendar days after\\n                     the originally scheduled date, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price\\n                     determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         Any Contract that cannot be resolved through the Source Agency hierarchy will\\n         instead be settled at the Last Fair Price. The Exchange will disclose the methodology\\n         used to determine the Last Fair Price (e.g., Last Traded Price, Time-Weighted\\n         Average Price) at the time of Issuance.\\n         If an event begins but is interrupted, abbreviated, or ends prematurely, words\\n         stated by \\u003centity\\u003e during the portion of the event that did occur will count and the\\n         market will otherwise resolve.\\n   If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window but the venue, format, or medium\\n   changes (e.g., moved to a different location, changed from in-person to virtual (with the\\n   exception of being closed to press)), words stated during the event will count.\\n   Special condition: Across both cases, whether an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike is\\n   listed or not, if the event specified as or in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast (or\\n   relayed as such) but the live stream/broadcast does not occur, the Exchange will instead\\n   use an officially released recording as the Underlying, and may delay resolution by up to\\n   one calendar day to allow for the release of such a recording.\\n\\f          If partial snippets are released, Contracts on words that do not appear will be\\n          resolved to last fair price, and Contracts on those that do will be resolved to “Yes”.\\n          If no recording is released, the relevant outcomes triggered by the\\n          presence/absence of an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike shall occur as outlined\\n          above.\\n\\nTECHNICAL DETAILS (UNLESS OTHERWISE SPECIFIED)\\n\\n     When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, pre-recorded content broadcast,\\n     streamed, or published as part of that event is included if presented as part of the official\\n     presentation.\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the concert” with pre-recorded video interlude\\n          where entity speaks → words from interlude count\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the television appearance” with pre-taped\\n          segment aired during broadcast → words from segment count\\n     Behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are NOT\\n     included unless officially broadcast or published as part of \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n     Subtitles and captions that display \\u003cword\\u003e on screen but are not spoken aloud by\\n     \\u003centity\\u003e do NOT count.\\n     Sign language interpretation or usage by entity does NOT count as saying \\u003cword\\u003e unless\\n     the Contract explicitly specifies that sign language counts.\\n     Text that entity displays on screen (presentation slides, teleprompter visible to audience,\\n     signatures) does NOT count unless entity reads it aloud.\\n     Content generated by AI, deepfakes, or synthetic voice technology impersonating entity\\n     does NOT count unless the synthetic content is officially commissioned, authorized, or\\n     published by entity, OR the Contract explicitly specifies that AI-generated content counts.\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e is muted due to technical failure or censorship it shall not count unless\\n     corroborating contextual evidence (including surrounding speech, or an official\\n     uncensored recording or transcript) confirms that \\u003centity\\u003e specifically uttered \\u003cword\\u003e\\n     during the muted period.\\n\\nMinimum Tick: The Minimum Tick size for the Contract shall be $0.01.\\n\\nPosition Accountability Level: The Position Accountability Level for the Contract shall be\\n$25,000 per strike, per Member.\\n\\nLast Trading Date: The Last Trading Date of the Contract will be the Expiration Date. The Last\\nTrading Time will be the Expiration time.\\n\\nSettlement Date: The Settlement Date of the Contract shall be no later than the day after the\\nExpiration Date, unless the Market Outcome is under review pursuant to Rule 7.1.\\n\\nExpiration Date: When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event: The latest Expiration Date of\\nthe Contract shall be fourteen (14) calendar days after the originally scheduled date of the\\nevent. If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window, expiration will be moved to an\\nearlier date and time in accordance with Rule 7.2. When \\u003ctime period\\u003e is defined by specific\\ndates: The latest Expiration Date of the Contract shall be two weeks after the end of \\u003ctime\\nperiod\\u003e. If an event described in the Payout Criterion occurs and a consensus has been\\nreached on all terms, then expiration will be moved to an earlier date and time in accordance\\nwith Rule 7.2.\\n\\fExpiration time: The Expiration time of the Contract shall be 10:00 AM ET.\\n\\nSettlement Value: The Settlement Value for this Contract is $1.00.\\n\\nExpiration Value: The Expiration Value is the value of the Underlying as documented by the\\nSource Agency on the Expiration Date at the Expiration time.\\n\\nContingencies: Before Settlement, Kalshi may, at its sole discretion, initiate the Market\\nOutcome Review Process pursuant to Rule 7.1 of the Rulebook. If an Expiration Value cannot\\nbe determined on the Expiration Date, Kalshi has the right to determine payouts pursuant to\\nRule 7.1 in the Rulebook.\\n\\f\\n\\n[defendant] DX-4 Market packet: Ronaldo strike and challenged No resolution\\nMarket URL: https://kalshi.com/markets/kxtrumpmentionb/trump-mention-b/kxtrumpmentionb-25dec06\\n\\nPublic market title: What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\n\\nContract family: PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION\\n\\nStrike at issue: Ronaldo\\n\\nChallenged resolution: No\\n\\nRequested resolution: Yes\\n\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R1 GovInfo transcript confirming Ronaldo utterances and Kennedy Center/FIFA Draw context\\nSource: GovInfo, Compilation of Presidential Documents, DCPD202501162\\nURL retrieved: https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/DCPD-202501162/html/DCPD-202501162.htm\\nRetrieval time: 2026-06-29T22:00:00Z\\nLocal captured HTML size/hash: 51,571 bytes; SHA-256 eadbceeecf3e94f5bd423bcb8e8511165fdc7265dd8c1e025870c2e8f34dfd99\\n\\nMaterial captured text from official GovInfo HTML/web.open:\\n\\nAdministration of Donald J. Trump, 2025\\n\\nTitle: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\nDate: December 5, 2025\\n\\nOpening note: [The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\\n\\nExcerpt - The President's Interest in Soccer (web.open lines 196-203):\\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\\\"football,\\\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\\n\\nExcerpt - The President's Interest in Soccer (web.open lines 322-329):\\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\\nThe President. But they have a little more speed. But no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\\n\\nTiming/context note (web.open lines 461-462):\\nNOTE: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. In his remarks, he referred to Trey Yingst, chief foreign correspondent, Fox News Channel; Cristiano Ronaldo, forward for Saudi Pro League club Al-Nass and Portugal's national soccer team; and Lionel Messi, forward for Major League Soccer club Inter Miami and Argentina's national team. A reporter referred to New York State Attorney General Letitia James.\\nThe transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\n\\nDocument category/location/name/subject metadata (web.open lines 463-468):\\nCategories: Interviews With the News Media: Exchanges with reporters, Washington, DC.\\nLocations: Washington, DC.\\nNames include: Cristiano Ronaldo and Lionel Messi.\\nSubjects include: Federation Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) World Cup; John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts; News media, Presidential interviews; Soccer.\\nDCPD Number: DCPD202501162.\\n\\nCapture limits: This item is a focused text capture of the material official transcript title, Ronaldo excerpts, timing/correction note, and metadata. It is not a full video or audio artifact. The official transcript itself notes some portions could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R2 FIFA timing capture showing formal commencement time but not market-specific exclusion\\nSource: FIFA official page, FIFA World Cup 2026 Final Draw\\nURL: https://www.fifa.com/en/tournaments/mens/worldcup/canadamexicousa2026/live-draw\\nRetrieval time: 2026-06-29T22:01:00Z\\n\\nMaterial captured text from web search/open result:\\n- Page title/source: FIFA World Cup 2026™ Final Draw\\n- The draw takes place at the Kennedy Center in Washington DC, USA.\\n- The draw commences at 12:00 local time (17:00 UTC) on Friday 5 December 2025.\\n\\nCapture limits: This is a focused text capture of the official FIFA page timing statement located by web search. It is not a video capture of the draw ceremony.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R3 Event-period terms and exclusions\\n                                         NEWMENTION\\n\\nScope: These rules shall apply to this contract.\\n\\nUnderlying: The Underlying for this Contract is words used by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nRevisions to the Underlying made after Expiration will not be accounted for in determining the\\nExpiration Value.\\n\\nSource Agency: The Source Agencies are \\u003csource\\u003e.\\n\\nType: The type of Contract is an Event Contract.\\n\\nIssuance: After the initial Contract, Contract iterations will be listed on an as-needed basis at\\nthe discretion of the Exchange and corresponding to the risk management needs of Members.\\n\\n\\u003centity\\u003e: \\u003centity\\u003e refers to the speaker, writer, performer, or communicator specified by the\\nExchange. This may include (but is not limited to): a specific named individual, multiple\\nindividuals specified using AND/OR logic, an individual identified by position or title, a group,\\nband, team or collective entity, a specified member or members of a group, an organization,\\ncompany, or institutional entity, or any combination of the aforementioned.\\n\\nWhen \\u003centity\\u003e is defined by a position or title, the Contract tracks whoever holds that position\\nduring \\u003ctime period\\u003e, even if the individual holding the position changes. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a\\nspecific named individual, the identity remains consistent throughout. Name changes (e.g.,\\nstage names, married names) do not create a new entity. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a group or\\norganization and the Contract does not specify particular members, any official\\ncommunication or statement by any member or designated spokesperson counts. When using\\nAND logic, all specified entities must independently say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e. When\\nusing OR logic, at least one of the specified entities must say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nThe Exchange may specify additional conditions such as “at least X members of” a group or\\n“the majority of” a group.\\n\\n\\u003csource\\u003e: \\u003csource\\u003e refers to a Source Agency or ordered collection of Source Agencies\\nspecified by the Exchange at the time of Contract listing, which will be incorporated into the\\nSource Agency hierarchy above and used to determine the occurrence of the Underlying.\\n\\u003csource\\u003e may refer to a singular agency, multiple agencies, an agency by distinguishing\\ncharacteristics, by category or type (e.g., “official government statistical body,” “primary wire\\nservice”), or any combination thereof. When multiple agencies are specified, they may be\\napplied in the hierarchical order designated by the Exchange if so specified, with the highest-\\nranked available and responsive agency taking precedence for purposes of determining the\\nExpiration Value. A lower-ranked agency shall only be consulted if all higher-ranked agencies\\nare unavailable, unresponsive, have not reported on the Underlying by the Expiration time, or\\nif the Exchange, in its sole discretion, determines that a higher-ranked agency’s reporting is\\nincomplete, erroneous, or otherwise insufficient to determine the Expiration Value. If \\u003csource\\u003e\\ndesignates multiple agencies without specifying a hierarchical order, the Exchange shall\\nresolve any conflict between reporting agencies at its sole discretion.\\n\\n\\u003cword\\u003e: \\u003cword\\u003e refers to the particular word or phrase potentially to be mentioned by\\n\\u003centity\\u003e. It may refer to a word being said a minimum number of times. It may also refer to\\none of multiple words/phrases, any of which are acceptable (e.g., “Doge/Dogecoin”).\\n\\f\\u003ctime period\\u003e: \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific range of time, event or discrete date and\\ntime specified by the Exchange. This may be defined by, but is not limited to: a specific event\\nor context (e.g., “during the State of the Union address”), exact dates or times, relative time\\nmarkers (e.g., “before July 1, 2027,” “in Q1 2026”), event-based periods (e.g., “during any\\ncampaign rally in October 2026,” “during the awards ceremony”), and broader intervals (e.g.,\\n“Q1–Q2 2027,” “January–March 2026”).\\n\\nUnless stated otherwise, “Between” is inclusive of both endpoints, while “before” and “after”\\nexclude the specified date. \\u003ctime period\\u003e may also refer to “Any” or “None”, to multiple dates\\n(even if non-consecutive), or to a singular and discrete date or time.\\n\\nWhen \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event (such as an address, speech, performance, or\\nbroadcast), the Exchange may specify what is included, including whether it includes both live\\nand pre-recorded segments (including whether advertisements are included). Where a\\ntimezone is not specified, ET is assumed.\\n\\n\\nPayout Criterion: The Payout Criterion for the Contract encompasses the Expiration Values that\\n\\u003cword\\u003e is said by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n\\n\\nThe word must appear as a distinct, standalone unit, not buried inside another word. Plural\\nand possessive noun forms count. Other grammatical changes (tense, conjugation, derivation)\\ndo not. If \\u003cword\\u003e appears separated from other words by a space or hyphen or in a\\ncompound form with a space or hyphen, it counts. If \\u003cword\\u003e is fused into a single\\nunhyphenated word, it does not count.\\n\\nIf \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled, and the market contains a\\nstrike stating “Event does not qualify/occur”, such a strike shall resolve “Yes” and all others\\n“No”. If \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled but such strikes are NOT\\nlisted, the Contracts will resolve to the last fair price determined at the discretion of the\\nExchange. If the event is postponed, and such a postponement is announced by the end of the\\nfollowing calendar day to be rescheduled to a time within 14 calendar days, the markets shall\\nremain open. If the event captured in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast, the\\nExchange may keep the market open for 24 hours for the release of an official recording.\\nFurther granular details on conditions for these Contracts is available below.\\n\\nAdditional clarification(s):\\n\\n     Possessive noun forms of \\u003cword\\u003e, plurals, and possessive plural noun forms are\\n     INCLUDED:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigrants” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Egg” → “eggs’ shells” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Russia” → “Russia’s” counts, “Russian” does not\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e exists only in adjective form, no plural form exists:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Economic” → “Economics” does not count (“Economic” is an adjective\\n          for which “Economics” is not a plural)\\n     Plural nouns occurring within proper nouns and noun phrases are included:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Cat” → “Cats the musical” counts\\n\\f    Grammatical variations beyond plurals/possessives are NOT included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigration” does NOT count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Run” → “Running” or “Ran” do NOT count\\n    When \\u003cword\\u003e specifies a plural form, the singular does NOT count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Veterans” → “Veteran” does NOT count\\n    Words that are spelled the same as the plural form of \\u003cword\\u003e (if such exists) but are\\n    themselves not a plural noun are included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Wind” → “Winds up the clock” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Border” → “The United States has strong borders” counts\\n    Open compounds (words separated by spaces) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fire station” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “couch” → “couch potato” counts\\n    Hyphenated compounds (words connected by hyphens) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Palestine” → “pro-Palestine” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fat” → “non-fat” counts\\n    Closed compounds (single word, no spaces/hyphens) do not count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire” does not count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firefighter” does not count\\n    Multi-word \\u003cword\\u003e in larger constructions: When \\u003cword\\u003e is a multi-word phrase\\n    appearing within a hyphenated construction, it counts only if \\u003cword\\u003e appears as a\\n    complete, unmodified element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “New York” → “New York-based” counts (complete element)\\n    Portmanteaus (words blended from two words where parts of each are combined) are\\n    NOT included unless the portmanteau clearly contains \\u003cword\\u003e as a distinct, unaltered\\n    element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “MAGA” → “MAGA-nificent” counts (MAGA appears as distinct element)\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “magnificent” → “MAGA-nificent” does NOT count (portmanteau blend)\\n\\nDictionary determination: Both the Merriam-Webster Dictionary (available online) AND the\\nOxford English Dictionary shall be used to determine compound type and/or conventional\\nspelling patterns. Inclusion in either dictionary as an open or hyphenated compound shall\\nsatisfy the Payout Criterion. If neither provides clarity (or the word is not included),\\ndetermination is based on whether written as single unit (closed/doesn’t count) vs. spaces or\\nhyphens (open or hyphenated/counts) and/or context and previous usage.\\n\\nPHONETIC EQUIVALENCIES\\n\\n    Homophones (same sound, different spelling) do not count:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “write” → “right” does not count\\n    Homonyms and homographs (same spelling) COUNT regardless of meaning or\\n    pronunciation:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “bass” → both “bass guitar” and “bass fishing” count\\n    Proper and common nouns are treated identically:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Apple” → both “Apple Inc.” and “apple” (fruit) count\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Will” → both “Will Smith” and “I will go” count\\n    Minor unintentional mispronunciations COUNT if context makes intent clear:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Mamdani” → “Mandani” counts\\n    Severe mispronunciations that make \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable do NOT count.\\n    Trademarked spellings do not count, even when pronounced identically, unless the word\\n\\fitself is the same:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “lift” → “Lyft” (pronounced “lift”) does not count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “uber” → “Uber” counts\\nWords with non-standard transliteration to English count within reason, provided they are\\nphonetically equivalent:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Zelensky” → any of “Zelenski,” “Zelenskii,” “Zelensky,” or “Zelenskiy”\\n      count if pronounced equivalently\\nContractions do not count for their constituent words unless otherwise explicitly specified\\nby the Exchange:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “not” → “won’t,” “can’t,” “don’t,” “isn’t” do not count\\nNumbers spoken as words COUNT, when spoken exactly (not part of a larger number):\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “five” → saying “five” or reading “$5” aloud as “five dollars” counts,\\n      saying “five hundred” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “410” → “four hundred ten”, “four one zero” or “four ten” counts\\nOrdinals COUNT when \\u003cword\\u003e is written numerically OR a phrase that includes a\\nnumber:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “January 6” → “January 6th” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “3” (written numerically) → “3rd” (spoken as “third”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Eight War” → “8 Wars” and “Eighth War” will count\\nCardinal and ordinal number words are distinct:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “one” → “first” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “first” → “one” does NOT count\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count when pronunciation or letter-by-letter spelling\\nmatches \\u003cword\\u003e:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “NASA” (pronounced “NAH-suh”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “N-A-S-A” (spelled out) counts\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count as \\u003cword\\u003e when pronounced as the full word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Doctor” → “Dr.” (pronounced “Doctor”) counts\\nExpanded forms of acronyms do NOT count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “AI” → “artificial intelligence” does not count\\nWords in foreign languages do NOT count unless they are perfect cognates with an\\nEnglish word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fuego” (Spanish) does NOT count\\nEnglish words within foreign sentences count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “policy” → “Nuestra policy es clara” counts\\n\\u003cword\\u003e in organization/company names counts:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Securities” → “Bank of America Securities” counts\\nWords in URLs, emails, handles, and hashtags (exclusive of domain structure, email\\nprovider or symbols) are treated as compounds when spoken as complete words, with the\\ntype of compound subject to aforementioned rules:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firestation.com” pronounced “fire station dot com” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire.com” pronounced “wildfire dot com” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “apple” → “apple.com” pronounced “apple dot com” does count\\n      When presented in URL, email, handle, or hashtag form, \\u003cword\\u003e shall be treated as\\n      a compound, not a multi-word word\\nSung, rapped, or poetic words COUNT if phonetically recognizable:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “money” → “moneyyy” (extended in rap) counts\\n      Extreme distortion making \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable does NOT count.\\nPhonetic alphabet spelling (“Foxtrot India Romeo Echo” for “FIRE”) does NOT count.\\n\\fCANCELLATIONS AND DELAYS\\n\\n   The Exchange may list an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike for any Contract. If listed,\\n   such a strike refers to the structural conditions of the market, and is NOT adjudicated as a\\n   \\u003cword\\u003e needing to be said by or validated by having been said by \\u003centity\\u003e. If listed, this\\n   strike resolves to “Yes” whenever the event fails to occur or qualify under the Payout\\n   Criterion, or any other circumstance prevents normal resolution.\\n   If no such strike is listed, and \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, the following rules\\n   apply if the event is cancelled, postponed, rescheduled, or materially altered (including\\n   being closed to press) such that no video is released within one calendar day of the\\n   original start time of the event:\\n         If the event is cancelled, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price determined in\\n         the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         If the event is postponed or rescheduled, the outcome depends on whether a new\\n         date is publicly announced within one calendar day (i.e. if the event was scheduled\\n         to begin on Monday, any time up to 11:59PM on Tuesday falls within this period) of\\n         the originally scheduled start time:\\n               If no new date is announced within one calendar day, the Contract will resolve\\n               to the last fair price determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n               If a new date is announced within one calendar day, the outcome depends on\\n               when the rescheduled event is set to occur:\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls within fourteen (14) calendar days of the\\n                     originally scheduled date, the Contract shall remain open and \\u003cword\\u003e\\n                     stated during the rescheduled event will count.\\n                           The fourteen-day window begins at 12:00 AM ET on the originally\\n                           scheduled date and ends at 11:59 PM ET fourteen days later, unless\\n                           an alternate timezone is explicitly specified.\\n                           Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the State of the Union on January\\n                           15, 2026” rescheduled to January 20, 2026 → words spoken during\\n                           the rescheduled address count.\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls more than fourteen (14) calendar days after\\n                     the originally scheduled date, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price\\n                     determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         Any Contract that cannot be resolved through the Source Agency hierarchy will\\n         instead be settled at the Last Fair Price. The Exchange will disclose the methodology\\n         used to determine the Last Fair Price (e.g., Last Traded Price, Time-Weighted\\n         Average Price) at the time of Issuance.\\n         If an event begins but is interrupted, abbreviated, or ends prematurely, words\\n         stated by \\u003centity\\u003e during the portion of the event that did occur will count and the\\n         market will otherwise resolve.\\n   If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window but the venue, format, or medium\\n   changes (e.g., moved to a different location, changed from in-person to virtual (with the\\n   exception of being closed to press)), words stated during the event will count.\\n   Special condition: Across both cases, whether an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike is\\n   listed or not, if the event specified as or in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast (or\\n   relayed as such) but the live stream/broadcast does not occur, the Exchange will instead\\n   use an officially released recording as the Underlying, and may delay resolution by up to\\n   one calendar day to allow for the release of such a recording.\\n\\f          If partial snippets are released, Contracts on words that do not appear will be\\n          resolved to last fair price, and Contracts on those that do will be resolved to “Yes”.\\n          If no recording is released, the relevant outcomes triggered by the\\n          presence/absence of an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike shall occur as outlined\\n          above.\\n\\nTECHNICAL DETAILS (UNLESS OTHERWISE SPECIFIED)\\n\\n     When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, pre-recorded content broadcast,\\n     streamed, or published as part of that event is included if presented as part of the official\\n     presentation.\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the concert” with pre-recorded video interlude\\n          where entity speaks → words from interlude count\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the television appearance” with pre-taped\\n          segment aired during broadcast → words from segment count\\n     Behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are NOT\\n     included unless officially broadcast or published as part of \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n     Subtitles and captions that display \\u003cword\\u003e on screen but are not spoken aloud by\\n     \\u003centity\\u003e do NOT count.\\n     Sign language interpretation or usage by entity does NOT count as saying \\u003cword\\u003e unless\\n     the Contract explicitly specifies that sign language counts.\\n     Text that entity displays on screen (presentation slides, teleprompter visible to audience,\\n     signatures) does NOT count unless entity reads it aloud.\\n     Content generated by AI, deepfakes, or synthetic voice technology impersonating entity\\n     does NOT count unless the synthetic content is officially commissioned, authorized, or\\n     published by entity, OR the Contract explicitly specifies that AI-generated content counts.\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e is muted due to technical failure or censorship it shall not count unless\\n     corroborating contextual evidence (including surrounding speech, or an official\\n     uncensored recording or transcript) confirms that \\u003centity\\u003e specifically uttered \\u003cword\\u003e\\n     during the muted period.\\n\\nMinimum Tick: The Minimum Tick size for the Contract shall be $0.01.\\n\\nPosition Accountability Level: The Position Accountability Level for the Contract shall be\\n$25,000 per strike, per Member.\\n\\nLast Trading Date: The Last Trading Date of the Contract will be the Expiration Date. The Last\\nTrading Time will be the Expiration time.\\n\\nSettlement Date: The Settlement Date of the Contract shall be no later than the day after the\\nExpiration Date, unless the Market Outcome is under review pursuant to Rule 7.1.\\n\\nExpiration Date: When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event: The latest Expiration Date of\\nthe Contract shall be fourteen (14) calendar days after the originally scheduled date of the\\nevent. If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window, expiration will be moved to an\\nearlier date and time in accordance with Rule 7.2. When \\u003ctime period\\u003e is defined by specific\\ndates: The latest Expiration Date of the Contract shall be two weeks after the end of \\u003ctime\\nperiod\\u003e. If an event described in the Payout Criterion occurs and a consensus has been\\nreached on all terms, then expiration will be moved to an earlier date and time in accordance\\nwith Rule 7.2.\\n\\fExpiration time: The Expiration time of the Contract shall be 10:00 AM ET.\\n\\nSettlement Value: The Settlement Value for this Contract is $1.00.\\n\\nExpiration Value: The Expiration Value is the value of the Underlying as documented by the\\nSource Agency on the Expiration Date at the Expiration time.\\n\\nContingencies: Before Settlement, Kalshi may, at its sole discretion, initiate the Market\\nOutcome Review Process pursuant to Rule 7.1 of the Rulebook. If an Expiration Value cannot\\nbe determined on the Expiration Date, Kalshi has the right to determine payouts pursuant to\\nRule 7.1 in the Rulebook.\\n\\f\\n\\n[defendant] DX-S1 GovInfo official transcript: prior reporter exchange\\nSource: GovInfo, Compilation of Presidential Documents, DCPD202501162\\nURL retrieved: https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/DCPD-202501162/html/DCPD-202501162.htm\\nRetrieval time: 2026-06-29T22:00:00Z\\nLocal captured HTML size/hash: 51,571 bytes; SHA-256 eadbceeecf3e94f5bd423bcb8e8511165fdc7265dd8c1e025870c2e8f34dfd99\\n\\nMaterial captured text from official GovInfo HTML/web.open:\\n\\nAdministration of Donald J. Trump, 2025\\n\\nTitle: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\nDate: December 5, 2025\\n\\nOpening note: [The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\\n\\nExcerpt - The President's Interest in Soccer (web.open lines 196-203):\\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\\\"football,\\\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\\n\\nExcerpt - The President's Interest in Soccer (web.open lines 322-329):\\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\\nThe President. But they have a little more speed. But no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\\n\\nTiming/context note (web.open lines 461-462):\\nNOTE: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. In his remarks, he referred to Trey Yingst, chief foreign correspondent, Fox News Channel; Cristiano Ronaldo, forward for Saudi Pro League club Al-Nass and Portugal's national soccer team; and Lionel Messi, forward for Major League Soccer club Inter Miami and Argentina's national team. A reporter referred to New York State Attorney General Letitia James.\\nThe transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\n\\nDocument category/location/name/subject metadata (web.open lines 463-468):\\nCategories: Interviews With the News Media: Exchanges with reporters, Washington, DC.\\nLocations: Washington, DC.\\nNames include: Cristiano Ronaldo and Lionel Messi.\\nSubjects include: Federation Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) World Cup; John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts; News media, Presidential interviews; Soccer.\\nDCPD Number: DCPD202501162.\\n\\nCapture limits: This item is a focused text capture of the material official transcript title, Ronaldo excerpts, timing/correction note, and metadata. It is not a full video or audio artifact. The official transcript itself notes some portions could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-S2 FIFA official draw commencement time\\nSource: FIFA official page, FIFA World Cup 2026 Final Draw\\nURL: https://www.fifa.com/en/tournaments/mens/worldcup/canadamexicousa2026/live-draw\\nRetrieval time: 2026-06-29T22:01:00Z\\n\\nMaterial captured text from web search/open result:\\n- Page title/source: FIFA World Cup 2026™ Final Draw\\n- The draw takes place at the Kennedy Center in Washington DC, USA.\\n- The draw commences at 12:00 local time (17:00 UTC) on Friday 5 December 2025.\\n\\nCapture limits: This is a focused text capture of the official FIFA page timing statement located by web search. It is not a video capture of the draw ceremony.\\n\\nSubmitted evidence:\\n[plaintiff arguments] Official White House video page capture: President Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing (ev_db357d4e9407_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-db357d4e9407)\\nSource: https://www.whitehouse.gov/videos/president-trump-attends-the-fifa-world-cup-drawing/\\nSHA-256: `db357d4e940728d417ae4f7f3caac6b78d3fd3e4aba70d46fe10c6132d45997a`\\nBytes: 1300\\nRelevance: Establishes that the White House officially published a video page titled President Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing, dated December 5, 2025, with a full-video link and related World Cup Draw videos; relevant to source chain and event context.\\n\\n[plaintiff arguments] YouTube metadata capture: Trump Talks Cristiano Ronaldo at FIFA Draw (ev_4e1045905547_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-4e1045905547)\\nSource: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Cb2yO0lLEnM\\nSHA-256: `4e10459055477440085fe5e20d970eb2488e61d13a5e2b3133a3656bed7526d7`\\nBytes: 1779\\nRelevance: Provides a public clip source and page metadata asserting that at the FIFA World Cup Draw Ceremony Trump shared a story about meeting Cristiano Ronaldo and said Ronaldo was a great person; relevant to the alleged Ronaldo utterance, though weaker than an official full transcript or video.\\n\\n[defendant arguments] GovInfo official transcript capture: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the FIFA World Cup Draw (ev_a1b1f6b1b7bd_submitted-evidence-03-defendant-a1b1f6b1b7bd)\\nSource: https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/DCPD-202501162/html/DCPD-202501162.htm\\nSHA-256: `a1b1f6b1b7bd0b691c7fe8d97467dd0d085e2b22387ae4198270764de66e56e2`\\nBytes: 3070\\nRelevance: Official transcript identifies the relevant Trump remarks as an exchange with reporters prior to the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw; it includes the Ronaldo utterances and timing/correction notes, directly bearing on whether the utterances were during the countable event period.\\n\\n[defendant arguments] FIFA official page capture: 2026 World Cup Final Draw start time (ev_3973dc8f98c0_submitted-evidence-04-defendant-3973dc8f98c0)\\nSource: https://www.fifa.com/en/tournaments/mens/worldcup/canadamexicousa2026/live-draw\\nSHA-256: `3973dc8f98c01702174f61f5548eb1e80efe64dd72b44f21ed0fa7d944f93248`\\nBytes: 598\\nRelevance: Establishes the official Final Draw start time as 12:00 local time on December 5, 2025, which helps compare the draw event period against the GovInfo transcript note that the reporter exchange occurred at 11:13 a.m.\\n\\nTechnical reports:\\n[plaintiff] Plaintiff source-search and capture ledger\\nSearched exact market/strike phrases, White House domain, public video pages, YouTube video IDs, and Kalshi live market URL. Submitted official White House page capture and YouTube metadata capture. Kalshi live page returned a Vercel security checkpoint/429; local browser was unavailable; Python pip/ensurepip unavailable for yt-dlp; direct YouTube caption/open paths were throttled or unavailable. Remaining best evidence would be a full official video/transcript or Kalshi resolution rationale if later accessible.\\n\\n[defendant] Defendant source-search and capture ledger\\nInspected current AAR evidence and exact contents of plaintiff's White House and YouTube captures. Retrieved GovInfo official HTML transcript with curl from DCPD-202501162; local full HTML was 51,571 bytes with SHA-256 eadbceeecf3e94f5bd423bcb8e8511165fdc7265dd8c1e025870c2e8f34dfd99, then submitted a focused material text capture as DX-1. Searched official draw timing and submitted the FIFA official page timing statement as DX-2. Remaining gaps: full Kalshi market source hierarchy/resolution rationale and full WH/FIFA video were not captured, but official GovInfo timing/title plus FIFA start time resolve the material timing issue.\\n\\nCall submit_council_vote with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated.\\nKeep the rationale brief: no more than three sentences.\\n\\nCouncil API instructions:\\nYou are a council member. Decide the proposition from the admitted record.\\nYou may examine admitted evidence through read-only tools when exact bytes, metadata, or exhibit contents matter.\\nDo not search the web, introduce new facts, create new evidence, or upload evidence.\\nWhen ready, call submit_council_vote exactly once with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated and a concise rationale.\\n\",\"state\":\"ready\",\"status\":\"ready\",\"tools\":[{\"description\":\"Return the current visible arbitration record for this council member.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"get_case\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"List visible immutable record evidence.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"list_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Return metadata and read limits for one visible evidence item.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"stat_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Read a bounded byte range from one visible evidence item as base64.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"length\":{\"minimum\":1,\"type\":\"integer\"},\"offset\":{\"minimum\":0,\"type\":\"integer\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\",\"offset\",\"length\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"read_evidence_range\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Submit one council vote for the current deliberation opportunity.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"rationale\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"vote\":{\"enum\":[\"demonstrated\",\"not_demonstrated\"],\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"vote\",\"rationale\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"submit_council_vote\",\"read_only\":false}],\"turn\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"completed\":false,\"deadline\":\"2026-06-29T22:18:45.386037689Z\",\"deliberation_round\":1,\"member_id\":\"C2\",\"opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C2\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"remaining_ms\":889046,\"role_id\":\"council\",\"turn_number\":10},\"wait\":{\"reason\":\"ready\",\"state_version\":14,\"version\":17}}"}],"details":{"mode":"call","mcpResult":{"content":[{"type":"text","text":"ok: true\nstatus: ready\nstate: ready\nmessage: An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\nafter_version: 17\nafter_opportunity_id: deliberation:1:C2\nmember_id: C2\ncase_id: arb-ex03a-20260629214245\nwait_reason: ready\nphase: deliberation\nopportunity_id: deliberation:1:C2\nremaining_ms: 889046\nattempts_remaining: 3\njson: {\"after_opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C2\",\"after_version\":17,\"case_id\":\"arb-ex03a-20260629214245\",\"limits\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"max_evidence_read_bytes\":65536,\"max_evidence_read_bytes_per_opportunity\":524288,\"max_evidence_reads_per_opportunity\":32,\"max_response_bytes\":131072,\"remaining_evidence_read_bytes_for_opportunity\":524288,\"remaining_evidence_reads_for_opportunity\":32},\"member_id\":\"C2\",\"message\":\"An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\",\"ok\":true,\"prompt\":\"Role: council member\\nMember ID: C2\\nDeliberation round: 1\\nProposition: For the Kalshi market \\\"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\\", the strike \\\"Ronaldo\\\" should resolve Yes because Trump said \\\"Ronaldo\\\" in public remarks at the World Cup Draw venue immediately before the formal program, and the market wording plus the governing mention-market terms did not clearly exclude those event-linked remarks.\\nStandard of evidence: Preponderance of the evidence.\\nPersona:\\nYou are a careful juror and council member.\\n\\nEvaluate the record faithfully. Decide only from the evidence, the stated rules, and the applicable burden of proof. Do not favor either side, fill gaps with speculation, or ignore uncertainty.\\n\\nGive weight to reliable sources, direct evidence, consistent reasoning, and clear admissions. Discount unsupported claims, rhetorical force, irrelevant facts, and conclusions that exceed the record.\\n\\nWhen the evidence supports one answer, state it plainly. When the evidence is incomplete or balanced, say so. Be concise, honest, and exact.\\n\\nRecord:\\nOpenings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, this case is not about whether the word \\\"Ronaldo\\\" would count if President Trump clearly said it. The current packet makes that part straightforward: the market is the Kalshi PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION market titled \\\"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\\"; the strike is \\\"Ronaldo\\\"; Kalshi’s challenged resolution is No; and plaintiff seeks Yes.\\n\\nThe real dispute is temporal and contextual. Did the market phrase \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw,\\\" read with the governing mention-market terms, include public event-linked remarks at the World Cup Draw venue immediately before the formal draw program? Or did it clearly confine countable words to a narrower formal broadcast segment? Plaintiff’s position is that a No resolution cannot stand unless the record shows that the counting window clearly excluded those event-linked remarks.\\n\\nThe admitted terms matter. They define the underlying as words used by the specified entity during the specified time period. They expressly recognize event-based time periods, and they say the payout criterion is satisfied when the word is said by the entity during that period. They also contain exclusions: behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings do not count unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period; captions or text alone do not count; and the word must appear as a distinct standalone unit. Those exclusions are important, but they do not by themselves answer this case. A public remark at the event venue, tied to the Draw and immediately before the formal program, is not automatically a rehearsal, sound check, or private behind-the-scenes moment.\\n\\nAt this opening stage, the record proves the market identity, the challenged resolution, the requested resolution, and the generic governing terms. It does not yet prove the utterance itself, the exact sequence of the venue remarks, the source-agency hierarchy or any market-specific time-period language beyond the packet, or Kalshi’s reason for treating the strike as No. Those are the factual links that should decide the case under a preponderance standard.\\n\\nPlaintiff expects the decisive proof to be the full official or otherwise reliable event video or transcript, with enough surrounding context to show whether Trump said \\\"Ronaldo\\\" aloud as a standalone word; when he said it relative to the Draw event; whether the remarks were public and event-linked rather than backstage or a sound check; and whether any market-specific rule clearly excluded that segment. Plaintiff also expects the market page, archived market details, and any resolution rationale to be important because ambiguity in the market’s own event wording should not be resolved against Yes after the fact.\\n\\nThe defense will likely argue that \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw\\\" means only the formal draw ceremony or broadcast, and that anything before the formal program is outside the counting period. That theory can win only if the evidence shows a clear exclusion or a source record that separates the alleged remarks from the event itself. If the evidence instead shows public remarks at the Draw venue, officially connected to the event, immediately before the formal program, and no clear rule excluding them, then the terms favor counting the word and resolving the Ronaldo strike Yes.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the defense position is straightforward: the admitted record does not yet prove that the Ronaldo strike should resolve Yes. It proves a market title, a generic mention-market rule set, and Kalshi's challenged No resolution. It does not prove that any qualifying utterance of \\\"Ronaldo\\\" occurred during the market's countable time period.\\n\\nThe plaintiff's opening usefully narrows the dispute. This is not primarily a word-boundary case. If President Trump said \\\"Ronaldo\\\" as a standalone spoken word during the countable FIFA World Cup Draw period, the generic terms would ordinarily treat that as the kind of word that can count. The real question is whether plaintiff can carry the burden of showing that alleged pre-program, venue-adjacent remarks were part of the market's specified time period: \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\\\"\\n\\nThe case-packet terms matter, but they cut both ways. They say the underlying is words used by the entity during the specified time period. They recognize that a time period can be an event, and they allow the Exchange to specify what is included when an event is involved. They also distinguish official event presentation from material outside the event: behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are not included unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period; text or captions alone do not count; and the relevant word must be spoken aloud by the entity. Those provisions do not support a rule that every public comment inside the same building, or every press exchange near the formal program, is automatically \\\"during\\\" the Draw.\\n\\nThat is the burden problem for plaintiff. The admitted market-page file identifies the public title, contract family, strike, challenged resolution, and requested resolution. It does not supply a full market-specific source hierarchy, a formal start time, a transcript, a video, a resolution rationale, or the alleged remarks. The terms file supplies the generic framework, but not the factual bridge from \\\"immediately before the formal program\\\" to \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\\\" Without that bridge, the No resolution is not shown to be wrong by a preponderance of the evidence.\\n\\nThe defense expects the decisive proof to be source-chain evidence, not characterization. The council should want the market's full rule page if available, the source agency hierarchy, the official draw program or broadcast, any official transcript or recording of the alleged exchange, and enough surrounding timestamps to separate the formal draw from pre-event reporter access, red-carpet exchanges, arrivals, or other ancillary material. If later evidence shows that the alleged Ronaldo comment was in a segment officially presented as part of the Draw itself, plaintiff's argument becomes stronger. If the evidence instead shows a separate exchange with reporters before the draw, or an event-linked but pre-program interaction not incorporated into the official presentation, the generic terms support Kalshi's No.\\n\\nSo the defense opening is not that the word Ronaldo could never count. It is that this record has not established the necessary time-period link. The proposition asks the council to overturn No because the market wording and terms did not clearly exclude pre-program remarks. That reverses the burden. Plaintiff must show that the remarks were included in the countable period. Ambiguity about the outer edge of an event is not the same as proof that a specific pre-event utterance satisfies the payout criterion.\\n\\nArguments:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, plaintiff has now supplied the record links that were missing at opening.\\n\\nFirst, the market packet fixes what this dispute is: the Kalshi market title is \\\"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\\"; the contract family is PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION; the strike is \\\"Ronaldo\\\"; Kalshi's challenged resolution is No; and plaintiff seeks Yes. That is PX-1.\\n\\nSecond, the governing terms make this an event-period mention question, not a narrow formal-program-only question. PX-2 says the underlying is words used by the entity during the time period, recognizes that a time period may be a specific event, and sets the payout criterion as the word being said by the entity during that period. It also tells us what does not count: text/captions alone, unofficial behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, and sound checks unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. Those exclusions matter, but none says that public event-linked remarks at the venue immediately before the formal program are categorically outside \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\\\"\\n\\nThird, the source-chain evidence now points to the disputed event and the Ronaldo utterance. PX-3 is an official White House page titled \\\"President Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing,\\\" dated December 5, 2025, with a full-video link and related World Cup Draw videos. That establishes an official White House event-video source for Trump's attendance at the World Cup Drawing. PX-4 is a public YouTube watch-page metadata capture for video ID Cb2yO0lLEnM, titled \\\"Trump Talks Cristiano Ronaldo at FIFA Draw -- 'He's a Great Person'.\\\" Its description states that at the FIFA World Cup Draw Ceremony, Trump shared a story about meeting Cristiano Ronaldo at the White House, said Ronaldo was a great person, and mentioned Ronaldo spoke with his son. PX-4 is not as strong as an official transcript, and plaintiff says that plainly. But it is admitted source content that directly links Trump, Cristiano Ronaldo, and the FIFA Draw ceremony.\\n\\nOn a preponderance standard, that is enough to defeat the challenged No resolution unless the defense can supply a clearer exclusion. The market did not ask only what Trump would say during the ball-pulling segment, during the televised main show, or after a particular formal start cue. It asked what he would say \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\\\" The terms recognize event-based periods and exclude particular non-event categories. A public remark at the Draw venue, tied to the Draw, is far closer to the event period than to a rehearsal, sound check, caption, or private backstage recording.\\n\\nThe defense's burden framing is too strict. Plaintiff must prove Yes by a preponderance; plaintiff need not prove that Kalshi drafted every boundary with perfect precision. Once the admitted sources show a Ronaldo mention in connection with the FIFA Draw ceremony, the remaining question is whether the rules clearly remove that event-linked remark from the counting period. They do not. Ambiguity in a mention market's event wording should not be converted into an unstated formal-program limitation after the fact.\\n\\nProvenance and gaps: plaintiff attempted to retrieve the live Kalshi page, official/full video, caption, and transcript. Kalshi returned a Vercel security checkpoint; the local browser tool was unavailable; Python pip/ensurepip was unavailable for yt-dlp; and direct YouTube caption/open paths were throttled or unavailable. That leaves PX-4 weaker than ideal, but not weightless. PX-3 supplies official event context, PX-4 supplies the Ronaldo-at-FIFA-Draw metadata, and PX-2 supplies the rule that event-linked spoken words count absent a clear exclusion.\\n\\nThe council should resolve the proposition Yes: the Ronaldo strike should have resolved Yes because the record more likely than not shows Trump said Ronaldo in public remarks tied to the FIFA World Cup Draw, and the market wording plus governing terms did not clearly exclude those remarks.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the merits record now shows why the challenged No resolution should stand.\\n\\nPlaintiff's best point is that Trump did say the word \\\"Ronaldo.\\\" The defense does not need to fight that. The question is whether he said it during the market's countable time period: \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\\\" On that decisive question, the strongest official sources favor No.\\n\\nThe admitted GovInfo transcript, DX-1, is an official Compilation of Presidential Documents capture. Its title is not merely \\\"World Cup Draw\\\" or \\\"FIFA ceremony.\\\" It is \\\"Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw.\\\" That same transcript contains the Ronaldo passages: Trump says he met Ronaldo at the White House, later says he was \\\"not Ronaldo or Messi,\\\" and the note identifies Ronaldo among the people referenced. So DX-1 is not adverse to the defense because it confirms the word; it is decisive because it places the word in an exchange with reporters prior to the Draw.\\n\\nDX-2 supplies the timing anchor. The official FIFA Final Draw page states that the Draw at the Kennedy Center commenced at 12:00 local time on Friday, December 5, 2025. DX-1 states that the President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the Kennedy Center. A reporter exchange at 11:13, officially titled as prior to a 12:00 draw, is not more likely than not \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\\\" It is before it.\\n\\nThat reading matches the governing PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION terms. PX-2 says the payout criterion is satisfied when the word is said by the entity during the specified time period. It recognizes event-based periods and permits the Exchange to specify what is included for an event. It also treats official presentation differently from adjacent material: pre-recorded content counts if presented as part of the official event presentation, while behind-the-scenes, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings do not count unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. The point is not that this reporter exchange was a rehearsal or sound check. The point is that the terms require a link to the time period itself. Plaintiff has supplied no market-specific language saying pre-event reporter availability, arrivals, or venue interviews count as part of the Draw.\\n\\nPlaintiff's new exhibits do not fill that gap. PX-3, the White House page capture, establishes that the White House had a page titled \\\"President Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing,\\\" but plaintiff's own capture says the embedded/full video was not captured. It does not prove that the Ronaldo words occurred inside the official draw program. PX-4 is weaker still: it is metadata from a nonofficial YouTube channel. It says the clip is about Trump talking Ronaldo at the FIFA Draw, but it is not a transcript, not an official source, and not an audio extraction. When a nonofficial clip description is weighed against GovInfo's official transcript title and FIFA's official start time, the official sources control.\\n\\nNor is this a burden-shifting problem. The proposition asks the council to overturn Kalshi's No because the market supposedly did not clearly exclude remarks immediately before the formal program. But the preponderance burden is on Yes. The record must show that the strike satisfied the payout criterion. The admitted terms do not say that ambiguous pre-event remarks count by default; they say the word must be said during the specified time period. Here, the best evidence identifies the remarks as prior to the Draw and before the official commencement time.\\n\\nProvenance also matters. DX-1 is an official government transcript with a correction note and an audio-incomplete caveat. That caveat affects stray inaudible portions, but it does not weaken the title, the 11:13 timing note, or the Ronaldo passages preserved in the transcript. DX-2 is an official FIFA timing source. Plaintiff's YouTube metadata may explain why the dispute arose, but it cannot outweigh those primary sources on timing and event classification.\\n\\nThe council should resolve the proposition against plaintiff. Trump said Ronaldo, but the record more likely shows he did so in a reporter exchange prior to the FIFA World Cup Draw, not during the countable Draw event. Kalshi's No resolution should be upheld.\\n\\nRebuttals:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, defendant’s new evidence narrows the case but does not end it.\\n\\nPlaintiff accepts the important parts of DX-1 and DX-2. The GovInfo transcript is official; it labels the item an exchange with reporters \\\"Prior to\\\" the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw; it places the exchange at 11:13 a.m. at the Kennedy Center; and the FIFA capture states the draw commenced at 12:00 local time. Plaintiff should not pretend those facts are weak.\\n\\nBut defendant asks those facts to do more than they do. The market was not drafted as \\\"what will Trump say after the official 12:00 commencement,\\\" \\\"during the televised draw program,\\\" or \\\"during the ball-drawing segment.\\\" PX-1 says the public market title was \\\"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\\" That is ordinary event language, and PX-2 recognizes event-based time periods while leaving room for the Exchange to specify what is included. The record still contains no market-specific exclusion for official venue press remarks immediately before the formal program.\\n\\nDX-1 also helps plaintiff on the facts defendant originally said were missing. It confirms the relevant spoken word. Trump said he met Ronaldo, that Ronaldo is great, and that he was not Ronaldo or Messi. It also places those remarks at the Kennedy Center in a FIFA World Cup Draw-centered exchange with reporters, not in an unrelated private dinner or stale campaign setting. The transcript’s own subject metadata includes the FIFA World Cup, the Kennedy Center, news media, presidential interviews, and soccer. That is event-linked public context.\\n\\nThe terms’ exclusions do not fit defendant’s leap. PX-2 excludes captions alone, rehearsals, sound checks, behind-the-scenes content, and unofficial recordings unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. DX-1 is not a rehearsal transcript. It is not a sound check. It is not merely a caption. It is an official presidential transcript of a public reporter exchange at the venue, released in the Compilation of Presidential Documents. If Kalshi meant to exclude that category because it occurred before a formal noon commencement, the market needed to say so clearly.\\n\\nSo the dispositive question remains one of market construction: does \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw\\\" clearly exclude public, official, event-site remarks immediately before the formal program? Defendant has proved \\\"prior to\\\" the formal draw start. Defendant has not proved a clear market rule that treats the broader Draw event as beginning only at 12:00 for mention purposes.\\n\\nUnder a preponderance standard, the record now confirms the Ronaldo utterance and confirms the FIFA Draw setting. The challenged No resolution should not be upheld by importing a narrow formal-program limitation that the market title and generic terms did not state.\\n\\nSurrebuttals:\\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff's rebuttal usefully clarifies the remaining dispute: plaintiff accepts that DX-1 is official, that it labels the relevant item an exchange with reporters \\\"Prior to\\\" the FIFA World Cup Draw, that the exchange occurred at 11:13 a.m. at the Kennedy Center, and that DX-2 places the official Draw commencement at 12:00 local time. Those concessions should decide the case.\\n\\nPlaintiff's answer is that the market did not say \\\"after 12:00,\\\" \\\"during the televised program,\\\" or \\\"during the ball-drawing segment.\\\" But the market also did not say \\\"at the venue before the Draw,\\\" \\\"in pre-event reporter exchanges,\\\" or \\\"in any public remarks connected to the Draw.\\\" The phrase it chose was \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\\\" Ordinary event language has a start, and the official FIFA source fixes that start at noon. Official GovInfo then fixes this exchange at 11:13 and titles it as prior to the Draw.\\n\\nThat is not a technicality. The terms require the word to be said during the specified time period. They recognize event-based periods and allow event-specific inclusions, but no admitted market-specific rule includes pre-event press access. Plaintiff's construction would turn any event-adjacent public remark into part of the event unless expressly excluded. That reverses the payout criterion. The claimant must show the word occurred during the time period; it is not enough to show the same venue, the same general topic, and official publication.\\n\\nPlaintiff says the exclusions do not fit because DX-1 is not a rehearsal, sound check, caption, or private backstage recording. Fair enough; the defense is not relying on those categories as labels. The defense relies on the affirmative timing requirement. A remark need not be a rehearsal to be outside the event. A reporter exchange officially described as prior to a noon event and occurring at 11:13 is outside because it is before the event began.\\n\\nThe record therefore proves the wrong fact for plaintiff. It proves Trump said Ronaldo, but in a pre-event reporter exchange. The proposition requires Yes only if those words count during the FIFA World Cup Draw. On this record, they do not. Kalshi's No resolution should be upheld.\\n\\nClosings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the final record leaves one legal question.\\n\\nThe easy factual question is resolved in plaintiff’s favor: Trump said \\\"Ronaldo.\\\" The official GovInfo transcript confirms it twice in substance: he said he met Ronaldo, praised him, and later said he was not Ronaldo or Messi. That is a spoken standalone use of the strike word. The record also places the remarks at the Kennedy Center in a FIFA World Cup Draw-centered reporter exchange. This was not an unrelated dinner, a caption, an AI voice, or a social-media paraphrase.\\n\\nThe hard point is timing. Defendant has the strongest evidence on the formal program boundary: GovInfo titled the exchange as \\\"Prior to\\\" the Draw, notes 11:13 a.m., and FIFA states the Final Draw commenced at 12:00 local time. Plaintiff does not ask the council to ignore that. The question is what the Kalshi market actually required.\\n\\nPX-1 did not say \\\"after 12:00.\\\" It did not say \\\"during the televised draw program\\\" or \\\"during the ball-drawing segment.\\\" It asked, in public market wording, \\\"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\\" PX-2’s generic terms recognize event-based periods and say the Exchange may specify what is included when a time period refers to an event. They also give specific exclusions: captions alone, rehearsals, sound checks, behind-the-scenes content, and unofficial recordings unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. None of those exclusions is this case. The GovInfo transcript is an official public presidential record of an event-site reporter exchange, not a rehearsal or sound check.\\n\\nDefendant’s best argument is that ordinary events have start times. True. But this market dispute is about public remarks at the venue immediately before the formal program, in the official context of the Draw, where the market and rules did not clearly define a noon-only boundary. If Kalshi wanted that narrower rule, it could have said so in the strike, the market title, or the event inclusion language. It did not.\\n\\nThe preponderance record therefore shows: Ronaldo was spoken; the remarks were public and officially documented; they were at the Kennedy Center in the FIFA World Cup Draw setting; and the governing market language did not clearly exclude that immediately-before-program event context. The challenged No resolution depends on importing a formal commencement limitation that is absent from the market packet.\\n\\nFor that reason, the Ronaldo strike should resolve Yes.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the closing record is narrow and concrete.\\n\\nEveryone now agrees on the easy fact: Trump said \\\"Ronaldo.\\\" The official GovInfo transcript proves that. But the proposition is not simply that Trump said the word somewhere near the FIFA World Cup Draw. The proposition asks you to overturn Kalshi's No because remarks immediately before the formal program should count under a market asking what Trump would say \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\\\" Plaintiff has not carried that burden.\\n\\nThe two strongest sources are official and aligned. GovInfo, in DX-1, titles the relevant document \\\"Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw.\\\" It notes that the President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the Kennedy Center. FIFA, in DX-2, states that the Final Draw commenced at 12:00 local time. Those facts are not peripheral. They answer the timing question: the Ronaldo words were in a reporter exchange before the Draw began.\\n\\nPlaintiff's closing says the market did not specify \\\"after 12:00,\\\" \\\"during the televised draw program,\\\" or \\\"during the ball-drawing segment.\\\" True, but that does not prove Yes. The market did specify \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\\\" The ordinary function of \\\"during\\\" is to define the event period, not to include anything public, official, and thematically related that happens beforehand. A 47-minute-before reporter exchange officially titled as prior to the Draw is outside that period unless the market or governing terms affirmatively include it. The record contains no such inclusion.\\n\\nThe governing terms reinforce that conclusion. They require the word to be said by the entity during the specified time period. They recognize event-based periods and allow the Exchange to specify event inclusions. They include official-presentation concepts for material presented as part of an event. But they do not say that pre-event press availability counts by default. Plaintiff's argument turns the absence of an exclusion into proof of inclusion. That is backwards under a preponderance standard.\\n\\nPlaintiff also leans on setting: Kennedy Center, FIFA World Cup subject matter, official transcript, public reporters. Those facts show why the issue is understandable. They do not move 11:13 into a 12:00 event. A source can be official and still describe something outside the event. Indeed, that is exactly what DX-1 does: it officially documents the remarks and officially labels them prior to the Draw.\\n\\nThe weaker evidence points the same way once weighed properly. The White House page capture does not include the video or transcript. The YouTube metadata is nonofficial and not an audio transcript. Neither overcomes GovInfo's title and timing note plus FIFA's commencement time.\\n\\nSo the final answer is simple: the word was spoken, but not during the countable event period shown by the best evidence. Plaintiff has not shown that Kalshi's No resolution was wrong. The council should reject the proposition and uphold No.\\n\\nExhibits:\\n[plaintiff] PX-1 Market page packet: Ronaldo strike and challenged No resolution\\nMarket URL: https://kalshi.com/markets/kxtrumpmentionb/trump-mention-b/kxtrumpmentionb-25dec06\\n\\nPublic market title: What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\n\\nContract family: PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION\\n\\nStrike at issue: Ronaldo\\n\\nChallenged resolution: No\\n\\nRequested resolution: Yes\\n\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-2 Governing PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION terms\\n                                         NEWMENTION\\n\\nScope: These rules shall apply to this contract.\\n\\nUnderlying: The Underlying for this Contract is words used by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nRevisions to the Underlying made after Expiration will not be accounted for in determining the\\nExpiration Value.\\n\\nSource Agency: The Source Agencies are \\u003csource\\u003e.\\n\\nType: The type of Contract is an Event Contract.\\n\\nIssuance: After the initial Contract, Contract iterations will be listed on an as-needed basis at\\nthe discretion of the Exchange and corresponding to the risk management needs of Members.\\n\\n\\u003centity\\u003e: \\u003centity\\u003e refers to the speaker, writer, performer, or communicator specified by the\\nExchange. This may include (but is not limited to): a specific named individual, multiple\\nindividuals specified using AND/OR logic, an individual identified by position or title, a group,\\nband, team or collective entity, a specified member or members of a group, an organization,\\ncompany, or institutional entity, or any combination of the aforementioned.\\n\\nWhen \\u003centity\\u003e is defined by a position or title, the Contract tracks whoever holds that position\\nduring \\u003ctime period\\u003e, even if the individual holding the position changes. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a\\nspecific named individual, the identity remains consistent throughout. Name changes (e.g.,\\nstage names, married names) do not create a new entity. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a group or\\norganization and the Contract does not specify particular members, any official\\ncommunication or statement by any member or designated spokesperson counts. When using\\nAND logic, all specified entities must independently say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e. When\\nusing OR logic, at least one of the specified entities must say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nThe Exchange may specify additional conditions such as “at least X members of” a group or\\n“the majority of” a group.\\n\\n\\u003csource\\u003e: \\u003csource\\u003e refers to a Source Agency or ordered collection of Source Agencies\\nspecified by the Exchange at the time of Contract listing, which will be incorporated into the\\nSource Agency hierarchy above and used to determine the occurrence of the Underlying.\\n\\u003csource\\u003e may refer to a singular agency, multiple agencies, an agency by distinguishing\\ncharacteristics, by category or type (e.g., “official government statistical body,” “primary wire\\nservice”), or any combination thereof. When multiple agencies are specified, they may be\\napplied in the hierarchical order designated by the Exchange if so specified, with the highest-\\nranked available and responsive agency taking precedence for purposes of determining the\\nExpiration Value. A lower-ranked agency shall only be consulted if all higher-ranked agencies\\nare unavailable, unresponsive, have not reported on the Underlying by the Expiration time, or\\nif the Exchange, in its sole discretion, determines that a higher-ranked agency’s reporting is\\nincomplete, erroneous, or otherwise insufficient to determine the Expiration Value. If \\u003csource\\u003e\\ndesignates multiple agencies without specifying a hierarchical order, the Exchange shall\\nresolve any conflict between reporting agencies at its sole discretion.\\n\\n\\u003cword\\u003e: \\u003cword\\u003e refers to the particular word or phrase potentially to be mentioned by\\n\\u003centity\\u003e. It may refer to a word being said a minimum number of times. It may also refer to\\none of multiple words/phrases, any of which are acceptable (e.g., “Doge/Dogecoin”).\\n\\f\\u003ctime period\\u003e: \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific range of time, event or discrete date and\\ntime specified by the Exchange. This may be defined by, but is not limited to: a specific event\\nor context (e.g., “during the State of the Union address”), exact dates or times, relative time\\nmarkers (e.g., “before July 1, 2027,” “in Q1 2026”), event-based periods (e.g., “during any\\ncampaign rally in October 2026,” “during the awards ceremony”), and broader intervals (e.g.,\\n“Q1–Q2 2027,” “January–March 2026”).\\n\\nUnless stated otherwise, “Between” is inclusive of both endpoints, while “before” and “after”\\nexclude the specified date. \\u003ctime period\\u003e may also refer to “Any” or “None”, to multiple dates\\n(even if non-consecutive), or to a singular and discrete date or time.\\n\\nWhen \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event (such as an address, speech, performance, or\\nbroadcast), the Exchange may specify what is included, including whether it includes both live\\nand pre-recorded segments (including whether advertisements are included). Where a\\ntimezone is not specified, ET is assumed.\\n\\n\\nPayout Criterion: The Payout Criterion for the Contract encompasses the Expiration Values that\\n\\u003cword\\u003e is said by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n\\n\\nThe word must appear as a distinct, standalone unit, not buried inside another word. Plural\\nand possessive noun forms count. Other grammatical changes (tense, conjugation, derivation)\\ndo not. If \\u003cword\\u003e appears separated from other words by a space or hyphen or in a\\ncompound form with a space or hyphen, it counts. If \\u003cword\\u003e is fused into a single\\nunhyphenated word, it does not count.\\n\\nIf \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled, and the market contains a\\nstrike stating “Event does not qualify/occur”, such a strike shall resolve “Yes” and all others\\n“No”. If \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled but such strikes are NOT\\nlisted, the Contracts will resolve to the last fair price determined at the discretion of the\\nExchange. If the event is postponed, and such a postponement is announced by the end of the\\nfollowing calendar day to be rescheduled to a time within 14 calendar days, the markets shall\\nremain open. If the event captured in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast, the\\nExchange may keep the market open for 24 hours for the release of an official recording.\\nFurther granular details on conditions for these Contracts is available below.\\n\\nAdditional clarification(s):\\n\\n     Possessive noun forms of \\u003cword\\u003e, plurals, and possessive plural noun forms are\\n     INCLUDED:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigrants” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Egg” → “eggs’ shells” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Russia” → “Russia’s” counts, “Russian” does not\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e exists only in adjective form, no plural form exists:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Economic” → “Economics” does not count (“Economic” is an adjective\\n          for which “Economics” is not a plural)\\n     Plural nouns occurring within proper nouns and noun phrases are included:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Cat” → “Cats the musical” counts\\n\\f    Grammatical variations beyond plurals/possessives are NOT included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigration” does NOT count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Run” → “Running” or “Ran” do NOT count\\n    When \\u003cword\\u003e specifies a plural form, the singular does NOT count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Veterans” → “Veteran” does NOT count\\n    Words that are spelled the same as the plural form of \\u003cword\\u003e (if such exists) but are\\n    themselves not a plural noun are included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Wind” → “Winds up the clock” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Border” → “The United States has strong borders” counts\\n    Open compounds (words separated by spaces) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fire station” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “couch” → “couch potato” counts\\n    Hyphenated compounds (words connected by hyphens) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Palestine” → “pro-Palestine” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fat” → “non-fat” counts\\n    Closed compounds (single word, no spaces/hyphens) do not count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire” does not count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firefighter” does not count\\n    Multi-word \\u003cword\\u003e in larger constructions: When \\u003cword\\u003e is a multi-word phrase\\n    appearing within a hyphenated construction, it counts only if \\u003cword\\u003e appears as a\\n    complete, unmodified element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “New York” → “New York-based” counts (complete element)\\n    Portmanteaus (words blended from two words where parts of each are combined) are\\n    NOT included unless the portmanteau clearly contains \\u003cword\\u003e as a distinct, unaltered\\n    element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “MAGA” → “MAGA-nificent” counts (MAGA appears as distinct element)\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “magnificent” → “MAGA-nificent” does NOT count (portmanteau blend)\\n\\nDictionary determination: Both the Merriam-Webster Dictionary (available online) AND the\\nOxford English Dictionary shall be used to determine compound type and/or conventional\\nspelling patterns. Inclusion in either dictionary as an open or hyphenated compound shall\\nsatisfy the Payout Criterion. If neither provides clarity (or the word is not included),\\ndetermination is based on whether written as single unit (closed/doesn’t count) vs. spaces or\\nhyphens (open or hyphenated/counts) and/or context and previous usage.\\n\\nPHONETIC EQUIVALENCIES\\n\\n    Homophones (same sound, different spelling) do not count:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “write” → “right” does not count\\n    Homonyms and homographs (same spelling) COUNT regardless of meaning or\\n    pronunciation:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “bass” → both “bass guitar” and “bass fishing” count\\n    Proper and common nouns are treated identically:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Apple” → both “Apple Inc.” and “apple” (fruit) count\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Will” → both “Will Smith” and “I will go” count\\n    Minor unintentional mispronunciations COUNT if context makes intent clear:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Mamdani” → “Mandani” counts\\n    Severe mispronunciations that make \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable do NOT count.\\n    Trademarked spellings do not count, even when pronounced identically, unless the word\\n\\fitself is the same:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “lift” → “Lyft” (pronounced “lift”) does not count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “uber” → “Uber” counts\\nWords with non-standard transliteration to English count within reason, provided they are\\nphonetically equivalent:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Zelensky” → any of “Zelenski,” “Zelenskii,” “Zelensky,” or “Zelenskiy”\\n      count if pronounced equivalently\\nContractions do not count for their constituent words unless otherwise explicitly specified\\nby the Exchange:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “not” → “won’t,” “can’t,” “don’t,” “isn’t” do not count\\nNumbers spoken as words COUNT, when spoken exactly (not part of a larger number):\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “five” → saying “five” or reading “$5” aloud as “five dollars” counts,\\n      saying “five hundred” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “410” → “four hundred ten”, “four one zero” or “four ten” counts\\nOrdinals COUNT when \\u003cword\\u003e is written numerically OR a phrase that includes a\\nnumber:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “January 6” → “January 6th” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “3” (written numerically) → “3rd” (spoken as “third”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Eight War” → “8 Wars” and “Eighth War” will count\\nCardinal and ordinal number words are distinct:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “one” → “first” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “first” → “one” does NOT count\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count when pronunciation or letter-by-letter spelling\\nmatches \\u003cword\\u003e:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “NASA” (pronounced “NAH-suh”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “N-A-S-A” (spelled out) counts\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count as \\u003cword\\u003e when pronounced as the full word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Doctor” → “Dr.” (pronounced “Doctor”) counts\\nExpanded forms of acronyms do NOT count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “AI” → “artificial intelligence” does not count\\nWords in foreign languages do NOT count unless they are perfect cognates with an\\nEnglish word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fuego” (Spanish) does NOT count\\nEnglish words within foreign sentences count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “policy” → “Nuestra policy es clara” counts\\n\\u003cword\\u003e in organization/company names counts:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Securities” → “Bank of America Securities” counts\\nWords in URLs, emails, handles, and hashtags (exclusive of domain structure, email\\nprovider or symbols) are treated as compounds when spoken as complete words, with the\\ntype of compound subject to aforementioned rules:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firestation.com” pronounced “fire station dot com” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire.com” pronounced “wildfire dot com” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “apple” → “apple.com” pronounced “apple dot com” does count\\n      When presented in URL, email, handle, or hashtag form, \\u003cword\\u003e shall be treated as\\n      a compound, not a multi-word word\\nSung, rapped, or poetic words COUNT if phonetically recognizable:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “money” → “moneyyy” (extended in rap) counts\\n      Extreme distortion making \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable does NOT count.\\nPhonetic alphabet spelling (“Foxtrot India Romeo Echo” for “FIRE”) does NOT count.\\n\\fCANCELLATIONS AND DELAYS\\n\\n   The Exchange may list an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike for any Contract. If listed,\\n   such a strike refers to the structural conditions of the market, and is NOT adjudicated as a\\n   \\u003cword\\u003e needing to be said by or validated by having been said by \\u003centity\\u003e. If listed, this\\n   strike resolves to “Yes” whenever the event fails to occur or qualify under the Payout\\n   Criterion, or any other circumstance prevents normal resolution.\\n   If no such strike is listed, and \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, the following rules\\n   apply if the event is cancelled, postponed, rescheduled, or materially altered (including\\n   being closed to press) such that no video is released within one calendar day of the\\n   original start time of the event:\\n         If the event is cancelled, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price determined in\\n         the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         If the event is postponed or rescheduled, the outcome depends on whether a new\\n         date is publicly announced within one calendar day (i.e. if the event was scheduled\\n         to begin on Monday, any time up to 11:59PM on Tuesday falls within this period) of\\n         the originally scheduled start time:\\n               If no new date is announced within one calendar day, the Contract will resolve\\n               to the last fair price determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n               If a new date is announced within one calendar day, the outcome depends on\\n               when the rescheduled event is set to occur:\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls within fourteen (14) calendar days of the\\n                     originally scheduled date, the Contract shall remain open and \\u003cword\\u003e\\n                     stated during the rescheduled event will count.\\n                           The fourteen-day window begins at 12:00 AM ET on the originally\\n                           scheduled date and ends at 11:59 PM ET fourteen days later, unless\\n                           an alternate timezone is explicitly specified.\\n                           Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the State of the Union on January\\n                           15, 2026” rescheduled to January 20, 2026 → words spoken during\\n                           the rescheduled address count.\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls more than fourteen (14) calendar days after\\n                     the originally scheduled date, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price\\n                     determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         Any Contract that cannot be resolved through the Source Agency hierarchy will\\n         instead be settled at the Last Fair Price. The Exchange will disclose the methodology\\n         used to determine the Last Fair Price (e.g., Last Traded Price, Time-Weighted\\n         Average Price) at the time of Issuance.\\n         If an event begins but is interrupted, abbreviated, or ends prematurely, words\\n         stated by \\u003centity\\u003e during the portion of the event that did occur will count and the\\n         market will otherwise resolve.\\n   If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window but the venue, format, or medium\\n   changes (e.g., moved to a different location, changed from in-person to virtual (with the\\n   exception of being closed to press)), words stated during the event will count.\\n   Special condition: Across both cases, whether an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike is\\n   listed or not, if the event specified as or in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast (or\\n   relayed as such) but the live stream/broadcast does not occur, the Exchange will instead\\n   use an officially released recording as the Underlying, and may delay resolution by up to\\n   one calendar day to allow for the release of such a recording.\\n\\f          If partial snippets are released, Contracts on words that do not appear will be\\n          resolved to last fair price, and Contracts on those that do will be resolved to “Yes”.\\n          If no recording is released, the relevant outcomes triggered by the\\n          presence/absence of an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike shall occur as outlined\\n          above.\\n\\nTECHNICAL DETAILS (UNLESS OTHERWISE SPECIFIED)\\n\\n     When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, pre-recorded content broadcast,\\n     streamed, or published as part of that event is included if presented as part of the official\\n     presentation.\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the concert” with pre-recorded video interlude\\n          where entity speaks → words from interlude count\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the television appearance” with pre-taped\\n          segment aired during broadcast → words from segment count\\n     Behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are NOT\\n     included unless officially broadcast or published as part of \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n     Subtitles and captions that display \\u003cword\\u003e on screen but are not spoken aloud by\\n     \\u003centity\\u003e do NOT count.\\n     Sign language interpretation or usage by entity does NOT count as saying \\u003cword\\u003e unless\\n     the Contract explicitly specifies that sign language counts.\\n     Text that entity displays on screen (presentation slides, teleprompter visible to audience,\\n     signatures) does NOT count unless entity reads it aloud.\\n     Content generated by AI, deepfakes, or synthetic voice technology impersonating entity\\n     does NOT count unless the synthetic content is officially commissioned, authorized, or\\n     published by entity, OR the Contract explicitly specifies that AI-generated content counts.\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e is muted due to technical failure or censorship it shall not count unless\\n     corroborating contextual evidence (including surrounding speech, or an official\\n     uncensored recording or transcript) confirms that \\u003centity\\u003e specifically uttered \\u003cword\\u003e\\n     during the muted period.\\n\\nMinimum Tick: The Minimum Tick size for the Contract shall be $0.01.\\n\\nPosition Accountability Level: The Position Accountability Level for the Contract shall be\\n$25,000 per strike, per Member.\\n\\nLast Trading Date: The Last Trading Date of the Contract will be the Expiration Date. The Last\\nTrading Time will be the Expiration time.\\n\\nSettlement Date: The Settlement Date of the Contract shall be no later than the day after the\\nExpiration Date, unless the Market Outcome is under review pursuant to Rule 7.1.\\n\\nExpiration Date: When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event: The latest Expiration Date of\\nthe Contract shall be fourteen (14) calendar days after the originally scheduled date of the\\nevent. If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window, expiration will be moved to an\\nearlier date and time in accordance with Rule 7.2. When \\u003ctime period\\u003e is defined by specific\\ndates: The latest Expiration Date of the Contract shall be two weeks after the end of \\u003ctime\\nperiod\\u003e. If an event described in the Payout Criterion occurs and a consensus has been\\nreached on all terms, then expiration will be moved to an earlier date and time in accordance\\nwith Rule 7.2.\\n\\fExpiration time: The Expiration time of the Contract shall be 10:00 AM ET.\\n\\nSettlement Value: The Settlement Value for this Contract is $1.00.\\n\\nExpiration Value: The Expiration Value is the value of the Underlying as documented by the\\nSource Agency on the Expiration Date at the Expiration time.\\n\\nContingencies: Before Settlement, Kalshi may, at its sole discretion, initiate the Market\\nOutcome Review Process pursuant to Rule 7.1 of the Rulebook. If an Expiration Value cannot\\nbe determined on the Expiration Date, Kalshi has the right to determine payouts pursuant to\\nRule 7.1 in the Rulebook.\\n\\f\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-3 Official White House World Cup Drawing video page capture\\nSource capture from official White House page https://www.whitehouse.gov/videos/president-trump-attends-the-fifa-world-cup-drawing/\\nRetrieval: 2026-06-29T21:52:12Z via OpenClaw web_fetch and web.open.\\n\\nVisible page facts captured:\\n- Page title: President Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing\\n- Date shown on page: December 5, 2025\\n- Page section: Videos\\n- The page contains a link labeled View Full Video to Instagram.\\n- Related video listed: FIFA World Cup 2026 Draw at The Kennedy Center, duration 00:45, dated December 6, 2025.\\n- Related video listed: FIFA World Cup Drawing Announced to Take Place at The Kennedy Center, duration 00:56, dated August 23, 2025.\\n- Related video listed: President Trump on the 2026 FIFA World Cup, duration 01:22, dated May 6, 2025.\\n\\nRelevant extracted lines from web.open capture:\\nL142: Videos\\nL143: # President Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing\\nL145: December 5, 2025\\nL133: ... View Full Video [instagram.com] ...\\nL151: FIFA World Cup 2026 Draw at The Kennedy Center\\nL153: December 6, 2025\\nL167-L170: President Trump on the 2026 FIFA World Cup, May 6, 2025\\n\\nNotes on capture limits: readability extraction returned minimal content, so the above preserves visible lines from the page capture. The embedded/full video itself was not captured in this item.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-4 YouTube metadata capture for Ronaldo-at-FIFA-Draw clip\\nSource capture: YouTube watch page https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Cb2yO0lLEnM\\nVideo ID: Cb2yO0lLEnM\\nRetrieval: 2026-06-29T21:53:00Z via web search and curl of the YouTube watch page.\\n\\nCaptured title / page metadata:\\n- Title shown in search and page metadata: Trump Talks Cristiano Ronaldo at FIFA Draw — ‘He’s a Great Person’\\n- Channel shown in page metadata: interestingText You / @InterestingTextYou\\n- Subscriber count shown in page metadata at capture: about 10.3K subscribers\\n\\nCaptured description text from YouTube page metadata:\\n\\\"Trump Talks Cristiano Ronaldo at FIFA Draw — ‘He’s a Great Person’\\n\\nAt the FIFA World Cup Draw Ceremony, Donald Trump shared a story about meeting Cristiano Ronaldo at the White House. Trump said Ronaldo was “a great person” and even mentioned that Ronaldo spoke with his son about soccer during the visit.\\n\\nThis unexpected crossover between world politics and one of the biggest global sports stars quickly caught viewers' attention.\\n\\nTrump FIFA Draw\\nDonald Trump FIFA World Cup\\nTrump Cristiano Ronaldo\\nCristiano Ronaldo Trump meeting\\nFIFA World Cup draw 2026\\nRonaldo White House visit\\nTrump soccer comments\\nWorld Cup trending 2025\\nsports politics crossover\\nCristiano Ronaldo story\\nDonald Trump viral moment\\nFIFA draw ceremony Trump\\nWorld Cup 2026 news\\nRonaldo fan reaction\\npolitical celebrity moments\\nviral sports clips 2025\\nFIFA draw highlights\\nTrump speech FIFA\\nglobal sports news\\\"\\n\\nCapture limits and provenance caveat: direct video/caption extraction was attempted but YouTube transcript/open paths were throttled or unavailable in this environment. This item preserves the public watch-page metadata and description, not an independently extracted audio transcript. It is not an official White House or FIFA source.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-1 GovInfo official transcript: remarks prior to FIFA World Cup Draw\\nSource: GovInfo, Compilation of Presidential Documents, DCPD202501162\\nURL retrieved: https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/DCPD-202501162/html/DCPD-202501162.htm\\nRetrieval time: 2026-06-29T22:00:00Z\\nLocal captured HTML size/hash: 51,571 bytes; SHA-256 eadbceeecf3e94f5bd423bcb8e8511165fdc7265dd8c1e025870c2e8f34dfd99\\n\\nMaterial captured text from official GovInfo HTML/web.open:\\n\\nAdministration of Donald J. Trump, 2025\\n\\nTitle: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\nDate: December 5, 2025\\n\\nOpening note: [The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\\n\\nExcerpt - The President's Interest in Soccer (web.open lines 196-203):\\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\\\"football,\\\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\\n\\nExcerpt - The President's Interest in Soccer (web.open lines 322-329):\\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\\nThe President. But they have a little more speed. But no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\\n\\nTiming/context note (web.open lines 461-462):\\nNOTE: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. In his remarks, he referred to Trey Yingst, chief foreign correspondent, Fox News Channel; Cristiano Ronaldo, forward for Saudi Pro League club Al-Nass and Portugal's national soccer team; and Lionel Messi, forward for Major League Soccer club Inter Miami and Argentina's national team. A reporter referred to New York State Attorney General Letitia James.\\nThe transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\n\\nDocument category/location/name/subject metadata (web.open lines 463-468):\\nCategories: Interviews With the News Media: Exchanges with reporters, Washington, DC.\\nLocations: Washington, DC.\\nNames include: Cristiano Ronaldo and Lionel Messi.\\nSubjects include: Federation Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) World Cup; John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts; News media, Presidential interviews; Soccer.\\nDCPD Number: DCPD202501162.\\n\\nCapture limits: This item is a focused text capture of the material official transcript title, Ronaldo excerpts, timing/correction note, and metadata. It is not a full video or audio artifact. The official transcript itself notes some portions could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-2 FIFA official Final Draw start-time capture\\nSource: FIFA official page, FIFA World Cup 2026 Final Draw\\nURL: https://www.fifa.com/en/tournaments/mens/worldcup/canadamexicousa2026/live-draw\\nRetrieval time: 2026-06-29T22:01:00Z\\n\\nMaterial captured text from web search/open result:\\n- Page title/source: FIFA World Cup 2026™ Final Draw\\n- The draw takes place at the Kennedy Center in Washington DC, USA.\\n- The draw commences at 12:00 local time (17:00 UTC) on Friday 5 December 2025.\\n\\nCapture limits: This is a focused text capture of the official FIFA page timing statement located by web search. It is not a video capture of the draw ceremony.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-3 Governing PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION terms\\n                                         NEWMENTION\\n\\nScope: These rules shall apply to this contract.\\n\\nUnderlying: The Underlying for this Contract is words used by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nRevisions to the Underlying made after Expiration will not be accounted for in determining the\\nExpiration Value.\\n\\nSource Agency: The Source Agencies are \\u003csource\\u003e.\\n\\nType: The type of Contract is an Event Contract.\\n\\nIssuance: After the initial Contract, Contract iterations will be listed on an as-needed basis at\\nthe discretion of the Exchange and corresponding to the risk management needs of Members.\\n\\n\\u003centity\\u003e: \\u003centity\\u003e refers to the speaker, writer, performer, or communicator specified by the\\nExchange. This may include (but is not limited to): a specific named individual, multiple\\nindividuals specified using AND/OR logic, an individual identified by position or title, a group,\\nband, team or collective entity, a specified member or members of a group, an organization,\\ncompany, or institutional entity, or any combination of the aforementioned.\\n\\nWhen \\u003centity\\u003e is defined by a position or title, the Contract tracks whoever holds that position\\nduring \\u003ctime period\\u003e, even if the individual holding the position changes. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a\\nspecific named individual, the identity remains consistent throughout. Name changes (e.g.,\\nstage names, married names) do not create a new entity. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a group or\\norganization and the Contract does not specify particular members, any official\\ncommunication or statement by any member or designated spokesperson counts. When using\\nAND logic, all specified entities must independently say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e. When\\nusing OR logic, at least one of the specified entities must say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nThe Exchange may specify additional conditions such as “at least X members of” a group or\\n“the majority of” a group.\\n\\n\\u003csource\\u003e: \\u003csource\\u003e refers to a Source Agency or ordered collection of Source Agencies\\nspecified by the Exchange at the time of Contract listing, which will be incorporated into the\\nSource Agency hierarchy above and used to determine the occurrence of the Underlying.\\n\\u003csource\\u003e may refer to a singular agency, multiple agencies, an agency by distinguishing\\ncharacteristics, by category or type (e.g., “official government statistical body,” “primary wire\\nservice”), or any combination thereof. When multiple agencies are specified, they may be\\napplied in the hierarchical order designated by the Exchange if so specified, with the highest-\\nranked available and responsive agency taking precedence for purposes of determining the\\nExpiration Value. A lower-ranked agency shall only be consulted if all higher-ranked agencies\\nare unavailable, unresponsive, have not reported on the Underlying by the Expiration time, or\\nif the Exchange, in its sole discretion, determines that a higher-ranked agency’s reporting is\\nincomplete, erroneous, or otherwise insufficient to determine the Expiration Value. If \\u003csource\\u003e\\ndesignates multiple agencies without specifying a hierarchical order, the Exchange shall\\nresolve any conflict between reporting agencies at its sole discretion.\\n\\n\\u003cword\\u003e: \\u003cword\\u003e refers to the particular word or phrase potentially to be mentioned by\\n\\u003centity\\u003e. It may refer to a word being said a minimum number of times. It may also refer to\\none of multiple words/phrases, any of which are acceptable (e.g., “Doge/Dogecoin”).\\n\\f\\u003ctime period\\u003e: \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific range of time, event or discrete date and\\ntime specified by the Exchange. This may be defined by, but is not limited to: a specific event\\nor context (e.g., “during the State of the Union address”), exact dates or times, relative time\\nmarkers (e.g., “before July 1, 2027,” “in Q1 2026”), event-based periods (e.g., “during any\\ncampaign rally in October 2026,” “during the awards ceremony”), and broader intervals (e.g.,\\n“Q1–Q2 2027,” “January–March 2026”).\\n\\nUnless stated otherwise, “Between” is inclusive of both endpoints, while “before” and “after”\\nexclude the specified date. \\u003ctime period\\u003e may also refer to “Any” or “None”, to multiple dates\\n(even if non-consecutive), or to a singular and discrete date or time.\\n\\nWhen \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event (such as an address, speech, performance, or\\nbroadcast), the Exchange may specify what is included, including whether it includes both live\\nand pre-recorded segments (including whether advertisements are included). Where a\\ntimezone is not specified, ET is assumed.\\n\\n\\nPayout Criterion: The Payout Criterion for the Contract encompasses the Expiration Values that\\n\\u003cword\\u003e is said by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n\\n\\nThe word must appear as a distinct, standalone unit, not buried inside another word. Plural\\nand possessive noun forms count. Other grammatical changes (tense, conjugation, derivation)\\ndo not. If \\u003cword\\u003e appears separated from other words by a space or hyphen or in a\\ncompound form with a space or hyphen, it counts. If \\u003cword\\u003e is fused into a single\\nunhyphenated word, it does not count.\\n\\nIf \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled, and the market contains a\\nstrike stating “Event does not qualify/occur”, such a strike shall resolve “Yes” and all others\\n“No”. If \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled but such strikes are NOT\\nlisted, the Contracts will resolve to the last fair price determined at the discretion of the\\nExchange. If the event is postponed, and such a postponement is announced by the end of the\\nfollowing calendar day to be rescheduled to a time within 14 calendar days, the markets shall\\nremain open. If the event captured in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast, the\\nExchange may keep the market open for 24 hours for the release of an official recording.\\nFurther granular details on conditions for these Contracts is available below.\\n\\nAdditional clarification(s):\\n\\n     Possessive noun forms of \\u003cword\\u003e, plurals, and possessive plural noun forms are\\n     INCLUDED:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigrants” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Egg” → “eggs’ shells” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Russia” → “Russia’s” counts, “Russian” does not\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e exists only in adjective form, no plural form exists:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Economic” → “Economics” does not count (“Economic” is an adjective\\n          for which “Economics” is not a plural)\\n     Plural nouns occurring within proper nouns and noun phrases are included:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Cat” → “Cats the musical” counts\\n\\f    Grammatical variations beyond plurals/possessives are NOT included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigration” does NOT count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Run” → “Running” or “Ran” do NOT count\\n    When \\u003cword\\u003e specifies a plural form, the singular does NOT count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Veterans” → “Veteran” does NOT count\\n    Words that are spelled the same as the plural form of \\u003cword\\u003e (if such exists) but are\\n    themselves not a plural noun are included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Wind” → “Winds up the clock” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Border” → “The United States has strong borders” counts\\n    Open compounds (words separated by spaces) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fire station” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “couch” → “couch potato” counts\\n    Hyphenated compounds (words connected by hyphens) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Palestine” → “pro-Palestine” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fat” → “non-fat” counts\\n    Closed compounds (single word, no spaces/hyphens) do not count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire” does not count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firefighter” does not count\\n    Multi-word \\u003cword\\u003e in larger constructions: When \\u003cword\\u003e is a multi-word phrase\\n    appearing within a hyphenated construction, it counts only if \\u003cword\\u003e appears as a\\n    complete, unmodified element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “New York” → “New York-based” counts (complete element)\\n    Portmanteaus (words blended from two words where parts of each are combined) are\\n    NOT included unless the portmanteau clearly contains \\u003cword\\u003e as a distinct, unaltered\\n    element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “MAGA” → “MAGA-nificent” counts (MAGA appears as distinct element)\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “magnificent” → “MAGA-nificent” does NOT count (portmanteau blend)\\n\\nDictionary determination: Both the Merriam-Webster Dictionary (available online) AND the\\nOxford English Dictionary shall be used to determine compound type and/or conventional\\nspelling patterns. Inclusion in either dictionary as an open or hyphenated compound shall\\nsatisfy the Payout Criterion. If neither provides clarity (or the word is not included),\\ndetermination is based on whether written as single unit (closed/doesn’t count) vs. spaces or\\nhyphens (open or hyphenated/counts) and/or context and previous usage.\\n\\nPHONETIC EQUIVALENCIES\\n\\n    Homophones (same sound, different spelling) do not count:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “write” → “right” does not count\\n    Homonyms and homographs (same spelling) COUNT regardless of meaning or\\n    pronunciation:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “bass” → both “bass guitar” and “bass fishing” count\\n    Proper and common nouns are treated identically:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Apple” → both “Apple Inc.” and “apple” (fruit) count\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Will” → both “Will Smith” and “I will go” count\\n    Minor unintentional mispronunciations COUNT if context makes intent clear:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Mamdani” → “Mandani” counts\\n    Severe mispronunciations that make \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable do NOT count.\\n    Trademarked spellings do not count, even when pronounced identically, unless the word\\n\\fitself is the same:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “lift” → “Lyft” (pronounced “lift”) does not count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “uber” → “Uber” counts\\nWords with non-standard transliteration to English count within reason, provided they are\\nphonetically equivalent:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Zelensky” → any of “Zelenski,” “Zelenskii,” “Zelensky,” or “Zelenskiy”\\n      count if pronounced equivalently\\nContractions do not count for their constituent words unless otherwise explicitly specified\\nby the Exchange:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “not” → “won’t,” “can’t,” “don’t,” “isn’t” do not count\\nNumbers spoken as words COUNT, when spoken exactly (not part of a larger number):\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “five” → saying “five” or reading “$5” aloud as “five dollars” counts,\\n      saying “five hundred” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “410” → “four hundred ten”, “four one zero” or “four ten” counts\\nOrdinals COUNT when \\u003cword\\u003e is written numerically OR a phrase that includes a\\nnumber:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “January 6” → “January 6th” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “3” (written numerically) → “3rd” (spoken as “third”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Eight War” → “8 Wars” and “Eighth War” will count\\nCardinal and ordinal number words are distinct:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “one” → “first” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “first” → “one” does NOT count\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count when pronunciation or letter-by-letter spelling\\nmatches \\u003cword\\u003e:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “NASA” (pronounced “NAH-suh”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “N-A-S-A” (spelled out) counts\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count as \\u003cword\\u003e when pronounced as the full word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Doctor” → “Dr.” (pronounced “Doctor”) counts\\nExpanded forms of acronyms do NOT count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “AI” → “artificial intelligence” does not count\\nWords in foreign languages do NOT count unless they are perfect cognates with an\\nEnglish word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fuego” (Spanish) does NOT count\\nEnglish words within foreign sentences count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “policy” → “Nuestra policy es clara” counts\\n\\u003cword\\u003e in organization/company names counts:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Securities” → “Bank of America Securities” counts\\nWords in URLs, emails, handles, and hashtags (exclusive of domain structure, email\\nprovider or symbols) are treated as compounds when spoken as complete words, with the\\ntype of compound subject to aforementioned rules:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firestation.com” pronounced “fire station dot com” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire.com” pronounced “wildfire dot com” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “apple” → “apple.com” pronounced “apple dot com” does count\\n      When presented in URL, email, handle, or hashtag form, \\u003cword\\u003e shall be treated as\\n      a compound, not a multi-word word\\nSung, rapped, or poetic words COUNT if phonetically recognizable:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “money” → “moneyyy” (extended in rap) counts\\n      Extreme distortion making \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable does NOT count.\\nPhonetic alphabet spelling (“Foxtrot India Romeo Echo” for “FIRE”) does NOT count.\\n\\fCANCELLATIONS AND DELAYS\\n\\n   The Exchange may list an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike for any Contract. If listed,\\n   such a strike refers to the structural conditions of the market, and is NOT adjudicated as a\\n   \\u003cword\\u003e needing to be said by or validated by having been said by \\u003centity\\u003e. If listed, this\\n   strike resolves to “Yes” whenever the event fails to occur or qualify under the Payout\\n   Criterion, or any other circumstance prevents normal resolution.\\n   If no such strike is listed, and \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, the following rules\\n   apply if the event is cancelled, postponed, rescheduled, or materially altered (including\\n   being closed to press) such that no video is released within one calendar day of the\\n   original start time of the event:\\n         If the event is cancelled, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price determined in\\n         the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         If the event is postponed or rescheduled, the outcome depends on whether a new\\n         date is publicly announced within one calendar day (i.e. if the event was scheduled\\n         to begin on Monday, any time up to 11:59PM on Tuesday falls within this period) of\\n         the originally scheduled start time:\\n               If no new date is announced within one calendar day, the Contract will resolve\\n               to the last fair price determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n               If a new date is announced within one calendar day, the outcome depends on\\n               when the rescheduled event is set to occur:\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls within fourteen (14) calendar days of the\\n                     originally scheduled date, the Contract shall remain open and \\u003cword\\u003e\\n                     stated during the rescheduled event will count.\\n                           The fourteen-day window begins at 12:00 AM ET on the originally\\n                           scheduled date and ends at 11:59 PM ET fourteen days later, unless\\n                           an alternate timezone is explicitly specified.\\n                           Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the State of the Union on January\\n                           15, 2026” rescheduled to January 20, 2026 → words spoken during\\n                           the rescheduled address count.\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls more than fourteen (14) calendar days after\\n                     the originally scheduled date, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price\\n                     determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         Any Contract that cannot be resolved through the Source Agency hierarchy will\\n         instead be settled at the Last Fair Price. The Exchange will disclose the methodology\\n         used to determine the Last Fair Price (e.g., Last Traded Price, Time-Weighted\\n         Average Price) at the time of Issuance.\\n         If an event begins but is interrupted, abbreviated, or ends prematurely, words\\n         stated by \\u003centity\\u003e during the portion of the event that did occur will count and the\\n         market will otherwise resolve.\\n   If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window but the venue, format, or medium\\n   changes (e.g., moved to a different location, changed from in-person to virtual (with the\\n   exception of being closed to press)), words stated during the event will count.\\n   Special condition: Across both cases, whether an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike is\\n   listed or not, if the event specified as or in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast (or\\n   relayed as such) but the live stream/broadcast does not occur, the Exchange will instead\\n   use an officially released recording as the Underlying, and may delay resolution by up to\\n   one calendar day to allow for the release of such a recording.\\n\\f          If partial snippets are released, Contracts on words that do not appear will be\\n          resolved to last fair price, and Contracts on those that do will be resolved to “Yes”.\\n          If no recording is released, the relevant outcomes triggered by the\\n          presence/absence of an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike shall occur as outlined\\n          above.\\n\\nTECHNICAL DETAILS (UNLESS OTHERWISE SPECIFIED)\\n\\n     When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, pre-recorded content broadcast,\\n     streamed, or published as part of that event is included if presented as part of the official\\n     presentation.\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the concert” with pre-recorded video interlude\\n          where entity speaks → words from interlude count\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the television appearance” with pre-taped\\n          segment aired during broadcast → words from segment count\\n     Behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are NOT\\n     included unless officially broadcast or published as part of \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n     Subtitles and captions that display \\u003cword\\u003e on screen but are not spoken aloud by\\n     \\u003centity\\u003e do NOT count.\\n     Sign language interpretation or usage by entity does NOT count as saying \\u003cword\\u003e unless\\n     the Contract explicitly specifies that sign language counts.\\n     Text that entity displays on screen (presentation slides, teleprompter visible to audience,\\n     signatures) does NOT count unless entity reads it aloud.\\n     Content generated by AI, deepfakes, or synthetic voice technology impersonating entity\\n     does NOT count unless the synthetic content is officially commissioned, authorized, or\\n     published by entity, OR the Contract explicitly specifies that AI-generated content counts.\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e is muted due to technical failure or censorship it shall not count unless\\n     corroborating contextual evidence (including surrounding speech, or an official\\n     uncensored recording or transcript) confirms that \\u003centity\\u003e specifically uttered \\u003cword\\u003e\\n     during the muted period.\\n\\nMinimum Tick: The Minimum Tick size for the Contract shall be $0.01.\\n\\nPosition Accountability Level: The Position Accountability Level for the Contract shall be\\n$25,000 per strike, per Member.\\n\\nLast Trading Date: The Last Trading Date of the Contract will be the Expiration Date. The Last\\nTrading Time will be the Expiration time.\\n\\nSettlement Date: The Settlement Date of the Contract shall be no later than the day after the\\nExpiration Date, unless the Market Outcome is under review pursuant to Rule 7.1.\\n\\nExpiration Date: When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event: The latest Expiration Date of\\nthe Contract shall be fourteen (14) calendar days after the originally scheduled date of the\\nevent. If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window, expiration will be moved to an\\nearlier date and time in accordance with Rule 7.2. When \\u003ctime period\\u003e is defined by specific\\ndates: The latest Expiration Date of the Contract shall be two weeks after the end of \\u003ctime\\nperiod\\u003e. If an event described in the Payout Criterion occurs and a consensus has been\\nreached on all terms, then expiration will be moved to an earlier date and time in accordance\\nwith Rule 7.2.\\n\\fExpiration time: The Expiration time of the Contract shall be 10:00 AM ET.\\n\\nSettlement Value: The Settlement Value for this Contract is $1.00.\\n\\nExpiration Value: The Expiration Value is the value of the Underlying as documented by the\\nSource Agency on the Expiration Date at the Expiration time.\\n\\nContingencies: Before Settlement, Kalshi may, at its sole discretion, initiate the Market\\nOutcome Review Process pursuant to Rule 7.1 of the Rulebook. If an Expiration Value cannot\\nbe determined on the Expiration Date, Kalshi has the right to determine payouts pursuant to\\nRule 7.1 in the Rulebook.\\n\\f\\n\\n[defendant] DX-4 Market packet: Ronaldo strike and challenged No resolution\\nMarket URL: https://kalshi.com/markets/kxtrumpmentionb/trump-mention-b/kxtrumpmentionb-25dec06\\n\\nPublic market title: What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\n\\nContract family: PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION\\n\\nStrike at issue: Ronaldo\\n\\nChallenged resolution: No\\n\\nRequested resolution: Yes\\n\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R1 GovInfo transcript confirming Ronaldo utterances and Kennedy Center/FIFA Draw context\\nSource: GovInfo, Compilation of Presidential Documents, DCPD202501162\\nURL retrieved: https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/DCPD-202501162/html/DCPD-202501162.htm\\nRetrieval time: 2026-06-29T22:00:00Z\\nLocal captured HTML size/hash: 51,571 bytes; SHA-256 eadbceeecf3e94f5bd423bcb8e8511165fdc7265dd8c1e025870c2e8f34dfd99\\n\\nMaterial captured text from official GovInfo HTML/web.open:\\n\\nAdministration of Donald J. Trump, 2025\\n\\nTitle: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\nDate: December 5, 2025\\n\\nOpening note: [The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\\n\\nExcerpt - The President's Interest in Soccer (web.open lines 196-203):\\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\\\"football,\\\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\\n\\nExcerpt - The President's Interest in Soccer (web.open lines 322-329):\\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\\nThe President. But they have a little more speed. But no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\\n\\nTiming/context note (web.open lines 461-462):\\nNOTE: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. In his remarks, he referred to Trey Yingst, chief foreign correspondent, Fox News Channel; Cristiano Ronaldo, forward for Saudi Pro League club Al-Nass and Portugal's national soccer team; and Lionel Messi, forward for Major League Soccer club Inter Miami and Argentina's national team. A reporter referred to New York State Attorney General Letitia James.\\nThe transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\n\\nDocument category/location/name/subject metadata (web.open lines 463-468):\\nCategories: Interviews With the News Media: Exchanges with reporters, Washington, DC.\\nLocations: Washington, DC.\\nNames include: Cristiano Ronaldo and Lionel Messi.\\nSubjects include: Federation Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) World Cup; John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts; News media, Presidential interviews; Soccer.\\nDCPD Number: DCPD202501162.\\n\\nCapture limits: This item is a focused text capture of the material official transcript title, Ronaldo excerpts, timing/correction note, and metadata. It is not a full video or audio artifact. The official transcript itself notes some portions could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R2 FIFA timing capture showing formal commencement time but not market-specific exclusion\\nSource: FIFA official page, FIFA World Cup 2026 Final Draw\\nURL: https://www.fifa.com/en/tournaments/mens/worldcup/canadamexicousa2026/live-draw\\nRetrieval time: 2026-06-29T22:01:00Z\\n\\nMaterial captured text from web search/open result:\\n- Page title/source: FIFA World Cup 2026™ Final Draw\\n- The draw takes place at the Kennedy Center in Washington DC, USA.\\n- The draw commences at 12:00 local time (17:00 UTC) on Friday 5 December 2025.\\n\\nCapture limits: This is a focused text capture of the official FIFA page timing statement located by web search. It is not a video capture of the draw ceremony.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R3 Event-period terms and exclusions\\n                                         NEWMENTION\\n\\nScope: These rules shall apply to this contract.\\n\\nUnderlying: The Underlying for this Contract is words used by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nRevisions to the Underlying made after Expiration will not be accounted for in determining the\\nExpiration Value.\\n\\nSource Agency: The Source Agencies are \\u003csource\\u003e.\\n\\nType: The type of Contract is an Event Contract.\\n\\nIssuance: After the initial Contract, Contract iterations will be listed on an as-needed basis at\\nthe discretion of the Exchange and corresponding to the risk management needs of Members.\\n\\n\\u003centity\\u003e: \\u003centity\\u003e refers to the speaker, writer, performer, or communicator specified by the\\nExchange. This may include (but is not limited to): a specific named individual, multiple\\nindividuals specified using AND/OR logic, an individual identified by position or title, a group,\\nband, team or collective entity, a specified member or members of a group, an organization,\\ncompany, or institutional entity, or any combination of the aforementioned.\\n\\nWhen \\u003centity\\u003e is defined by a position or title, the Contract tracks whoever holds that position\\nduring \\u003ctime period\\u003e, even if the individual holding the position changes. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a\\nspecific named individual, the identity remains consistent throughout. Name changes (e.g.,\\nstage names, married names) do not create a new entity. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a group or\\norganization and the Contract does not specify particular members, any official\\ncommunication or statement by any member or designated spokesperson counts. When using\\nAND logic, all specified entities must independently say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e. When\\nusing OR logic, at least one of the specified entities must say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nThe Exchange may specify additional conditions such as “at least X members of” a group or\\n“the majority of” a group.\\n\\n\\u003csource\\u003e: \\u003csource\\u003e refers to a Source Agency or ordered collection of Source Agencies\\nspecified by the Exchange at the time of Contract listing, which will be incorporated into the\\nSource Agency hierarchy above and used to determine the occurrence of the Underlying.\\n\\u003csource\\u003e may refer to a singular agency, multiple agencies, an agency by distinguishing\\ncharacteristics, by category or type (e.g., “official government statistical body,” “primary wire\\nservice”), or any combination thereof. When multiple agencies are specified, they may be\\napplied in the hierarchical order designated by the Exchange if so specified, with the highest-\\nranked available and responsive agency taking precedence for purposes of determining the\\nExpiration Value. A lower-ranked agency shall only be consulted if all higher-ranked agencies\\nare unavailable, unresponsive, have not reported on the Underlying by the Expiration time, or\\nif the Exchange, in its sole discretion, determines that a higher-ranked agency’s reporting is\\nincomplete, erroneous, or otherwise insufficient to determine the Expiration Value. If \\u003csource\\u003e\\ndesignates multiple agencies without specifying a hierarchical order, the Exchange shall\\nresolve any conflict between reporting agencies at its sole discretion.\\n\\n\\u003cword\\u003e: \\u003cword\\u003e refers to the particular word or phrase potentially to be mentioned by\\n\\u003centity\\u003e. It may refer to a word being said a minimum number of times. It may also refer to\\none of multiple words/phrases, any of which are acceptable (e.g., “Doge/Dogecoin”).\\n\\f\\u003ctime period\\u003e: \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific range of time, event or discrete date and\\ntime specified by the Exchange. This may be defined by, but is not limited to: a specific event\\nor context (e.g., “during the State of the Union address”), exact dates or times, relative time\\nmarkers (e.g., “before July 1, 2027,” “in Q1 2026”), event-based periods (e.g., “during any\\ncampaign rally in October 2026,” “during the awards ceremony”), and broader intervals (e.g.,\\n“Q1–Q2 2027,” “January–March 2026”).\\n\\nUnless stated otherwise, “Between” is inclusive of both endpoints, while “before” and “after”\\nexclude the specified date. \\u003ctime period\\u003e may also refer to “Any” or “None”, to multiple dates\\n(even if non-consecutive), or to a singular and discrete date or time.\\n\\nWhen \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event (such as an address, speech, performance, or\\nbroadcast), the Exchange may specify what is included, including whether it includes both live\\nand pre-recorded segments (including whether advertisements are included). Where a\\ntimezone is not specified, ET is assumed.\\n\\n\\nPayout Criterion: The Payout Criterion for the Contract encompasses the Expiration Values that\\n\\u003cword\\u003e is said by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n\\n\\nThe word must appear as a distinct, standalone unit, not buried inside another word. Plural\\nand possessive noun forms count. Other grammatical changes (tense, conjugation, derivation)\\ndo not. If \\u003cword\\u003e appears separated from other words by a space or hyphen or in a\\ncompound form with a space or hyphen, it counts. If \\u003cword\\u003e is fused into a single\\nunhyphenated word, it does not count.\\n\\nIf \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled, and the market contains a\\nstrike stating “Event does not qualify/occur”, such a strike shall resolve “Yes” and all others\\n“No”. If \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled but such strikes are NOT\\nlisted, the Contracts will resolve to the last fair price determined at the discretion of the\\nExchange. If the event is postponed, and such a postponement is announced by the end of the\\nfollowing calendar day to be rescheduled to a time within 14 calendar days, the markets shall\\nremain open. If the event captured in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast, the\\nExchange may keep the market open for 24 hours for the release of an official recording.\\nFurther granular details on conditions for these Contracts is available below.\\n\\nAdditional clarification(s):\\n\\n     Possessive noun forms of \\u003cword\\u003e, plurals, and possessive plural noun forms are\\n     INCLUDED:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigrants” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Egg” → “eggs’ shells” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Russia” → “Russia’s” counts, “Russian” does not\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e exists only in adjective form, no plural form exists:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Economic” → “Economics” does not count (“Economic” is an adjective\\n          for which “Economics” is not a plural)\\n     Plural nouns occurring within proper nouns and noun phrases are included:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Cat” → “Cats the musical” counts\\n\\f    Grammatical variations beyond plurals/possessives are NOT included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigration” does NOT count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Run” → “Running” or “Ran” do NOT count\\n    When \\u003cword\\u003e specifies a plural form, the singular does NOT count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Veterans” → “Veteran” does NOT count\\n    Words that are spelled the same as the plural form of \\u003cword\\u003e (if such exists) but are\\n    themselves not a plural noun are included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Wind” → “Winds up the clock” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Border” → “The United States has strong borders” counts\\n    Open compounds (words separated by spaces) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fire station” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “couch” → “couch potato” counts\\n    Hyphenated compounds (words connected by hyphens) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Palestine” → “pro-Palestine” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fat” → “non-fat” counts\\n    Closed compounds (single word, no spaces/hyphens) do not count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire” does not count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firefighter” does not count\\n    Multi-word \\u003cword\\u003e in larger constructions: When \\u003cword\\u003e is a multi-word phrase\\n    appearing within a hyphenated construction, it counts only if \\u003cword\\u003e appears as a\\n    complete, unmodified element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “New York” → “New York-based” counts (complete element)\\n    Portmanteaus (words blended from two words where parts of each are combined) are\\n    NOT included unless the portmanteau clearly contains \\u003cword\\u003e as a distinct, unaltered\\n    element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “MAGA” → “MAGA-nificent” counts (MAGA appears as distinct element)\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “magnificent” → “MAGA-nificent” does NOT count (portmanteau blend)\\n\\nDictionary determination: Both the Merriam-Webster Dictionary (available online) AND the\\nOxford English Dictionary shall be used to determine compound type and/or conventional\\nspelling patterns. Inclusion in either dictionary as an open or hyphenated compound shall\\nsatisfy the Payout Criterion. If neither provides clarity (or the word is not included),\\ndetermination is based on whether written as single unit (closed/doesn’t count) vs. spaces or\\nhyphens (open or hyphenated/counts) and/or context and previous usage.\\n\\nPHONETIC EQUIVALENCIES\\n\\n    Homophones (same sound, different spelling) do not count:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “write” → “right” does not count\\n    Homonyms and homographs (same spelling) COUNT regardless of meaning or\\n    pronunciation:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “bass” → both “bass guitar” and “bass fishing” count\\n    Proper and common nouns are treated identically:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Apple” → both “Apple Inc.” and “apple” (fruit) count\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Will” → both “Will Smith” and “I will go” count\\n    Minor unintentional mispronunciations COUNT if context makes intent clear:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Mamdani” → “Mandani” counts\\n    Severe mispronunciations that make \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable do NOT count.\\n    Trademarked spellings do not count, even when pronounced identically, unless the word\\n\\fitself is the same:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “lift” → “Lyft” (pronounced “lift”) does not count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “uber” → “Uber” counts\\nWords with non-standard transliteration to English count within reason, provided they are\\nphonetically equivalent:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Zelensky” → any of “Zelenski,” “Zelenskii,” “Zelensky,” or “Zelenskiy”\\n      count if pronounced equivalently\\nContractions do not count for their constituent words unless otherwise explicitly specified\\nby the Exchange:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “not” → “won’t,” “can’t,” “don’t,” “isn’t” do not count\\nNumbers spoken as words COUNT, when spoken exactly (not part of a larger number):\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “five” → saying “five” or reading “$5” aloud as “five dollars” counts,\\n      saying “five hundred” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “410” → “four hundred ten”, “four one zero” or “four ten” counts\\nOrdinals COUNT when \\u003cword\\u003e is written numerically OR a phrase that includes a\\nnumber:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “January 6” → “January 6th” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “3” (written numerically) → “3rd” (spoken as “third”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Eight War” → “8 Wars” and “Eighth War” will count\\nCardinal and ordinal number words are distinct:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “one” → “first” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “first” → “one” does NOT count\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count when pronunciation or letter-by-letter spelling\\nmatches \\u003cword\\u003e:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “NASA” (pronounced “NAH-suh”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “N-A-S-A” (spelled out) counts\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count as \\u003cword\\u003e when pronounced as the full word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Doctor” → “Dr.” (pronounced “Doctor”) counts\\nExpanded forms of acronyms do NOT count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “AI” → “artificial intelligence” does not count\\nWords in foreign languages do NOT count unless they are perfect cognates with an\\nEnglish word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fuego” (Spanish) does NOT count\\nEnglish words within foreign sentences count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “policy” → “Nuestra policy es clara” counts\\n\\u003cword\\u003e in organization/company names counts:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Securities” → “Bank of America Securities” counts\\nWords in URLs, emails, handles, and hashtags (exclusive of domain structure, email\\nprovider or symbols) are treated as compounds when spoken as complete words, with the\\ntype of compound subject to aforementioned rules:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firestation.com” pronounced “fire station dot com” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire.com” pronounced “wildfire dot com” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “apple” → “apple.com” pronounced “apple dot com” does count\\n      When presented in URL, email, handle, or hashtag form, \\u003cword\\u003e shall be treated as\\n      a compound, not a multi-word word\\nSung, rapped, or poetic words COUNT if phonetically recognizable:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “money” → “moneyyy” (extended in rap) counts\\n      Extreme distortion making \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable does NOT count.\\nPhonetic alphabet spelling (“Foxtrot India Romeo Echo” for “FIRE”) does NOT count.\\n\\fCANCELLATIONS AND DELAYS\\n\\n   The Exchange may list an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike for any Contract. If listed,\\n   such a strike refers to the structural conditions of the market, and is NOT adjudicated as a\\n   \\u003cword\\u003e needing to be said by or validated by having been said by \\u003centity\\u003e. If listed, this\\n   strike resolves to “Yes” whenever the event fails to occur or qualify under the Payout\\n   Criterion, or any other circumstance prevents normal resolution.\\n   If no such strike is listed, and \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, the following rules\\n   apply if the event is cancelled, postponed, rescheduled, or materially altered (including\\n   being closed to press) such that no video is released within one calendar day of the\\n   original start time of the event:\\n         If the event is cancelled, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price determined in\\n         the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         If the event is postponed or rescheduled, the outcome depends on whether a new\\n         date is publicly announced within one calendar day (i.e. if the event was scheduled\\n         to begin on Monday, any time up to 11:59PM on Tuesday falls within this period) of\\n         the originally scheduled start time:\\n               If no new date is announced within one calendar day, the Contract will resolve\\n               to the last fair price determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n               If a new date is announced within one calendar day, the outcome depends on\\n               when the rescheduled event is set to occur:\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls within fourteen (14) calendar days of the\\n                     originally scheduled date, the Contract shall remain open and \\u003cword\\u003e\\n                     stated during the rescheduled event will count.\\n                           The fourteen-day window begins at 12:00 AM ET on the originally\\n                           scheduled date and ends at 11:59 PM ET fourteen days later, unless\\n                           an alternate timezone is explicitly specified.\\n                           Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the State of the Union on January\\n                           15, 2026” rescheduled to January 20, 2026 → words spoken during\\n                           the rescheduled address count.\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls more than fourteen (14) calendar days after\\n                     the originally scheduled date, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price\\n                     determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         Any Contract that cannot be resolved through the Source Agency hierarchy will\\n         instead be settled at the Last Fair Price. The Exchange will disclose the methodology\\n         used to determine the Last Fair Price (e.g., Last Traded Price, Time-Weighted\\n         Average Price) at the time of Issuance.\\n         If an event begins but is interrupted, abbreviated, or ends prematurely, words\\n         stated by \\u003centity\\u003e during the portion of the event that did occur will count and the\\n         market will otherwise resolve.\\n   If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window but the venue, format, or medium\\n   changes (e.g., moved to a different location, changed from in-person to virtual (with the\\n   exception of being closed to press)), words stated during the event will count.\\n   Special condition: Across both cases, whether an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike is\\n   listed or not, if the event specified as or in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast (or\\n   relayed as such) but the live stream/broadcast does not occur, the Exchange will instead\\n   use an officially released recording as the Underlying, and may delay resolution by up to\\n   one calendar day to allow for the release of such a recording.\\n\\f          If partial snippets are released, Contracts on words that do not appear will be\\n          resolved to last fair price, and Contracts on those that do will be resolved to “Yes”.\\n          If no recording is released, the relevant outcomes triggered by the\\n          presence/absence of an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike shall occur as outlined\\n          above.\\n\\nTECHNICAL DETAILS (UNLESS OTHERWISE SPECIFIED)\\n\\n     When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, pre-recorded content broadcast,\\n     streamed, or published as part of that event is included if presented as part of the official\\n     presentation.\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the concert” with pre-recorded video interlude\\n          where entity speaks → words from interlude count\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the television appearance” with pre-taped\\n          segment aired during broadcast → words from segment count\\n     Behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are NOT\\n     included unless officially broadcast or published as part of \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n     Subtitles and captions that display \\u003cword\\u003e on screen but are not spoken aloud by\\n     \\u003centity\\u003e do NOT count.\\n     Sign language interpretation or usage by entity does NOT count as saying \\u003cword\\u003e unless\\n     the Contract explicitly specifies that sign language counts.\\n     Text that entity displays on screen (presentation slides, teleprompter visible to audience,\\n     signatures) does NOT count unless entity reads it aloud.\\n     Content generated by AI, deepfakes, or synthetic voice technology impersonating entity\\n     does NOT count unless the synthetic content is officially commissioned, authorized, or\\n     published by entity, OR the Contract explicitly specifies that AI-generated content counts.\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e is muted due to technical failure or censorship it shall not count unless\\n     corroborating contextual evidence (including surrounding speech, or an official\\n     uncensored recording or transcript) confirms that \\u003centity\\u003e specifically uttered \\u003cword\\u003e\\n     during the muted period.\\n\\nMinimum Tick: The Minimum Tick size for the Contract shall be $0.01.\\n\\nPosition Accountability Level: The Position Accountability Level for the Contract shall be\\n$25,000 per strike, per Member.\\n\\nLast Trading Date: The Last Trading Date of the Contract will be the Expiration Date. The Last\\nTrading Time will be the Expiration time.\\n\\nSettlement Date: The Settlement Date of the Contract shall be no later than the day after the\\nExpiration Date, unless the Market Outcome is under review pursuant to Rule 7.1.\\n\\nExpiration Date: When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event: The latest Expiration Date of\\nthe Contract shall be fourteen (14) calendar days after the originally scheduled date of the\\nevent. If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window, expiration will be moved to an\\nearlier date and time in accordance with Rule 7.2. When \\u003ctime period\\u003e is defined by specific\\ndates: The latest Expiration Date of the Contract shall be two weeks after the end of \\u003ctime\\nperiod\\u003e. If an event described in the Payout Criterion occurs and a consensus has been\\nreached on all terms, then expiration will be moved to an earlier date and time in accordance\\nwith Rule 7.2.\\n\\fExpiration time: The Expiration time of the Contract shall be 10:00 AM ET.\\n\\nSettlement Value: The Settlement Value for this Contract is $1.00.\\n\\nExpiration Value: The Expiration Value is the value of the Underlying as documented by the\\nSource Agency on the Expiration Date at the Expiration time.\\n\\nContingencies: Before Settlement, Kalshi may, at its sole discretion, initiate the Market\\nOutcome Review Process pursuant to Rule 7.1 of the Rulebook. If an Expiration Value cannot\\nbe determined on the Expiration Date, Kalshi has the right to determine payouts pursuant to\\nRule 7.1 in the Rulebook.\\n\\f\\n\\n[defendant] DX-S1 GovInfo official transcript: prior reporter exchange\\nSource: GovInfo, Compilation of Presidential Documents, DCPD202501162\\nURL retrieved: https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/DCPD-202501162/html/DCPD-202501162.htm\\nRetrieval time: 2026-06-29T22:00:00Z\\nLocal captured HTML size/hash: 51,571 bytes; SHA-256 eadbceeecf3e94f5bd423bcb8e8511165fdc7265dd8c1e025870c2e8f34dfd99\\n\\nMaterial captured text from official GovInfo HTML/web.open:\\n\\nAdministration of Donald J. Trump, 2025\\n\\nTitle: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\nDate: December 5, 2025\\n\\nOpening note: [The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\\n\\nExcerpt - The President's Interest in Soccer (web.open lines 196-203):\\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\\\"football,\\\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\\n\\nExcerpt - The President's Interest in Soccer (web.open lines 322-329):\\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\\nThe President. But they have a little more speed. But no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\\n\\nTiming/context note (web.open lines 461-462):\\nNOTE: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. In his remarks, he referred to Trey Yingst, chief foreign correspondent, Fox News Channel; Cristiano Ronaldo, forward for Saudi Pro League club Al-Nass and Portugal's national soccer team; and Lionel Messi, forward for Major League Soccer club Inter Miami and Argentina's national team. A reporter referred to New York State Attorney General Letitia James.\\nThe transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\n\\nDocument category/location/name/subject metadata (web.open lines 463-468):\\nCategories: Interviews With the News Media: Exchanges with reporters, Washington, DC.\\nLocations: Washington, DC.\\nNames include: Cristiano Ronaldo and Lionel Messi.\\nSubjects include: Federation Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) World Cup; John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts; News media, Presidential interviews; Soccer.\\nDCPD Number: DCPD202501162.\\n\\nCapture limits: This item is a focused text capture of the material official transcript title, Ronaldo excerpts, timing/correction note, and metadata. It is not a full video or audio artifact. The official transcript itself notes some portions could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-S2 FIFA official draw commencement time\\nSource: FIFA official page, FIFA World Cup 2026 Final Draw\\nURL: https://www.fifa.com/en/tournaments/mens/worldcup/canadamexicousa2026/live-draw\\nRetrieval time: 2026-06-29T22:01:00Z\\n\\nMaterial captured text from web search/open result:\\n- Page title/source: FIFA World Cup 2026™ Final Draw\\n- The draw takes place at the Kennedy Center in Washington DC, USA.\\n- The draw commences at 12:00 local time (17:00 UTC) on Friday 5 December 2025.\\n\\nCapture limits: This is a focused text capture of the official FIFA page timing statement located by web search. It is not a video capture of the draw ceremony.\\n\\nSubmitted evidence:\\n[plaintiff arguments] Official White House video page capture: President Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing (ev_db357d4e9407_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-db357d4e9407)\\nSource: https://www.whitehouse.gov/videos/president-trump-attends-the-fifa-world-cup-drawing/\\nSHA-256: `db357d4e940728d417ae4f7f3caac6b78d3fd3e4aba70d46fe10c6132d45997a`\\nBytes: 1300\\nRelevance: Establishes that the White House officially published a video page titled President Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing, dated December 5, 2025, with a full-video link and related World Cup Draw videos; relevant to source chain and event context.\\n\\n[plaintiff arguments] YouTube metadata capture: Trump Talks Cristiano Ronaldo at FIFA Draw (ev_4e1045905547_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-4e1045905547)\\nSource: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Cb2yO0lLEnM\\nSHA-256: `4e10459055477440085fe5e20d970eb2488e61d13a5e2b3133a3656bed7526d7`\\nBytes: 1779\\nRelevance: Provides a public clip source and page metadata asserting that at the FIFA World Cup Draw Ceremony Trump shared a story about meeting Cristiano Ronaldo and said Ronaldo was a great person; relevant to the alleged Ronaldo utterance, though weaker than an official full transcript or video.\\n\\n[defendant arguments] GovInfo official transcript capture: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the FIFA World Cup Draw (ev_a1b1f6b1b7bd_submitted-evidence-03-defendant-a1b1f6b1b7bd)\\nSource: https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/DCPD-202501162/html/DCPD-202501162.htm\\nSHA-256: `a1b1f6b1b7bd0b691c7fe8d97467dd0d085e2b22387ae4198270764de66e56e2`\\nBytes: 3070\\nRelevance: Official transcript identifies the relevant Trump remarks as an exchange with reporters prior to the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw; it includes the Ronaldo utterances and timing/correction notes, directly bearing on whether the utterances were during the countable event period.\\n\\n[defendant arguments] FIFA official page capture: 2026 World Cup Final Draw start time (ev_3973dc8f98c0_submitted-evidence-04-defendant-3973dc8f98c0)\\nSource: https://www.fifa.com/en/tournaments/mens/worldcup/canadamexicousa2026/live-draw\\nSHA-256: `3973dc8f98c01702174f61f5548eb1e80efe64dd72b44f21ed0fa7d944f93248`\\nBytes: 598\\nRelevance: Establishes the official Final Draw start time as 12:00 local time on December 5, 2025, which helps compare the draw event period against the GovInfo transcript note that the reporter exchange occurred at 11:13 a.m.\\n\\nTechnical reports:\\n[plaintiff] Plaintiff source-search and capture ledger\\nSearched exact market/strike phrases, White House domain, public video pages, YouTube video IDs, and Kalshi live market URL. Submitted official White House page capture and YouTube metadata capture. Kalshi live page returned a Vercel security checkpoint/429; local browser was unavailable; Python pip/ensurepip unavailable for yt-dlp; direct YouTube caption/open paths were throttled or unavailable. Remaining best evidence would be a full official video/transcript or Kalshi resolution rationale if later accessible.\\n\\n[defendant] Defendant source-search and capture ledger\\nInspected current AAR evidence and exact contents of plaintiff's White House and YouTube captures. Retrieved GovInfo official HTML transcript with curl from DCPD-202501162; local full HTML was 51,571 bytes with SHA-256 eadbceeecf3e94f5bd423bcb8e8511165fdc7265dd8c1e025870c2e8f34dfd99, then submitted a focused material text capture as DX-1. Searched official draw timing and submitted the FIFA official page timing statement as DX-2. Remaining gaps: full Kalshi market source hierarchy/resolution rationale and full WH/FIFA video were not captured, but official GovInfo timing/title plus FIFA start time resolve the material timing issue.\\n\\nCall submit_council_vote with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated.\\nKeep the rationale brief: no more than three sentences.\\n\\nCouncil API instructions:\\nYou are a council member. Decide the proposition from the admitted record.\\nYou may examine admitted evidence through read-only tools when exact bytes, metadata, or exhibit contents matter.\\nDo not search the web, introduce new facts, create new evidence, or upload evidence.\\nWhen ready, call submit_council_vote exactly once with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated and a concise rationale.\\n\",\"state\":\"ready\",\"status\":\"ready\",\"tools\":[{\"description\":\"Return the current visible arbitration record for this council member.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"get_case\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"List visible immutable record evidence.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"list_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Return metadata and read limits for one visible evidence item.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"stat_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Read a bounded byte range from one visible evidence item as base64.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"length\":{\"minimum\":1,\"type\":\"integer\"},\"offset\":{\"minimum\":0,\"type\":\"integer\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\",\"offset\",\"length\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"read_evidence_range\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Submit one council vote for the current deliberation opportunity.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"rationale\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"vote\":{\"enum\":[\"demonstrated\",\"not_demonstrated\"],\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"vote\",\"rationale\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"submit_council_vote\",\"read_only\":false}],\"turn\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"completed\":false,\"deadline\":\"2026-06-29T22:18:45.386037689Z\",\"deliberation_round\":1,\"member_id\":\"C2\",\"opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C2\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"remaining_ms\":889046,\"role_id\":\"council\",\"turn_number\":10},\"wait\":{\"reason\":\"ready\",\"state_version\":14,\"version\":17}}"}],"structuredContent":{"after_opportunity_id":"deliberation:1:C2","after_version":17,"case_id":"arb-ex03a-20260629214245","limits":{"attempts_max":3,"attempts_remaining":3,"max_evidence_read_bytes":65536,"max_evidence_read_bytes_per_opportunity":524288,"max_evidence_reads_per_opportunity":32,"max_response_bytes":131072,"remaining_evidence_read_bytes_for_opportunity":524288,"remaining_evidence_reads_for_opportunity":32},"member_id":"C2","message":"An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.","ok":true,"prompt":"Role: council member\nMember ID: C2\nDeliberation round: 1\nProposition: For the Kalshi market \"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\", the strike \"Ronaldo\" should resolve Yes because Trump said \"Ronaldo\" in public remarks at the World Cup Draw venue immediately before the formal program, and the market wording plus the governing mention-market terms did not clearly exclude those event-linked remarks.\nStandard of evidence: Preponderance of the evidence.\nPersona:\nYou are a careful juror and council member.\n\nEvaluate the record faithfully. Decide only from the evidence, the stated rules, and the applicable burden of proof. Do not favor either side, fill gaps with speculation, or ignore uncertainty.\n\nGive weight to reliable sources, direct evidence, consistent reasoning, and clear admissions. Discount unsupported claims, rhetorical force, irrelevant facts, and conclusions that exceed the record.\n\nWhen the evidence supports one answer, state it plainly. When the evidence is incomplete or balanced, say so. Be concise, honest, and exact.\n\nRecord:\nOpenings:\n[plaintiff] Council members, this case is not about whether the word \"Ronaldo\" would count if President Trump clearly said it. The current packet makes that part straightforward: the market is the Kalshi PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION market titled \"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\"; the strike is \"Ronaldo\"; Kalshi’s challenged resolution is No; and plaintiff seeks Yes.\n\nThe real dispute is temporal and contextual. Did the market phrase \"during the FIFA World Cup Draw,\" read with the governing mention-market terms, include public event-linked remarks at the World Cup Draw venue immediately before the formal draw program? Or did it clearly confine countable words to a narrower formal broadcast segment? Plaintiff’s position is that a No resolution cannot stand unless the record shows that the counting window clearly excluded those event-linked remarks.\n\nThe admitted terms matter. They define the underlying as words used by the specified entity during the specified time period. They expressly recognize event-based time periods, and they say the payout criterion is satisfied when the word is said by the entity during that period. They also contain exclusions: behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings do not count unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period; captions or text alone do not count; and the word must appear as a distinct standalone unit. Those exclusions are important, but they do not by themselves answer this case. A public remark at the event venue, tied to the Draw and immediately before the formal program, is not automatically a rehearsal, sound check, or private behind-the-scenes moment.\n\nAt this opening stage, the record proves the market identity, the challenged resolution, the requested resolution, and the generic governing terms. It does not yet prove the utterance itself, the exact sequence of the venue remarks, the source-agency hierarchy or any market-specific time-period language beyond the packet, or Kalshi’s reason for treating the strike as No. Those are the factual links that should decide the case under a preponderance standard.\n\nPlaintiff expects the decisive proof to be the full official or otherwise reliable event video or transcript, with enough surrounding context to show whether Trump said \"Ronaldo\" aloud as a standalone word; when he said it relative to the Draw event; whether the remarks were public and event-linked rather than backstage or a sound check; and whether any market-specific rule clearly excluded that segment. Plaintiff also expects the market page, archived market details, and any resolution rationale to be important because ambiguity in the market’s own event wording should not be resolved against Yes after the fact.\n\nThe defense will likely argue that \"during the FIFA World Cup Draw\" means only the formal draw ceremony or broadcast, and that anything before the formal program is outside the counting period. That theory can win only if the evidence shows a clear exclusion or a source record that separates the alleged remarks from the event itself. If the evidence instead shows public remarks at the Draw venue, officially connected to the event, immediately before the formal program, and no clear rule excluding them, then the terms favor counting the word and resolving the Ronaldo strike Yes.\n\n[defendant] Council members, the defense position is straightforward: the admitted record does not yet prove that the Ronaldo strike should resolve Yes. It proves a market title, a generic mention-market rule set, and Kalshi's challenged No resolution. It does not prove that any qualifying utterance of \"Ronaldo\" occurred during the market's countable time period.\n\nThe plaintiff's opening usefully narrows the dispute. This is not primarily a word-boundary case. If President Trump said \"Ronaldo\" as a standalone spoken word during the countable FIFA World Cup Draw period, the generic terms would ordinarily treat that as the kind of word that can count. The real question is whether plaintiff can carry the burden of showing that alleged pre-program, venue-adjacent remarks were part of the market's specified time period: \"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\"\n\nThe case-packet terms matter, but they cut both ways. They say the underlying is words used by the entity during the specified time period. They recognize that a time period can be an event, and they allow the Exchange to specify what is included when an event is involved. They also distinguish official event presentation from material outside the event: behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are not included unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period; text or captions alone do not count; and the relevant word must be spoken aloud by the entity. Those provisions do not support a rule that every public comment inside the same building, or every press exchange near the formal program, is automatically \"during\" the Draw.\n\nThat is the burden problem for plaintiff. The admitted market-page file identifies the public title, contract family, strike, challenged resolution, and requested resolution. It does not supply a full market-specific source hierarchy, a formal start time, a transcript, a video, a resolution rationale, or the alleged remarks. The terms file supplies the generic framework, but not the factual bridge from \"immediately before the formal program\" to \"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\" Without that bridge, the No resolution is not shown to be wrong by a preponderance of the evidence.\n\nThe defense expects the decisive proof to be source-chain evidence, not characterization. The council should want the market's full rule page if available, the source agency hierarchy, the official draw program or broadcast, any official transcript or recording of the alleged exchange, and enough surrounding timestamps to separate the formal draw from pre-event reporter access, red-carpet exchanges, arrivals, or other ancillary material. If later evidence shows that the alleged Ronaldo comment was in a segment officially presented as part of the Draw itself, plaintiff's argument becomes stronger. If the evidence instead shows a separate exchange with reporters before the draw, or an event-linked but pre-program interaction not incorporated into the official presentation, the generic terms support Kalshi's No.\n\nSo the defense opening is not that the word Ronaldo could never count. It is that this record has not established the necessary time-period link. The proposition asks the council to overturn No because the market wording and terms did not clearly exclude pre-program remarks. That reverses the burden. Plaintiff must show that the remarks were included in the countable period. Ambiguity about the outer edge of an event is not the same as proof that a specific pre-event utterance satisfies the payout criterion.\n\nArguments:\n[plaintiff] Council members, plaintiff has now supplied the record links that were missing at opening.\n\nFirst, the market packet fixes what this dispute is: the Kalshi market title is \"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\"; the contract family is PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION; the strike is \"Ronaldo\"; Kalshi's challenged resolution is No; and plaintiff seeks Yes. That is PX-1.\n\nSecond, the governing terms make this an event-period mention question, not a narrow formal-program-only question. PX-2 says the underlying is words used by the entity during the time period, recognizes that a time period may be a specific event, and sets the payout criterion as the word being said by the entity during that period. It also tells us what does not count: text/captions alone, unofficial behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, and sound checks unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. Those exclusions matter, but none says that public event-linked remarks at the venue immediately before the formal program are categorically outside \"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\"\n\nThird, the source-chain evidence now points to the disputed event and the Ronaldo utterance. PX-3 is an official White House page titled \"President Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing,\" dated December 5, 2025, with a full-video link and related World Cup Draw videos. That establishes an official White House event-video source for Trump's attendance at the World Cup Drawing. PX-4 is a public YouTube watch-page metadata capture for video ID Cb2yO0lLEnM, titled \"Trump Talks Cristiano Ronaldo at FIFA Draw -- 'He's a Great Person'.\" Its description states that at the FIFA World Cup Draw Ceremony, Trump shared a story about meeting Cristiano Ronaldo at the White House, said Ronaldo was a great person, and mentioned Ronaldo spoke with his son. PX-4 is not as strong as an official transcript, and plaintiff says that plainly. But it is admitted source content that directly links Trump, Cristiano Ronaldo, and the FIFA Draw ceremony.\n\nOn a preponderance standard, that is enough to defeat the challenged No resolution unless the defense can supply a clearer exclusion. The market did not ask only what Trump would say during the ball-pulling segment, during the televised main show, or after a particular formal start cue. It asked what he would say \"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\" The terms recognize event-based periods and exclude particular non-event categories. A public remark at the Draw venue, tied to the Draw, is far closer to the event period than to a rehearsal, sound check, caption, or private backstage recording.\n\nThe defense's burden framing is too strict. Plaintiff must prove Yes by a preponderance; plaintiff need not prove that Kalshi drafted every boundary with perfect precision. Once the admitted sources show a Ronaldo mention in connection with the FIFA Draw ceremony, the remaining question is whether the rules clearly remove that event-linked remark from the counting period. They do not. Ambiguity in a mention market's event wording should not be converted into an unstated formal-program limitation after the fact.\n\nProvenance and gaps: plaintiff attempted to retrieve the live Kalshi page, official/full video, caption, and transcript. Kalshi returned a Vercel security checkpoint; the local browser tool was unavailable; Python pip/ensurepip was unavailable for yt-dlp; and direct YouTube caption/open paths were throttled or unavailable. That leaves PX-4 weaker than ideal, but not weightless. PX-3 supplies official event context, PX-4 supplies the Ronaldo-at-FIFA-Draw metadata, and PX-2 supplies the rule that event-linked spoken words count absent a clear exclusion.\n\nThe council should resolve the proposition Yes: the Ronaldo strike should have resolved Yes because the record more likely than not shows Trump said Ronaldo in public remarks tied to the FIFA World Cup Draw, and the market wording plus governing terms did not clearly exclude those remarks.\n\n[defendant] Council members, the merits record now shows why the challenged No resolution should stand.\n\nPlaintiff's best point is that Trump did say the word \"Ronaldo.\" The defense does not need to fight that. The question is whether he said it during the market's countable time period: \"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\" On that decisive question, the strongest official sources favor No.\n\nThe admitted GovInfo transcript, DX-1, is an official Compilation of Presidential Documents capture. Its title is not merely \"World Cup Draw\" or \"FIFA ceremony.\" It is \"Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw.\" That same transcript contains the Ronaldo passages: Trump says he met Ronaldo at the White House, later says he was \"not Ronaldo or Messi,\" and the note identifies Ronaldo among the people referenced. So DX-1 is not adverse to the defense because it confirms the word; it is decisive because it places the word in an exchange with reporters prior to the Draw.\n\nDX-2 supplies the timing anchor. The official FIFA Final Draw page states that the Draw at the Kennedy Center commenced at 12:00 local time on Friday, December 5, 2025. DX-1 states that the President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the Kennedy Center. A reporter exchange at 11:13, officially titled as prior to a 12:00 draw, is not more likely than not \"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\" It is before it.\n\nThat reading matches the governing PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION terms. PX-2 says the payout criterion is satisfied when the word is said by the entity during the specified time period. It recognizes event-based periods and permits the Exchange to specify what is included for an event. It also treats official presentation differently from adjacent material: pre-recorded content counts if presented as part of the official event presentation, while behind-the-scenes, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings do not count unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. The point is not that this reporter exchange was a rehearsal or sound check. The point is that the terms require a link to the time period itself. Plaintiff has supplied no market-specific language saying pre-event reporter availability, arrivals, or venue interviews count as part of the Draw.\n\nPlaintiff's new exhibits do not fill that gap. PX-3, the White House page capture, establishes that the White House had a page titled \"President Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing,\" but plaintiff's own capture says the embedded/full video was not captured. It does not prove that the Ronaldo words occurred inside the official draw program. PX-4 is weaker still: it is metadata from a nonofficial YouTube channel. It says the clip is about Trump talking Ronaldo at the FIFA Draw, but it is not a transcript, not an official source, and not an audio extraction. When a nonofficial clip description is weighed against GovInfo's official transcript title and FIFA's official start time, the official sources control.\n\nNor is this a burden-shifting problem. The proposition asks the council to overturn Kalshi's No because the market supposedly did not clearly exclude remarks immediately before the formal program. But the preponderance burden is on Yes. The record must show that the strike satisfied the payout criterion. The admitted terms do not say that ambiguous pre-event remarks count by default; they say the word must be said during the specified time period. Here, the best evidence identifies the remarks as prior to the Draw and before the official commencement time.\n\nProvenance also matters. DX-1 is an official government transcript with a correction note and an audio-incomplete caveat. That caveat affects stray inaudible portions, but it does not weaken the title, the 11:13 timing note, or the Ronaldo passages preserved in the transcript. DX-2 is an official FIFA timing source. Plaintiff's YouTube metadata may explain why the dispute arose, but it cannot outweigh those primary sources on timing and event classification.\n\nThe council should resolve the proposition against plaintiff. Trump said Ronaldo, but the record more likely shows he did so in a reporter exchange prior to the FIFA World Cup Draw, not during the countable Draw event. Kalshi's No resolution should be upheld.\n\nRebuttals:\n[plaintiff] Council members, defendant’s new evidence narrows the case but does not end it.\n\nPlaintiff accepts the important parts of DX-1 and DX-2. The GovInfo transcript is official; it labels the item an exchange with reporters \"Prior to\" the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw; it places the exchange at 11:13 a.m. at the Kennedy Center; and the FIFA capture states the draw commenced at 12:00 local time. Plaintiff should not pretend those facts are weak.\n\nBut defendant asks those facts to do more than they do. The market was not drafted as \"what will Trump say after the official 12:00 commencement,\" \"during the televised draw program,\" or \"during the ball-drawing segment.\" PX-1 says the public market title was \"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\" That is ordinary event language, and PX-2 recognizes event-based time periods while leaving room for the Exchange to specify what is included. The record still contains no market-specific exclusion for official venue press remarks immediately before the formal program.\n\nDX-1 also helps plaintiff on the facts defendant originally said were missing. It confirms the relevant spoken word. Trump said he met Ronaldo, that Ronaldo is great, and that he was not Ronaldo or Messi. It also places those remarks at the Kennedy Center in a FIFA World Cup Draw-centered exchange with reporters, not in an unrelated private dinner or stale campaign setting. The transcript’s own subject metadata includes the FIFA World Cup, the Kennedy Center, news media, presidential interviews, and soccer. That is event-linked public context.\n\nThe terms’ exclusions do not fit defendant’s leap. PX-2 excludes captions alone, rehearsals, sound checks, behind-the-scenes content, and unofficial recordings unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. DX-1 is not a rehearsal transcript. It is not a sound check. It is not merely a caption. It is an official presidential transcript of a public reporter exchange at the venue, released in the Compilation of Presidential Documents. If Kalshi meant to exclude that category because it occurred before a formal noon commencement, the market needed to say so clearly.\n\nSo the dispositive question remains one of market construction: does \"during the FIFA World Cup Draw\" clearly exclude public, official, event-site remarks immediately before the formal program? Defendant has proved \"prior to\" the formal draw start. Defendant has not proved a clear market rule that treats the broader Draw event as beginning only at 12:00 for mention purposes.\n\nUnder a preponderance standard, the record now confirms the Ronaldo utterance and confirms the FIFA Draw setting. The challenged No resolution should not be upheld by importing a narrow formal-program limitation that the market title and generic terms did not state.\n\nSurrebuttals:\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff's rebuttal usefully clarifies the remaining dispute: plaintiff accepts that DX-1 is official, that it labels the relevant item an exchange with reporters \"Prior to\" the FIFA World Cup Draw, that the exchange occurred at 11:13 a.m. at the Kennedy Center, and that DX-2 places the official Draw commencement at 12:00 local time. Those concessions should decide the case.\n\nPlaintiff's answer is that the market did not say \"after 12:00,\" \"during the televised program,\" or \"during the ball-drawing segment.\" But the market also did not say \"at the venue before the Draw,\" \"in pre-event reporter exchanges,\" or \"in any public remarks connected to the Draw.\" The phrase it chose was \"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\" Ordinary event language has a start, and the official FIFA source fixes that start at noon. Official GovInfo then fixes this exchange at 11:13 and titles it as prior to the Draw.\n\nThat is not a technicality. The terms require the word to be said during the specified time period. They recognize event-based periods and allow event-specific inclusions, but no admitted market-specific rule includes pre-event press access. Plaintiff's construction would turn any event-adjacent public remark into part of the event unless expressly excluded. That reverses the payout criterion. The claimant must show the word occurred during the time period; it is not enough to show the same venue, the same general topic, and official publication.\n\nPlaintiff says the exclusions do not fit because DX-1 is not a rehearsal, sound check, caption, or private backstage recording. Fair enough; the defense is not relying on those categories as labels. The defense relies on the affirmative timing requirement. A remark need not be a rehearsal to be outside the event. A reporter exchange officially described as prior to a noon event and occurring at 11:13 is outside because it is before the event began.\n\nThe record therefore proves the wrong fact for plaintiff. It proves Trump said Ronaldo, but in a pre-event reporter exchange. The proposition requires Yes only if those words count during the FIFA World Cup Draw. On this record, they do not. Kalshi's No resolution should be upheld.\n\nClosings:\n[plaintiff] Council members, the final record leaves one legal question.\n\nThe easy factual question is resolved in plaintiff’s favor: Trump said \"Ronaldo.\" The official GovInfo transcript confirms it twice in substance: he said he met Ronaldo, praised him, and later said he was not Ronaldo or Messi. That is a spoken standalone use of the strike word. The record also places the remarks at the Kennedy Center in a FIFA World Cup Draw-centered reporter exchange. This was not an unrelated dinner, a caption, an AI voice, or a social-media paraphrase.\n\nThe hard point is timing. Defendant has the strongest evidence on the formal program boundary: GovInfo titled the exchange as \"Prior to\" the Draw, notes 11:13 a.m., and FIFA states the Final Draw commenced at 12:00 local time. Plaintiff does not ask the council to ignore that. The question is what the Kalshi market actually required.\n\nPX-1 did not say \"after 12:00.\" It did not say \"during the televised draw program\" or \"during the ball-drawing segment.\" It asked, in public market wording, \"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\" PX-2’s generic terms recognize event-based periods and say the Exchange may specify what is included when a time period refers to an event. They also give specific exclusions: captions alone, rehearsals, sound checks, behind-the-scenes content, and unofficial recordings unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. None of those exclusions is this case. The GovInfo transcript is an official public presidential record of an event-site reporter exchange, not a rehearsal or sound check.\n\nDefendant’s best argument is that ordinary events have start times. True. But this market dispute is about public remarks at the venue immediately before the formal program, in the official context of the Draw, where the market and rules did not clearly define a noon-only boundary. If Kalshi wanted that narrower rule, it could have said so in the strike, the market title, or the event inclusion language. It did not.\n\nThe preponderance record therefore shows: Ronaldo was spoken; the remarks were public and officially documented; they were at the Kennedy Center in the FIFA World Cup Draw setting; and the governing market language did not clearly exclude that immediately-before-program event context. The challenged No resolution depends on importing a formal commencement limitation that is absent from the market packet.\n\nFor that reason, the Ronaldo strike should resolve Yes.\n\n[defendant] Council members, the closing record is narrow and concrete.\n\nEveryone now agrees on the easy fact: Trump said \"Ronaldo.\" The official GovInfo transcript proves that. But the proposition is not simply that Trump said the word somewhere near the FIFA World Cup Draw. The proposition asks you to overturn Kalshi's No because remarks immediately before the formal program should count under a market asking what Trump would say \"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\" Plaintiff has not carried that burden.\n\nThe two strongest sources are official and aligned. GovInfo, in DX-1, titles the relevant document \"Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw.\" It notes that the President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the Kennedy Center. FIFA, in DX-2, states that the Final Draw commenced at 12:00 local time. Those facts are not peripheral. They answer the timing question: the Ronaldo words were in a reporter exchange before the Draw began.\n\nPlaintiff's closing says the market did not specify \"after 12:00,\" \"during the televised draw program,\" or \"during the ball-drawing segment.\" True, but that does not prove Yes. The market did specify \"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\" The ordinary function of \"during\" is to define the event period, not to include anything public, official, and thematically related that happens beforehand. A 47-minute-before reporter exchange officially titled as prior to the Draw is outside that period unless the market or governing terms affirmatively include it. The record contains no such inclusion.\n\nThe governing terms reinforce that conclusion. They require the word to be said by the entity during the specified time period. They recognize event-based periods and allow the Exchange to specify event inclusions. They include official-presentation concepts for material presented as part of an event. But they do not say that pre-event press availability counts by default. Plaintiff's argument turns the absence of an exclusion into proof of inclusion. That is backwards under a preponderance standard.\n\nPlaintiff also leans on setting: Kennedy Center, FIFA World Cup subject matter, official transcript, public reporters. Those facts show why the issue is understandable. They do not move 11:13 into a 12:00 event. A source can be official and still describe something outside the event. Indeed, that is exactly what DX-1 does: it officially documents the remarks and officially labels them prior to the Draw.\n\nThe weaker evidence points the same way once weighed properly. The White House page capture does not include the video or transcript. The YouTube metadata is nonofficial and not an audio transcript. Neither overcomes GovInfo's title and timing note plus FIFA's commencement time.\n\nSo the final answer is simple: the word was spoken, but not during the countable event period shown by the best evidence. Plaintiff has not shown that Kalshi's No resolution was wrong. The council should reject the proposition and uphold No.\n\nExhibits:\n[plaintiff] PX-1 Market page packet: Ronaldo strike and challenged No resolution\nMarket URL: https://kalshi.com/markets/kxtrumpmentionb/trump-mention-b/kxtrumpmentionb-25dec06\n\nPublic market title: What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\n\nContract family: PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION\n\nStrike at issue: Ronaldo\n\nChallenged resolution: No\n\nRequested resolution: Yes\n\n\n[plaintiff] PX-2 Governing PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION terms\n                                         NEWMENTION\n\nScope: These rules shall apply to this contract.\n\nUnderlying: The Underlying for this Contract is words used by <entity> <time period>.\nRevisions to the Underlying made after Expiration will not be accounted for in determining the\nExpiration Value.\n\nSource Agency: The Source Agencies are <source>.\n\nType: The type of Contract is an Event Contract.\n\nIssuance: After the initial Contract, Contract iterations will be listed on an as-needed basis at\nthe discretion of the Exchange and corresponding to the risk management needs of Members.\n\n<entity>: <entity> refers to the speaker, writer, performer, or communicator specified by the\nExchange. This may include (but is not limited to): a specific named individual, multiple\nindividuals specified using AND/OR logic, an individual identified by position or title, a group,\nband, team or collective entity, a specified member or members of a group, an organization,\ncompany, or institutional entity, or any combination of the aforementioned.\n\nWhen <entity> is defined by a position or title, the Contract tracks whoever holds that position\nduring <time period>, even if the individual holding the position changes. When <entity> is a\nspecific named individual, the identity remains consistent throughout. Name changes (e.g.,\nstage names, married names) do not create a new entity. When <entity> is a group or\norganization and the Contract does not specify particular members, any official\ncommunication or statement by any member or designated spokesperson counts. When using\nAND logic, all specified entities must independently say <word> during <time period>. When\nusing OR logic, at least one of the specified entities must say <word> during <time period>.\nThe Exchange may specify additional conditions such as “at least X members of” a group or\n“the majority of” a group.\n\n<source>: <source> refers to a Source Agency or ordered collection of Source Agencies\nspecified by the Exchange at the time of Contract listing, which will be incorporated into the\nSource Agency hierarchy above and used to determine the occurrence of the Underlying.\n<source> may refer to a singular agency, multiple agencies, an agency by distinguishing\ncharacteristics, by category or type (e.g., “official government statistical body,” “primary wire\nservice”), or any combination thereof. When multiple agencies are specified, they may be\napplied in the hierarchical order designated by the Exchange if so specified, with the highest-\nranked available and responsive agency taking precedence for purposes of determining the\nExpiration Value. A lower-ranked agency shall only be consulted if all higher-ranked agencies\nare unavailable, unresponsive, have not reported on the Underlying by the Expiration time, or\nif the Exchange, in its sole discretion, determines that a higher-ranked agency’s reporting is\nincomplete, erroneous, or otherwise insufficient to determine the Expiration Value. If <source>\ndesignates multiple agencies without specifying a hierarchical order, the Exchange shall\nresolve any conflict between reporting agencies at its sole discretion.\n\n<word>: <word> refers to the particular word or phrase potentially to be mentioned by\n<entity>. It may refer to a word being said a minimum number of times. It may also refer to\none of multiple words/phrases, any of which are acceptable (e.g., “Doge/Dogecoin”).\n\f<time period>: <time period> refers to a specific range of time, event or discrete date and\ntime specified by the Exchange. This may be defined by, but is not limited to: a specific event\nor context (e.g., “during the State of the Union address”), exact dates or times, relative time\nmarkers (e.g., “before July 1, 2027,” “in Q1 2026”), event-based periods (e.g., “during any\ncampaign rally in October 2026,” “during the awards ceremony”), and broader intervals (e.g.,\n“Q1–Q2 2027,” “January–March 2026”).\n\nUnless stated otherwise, “Between” is inclusive of both endpoints, while “before” and “after”\nexclude the specified date. <time period> may also refer to “Any” or “None”, to multiple dates\n(even if non-consecutive), or to a singular and discrete date or time.\n\nWhen <time period> refers to a specific event (such as an address, speech, performance, or\nbroadcast), the Exchange may specify what is included, including whether it includes both live\nand pre-recorded segments (including whether advertisements are included). Where a\ntimezone is not specified, ET is assumed.\n\n\nPayout Criterion: The Payout Criterion for the Contract encompasses the Expiration Values that\n<word> is said by <entity> <time period>.\n\n\nThe word must appear as a distinct, standalone unit, not buried inside another word. Plural\nand possessive noun forms count. Other grammatical changes (tense, conjugation, derivation)\ndo not. If <word> appears separated from other words by a space or hyphen or in a\ncompound form with a space or hyphen, it counts. If <word> is fused into a single\nunhyphenated word, it does not count.\n\nIf <time period> refers to an event and that event is cancelled, and the market contains a\nstrike stating “Event does not qualify/occur”, such a strike shall resolve “Yes” and all others\n“No”. If <time period> refers to an event and that event is cancelled but such strikes are NOT\nlisted, the Contracts will resolve to the last fair price determined at the discretion of the\nExchange. If the event is postponed, and such a postponement is announced by the end of the\nfollowing calendar day to be rescheduled to a time within 14 calendar days, the markets shall\nremain open. If the event captured in <time period> is a live-stream or broadcast, the\nExchange may keep the market open for 24 hours for the release of an official recording.\nFurther granular details on conditions for these Contracts is available below.\n\nAdditional clarification(s):\n\n     Possessive noun forms of <word>, plurals, and possessive plural noun forms are\n     INCLUDED:\n          <word> is “Immigrant” → “Immigrants” counts\n          <word> is “Egg” → “eggs’ shells” counts\n          <word> is “Russia” → “Russia’s” counts, “Russian” does not\n     If <word> exists only in adjective form, no plural form exists:\n          <word> is “Economic” → “Economics” does not count (“Economic” is an adjective\n          for which “Economics” is not a plural)\n     Plural nouns occurring within proper nouns and noun phrases are included:\n          <word> is “Cat” → “Cats the musical” counts\n\f    Grammatical variations beyond plurals/possessives are NOT included:\n         <word> is “Immigrant” → “Immigration” does NOT count\n         <word> is “Run” → “Running” or “Ran” do NOT count\n    When <word> specifies a plural form, the singular does NOT count:\n         <word> is “Veterans” → “Veteran” does NOT count\n    Words that are spelled the same as the plural form of <word> (if such exists) but are\n    themselves not a plural noun are included:\n         <word> is “Wind” → “Winds up the clock” counts\n         <word> is “Border” → “The United States has strong borders” counts\n    Open compounds (words separated by spaces) count:\n         <word> is “fire” → “fire station” counts\n         <word> is “couch” → “couch potato” counts\n    Hyphenated compounds (words connected by hyphens) count:\n         <word> is “Palestine” → “pro-Palestine” counts\n         <word> is “fat” → “non-fat” counts\n    Closed compounds (single word, no spaces/hyphens) do not count:\n         <word> is “fire” → “wildfire” does not count\n         <word> is “fire” → “firefighter” does not count\n    Multi-word <word> in larger constructions: When <word> is a multi-word phrase\n    appearing within a hyphenated construction, it counts only if <word> appears as a\n    complete, unmodified element:\n         <word> is “New York” → “New York-based” counts (complete element)\n    Portmanteaus (words blended from two words where parts of each are combined) are\n    NOT included unless the portmanteau clearly contains <word> as a distinct, unaltered\n    element:\n         <word> is “MAGA” → “MAGA-nificent” counts (MAGA appears as distinct element)\n         <word> is “magnificent” → “MAGA-nificent” does NOT count (portmanteau blend)\n\nDictionary determination: Both the Merriam-Webster Dictionary (available online) AND the\nOxford English Dictionary shall be used to determine compound type and/or conventional\nspelling patterns. Inclusion in either dictionary as an open or hyphenated compound shall\nsatisfy the Payout Criterion. If neither provides clarity (or the word is not included),\ndetermination is based on whether written as single unit (closed/doesn’t count) vs. spaces or\nhyphens (open or hyphenated/counts) and/or context and previous usage.\n\nPHONETIC EQUIVALENCIES\n\n    Homophones (same sound, different spelling) do not count:\n        <word> is “write” → “right” does not count\n    Homonyms and homographs (same spelling) COUNT regardless of meaning or\n    pronunciation:\n        <word> is “bass” → both “bass guitar” and “bass fishing” count\n    Proper and common nouns are treated identically:\n        <word> is “Apple” → both “Apple Inc.” and “apple” (fruit) count\n        <word> is “Will” → both “Will Smith” and “I will go” count\n    Minor unintentional mispronunciations COUNT if context makes intent clear:\n        <word> is “Mamdani” → “Mandani” counts\n    Severe mispronunciations that make <word> unrecognizable do NOT count.\n    Trademarked spellings do not count, even when pronounced identically, unless the word\n\fitself is the same:\n      <word> is “lift” → “Lyft” (pronounced “lift”) does not count\n      <word> is “uber” → “Uber” counts\nWords with non-standard transliteration to English count within reason, provided they are\nphonetically equivalent:\n      <word> is “Zelensky” → any of “Zelenski,” “Zelenskii,” “Zelensky,” or “Zelenskiy”\n      count if pronounced equivalently\nContractions do not count for their constituent words unless otherwise explicitly specified\nby the Exchange:\n      <word> is “not” → “won’t,” “can’t,” “don’t,” “isn’t” do not count\nNumbers spoken as words COUNT, when spoken exactly (not part of a larger number):\n      <word> is “five” → saying “five” or reading “$5” aloud as “five dollars” counts,\n      saying “five hundred” does NOT count\n      <word> is “410” → “four hundred ten”, “four one zero” or “four ten” counts\nOrdinals COUNT when <word> is written numerically OR a phrase that includes a\nnumber:\n      <word> is “January 6” → “January 6th” counts\n      <word> is “3” (written numerically) → “3rd” (spoken as “third”) counts\n      <word> is “Eight War” → “8 Wars” and “Eighth War” will count\nCardinal and ordinal number words are distinct:\n      <word> is “one” → “first” does NOT count\n      <word> is “first” → “one” does NOT count\nAcronyms and abbreviations count when pronunciation or letter-by-letter spelling\nmatches <word>:\n      <word> is “NASA” → “NASA” (pronounced “NAH-suh”) counts\n      <word> is “NASA” → “N-A-S-A” (spelled out) counts\nAcronyms and abbreviations count as <word> when pronounced as the full word:\n      <word> is “Doctor” → “Dr.” (pronounced “Doctor”) counts\nExpanded forms of acronyms do NOT count:\n      <word> is “AI” → “artificial intelligence” does not count\nWords in foreign languages do NOT count unless they are perfect cognates with an\nEnglish word:\n      <word> is “fire” → “fuego” (Spanish) does NOT count\nEnglish words within foreign sentences count:\n      <word> is “policy” → “Nuestra policy es clara” counts\n<word> in organization/company names counts:\n      <word> is “Securities” → “Bank of America Securities” counts\nWords in URLs, emails, handles, and hashtags (exclusive of domain structure, email\nprovider or symbols) are treated as compounds when spoken as complete words, with the\ntype of compound subject to aforementioned rules:\n      <word> is “fire” → “firestation.com” pronounced “fire station dot com” counts\n      <word> is “fire” → “wildfire.com” pronounced “wildfire dot com” does NOT count\n      <word> is “apple” → “apple.com” pronounced “apple dot com” does count\n      When presented in URL, email, handle, or hashtag form, <word> shall be treated as\n      a compound, not a multi-word word\nSung, rapped, or poetic words COUNT if phonetically recognizable:\n      <word> is “money” → “moneyyy” (extended in rap) counts\n      Extreme distortion making <word> unrecognizable does NOT count.\nPhonetic alphabet spelling (“Foxtrot India Romeo Echo” for “FIRE”) does NOT count.\n\fCANCELLATIONS AND DELAYS\n\n   The Exchange may list an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike for any Contract. If listed,\n   such a strike refers to the structural conditions of the market, and is NOT adjudicated as a\n   <word> needing to be said by or validated by having been said by <entity>. If listed, this\n   strike resolves to “Yes” whenever the event fails to occur or qualify under the Payout\n   Criterion, or any other circumstance prevents normal resolution.\n   If no such strike is listed, and <time period> refers to a specific event, the following rules\n   apply if the event is cancelled, postponed, rescheduled, or materially altered (including\n   being closed to press) such that no video is released within one calendar day of the\n   original start time of the event:\n         If the event is cancelled, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price determined in\n         the sole discretion of the Exchange.\n         If the event is postponed or rescheduled, the outcome depends on whether a new\n         date is publicly announced within one calendar day (i.e. if the event was scheduled\n         to begin on Monday, any time up to 11:59PM on Tuesday falls within this period) of\n         the originally scheduled start time:\n               If no new date is announced within one calendar day, the Contract will resolve\n               to the last fair price determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\n               If a new date is announced within one calendar day, the outcome depends on\n               when the rescheduled event is set to occur:\n                     If the rescheduled date falls within fourteen (14) calendar days of the\n                     originally scheduled date, the Contract shall remain open and <word>\n                     stated during the rescheduled event will count.\n                           The fourteen-day window begins at 12:00 AM ET on the originally\n                           scheduled date and ends at 11:59 PM ET fourteen days later, unless\n                           an alternate timezone is explicitly specified.\n                           Example: <time period> is “during the State of the Union on January\n                           15, 2026” rescheduled to January 20, 2026 → words spoken during\n                           the rescheduled address count.\n                     If the rescheduled date falls more than fourteen (14) calendar days after\n                     the originally scheduled date, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price\n                     determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\n         Any Contract that cannot be resolved through the Source Agency hierarchy will\n         instead be settled at the Last Fair Price. The Exchange will disclose the methodology\n         used to determine the Last Fair Price (e.g., Last Traded Price, Time-Weighted\n         Average Price) at the time of Issuance.\n         If an event begins but is interrupted, abbreviated, or ends prematurely, words\n         stated by <entity> during the portion of the event that did occur will count and the\n         market will otherwise resolve.\n   If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window but the venue, format, or medium\n   changes (e.g., moved to a different location, changed from in-person to virtual (with the\n   exception of being closed to press)), words stated during the event will count.\n   Special condition: Across both cases, whether an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike is\n   listed or not, if the event specified as or in <time period> is a live-stream or broadcast (or\n   relayed as such) but the live stream/broadcast does not occur, the Exchange will instead\n   use an officially released recording as the Underlying, and may delay resolution by up to\n   one calendar day to allow for the release of such a recording.\n\f          If partial snippets are released, Contracts on words that do not appear will be\n          resolved to last fair price, and Contracts on those that do will be resolved to “Yes”.\n          If no recording is released, the relevant outcomes triggered by the\n          presence/absence of an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike shall occur as outlined\n          above.\n\nTECHNICAL DETAILS (UNLESS OTHERWISE SPECIFIED)\n\n     When <time period> refers to a specific event, pre-recorded content broadcast,\n     streamed, or published as part of that event is included if presented as part of the official\n     presentation.\n          Example: <time period> is “during the concert” with pre-recorded video interlude\n          where entity speaks → words from interlude count\n          Example: <time period> is “during the television appearance” with pre-taped\n          segment aired during broadcast → words from segment count\n     Behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are NOT\n     included unless officially broadcast or published as part of <time period>.\n     Subtitles and captions that display <word> on screen but are not spoken aloud by\n     <entity> do NOT count.\n     Sign language interpretation or usage by entity does NOT count as saying <word> unless\n     the Contract explicitly specifies that sign language counts.\n     Text that entity displays on screen (presentation slides, teleprompter visible to audience,\n     signatures) does NOT count unless entity reads it aloud.\n     Content generated by AI, deepfakes, or synthetic voice technology impersonating entity\n     does NOT count unless the synthetic content is officially commissioned, authorized, or\n     published by entity, OR the Contract explicitly specifies that AI-generated content counts.\n     If <word> is muted due to technical failure or censorship it shall not count unless\n     corroborating contextual evidence (including surrounding speech, or an official\n     uncensored recording or transcript) confirms that <entity> specifically uttered <word>\n     during the muted period.\n\nMinimum Tick: The Minimum Tick size for the Contract shall be $0.01.\n\nPosition Accountability Level: The Position Accountability Level for the Contract shall be\n$25,000 per strike, per Member.\n\nLast Trading Date: The Last Trading Date of the Contract will be the Expiration Date. The Last\nTrading Time will be the Expiration time.\n\nSettlement Date: The Settlement Date of the Contract shall be no later than the day after the\nExpiration Date, unless the Market Outcome is under review pursuant to Rule 7.1.\n\nExpiration Date: When <time period> refers to a specific event: The latest Expiration Date of\nthe Contract shall be fourteen (14) calendar days after the originally scheduled date of the\nevent. If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window, expiration will be moved to an\nearlier date and time in accordance with Rule 7.2. When <time period> is defined by specific\ndates: The latest Expiration Date of the Contract shall be two weeks after the end of <time\nperiod>. If an event described in the Payout Criterion occurs and a consensus has been\nreached on all terms, then expiration will be moved to an earlier date and time in accordance\nwith Rule 7.2.\n\fExpiration time: The Expiration time of the Contract shall be 10:00 AM ET.\n\nSettlement Value: The Settlement Value for this Contract is $1.00.\n\nExpiration Value: The Expiration Value is the value of the Underlying as documented by the\nSource Agency on the Expiration Date at the Expiration time.\n\nContingencies: Before Settlement, Kalshi may, at its sole discretion, initiate the Market\nOutcome Review Process pursuant to Rule 7.1 of the Rulebook. If an Expiration Value cannot\nbe determined on the Expiration Date, Kalshi has the right to determine payouts pursuant to\nRule 7.1 in the Rulebook.\n\f\n\n[plaintiff] PX-3 Official White House World Cup Drawing video page capture\nSource capture from official White House page https://www.whitehouse.gov/videos/president-trump-attends-the-fifa-world-cup-drawing/\nRetrieval: 2026-06-29T21:52:12Z via OpenClaw web_fetch and web.open.\n\nVisible page facts captured:\n- Page title: President Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing\n- Date shown on page: December 5, 2025\n- Page section: Videos\n- The page contains a link labeled View Full Video to Instagram.\n- Related video listed: FIFA World Cup 2026 Draw at The Kennedy Center, duration 00:45, dated December 6, 2025.\n- Related video listed: FIFA World Cup Drawing Announced to Take Place at The Kennedy Center, duration 00:56, dated August 23, 2025.\n- Related video listed: President Trump on the 2026 FIFA World Cup, duration 01:22, dated May 6, 2025.\n\nRelevant extracted lines from web.open capture:\nL142: Videos\nL143: # President Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing\nL145: December 5, 2025\nL133: ... View Full Video [instagram.com] ...\nL151: FIFA World Cup 2026 Draw at The Kennedy Center\nL153: December 6, 2025\nL167-L170: President Trump on the 2026 FIFA World Cup, May 6, 2025\n\nNotes on capture limits: readability extraction returned minimal content, so the above preserves visible lines from the page capture. The embedded/full video itself was not captured in this item.\n\n[plaintiff] PX-4 YouTube metadata capture for Ronaldo-at-FIFA-Draw clip\nSource capture: YouTube watch page https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Cb2yO0lLEnM\nVideo ID: Cb2yO0lLEnM\nRetrieval: 2026-06-29T21:53:00Z via web search and curl of the YouTube watch page.\n\nCaptured title / page metadata:\n- Title shown in search and page metadata: Trump Talks Cristiano Ronaldo at FIFA Draw — ‘He’s a Great Person’\n- Channel shown in page metadata: interestingText You / @InterestingTextYou\n- Subscriber count shown in page metadata at capture: about 10.3K subscribers\n\nCaptured description text from YouTube page metadata:\n\"Trump Talks Cristiano Ronaldo at FIFA Draw — ‘He’s a Great Person’\n\nAt the FIFA World Cup Draw Ceremony, Donald Trump shared a story about meeting Cristiano Ronaldo at the White House. Trump said Ronaldo was “a great person” and even mentioned that Ronaldo spoke with his son about soccer during the visit.\n\nThis unexpected crossover between world politics and one of the biggest global sports stars quickly caught viewers' attention.\n\nTrump FIFA Draw\nDonald Trump FIFA World Cup\nTrump Cristiano Ronaldo\nCristiano Ronaldo Trump meeting\nFIFA World Cup draw 2026\nRonaldo White House visit\nTrump soccer comments\nWorld Cup trending 2025\nsports politics crossover\nCristiano Ronaldo story\nDonald Trump viral moment\nFIFA draw ceremony Trump\nWorld Cup 2026 news\nRonaldo fan reaction\npolitical celebrity moments\nviral sports clips 2025\nFIFA draw highlights\nTrump speech FIFA\nglobal sports news\"\n\nCapture limits and provenance caveat: direct video/caption extraction was attempted but YouTube transcript/open paths were throttled or unavailable in this environment. This item preserves the public watch-page metadata and description, not an independently extracted audio transcript. It is not an official White House or FIFA source.\n\n[defendant] DX-1 GovInfo official transcript: remarks prior to FIFA World Cup Draw\nSource: GovInfo, Compilation of Presidential Documents, DCPD202501162\nURL retrieved: https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/DCPD-202501162/html/DCPD-202501162.htm\nRetrieval time: 2026-06-29T22:00:00Z\nLocal captured HTML size/hash: 51,571 bytes; SHA-256 eadbceeecf3e94f5bd423bcb8e8511165fdc7265dd8c1e025870c2e8f34dfd99\n\nMaterial captured text from official GovInfo HTML/web.open:\n\nAdministration of Donald J. Trump, 2025\n\nTitle: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\nDate: December 5, 2025\n\nOpening note: [The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\n\nExcerpt - The President's Interest in Soccer (web.open lines 196-203):\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\"football,\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\n\nExcerpt - The President's Interest in Soccer (web.open lines 322-329):\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\nThe President. But they have a little more speed. But no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\n\nTiming/context note (web.open lines 461-462):\nNOTE: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. In his remarks, he referred to Trey Yingst, chief foreign correspondent, Fox News Channel; Cristiano Ronaldo, forward for Saudi Pro League club Al-Nass and Portugal's national soccer team; and Lionel Messi, forward for Major League Soccer club Inter Miami and Argentina's national team. A reporter referred to New York State Attorney General Letitia James.\nThe transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\n\nDocument category/location/name/subject metadata (web.open lines 463-468):\nCategories: Interviews With the News Media: Exchanges with reporters, Washington, DC.\nLocations: Washington, DC.\nNames include: Cristiano Ronaldo and Lionel Messi.\nSubjects include: Federation Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) World Cup; John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts; News media, Presidential interviews; Soccer.\nDCPD Number: DCPD202501162.\n\nCapture limits: This item is a focused text capture of the material official transcript title, Ronaldo excerpts, timing/correction note, and metadata. It is not a full video or audio artifact. The official transcript itself notes some portions could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\n\n[defendant] DX-2 FIFA official Final Draw start-time capture\nSource: FIFA official page, FIFA World Cup 2026 Final Draw\nURL: https://www.fifa.com/en/tournaments/mens/worldcup/canadamexicousa2026/live-draw\nRetrieval time: 2026-06-29T22:01:00Z\n\nMaterial captured text from web search/open result:\n- Page title/source: FIFA World Cup 2026™ Final Draw\n- The draw takes place at the Kennedy Center in Washington DC, USA.\n- The draw commences at 12:00 local time (17:00 UTC) on Friday 5 December 2025.\n\nCapture limits: This is a focused text capture of the official FIFA page timing statement located by web search. It is not a video capture of the draw ceremony.\n\n[defendant] DX-3 Governing PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION terms\n                                         NEWMENTION\n\nScope: These rules shall apply to this contract.\n\nUnderlying: The Underlying for this Contract is words used by <entity> <time period>.\nRevisions to the Underlying made after Expiration will not be accounted for in determining the\nExpiration Value.\n\nSource Agency: The Source Agencies are <source>.\n\nType: The type of Contract is an Event Contract.\n\nIssuance: After the initial Contract, Contract iterations will be listed on an as-needed basis at\nthe discretion of the Exchange and corresponding to the risk management needs of Members.\n\n<entity>: <entity> refers to the speaker, writer, performer, or communicator specified by the\nExchange. This may include (but is not limited to): a specific named individual, multiple\nindividuals specified using AND/OR logic, an individual identified by position or title, a group,\nband, team or collective entity, a specified member or members of a group, an organization,\ncompany, or institutional entity, or any combination of the aforementioned.\n\nWhen <entity> is defined by a position or title, the Contract tracks whoever holds that position\nduring <time period>, even if the individual holding the position changes. When <entity> is a\nspecific named individual, the identity remains consistent throughout. Name changes (e.g.,\nstage names, married names) do not create a new entity. When <entity> is a group or\norganization and the Contract does not specify particular members, any official\ncommunication or statement by any member or designated spokesperson counts. When using\nAND logic, all specified entities must independently say <word> during <time period>. When\nusing OR logic, at least one of the specified entities must say <word> during <time period>.\nThe Exchange may specify additional conditions such as “at least X members of” a group or\n“the majority of” a group.\n\n<source>: <source> refers to a Source Agency or ordered collection of Source Agencies\nspecified by the Exchange at the time of Contract listing, which will be incorporated into the\nSource Agency hierarchy above and used to determine the occurrence of the Underlying.\n<source> may refer to a singular agency, multiple agencies, an agency by distinguishing\ncharacteristics, by category or type (e.g., “official government statistical body,” “primary wire\nservice”), or any combination thereof. When multiple agencies are specified, they may be\napplied in the hierarchical order designated by the Exchange if so specified, with the highest-\nranked available and responsive agency taking precedence for purposes of determining the\nExpiration Value. A lower-ranked agency shall only be consulted if all higher-ranked agencies\nare unavailable, unresponsive, have not reported on the Underlying by the Expiration time, or\nif the Exchange, in its sole discretion, determines that a higher-ranked agency’s reporting is\nincomplete, erroneous, or otherwise insufficient to determine the Expiration Value. If <source>\ndesignates multiple agencies without specifying a hierarchical order, the Exchange shall\nresolve any conflict between reporting agencies at its sole discretion.\n\n<word>: <word> refers to the particular word or phrase potentially to be mentioned by\n<entity>. It may refer to a word being said a minimum number of times. It may also refer to\none of multiple words/phrases, any of which are acceptable (e.g., “Doge/Dogecoin”).\n\f<time period>: <time period> refers to a specific range of time, event or discrete date and\ntime specified by the Exchange. This may be defined by, but is not limited to: a specific event\nor context (e.g., “during the State of the Union address”), exact dates or times, relative time\nmarkers (e.g., “before July 1, 2027,” “in Q1 2026”), event-based periods (e.g., “during any\ncampaign rally in October 2026,” “during the awards ceremony”), and broader intervals (e.g.,\n“Q1–Q2 2027,” “January–March 2026”).\n\nUnless stated otherwise, “Between” is inclusive of both endpoints, while “before” and “after”\nexclude the specified date. <time period> may also refer to “Any” or “None”, to multiple dates\n(even if non-consecutive), or to a singular and discrete date or time.\n\nWhen <time period> refers to a specific event (such as an address, speech, performance, or\nbroadcast), the Exchange may specify what is included, including whether it includes both live\nand pre-recorded segments (including whether advertisements are included). Where a\ntimezone is not specified, ET is assumed.\n\n\nPayout Criterion: The Payout Criterion for the Contract encompasses the Expiration Values that\n<word> is said by <entity> <time period>.\n\n\nThe word must appear as a distinct, standalone unit, not buried inside another word. Plural\nand possessive noun forms count. Other grammatical changes (tense, conjugation, derivation)\ndo not. If <word> appears separated from other words by a space or hyphen or in a\ncompound form with a space or hyphen, it counts. If <word> is fused into a single\nunhyphenated word, it does not count.\n\nIf <time period> refers to an event and that event is cancelled, and the market contains a\nstrike stating “Event does not qualify/occur”, such a strike shall resolve “Yes” and all others\n“No”. If <time period> refers to an event and that event is cancelled but such strikes are NOT\nlisted, the Contracts will resolve to the last fair price determined at the discretion of the\nExchange. If the event is postponed, and such a postponement is announced by the end of the\nfollowing calendar day to be rescheduled to a time within 14 calendar days, the markets shall\nremain open. If the event captured in <time period> is a live-stream or broadcast, the\nExchange may keep the market open for 24 hours for the release of an official recording.\nFurther granular details on conditions for these Contracts is available below.\n\nAdditional clarification(s):\n\n     Possessive noun forms of <word>, plurals, and possessive plural noun forms are\n     INCLUDED:\n          <word> is “Immigrant” → “Immigrants” counts\n          <word> is “Egg” → “eggs’ shells” counts\n          <word> is “Russia” → “Russia’s” counts, “Russian” does not\n     If <word> exists only in adjective form, no plural form exists:\n          <word> is “Economic” → “Economics” does not count (“Economic” is an adjective\n          for which “Economics” is not a plural)\n     Plural nouns occurring within proper nouns and noun phrases are included:\n          <word> is “Cat” → “Cats the musical” counts\n\f    Grammatical variations beyond plurals/possessives are NOT included:\n         <word> is “Immigrant” → “Immigration” does NOT count\n         <word> is “Run” → “Running” or “Ran” do NOT count\n    When <word> specifies a plural form, the singular does NOT count:\n         <word> is “Veterans” → “Veteran” does NOT count\n    Words that are spelled the same as the plural form of <word> (if such exists) but are\n    themselves not a plural noun are included:\n         <word> is “Wind” → “Winds up the clock” counts\n         <word> is “Border” → “The United States has strong borders” counts\n    Open compounds (words separated by spaces) count:\n         <word> is “fire” → “fire station” counts\n         <word> is “couch” → “couch potato” counts\n    Hyphenated compounds (words connected by hyphens) count:\n         <word> is “Palestine” → “pro-Palestine” counts\n         <word> is “fat” → “non-fat” counts\n    Closed compounds (single word, no spaces/hyphens) do not count:\n         <word> is “fire” → “wildfire” does not count\n         <word> is “fire” → “firefighter” does not count\n    Multi-word <word> in larger constructions: When <word> is a multi-word phrase\n    appearing within a hyphenated construction, it counts only if <word> appears as a\n    complete, unmodified element:\n         <word> is “New York” → “New York-based” counts (complete element)\n    Portmanteaus (words blended from two words where parts of each are combined) are\n    NOT included unless the portmanteau clearly contains <word> as a distinct, unaltered\n    element:\n         <word> is “MAGA” → “MAGA-nificent” counts (MAGA appears as distinct element)\n         <word> is “magnificent” → “MAGA-nificent” does NOT count (portmanteau blend)\n\nDictionary determination: Both the Merriam-Webster Dictionary (available online) AND the\nOxford English Dictionary shall be used to determine compound type and/or conventional\nspelling patterns. Inclusion in either dictionary as an open or hyphenated compound shall\nsatisfy the Payout Criterion. If neither provides clarity (or the word is not included),\ndetermination is based on whether written as single unit (closed/doesn’t count) vs. spaces or\nhyphens (open or hyphenated/counts) and/or context and previous usage.\n\nPHONETIC EQUIVALENCIES\n\n    Homophones (same sound, different spelling) do not count:\n        <word> is “write” → “right” does not count\n    Homonyms and homographs (same spelling) COUNT regardless of meaning or\n    pronunciation:\n        <word> is “bass” → both “bass guitar” and “bass fishing” count\n    Proper and common nouns are treated identically:\n        <word> is “Apple” → both “Apple Inc.” and “apple” (fruit) count\n        <word> is “Will” → both “Will Smith” and “I will go” count\n    Minor unintentional mispronunciations COUNT if context makes intent clear:\n        <word> is “Mamdani” → “Mandani” counts\n    Severe mispronunciations that make <word> unrecognizable do NOT count.\n    Trademarked spellings do not count, even when pronounced identically, unless the word\n\fitself is the same:\n      <word> is “lift” → “Lyft” (pronounced “lift”) does not count\n      <word> is “uber” → “Uber” counts\nWords with non-standard transliteration to English count within reason, provided they are\nphonetically equivalent:\n      <word> is “Zelensky” → any of “Zelenski,” “Zelenskii,” “Zelensky,” or “Zelenskiy”\n      count if pronounced equivalently\nContractions do not count for their constituent words unless otherwise explicitly specified\nby the Exchange:\n      <word> is “not” → “won’t,” “can’t,” “don’t,” “isn’t” do not count\nNumbers spoken as words COUNT, when spoken exactly (not part of a larger number):\n      <word> is “five” → saying “five” or reading “$5” aloud as “five dollars” counts,\n      saying “five hundred” does NOT count\n      <word> is “410” → “four hundred ten”, “four one zero” or “four ten” counts\nOrdinals COUNT when <word> is written numerically OR a phrase that includes a\nnumber:\n      <word> is “January 6” → “January 6th” counts\n      <word> is “3” (written numerically) → “3rd” (spoken as “third”) counts\n      <word> is “Eight War” → “8 Wars” and “Eighth War” will count\nCardinal and ordinal number words are distinct:\n      <word> is “one” → “first” does NOT count\n      <word> is “first” → “one” does NOT count\nAcronyms and abbreviations count when pronunciation or letter-by-letter spelling\nmatches <word>:\n      <word> is “NASA” → “NASA” (pronounced “NAH-suh”) counts\n      <word> is “NASA” → “N-A-S-A” (spelled out) counts\nAcronyms and abbreviations count as <word> when pronounced as the full word:\n      <word> is “Doctor” → “Dr.” (pronounced “Doctor”) counts\nExpanded forms of acronyms do NOT count:\n      <word> is “AI” → “artificial intelligence” does not count\nWords in foreign languages do NOT count unless they are perfect cognates with an\nEnglish word:\n      <word> is “fire” → “fuego” (Spanish) does NOT count\nEnglish words within foreign sentences count:\n      <word> is “policy” → “Nuestra policy es clara” counts\n<word> in organization/company names counts:\n      <word> is “Securities” → “Bank of America Securities” counts\nWords in URLs, emails, handles, and hashtags (exclusive of domain structure, email\nprovider or symbols) are treated as compounds when spoken as complete words, with the\ntype of compound subject to aforementioned rules:\n      <word> is “fire” → “firestation.com” pronounced “fire station dot com” counts\n      <word> is “fire” → “wildfire.com” pronounced “wildfire dot com” does NOT count\n      <word> is “apple” → “apple.com” pronounced “apple dot com” does count\n      When presented in URL, email, handle, or hashtag form, <word> shall be treated as\n      a compound, not a multi-word word\nSung, rapped, or poetic words COUNT if phonetically recognizable:\n      <word> is “money” → “moneyyy” (extended in rap) counts\n      Extreme distortion making <word> unrecognizable does NOT count.\nPhonetic alphabet spelling (“Foxtrot India Romeo Echo” for “FIRE”) does NOT count.\n\fCANCELLATIONS AND DELAYS\n\n   The Exchange may list an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike for any Contract. If listed,\n   such a strike refers to the structural conditions of the market, and is NOT adjudicated as a\n   <word> needing to be said by or validated by having been said by <entity>. If listed, this\n   strike resolves to “Yes” whenever the event fails to occur or qualify under the Payout\n   Criterion, or any other circumstance prevents normal resolution.\n   If no such strike is listed, and <time period> refers to a specific event, the following rules\n   apply if the event is cancelled, postponed, rescheduled, or materially altered (including\n   being closed to press) such that no video is released within one calendar day of the\n   original start time of the event:\n         If the event is cancelled, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price determined in\n         the sole discretion of the Exchange.\n         If the event is postponed or rescheduled, the outcome depends on whether a new\n         date is publicly announced within one calendar day (i.e. if the event was scheduled\n         to begin on Monday, any time up to 11:59PM on Tuesday falls within this period) of\n         the originally scheduled start time:\n               If no new date is announced within one calendar day, the Contract will resolve\n               to the last fair price determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\n               If a new date is announced within one calendar day, the outcome depends on\n               when the rescheduled event is set to occur:\n                     If the rescheduled date falls within fourteen (14) calendar days of the\n                     originally scheduled date, the Contract shall remain open and <word>\n                     stated during the rescheduled event will count.\n                           The fourteen-day window begins at 12:00 AM ET on the originally\n                           scheduled date and ends at 11:59 PM ET fourteen days later, unless\n                           an alternate timezone is explicitly specified.\n                           Example: <time period> is “during the State of the Union on January\n                           15, 2026” rescheduled to January 20, 2026 → words spoken during\n                           the rescheduled address count.\n                     If the rescheduled date falls more than fourteen (14) calendar days after\n                     the originally scheduled date, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price\n                     determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\n         Any Contract that cannot be resolved through the Source Agency hierarchy will\n         instead be settled at the Last Fair Price. The Exchange will disclose the methodology\n         used to determine the Last Fair Price (e.g., Last Traded Price, Time-Weighted\n         Average Price) at the time of Issuance.\n         If an event begins but is interrupted, abbreviated, or ends prematurely, words\n         stated by <entity> during the portion of the event that did occur will count and the\n         market will otherwise resolve.\n   If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window but the venue, format, or medium\n   changes (e.g., moved to a different location, changed from in-person to virtual (with the\n   exception of being closed to press)), words stated during the event will count.\n   Special condition: Across both cases, whether an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike is\n   listed or not, if the event specified as or in <time period> is a live-stream or broadcast (or\n   relayed as such) but the live stream/broadcast does not occur, the Exchange will instead\n   use an officially released recording as the Underlying, and may delay resolution by up to\n   one calendar day to allow for the release of such a recording.\n\f          If partial snippets are released, Contracts on words that do not appear will be\n          resolved to last fair price, and Contracts on those that do will be resolved to “Yes”.\n          If no recording is released, the relevant outcomes triggered by the\n          presence/absence of an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike shall occur as outlined\n          above.\n\nTECHNICAL DETAILS (UNLESS OTHERWISE SPECIFIED)\n\n     When <time period> refers to a specific event, pre-recorded content broadcast,\n     streamed, or published as part of that event is included if presented as part of the official\n     presentation.\n          Example: <time period> is “during the concert” with pre-recorded video interlude\n          where entity speaks → words from interlude count\n          Example: <time period> is “during the television appearance” with pre-taped\n          segment aired during broadcast → words from segment count\n     Behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are NOT\n     included unless officially broadcast or published as part of <time period>.\n     Subtitles and captions that display <word> on screen but are not spoken aloud by\n     <entity> do NOT count.\n     Sign language interpretation or usage by entity does NOT count as saying <word> unless\n     the Contract explicitly specifies that sign language counts.\n     Text that entity displays on screen (presentation slides, teleprompter visible to audience,\n     signatures) does NOT count unless entity reads it aloud.\n     Content generated by AI, deepfakes, or synthetic voice technology impersonating entity\n     does NOT count unless the synthetic content is officially commissioned, authorized, or\n     published by entity, OR the Contract explicitly specifies that AI-generated content counts.\n     If <word> is muted due to technical failure or censorship it shall not count unless\n     corroborating contextual evidence (including surrounding speech, or an official\n     uncensored recording or transcript) confirms that <entity> specifically uttered <word>\n     during the muted period.\n\nMinimum Tick: The Minimum Tick size for the Contract shall be $0.01.\n\nPosition Accountability Level: The Position Accountability Level for the Contract shall be\n$25,000 per strike, per Member.\n\nLast Trading Date: The Last Trading Date of the Contract will be the Expiration Date. The Last\nTrading Time will be the Expiration time.\n\nSettlement Date: The Settlement Date of the Contract shall be no later than the day after the\nExpiration Date, unless the Market Outcome is under review pursuant to Rule 7.1.\n\nExpiration Date: When <time period> refers to a specific event: The latest Expiration Date of\nthe Contract shall be fourteen (14) calendar days after the originally scheduled date of the\nevent. If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window, expiration will be moved to an\nearlier date and time in accordance with Rule 7.2. When <time period> is defined by specific\ndates: The latest Expiration Date of the Contract shall be two weeks after the end of <time\nperiod>. If an event described in the Payout Criterion occurs and a consensus has been\nreached on all terms, then expiration will be moved to an earlier date and time in accordance\nwith Rule 7.2.\n\fExpiration time: The Expiration time of the Contract shall be 10:00 AM ET.\n\nSettlement Value: The Settlement Value for this Contract is $1.00.\n\nExpiration Value: The Expiration Value is the value of the Underlying as documented by the\nSource Agency on the Expiration Date at the Expiration time.\n\nContingencies: Before Settlement, Kalshi may, at its sole discretion, initiate the Market\nOutcome Review Process pursuant to Rule 7.1 of the Rulebook. If an Expiration Value cannot\nbe determined on the Expiration Date, Kalshi has the right to determine payouts pursuant to\nRule 7.1 in the Rulebook.\n\f\n\n[defendant] DX-4 Market packet: Ronaldo strike and challenged No resolution\nMarket URL: https://kalshi.com/markets/kxtrumpmentionb/trump-mention-b/kxtrumpmentionb-25dec06\n\nPublic market title: What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\n\nContract family: PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION\n\nStrike at issue: Ronaldo\n\nChallenged resolution: No\n\nRequested resolution: Yes\n\n\n[plaintiff] PX-R1 GovInfo transcript confirming Ronaldo utterances and Kennedy Center/FIFA Draw context\nSource: GovInfo, Compilation of Presidential Documents, DCPD202501162\nURL retrieved: https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/DCPD-202501162/html/DCPD-202501162.htm\nRetrieval time: 2026-06-29T22:00:00Z\nLocal captured HTML size/hash: 51,571 bytes; SHA-256 eadbceeecf3e94f5bd423bcb8e8511165fdc7265dd8c1e025870c2e8f34dfd99\n\nMaterial captured text from official GovInfo HTML/web.open:\n\nAdministration of Donald J. Trump, 2025\n\nTitle: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\nDate: December 5, 2025\n\nOpening note: [The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\n\nExcerpt - The President's Interest in Soccer (web.open lines 196-203):\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\"football,\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\n\nExcerpt - The President's Interest in Soccer (web.open lines 322-329):\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\nThe President. But they have a little more speed. But no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\n\nTiming/context note (web.open lines 461-462):\nNOTE: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. In his remarks, he referred to Trey Yingst, chief foreign correspondent, Fox News Channel; Cristiano Ronaldo, forward for Saudi Pro League club Al-Nass and Portugal's national soccer team; and Lionel Messi, forward for Major League Soccer club Inter Miami and Argentina's national team. A reporter referred to New York State Attorney General Letitia James.\nThe transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\n\nDocument category/location/name/subject metadata (web.open lines 463-468):\nCategories: Interviews With the News Media: Exchanges with reporters, Washington, DC.\nLocations: Washington, DC.\nNames include: Cristiano Ronaldo and Lionel Messi.\nSubjects include: Federation Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) World Cup; John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts; News media, Presidential interviews; Soccer.\nDCPD Number: DCPD202501162.\n\nCapture limits: This item is a focused text capture of the material official transcript title, Ronaldo excerpts, timing/correction note, and metadata. It is not a full video or audio artifact. The official transcript itself notes some portions could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\n\n[plaintiff] PX-R2 FIFA timing capture showing formal commencement time but not market-specific exclusion\nSource: FIFA official page, FIFA World Cup 2026 Final Draw\nURL: https://www.fifa.com/en/tournaments/mens/worldcup/canadamexicousa2026/live-draw\nRetrieval time: 2026-06-29T22:01:00Z\n\nMaterial captured text from web search/open result:\n- Page title/source: FIFA World Cup 2026™ Final Draw\n- The draw takes place at the Kennedy Center in Washington DC, USA.\n- The draw commences at 12:00 local time (17:00 UTC) on Friday 5 December 2025.\n\nCapture limits: This is a focused text capture of the official FIFA page timing statement located by web search. It is not a video capture of the draw ceremony.\n\n[plaintiff] PX-R3 Event-period terms and exclusions\n                                         NEWMENTION\n\nScope: These rules shall apply to this contract.\n\nUnderlying: The Underlying for this Contract is words used by <entity> <time period>.\nRevisions to the Underlying made after Expiration will not be accounted for in determining the\nExpiration Value.\n\nSource Agency: The Source Agencies are <source>.\n\nType: The type of Contract is an Event Contract.\n\nIssuance: After the initial Contract, Contract iterations will be listed on an as-needed basis at\nthe discretion of the Exchange and corresponding to the risk management needs of Members.\n\n<entity>: <entity> refers to the speaker, writer, performer, or communicator specified by the\nExchange. This may include (but is not limited to): a specific named individual, multiple\nindividuals specified using AND/OR logic, an individual identified by position or title, a group,\nband, team or collective entity, a specified member or members of a group, an organization,\ncompany, or institutional entity, or any combination of the aforementioned.\n\nWhen <entity> is defined by a position or title, the Contract tracks whoever holds that position\nduring <time period>, even if the individual holding the position changes. When <entity> is a\nspecific named individual, the identity remains consistent throughout. Name changes (e.g.,\nstage names, married names) do not create a new entity. When <entity> is a group or\norganization and the Contract does not specify particular members, any official\ncommunication or statement by any member or designated spokesperson counts. When using\nAND logic, all specified entities must independently say <word> during <time period>. When\nusing OR logic, at least one of the specified entities must say <word> during <time period>.\nThe Exchange may specify additional conditions such as “at least X members of” a group or\n“the majority of” a group.\n\n<source>: <source> refers to a Source Agency or ordered collection of Source Agencies\nspecified by the Exchange at the time of Contract listing, which will be incorporated into the\nSource Agency hierarchy above and used to determine the occurrence of the Underlying.\n<source> may refer to a singular agency, multiple agencies, an agency by distinguishing\ncharacteristics, by category or type (e.g., “official government statistical body,” “primary wire\nservice”), or any combination thereof. When multiple agencies are specified, they may be\napplied in the hierarchical order designated by the Exchange if so specified, with the highest-\nranked available and responsive agency taking precedence for purposes of determining the\nExpiration Value. A lower-ranked agency shall only be consulted if all higher-ranked agencies\nare unavailable, unresponsive, have not reported on the Underlying by the Expiration time, or\nif the Exchange, in its sole discretion, determines that a higher-ranked agency’s reporting is\nincomplete, erroneous, or otherwise insufficient to determine the Expiration Value. If <source>\ndesignates multiple agencies without specifying a hierarchical order, the Exchange shall\nresolve any conflict between reporting agencies at its sole discretion.\n\n<word>: <word> refers to the particular word or phrase potentially to be mentioned by\n<entity>. It may refer to a word being said a minimum number of times. It may also refer to\none of multiple words/phrases, any of which are acceptable (e.g., “Doge/Dogecoin”).\n\f<time period>: <time period> refers to a specific range of time, event or discrete date and\ntime specified by the Exchange. This may be defined by, but is not limited to: a specific event\nor context (e.g., “during the State of the Union address”), exact dates or times, relative time\nmarkers (e.g., “before July 1, 2027,” “in Q1 2026”), event-based periods (e.g., “during any\ncampaign rally in October 2026,” “during the awards ceremony”), and broader intervals (e.g.,\n“Q1–Q2 2027,” “January–March 2026”).\n\nUnless stated otherwise, “Between” is inclusive of both endpoints, while “before” and “after”\nexclude the specified date. <time period> may also refer to “Any” or “None”, to multiple dates\n(even if non-consecutive), or to a singular and discrete date or time.\n\nWhen <time period> refers to a specific event (such as an address, speech, performance, or\nbroadcast), the Exchange may specify what is included, including whether it includes both live\nand pre-recorded segments (including whether advertisements are included). Where a\ntimezone is not specified, ET is assumed.\n\n\nPayout Criterion: The Payout Criterion for the Contract encompasses the Expiration Values that\n<word> is said by <entity> <time period>.\n\n\nThe word must appear as a distinct, standalone unit, not buried inside another word. Plural\nand possessive noun forms count. Other grammatical changes (tense, conjugation, derivation)\ndo not. If <word> appears separated from other words by a space or hyphen or in a\ncompound form with a space or hyphen, it counts. If <word> is fused into a single\nunhyphenated word, it does not count.\n\nIf <time period> refers to an event and that event is cancelled, and the market contains a\nstrike stating “Event does not qualify/occur”, such a strike shall resolve “Yes” and all others\n“No”. If <time period> refers to an event and that event is cancelled but such strikes are NOT\nlisted, the Contracts will resolve to the last fair price determined at the discretion of the\nExchange. If the event is postponed, and such a postponement is announced by the end of the\nfollowing calendar day to be rescheduled to a time within 14 calendar days, the markets shall\nremain open. If the event captured in <time period> is a live-stream or broadcast, the\nExchange may keep the market open for 24 hours for the release of an official recording.\nFurther granular details on conditions for these Contracts is available below.\n\nAdditional clarification(s):\n\n     Possessive noun forms of <word>, plurals, and possessive plural noun forms are\n     INCLUDED:\n          <word> is “Immigrant” → “Immigrants” counts\n          <word> is “Egg” → “eggs’ shells” counts\n          <word> is “Russia” → “Russia’s” counts, “Russian” does not\n     If <word> exists only in adjective form, no plural form exists:\n          <word> is “Economic” → “Economics” does not count (“Economic” is an adjective\n          for which “Economics” is not a plural)\n     Plural nouns occurring within proper nouns and noun phrases are included:\n          <word> is “Cat” → “Cats the musical” counts\n\f    Grammatical variations beyond plurals/possessives are NOT included:\n         <word> is “Immigrant” → “Immigration” does NOT count\n         <word> is “Run” → “Running” or “Ran” do NOT count\n    When <word> specifies a plural form, the singular does NOT count:\n         <word> is “Veterans” → “Veteran” does NOT count\n    Words that are spelled the same as the plural form of <word> (if such exists) but are\n    themselves not a plural noun are included:\n         <word> is “Wind” → “Winds up the clock” counts\n         <word> is “Border” → “The United States has strong borders” counts\n    Open compounds (words separated by spaces) count:\n         <word> is “fire” → “fire station” counts\n         <word> is “couch” → “couch potato” counts\n    Hyphenated compounds (words connected by hyphens) count:\n         <word> is “Palestine” → “pro-Palestine” counts\n         <word> is “fat” → “non-fat” counts\n    Closed compounds (single word, no spaces/hyphens) do not count:\n         <word> is “fire” → “wildfire” does not count\n         <word> is “fire” → “firefighter” does not count\n    Multi-word <word> in larger constructions: When <word> is a multi-word phrase\n    appearing within a hyphenated construction, it counts only if <word> appears as a\n    complete, unmodified element:\n         <word> is “New York” → “New York-based” counts (complete element)\n    Portmanteaus (words blended from two words where parts of each are combined) are\n    NOT included unless the portmanteau clearly contains <word> as a distinct, unaltered\n    element:\n         <word> is “MAGA” → “MAGA-nificent” counts (MAGA appears as distinct element)\n         <word> is “magnificent” → “MAGA-nificent” does NOT count (portmanteau blend)\n\nDictionary determination: Both the Merriam-Webster Dictionary (available online) AND the\nOxford English Dictionary shall be used to determine compound type and/or conventional\nspelling patterns. Inclusion in either dictionary as an open or hyphenated compound shall\nsatisfy the Payout Criterion. If neither provides clarity (or the word is not included),\ndetermination is based on whether written as single unit (closed/doesn’t count) vs. spaces or\nhyphens (open or hyphenated/counts) and/or context and previous usage.\n\nPHONETIC EQUIVALENCIES\n\n    Homophones (same sound, different spelling) do not count:\n        <word> is “write” → “right” does not count\n    Homonyms and homographs (same spelling) COUNT regardless of meaning or\n    pronunciation:\n        <word> is “bass” → both “bass guitar” and “bass fishing” count\n    Proper and common nouns are treated identically:\n        <word> is “Apple” → both “Apple Inc.” and “apple” (fruit) count\n        <word> is “Will” → both “Will Smith” and “I will go” count\n    Minor unintentional mispronunciations COUNT if context makes intent clear:\n        <word> is “Mamdani” → “Mandani” counts\n    Severe mispronunciations that make <word> unrecognizable do NOT count.\n    Trademarked spellings do not count, even when pronounced identically, unless the word\n\fitself is the same:\n      <word> is “lift” → “Lyft” (pronounced “lift”) does not count\n      <word> is “uber” → “Uber” counts\nWords with non-standard transliteration to English count within reason, provided they are\nphonetically equivalent:\n      <word> is “Zelensky” → any of “Zelenski,” “Zelenskii,” “Zelensky,” or “Zelenskiy”\n      count if pronounced equivalently\nContractions do not count for their constituent words unless otherwise explicitly specified\nby the Exchange:\n      <word> is “not” → “won’t,” “can’t,” “don’t,” “isn’t” do not count\nNumbers spoken as words COUNT, when spoken exactly (not part of a larger number):\n      <word> is “five” → saying “five” or reading “$5” aloud as “five dollars” counts,\n      saying “five hundred” does NOT count\n      <word> is “410” → “four hundred ten”, “four one zero” or “four ten” counts\nOrdinals COUNT when <word> is written numerically OR a phrase that includes a\nnumber:\n      <word> is “January 6” → “January 6th” counts\n      <word> is “3” (written numerically) → “3rd” (spoken as “third”) counts\n      <word> is “Eight War” → “8 Wars” and “Eighth War” will count\nCardinal and ordinal number words are distinct:\n      <word> is “one” → “first” does NOT count\n      <word> is “first” → “one” does NOT count\nAcronyms and abbreviations count when pronunciation or letter-by-letter spelling\nmatches <word>:\n      <word> is “NASA” → “NASA” (pronounced “NAH-suh”) counts\n      <word> is “NASA” → “N-A-S-A” (spelled out) counts\nAcronyms and abbreviations count as <word> when pronounced as the full word:\n      <word> is “Doctor” → “Dr.” (pronounced “Doctor”) counts\nExpanded forms of acronyms do NOT count:\n      <word> is “AI” → “artificial intelligence” does not count\nWords in foreign languages do NOT count unless they are perfect cognates with an\nEnglish word:\n      <word> is “fire” → “fuego” (Spanish) does NOT count\nEnglish words within foreign sentences count:\n      <word> is “policy” → “Nuestra policy es clara” counts\n<word> in organization/company names counts:\n      <word> is “Securities” → “Bank of America Securities” counts\nWords in URLs, emails, handles, and hashtags (exclusive of domain structure, email\nprovider or symbols) are treated as compounds when spoken as complete words, with the\ntype of compound subject to aforementioned rules:\n      <word> is “fire” → “firestation.com” pronounced “fire station dot com” counts\n      <word> is “fire” → “wildfire.com” pronounced “wildfire dot com” does NOT count\n      <word> is “apple” → “apple.com” pronounced “apple dot com” does count\n      When presented in URL, email, handle, or hashtag form, <word> shall be treated as\n      a compound, not a multi-word word\nSung, rapped, or poetic words COUNT if phonetically recognizable:\n      <word> is “money” → “moneyyy” (extended in rap) counts\n      Extreme distortion making <word> unrecognizable does NOT count.\nPhonetic alphabet spelling (“Foxtrot India Romeo Echo” for “FIRE”) does NOT count.\n\fCANCELLATIONS AND DELAYS\n\n   The Exchange may list an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike for any Contract. If listed,\n   such a strike refers to the structural conditions of the market, and is NOT adjudicated as a\n   <word> needing to be said by or validated by having been said by <entity>. If listed, this\n   strike resolves to “Yes” whenever the event fails to occur or qualify under the Payout\n   Criterion, or any other circumstance prevents normal resolution.\n   If no such strike is listed, and <time period> refers to a specific event, the following rules\n   apply if the event is cancelled, postponed, rescheduled, or materially altered (including\n   being closed to press) such that no video is released within one calendar day of the\n   original start time of the event:\n         If the event is cancelled, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price determined in\n         the sole discretion of the Exchange.\n         If the event is postponed or rescheduled, the outcome depends on whether a new\n         date is publicly announced within one calendar day (i.e. if the event was scheduled\n         to begin on Monday, any time up to 11:59PM on Tuesday falls within this period) of\n         the originally scheduled start time:\n               If no new date is announced within one calendar day, the Contract will resolve\n               to the last fair price determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\n               If a new date is announced within one calendar day, the outcome depends on\n               when the rescheduled event is set to occur:\n                     If the rescheduled date falls within fourteen (14) calendar days of the\n                     originally scheduled date, the Contract shall remain open and <word>\n                     stated during the rescheduled event will count.\n                           The fourteen-day window begins at 12:00 AM ET on the originally\n                           scheduled date and ends at 11:59 PM ET fourteen days later, unless\n                           an alternate timezone is explicitly specified.\n                           Example: <time period> is “during the State of the Union on January\n                           15, 2026” rescheduled to January 20, 2026 → words spoken during\n                           the rescheduled address count.\n                     If the rescheduled date falls more than fourteen (14) calendar days after\n                     the originally scheduled date, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price\n                     determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\n         Any Contract that cannot be resolved through the Source Agency hierarchy will\n         instead be settled at the Last Fair Price. The Exchange will disclose the methodology\n         used to determine the Last Fair Price (e.g., Last Traded Price, Time-Weighted\n         Average Price) at the time of Issuance.\n         If an event begins but is interrupted, abbreviated, or ends prematurely, words\n         stated by <entity> during the portion of the event that did occur will count and the\n         market will otherwise resolve.\n   If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window but the venue, format, or medium\n   changes (e.g., moved to a different location, changed from in-person to virtual (with the\n   exception of being closed to press)), words stated during the event will count.\n   Special condition: Across both cases, whether an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike is\n   listed or not, if the event specified as or in <time period> is a live-stream or broadcast (or\n   relayed as such) but the live stream/broadcast does not occur, the Exchange will instead\n   use an officially released recording as the Underlying, and may delay resolution by up to\n   one calendar day to allow for the release of such a recording.\n\f          If partial snippets are released, Contracts on words that do not appear will be\n          resolved to last fair price, and Contracts on those that do will be resolved to “Yes”.\n          If no recording is released, the relevant outcomes triggered by the\n          presence/absence of an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike shall occur as outlined\n          above.\n\nTECHNICAL DETAILS (UNLESS OTHERWISE SPECIFIED)\n\n     When <time period> refers to a specific event, pre-recorded content broadcast,\n     streamed, or published as part of that event is included if presented as part of the official\n     presentation.\n          Example: <time period> is “during the concert” with pre-recorded video interlude\n          where entity speaks → words from interlude count\n          Example: <time period> is “during the television appearance” with pre-taped\n          segment aired during broadcast → words from segment count\n     Behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are NOT\n     included unless officially broadcast or published as part of <time period>.\n     Subtitles and captions that display <word> on screen but are not spoken aloud by\n     <entity> do NOT count.\n     Sign language interpretation or usage by entity does NOT count as saying <word> unless\n     the Contract explicitly specifies that sign language counts.\n     Text that entity displays on screen (presentation slides, teleprompter visible to audience,\n     signatures) does NOT count unless entity reads it aloud.\n     Content generated by AI, deepfakes, or synthetic voice technology impersonating entity\n     does NOT count unless the synthetic content is officially commissioned, authorized, or\n     published by entity, OR the Contract explicitly specifies that AI-generated content counts.\n     If <word> is muted due to technical failure or censorship it shall not count unless\n     corroborating contextual evidence (including surrounding speech, or an official\n     uncensored recording or transcript) confirms that <entity> specifically uttered <word>\n     during the muted period.\n\nMinimum Tick: The Minimum Tick size for the Contract shall be $0.01.\n\nPosition Accountability Level: The Position Accountability Level for the Contract shall be\n$25,000 per strike, per Member.\n\nLast Trading Date: The Last Trading Date of the Contract will be the Expiration Date. The Last\nTrading Time will be the Expiration time.\n\nSettlement Date: The Settlement Date of the Contract shall be no later than the day after the\nExpiration Date, unless the Market Outcome is under review pursuant to Rule 7.1.\n\nExpiration Date: When <time period> refers to a specific event: The latest Expiration Date of\nthe Contract shall be fourteen (14) calendar days after the originally scheduled date of the\nevent. If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window, expiration will be moved to an\nearlier date and time in accordance with Rule 7.2. When <time period> is defined by specific\ndates: The latest Expiration Date of the Contract shall be two weeks after the end of <time\nperiod>. If an event described in the Payout Criterion occurs and a consensus has been\nreached on all terms, then expiration will be moved to an earlier date and time in accordance\nwith Rule 7.2.\n\fExpiration time: The Expiration time of the Contract shall be 10:00 AM ET.\n\nSettlement Value: The Settlement Value for this Contract is $1.00.\n\nExpiration Value: The Expiration Value is the value of the Underlying as documented by the\nSource Agency on the Expiration Date at the Expiration time.\n\nContingencies: Before Settlement, Kalshi may, at its sole discretion, initiate the Market\nOutcome Review Process pursuant to Rule 7.1 of the Rulebook. If an Expiration Value cannot\nbe determined on the Expiration Date, Kalshi has the right to determine payouts pursuant to\nRule 7.1 in the Rulebook.\n\f\n\n[defendant] DX-S1 GovInfo official transcript: prior reporter exchange\nSource: GovInfo, Compilation of Presidential Documents, DCPD202501162\nURL retrieved: https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/DCPD-202501162/html/DCPD-202501162.htm\nRetrieval time: 2026-06-29T22:00:00Z\nLocal captured HTML size/hash: 51,571 bytes; SHA-256 eadbceeecf3e94f5bd423bcb8e8511165fdc7265dd8c1e025870c2e8f34dfd99\n\nMaterial captured text from official GovInfo HTML/web.open:\n\nAdministration of Donald J. Trump, 2025\n\nTitle: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\nDate: December 5, 2025\n\nOpening note: [The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\n\nExcerpt - The President's Interest in Soccer (web.open lines 196-203):\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\"football,\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\n\nExcerpt - The President's Interest in Soccer (web.open lines 322-329):\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\nThe President. But they have a little more speed. But no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\n\nTiming/context note (web.open lines 461-462):\nNOTE: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. In his remarks, he referred to Trey Yingst, chief foreign correspondent, Fox News Channel; Cristiano Ronaldo, forward for Saudi Pro League club Al-Nass and Portugal's national soccer team; and Lionel Messi, forward for Major League Soccer club Inter Miami and Argentina's national team. A reporter referred to New York State Attorney General Letitia James.\nThe transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\n\nDocument category/location/name/subject metadata (web.open lines 463-468):\nCategories: Interviews With the News Media: Exchanges with reporters, Washington, DC.\nLocations: Washington, DC.\nNames include: Cristiano Ronaldo and Lionel Messi.\nSubjects include: Federation Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) World Cup; John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts; News media, Presidential interviews; Soccer.\nDCPD Number: DCPD202501162.\n\nCapture limits: This item is a focused text capture of the material official transcript title, Ronaldo excerpts, timing/correction note, and metadata. It is not a full video or audio artifact. The official transcript itself notes some portions could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\n\n[defendant] DX-S2 FIFA official draw commencement time\nSource: FIFA official page, FIFA World Cup 2026 Final Draw\nURL: https://www.fifa.com/en/tournaments/mens/worldcup/canadamexicousa2026/live-draw\nRetrieval time: 2026-06-29T22:01:00Z\n\nMaterial captured text from web search/open result:\n- Page title/source: FIFA World Cup 2026™ Final Draw\n- The draw takes place at the Kennedy Center in Washington DC, USA.\n- The draw commences at 12:00 local time (17:00 UTC) on Friday 5 December 2025.\n\nCapture limits: This is a focused text capture of the official FIFA page timing statement located by web search. It is not a video capture of the draw ceremony.\n\nSubmitted evidence:\n[plaintiff arguments] Official White House video page capture: President Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing (ev_db357d4e9407_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-db357d4e9407)\nSource: https://www.whitehouse.gov/videos/president-trump-attends-the-fifa-world-cup-drawing/\nSHA-256: `db357d4e940728d417ae4f7f3caac6b78d3fd3e4aba70d46fe10c6132d45997a`\nBytes: 1300\nRelevance: Establishes that the White House officially published a video page titled President Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing, dated December 5, 2025, with a full-video link and related World Cup Draw videos; relevant to source chain and event context.\n\n[plaintiff arguments] YouTube metadata capture: Trump Talks Cristiano Ronaldo at FIFA Draw (ev_4e1045905547_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-4e1045905547)\nSource: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Cb2yO0lLEnM\nSHA-256: `4e10459055477440085fe5e20d970eb2488e61d13a5e2b3133a3656bed7526d7`\nBytes: 1779\nRelevance: Provides a public clip source and page metadata asserting that at the FIFA World Cup Draw Ceremony Trump shared a story about meeting Cristiano Ronaldo and said Ronaldo was a great person; relevant to the alleged Ronaldo utterance, though weaker than an official full transcript or video.\n\n[defendant arguments] GovInfo official transcript capture: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the FIFA World Cup Draw (ev_a1b1f6b1b7bd_submitted-evidence-03-defendant-a1b1f6b1b7bd)\nSource: https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/DCPD-202501162/html/DCPD-202501162.htm\nSHA-256: `a1b1f6b1b7bd0b691c7fe8d97467dd0d085e2b22387ae4198270764de66e56e2`\nBytes: 3070\nRelevance: Official transcript identifies the relevant Trump remarks as an exchange with reporters prior to the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw; it includes the Ronaldo utterances and timing/correction notes, directly bearing on whether the utterances were during the countable event period.\n\n[defendant arguments] FIFA official page capture: 2026 World Cup Final Draw start time (ev_3973dc8f98c0_submitted-evidence-04-defendant-3973dc8f98c0)\nSource: https://www.fifa.com/en/tournaments/mens/worldcup/canadamexicousa2026/live-draw\nSHA-256: `3973dc8f98c01702174f61f5548eb1e80efe64dd72b44f21ed0fa7d944f93248`\nBytes: 598\nRelevance: Establishes the official Final Draw start time as 12:00 local time on December 5, 2025, which helps compare the draw event period against the GovInfo transcript note that the reporter exchange occurred at 11:13 a.m.\n\nTechnical reports:\n[plaintiff] Plaintiff source-search and capture ledger\nSearched exact market/strike phrases, White House domain, public video pages, YouTube video IDs, and Kalshi live market URL. Submitted official White House page capture and YouTube metadata capture. Kalshi live page returned a Vercel security checkpoint/429; local browser was unavailable; Python pip/ensurepip unavailable for yt-dlp; direct YouTube caption/open paths were throttled or unavailable. Remaining best evidence would be a full official video/transcript or Kalshi resolution rationale if later accessible.\n\n[defendant] Defendant source-search and capture ledger\nInspected current AAR evidence and exact contents of plaintiff's White House and YouTube captures. Retrieved GovInfo official HTML transcript with curl from DCPD-202501162; local full HTML was 51,571 bytes with SHA-256 eadbceeecf3e94f5bd423bcb8e8511165fdc7265dd8c1e025870c2e8f34dfd99, then submitted a focused material text capture as DX-1. Searched official draw timing and submitted the FIFA official page timing statement as DX-2. Remaining gaps: full Kalshi market source hierarchy/resolution rationale and full WH/FIFA video were not captured, but official GovInfo timing/title plus FIFA start time resolve the material timing issue.\n\nCall submit_council_vote with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated.\nKeep the rationale brief: no more than three sentences.\n\nCouncil API instructions:\nYou are a council member. Decide the proposition from the admitted record.\nYou may examine admitted evidence through read-only tools when exact bytes, metadata, or exhibit contents matter.\nDo not search the web, introduce new facts, create new evidence, or upload evidence.\nWhen ready, call submit_council_vote exactly once with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated and a concise rationale.\n","state":"ready","status":"ready","tools":[{"description":"Return the current visible arbitration record for this council member.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{},"type":"object"},"name":"get_case","read_only":true},{"description":"List visible immutable record evidence.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{},"type":"object"},"name":"list_evidence","read_only":true},{"description":"Return metadata and read limits for one visible evidence item.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"evidence_id":{"type":"string"}},"required":["evidence_id"],"type":"object"},"name":"stat_evidence","read_only":true},{"description":"Read a bounded byte range from one visible evidence item as base64.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"evidence_id":{"type":"string"},"length":{"minimum":1,"type":"integer"},"offset":{"minimum":0,"type":"integer"}},"required":["evidence_id","offset","length"],"type":"object"},"name":"read_evidence_range","read_only":true},{"description":"Submit one council vote for the current deliberation opportunity.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"rationale":{"type":"string"},"vote":{"enum":["demonstrated","not_demonstrated"],"type":"string"}},"required":["vote","rationale"],"type":"object"},"name":"submit_council_vote","read_only":false}],"turn":{"attempts_max":3,"attempts_remaining":3,"completed":false,"deadline":"2026-06-29T22:18:45.386037689Z","deliberation_round":1,"member_id":"C2","opportunity_id":"deliberation:1:C2","phase":"deliberation","remaining_ms":889046,"role_id":"council","turn_number":10},"wait":{"reason":"ready","state_version":14,"version":17}},"isError":false},"server":"aar","tool":"wait_for_opportunity"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1782770636345}}
{"type":"turn_end","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_4OMctTF3Tl2BBcznCUaZhAHt","name":"mcp","arguments":{"tool":"aar_wait_for_opportunity","args":"{}"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"openai/gpt-4o-mini","usage":{"input":1945,"output":22,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":1967,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1782770635107,"responseId":"gen-1782770635-W8kfH4sfoe2jcoClxnuf"},"toolResults":[{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_4OMctTF3Tl2BBcznCUaZhAHt","toolName":"mcp","content":[{"type":"text","text":"ok: true\nstatus: ready\nstate: ready\nmessage: An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\nafter_version: 17\nafter_opportunity_id: deliberation:1:C2\nmember_id: C2\ncase_id: arb-ex03a-20260629214245\nwait_reason: ready\nphase: deliberation\nopportunity_id: deliberation:1:C2\nremaining_ms: 889046\nattempts_remaining: 3\njson: {\"after_opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C2\",\"after_version\":17,\"case_id\":\"arb-ex03a-20260629214245\",\"limits\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"max_evidence_read_bytes\":65536,\"max_evidence_read_bytes_per_opportunity\":524288,\"max_evidence_reads_per_opportunity\":32,\"max_response_bytes\":131072,\"remaining_evidence_read_bytes_for_opportunity\":524288,\"remaining_evidence_reads_for_opportunity\":32},\"member_id\":\"C2\",\"message\":\"An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\",\"ok\":true,\"prompt\":\"Role: council member\\nMember ID: C2\\nDeliberation round: 1\\nProposition: For the Kalshi market \\\"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\\", the strike \\\"Ronaldo\\\" should resolve Yes because Trump said \\\"Ronaldo\\\" in public remarks at the World Cup Draw venue immediately before the formal program, and the market wording plus the governing mention-market terms did not clearly exclude those event-linked remarks.\\nStandard of evidence: Preponderance of the evidence.\\nPersona:\\nYou are a careful juror and council member.\\n\\nEvaluate the record faithfully. Decide only from the evidence, the stated rules, and the applicable burden of proof. Do not favor either side, fill gaps with speculation, or ignore uncertainty.\\n\\nGive weight to reliable sources, direct evidence, consistent reasoning, and clear admissions. Discount unsupported claims, rhetorical force, irrelevant facts, and conclusions that exceed the record.\\n\\nWhen the evidence supports one answer, state it plainly. When the evidence is incomplete or balanced, say so. Be concise, honest, and exact.\\n\\nRecord:\\nOpenings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, this case is not about whether the word \\\"Ronaldo\\\" would count if President Trump clearly said it. The current packet makes that part straightforward: the market is the Kalshi PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION market titled \\\"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\\"; the strike is \\\"Ronaldo\\\"; Kalshi’s challenged resolution is No; and plaintiff seeks Yes.\\n\\nThe real dispute is temporal and contextual. Did the market phrase \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw,\\\" read with the governing mention-market terms, include public event-linked remarks at the World Cup Draw venue immediately before the formal draw program? Or did it clearly confine countable words to a narrower formal broadcast segment? Plaintiff’s position is that a No resolution cannot stand unless the record shows that the counting window clearly excluded those event-linked remarks.\\n\\nThe admitted terms matter. They define the underlying as words used by the specified entity during the specified time period. They expressly recognize event-based time periods, and they say the payout criterion is satisfied when the word is said by the entity during that period. They also contain exclusions: behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings do not count unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period; captions or text alone do not count; and the word must appear as a distinct standalone unit. Those exclusions are important, but they do not by themselves answer this case. A public remark at the event venue, tied to the Draw and immediately before the formal program, is not automatically a rehearsal, sound check, or private behind-the-scenes moment.\\n\\nAt this opening stage, the record proves the market identity, the challenged resolution, the requested resolution, and the generic governing terms. It does not yet prove the utterance itself, the exact sequence of the venue remarks, the source-agency hierarchy or any market-specific time-period language beyond the packet, or Kalshi’s reason for treating the strike as No. Those are the factual links that should decide the case under a preponderance standard.\\n\\nPlaintiff expects the decisive proof to be the full official or otherwise reliable event video or transcript, with enough surrounding context to show whether Trump said \\\"Ronaldo\\\" aloud as a standalone word; when he said it relative to the Draw event; whether the remarks were public and event-linked rather than backstage or a sound check; and whether any market-specific rule clearly excluded that segment. Plaintiff also expects the market page, archived market details, and any resolution rationale to be important because ambiguity in the market’s own event wording should not be resolved against Yes after the fact.\\n\\nThe defense will likely argue that \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw\\\" means only the formal draw ceremony or broadcast, and that anything before the formal program is outside the counting period. That theory can win only if the evidence shows a clear exclusion or a source record that separates the alleged remarks from the event itself. If the evidence instead shows public remarks at the Draw venue, officially connected to the event, immediately before the formal program, and no clear rule excluding them, then the terms favor counting the word and resolving the Ronaldo strike Yes.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the defense position is straightforward: the admitted record does not yet prove that the Ronaldo strike should resolve Yes. It proves a market title, a generic mention-market rule set, and Kalshi's challenged No resolution. It does not prove that any qualifying utterance of \\\"Ronaldo\\\" occurred during the market's countable time period.\\n\\nThe plaintiff's opening usefully narrows the dispute. This is not primarily a word-boundary case. If President Trump said \\\"Ronaldo\\\" as a standalone spoken word during the countable FIFA World Cup Draw period, the generic terms would ordinarily treat that as the kind of word that can count. The real question is whether plaintiff can carry the burden of showing that alleged pre-program, venue-adjacent remarks were part of the market's specified time period: \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\\\"\\n\\nThe case-packet terms matter, but they cut both ways. They say the underlying is words used by the entity during the specified time period. They recognize that a time period can be an event, and they allow the Exchange to specify what is included when an event is involved. They also distinguish official event presentation from material outside the event: behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are not included unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period; text or captions alone do not count; and the relevant word must be spoken aloud by the entity. Those provisions do not support a rule that every public comment inside the same building, or every press exchange near the formal program, is automatically \\\"during\\\" the Draw.\\n\\nThat is the burden problem for plaintiff. The admitted market-page file identifies the public title, contract family, strike, challenged resolution, and requested resolution. It does not supply a full market-specific source hierarchy, a formal start time, a transcript, a video, a resolution rationale, or the alleged remarks. The terms file supplies the generic framework, but not the factual bridge from \\\"immediately before the formal program\\\" to \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\\\" Without that bridge, the No resolution is not shown to be wrong by a preponderance of the evidence.\\n\\nThe defense expects the decisive proof to be source-chain evidence, not characterization. The council should want the market's full rule page if available, the source agency hierarchy, the official draw program or broadcast, any official transcript or recording of the alleged exchange, and enough surrounding timestamps to separate the formal draw from pre-event reporter access, red-carpet exchanges, arrivals, or other ancillary material. If later evidence shows that the alleged Ronaldo comment was in a segment officially presented as part of the Draw itself, plaintiff's argument becomes stronger. If the evidence instead shows a separate exchange with reporters before the draw, or an event-linked but pre-program interaction not incorporated into the official presentation, the generic terms support Kalshi's No.\\n\\nSo the defense opening is not that the word Ronaldo could never count. It is that this record has not established the necessary time-period link. The proposition asks the council to overturn No because the market wording and terms did not clearly exclude pre-program remarks. That reverses the burden. Plaintiff must show that the remarks were included in the countable period. Ambiguity about the outer edge of an event is not the same as proof that a specific pre-event utterance satisfies the payout criterion.\\n\\nArguments:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, plaintiff has now supplied the record links that were missing at opening.\\n\\nFirst, the market packet fixes what this dispute is: the Kalshi market title is \\\"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\\"; the contract family is PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION; the strike is \\\"Ronaldo\\\"; Kalshi's challenged resolution is No; and plaintiff seeks Yes. That is PX-1.\\n\\nSecond, the governing terms make this an event-period mention question, not a narrow formal-program-only question. PX-2 says the underlying is words used by the entity during the time period, recognizes that a time period may be a specific event, and sets the payout criterion as the word being said by the entity during that period. It also tells us what does not count: text/captions alone, unofficial behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, and sound checks unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. Those exclusions matter, but none says that public event-linked remarks at the venue immediately before the formal program are categorically outside \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\\\"\\n\\nThird, the source-chain evidence now points to the disputed event and the Ronaldo utterance. PX-3 is an official White House page titled \\\"President Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing,\\\" dated December 5, 2025, with a full-video link and related World Cup Draw videos. That establishes an official White House event-video source for Trump's attendance at the World Cup Drawing. PX-4 is a public YouTube watch-page metadata capture for video ID Cb2yO0lLEnM, titled \\\"Trump Talks Cristiano Ronaldo at FIFA Draw -- 'He's a Great Person'.\\\" Its description states that at the FIFA World Cup Draw Ceremony, Trump shared a story about meeting Cristiano Ronaldo at the White House, said Ronaldo was a great person, and mentioned Ronaldo spoke with his son. PX-4 is not as strong as an official transcript, and plaintiff says that plainly. But it is admitted source content that directly links Trump, Cristiano Ronaldo, and the FIFA Draw ceremony.\\n\\nOn a preponderance standard, that is enough to defeat the challenged No resolution unless the defense can supply a clearer exclusion. The market did not ask only what Trump would say during the ball-pulling segment, during the televised main show, or after a particular formal start cue. It asked what he would say \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\\\" The terms recognize event-based periods and exclude particular non-event categories. A public remark at the Draw venue, tied to the Draw, is far closer to the event period than to a rehearsal, sound check, caption, or private backstage recording.\\n\\nThe defense's burden framing is too strict. Plaintiff must prove Yes by a preponderance; plaintiff need not prove that Kalshi drafted every boundary with perfect precision. Once the admitted sources show a Ronaldo mention in connection with the FIFA Draw ceremony, the remaining question is whether the rules clearly remove that event-linked remark from the counting period. They do not. Ambiguity in a mention market's event wording should not be converted into an unstated formal-program limitation after the fact.\\n\\nProvenance and gaps: plaintiff attempted to retrieve the live Kalshi page, official/full video, caption, and transcript. Kalshi returned a Vercel security checkpoint; the local browser tool was unavailable; Python pip/ensurepip was unavailable for yt-dlp; and direct YouTube caption/open paths were throttled or unavailable. That leaves PX-4 weaker than ideal, but not weightless. PX-3 supplies official event context, PX-4 supplies the Ronaldo-at-FIFA-Draw metadata, and PX-2 supplies the rule that event-linked spoken words count absent a clear exclusion.\\n\\nThe council should resolve the proposition Yes: the Ronaldo strike should have resolved Yes because the record more likely than not shows Trump said Ronaldo in public remarks tied to the FIFA World Cup Draw, and the market wording plus governing terms did not clearly exclude those remarks.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the merits record now shows why the challenged No resolution should stand.\\n\\nPlaintiff's best point is that Trump did say the word \\\"Ronaldo.\\\" The defense does not need to fight that. The question is whether he said it during the market's countable time period: \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\\\" On that decisive question, the strongest official sources favor No.\\n\\nThe admitted GovInfo transcript, DX-1, is an official Compilation of Presidential Documents capture. Its title is not merely \\\"World Cup Draw\\\" or \\\"FIFA ceremony.\\\" It is \\\"Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw.\\\" That same transcript contains the Ronaldo passages: Trump says he met Ronaldo at the White House, later says he was \\\"not Ronaldo or Messi,\\\" and the note identifies Ronaldo among the people referenced. So DX-1 is not adverse to the defense because it confirms the word; it is decisive because it places the word in an exchange with reporters prior to the Draw.\\n\\nDX-2 supplies the timing anchor. The official FIFA Final Draw page states that the Draw at the Kennedy Center commenced at 12:00 local time on Friday, December 5, 2025. DX-1 states that the President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the Kennedy Center. A reporter exchange at 11:13, officially titled as prior to a 12:00 draw, is not more likely than not \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\\\" It is before it.\\n\\nThat reading matches the governing PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION terms. PX-2 says the payout criterion is satisfied when the word is said by the entity during the specified time period. It recognizes event-based periods and permits the Exchange to specify what is included for an event. It also treats official presentation differently from adjacent material: pre-recorded content counts if presented as part of the official event presentation, while behind-the-scenes, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings do not count unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. The point is not that this reporter exchange was a rehearsal or sound check. The point is that the terms require a link to the time period itself. Plaintiff has supplied no market-specific language saying pre-event reporter availability, arrivals, or venue interviews count as part of the Draw.\\n\\nPlaintiff's new exhibits do not fill that gap. PX-3, the White House page capture, establishes that the White House had a page titled \\\"President Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing,\\\" but plaintiff's own capture says the embedded/full video was not captured. It does not prove that the Ronaldo words occurred inside the official draw program. PX-4 is weaker still: it is metadata from a nonofficial YouTube channel. It says the clip is about Trump talking Ronaldo at the FIFA Draw, but it is not a transcript, not an official source, and not an audio extraction. When a nonofficial clip description is weighed against GovInfo's official transcript title and FIFA's official start time, the official sources control.\\n\\nNor is this a burden-shifting problem. The proposition asks the council to overturn Kalshi's No because the market supposedly did not clearly exclude remarks immediately before the formal program. But the preponderance burden is on Yes. The record must show that the strike satisfied the payout criterion. The admitted terms do not say that ambiguous pre-event remarks count by default; they say the word must be said during the specified time period. Here, the best evidence identifies the remarks as prior to the Draw and before the official commencement time.\\n\\nProvenance also matters. DX-1 is an official government transcript with a correction note and an audio-incomplete caveat. That caveat affects stray inaudible portions, but it does not weaken the title, the 11:13 timing note, or the Ronaldo passages preserved in the transcript. DX-2 is an official FIFA timing source. Plaintiff's YouTube metadata may explain why the dispute arose, but it cannot outweigh those primary sources on timing and event classification.\\n\\nThe council should resolve the proposition against plaintiff. Trump said Ronaldo, but the record more likely shows he did so in a reporter exchange prior to the FIFA World Cup Draw, not during the countable Draw event. Kalshi's No resolution should be upheld.\\n\\nRebuttals:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, defendant’s new evidence narrows the case but does not end it.\\n\\nPlaintiff accepts the important parts of DX-1 and DX-2. The GovInfo transcript is official; it labels the item an exchange with reporters \\\"Prior to\\\" the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw; it places the exchange at 11:13 a.m. at the Kennedy Center; and the FIFA capture states the draw commenced at 12:00 local time. Plaintiff should not pretend those facts are weak.\\n\\nBut defendant asks those facts to do more than they do. The market was not drafted as \\\"what will Trump say after the official 12:00 commencement,\\\" \\\"during the televised draw program,\\\" or \\\"during the ball-drawing segment.\\\" PX-1 says the public market title was \\\"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\\" That is ordinary event language, and PX-2 recognizes event-based time periods while leaving room for the Exchange to specify what is included. The record still contains no market-specific exclusion for official venue press remarks immediately before the formal program.\\n\\nDX-1 also helps plaintiff on the facts defendant originally said were missing. It confirms the relevant spoken word. Trump said he met Ronaldo, that Ronaldo is great, and that he was not Ronaldo or Messi. It also places those remarks at the Kennedy Center in a FIFA World Cup Draw-centered exchange with reporters, not in an unrelated private dinner or stale campaign setting. The transcript’s own subject metadata includes the FIFA World Cup, the Kennedy Center, news media, presidential interviews, and soccer. That is event-linked public context.\\n\\nThe terms’ exclusions do not fit defendant’s leap. PX-2 excludes captions alone, rehearsals, sound checks, behind-the-scenes content, and unofficial recordings unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. DX-1 is not a rehearsal transcript. It is not a sound check. It is not merely a caption. It is an official presidential transcript of a public reporter exchange at the venue, released in the Compilation of Presidential Documents. If Kalshi meant to exclude that category because it occurred before a formal noon commencement, the market needed to say so clearly.\\n\\nSo the dispositive question remains one of market construction: does \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw\\\" clearly exclude public, official, event-site remarks immediately before the formal program? Defendant has proved \\\"prior to\\\" the formal draw start. Defendant has not proved a clear market rule that treats the broader Draw event as beginning only at 12:00 for mention purposes.\\n\\nUnder a preponderance standard, the record now confirms the Ronaldo utterance and confirms the FIFA Draw setting. The challenged No resolution should not be upheld by importing a narrow formal-program limitation that the market title and generic terms did not state.\\n\\nSurrebuttals:\\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff's rebuttal usefully clarifies the remaining dispute: plaintiff accepts that DX-1 is official, that it labels the relevant item an exchange with reporters \\\"Prior to\\\" the FIFA World Cup Draw, that the exchange occurred at 11:13 a.m. at the Kennedy Center, and that DX-2 places the official Draw commencement at 12:00 local time. Those concessions should decide the case.\\n\\nPlaintiff's answer is that the market did not say \\\"after 12:00,\\\" \\\"during the televised program,\\\" or \\\"during the ball-drawing segment.\\\" But the market also did not say \\\"at the venue before the Draw,\\\" \\\"in pre-event reporter exchanges,\\\" or \\\"in any public remarks connected to the Draw.\\\" The phrase it chose was \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\\\" Ordinary event language has a start, and the official FIFA source fixes that start at noon. Official GovInfo then fixes this exchange at 11:13 and titles it as prior to the Draw.\\n\\nThat is not a technicality. The terms require the word to be said during the specified time period. They recognize event-based periods and allow event-specific inclusions, but no admitted market-specific rule includes pre-event press access. Plaintiff's construction would turn any event-adjacent public remark into part of the event unless expressly excluded. That reverses the payout criterion. The claimant must show the word occurred during the time period; it is not enough to show the same venue, the same general topic, and official publication.\\n\\nPlaintiff says the exclusions do not fit because DX-1 is not a rehearsal, sound check, caption, or private backstage recording. Fair enough; the defense is not relying on those categories as labels. The defense relies on the affirmative timing requirement. A remark need not be a rehearsal to be outside the event. A reporter exchange officially described as prior to a noon event and occurring at 11:13 is outside because it is before the event began.\\n\\nThe record therefore proves the wrong fact for plaintiff. It proves Trump said Ronaldo, but in a pre-event reporter exchange. The proposition requires Yes only if those words count during the FIFA World Cup Draw. On this record, they do not. Kalshi's No resolution should be upheld.\\n\\nClosings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the final record leaves one legal question.\\n\\nThe easy factual question is resolved in plaintiff’s favor: Trump said \\\"Ronaldo.\\\" The official GovInfo transcript confirms it twice in substance: he said he met Ronaldo, praised him, and later said he was not Ronaldo or Messi. That is a spoken standalone use of the strike word. The record also places the remarks at the Kennedy Center in a FIFA World Cup Draw-centered reporter exchange. This was not an unrelated dinner, a caption, an AI voice, or a social-media paraphrase.\\n\\nThe hard point is timing. Defendant has the strongest evidence on the formal program boundary: GovInfo titled the exchange as \\\"Prior to\\\" the Draw, notes 11:13 a.m., and FIFA states the Final Draw commenced at 12:00 local time. Plaintiff does not ask the council to ignore that. The question is what the Kalshi market actually required.\\n\\nPX-1 did not say \\\"after 12:00.\\\" It did not say \\\"during the televised draw program\\\" or \\\"during the ball-drawing segment.\\\" It asked, in public market wording, \\\"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\\" PX-2’s generic terms recognize event-based periods and say the Exchange may specify what is included when a time period refers to an event. They also give specific exclusions: captions alone, rehearsals, sound checks, behind-the-scenes content, and unofficial recordings unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. None of those exclusions is this case. The GovInfo transcript is an official public presidential record of an event-site reporter exchange, not a rehearsal or sound check.\\n\\nDefendant’s best argument is that ordinary events have start times. True. But this market dispute is about public remarks at the venue immediately before the formal program, in the official context of the Draw, where the market and rules did not clearly define a noon-only boundary. If Kalshi wanted that narrower rule, it could have said so in the strike, the market title, or the event inclusion language. It did not.\\n\\nThe preponderance record therefore shows: Ronaldo was spoken; the remarks were public and officially documented; they were at the Kennedy Center in the FIFA World Cup Draw setting; and the governing market language did not clearly exclude that immediately-before-program event context. The challenged No resolution depends on importing a formal commencement limitation that is absent from the market packet.\\n\\nFor that reason, the Ronaldo strike should resolve Yes.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the closing record is narrow and concrete.\\n\\nEveryone now agrees on the easy fact: Trump said \\\"Ronaldo.\\\" The official GovInfo transcript proves that. But the proposition is not simply that Trump said the word somewhere near the FIFA World Cup Draw. The proposition asks you to overturn Kalshi's No because remarks immediately before the formal program should count under a market asking what Trump would say \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\\\" Plaintiff has not carried that burden.\\n\\nThe two strongest sources are official and aligned. GovInfo, in DX-1, titles the relevant document \\\"Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw.\\\" It notes that the President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the Kennedy Center. FIFA, in DX-2, states that the Final Draw commenced at 12:00 local time. Those facts are not peripheral. They answer the timing question: the Ronaldo words were in a reporter exchange before the Draw began.\\n\\nPlaintiff's closing says the market did not specify \\\"after 12:00,\\\" \\\"during the televised draw program,\\\" or \\\"during the ball-drawing segment.\\\" True, but that does not prove Yes. The market did specify \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\\\" The ordinary function of \\\"during\\\" is to define the event period, not to include anything public, official, and thematically related that happens beforehand. A 47-minute-before reporter exchange officially titled as prior to the Draw is outside that period unless the market or governing terms affirmatively include it. The record contains no such inclusion.\\n\\nThe governing terms reinforce that conclusion. They require the word to be said by the entity during the specified time period. They recognize event-based periods and allow the Exchange to specify event inclusions. They include official-presentation concepts for material presented as part of an event. But they do not say that pre-event press availability counts by default. Plaintiff's argument turns the absence of an exclusion into proof of inclusion. That is backwards under a preponderance standard.\\n\\nPlaintiff also leans on setting: Kennedy Center, FIFA World Cup subject matter, official transcript, public reporters. Those facts show why the issue is understandable. They do not move 11:13 into a 12:00 event. A source can be official and still describe something outside the event. Indeed, that is exactly what DX-1 does: it officially documents the remarks and officially labels them prior to the Draw.\\n\\nThe weaker evidence points the same way once weighed properly. The White House page capture does not include the video or transcript. The YouTube metadata is nonofficial and not an audio transcript. Neither overcomes GovInfo's title and timing note plus FIFA's commencement time.\\n\\nSo the final answer is simple: the word was spoken, but not during the countable event period shown by the best evidence. Plaintiff has not shown that Kalshi's No resolution was wrong. The council should reject the proposition and uphold No.\\n\\nExhibits:\\n[plaintiff] PX-1 Market page packet: Ronaldo strike and challenged No resolution\\nMarket URL: https://kalshi.com/markets/kxtrumpmentionb/trump-mention-b/kxtrumpmentionb-25dec06\\n\\nPublic market title: What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\n\\nContract family: PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION\\n\\nStrike at issue: Ronaldo\\n\\nChallenged resolution: No\\n\\nRequested resolution: Yes\\n\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-2 Governing PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION terms\\n                                         NEWMENTION\\n\\nScope: These rules shall apply to this contract.\\n\\nUnderlying: The Underlying for this Contract is words used by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nRevisions to the Underlying made after Expiration will not be accounted for in determining the\\nExpiration Value.\\n\\nSource Agency: The Source Agencies are \\u003csource\\u003e.\\n\\nType: The type of Contract is an Event Contract.\\n\\nIssuance: After the initial Contract, Contract iterations will be listed on an as-needed basis at\\nthe discretion of the Exchange and corresponding to the risk management needs of Members.\\n\\n\\u003centity\\u003e: \\u003centity\\u003e refers to the speaker, writer, performer, or communicator specified by the\\nExchange. This may include (but is not limited to): a specific named individual, multiple\\nindividuals specified using AND/OR logic, an individual identified by position or title, a group,\\nband, team or collective entity, a specified member or members of a group, an organization,\\ncompany, or institutional entity, or any combination of the aforementioned.\\n\\nWhen \\u003centity\\u003e is defined by a position or title, the Contract tracks whoever holds that position\\nduring \\u003ctime period\\u003e, even if the individual holding the position changes. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a\\nspecific named individual, the identity remains consistent throughout. Name changes (e.g.,\\nstage names, married names) do not create a new entity. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a group or\\norganization and the Contract does not specify particular members, any official\\ncommunication or statement by any member or designated spokesperson counts. When using\\nAND logic, all specified entities must independently say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e. When\\nusing OR logic, at least one of the specified entities must say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nThe Exchange may specify additional conditions such as “at least X members of” a group or\\n“the majority of” a group.\\n\\n\\u003csource\\u003e: \\u003csource\\u003e refers to a Source Agency or ordered collection of Source Agencies\\nspecified by the Exchange at the time of Contract listing, which will be incorporated into the\\nSource Agency hierarchy above and used to determine the occurrence of the Underlying.\\n\\u003csource\\u003e may refer to a singular agency, multiple agencies, an agency by distinguishing\\ncharacteristics, by category or type (e.g., “official government statistical body,” “primary wire\\nservice”), or any combination thereof. When multiple agencies are specified, they may be\\napplied in the hierarchical order designated by the Exchange if so specified, with the highest-\\nranked available and responsive agency taking precedence for purposes of determining the\\nExpiration Value. A lower-ranked agency shall only be consulted if all higher-ranked agencies\\nare unavailable, unresponsive, have not reported on the Underlying by the Expiration time, or\\nif the Exchange, in its sole discretion, determines that a higher-ranked agency’s reporting is\\nincomplete, erroneous, or otherwise insufficient to determine the Expiration Value. If \\u003csource\\u003e\\ndesignates multiple agencies without specifying a hierarchical order, the Exchange shall\\nresolve any conflict between reporting agencies at its sole discretion.\\n\\n\\u003cword\\u003e: \\u003cword\\u003e refers to the particular word or phrase potentially to be mentioned by\\n\\u003centity\\u003e. It may refer to a word being said a minimum number of times. It may also refer to\\none of multiple words/phrases, any of which are acceptable (e.g., “Doge/Dogecoin”).\\n\\f\\u003ctime period\\u003e: \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific range of time, event or discrete date and\\ntime specified by the Exchange. This may be defined by, but is not limited to: a specific event\\nor context (e.g., “during the State of the Union address”), exact dates or times, relative time\\nmarkers (e.g., “before July 1, 2027,” “in Q1 2026”), event-based periods (e.g., “during any\\ncampaign rally in October 2026,” “during the awards ceremony”), and broader intervals (e.g.,\\n“Q1–Q2 2027,” “January–March 2026”).\\n\\nUnless stated otherwise, “Between” is inclusive of both endpoints, while “before” and “after”\\nexclude the specified date. \\u003ctime period\\u003e may also refer to “Any” or “None”, to multiple dates\\n(even if non-consecutive), or to a singular and discrete date or time.\\n\\nWhen \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event (such as an address, speech, performance, or\\nbroadcast), the Exchange may specify what is included, including whether it includes both live\\nand pre-recorded segments (including whether advertisements are included). Where a\\ntimezone is not specified, ET is assumed.\\n\\n\\nPayout Criterion: The Payout Criterion for the Contract encompasses the Expiration Values that\\n\\u003cword\\u003e is said by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n\\n\\nThe word must appear as a distinct, standalone unit, not buried inside another word. Plural\\nand possessive noun forms count. Other grammatical changes (tense, conjugation, derivation)\\ndo not. If \\u003cword\\u003e appears separated from other words by a space or hyphen or in a\\ncompound form with a space or hyphen, it counts. If \\u003cword\\u003e is fused into a single\\nunhyphenated word, it does not count.\\n\\nIf \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled, and the market contains a\\nstrike stating “Event does not qualify/occur”, such a strike shall resolve “Yes” and all others\\n“No”. If \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled but such strikes are NOT\\nlisted, the Contracts will resolve to the last fair price determined at the discretion of the\\nExchange. If the event is postponed, and such a postponement is announced by the end of the\\nfollowing calendar day to be rescheduled to a time within 14 calendar days, the markets shall\\nremain open. If the event captured in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast, the\\nExchange may keep the market open for 24 hours for the release of an official recording.\\nFurther granular details on conditions for these Contracts is available below.\\n\\nAdditional clarification(s):\\n\\n     Possessive noun forms of \\u003cword\\u003e, plurals, and possessive plural noun forms are\\n     INCLUDED:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigrants” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Egg” → “eggs’ shells” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Russia” → “Russia’s” counts, “Russian” does not\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e exists only in adjective form, no plural form exists:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Economic” → “Economics” does not count (“Economic” is an adjective\\n          for which “Economics” is not a plural)\\n     Plural nouns occurring within proper nouns and noun phrases are included:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Cat” → “Cats the musical” counts\\n\\f    Grammatical variations beyond plurals/possessives are NOT included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigration” does NOT count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Run” → “Running” or “Ran” do NOT count\\n    When \\u003cword\\u003e specifies a plural form, the singular does NOT count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Veterans” → “Veteran” does NOT count\\n    Words that are spelled the same as the plural form of \\u003cword\\u003e (if such exists) but are\\n    themselves not a plural noun are included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Wind” → “Winds up the clock” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Border” → “The United States has strong borders” counts\\n    Open compounds (words separated by spaces) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fire station” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “couch” → “couch potato” counts\\n    Hyphenated compounds (words connected by hyphens) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Palestine” → “pro-Palestine” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fat” → “non-fat” counts\\n    Closed compounds (single word, no spaces/hyphens) do not count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire” does not count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firefighter” does not count\\n    Multi-word \\u003cword\\u003e in larger constructions: When \\u003cword\\u003e is a multi-word phrase\\n    appearing within a hyphenated construction, it counts only if \\u003cword\\u003e appears as a\\n    complete, unmodified element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “New York” → “New York-based” counts (complete element)\\n    Portmanteaus (words blended from two words where parts of each are combined) are\\n    NOT included unless the portmanteau clearly contains \\u003cword\\u003e as a distinct, unaltered\\n    element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “MAGA” → “MAGA-nificent” counts (MAGA appears as distinct element)\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “magnificent” → “MAGA-nificent” does NOT count (portmanteau blend)\\n\\nDictionary determination: Both the Merriam-Webster Dictionary (available online) AND the\\nOxford English Dictionary shall be used to determine compound type and/or conventional\\nspelling patterns. Inclusion in either dictionary as an open or hyphenated compound shall\\nsatisfy the Payout Criterion. If neither provides clarity (or the word is not included),\\ndetermination is based on whether written as single unit (closed/doesn’t count) vs. spaces or\\nhyphens (open or hyphenated/counts) and/or context and previous usage.\\n\\nPHONETIC EQUIVALENCIES\\n\\n    Homophones (same sound, different spelling) do not count:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “write” → “right” does not count\\n    Homonyms and homographs (same spelling) COUNT regardless of meaning or\\n    pronunciation:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “bass” → both “bass guitar” and “bass fishing” count\\n    Proper and common nouns are treated identically:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Apple” → both “Apple Inc.” and “apple” (fruit) count\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Will” → both “Will Smith” and “I will go” count\\n    Minor unintentional mispronunciations COUNT if context makes intent clear:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Mamdani” → “Mandani” counts\\n    Severe mispronunciations that make \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable do NOT count.\\n    Trademarked spellings do not count, even when pronounced identically, unless the word\\n\\fitself is the same:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “lift” → “Lyft” (pronounced “lift”) does not count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “uber” → “Uber” counts\\nWords with non-standard transliteration to English count within reason, provided they are\\nphonetically equivalent:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Zelensky” → any of “Zelenski,” “Zelenskii,” “Zelensky,” or “Zelenskiy”\\n      count if pronounced equivalently\\nContractions do not count for their constituent words unless otherwise explicitly specified\\nby the Exchange:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “not” → “won’t,” “can’t,” “don’t,” “isn’t” do not count\\nNumbers spoken as words COUNT, when spoken exactly (not part of a larger number):\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “five” → saying “five” or reading “$5” aloud as “five dollars” counts,\\n      saying “five hundred” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “410” → “four hundred ten”, “four one zero” or “four ten” counts\\nOrdinals COUNT when \\u003cword\\u003e is written numerically OR a phrase that includes a\\nnumber:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “January 6” → “January 6th” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “3” (written numerically) → “3rd” (spoken as “third”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Eight War” → “8 Wars” and “Eighth War” will count\\nCardinal and ordinal number words are distinct:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “one” → “first” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “first” → “one” does NOT count\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count when pronunciation or letter-by-letter spelling\\nmatches \\u003cword\\u003e:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “NASA” (pronounced “NAH-suh”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “N-A-S-A” (spelled out) counts\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count as \\u003cword\\u003e when pronounced as the full word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Doctor” → “Dr.” (pronounced “Doctor”) counts\\nExpanded forms of acronyms do NOT count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “AI” → “artificial intelligence” does not count\\nWords in foreign languages do NOT count unless they are perfect cognates with an\\nEnglish word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fuego” (Spanish) does NOT count\\nEnglish words within foreign sentences count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “policy” → “Nuestra policy es clara” counts\\n\\u003cword\\u003e in organization/company names counts:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Securities” → “Bank of America Securities” counts\\nWords in URLs, emails, handles, and hashtags (exclusive of domain structure, email\\nprovider or symbols) are treated as compounds when spoken as complete words, with the\\ntype of compound subject to aforementioned rules:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firestation.com” pronounced “fire station dot com” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire.com” pronounced “wildfire dot com” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “apple” → “apple.com” pronounced “apple dot com” does count\\n      When presented in URL, email, handle, or hashtag form, \\u003cword\\u003e shall be treated as\\n      a compound, not a multi-word word\\nSung, rapped, or poetic words COUNT if phonetically recognizable:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “money” → “moneyyy” (extended in rap) counts\\n      Extreme distortion making \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable does NOT count.\\nPhonetic alphabet spelling (“Foxtrot India Romeo Echo” for “FIRE”) does NOT count.\\n\\fCANCELLATIONS AND DELAYS\\n\\n   The Exchange may list an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike for any Contract. If listed,\\n   such a strike refers to the structural conditions of the market, and is NOT adjudicated as a\\n   \\u003cword\\u003e needing to be said by or validated by having been said by \\u003centity\\u003e. If listed, this\\n   strike resolves to “Yes” whenever the event fails to occur or qualify under the Payout\\n   Criterion, or any other circumstance prevents normal resolution.\\n   If no such strike is listed, and \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, the following rules\\n   apply if the event is cancelled, postponed, rescheduled, or materially altered (including\\n   being closed to press) such that no video is released within one calendar day of the\\n   original start time of the event:\\n         If the event is cancelled, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price determined in\\n         the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         If the event is postponed or rescheduled, the outcome depends on whether a new\\n         date is publicly announced within one calendar day (i.e. if the event was scheduled\\n         to begin on Monday, any time up to 11:59PM on Tuesday falls within this period) of\\n         the originally scheduled start time:\\n               If no new date is announced within one calendar day, the Contract will resolve\\n               to the last fair price determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n               If a new date is announced within one calendar day, the outcome depends on\\n               when the rescheduled event is set to occur:\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls within fourteen (14) calendar days of the\\n                     originally scheduled date, the Contract shall remain open and \\u003cword\\u003e\\n                     stated during the rescheduled event will count.\\n                           The fourteen-day window begins at 12:00 AM ET on the originally\\n                           scheduled date and ends at 11:59 PM ET fourteen days later, unless\\n                           an alternate timezone is explicitly specified.\\n                           Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the State of the Union on January\\n                           15, 2026” rescheduled to January 20, 2026 → words spoken during\\n                           the rescheduled address count.\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls more than fourteen (14) calendar days after\\n                     the originally scheduled date, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price\\n                     determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         Any Contract that cannot be resolved through the Source Agency hierarchy will\\n         instead be settled at the Last Fair Price. The Exchange will disclose the methodology\\n         used to determine the Last Fair Price (e.g., Last Traded Price, Time-Weighted\\n         Average Price) at the time of Issuance.\\n         If an event begins but is interrupted, abbreviated, or ends prematurely, words\\n         stated by \\u003centity\\u003e during the portion of the event that did occur will count and the\\n         market will otherwise resolve.\\n   If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window but the venue, format, or medium\\n   changes (e.g., moved to a different location, changed from in-person to virtual (with the\\n   exception of being closed to press)), words stated during the event will count.\\n   Special condition: Across both cases, whether an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike is\\n   listed or not, if the event specified as or in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast (or\\n   relayed as such) but the live stream/broadcast does not occur, the Exchange will instead\\n   use an officially released recording as the Underlying, and may delay resolution by up to\\n   one calendar day to allow for the release of such a recording.\\n\\f          If partial snippets are released, Contracts on words that do not appear will be\\n          resolved to last fair price, and Contracts on those that do will be resolved to “Yes”.\\n          If no recording is released, the relevant outcomes triggered by the\\n          presence/absence of an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike shall occur as outlined\\n          above.\\n\\nTECHNICAL DETAILS (UNLESS OTHERWISE SPECIFIED)\\n\\n     When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, pre-recorded content broadcast,\\n     streamed, or published as part of that event is included if presented as part of the official\\n     presentation.\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the concert” with pre-recorded video interlude\\n          where entity speaks → words from interlude count\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the television appearance” with pre-taped\\n          segment aired during broadcast → words from segment count\\n     Behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are NOT\\n     included unless officially broadcast or published as part of \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n     Subtitles and captions that display \\u003cword\\u003e on screen but are not spoken aloud by\\n     \\u003centity\\u003e do NOT count.\\n     Sign language interpretation or usage by entity does NOT count as saying \\u003cword\\u003e unless\\n     the Contract explicitly specifies that sign language counts.\\n     Text that entity displays on screen (presentation slides, teleprompter visible to audience,\\n     signatures) does NOT count unless entity reads it aloud.\\n     Content generated by AI, deepfakes, or synthetic voice technology impersonating entity\\n     does NOT count unless the synthetic content is officially commissioned, authorized, or\\n     published by entity, OR the Contract explicitly specifies that AI-generated content counts.\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e is muted due to technical failure or censorship it shall not count unless\\n     corroborating contextual evidence (including surrounding speech, or an official\\n     uncensored recording or transcript) confirms that \\u003centity\\u003e specifically uttered \\u003cword\\u003e\\n     during the muted period.\\n\\nMinimum Tick: The Minimum Tick size for the Contract shall be $0.01.\\n\\nPosition Accountability Level: The Position Accountability Level for the Contract shall be\\n$25,000 per strike, per Member.\\n\\nLast Trading Date: The Last Trading Date of the Contract will be the Expiration Date. The Last\\nTrading Time will be the Expiration time.\\n\\nSettlement Date: The Settlement Date of the Contract shall be no later than the day after the\\nExpiration Date, unless the Market Outcome is under review pursuant to Rule 7.1.\\n\\nExpiration Date: When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event: The latest Expiration Date of\\nthe Contract shall be fourteen (14) calendar days after the originally scheduled date of the\\nevent. If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window, expiration will be moved to an\\nearlier date and time in accordance with Rule 7.2. When \\u003ctime period\\u003e is defined by specific\\ndates: The latest Expiration Date of the Contract shall be two weeks after the end of \\u003ctime\\nperiod\\u003e. If an event described in the Payout Criterion occurs and a consensus has been\\nreached on all terms, then expiration will be moved to an earlier date and time in accordance\\nwith Rule 7.2.\\n\\fExpiration time: The Expiration time of the Contract shall be 10:00 AM ET.\\n\\nSettlement Value: The Settlement Value for this Contract is $1.00.\\n\\nExpiration Value: The Expiration Value is the value of the Underlying as documented by the\\nSource Agency on the Expiration Date at the Expiration time.\\n\\nContingencies: Before Settlement, Kalshi may, at its sole discretion, initiate the Market\\nOutcome Review Process pursuant to Rule 7.1 of the Rulebook. If an Expiration Value cannot\\nbe determined on the Expiration Date, Kalshi has the right to determine payouts pursuant to\\nRule 7.1 in the Rulebook.\\n\\f\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-3 Official White House World Cup Drawing video page capture\\nSource capture from official White House page https://www.whitehouse.gov/videos/president-trump-attends-the-fifa-world-cup-drawing/\\nRetrieval: 2026-06-29T21:52:12Z via OpenClaw web_fetch and web.open.\\n\\nVisible page facts captured:\\n- Page title: President Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing\\n- Date shown on page: December 5, 2025\\n- Page section: Videos\\n- The page contains a link labeled View Full Video to Instagram.\\n- Related video listed: FIFA World Cup 2026 Draw at The Kennedy Center, duration 00:45, dated December 6, 2025.\\n- Related video listed: FIFA World Cup Drawing Announced to Take Place at The Kennedy Center, duration 00:56, dated August 23, 2025.\\n- Related video listed: President Trump on the 2026 FIFA World Cup, duration 01:22, dated May 6, 2025.\\n\\nRelevant extracted lines from web.open capture:\\nL142: Videos\\nL143: # President Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing\\nL145: December 5, 2025\\nL133: ... View Full Video [instagram.com] ...\\nL151: FIFA World Cup 2026 Draw at The Kennedy Center\\nL153: December 6, 2025\\nL167-L170: President Trump on the 2026 FIFA World Cup, May 6, 2025\\n\\nNotes on capture limits: readability extraction returned minimal content, so the above preserves visible lines from the page capture. The embedded/full video itself was not captured in this item.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-4 YouTube metadata capture for Ronaldo-at-FIFA-Draw clip\\nSource capture: YouTube watch page https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Cb2yO0lLEnM\\nVideo ID: Cb2yO0lLEnM\\nRetrieval: 2026-06-29T21:53:00Z via web search and curl of the YouTube watch page.\\n\\nCaptured title / page metadata:\\n- Title shown in search and page metadata: Trump Talks Cristiano Ronaldo at FIFA Draw — ‘He’s a Great Person’\\n- Channel shown in page metadata: interestingText You / @InterestingTextYou\\n- Subscriber count shown in page metadata at capture: about 10.3K subscribers\\n\\nCaptured description text from YouTube page metadata:\\n\\\"Trump Talks Cristiano Ronaldo at FIFA Draw — ‘He’s a Great Person’\\n\\nAt the FIFA World Cup Draw Ceremony, Donald Trump shared a story about meeting Cristiano Ronaldo at the White House. Trump said Ronaldo was “a great person” and even mentioned that Ronaldo spoke with his son about soccer during the visit.\\n\\nThis unexpected crossover between world politics and one of the biggest global sports stars quickly caught viewers' attention.\\n\\nTrump FIFA Draw\\nDonald Trump FIFA World Cup\\nTrump Cristiano Ronaldo\\nCristiano Ronaldo Trump meeting\\nFIFA World Cup draw 2026\\nRonaldo White House visit\\nTrump soccer comments\\nWorld Cup trending 2025\\nsports politics crossover\\nCristiano Ronaldo story\\nDonald Trump viral moment\\nFIFA draw ceremony Trump\\nWorld Cup 2026 news\\nRonaldo fan reaction\\npolitical celebrity moments\\nviral sports clips 2025\\nFIFA draw highlights\\nTrump speech FIFA\\nglobal sports news\\\"\\n\\nCapture limits and provenance caveat: direct video/caption extraction was attempted but YouTube transcript/open paths were throttled or unavailable in this environment. This item preserves the public watch-page metadata and description, not an independently extracted audio transcript. It is not an official White House or FIFA source.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-1 GovInfo official transcript: remarks prior to FIFA World Cup Draw\\nSource: GovInfo, Compilation of Presidential Documents, DCPD202501162\\nURL retrieved: https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/DCPD-202501162/html/DCPD-202501162.htm\\nRetrieval time: 2026-06-29T22:00:00Z\\nLocal captured HTML size/hash: 51,571 bytes; SHA-256 eadbceeecf3e94f5bd423bcb8e8511165fdc7265dd8c1e025870c2e8f34dfd99\\n\\nMaterial captured text from official GovInfo HTML/web.open:\\n\\nAdministration of Donald J. Trump, 2025\\n\\nTitle: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\nDate: December 5, 2025\\n\\nOpening note: [The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\\n\\nExcerpt - The President's Interest in Soccer (web.open lines 196-203):\\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\\\"football,\\\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\\n\\nExcerpt - The President's Interest in Soccer (web.open lines 322-329):\\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\\nThe President. But they have a little more speed. But no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\\n\\nTiming/context note (web.open lines 461-462):\\nNOTE: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. In his remarks, he referred to Trey Yingst, chief foreign correspondent, Fox News Channel; Cristiano Ronaldo, forward for Saudi Pro League club Al-Nass and Portugal's national soccer team; and Lionel Messi, forward for Major League Soccer club Inter Miami and Argentina's national team. A reporter referred to New York State Attorney General Letitia James.\\nThe transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\n\\nDocument category/location/name/subject metadata (web.open lines 463-468):\\nCategories: Interviews With the News Media: Exchanges with reporters, Washington, DC.\\nLocations: Washington, DC.\\nNames include: Cristiano Ronaldo and Lionel Messi.\\nSubjects include: Federation Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) World Cup; John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts; News media, Presidential interviews; Soccer.\\nDCPD Number: DCPD202501162.\\n\\nCapture limits: This item is a focused text capture of the material official transcript title, Ronaldo excerpts, timing/correction note, and metadata. It is not a full video or audio artifact. The official transcript itself notes some portions could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-2 FIFA official Final Draw start-time capture\\nSource: FIFA official page, FIFA World Cup 2026 Final Draw\\nURL: https://www.fifa.com/en/tournaments/mens/worldcup/canadamexicousa2026/live-draw\\nRetrieval time: 2026-06-29T22:01:00Z\\n\\nMaterial captured text from web search/open result:\\n- Page title/source: FIFA World Cup 2026™ Final Draw\\n- The draw takes place at the Kennedy Center in Washington DC, USA.\\n- The draw commences at 12:00 local time (17:00 UTC) on Friday 5 December 2025.\\n\\nCapture limits: This is a focused text capture of the official FIFA page timing statement located by web search. It is not a video capture of the draw ceremony.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-3 Governing PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION terms\\n                                         NEWMENTION\\n\\nScope: These rules shall apply to this contract.\\n\\nUnderlying: The Underlying for this Contract is words used by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nRevisions to the Underlying made after Expiration will not be accounted for in determining the\\nExpiration Value.\\n\\nSource Agency: The Source Agencies are \\u003csource\\u003e.\\n\\nType: The type of Contract is an Event Contract.\\n\\nIssuance: After the initial Contract, Contract iterations will be listed on an as-needed basis at\\nthe discretion of the Exchange and corresponding to the risk management needs of Members.\\n\\n\\u003centity\\u003e: \\u003centity\\u003e refers to the speaker, writer, performer, or communicator specified by the\\nExchange. This may include (but is not limited to): a specific named individual, multiple\\nindividuals specified using AND/OR logic, an individual identified by position or title, a group,\\nband, team or collective entity, a specified member or members of a group, an organization,\\ncompany, or institutional entity, or any combination of the aforementioned.\\n\\nWhen \\u003centity\\u003e is defined by a position or title, the Contract tracks whoever holds that position\\nduring \\u003ctime period\\u003e, even if the individual holding the position changes. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a\\nspecific named individual, the identity remains consistent throughout. Name changes (e.g.,\\nstage names, married names) do not create a new entity. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a group or\\norganization and the Contract does not specify particular members, any official\\ncommunication or statement by any member or designated spokesperson counts. When using\\nAND logic, all specified entities must independently say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e. When\\nusing OR logic, at least one of the specified entities must say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nThe Exchange may specify additional conditions such as “at least X members of” a group or\\n“the majority of” a group.\\n\\n\\u003csource\\u003e: \\u003csource\\u003e refers to a Source Agency or ordered collection of Source Agencies\\nspecified by the Exchange at the time of Contract listing, which will be incorporated into the\\nSource Agency hierarchy above and used to determine the occurrence of the Underlying.\\n\\u003csource\\u003e may refer to a singular agency, multiple agencies, an agency by distinguishing\\ncharacteristics, by category or type (e.g., “official government statistical body,” “primary wire\\nservice”), or any combination thereof. When multiple agencies are specified, they may be\\napplied in the hierarchical order designated by the Exchange if so specified, with the highest-\\nranked available and responsive agency taking precedence for purposes of determining the\\nExpiration Value. A lower-ranked agency shall only be consulted if all higher-ranked agencies\\nare unavailable, unresponsive, have not reported on the Underlying by the Expiration time, or\\nif the Exchange, in its sole discretion, determines that a higher-ranked agency’s reporting is\\nincomplete, erroneous, or otherwise insufficient to determine the Expiration Value. If \\u003csource\\u003e\\ndesignates multiple agencies without specifying a hierarchical order, the Exchange shall\\nresolve any conflict between reporting agencies at its sole discretion.\\n\\n\\u003cword\\u003e: \\u003cword\\u003e refers to the particular word or phrase potentially to be mentioned by\\n\\u003centity\\u003e. It may refer to a word being said a minimum number of times. It may also refer to\\none of multiple words/phrases, any of which are acceptable (e.g., “Doge/Dogecoin”).\\n\\f\\u003ctime period\\u003e: \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific range of time, event or discrete date and\\ntime specified by the Exchange. This may be defined by, but is not limited to: a specific event\\nor context (e.g., “during the State of the Union address”), exact dates or times, relative time\\nmarkers (e.g., “before July 1, 2027,” “in Q1 2026”), event-based periods (e.g., “during any\\ncampaign rally in October 2026,” “during the awards ceremony”), and broader intervals (e.g.,\\n“Q1–Q2 2027,” “January–March 2026”).\\n\\nUnless stated otherwise, “Between” is inclusive of both endpoints, while “before” and “after”\\nexclude the specified date. \\u003ctime period\\u003e may also refer to “Any” or “None”, to multiple dates\\n(even if non-consecutive), or to a singular and discrete date or time.\\n\\nWhen \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event (such as an address, speech, performance, or\\nbroadcast), the Exchange may specify what is included, including whether it includes both live\\nand pre-recorded segments (including whether advertisements are included). Where a\\ntimezone is not specified, ET is assumed.\\n\\n\\nPayout Criterion: The Payout Criterion for the Contract encompasses the Expiration Values that\\n\\u003cword\\u003e is said by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n\\n\\nThe word must appear as a distinct, standalone unit, not buried inside another word. Plural\\nand possessive noun forms count. Other grammatical changes (tense, conjugation, derivation)\\ndo not. If \\u003cword\\u003e appears separated from other words by a space or hyphen or in a\\ncompound form with a space or hyphen, it counts. If \\u003cword\\u003e is fused into a single\\nunhyphenated word, it does not count.\\n\\nIf \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled, and the market contains a\\nstrike stating “Event does not qualify/occur”, such a strike shall resolve “Yes” and all others\\n“No”. If \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled but such strikes are NOT\\nlisted, the Contracts will resolve to the last fair price determined at the discretion of the\\nExchange. If the event is postponed, and such a postponement is announced by the end of the\\nfollowing calendar day to be rescheduled to a time within 14 calendar days, the markets shall\\nremain open. If the event captured in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast, the\\nExchange may keep the market open for 24 hours for the release of an official recording.\\nFurther granular details on conditions for these Contracts is available below.\\n\\nAdditional clarification(s):\\n\\n     Possessive noun forms of \\u003cword\\u003e, plurals, and possessive plural noun forms are\\n     INCLUDED:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigrants” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Egg” → “eggs’ shells” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Russia” → “Russia’s” counts, “Russian” does not\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e exists only in adjective form, no plural form exists:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Economic” → “Economics” does not count (“Economic” is an adjective\\n          for which “Economics” is not a plural)\\n     Plural nouns occurring within proper nouns and noun phrases are included:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Cat” → “Cats the musical” counts\\n\\f    Grammatical variations beyond plurals/possessives are NOT included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigration” does NOT count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Run” → “Running” or “Ran” do NOT count\\n    When \\u003cword\\u003e specifies a plural form, the singular does NOT count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Veterans” → “Veteran” does NOT count\\n    Words that are spelled the same as the plural form of \\u003cword\\u003e (if such exists) but are\\n    themselves not a plural noun are included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Wind” → “Winds up the clock” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Border” → “The United States has strong borders” counts\\n    Open compounds (words separated by spaces) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fire station” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “couch” → “couch potato” counts\\n    Hyphenated compounds (words connected by hyphens) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Palestine” → “pro-Palestine” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fat” → “non-fat” counts\\n    Closed compounds (single word, no spaces/hyphens) do not count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire” does not count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firefighter” does not count\\n    Multi-word \\u003cword\\u003e in larger constructions: When \\u003cword\\u003e is a multi-word phrase\\n    appearing within a hyphenated construction, it counts only if \\u003cword\\u003e appears as a\\n    complete, unmodified element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “New York” → “New York-based” counts (complete element)\\n    Portmanteaus (words blended from two words where parts of each are combined) are\\n    NOT included unless the portmanteau clearly contains \\u003cword\\u003e as a distinct, unaltered\\n    element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “MAGA” → “MAGA-nificent” counts (MAGA appears as distinct element)\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “magnificent” → “MAGA-nificent” does NOT count (portmanteau blend)\\n\\nDictionary determination: Both the Merriam-Webster Dictionary (available online) AND the\\nOxford English Dictionary shall be used to determine compound type and/or conventional\\nspelling patterns. Inclusion in either dictionary as an open or hyphenated compound shall\\nsatisfy the Payout Criterion. If neither provides clarity (or the word is not included),\\ndetermination is based on whether written as single unit (closed/doesn’t count) vs. spaces or\\nhyphens (open or hyphenated/counts) and/or context and previous usage.\\n\\nPHONETIC EQUIVALENCIES\\n\\n    Homophones (same sound, different spelling) do not count:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “write” → “right” does not count\\n    Homonyms and homographs (same spelling) COUNT regardless of meaning or\\n    pronunciation:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “bass” → both “bass guitar” and “bass fishing” count\\n    Proper and common nouns are treated identically:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Apple” → both “Apple Inc.” and “apple” (fruit) count\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Will” → both “Will Smith” and “I will go” count\\n    Minor unintentional mispronunciations COUNT if context makes intent clear:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Mamdani” → “Mandani” counts\\n    Severe mispronunciations that make \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable do NOT count.\\n    Trademarked spellings do not count, even when pronounced identically, unless the word\\n\\fitself is the same:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “lift” → “Lyft” (pronounced “lift”) does not count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “uber” → “Uber” counts\\nWords with non-standard transliteration to English count within reason, provided they are\\nphonetically equivalent:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Zelensky” → any of “Zelenski,” “Zelenskii,” “Zelensky,” or “Zelenskiy”\\n      count if pronounced equivalently\\nContractions do not count for their constituent words unless otherwise explicitly specified\\nby the Exchange:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “not” → “won’t,” “can’t,” “don’t,” “isn’t” do not count\\nNumbers spoken as words COUNT, when spoken exactly (not part of a larger number):\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “five” → saying “five” or reading “$5” aloud as “five dollars” counts,\\n      saying “five hundred” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “410” → “four hundred ten”, “four one zero” or “four ten” counts\\nOrdinals COUNT when \\u003cword\\u003e is written numerically OR a phrase that includes a\\nnumber:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “January 6” → “January 6th” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “3” (written numerically) → “3rd” (spoken as “third”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Eight War” → “8 Wars” and “Eighth War” will count\\nCardinal and ordinal number words are distinct:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “one” → “first” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “first” → “one” does NOT count\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count when pronunciation or letter-by-letter spelling\\nmatches \\u003cword\\u003e:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “NASA” (pronounced “NAH-suh”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “N-A-S-A” (spelled out) counts\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count as \\u003cword\\u003e when pronounced as the full word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Doctor” → “Dr.” (pronounced “Doctor”) counts\\nExpanded forms of acronyms do NOT count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “AI” → “artificial intelligence” does not count\\nWords in foreign languages do NOT count unless they are perfect cognates with an\\nEnglish word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fuego” (Spanish) does NOT count\\nEnglish words within foreign sentences count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “policy” → “Nuestra policy es clara” counts\\n\\u003cword\\u003e in organization/company names counts:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Securities” → “Bank of America Securities” counts\\nWords in URLs, emails, handles, and hashtags (exclusive of domain structure, email\\nprovider or symbols) are treated as compounds when spoken as complete words, with the\\ntype of compound subject to aforementioned rules:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firestation.com” pronounced “fire station dot com” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire.com” pronounced “wildfire dot com” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “apple” → “apple.com” pronounced “apple dot com” does count\\n      When presented in URL, email, handle, or hashtag form, \\u003cword\\u003e shall be treated as\\n      a compound, not a multi-word word\\nSung, rapped, or poetic words COUNT if phonetically recognizable:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “money” → “moneyyy” (extended in rap) counts\\n      Extreme distortion making \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable does NOT count.\\nPhonetic alphabet spelling (“Foxtrot India Romeo Echo” for “FIRE”) does NOT count.\\n\\fCANCELLATIONS AND DELAYS\\n\\n   The Exchange may list an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike for any Contract. If listed,\\n   such a strike refers to the structural conditions of the market, and is NOT adjudicated as a\\n   \\u003cword\\u003e needing to be said by or validated by having been said by \\u003centity\\u003e. If listed, this\\n   strike resolves to “Yes” whenever the event fails to occur or qualify under the Payout\\n   Criterion, or any other circumstance prevents normal resolution.\\n   If no such strike is listed, and \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, the following rules\\n   apply if the event is cancelled, postponed, rescheduled, or materially altered (including\\n   being closed to press) such that no video is released within one calendar day of the\\n   original start time of the event:\\n         If the event is cancelled, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price determined in\\n         the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         If the event is postponed or rescheduled, the outcome depends on whether a new\\n         date is publicly announced within one calendar day (i.e. if the event was scheduled\\n         to begin on Monday, any time up to 11:59PM on Tuesday falls within this period) of\\n         the originally scheduled start time:\\n               If no new date is announced within one calendar day, the Contract will resolve\\n               to the last fair price determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n               If a new date is announced within one calendar day, the outcome depends on\\n               when the rescheduled event is set to occur:\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls within fourteen (14) calendar days of the\\n                     originally scheduled date, the Contract shall remain open and \\u003cword\\u003e\\n                     stated during the rescheduled event will count.\\n                           The fourteen-day window begins at 12:00 AM ET on the originally\\n                           scheduled date and ends at 11:59 PM ET fourteen days later, unless\\n                           an alternate timezone is explicitly specified.\\n                           Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the State of the Union on January\\n                           15, 2026” rescheduled to January 20, 2026 → words spoken during\\n                           the rescheduled address count.\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls more than fourteen (14) calendar days after\\n                     the originally scheduled date, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price\\n                     determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         Any Contract that cannot be resolved through the Source Agency hierarchy will\\n         instead be settled at the Last Fair Price. The Exchange will disclose the methodology\\n         used to determine the Last Fair Price (e.g., Last Traded Price, Time-Weighted\\n         Average Price) at the time of Issuance.\\n         If an event begins but is interrupted, abbreviated, or ends prematurely, words\\n         stated by \\u003centity\\u003e during the portion of the event that did occur will count and the\\n         market will otherwise resolve.\\n   If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window but the venue, format, or medium\\n   changes (e.g., moved to a different location, changed from in-person to virtual (with the\\n   exception of being closed to press)), words stated during the event will count.\\n   Special condition: Across both cases, whether an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike is\\n   listed or not, if the event specified as or in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast (or\\n   relayed as such) but the live stream/broadcast does not occur, the Exchange will instead\\n   use an officially released recording as the Underlying, and may delay resolution by up to\\n   one calendar day to allow for the release of such a recording.\\n\\f          If partial snippets are released, Contracts on words that do not appear will be\\n          resolved to last fair price, and Contracts on those that do will be resolved to “Yes”.\\n          If no recording is released, the relevant outcomes triggered by the\\n          presence/absence of an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike shall occur as outlined\\n          above.\\n\\nTECHNICAL DETAILS (UNLESS OTHERWISE SPECIFIED)\\n\\n     When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, pre-recorded content broadcast,\\n     streamed, or published as part of that event is included if presented as part of the official\\n     presentation.\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the concert” with pre-recorded video interlude\\n          where entity speaks → words from interlude count\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the television appearance” with pre-taped\\n          segment aired during broadcast → words from segment count\\n     Behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are NOT\\n     included unless officially broadcast or published as part of \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n     Subtitles and captions that display \\u003cword\\u003e on screen but are not spoken aloud by\\n     \\u003centity\\u003e do NOT count.\\n     Sign language interpretation or usage by entity does NOT count as saying \\u003cword\\u003e unless\\n     the Contract explicitly specifies that sign language counts.\\n     Text that entity displays on screen (presentation slides, teleprompter visible to audience,\\n     signatures) does NOT count unless entity reads it aloud.\\n     Content generated by AI, deepfakes, or synthetic voice technology impersonating entity\\n     does NOT count unless the synthetic content is officially commissioned, authorized, or\\n     published by entity, OR the Contract explicitly specifies that AI-generated content counts.\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e is muted due to technical failure or censorship it shall not count unless\\n     corroborating contextual evidence (including surrounding speech, or an official\\n     uncensored recording or transcript) confirms that \\u003centity\\u003e specifically uttered \\u003cword\\u003e\\n     during the muted period.\\n\\nMinimum Tick: The Minimum Tick size for the Contract shall be $0.01.\\n\\nPosition Accountability Level: The Position Accountability Level for the Contract shall be\\n$25,000 per strike, per Member.\\n\\nLast Trading Date: The Last Trading Date of the Contract will be the Expiration Date. The Last\\nTrading Time will be the Expiration time.\\n\\nSettlement Date: The Settlement Date of the Contract shall be no later than the day after the\\nExpiration Date, unless the Market Outcome is under review pursuant to Rule 7.1.\\n\\nExpiration Date: When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event: The latest Expiration Date of\\nthe Contract shall be fourteen (14) calendar days after the originally scheduled date of the\\nevent. If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window, expiration will be moved to an\\nearlier date and time in accordance with Rule 7.2. When \\u003ctime period\\u003e is defined by specific\\ndates: The latest Expiration Date of the Contract shall be two weeks after the end of \\u003ctime\\nperiod\\u003e. If an event described in the Payout Criterion occurs and a consensus has been\\nreached on all terms, then expiration will be moved to an earlier date and time in accordance\\nwith Rule 7.2.\\n\\fExpiration time: The Expiration time of the Contract shall be 10:00 AM ET.\\n\\nSettlement Value: The Settlement Value for this Contract is $1.00.\\n\\nExpiration Value: The Expiration Value is the value of the Underlying as documented by the\\nSource Agency on the Expiration Date at the Expiration time.\\n\\nContingencies: Before Settlement, Kalshi may, at its sole discretion, initiate the Market\\nOutcome Review Process pursuant to Rule 7.1 of the Rulebook. If an Expiration Value cannot\\nbe determined on the Expiration Date, Kalshi has the right to determine payouts pursuant to\\nRule 7.1 in the Rulebook.\\n\\f\\n\\n[defendant] DX-4 Market packet: Ronaldo strike and challenged No resolution\\nMarket URL: https://kalshi.com/markets/kxtrumpmentionb/trump-mention-b/kxtrumpmentionb-25dec06\\n\\nPublic market title: What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\n\\nContract family: PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION\\n\\nStrike at issue: Ronaldo\\n\\nChallenged resolution: No\\n\\nRequested resolution: Yes\\n\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R1 GovInfo transcript confirming Ronaldo utterances and Kennedy Center/FIFA Draw context\\nSource: GovInfo, Compilation of Presidential Documents, DCPD202501162\\nURL retrieved: https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/DCPD-202501162/html/DCPD-202501162.htm\\nRetrieval time: 2026-06-29T22:00:00Z\\nLocal captured HTML size/hash: 51,571 bytes; SHA-256 eadbceeecf3e94f5bd423bcb8e8511165fdc7265dd8c1e025870c2e8f34dfd99\\n\\nMaterial captured text from official GovInfo HTML/web.open:\\n\\nAdministration of Donald J. Trump, 2025\\n\\nTitle: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\nDate: December 5, 2025\\n\\nOpening note: [The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\\n\\nExcerpt - The President's Interest in Soccer (web.open lines 196-203):\\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\\\"football,\\\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\\n\\nExcerpt - The President's Interest in Soccer (web.open lines 322-329):\\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\\nThe President. But they have a little more speed. But no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\\n\\nTiming/context note (web.open lines 461-462):\\nNOTE: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. In his remarks, he referred to Trey Yingst, chief foreign correspondent, Fox News Channel; Cristiano Ronaldo, forward for Saudi Pro League club Al-Nass and Portugal's national soccer team; and Lionel Messi, forward for Major League Soccer club Inter Miami and Argentina's national team. A reporter referred to New York State Attorney General Letitia James.\\nThe transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\n\\nDocument category/location/name/subject metadata (web.open lines 463-468):\\nCategories: Interviews With the News Media: Exchanges with reporters, Washington, DC.\\nLocations: Washington, DC.\\nNames include: Cristiano Ronaldo and Lionel Messi.\\nSubjects include: Federation Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) World Cup; John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts; News media, Presidential interviews; Soccer.\\nDCPD Number: DCPD202501162.\\n\\nCapture limits: This item is a focused text capture of the material official transcript title, Ronaldo excerpts, timing/correction note, and metadata. It is not a full video or audio artifact. The official transcript itself notes some portions could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R2 FIFA timing capture showing formal commencement time but not market-specific exclusion\\nSource: FIFA official page, FIFA World Cup 2026 Final Draw\\nURL: https://www.fifa.com/en/tournaments/mens/worldcup/canadamexicousa2026/live-draw\\nRetrieval time: 2026-06-29T22:01:00Z\\n\\nMaterial captured text from web search/open result:\\n- Page title/source: FIFA World Cup 2026™ Final Draw\\n- The draw takes place at the Kennedy Center in Washington DC, USA.\\n- The draw commences at 12:00 local time (17:00 UTC) on Friday 5 December 2025.\\n\\nCapture limits: This is a focused text capture of the official FIFA page timing statement located by web search. It is not a video capture of the draw ceremony.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R3 Event-period terms and exclusions\\n                                         NEWMENTION\\n\\nScope: These rules shall apply to this contract.\\n\\nUnderlying: The Underlying for this Contract is words used by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nRevisions to the Underlying made after Expiration will not be accounted for in determining the\\nExpiration Value.\\n\\nSource Agency: The Source Agencies are \\u003csource\\u003e.\\n\\nType: The type of Contract is an Event Contract.\\n\\nIssuance: After the initial Contract, Contract iterations will be listed on an as-needed basis at\\nthe discretion of the Exchange and corresponding to the risk management needs of Members.\\n\\n\\u003centity\\u003e: \\u003centity\\u003e refers to the speaker, writer, performer, or communicator specified by the\\nExchange. This may include (but is not limited to): a specific named individual, multiple\\nindividuals specified using AND/OR logic, an individual identified by position or title, a group,\\nband, team or collective entity, a specified member or members of a group, an organization,\\ncompany, or institutional entity, or any combination of the aforementioned.\\n\\nWhen \\u003centity\\u003e is defined by a position or title, the Contract tracks whoever holds that position\\nduring \\u003ctime period\\u003e, even if the individual holding the position changes. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a\\nspecific named individual, the identity remains consistent throughout. Name changes (e.g.,\\nstage names, married names) do not create a new entity. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a group or\\norganization and the Contract does not specify particular members, any official\\ncommunication or statement by any member or designated spokesperson counts. When using\\nAND logic, all specified entities must independently say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e. When\\nusing OR logic, at least one of the specified entities must say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nThe Exchange may specify additional conditions such as “at least X members of” a group or\\n“the majority of” a group.\\n\\n\\u003csource\\u003e: \\u003csource\\u003e refers to a Source Agency or ordered collection of Source Agencies\\nspecified by the Exchange at the time of Contract listing, which will be incorporated into the\\nSource Agency hierarchy above and used to determine the occurrence of the Underlying.\\n\\u003csource\\u003e may refer to a singular agency, multiple agencies, an agency by distinguishing\\ncharacteristics, by category or type (e.g., “official government statistical body,” “primary wire\\nservice”), or any combination thereof. When multiple agencies are specified, they may be\\napplied in the hierarchical order designated by the Exchange if so specified, with the highest-\\nranked available and responsive agency taking precedence for purposes of determining the\\nExpiration Value. A lower-ranked agency shall only be consulted if all higher-ranked agencies\\nare unavailable, unresponsive, have not reported on the Underlying by the Expiration time, or\\nif the Exchange, in its sole discretion, determines that a higher-ranked agency’s reporting is\\nincomplete, erroneous, or otherwise insufficient to determine the Expiration Value. If \\u003csource\\u003e\\ndesignates multiple agencies without specifying a hierarchical order, the Exchange shall\\nresolve any conflict between reporting agencies at its sole discretion.\\n\\n\\u003cword\\u003e: \\u003cword\\u003e refers to the particular word or phrase potentially to be mentioned by\\n\\u003centity\\u003e. It may refer to a word being said a minimum number of times. It may also refer to\\none of multiple words/phrases, any of which are acceptable (e.g., “Doge/Dogecoin”).\\n\\f\\u003ctime period\\u003e: \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific range of time, event or discrete date and\\ntime specified by the Exchange. This may be defined by, but is not limited to: a specific event\\nor context (e.g., “during the State of the Union address”), exact dates or times, relative time\\nmarkers (e.g., “before July 1, 2027,” “in Q1 2026”), event-based periods (e.g., “during any\\ncampaign rally in October 2026,” “during the awards ceremony”), and broader intervals (e.g.,\\n“Q1–Q2 2027,” “January–March 2026”).\\n\\nUnless stated otherwise, “Between” is inclusive of both endpoints, while “before” and “after”\\nexclude the specified date. \\u003ctime period\\u003e may also refer to “Any” or “None”, to multiple dates\\n(even if non-consecutive), or to a singular and discrete date or time.\\n\\nWhen \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event (such as an address, speech, performance, or\\nbroadcast), the Exchange may specify what is included, including whether it includes both live\\nand pre-recorded segments (including whether advertisements are included). Where a\\ntimezone is not specified, ET is assumed.\\n\\n\\nPayout Criterion: The Payout Criterion for the Contract encompasses the Expiration Values that\\n\\u003cword\\u003e is said by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n\\n\\nThe word must appear as a distinct, standalone unit, not buried inside another word. Plural\\nand possessive noun forms count. Other grammatical changes (tense, conjugation, derivation)\\ndo not. If \\u003cword\\u003e appears separated from other words by a space or hyphen or in a\\ncompound form with a space or hyphen, it counts. If \\u003cword\\u003e is fused into a single\\nunhyphenated word, it does not count.\\n\\nIf \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled, and the market contains a\\nstrike stating “Event does not qualify/occur”, such a strike shall resolve “Yes” and all others\\n“No”. If \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled but such strikes are NOT\\nlisted, the Contracts will resolve to the last fair price determined at the discretion of the\\nExchange. If the event is postponed, and such a postponement is announced by the end of the\\nfollowing calendar day to be rescheduled to a time within 14 calendar days, the markets shall\\nremain open. If the event captured in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast, the\\nExchange may keep the market open for 24 hours for the release of an official recording.\\nFurther granular details on conditions for these Contracts is available below.\\n\\nAdditional clarification(s):\\n\\n     Possessive noun forms of \\u003cword\\u003e, plurals, and possessive plural noun forms are\\n     INCLUDED:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigrants” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Egg” → “eggs’ shells” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Russia” → “Russia’s” counts, “Russian” does not\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e exists only in adjective form, no plural form exists:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Economic” → “Economics” does not count (“Economic” is an adjective\\n          for which “Economics” is not a plural)\\n     Plural nouns occurring within proper nouns and noun phrases are included:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Cat” → “Cats the musical” counts\\n\\f    Grammatical variations beyond plurals/possessives are NOT included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigration” does NOT count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Run” → “Running” or “Ran” do NOT count\\n    When \\u003cword\\u003e specifies a plural form, the singular does NOT count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Veterans” → “Veteran” does NOT count\\n    Words that are spelled the same as the plural form of \\u003cword\\u003e (if such exists) but are\\n    themselves not a plural noun are included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Wind” → “Winds up the clock” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Border” → “The United States has strong borders” counts\\n    Open compounds (words separated by spaces) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fire station” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “couch” → “couch potato” counts\\n    Hyphenated compounds (words connected by hyphens) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Palestine” → “pro-Palestine” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fat” → “non-fat” counts\\n    Closed compounds (single word, no spaces/hyphens) do not count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire” does not count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firefighter” does not count\\n    Multi-word \\u003cword\\u003e in larger constructions: When \\u003cword\\u003e is a multi-word phrase\\n    appearing within a hyphenated construction, it counts only if \\u003cword\\u003e appears as a\\n    complete, unmodified element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “New York” → “New York-based” counts (complete element)\\n    Portmanteaus (words blended from two words where parts of each are combined) are\\n    NOT included unless the portmanteau clearly contains \\u003cword\\u003e as a distinct, unaltered\\n    element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “MAGA” → “MAGA-nificent” counts (MAGA appears as distinct element)\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “magnificent” → “MAGA-nificent” does NOT count (portmanteau blend)\\n\\nDictionary determination: Both the Merriam-Webster Dictionary (available online) AND the\\nOxford English Dictionary shall be used to determine compound type and/or conventional\\nspelling patterns. Inclusion in either dictionary as an open or hyphenated compound shall\\nsatisfy the Payout Criterion. If neither provides clarity (or the word is not included),\\ndetermination is based on whether written as single unit (closed/doesn’t count) vs. spaces or\\nhyphens (open or hyphenated/counts) and/or context and previous usage.\\n\\nPHONETIC EQUIVALENCIES\\n\\n    Homophones (same sound, different spelling) do not count:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “write” → “right” does not count\\n    Homonyms and homographs (same spelling) COUNT regardless of meaning or\\n    pronunciation:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “bass” → both “bass guitar” and “bass fishing” count\\n    Proper and common nouns are treated identically:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Apple” → both “Apple Inc.” and “apple” (fruit) count\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Will” → both “Will Smith” and “I will go” count\\n    Minor unintentional mispronunciations COUNT if context makes intent clear:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Mamdani” → “Mandani” counts\\n    Severe mispronunciations that make \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable do NOT count.\\n    Trademarked spellings do not count, even when pronounced identically, unless the word\\n\\fitself is the same:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “lift” → “Lyft” (pronounced “lift”) does not count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “uber” → “Uber” counts\\nWords with non-standard transliteration to English count within reason, provided they are\\nphonetically equivalent:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Zelensky” → any of “Zelenski,” “Zelenskii,” “Zelensky,” or “Zelenskiy”\\n      count if pronounced equivalently\\nContractions do not count for their constituent words unless otherwise explicitly specified\\nby the Exchange:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “not” → “won’t,” “can’t,” “don’t,” “isn’t” do not count\\nNumbers spoken as words COUNT, when spoken exactly (not part of a larger number):\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “five” → saying “five” or reading “$5” aloud as “five dollars” counts,\\n      saying “five hundred” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “410” → “four hundred ten”, “four one zero” or “four ten” counts\\nOrdinals COUNT when \\u003cword\\u003e is written numerically OR a phrase that includes a\\nnumber:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “January 6” → “January 6th” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “3” (written numerically) → “3rd” (spoken as “third”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Eight War” → “8 Wars” and “Eighth War” will count\\nCardinal and ordinal number words are distinct:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “one” → “first” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “first” → “one” does NOT count\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count when pronunciation or letter-by-letter spelling\\nmatches \\u003cword\\u003e:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “NASA” (pronounced “NAH-suh”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “N-A-S-A” (spelled out) counts\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count as \\u003cword\\u003e when pronounced as the full word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Doctor” → “Dr.” (pronounced “Doctor”) counts\\nExpanded forms of acronyms do NOT count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “AI” → “artificial intelligence” does not count\\nWords in foreign languages do NOT count unless they are perfect cognates with an\\nEnglish word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fuego” (Spanish) does NOT count\\nEnglish words within foreign sentences count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “policy” → “Nuestra policy es clara” counts\\n\\u003cword\\u003e in organization/company names counts:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Securities” → “Bank of America Securities” counts\\nWords in URLs, emails, handles, and hashtags (exclusive of domain structure, email\\nprovider or symbols) are treated as compounds when spoken as complete words, with the\\ntype of compound subject to aforementioned rules:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firestation.com” pronounced “fire station dot com” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire.com” pronounced “wildfire dot com” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “apple” → “apple.com” pronounced “apple dot com” does count\\n      When presented in URL, email, handle, or hashtag form, \\u003cword\\u003e shall be treated as\\n      a compound, not a multi-word word\\nSung, rapped, or poetic words COUNT if phonetically recognizable:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “money” → “moneyyy” (extended in rap) counts\\n      Extreme distortion making \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable does NOT count.\\nPhonetic alphabet spelling (“Foxtrot India Romeo Echo” for “FIRE”) does NOT count.\\n\\fCANCELLATIONS AND DELAYS\\n\\n   The Exchange may list an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike for any Contract. If listed,\\n   such a strike refers to the structural conditions of the market, and is NOT adjudicated as a\\n   \\u003cword\\u003e needing to be said by or validated by having been said by \\u003centity\\u003e. If listed, this\\n   strike resolves to “Yes” whenever the event fails to occur or qualify under the Payout\\n   Criterion, or any other circumstance prevents normal resolution.\\n   If no such strike is listed, and \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, the following rules\\n   apply if the event is cancelled, postponed, rescheduled, or materially altered (including\\n   being closed to press) such that no video is released within one calendar day of the\\n   original start time of the event:\\n         If the event is cancelled, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price determined in\\n         the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         If the event is postponed or rescheduled, the outcome depends on whether a new\\n         date is publicly announced within one calendar day (i.e. if the event was scheduled\\n         to begin on Monday, any time up to 11:59PM on Tuesday falls within this period) of\\n         the originally scheduled start time:\\n               If no new date is announced within one calendar day, the Contract will resolve\\n               to the last fair price determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n               If a new date is announced within one calendar day, the outcome depends on\\n               when the rescheduled event is set to occur:\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls within fourteen (14) calendar days of the\\n                     originally scheduled date, the Contract shall remain open and \\u003cword\\u003e\\n                     stated during the rescheduled event will count.\\n                           The fourteen-day window begins at 12:00 AM ET on the originally\\n                           scheduled date and ends at 11:59 PM ET fourteen days later, unless\\n                           an alternate timezone is explicitly specified.\\n                           Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the State of the Union on January\\n                           15, 2026” rescheduled to January 20, 2026 → words spoken during\\n                           the rescheduled address count.\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls more than fourteen (14) calendar days after\\n                     the originally scheduled date, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price\\n                     determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         Any Contract that cannot be resolved through the Source Agency hierarchy will\\n         instead be settled at the Last Fair Price. The Exchange will disclose the methodology\\n         used to determine the Last Fair Price (e.g., Last Traded Price, Time-Weighted\\n         Average Price) at the time of Issuance.\\n         If an event begins but is interrupted, abbreviated, or ends prematurely, words\\n         stated by \\u003centity\\u003e during the portion of the event that did occur will count and the\\n         market will otherwise resolve.\\n   If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window but the venue, format, or medium\\n   changes (e.g., moved to a different location, changed from in-person to virtual (with the\\n   exception of being closed to press)), words stated during the event will count.\\n   Special condition: Across both cases, whether an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike is\\n   listed or not, if the event specified as or in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast (or\\n   relayed as such) but the live stream/broadcast does not occur, the Exchange will instead\\n   use an officially released recording as the Underlying, and may delay resolution by up to\\n   one calendar day to allow for the release of such a recording.\\n\\f          If partial snippets are released, Contracts on words that do not appear will be\\n          resolved to last fair price, and Contracts on those that do will be resolved to “Yes”.\\n          If no recording is released, the relevant outcomes triggered by the\\n          presence/absence of an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike shall occur as outlined\\n          above.\\n\\nTECHNICAL DETAILS (UNLESS OTHERWISE SPECIFIED)\\n\\n     When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, pre-recorded content broadcast,\\n     streamed, or published as part of that event is included if presented as part of the official\\n     presentation.\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the concert” with pre-recorded video interlude\\n          where entity speaks → words from interlude count\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the television appearance” with pre-taped\\n          segment aired during broadcast → words from segment count\\n     Behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are NOT\\n     included unless officially broadcast or published as part of \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n     Subtitles and captions that display \\u003cword\\u003e on screen but are not spoken aloud by\\n     \\u003centity\\u003e do NOT count.\\n     Sign language interpretation or usage by entity does NOT count as saying \\u003cword\\u003e unless\\n     the Contract explicitly specifies that sign language counts.\\n     Text that entity displays on screen (presentation slides, teleprompter visible to audience,\\n     signatures) does NOT count unless entity reads it aloud.\\n     Content generated by AI, deepfakes, or synthetic voice technology impersonating entity\\n     does NOT count unless the synthetic content is officially commissioned, authorized, or\\n     published by entity, OR the Contract explicitly specifies that AI-generated content counts.\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e is muted due to technical failure or censorship it shall not count unless\\n     corroborating contextual evidence (including surrounding speech, or an official\\n     uncensored recording or transcript) confirms that \\u003centity\\u003e specifically uttered \\u003cword\\u003e\\n     during the muted period.\\n\\nMinimum Tick: The Minimum Tick size for the Contract shall be $0.01.\\n\\nPosition Accountability Level: The Position Accountability Level for the Contract shall be\\n$25,000 per strike, per Member.\\n\\nLast Trading Date: The Last Trading Date of the Contract will be the Expiration Date. The Last\\nTrading Time will be the Expiration time.\\n\\nSettlement Date: The Settlement Date of the Contract shall be no later than the day after the\\nExpiration Date, unless the Market Outcome is under review pursuant to Rule 7.1.\\n\\nExpiration Date: When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event: The latest Expiration Date of\\nthe Contract shall be fourteen (14) calendar days after the originally scheduled date of the\\nevent. If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window, expiration will be moved to an\\nearlier date and time in accordance with Rule 7.2. When \\u003ctime period\\u003e is defined by specific\\ndates: The latest Expiration Date of the Contract shall be two weeks after the end of \\u003ctime\\nperiod\\u003e. If an event described in the Payout Criterion occurs and a consensus has been\\nreached on all terms, then expiration will be moved to an earlier date and time in accordance\\nwith Rule 7.2.\\n\\fExpiration time: The Expiration time of the Contract shall be 10:00 AM ET.\\n\\nSettlement Value: The Settlement Value for this Contract is $1.00.\\n\\nExpiration Value: The Expiration Value is the value of the Underlying as documented by the\\nSource Agency on the Expiration Date at the Expiration time.\\n\\nContingencies: Before Settlement, Kalshi may, at its sole discretion, initiate the Market\\nOutcome Review Process pursuant to Rule 7.1 of the Rulebook. If an Expiration Value cannot\\nbe determined on the Expiration Date, Kalshi has the right to determine payouts pursuant to\\nRule 7.1 in the Rulebook.\\n\\f\\n\\n[defendant] DX-S1 GovInfo official transcript: prior reporter exchange\\nSource: GovInfo, Compilation of Presidential Documents, DCPD202501162\\nURL retrieved: https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/DCPD-202501162/html/DCPD-202501162.htm\\nRetrieval time: 2026-06-29T22:00:00Z\\nLocal captured HTML size/hash: 51,571 bytes; SHA-256 eadbceeecf3e94f5bd423bcb8e8511165fdc7265dd8c1e025870c2e8f34dfd99\\n\\nMaterial captured text from official GovInfo HTML/web.open:\\n\\nAdministration of Donald J. Trump, 2025\\n\\nTitle: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\nDate: December 5, 2025\\n\\nOpening note: [The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\\n\\nExcerpt - The President's Interest in Soccer (web.open lines 196-203):\\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\\\"football,\\\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\\n\\nExcerpt - The President's Interest in Soccer (web.open lines 322-329):\\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\\nThe President. But they have a little more speed. But no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\\n\\nTiming/context note (web.open lines 461-462):\\nNOTE: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. In his remarks, he referred to Trey Yingst, chief foreign correspondent, Fox News Channel; Cristiano Ronaldo, forward for Saudi Pro League club Al-Nass and Portugal's national soccer team; and Lionel Messi, forward for Major League Soccer club Inter Miami and Argentina's national team. A reporter referred to New York State Attorney General Letitia James.\\nThe transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\n\\nDocument category/location/name/subject metadata (web.open lines 463-468):\\nCategories: Interviews With the News Media: Exchanges with reporters, Washington, DC.\\nLocations: Washington, DC.\\nNames include: Cristiano Ronaldo and Lionel Messi.\\nSubjects include: Federation Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) World Cup; John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts; News media, Presidential interviews; Soccer.\\nDCPD Number: DCPD202501162.\\n\\nCapture limits: This item is a focused text capture of the material official transcript title, Ronaldo excerpts, timing/correction note, and metadata. It is not a full video or audio artifact. The official transcript itself notes some portions could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-S2 FIFA official draw commencement time\\nSource: FIFA official page, FIFA World Cup 2026 Final Draw\\nURL: https://www.fifa.com/en/tournaments/mens/worldcup/canadamexicousa2026/live-draw\\nRetrieval time: 2026-06-29T22:01:00Z\\n\\nMaterial captured text from web search/open result:\\n- Page title/source: FIFA World Cup 2026™ Final Draw\\n- The draw takes place at the Kennedy Center in Washington DC, USA.\\n- The draw commences at 12:00 local time (17:00 UTC) on Friday 5 December 2025.\\n\\nCapture limits: This is a focused text capture of the official FIFA page timing statement located by web search. It is not a video capture of the draw ceremony.\\n\\nSubmitted evidence:\\n[plaintiff arguments] Official White House video page capture: President Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing (ev_db357d4e9407_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-db357d4e9407)\\nSource: https://www.whitehouse.gov/videos/president-trump-attends-the-fifa-world-cup-drawing/\\nSHA-256: `db357d4e940728d417ae4f7f3caac6b78d3fd3e4aba70d46fe10c6132d45997a`\\nBytes: 1300\\nRelevance: Establishes that the White House officially published a video page titled President Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing, dated December 5, 2025, with a full-video link and related World Cup Draw videos; relevant to source chain and event context.\\n\\n[plaintiff arguments] YouTube metadata capture: Trump Talks Cristiano Ronaldo at FIFA Draw (ev_4e1045905547_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-4e1045905547)\\nSource: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Cb2yO0lLEnM\\nSHA-256: `4e10459055477440085fe5e20d970eb2488e61d13a5e2b3133a3656bed7526d7`\\nBytes: 1779\\nRelevance: Provides a public clip source and page metadata asserting that at the FIFA World Cup Draw Ceremony Trump shared a story about meeting Cristiano Ronaldo and said Ronaldo was a great person; relevant to the alleged Ronaldo utterance, though weaker than an official full transcript or video.\\n\\n[defendant arguments] GovInfo official transcript capture: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the FIFA World Cup Draw (ev_a1b1f6b1b7bd_submitted-evidence-03-defendant-a1b1f6b1b7bd)\\nSource: https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/DCPD-202501162/html/DCPD-202501162.htm\\nSHA-256: `a1b1f6b1b7bd0b691c7fe8d97467dd0d085e2b22387ae4198270764de66e56e2`\\nBytes: 3070\\nRelevance: Official transcript identifies the relevant Trump remarks as an exchange with reporters prior to the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw; it includes the Ronaldo utterances and timing/correction notes, directly bearing on whether the utterances were during the countable event period.\\n\\n[defendant arguments] FIFA official page capture: 2026 World Cup Final Draw start time (ev_3973dc8f98c0_submitted-evidence-04-defendant-3973dc8f98c0)\\nSource: https://www.fifa.com/en/tournaments/mens/worldcup/canadamexicousa2026/live-draw\\nSHA-256: `3973dc8f98c01702174f61f5548eb1e80efe64dd72b44f21ed0fa7d944f93248`\\nBytes: 598\\nRelevance: Establishes the official Final Draw start time as 12:00 local time on December 5, 2025, which helps compare the draw event period against the GovInfo transcript note that the reporter exchange occurred at 11:13 a.m.\\n\\nTechnical reports:\\n[plaintiff] Plaintiff source-search and capture ledger\\nSearched exact market/strike phrases, White House domain, public video pages, YouTube video IDs, and Kalshi live market URL. Submitted official White House page capture and YouTube metadata capture. Kalshi live page returned a Vercel security checkpoint/429; local browser was unavailable; Python pip/ensurepip unavailable for yt-dlp; direct YouTube caption/open paths were throttled or unavailable. Remaining best evidence would be a full official video/transcript or Kalshi resolution rationale if later accessible.\\n\\n[defendant] Defendant source-search and capture ledger\\nInspected current AAR evidence and exact contents of plaintiff's White House and YouTube captures. Retrieved GovInfo official HTML transcript with curl from DCPD-202501162; local full HTML was 51,571 bytes with SHA-256 eadbceeecf3e94f5bd423bcb8e8511165fdc7265dd8c1e025870c2e8f34dfd99, then submitted a focused material text capture as DX-1. Searched official draw timing and submitted the FIFA official page timing statement as DX-2. Remaining gaps: full Kalshi market source hierarchy/resolution rationale and full WH/FIFA video were not captured, but official GovInfo timing/title plus FIFA start time resolve the material timing issue.\\n\\nCall submit_council_vote with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated.\\nKeep the rationale brief: no more than three sentences.\\n\\nCouncil API instructions:\\nYou are a council member. Decide the proposition from the admitted record.\\nYou may examine admitted evidence through read-only tools when exact bytes, metadata, or exhibit contents matter.\\nDo not search the web, introduce new facts, create new evidence, or upload evidence.\\nWhen ready, call submit_council_vote exactly once with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated and a concise rationale.\\n\",\"state\":\"ready\",\"status\":\"ready\",\"tools\":[{\"description\":\"Return the current visible arbitration record for this council member.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"get_case\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"List visible immutable record evidence.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"list_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Return metadata and read limits for one visible evidence item.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"stat_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Read a bounded byte range from one visible evidence item as base64.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"length\":{\"minimum\":1,\"type\":\"integer\"},\"offset\":{\"minimum\":0,\"type\":\"integer\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\",\"offset\",\"length\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"read_evidence_range\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Submit one council vote for the current deliberation opportunity.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"rationale\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"vote\":{\"enum\":[\"demonstrated\",\"not_demonstrated\"],\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"vote\",\"rationale\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"submit_council_vote\",\"read_only\":false}],\"turn\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"completed\":false,\"deadline\":\"2026-06-29T22:18:45.386037689Z\",\"deliberation_round\":1,\"member_id\":\"C2\",\"opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C2\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"remaining_ms\":889046,\"role_id\":\"council\",\"turn_number\":10},\"wait\":{\"reason\":\"ready\",\"state_version\":14,\"version\":17}}"}],"details":{"mode":"call","mcpResult":{"content":[{"type":"text","text":"ok: true\nstatus: ready\nstate: ready\nmessage: An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\nafter_version: 17\nafter_opportunity_id: deliberation:1:C2\nmember_id: C2\ncase_id: arb-ex03a-20260629214245\nwait_reason: ready\nphase: deliberation\nopportunity_id: deliberation:1:C2\nremaining_ms: 889046\nattempts_remaining: 3\njson: {\"after_opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C2\",\"after_version\":17,\"case_id\":\"arb-ex03a-20260629214245\",\"limits\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"max_evidence_read_bytes\":65536,\"max_evidence_read_bytes_per_opportunity\":524288,\"max_evidence_reads_per_opportunity\":32,\"max_response_bytes\":131072,\"remaining_evidence_read_bytes_for_opportunity\":524288,\"remaining_evidence_reads_for_opportunity\":32},\"member_id\":\"C2\",\"message\":\"An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\",\"ok\":true,\"prompt\":\"Role: council member\\nMember ID: C2\\nDeliberation round: 1\\nProposition: For the Kalshi market \\\"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\\", the strike \\\"Ronaldo\\\" should resolve Yes because Trump said \\\"Ronaldo\\\" in public remarks at the World Cup Draw venue immediately before the formal program, and the market wording plus the governing mention-market terms did not clearly exclude those event-linked remarks.\\nStandard of evidence: Preponderance of the evidence.\\nPersona:\\nYou are a careful juror and council member.\\n\\nEvaluate the record faithfully. Decide only from the evidence, the stated rules, and the applicable burden of proof. Do not favor either side, fill gaps with speculation, or ignore uncertainty.\\n\\nGive weight to reliable sources, direct evidence, consistent reasoning, and clear admissions. Discount unsupported claims, rhetorical force, irrelevant facts, and conclusions that exceed the record.\\n\\nWhen the evidence supports one answer, state it plainly. When the evidence is incomplete or balanced, say so. Be concise, honest, and exact.\\n\\nRecord:\\nOpenings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, this case is not about whether the word \\\"Ronaldo\\\" would count if President Trump clearly said it. The current packet makes that part straightforward: the market is the Kalshi PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION market titled \\\"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\\"; the strike is \\\"Ronaldo\\\"; Kalshi’s challenged resolution is No; and plaintiff seeks Yes.\\n\\nThe real dispute is temporal and contextual. Did the market phrase \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw,\\\" read with the governing mention-market terms, include public event-linked remarks at the World Cup Draw venue immediately before the formal draw program? Or did it clearly confine countable words to a narrower formal broadcast segment? Plaintiff’s position is that a No resolution cannot stand unless the record shows that the counting window clearly excluded those event-linked remarks.\\n\\nThe admitted terms matter. They define the underlying as words used by the specified entity during the specified time period. They expressly recognize event-based time periods, and they say the payout criterion is satisfied when the word is said by the entity during that period. They also contain exclusions: behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings do not count unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period; captions or text alone do not count; and the word must appear as a distinct standalone unit. Those exclusions are important, but they do not by themselves answer this case. A public remark at the event venue, tied to the Draw and immediately before the formal program, is not automatically a rehearsal, sound check, or private behind-the-scenes moment.\\n\\nAt this opening stage, the record proves the market identity, the challenged resolution, the requested resolution, and the generic governing terms. It does not yet prove the utterance itself, the exact sequence of the venue remarks, the source-agency hierarchy or any market-specific time-period language beyond the packet, or Kalshi’s reason for treating the strike as No. Those are the factual links that should decide the case under a preponderance standard.\\n\\nPlaintiff expects the decisive proof to be the full official or otherwise reliable event video or transcript, with enough surrounding context to show whether Trump said \\\"Ronaldo\\\" aloud as a standalone word; when he said it relative to the Draw event; whether the remarks were public and event-linked rather than backstage or a sound check; and whether any market-specific rule clearly excluded that segment. Plaintiff also expects the market page, archived market details, and any resolution rationale to be important because ambiguity in the market’s own event wording should not be resolved against Yes after the fact.\\n\\nThe defense will likely argue that \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw\\\" means only the formal draw ceremony or broadcast, and that anything before the formal program is outside the counting period. That theory can win only if the evidence shows a clear exclusion or a source record that separates the alleged remarks from the event itself. If the evidence instead shows public remarks at the Draw venue, officially connected to the event, immediately before the formal program, and no clear rule excluding them, then the terms favor counting the word and resolving the Ronaldo strike Yes.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the defense position is straightforward: the admitted record does not yet prove that the Ronaldo strike should resolve Yes. It proves a market title, a generic mention-market rule set, and Kalshi's challenged No resolution. It does not prove that any qualifying utterance of \\\"Ronaldo\\\" occurred during the market's countable time period.\\n\\nThe plaintiff's opening usefully narrows the dispute. This is not primarily a word-boundary case. If President Trump said \\\"Ronaldo\\\" as a standalone spoken word during the countable FIFA World Cup Draw period, the generic terms would ordinarily treat that as the kind of word that can count. The real question is whether plaintiff can carry the burden of showing that alleged pre-program, venue-adjacent remarks were part of the market's specified time period: \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\\\"\\n\\nThe case-packet terms matter, but they cut both ways. They say the underlying is words used by the entity during the specified time period. They recognize that a time period can be an event, and they allow the Exchange to specify what is included when an event is involved. They also distinguish official event presentation from material outside the event: behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are not included unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period; text or captions alone do not count; and the relevant word must be spoken aloud by the entity. Those provisions do not support a rule that every public comment inside the same building, or every press exchange near the formal program, is automatically \\\"during\\\" the Draw.\\n\\nThat is the burden problem for plaintiff. The admitted market-page file identifies the public title, contract family, strike, challenged resolution, and requested resolution. It does not supply a full market-specific source hierarchy, a formal start time, a transcript, a video, a resolution rationale, or the alleged remarks. The terms file supplies the generic framework, but not the factual bridge from \\\"immediately before the formal program\\\" to \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\\\" Without that bridge, the No resolution is not shown to be wrong by a preponderance of the evidence.\\n\\nThe defense expects the decisive proof to be source-chain evidence, not characterization. The council should want the market's full rule page if available, the source agency hierarchy, the official draw program or broadcast, any official transcript or recording of the alleged exchange, and enough surrounding timestamps to separate the formal draw from pre-event reporter access, red-carpet exchanges, arrivals, or other ancillary material. If later evidence shows that the alleged Ronaldo comment was in a segment officially presented as part of the Draw itself, plaintiff's argument becomes stronger. If the evidence instead shows a separate exchange with reporters before the draw, or an event-linked but pre-program interaction not incorporated into the official presentation, the generic terms support Kalshi's No.\\n\\nSo the defense opening is not that the word Ronaldo could never count. It is that this record has not established the necessary time-period link. The proposition asks the council to overturn No because the market wording and terms did not clearly exclude pre-program remarks. That reverses the burden. Plaintiff must show that the remarks were included in the countable period. Ambiguity about the outer edge of an event is not the same as proof that a specific pre-event utterance satisfies the payout criterion.\\n\\nArguments:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, plaintiff has now supplied the record links that were missing at opening.\\n\\nFirst, the market packet fixes what this dispute is: the Kalshi market title is \\\"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\\"; the contract family is PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION; the strike is \\\"Ronaldo\\\"; Kalshi's challenged resolution is No; and plaintiff seeks Yes. That is PX-1.\\n\\nSecond, the governing terms make this an event-period mention question, not a narrow formal-program-only question. PX-2 says the underlying is words used by the entity during the time period, recognizes that a time period may be a specific event, and sets the payout criterion as the word being said by the entity during that period. It also tells us what does not count: text/captions alone, unofficial behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, and sound checks unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. Those exclusions matter, but none says that public event-linked remarks at the venue immediately before the formal program are categorically outside \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\\\"\\n\\nThird, the source-chain evidence now points to the disputed event and the Ronaldo utterance. PX-3 is an official White House page titled \\\"President Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing,\\\" dated December 5, 2025, with a full-video link and related World Cup Draw videos. That establishes an official White House event-video source for Trump's attendance at the World Cup Drawing. PX-4 is a public YouTube watch-page metadata capture for video ID Cb2yO0lLEnM, titled \\\"Trump Talks Cristiano Ronaldo at FIFA Draw -- 'He's a Great Person'.\\\" Its description states that at the FIFA World Cup Draw Ceremony, Trump shared a story about meeting Cristiano Ronaldo at the White House, said Ronaldo was a great person, and mentioned Ronaldo spoke with his son. PX-4 is not as strong as an official transcript, and plaintiff says that plainly. But it is admitted source content that directly links Trump, Cristiano Ronaldo, and the FIFA Draw ceremony.\\n\\nOn a preponderance standard, that is enough to defeat the challenged No resolution unless the defense can supply a clearer exclusion. The market did not ask only what Trump would say during the ball-pulling segment, during the televised main show, or after a particular formal start cue. It asked what he would say \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\\\" The terms recognize event-based periods and exclude particular non-event categories. A public remark at the Draw venue, tied to the Draw, is far closer to the event period than to a rehearsal, sound check, caption, or private backstage recording.\\n\\nThe defense's burden framing is too strict. Plaintiff must prove Yes by a preponderance; plaintiff need not prove that Kalshi drafted every boundary with perfect precision. Once the admitted sources show a Ronaldo mention in connection with the FIFA Draw ceremony, the remaining question is whether the rules clearly remove that event-linked remark from the counting period. They do not. Ambiguity in a mention market's event wording should not be converted into an unstated formal-program limitation after the fact.\\n\\nProvenance and gaps: plaintiff attempted to retrieve the live Kalshi page, official/full video, caption, and transcript. Kalshi returned a Vercel security checkpoint; the local browser tool was unavailable; Python pip/ensurepip was unavailable for yt-dlp; and direct YouTube caption/open paths were throttled or unavailable. That leaves PX-4 weaker than ideal, but not weightless. PX-3 supplies official event context, PX-4 supplies the Ronaldo-at-FIFA-Draw metadata, and PX-2 supplies the rule that event-linked spoken words count absent a clear exclusion.\\n\\nThe council should resolve the proposition Yes: the Ronaldo strike should have resolved Yes because the record more likely than not shows Trump said Ronaldo in public remarks tied to the FIFA World Cup Draw, and the market wording plus governing terms did not clearly exclude those remarks.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the merits record now shows why the challenged No resolution should stand.\\n\\nPlaintiff's best point is that Trump did say the word \\\"Ronaldo.\\\" The defense does not need to fight that. The question is whether he said it during the market's countable time period: \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\\\" On that decisive question, the strongest official sources favor No.\\n\\nThe admitted GovInfo transcript, DX-1, is an official Compilation of Presidential Documents capture. Its title is not merely \\\"World Cup Draw\\\" or \\\"FIFA ceremony.\\\" It is \\\"Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw.\\\" That same transcript contains the Ronaldo passages: Trump says he met Ronaldo at the White House, later says he was \\\"not Ronaldo or Messi,\\\" and the note identifies Ronaldo among the people referenced. So DX-1 is not adverse to the defense because it confirms the word; it is decisive because it places the word in an exchange with reporters prior to the Draw.\\n\\nDX-2 supplies the timing anchor. The official FIFA Final Draw page states that the Draw at the Kennedy Center commenced at 12:00 local time on Friday, December 5, 2025. DX-1 states that the President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the Kennedy Center. A reporter exchange at 11:13, officially titled as prior to a 12:00 draw, is not more likely than not \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\\\" It is before it.\\n\\nThat reading matches the governing PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION terms. PX-2 says the payout criterion is satisfied when the word is said by the entity during the specified time period. It recognizes event-based periods and permits the Exchange to specify what is included for an event. It also treats official presentation differently from adjacent material: pre-recorded content counts if presented as part of the official event presentation, while behind-the-scenes, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings do not count unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. The point is not that this reporter exchange was a rehearsal or sound check. The point is that the terms require a link to the time period itself. Plaintiff has supplied no market-specific language saying pre-event reporter availability, arrivals, or venue interviews count as part of the Draw.\\n\\nPlaintiff's new exhibits do not fill that gap. PX-3, the White House page capture, establishes that the White House had a page titled \\\"President Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing,\\\" but plaintiff's own capture says the embedded/full video was not captured. It does not prove that the Ronaldo words occurred inside the official draw program. PX-4 is weaker still: it is metadata from a nonofficial YouTube channel. It says the clip is about Trump talking Ronaldo at the FIFA Draw, but it is not a transcript, not an official source, and not an audio extraction. When a nonofficial clip description is weighed against GovInfo's official transcript title and FIFA's official start time, the official sources control.\\n\\nNor is this a burden-shifting problem. The proposition asks the council to overturn Kalshi's No because the market supposedly did not clearly exclude remarks immediately before the formal program. But the preponderance burden is on Yes. The record must show that the strike satisfied the payout criterion. The admitted terms do not say that ambiguous pre-event remarks count by default; they say the word must be said during the specified time period. Here, the best evidence identifies the remarks as prior to the Draw and before the official commencement time.\\n\\nProvenance also matters. DX-1 is an official government transcript with a correction note and an audio-incomplete caveat. That caveat affects stray inaudible portions, but it does not weaken the title, the 11:13 timing note, or the Ronaldo passages preserved in the transcript. DX-2 is an official FIFA timing source. Plaintiff's YouTube metadata may explain why the dispute arose, but it cannot outweigh those primary sources on timing and event classification.\\n\\nThe council should resolve the proposition against plaintiff. Trump said Ronaldo, but the record more likely shows he did so in a reporter exchange prior to the FIFA World Cup Draw, not during the countable Draw event. Kalshi's No resolution should be upheld.\\n\\nRebuttals:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, defendant’s new evidence narrows the case but does not end it.\\n\\nPlaintiff accepts the important parts of DX-1 and DX-2. The GovInfo transcript is official; it labels the item an exchange with reporters \\\"Prior to\\\" the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw; it places the exchange at 11:13 a.m. at the Kennedy Center; and the FIFA capture states the draw commenced at 12:00 local time. Plaintiff should not pretend those facts are weak.\\n\\nBut defendant asks those facts to do more than they do. The market was not drafted as \\\"what will Trump say after the official 12:00 commencement,\\\" \\\"during the televised draw program,\\\" or \\\"during the ball-drawing segment.\\\" PX-1 says the public market title was \\\"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\\" That is ordinary event language, and PX-2 recognizes event-based time periods while leaving room for the Exchange to specify what is included. The record still contains no market-specific exclusion for official venue press remarks immediately before the formal program.\\n\\nDX-1 also helps plaintiff on the facts defendant originally said were missing. It confirms the relevant spoken word. Trump said he met Ronaldo, that Ronaldo is great, and that he was not Ronaldo or Messi. It also places those remarks at the Kennedy Center in a FIFA World Cup Draw-centered exchange with reporters, not in an unrelated private dinner or stale campaign setting. The transcript’s own subject metadata includes the FIFA World Cup, the Kennedy Center, news media, presidential interviews, and soccer. That is event-linked public context.\\n\\nThe terms’ exclusions do not fit defendant’s leap. PX-2 excludes captions alone, rehearsals, sound checks, behind-the-scenes content, and unofficial recordings unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. DX-1 is not a rehearsal transcript. It is not a sound check. It is not merely a caption. It is an official presidential transcript of a public reporter exchange at the venue, released in the Compilation of Presidential Documents. If Kalshi meant to exclude that category because it occurred before a formal noon commencement, the market needed to say so clearly.\\n\\nSo the dispositive question remains one of market construction: does \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw\\\" clearly exclude public, official, event-site remarks immediately before the formal program? Defendant has proved \\\"prior to\\\" the formal draw start. Defendant has not proved a clear market rule that treats the broader Draw event as beginning only at 12:00 for mention purposes.\\n\\nUnder a preponderance standard, the record now confirms the Ronaldo utterance and confirms the FIFA Draw setting. The challenged No resolution should not be upheld by importing a narrow formal-program limitation that the market title and generic terms did not state.\\n\\nSurrebuttals:\\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff's rebuttal usefully clarifies the remaining dispute: plaintiff accepts that DX-1 is official, that it labels the relevant item an exchange with reporters \\\"Prior to\\\" the FIFA World Cup Draw, that the exchange occurred at 11:13 a.m. at the Kennedy Center, and that DX-2 places the official Draw commencement at 12:00 local time. Those concessions should decide the case.\\n\\nPlaintiff's answer is that the market did not say \\\"after 12:00,\\\" \\\"during the televised program,\\\" or \\\"during the ball-drawing segment.\\\" But the market also did not say \\\"at the venue before the Draw,\\\" \\\"in pre-event reporter exchanges,\\\" or \\\"in any public remarks connected to the Draw.\\\" The phrase it chose was \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\\\" Ordinary event language has a start, and the official FIFA source fixes that start at noon. Official GovInfo then fixes this exchange at 11:13 and titles it as prior to the Draw.\\n\\nThat is not a technicality. The terms require the word to be said during the specified time period. They recognize event-based periods and allow event-specific inclusions, but no admitted market-specific rule includes pre-event press access. Plaintiff's construction would turn any event-adjacent public remark into part of the event unless expressly excluded. That reverses the payout criterion. The claimant must show the word occurred during the time period; it is not enough to show the same venue, the same general topic, and official publication.\\n\\nPlaintiff says the exclusions do not fit because DX-1 is not a rehearsal, sound check, caption, or private backstage recording. Fair enough; the defense is not relying on those categories as labels. The defense relies on the affirmative timing requirement. A remark need not be a rehearsal to be outside the event. A reporter exchange officially described as prior to a noon event and occurring at 11:13 is outside because it is before the event began.\\n\\nThe record therefore proves the wrong fact for plaintiff. It proves Trump said Ronaldo, but in a pre-event reporter exchange. The proposition requires Yes only if those words count during the FIFA World Cup Draw. On this record, they do not. Kalshi's No resolution should be upheld.\\n\\nClosings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the final record leaves one legal question.\\n\\nThe easy factual question is resolved in plaintiff’s favor: Trump said \\\"Ronaldo.\\\" The official GovInfo transcript confirms it twice in substance: he said he met Ronaldo, praised him, and later said he was not Ronaldo or Messi. That is a spoken standalone use of the strike word. The record also places the remarks at the Kennedy Center in a FIFA World Cup Draw-centered reporter exchange. This was not an unrelated dinner, a caption, an AI voice, or a social-media paraphrase.\\n\\nThe hard point is timing. Defendant has the strongest evidence on the formal program boundary: GovInfo titled the exchange as \\\"Prior to\\\" the Draw, notes 11:13 a.m., and FIFA states the Final Draw commenced at 12:00 local time. Plaintiff does not ask the council to ignore that. The question is what the Kalshi market actually required.\\n\\nPX-1 did not say \\\"after 12:00.\\\" It did not say \\\"during the televised draw program\\\" or \\\"during the ball-drawing segment.\\\" It asked, in public market wording, \\\"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\\" PX-2’s generic terms recognize event-based periods and say the Exchange may specify what is included when a time period refers to an event. They also give specific exclusions: captions alone, rehearsals, sound checks, behind-the-scenes content, and unofficial recordings unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. None of those exclusions is this case. The GovInfo transcript is an official public presidential record of an event-site reporter exchange, not a rehearsal or sound check.\\n\\nDefendant’s best argument is that ordinary events have start times. True. But this market dispute is about public remarks at the venue immediately before the formal program, in the official context of the Draw, where the market and rules did not clearly define a noon-only boundary. If Kalshi wanted that narrower rule, it could have said so in the strike, the market title, or the event inclusion language. It did not.\\n\\nThe preponderance record therefore shows: Ronaldo was spoken; the remarks were public and officially documented; they were at the Kennedy Center in the FIFA World Cup Draw setting; and the governing market language did not clearly exclude that immediately-before-program event context. The challenged No resolution depends on importing a formal commencement limitation that is absent from the market packet.\\n\\nFor that reason, the Ronaldo strike should resolve Yes.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the closing record is narrow and concrete.\\n\\nEveryone now agrees on the easy fact: Trump said \\\"Ronaldo.\\\" The official GovInfo transcript proves that. But the proposition is not simply that Trump said the word somewhere near the FIFA World Cup Draw. The proposition asks you to overturn Kalshi's No because remarks immediately before the formal program should count under a market asking what Trump would say \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\\\" Plaintiff has not carried that burden.\\n\\nThe two strongest sources are official and aligned. GovInfo, in DX-1, titles the relevant document \\\"Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw.\\\" It notes that the President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the Kennedy Center. FIFA, in DX-2, states that the Final Draw commenced at 12:00 local time. Those facts are not peripheral. They answer the timing question: the Ronaldo words were in a reporter exchange before the Draw began.\\n\\nPlaintiff's closing says the market did not specify \\\"after 12:00,\\\" \\\"during the televised draw program,\\\" or \\\"during the ball-drawing segment.\\\" True, but that does not prove Yes. The market did specify \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\\\" The ordinary function of \\\"during\\\" is to define the event period, not to include anything public, official, and thematically related that happens beforehand. A 47-minute-before reporter exchange officially titled as prior to the Draw is outside that period unless the market or governing terms affirmatively include it. The record contains no such inclusion.\\n\\nThe governing terms reinforce that conclusion. They require the word to be said by the entity during the specified time period. They recognize event-based periods and allow the Exchange to specify event inclusions. They include official-presentation concepts for material presented as part of an event. But they do not say that pre-event press availability counts by default. Plaintiff's argument turns the absence of an exclusion into proof of inclusion. That is backwards under a preponderance standard.\\n\\nPlaintiff also leans on setting: Kennedy Center, FIFA World Cup subject matter, official transcript, public reporters. Those facts show why the issue is understandable. They do not move 11:13 into a 12:00 event. A source can be official and still describe something outside the event. Indeed, that is exactly what DX-1 does: it officially documents the remarks and officially labels them prior to the Draw.\\n\\nThe weaker evidence points the same way once weighed properly. The White House page capture does not include the video or transcript. The YouTube metadata is nonofficial and not an audio transcript. Neither overcomes GovInfo's title and timing note plus FIFA's commencement time.\\n\\nSo the final answer is simple: the word was spoken, but not during the countable event period shown by the best evidence. Plaintiff has not shown that Kalshi's No resolution was wrong. The council should reject the proposition and uphold No.\\n\\nExhibits:\\n[plaintiff] PX-1 Market page packet: Ronaldo strike and challenged No resolution\\nMarket URL: https://kalshi.com/markets/kxtrumpmentionb/trump-mention-b/kxtrumpmentionb-25dec06\\n\\nPublic market title: What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\n\\nContract family: PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION\\n\\nStrike at issue: Ronaldo\\n\\nChallenged resolution: No\\n\\nRequested resolution: Yes\\n\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-2 Governing PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION terms\\n                                         NEWMENTION\\n\\nScope: These rules shall apply to this contract.\\n\\nUnderlying: The Underlying for this Contract is words used by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nRevisions to the Underlying made after Expiration will not be accounted for in determining the\\nExpiration Value.\\n\\nSource Agency: The Source Agencies are \\u003csource\\u003e.\\n\\nType: The type of Contract is an Event Contract.\\n\\nIssuance: After the initial Contract, Contract iterations will be listed on an as-needed basis at\\nthe discretion of the Exchange and corresponding to the risk management needs of Members.\\n\\n\\u003centity\\u003e: \\u003centity\\u003e refers to the speaker, writer, performer, or communicator specified by the\\nExchange. This may include (but is not limited to): a specific named individual, multiple\\nindividuals specified using AND/OR logic, an individual identified by position or title, a group,\\nband, team or collective entity, a specified member or members of a group, an organization,\\ncompany, or institutional entity, or any combination of the aforementioned.\\n\\nWhen \\u003centity\\u003e is defined by a position or title, the Contract tracks whoever holds that position\\nduring \\u003ctime period\\u003e, even if the individual holding the position changes. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a\\nspecific named individual, the identity remains consistent throughout. Name changes (e.g.,\\nstage names, married names) do not create a new entity. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a group or\\norganization and the Contract does not specify particular members, any official\\ncommunication or statement by any member or designated spokesperson counts. When using\\nAND logic, all specified entities must independently say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e. When\\nusing OR logic, at least one of the specified entities must say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nThe Exchange may specify additional conditions such as “at least X members of” a group or\\n“the majority of” a group.\\n\\n\\u003csource\\u003e: \\u003csource\\u003e refers to a Source Agency or ordered collection of Source Agencies\\nspecified by the Exchange at the time of Contract listing, which will be incorporated into the\\nSource Agency hierarchy above and used to determine the occurrence of the Underlying.\\n\\u003csource\\u003e may refer to a singular agency, multiple agencies, an agency by distinguishing\\ncharacteristics, by category or type (e.g., “official government statistical body,” “primary wire\\nservice”), or any combination thereof. When multiple agencies are specified, they may be\\napplied in the hierarchical order designated by the Exchange if so specified, with the highest-\\nranked available and responsive agency taking precedence for purposes of determining the\\nExpiration Value. A lower-ranked agency shall only be consulted if all higher-ranked agencies\\nare unavailable, unresponsive, have not reported on the Underlying by the Expiration time, or\\nif the Exchange, in its sole discretion, determines that a higher-ranked agency’s reporting is\\nincomplete, erroneous, or otherwise insufficient to determine the Expiration Value. If \\u003csource\\u003e\\ndesignates multiple agencies without specifying a hierarchical order, the Exchange shall\\nresolve any conflict between reporting agencies at its sole discretion.\\n\\n\\u003cword\\u003e: \\u003cword\\u003e refers to the particular word or phrase potentially to be mentioned by\\n\\u003centity\\u003e. It may refer to a word being said a minimum number of times. It may also refer to\\none of multiple words/phrases, any of which are acceptable (e.g., “Doge/Dogecoin”).\\n\\f\\u003ctime period\\u003e: \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific range of time, event or discrete date and\\ntime specified by the Exchange. This may be defined by, but is not limited to: a specific event\\nor context (e.g., “during the State of the Union address”), exact dates or times, relative time\\nmarkers (e.g., “before July 1, 2027,” “in Q1 2026”), event-based periods (e.g., “during any\\ncampaign rally in October 2026,” “during the awards ceremony”), and broader intervals (e.g.,\\n“Q1–Q2 2027,” “January–March 2026”).\\n\\nUnless stated otherwise, “Between” is inclusive of both endpoints, while “before” and “after”\\nexclude the specified date. \\u003ctime period\\u003e may also refer to “Any” or “None”, to multiple dates\\n(even if non-consecutive), or to a singular and discrete date or time.\\n\\nWhen \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event (such as an address, speech, performance, or\\nbroadcast), the Exchange may specify what is included, including whether it includes both live\\nand pre-recorded segments (including whether advertisements are included). Where a\\ntimezone is not specified, ET is assumed.\\n\\n\\nPayout Criterion: The Payout Criterion for the Contract encompasses the Expiration Values that\\n\\u003cword\\u003e is said by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n\\n\\nThe word must appear as a distinct, standalone unit, not buried inside another word. Plural\\nand possessive noun forms count. Other grammatical changes (tense, conjugation, derivation)\\ndo not. If \\u003cword\\u003e appears separated from other words by a space or hyphen or in a\\ncompound form with a space or hyphen, it counts. If \\u003cword\\u003e is fused into a single\\nunhyphenated word, it does not count.\\n\\nIf \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled, and the market contains a\\nstrike stating “Event does not qualify/occur”, such a strike shall resolve “Yes” and all others\\n“No”. If \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled but such strikes are NOT\\nlisted, the Contracts will resolve to the last fair price determined at the discretion of the\\nExchange. If the event is postponed, and such a postponement is announced by the end of the\\nfollowing calendar day to be rescheduled to a time within 14 calendar days, the markets shall\\nremain open. If the event captured in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast, the\\nExchange may keep the market open for 24 hours for the release of an official recording.\\nFurther granular details on conditions for these Contracts is available below.\\n\\nAdditional clarification(s):\\n\\n     Possessive noun forms of \\u003cword\\u003e, plurals, and possessive plural noun forms are\\n     INCLUDED:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigrants” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Egg” → “eggs’ shells” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Russia” → “Russia’s” counts, “Russian” does not\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e exists only in adjective form, no plural form exists:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Economic” → “Economics” does not count (“Economic” is an adjective\\n          for which “Economics” is not a plural)\\n     Plural nouns occurring within proper nouns and noun phrases are included:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Cat” → “Cats the musical” counts\\n\\f    Grammatical variations beyond plurals/possessives are NOT included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigration” does NOT count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Run” → “Running” or “Ran” do NOT count\\n    When \\u003cword\\u003e specifies a plural form, the singular does NOT count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Veterans” → “Veteran” does NOT count\\n    Words that are spelled the same as the plural form of \\u003cword\\u003e (if such exists) but are\\n    themselves not a plural noun are included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Wind” → “Winds up the clock” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Border” → “The United States has strong borders” counts\\n    Open compounds (words separated by spaces) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fire station” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “couch” → “couch potato” counts\\n    Hyphenated compounds (words connected by hyphens) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Palestine” → “pro-Palestine” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fat” → “non-fat” counts\\n    Closed compounds (single word, no spaces/hyphens) do not count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire” does not count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firefighter” does not count\\n    Multi-word \\u003cword\\u003e in larger constructions: When \\u003cword\\u003e is a multi-word phrase\\n    appearing within a hyphenated construction, it counts only if \\u003cword\\u003e appears as a\\n    complete, unmodified element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “New York” → “New York-based” counts (complete element)\\n    Portmanteaus (words blended from two words where parts of each are combined) are\\n    NOT included unless the portmanteau clearly contains \\u003cword\\u003e as a distinct, unaltered\\n    element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “MAGA” → “MAGA-nificent” counts (MAGA appears as distinct element)\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “magnificent” → “MAGA-nificent” does NOT count (portmanteau blend)\\n\\nDictionary determination: Both the Merriam-Webster Dictionary (available online) AND the\\nOxford English Dictionary shall be used to determine compound type and/or conventional\\nspelling patterns. Inclusion in either dictionary as an open or hyphenated compound shall\\nsatisfy the Payout Criterion. If neither provides clarity (or the word is not included),\\ndetermination is based on whether written as single unit (closed/doesn’t count) vs. spaces or\\nhyphens (open or hyphenated/counts) and/or context and previous usage.\\n\\nPHONETIC EQUIVALENCIES\\n\\n    Homophones (same sound, different spelling) do not count:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “write” → “right” does not count\\n    Homonyms and homographs (same spelling) COUNT regardless of meaning or\\n    pronunciation:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “bass” → both “bass guitar” and “bass fishing” count\\n    Proper and common nouns are treated identically:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Apple” → both “Apple Inc.” and “apple” (fruit) count\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Will” → both “Will Smith” and “I will go” count\\n    Minor unintentional mispronunciations COUNT if context makes intent clear:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Mamdani” → “Mandani” counts\\n    Severe mispronunciations that make \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable do NOT count.\\n    Trademarked spellings do not count, even when pronounced identically, unless the word\\n\\fitself is the same:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “lift” → “Lyft” (pronounced “lift”) does not count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “uber” → “Uber” counts\\nWords with non-standard transliteration to English count within reason, provided they are\\nphonetically equivalent:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Zelensky” → any of “Zelenski,” “Zelenskii,” “Zelensky,” or “Zelenskiy”\\n      count if pronounced equivalently\\nContractions do not count for their constituent words unless otherwise explicitly specified\\nby the Exchange:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “not” → “won’t,” “can’t,” “don’t,” “isn’t” do not count\\nNumbers spoken as words COUNT, when spoken exactly (not part of a larger number):\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “five” → saying “five” or reading “$5” aloud as “five dollars” counts,\\n      saying “five hundred” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “410” → “four hundred ten”, “four one zero” or “four ten” counts\\nOrdinals COUNT when \\u003cword\\u003e is written numerically OR a phrase that includes a\\nnumber:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “January 6” → “January 6th” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “3” (written numerically) → “3rd” (spoken as “third”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Eight War” → “8 Wars” and “Eighth War” will count\\nCardinal and ordinal number words are distinct:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “one” → “first” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “first” → “one” does NOT count\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count when pronunciation or letter-by-letter spelling\\nmatches \\u003cword\\u003e:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “NASA” (pronounced “NAH-suh”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “N-A-S-A” (spelled out) counts\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count as \\u003cword\\u003e when pronounced as the full word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Doctor” → “Dr.” (pronounced “Doctor”) counts\\nExpanded forms of acronyms do NOT count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “AI” → “artificial intelligence” does not count\\nWords in foreign languages do NOT count unless they are perfect cognates with an\\nEnglish word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fuego” (Spanish) does NOT count\\nEnglish words within foreign sentences count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “policy” → “Nuestra policy es clara” counts\\n\\u003cword\\u003e in organization/company names counts:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Securities” → “Bank of America Securities” counts\\nWords in URLs, emails, handles, and hashtags (exclusive of domain structure, email\\nprovider or symbols) are treated as compounds when spoken as complete words, with the\\ntype of compound subject to aforementioned rules:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firestation.com” pronounced “fire station dot com” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire.com” pronounced “wildfire dot com” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “apple” → “apple.com” pronounced “apple dot com” does count\\n      When presented in URL, email, handle, or hashtag form, \\u003cword\\u003e shall be treated as\\n      a compound, not a multi-word word\\nSung, rapped, or poetic words COUNT if phonetically recognizable:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “money” → “moneyyy” (extended in rap) counts\\n      Extreme distortion making \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable does NOT count.\\nPhonetic alphabet spelling (“Foxtrot India Romeo Echo” for “FIRE”) does NOT count.\\n\\fCANCELLATIONS AND DELAYS\\n\\n   The Exchange may list an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike for any Contract. If listed,\\n   such a strike refers to the structural conditions of the market, and is NOT adjudicated as a\\n   \\u003cword\\u003e needing to be said by or validated by having been said by \\u003centity\\u003e. If listed, this\\n   strike resolves to “Yes” whenever the event fails to occur or qualify under the Payout\\n   Criterion, or any other circumstance prevents normal resolution.\\n   If no such strike is listed, and \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, the following rules\\n   apply if the event is cancelled, postponed, rescheduled, or materially altered (including\\n   being closed to press) such that no video is released within one calendar day of the\\n   original start time of the event:\\n         If the event is cancelled, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price determined in\\n         the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         If the event is postponed or rescheduled, the outcome depends on whether a new\\n         date is publicly announced within one calendar day (i.e. if the event was scheduled\\n         to begin on Monday, any time up to 11:59PM on Tuesday falls within this period) of\\n         the originally scheduled start time:\\n               If no new date is announced within one calendar day, the Contract will resolve\\n               to the last fair price determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n               If a new date is announced within one calendar day, the outcome depends on\\n               when the rescheduled event is set to occur:\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls within fourteen (14) calendar days of the\\n                     originally scheduled date, the Contract shall remain open and \\u003cword\\u003e\\n                     stated during the rescheduled event will count.\\n                           The fourteen-day window begins at 12:00 AM ET on the originally\\n                           scheduled date and ends at 11:59 PM ET fourteen days later, unless\\n                           an alternate timezone is explicitly specified.\\n                           Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the State of the Union on January\\n                           15, 2026” rescheduled to January 20, 2026 → words spoken during\\n                           the rescheduled address count.\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls more than fourteen (14) calendar days after\\n                     the originally scheduled date, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price\\n                     determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         Any Contract that cannot be resolved through the Source Agency hierarchy will\\n         instead be settled at the Last Fair Price. The Exchange will disclose the methodology\\n         used to determine the Last Fair Price (e.g., Last Traded Price, Time-Weighted\\n         Average Price) at the time of Issuance.\\n         If an event begins but is interrupted, abbreviated, or ends prematurely, words\\n         stated by \\u003centity\\u003e during the portion of the event that did occur will count and the\\n         market will otherwise resolve.\\n   If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window but the venue, format, or medium\\n   changes (e.g., moved to a different location, changed from in-person to virtual (with the\\n   exception of being closed to press)), words stated during the event will count.\\n   Special condition: Across both cases, whether an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike is\\n   listed or not, if the event specified as or in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast (or\\n   relayed as such) but the live stream/broadcast does not occur, the Exchange will instead\\n   use an officially released recording as the Underlying, and may delay resolution by up to\\n   one calendar day to allow for the release of such a recording.\\n\\f          If partial snippets are released, Contracts on words that do not appear will be\\n          resolved to last fair price, and Contracts on those that do will be resolved to “Yes”.\\n          If no recording is released, the relevant outcomes triggered by the\\n          presence/absence of an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike shall occur as outlined\\n          above.\\n\\nTECHNICAL DETAILS (UNLESS OTHERWISE SPECIFIED)\\n\\n     When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, pre-recorded content broadcast,\\n     streamed, or published as part of that event is included if presented as part of the official\\n     presentation.\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the concert” with pre-recorded video interlude\\n          where entity speaks → words from interlude count\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the television appearance” with pre-taped\\n          segment aired during broadcast → words from segment count\\n     Behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are NOT\\n     included unless officially broadcast or published as part of \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n     Subtitles and captions that display \\u003cword\\u003e on screen but are not spoken aloud by\\n     \\u003centity\\u003e do NOT count.\\n     Sign language interpretation or usage by entity does NOT count as saying \\u003cword\\u003e unless\\n     the Contract explicitly specifies that sign language counts.\\n     Text that entity displays on screen (presentation slides, teleprompter visible to audience,\\n     signatures) does NOT count unless entity reads it aloud.\\n     Content generated by AI, deepfakes, or synthetic voice technology impersonating entity\\n     does NOT count unless the synthetic content is officially commissioned, authorized, or\\n     published by entity, OR the Contract explicitly specifies that AI-generated content counts.\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e is muted due to technical failure or censorship it shall not count unless\\n     corroborating contextual evidence (including surrounding speech, or an official\\n     uncensored recording or transcript) confirms that \\u003centity\\u003e specifically uttered \\u003cword\\u003e\\n     during the muted period.\\n\\nMinimum Tick: The Minimum Tick size for the Contract shall be $0.01.\\n\\nPosition Accountability Level: The Position Accountability Level for the Contract shall be\\n$25,000 per strike, per Member.\\n\\nLast Trading Date: The Last Trading Date of the Contract will be the Expiration Date. The Last\\nTrading Time will be the Expiration time.\\n\\nSettlement Date: The Settlement Date of the Contract shall be no later than the day after the\\nExpiration Date, unless the Market Outcome is under review pursuant to Rule 7.1.\\n\\nExpiration Date: When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event: The latest Expiration Date of\\nthe Contract shall be fourteen (14) calendar days after the originally scheduled date of the\\nevent. If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window, expiration will be moved to an\\nearlier date and time in accordance with Rule 7.2. When \\u003ctime period\\u003e is defined by specific\\ndates: The latest Expiration Date of the Contract shall be two weeks after the end of \\u003ctime\\nperiod\\u003e. If an event described in the Payout Criterion occurs and a consensus has been\\nreached on all terms, then expiration will be moved to an earlier date and time in accordance\\nwith Rule 7.2.\\n\\fExpiration time: The Expiration time of the Contract shall be 10:00 AM ET.\\n\\nSettlement Value: The Settlement Value for this Contract is $1.00.\\n\\nExpiration Value: The Expiration Value is the value of the Underlying as documented by the\\nSource Agency on the Expiration Date at the Expiration time.\\n\\nContingencies: Before Settlement, Kalshi may, at its sole discretion, initiate the Market\\nOutcome Review Process pursuant to Rule 7.1 of the Rulebook. If an Expiration Value cannot\\nbe determined on the Expiration Date, Kalshi has the right to determine payouts pursuant to\\nRule 7.1 in the Rulebook.\\n\\f\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-3 Official White House World Cup Drawing video page capture\\nSource capture from official White House page https://www.whitehouse.gov/videos/president-trump-attends-the-fifa-world-cup-drawing/\\nRetrieval: 2026-06-29T21:52:12Z via OpenClaw web_fetch and web.open.\\n\\nVisible page facts captured:\\n- Page title: President Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing\\n- Date shown on page: December 5, 2025\\n- Page section: Videos\\n- The page contains a link labeled View Full Video to Instagram.\\n- Related video listed: FIFA World Cup 2026 Draw at The Kennedy Center, duration 00:45, dated December 6, 2025.\\n- Related video listed: FIFA World Cup Drawing Announced to Take Place at The Kennedy Center, duration 00:56, dated August 23, 2025.\\n- Related video listed: President Trump on the 2026 FIFA World Cup, duration 01:22, dated May 6, 2025.\\n\\nRelevant extracted lines from web.open capture:\\nL142: Videos\\nL143: # President Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing\\nL145: December 5, 2025\\nL133: ... View Full Video [instagram.com] ...\\nL151: FIFA World Cup 2026 Draw at The Kennedy Center\\nL153: December 6, 2025\\nL167-L170: President Trump on the 2026 FIFA World Cup, May 6, 2025\\n\\nNotes on capture limits: readability extraction returned minimal content, so the above preserves visible lines from the page capture. The embedded/full video itself was not captured in this item.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-4 YouTube metadata capture for Ronaldo-at-FIFA-Draw clip\\nSource capture: YouTube watch page https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Cb2yO0lLEnM\\nVideo ID: Cb2yO0lLEnM\\nRetrieval: 2026-06-29T21:53:00Z via web search and curl of the YouTube watch page.\\n\\nCaptured title / page metadata:\\n- Title shown in search and page metadata: Trump Talks Cristiano Ronaldo at FIFA Draw — ‘He’s a Great Person’\\n- Channel shown in page metadata: interestingText You / @InterestingTextYou\\n- Subscriber count shown in page metadata at capture: about 10.3K subscribers\\n\\nCaptured description text from YouTube page metadata:\\n\\\"Trump Talks Cristiano Ronaldo at FIFA Draw — ‘He’s a Great Person’\\n\\nAt the FIFA World Cup Draw Ceremony, Donald Trump shared a story about meeting Cristiano Ronaldo at the White House. Trump said Ronaldo was “a great person” and even mentioned that Ronaldo spoke with his son about soccer during the visit.\\n\\nThis unexpected crossover between world politics and one of the biggest global sports stars quickly caught viewers' attention.\\n\\nTrump FIFA Draw\\nDonald Trump FIFA World Cup\\nTrump Cristiano Ronaldo\\nCristiano Ronaldo Trump meeting\\nFIFA World Cup draw 2026\\nRonaldo White House visit\\nTrump soccer comments\\nWorld Cup trending 2025\\nsports politics crossover\\nCristiano Ronaldo story\\nDonald Trump viral moment\\nFIFA draw ceremony Trump\\nWorld Cup 2026 news\\nRonaldo fan reaction\\npolitical celebrity moments\\nviral sports clips 2025\\nFIFA draw highlights\\nTrump speech FIFA\\nglobal sports news\\\"\\n\\nCapture limits and provenance caveat: direct video/caption extraction was attempted but YouTube transcript/open paths were throttled or unavailable in this environment. This item preserves the public watch-page metadata and description, not an independently extracted audio transcript. It is not an official White House or FIFA source.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-1 GovInfo official transcript: remarks prior to FIFA World Cup Draw\\nSource: GovInfo, Compilation of Presidential Documents, DCPD202501162\\nURL retrieved: https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/DCPD-202501162/html/DCPD-202501162.htm\\nRetrieval time: 2026-06-29T22:00:00Z\\nLocal captured HTML size/hash: 51,571 bytes; SHA-256 eadbceeecf3e94f5bd423bcb8e8511165fdc7265dd8c1e025870c2e8f34dfd99\\n\\nMaterial captured text from official GovInfo HTML/web.open:\\n\\nAdministration of Donald J. Trump, 2025\\n\\nTitle: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\nDate: December 5, 2025\\n\\nOpening note: [The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\\n\\nExcerpt - The President's Interest in Soccer (web.open lines 196-203):\\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\\\"football,\\\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\\n\\nExcerpt - The President's Interest in Soccer (web.open lines 322-329):\\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\\nThe President. But they have a little more speed. But no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\\n\\nTiming/context note (web.open lines 461-462):\\nNOTE: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. In his remarks, he referred to Trey Yingst, chief foreign correspondent, Fox News Channel; Cristiano Ronaldo, forward for Saudi Pro League club Al-Nass and Portugal's national soccer team; and Lionel Messi, forward for Major League Soccer club Inter Miami and Argentina's national team. A reporter referred to New York State Attorney General Letitia James.\\nThe transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\n\\nDocument category/location/name/subject metadata (web.open lines 463-468):\\nCategories: Interviews With the News Media: Exchanges with reporters, Washington, DC.\\nLocations: Washington, DC.\\nNames include: Cristiano Ronaldo and Lionel Messi.\\nSubjects include: Federation Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) World Cup; John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts; News media, Presidential interviews; Soccer.\\nDCPD Number: DCPD202501162.\\n\\nCapture limits: This item is a focused text capture of the material official transcript title, Ronaldo excerpts, timing/correction note, and metadata. It is not a full video or audio artifact. The official transcript itself notes some portions could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-2 FIFA official Final Draw start-time capture\\nSource: FIFA official page, FIFA World Cup 2026 Final Draw\\nURL: https://www.fifa.com/en/tournaments/mens/worldcup/canadamexicousa2026/live-draw\\nRetrieval time: 2026-06-29T22:01:00Z\\n\\nMaterial captured text from web search/open result:\\n- Page title/source: FIFA World Cup 2026™ Final Draw\\n- The draw takes place at the Kennedy Center in Washington DC, USA.\\n- The draw commences at 12:00 local time (17:00 UTC) on Friday 5 December 2025.\\n\\nCapture limits: This is a focused text capture of the official FIFA page timing statement located by web search. It is not a video capture of the draw ceremony.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-3 Governing PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION terms\\n                                         NEWMENTION\\n\\nScope: These rules shall apply to this contract.\\n\\nUnderlying: The Underlying for this Contract is words used by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nRevisions to the Underlying made after Expiration will not be accounted for in determining the\\nExpiration Value.\\n\\nSource Agency: The Source Agencies are \\u003csource\\u003e.\\n\\nType: The type of Contract is an Event Contract.\\n\\nIssuance: After the initial Contract, Contract iterations will be listed on an as-needed basis at\\nthe discretion of the Exchange and corresponding to the risk management needs of Members.\\n\\n\\u003centity\\u003e: \\u003centity\\u003e refers to the speaker, writer, performer, or communicator specified by the\\nExchange. This may include (but is not limited to): a specific named individual, multiple\\nindividuals specified using AND/OR logic, an individual identified by position or title, a group,\\nband, team or collective entity, a specified member or members of a group, an organization,\\ncompany, or institutional entity, or any combination of the aforementioned.\\n\\nWhen \\u003centity\\u003e is defined by a position or title, the Contract tracks whoever holds that position\\nduring \\u003ctime period\\u003e, even if the individual holding the position changes. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a\\nspecific named individual, the identity remains consistent throughout. Name changes (e.g.,\\nstage names, married names) do not create a new entity. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a group or\\norganization and the Contract does not specify particular members, any official\\ncommunication or statement by any member or designated spokesperson counts. When using\\nAND logic, all specified entities must independently say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e. When\\nusing OR logic, at least one of the specified entities must say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nThe Exchange may specify additional conditions such as “at least X members of” a group or\\n“the majority of” a group.\\n\\n\\u003csource\\u003e: \\u003csource\\u003e refers to a Source Agency or ordered collection of Source Agencies\\nspecified by the Exchange at the time of Contract listing, which will be incorporated into the\\nSource Agency hierarchy above and used to determine the occurrence of the Underlying.\\n\\u003csource\\u003e may refer to a singular agency, multiple agencies, an agency by distinguishing\\ncharacteristics, by category or type (e.g., “official government statistical body,” “primary wire\\nservice”), or any combination thereof. When multiple agencies are specified, they may be\\napplied in the hierarchical order designated by the Exchange if so specified, with the highest-\\nranked available and responsive agency taking precedence for purposes of determining the\\nExpiration Value. A lower-ranked agency shall only be consulted if all higher-ranked agencies\\nare unavailable, unresponsive, have not reported on the Underlying by the Expiration time, or\\nif the Exchange, in its sole discretion, determines that a higher-ranked agency’s reporting is\\nincomplete, erroneous, or otherwise insufficient to determine the Expiration Value. If \\u003csource\\u003e\\ndesignates multiple agencies without specifying a hierarchical order, the Exchange shall\\nresolve any conflict between reporting agencies at its sole discretion.\\n\\n\\u003cword\\u003e: \\u003cword\\u003e refers to the particular word or phrase potentially to be mentioned by\\n\\u003centity\\u003e. It may refer to a word being said a minimum number of times. It may also refer to\\none of multiple words/phrases, any of which are acceptable (e.g., “Doge/Dogecoin”).\\n\\f\\u003ctime period\\u003e: \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific range of time, event or discrete date and\\ntime specified by the Exchange. This may be defined by, but is not limited to: a specific event\\nor context (e.g., “during the State of the Union address”), exact dates or times, relative time\\nmarkers (e.g., “before July 1, 2027,” “in Q1 2026”), event-based periods (e.g., “during any\\ncampaign rally in October 2026,” “during the awards ceremony”), and broader intervals (e.g.,\\n“Q1–Q2 2027,” “January–March 2026”).\\n\\nUnless stated otherwise, “Between” is inclusive of both endpoints, while “before” and “after”\\nexclude the specified date. \\u003ctime period\\u003e may also refer to “Any” or “None”, to multiple dates\\n(even if non-consecutive), or to a singular and discrete date or time.\\n\\nWhen \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event (such as an address, speech, performance, or\\nbroadcast), the Exchange may specify what is included, including whether it includes both live\\nand pre-recorded segments (including whether advertisements are included). Where a\\ntimezone is not specified, ET is assumed.\\n\\n\\nPayout Criterion: The Payout Criterion for the Contract encompasses the Expiration Values that\\n\\u003cword\\u003e is said by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n\\n\\nThe word must appear as a distinct, standalone unit, not buried inside another word. Plural\\nand possessive noun forms count. Other grammatical changes (tense, conjugation, derivation)\\ndo not. If \\u003cword\\u003e appears separated from other words by a space or hyphen or in a\\ncompound form with a space or hyphen, it counts. If \\u003cword\\u003e is fused into a single\\nunhyphenated word, it does not count.\\n\\nIf \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled, and the market contains a\\nstrike stating “Event does not qualify/occur”, such a strike shall resolve “Yes” and all others\\n“No”. If \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled but such strikes are NOT\\nlisted, the Contracts will resolve to the last fair price determined at the discretion of the\\nExchange. If the event is postponed, and such a postponement is announced by the end of the\\nfollowing calendar day to be rescheduled to a time within 14 calendar days, the markets shall\\nremain open. If the event captured in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast, the\\nExchange may keep the market open for 24 hours for the release of an official recording.\\nFurther granular details on conditions for these Contracts is available below.\\n\\nAdditional clarification(s):\\n\\n     Possessive noun forms of \\u003cword\\u003e, plurals, and possessive plural noun forms are\\n     INCLUDED:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigrants” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Egg” → “eggs’ shells” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Russia” → “Russia’s” counts, “Russian” does not\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e exists only in adjective form, no plural form exists:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Economic” → “Economics” does not count (“Economic” is an adjective\\n          for which “Economics” is not a plural)\\n     Plural nouns occurring within proper nouns and noun phrases are included:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Cat” → “Cats the musical” counts\\n\\f    Grammatical variations beyond plurals/possessives are NOT included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigration” does NOT count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Run” → “Running” or “Ran” do NOT count\\n    When \\u003cword\\u003e specifies a plural form, the singular does NOT count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Veterans” → “Veteran” does NOT count\\n    Words that are spelled the same as the plural form of \\u003cword\\u003e (if such exists) but are\\n    themselves not a plural noun are included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Wind” → “Winds up the clock” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Border” → “The United States has strong borders” counts\\n    Open compounds (words separated by spaces) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fire station” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “couch” → “couch potato” counts\\n    Hyphenated compounds (words connected by hyphens) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Palestine” → “pro-Palestine” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fat” → “non-fat” counts\\n    Closed compounds (single word, no spaces/hyphens) do not count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire” does not count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firefighter” does not count\\n    Multi-word \\u003cword\\u003e in larger constructions: When \\u003cword\\u003e is a multi-word phrase\\n    appearing within a hyphenated construction, it counts only if \\u003cword\\u003e appears as a\\n    complete, unmodified element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “New York” → “New York-based” counts (complete element)\\n    Portmanteaus (words blended from two words where parts of each are combined) are\\n    NOT included unless the portmanteau clearly contains \\u003cword\\u003e as a distinct, unaltered\\n    element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “MAGA” → “MAGA-nificent” counts (MAGA appears as distinct element)\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “magnificent” → “MAGA-nificent” does NOT count (portmanteau blend)\\n\\nDictionary determination: Both the Merriam-Webster Dictionary (available online) AND the\\nOxford English Dictionary shall be used to determine compound type and/or conventional\\nspelling patterns. Inclusion in either dictionary as an open or hyphenated compound shall\\nsatisfy the Payout Criterion. If neither provides clarity (or the word is not included),\\ndetermination is based on whether written as single unit (closed/doesn’t count) vs. spaces or\\nhyphens (open or hyphenated/counts) and/or context and previous usage.\\n\\nPHONETIC EQUIVALENCIES\\n\\n    Homophones (same sound, different spelling) do not count:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “write” → “right” does not count\\n    Homonyms and homographs (same spelling) COUNT regardless of meaning or\\n    pronunciation:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “bass” → both “bass guitar” and “bass fishing” count\\n    Proper and common nouns are treated identically:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Apple” → both “Apple Inc.” and “apple” (fruit) count\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Will” → both “Will Smith” and “I will go” count\\n    Minor unintentional mispronunciations COUNT if context makes intent clear:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Mamdani” → “Mandani” counts\\n    Severe mispronunciations that make \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable do NOT count.\\n    Trademarked spellings do not count, even when pronounced identically, unless the word\\n\\fitself is the same:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “lift” → “Lyft” (pronounced “lift”) does not count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “uber” → “Uber” counts\\nWords with non-standard transliteration to English count within reason, provided they are\\nphonetically equivalent:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Zelensky” → any of “Zelenski,” “Zelenskii,” “Zelensky,” or “Zelenskiy”\\n      count if pronounced equivalently\\nContractions do not count for their constituent words unless otherwise explicitly specified\\nby the Exchange:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “not” → “won’t,” “can’t,” “don’t,” “isn’t” do not count\\nNumbers spoken as words COUNT, when spoken exactly (not part of a larger number):\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “five” → saying “five” or reading “$5” aloud as “five dollars” counts,\\n      saying “five hundred” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “410” → “four hundred ten”, “four one zero” or “four ten” counts\\nOrdinals COUNT when \\u003cword\\u003e is written numerically OR a phrase that includes a\\nnumber:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “January 6” → “January 6th” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “3” (written numerically) → “3rd” (spoken as “third”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Eight War” → “8 Wars” and “Eighth War” will count\\nCardinal and ordinal number words are distinct:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “one” → “first” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “first” → “one” does NOT count\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count when pronunciation or letter-by-letter spelling\\nmatches \\u003cword\\u003e:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “NASA” (pronounced “NAH-suh”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “N-A-S-A” (spelled out) counts\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count as \\u003cword\\u003e when pronounced as the full word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Doctor” → “Dr.” (pronounced “Doctor”) counts\\nExpanded forms of acronyms do NOT count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “AI” → “artificial intelligence” does not count\\nWords in foreign languages do NOT count unless they are perfect cognates with an\\nEnglish word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fuego” (Spanish) does NOT count\\nEnglish words within foreign sentences count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “policy” → “Nuestra policy es clara” counts\\n\\u003cword\\u003e in organization/company names counts:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Securities” → “Bank of America Securities” counts\\nWords in URLs, emails, handles, and hashtags (exclusive of domain structure, email\\nprovider or symbols) are treated as compounds when spoken as complete words, with the\\ntype of compound subject to aforementioned rules:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firestation.com” pronounced “fire station dot com” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire.com” pronounced “wildfire dot com” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “apple” → “apple.com” pronounced “apple dot com” does count\\n      When presented in URL, email, handle, or hashtag form, \\u003cword\\u003e shall be treated as\\n      a compound, not a multi-word word\\nSung, rapped, or poetic words COUNT if phonetically recognizable:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “money” → “moneyyy” (extended in rap) counts\\n      Extreme distortion making \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable does NOT count.\\nPhonetic alphabet spelling (“Foxtrot India Romeo Echo” for “FIRE”) does NOT count.\\n\\fCANCELLATIONS AND DELAYS\\n\\n   The Exchange may list an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike for any Contract. If listed,\\n   such a strike refers to the structural conditions of the market, and is NOT adjudicated as a\\n   \\u003cword\\u003e needing to be said by or validated by having been said by \\u003centity\\u003e. If listed, this\\n   strike resolves to “Yes” whenever the event fails to occur or qualify under the Payout\\n   Criterion, or any other circumstance prevents normal resolution.\\n   If no such strike is listed, and \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, the following rules\\n   apply if the event is cancelled, postponed, rescheduled, or materially altered (including\\n   being closed to press) such that no video is released within one calendar day of the\\n   original start time of the event:\\n         If the event is cancelled, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price determined in\\n         the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         If the event is postponed or rescheduled, the outcome depends on whether a new\\n         date is publicly announced within one calendar day (i.e. if the event was scheduled\\n         to begin on Monday, any time up to 11:59PM on Tuesday falls within this period) of\\n         the originally scheduled start time:\\n               If no new date is announced within one calendar day, the Contract will resolve\\n               to the last fair price determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n               If a new date is announced within one calendar day, the outcome depends on\\n               when the rescheduled event is set to occur:\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls within fourteen (14) calendar days of the\\n                     originally scheduled date, the Contract shall remain open and \\u003cword\\u003e\\n                     stated during the rescheduled event will count.\\n                           The fourteen-day window begins at 12:00 AM ET on the originally\\n                           scheduled date and ends at 11:59 PM ET fourteen days later, unless\\n                           an alternate timezone is explicitly specified.\\n                           Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the State of the Union on January\\n                           15, 2026” rescheduled to January 20, 2026 → words spoken during\\n                           the rescheduled address count.\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls more than fourteen (14) calendar days after\\n                     the originally scheduled date, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price\\n                     determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         Any Contract that cannot be resolved through the Source Agency hierarchy will\\n         instead be settled at the Last Fair Price. The Exchange will disclose the methodology\\n         used to determine the Last Fair Price (e.g., Last Traded Price, Time-Weighted\\n         Average Price) at the time of Issuance.\\n         If an event begins but is interrupted, abbreviated, or ends prematurely, words\\n         stated by \\u003centity\\u003e during the portion of the event that did occur will count and the\\n         market will otherwise resolve.\\n   If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window but the venue, format, or medium\\n   changes (e.g., moved to a different location, changed from in-person to virtual (with the\\n   exception of being closed to press)), words stated during the event will count.\\n   Special condition: Across both cases, whether an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike is\\n   listed or not, if the event specified as or in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast (or\\n   relayed as such) but the live stream/broadcast does not occur, the Exchange will instead\\n   use an officially released recording as the Underlying, and may delay resolution by up to\\n   one calendar day to allow for the release of such a recording.\\n\\f          If partial snippets are released, Contracts on words that do not appear will be\\n          resolved to last fair price, and Contracts on those that do will be resolved to “Yes”.\\n          If no recording is released, the relevant outcomes triggered by the\\n          presence/absence of an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike shall occur as outlined\\n          above.\\n\\nTECHNICAL DETAILS (UNLESS OTHERWISE SPECIFIED)\\n\\n     When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, pre-recorded content broadcast,\\n     streamed, or published as part of that event is included if presented as part of the official\\n     presentation.\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the concert” with pre-recorded video interlude\\n          where entity speaks → words from interlude count\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the television appearance” with pre-taped\\n          segment aired during broadcast → words from segment count\\n     Behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are NOT\\n     included unless officially broadcast or published as part of \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n     Subtitles and captions that display \\u003cword\\u003e on screen but are not spoken aloud by\\n     \\u003centity\\u003e do NOT count.\\n     Sign language interpretation or usage by entity does NOT count as saying \\u003cword\\u003e unless\\n     the Contract explicitly specifies that sign language counts.\\n     Text that entity displays on screen (presentation slides, teleprompter visible to audience,\\n     signatures) does NOT count unless entity reads it aloud.\\n     Content generated by AI, deepfakes, or synthetic voice technology impersonating entity\\n     does NOT count unless the synthetic content is officially commissioned, authorized, or\\n     published by entity, OR the Contract explicitly specifies that AI-generated content counts.\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e is muted due to technical failure or censorship it shall not count unless\\n     corroborating contextual evidence (including surrounding speech, or an official\\n     uncensored recording or transcript) confirms that \\u003centity\\u003e specifically uttered \\u003cword\\u003e\\n     during the muted period.\\n\\nMinimum Tick: The Minimum Tick size for the Contract shall be $0.01.\\n\\nPosition Accountability Level: The Position Accountability Level for the Contract shall be\\n$25,000 per strike, per Member.\\n\\nLast Trading Date: The Last Trading Date of the Contract will be the Expiration Date. The Last\\nTrading Time will be the Expiration time.\\n\\nSettlement Date: The Settlement Date of the Contract shall be no later than the day after the\\nExpiration Date, unless the Market Outcome is under review pursuant to Rule 7.1.\\n\\nExpiration Date: When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event: The latest Expiration Date of\\nthe Contract shall be fourteen (14) calendar days after the originally scheduled date of the\\nevent. If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window, expiration will be moved to an\\nearlier date and time in accordance with Rule 7.2. When \\u003ctime period\\u003e is defined by specific\\ndates: The latest Expiration Date of the Contract shall be two weeks after the end of \\u003ctime\\nperiod\\u003e. If an event described in the Payout Criterion occurs and a consensus has been\\nreached on all terms, then expiration will be moved to an earlier date and time in accordance\\nwith Rule 7.2.\\n\\fExpiration time: The Expiration time of the Contract shall be 10:00 AM ET.\\n\\nSettlement Value: The Settlement Value for this Contract is $1.00.\\n\\nExpiration Value: The Expiration Value is the value of the Underlying as documented by the\\nSource Agency on the Expiration Date at the Expiration time.\\n\\nContingencies: Before Settlement, Kalshi may, at its sole discretion, initiate the Market\\nOutcome Review Process pursuant to Rule 7.1 of the Rulebook. If an Expiration Value cannot\\nbe determined on the Expiration Date, Kalshi has the right to determine payouts pursuant to\\nRule 7.1 in the Rulebook.\\n\\f\\n\\n[defendant] DX-4 Market packet: Ronaldo strike and challenged No resolution\\nMarket URL: https://kalshi.com/markets/kxtrumpmentionb/trump-mention-b/kxtrumpmentionb-25dec06\\n\\nPublic market title: What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\n\\nContract family: PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION\\n\\nStrike at issue: Ronaldo\\n\\nChallenged resolution: No\\n\\nRequested resolution: Yes\\n\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R1 GovInfo transcript confirming Ronaldo utterances and Kennedy Center/FIFA Draw context\\nSource: GovInfo, Compilation of Presidential Documents, DCPD202501162\\nURL retrieved: https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/DCPD-202501162/html/DCPD-202501162.htm\\nRetrieval time: 2026-06-29T22:00:00Z\\nLocal captured HTML size/hash: 51,571 bytes; SHA-256 eadbceeecf3e94f5bd423bcb8e8511165fdc7265dd8c1e025870c2e8f34dfd99\\n\\nMaterial captured text from official GovInfo HTML/web.open:\\n\\nAdministration of Donald J. Trump, 2025\\n\\nTitle: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\nDate: December 5, 2025\\n\\nOpening note: [The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\\n\\nExcerpt - The President's Interest in Soccer (web.open lines 196-203):\\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\\\"football,\\\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\\n\\nExcerpt - The President's Interest in Soccer (web.open lines 322-329):\\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\\nThe President. But they have a little more speed. But no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\\n\\nTiming/context note (web.open lines 461-462):\\nNOTE: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. In his remarks, he referred to Trey Yingst, chief foreign correspondent, Fox News Channel; Cristiano Ronaldo, forward for Saudi Pro League club Al-Nass and Portugal's national soccer team; and Lionel Messi, forward for Major League Soccer club Inter Miami and Argentina's national team. A reporter referred to New York State Attorney General Letitia James.\\nThe transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\n\\nDocument category/location/name/subject metadata (web.open lines 463-468):\\nCategories: Interviews With the News Media: Exchanges with reporters, Washington, DC.\\nLocations: Washington, DC.\\nNames include: Cristiano Ronaldo and Lionel Messi.\\nSubjects include: Federation Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) World Cup; John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts; News media, Presidential interviews; Soccer.\\nDCPD Number: DCPD202501162.\\n\\nCapture limits: This item is a focused text capture of the material official transcript title, Ronaldo excerpts, timing/correction note, and metadata. It is not a full video or audio artifact. The official transcript itself notes some portions could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R2 FIFA timing capture showing formal commencement time but not market-specific exclusion\\nSource: FIFA official page, FIFA World Cup 2026 Final Draw\\nURL: https://www.fifa.com/en/tournaments/mens/worldcup/canadamexicousa2026/live-draw\\nRetrieval time: 2026-06-29T22:01:00Z\\n\\nMaterial captured text from web search/open result:\\n- Page title/source: FIFA World Cup 2026™ Final Draw\\n- The draw takes place at the Kennedy Center in Washington DC, USA.\\n- The draw commences at 12:00 local time (17:00 UTC) on Friday 5 December 2025.\\n\\nCapture limits: This is a focused text capture of the official FIFA page timing statement located by web search. It is not a video capture of the draw ceremony.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R3 Event-period terms and exclusions\\n                                         NEWMENTION\\n\\nScope: These rules shall apply to this contract.\\n\\nUnderlying: The Underlying for this Contract is words used by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nRevisions to the Underlying made after Expiration will not be accounted for in determining the\\nExpiration Value.\\n\\nSource Agency: The Source Agencies are \\u003csource\\u003e.\\n\\nType: The type of Contract is an Event Contract.\\n\\nIssuance: After the initial Contract, Contract iterations will be listed on an as-needed basis at\\nthe discretion of the Exchange and corresponding to the risk management needs of Members.\\n\\n\\u003centity\\u003e: \\u003centity\\u003e refers to the speaker, writer, performer, or communicator specified by the\\nExchange. This may include (but is not limited to): a specific named individual, multiple\\nindividuals specified using AND/OR logic, an individual identified by position or title, a group,\\nband, team or collective entity, a specified member or members of a group, an organization,\\ncompany, or institutional entity, or any combination of the aforementioned.\\n\\nWhen \\u003centity\\u003e is defined by a position or title, the Contract tracks whoever holds that position\\nduring \\u003ctime period\\u003e, even if the individual holding the position changes. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a\\nspecific named individual, the identity remains consistent throughout. Name changes (e.g.,\\nstage names, married names) do not create a new entity. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a group or\\norganization and the Contract does not specify particular members, any official\\ncommunication or statement by any member or designated spokesperson counts. When using\\nAND logic, all specified entities must independently say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e. When\\nusing OR logic, at least one of the specified entities must say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nThe Exchange may specify additional conditions such as “at least X members of” a group or\\n“the majority of” a group.\\n\\n\\u003csource\\u003e: \\u003csource\\u003e refers to a Source Agency or ordered collection of Source Agencies\\nspecified by the Exchange at the time of Contract listing, which will be incorporated into the\\nSource Agency hierarchy above and used to determine the occurrence of the Underlying.\\n\\u003csource\\u003e may refer to a singular agency, multiple agencies, an agency by distinguishing\\ncharacteristics, by category or type (e.g., “official government statistical body,” “primary wire\\nservice”), or any combination thereof. When multiple agencies are specified, they may be\\napplied in the hierarchical order designated by the Exchange if so specified, with the highest-\\nranked available and responsive agency taking precedence for purposes of determining the\\nExpiration Value. A lower-ranked agency shall only be consulted if all higher-ranked agencies\\nare unavailable, unresponsive, have not reported on the Underlying by the Expiration time, or\\nif the Exchange, in its sole discretion, determines that a higher-ranked agency’s reporting is\\nincomplete, erroneous, or otherwise insufficient to determine the Expiration Value. If \\u003csource\\u003e\\ndesignates multiple agencies without specifying a hierarchical order, the Exchange shall\\nresolve any conflict between reporting agencies at its sole discretion.\\n\\n\\u003cword\\u003e: \\u003cword\\u003e refers to the particular word or phrase potentially to be mentioned by\\n\\u003centity\\u003e. It may refer to a word being said a minimum number of times. It may also refer to\\none of multiple words/phrases, any of which are acceptable (e.g., “Doge/Dogecoin”).\\n\\f\\u003ctime period\\u003e: \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific range of time, event or discrete date and\\ntime specified by the Exchange. This may be defined by, but is not limited to: a specific event\\nor context (e.g., “during the State of the Union address”), exact dates or times, relative time\\nmarkers (e.g., “before July 1, 2027,” “in Q1 2026”), event-based periods (e.g., “during any\\ncampaign rally in October 2026,” “during the awards ceremony”), and broader intervals (e.g.,\\n“Q1–Q2 2027,” “January–March 2026”).\\n\\nUnless stated otherwise, “Between” is inclusive of both endpoints, while “before” and “after”\\nexclude the specified date. \\u003ctime period\\u003e may also refer to “Any” or “None”, to multiple dates\\n(even if non-consecutive), or to a singular and discrete date or time.\\n\\nWhen \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event (such as an address, speech, performance, or\\nbroadcast), the Exchange may specify what is included, including whether it includes both live\\nand pre-recorded segments (including whether advertisements are included). Where a\\ntimezone is not specified, ET is assumed.\\n\\n\\nPayout Criterion: The Payout Criterion for the Contract encompasses the Expiration Values that\\n\\u003cword\\u003e is said by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n\\n\\nThe word must appear as a distinct, standalone unit, not buried inside another word. Plural\\nand possessive noun forms count. Other grammatical changes (tense, conjugation, derivation)\\ndo not. If \\u003cword\\u003e appears separated from other words by a space or hyphen or in a\\ncompound form with a space or hyphen, it counts. If \\u003cword\\u003e is fused into a single\\nunhyphenated word, it does not count.\\n\\nIf \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled, and the market contains a\\nstrike stating “Event does not qualify/occur”, such a strike shall resolve “Yes” and all others\\n“No”. If \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled but such strikes are NOT\\nlisted, the Contracts will resolve to the last fair price determined at the discretion of the\\nExchange. If the event is postponed, and such a postponement is announced by the end of the\\nfollowing calendar day to be rescheduled to a time within 14 calendar days, the markets shall\\nremain open. If the event captured in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast, the\\nExchange may keep the market open for 24 hours for the release of an official recording.\\nFurther granular details on conditions for these Contracts is available below.\\n\\nAdditional clarification(s):\\n\\n     Possessive noun forms of \\u003cword\\u003e, plurals, and possessive plural noun forms are\\n     INCLUDED:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigrants” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Egg” → “eggs’ shells” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Russia” → “Russia’s” counts, “Russian” does not\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e exists only in adjective form, no plural form exists:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Economic” → “Economics” does not count (“Economic” is an adjective\\n          for which “Economics” is not a plural)\\n     Plural nouns occurring within proper nouns and noun phrases are included:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Cat” → “Cats the musical” counts\\n\\f    Grammatical variations beyond plurals/possessives are NOT included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigration” does NOT count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Run” → “Running” or “Ran” do NOT count\\n    When \\u003cword\\u003e specifies a plural form, the singular does NOT count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Veterans” → “Veteran” does NOT count\\n    Words that are spelled the same as the plural form of \\u003cword\\u003e (if such exists) but are\\n    themselves not a plural noun are included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Wind” → “Winds up the clock” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Border” → “The United States has strong borders” counts\\n    Open compounds (words separated by spaces) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fire station” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “couch” → “couch potato” counts\\n    Hyphenated compounds (words connected by hyphens) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Palestine” → “pro-Palestine” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fat” → “non-fat” counts\\n    Closed compounds (single word, no spaces/hyphens) do not count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire” does not count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firefighter” does not count\\n    Multi-word \\u003cword\\u003e in larger constructions: When \\u003cword\\u003e is a multi-word phrase\\n    appearing within a hyphenated construction, it counts only if \\u003cword\\u003e appears as a\\n    complete, unmodified element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “New York” → “New York-based” counts (complete element)\\n    Portmanteaus (words blended from two words where parts of each are combined) are\\n    NOT included unless the portmanteau clearly contains \\u003cword\\u003e as a distinct, unaltered\\n    element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “MAGA” → “MAGA-nificent” counts (MAGA appears as distinct element)\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “magnificent” → “MAGA-nificent” does NOT count (portmanteau blend)\\n\\nDictionary determination: Both the Merriam-Webster Dictionary (available online) AND the\\nOxford English Dictionary shall be used to determine compound type and/or conventional\\nspelling patterns. Inclusion in either dictionary as an open or hyphenated compound shall\\nsatisfy the Payout Criterion. If neither provides clarity (or the word is not included),\\ndetermination is based on whether written as single unit (closed/doesn’t count) vs. spaces or\\nhyphens (open or hyphenated/counts) and/or context and previous usage.\\n\\nPHONETIC EQUIVALENCIES\\n\\n    Homophones (same sound, different spelling) do not count:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “write” → “right” does not count\\n    Homonyms and homographs (same spelling) COUNT regardless of meaning or\\n    pronunciation:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “bass” → both “bass guitar” and “bass fishing” count\\n    Proper and common nouns are treated identically:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Apple” → both “Apple Inc.” and “apple” (fruit) count\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Will” → both “Will Smith” and “I will go” count\\n    Minor unintentional mispronunciations COUNT if context makes intent clear:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Mamdani” → “Mandani” counts\\n    Severe mispronunciations that make \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable do NOT count.\\n    Trademarked spellings do not count, even when pronounced identically, unless the word\\n\\fitself is the same:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “lift” → “Lyft” (pronounced “lift”) does not count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “uber” → “Uber” counts\\nWords with non-standard transliteration to English count within reason, provided they are\\nphonetically equivalent:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Zelensky” → any of “Zelenski,” “Zelenskii,” “Zelensky,” or “Zelenskiy”\\n      count if pronounced equivalently\\nContractions do not count for their constituent words unless otherwise explicitly specified\\nby the Exchange:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “not” → “won’t,” “can’t,” “don’t,” “isn’t” do not count\\nNumbers spoken as words COUNT, when spoken exactly (not part of a larger number):\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “five” → saying “five” or reading “$5” aloud as “five dollars” counts,\\n      saying “five hundred” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “410” → “four hundred ten”, “four one zero” or “four ten” counts\\nOrdinals COUNT when \\u003cword\\u003e is written numerically OR a phrase that includes a\\nnumber:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “January 6” → “January 6th” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “3” (written numerically) → “3rd” (spoken as “third”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Eight War” → “8 Wars” and “Eighth War” will count\\nCardinal and ordinal number words are distinct:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “one” → “first” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “first” → “one” does NOT count\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count when pronunciation or letter-by-letter spelling\\nmatches \\u003cword\\u003e:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “NASA” (pronounced “NAH-suh”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “N-A-S-A” (spelled out) counts\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count as \\u003cword\\u003e when pronounced as the full word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Doctor” → “Dr.” (pronounced “Doctor”) counts\\nExpanded forms of acronyms do NOT count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “AI” → “artificial intelligence” does not count\\nWords in foreign languages do NOT count unless they are perfect cognates with an\\nEnglish word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fuego” (Spanish) does NOT count\\nEnglish words within foreign sentences count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “policy” → “Nuestra policy es clara” counts\\n\\u003cword\\u003e in organization/company names counts:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Securities” → “Bank of America Securities” counts\\nWords in URLs, emails, handles, and hashtags (exclusive of domain structure, email\\nprovider or symbols) are treated as compounds when spoken as complete words, with the\\ntype of compound subject to aforementioned rules:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firestation.com” pronounced “fire station dot com” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire.com” pronounced “wildfire dot com” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “apple” → “apple.com” pronounced “apple dot com” does count\\n      When presented in URL, email, handle, or hashtag form, \\u003cword\\u003e shall be treated as\\n      a compound, not a multi-word word\\nSung, rapped, or poetic words COUNT if phonetically recognizable:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “money” → “moneyyy” (extended in rap) counts\\n      Extreme distortion making \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable does NOT count.\\nPhonetic alphabet spelling (“Foxtrot India Romeo Echo” for “FIRE”) does NOT count.\\n\\fCANCELLATIONS AND DELAYS\\n\\n   The Exchange may list an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike for any Contract. If listed,\\n   such a strike refers to the structural conditions of the market, and is NOT adjudicated as a\\n   \\u003cword\\u003e needing to be said by or validated by having been said by \\u003centity\\u003e. If listed, this\\n   strike resolves to “Yes” whenever the event fails to occur or qualify under the Payout\\n   Criterion, or any other circumstance prevents normal resolution.\\n   If no such strike is listed, and \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, the following rules\\n   apply if the event is cancelled, postponed, rescheduled, or materially altered (including\\n   being closed to press) such that no video is released within one calendar day of the\\n   original start time of the event:\\n         If the event is cancelled, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price determined in\\n         the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         If the event is postponed or rescheduled, the outcome depends on whether a new\\n         date is publicly announced within one calendar day (i.e. if the event was scheduled\\n         to begin on Monday, any time up to 11:59PM on Tuesday falls within this period) of\\n         the originally scheduled start time:\\n               If no new date is announced within one calendar day, the Contract will resolve\\n               to the last fair price determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n               If a new date is announced within one calendar day, the outcome depends on\\n               when the rescheduled event is set to occur:\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls within fourteen (14) calendar days of the\\n                     originally scheduled date, the Contract shall remain open and \\u003cword\\u003e\\n                     stated during the rescheduled event will count.\\n                           The fourteen-day window begins at 12:00 AM ET on the originally\\n                           scheduled date and ends at 11:59 PM ET fourteen days later, unless\\n                           an alternate timezone is explicitly specified.\\n                           Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the State of the Union on January\\n                           15, 2026” rescheduled to January 20, 2026 → words spoken during\\n                           the rescheduled address count.\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls more than fourteen (14) calendar days after\\n                     the originally scheduled date, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price\\n                     determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         Any Contract that cannot be resolved through the Source Agency hierarchy will\\n         instead be settled at the Last Fair Price. The Exchange will disclose the methodology\\n         used to determine the Last Fair Price (e.g., Last Traded Price, Time-Weighted\\n         Average Price) at the time of Issuance.\\n         If an event begins but is interrupted, abbreviated, or ends prematurely, words\\n         stated by \\u003centity\\u003e during the portion of the event that did occur will count and the\\n         market will otherwise resolve.\\n   If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window but the venue, format, or medium\\n   changes (e.g., moved to a different location, changed from in-person to virtual (with the\\n   exception of being closed to press)), words stated during the event will count.\\n   Special condition: Across both cases, whether an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike is\\n   listed or not, if the event specified as or in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast (or\\n   relayed as such) but the live stream/broadcast does not occur, the Exchange will instead\\n   use an officially released recording as the Underlying, and may delay resolution by up to\\n   one calendar day to allow for the release of such a recording.\\n\\f          If partial snippets are released, Contracts on words that do not appear will be\\n          resolved to last fair price, and Contracts on those that do will be resolved to “Yes”.\\n          If no recording is released, the relevant outcomes triggered by the\\n          presence/absence of an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike shall occur as outlined\\n          above.\\n\\nTECHNICAL DETAILS (UNLESS OTHERWISE SPECIFIED)\\n\\n     When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, pre-recorded content broadcast,\\n     streamed, or published as part of that event is included if presented as part of the official\\n     presentation.\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the concert” with pre-recorded video interlude\\n          where entity speaks → words from interlude count\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the television appearance” with pre-taped\\n          segment aired during broadcast → words from segment count\\n     Behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are NOT\\n     included unless officially broadcast or published as part of \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n     Subtitles and captions that display \\u003cword\\u003e on screen but are not spoken aloud by\\n     \\u003centity\\u003e do NOT count.\\n     Sign language interpretation or usage by entity does NOT count as saying \\u003cword\\u003e unless\\n     the Contract explicitly specifies that sign language counts.\\n     Text that entity displays on screen (presentation slides, teleprompter visible to audience,\\n     signatures) does NOT count unless entity reads it aloud.\\n     Content generated by AI, deepfakes, or synthetic voice technology impersonating entity\\n     does NOT count unless the synthetic content is officially commissioned, authorized, or\\n     published by entity, OR the Contract explicitly specifies that AI-generated content counts.\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e is muted due to technical failure or censorship it shall not count unless\\n     corroborating contextual evidence (including surrounding speech, or an official\\n     uncensored recording or transcript) confirms that \\u003centity\\u003e specifically uttered \\u003cword\\u003e\\n     during the muted period.\\n\\nMinimum Tick: The Minimum Tick size for the Contract shall be $0.01.\\n\\nPosition Accountability Level: The Position Accountability Level for the Contract shall be\\n$25,000 per strike, per Member.\\n\\nLast Trading Date: The Last Trading Date of the Contract will be the Expiration Date. The Last\\nTrading Time will be the Expiration time.\\n\\nSettlement Date: The Settlement Date of the Contract shall be no later than the day after the\\nExpiration Date, unless the Market Outcome is under review pursuant to Rule 7.1.\\n\\nExpiration Date: When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event: The latest Expiration Date of\\nthe Contract shall be fourteen (14) calendar days after the originally scheduled date of the\\nevent. If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window, expiration will be moved to an\\nearlier date and time in accordance with Rule 7.2. When \\u003ctime period\\u003e is defined by specific\\ndates: The latest Expiration Date of the Contract shall be two weeks after the end of \\u003ctime\\nperiod\\u003e. If an event described in the Payout Criterion occurs and a consensus has been\\nreached on all terms, then expiration will be moved to an earlier date and time in accordance\\nwith Rule 7.2.\\n\\fExpiration time: The Expiration time of the Contract shall be 10:00 AM ET.\\n\\nSettlement Value: The Settlement Value for this Contract is $1.00.\\n\\nExpiration Value: The Expiration Value is the value of the Underlying as documented by the\\nSource Agency on the Expiration Date at the Expiration time.\\n\\nContingencies: Before Settlement, Kalshi may, at its sole discretion, initiate the Market\\nOutcome Review Process pursuant to Rule 7.1 of the Rulebook. If an Expiration Value cannot\\nbe determined on the Expiration Date, Kalshi has the right to determine payouts pursuant to\\nRule 7.1 in the Rulebook.\\n\\f\\n\\n[defendant] DX-S1 GovInfo official transcript: prior reporter exchange\\nSource: GovInfo, Compilation of Presidential Documents, DCPD202501162\\nURL retrieved: https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/DCPD-202501162/html/DCPD-202501162.htm\\nRetrieval time: 2026-06-29T22:00:00Z\\nLocal captured HTML size/hash: 51,571 bytes; SHA-256 eadbceeecf3e94f5bd423bcb8e8511165fdc7265dd8c1e025870c2e8f34dfd99\\n\\nMaterial captured text from official GovInfo HTML/web.open:\\n\\nAdministration of Donald J. Trump, 2025\\n\\nTitle: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\nDate: December 5, 2025\\n\\nOpening note: [The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\\n\\nExcerpt - The President's Interest in Soccer (web.open lines 196-203):\\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\\\"football,\\\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\\n\\nExcerpt - The President's Interest in Soccer (web.open lines 322-329):\\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\\nThe President. But they have a little more speed. But no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\\n\\nTiming/context note (web.open lines 461-462):\\nNOTE: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. In his remarks, he referred to Trey Yingst, chief foreign correspondent, Fox News Channel; Cristiano Ronaldo, forward for Saudi Pro League club Al-Nass and Portugal's national soccer team; and Lionel Messi, forward for Major League Soccer club Inter Miami and Argentina's national team. A reporter referred to New York State Attorney General Letitia James.\\nThe transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\n\\nDocument category/location/name/subject metadata (web.open lines 463-468):\\nCategories: Interviews With the News Media: Exchanges with reporters, Washington, DC.\\nLocations: Washington, DC.\\nNames include: Cristiano Ronaldo and Lionel Messi.\\nSubjects include: Federation Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) World Cup; John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts; News media, Presidential interviews; Soccer.\\nDCPD Number: DCPD202501162.\\n\\nCapture limits: This item is a focused text capture of the material official transcript title, Ronaldo excerpts, timing/correction note, and metadata. It is not a full video or audio artifact. The official transcript itself notes some portions could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-S2 FIFA official draw commencement time\\nSource: FIFA official page, FIFA World Cup 2026 Final Draw\\nURL: https://www.fifa.com/en/tournaments/mens/worldcup/canadamexicousa2026/live-draw\\nRetrieval time: 2026-06-29T22:01:00Z\\n\\nMaterial captured text from web search/open result:\\n- Page title/source: FIFA World Cup 2026™ Final Draw\\n- The draw takes place at the Kennedy Center in Washington DC, USA.\\n- The draw commences at 12:00 local time (17:00 UTC) on Friday 5 December 2025.\\n\\nCapture limits: This is a focused text capture of the official FIFA page timing statement located by web search. It is not a video capture of the draw ceremony.\\n\\nSubmitted evidence:\\n[plaintiff arguments] Official White House video page capture: President Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing (ev_db357d4e9407_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-db357d4e9407)\\nSource: https://www.whitehouse.gov/videos/president-trump-attends-the-fifa-world-cup-drawing/\\nSHA-256: `db357d4e940728d417ae4f7f3caac6b78d3fd3e4aba70d46fe10c6132d45997a`\\nBytes: 1300\\nRelevance: Establishes that the White House officially published a video page titled President Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing, dated December 5, 2025, with a full-video link and related World Cup Draw videos; relevant to source chain and event context.\\n\\n[plaintiff arguments] YouTube metadata capture: Trump Talks Cristiano Ronaldo at FIFA Draw (ev_4e1045905547_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-4e1045905547)\\nSource: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Cb2yO0lLEnM\\nSHA-256: `4e10459055477440085fe5e20d970eb2488e61d13a5e2b3133a3656bed7526d7`\\nBytes: 1779\\nRelevance: Provides a public clip source and page metadata asserting that at the FIFA World Cup Draw Ceremony Trump shared a story about meeting Cristiano Ronaldo and said Ronaldo was a great person; relevant to the alleged Ronaldo utterance, though weaker than an official full transcript or video.\\n\\n[defendant arguments] GovInfo official transcript capture: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the FIFA World Cup Draw (ev_a1b1f6b1b7bd_submitted-evidence-03-defendant-a1b1f6b1b7bd)\\nSource: https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/DCPD-202501162/html/DCPD-202501162.htm\\nSHA-256: `a1b1f6b1b7bd0b691c7fe8d97467dd0d085e2b22387ae4198270764de66e56e2`\\nBytes: 3070\\nRelevance: Official transcript identifies the relevant Trump remarks as an exchange with reporters prior to the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw; it includes the Ronaldo utterances and timing/correction notes, directly bearing on whether the utterances were during the countable event period.\\n\\n[defendant arguments] FIFA official page capture: 2026 World Cup Final Draw start time (ev_3973dc8f98c0_submitted-evidence-04-defendant-3973dc8f98c0)\\nSource: https://www.fifa.com/en/tournaments/mens/worldcup/canadamexicousa2026/live-draw\\nSHA-256: `3973dc8f98c01702174f61f5548eb1e80efe64dd72b44f21ed0fa7d944f93248`\\nBytes: 598\\nRelevance: Establishes the official Final Draw start time as 12:00 local time on December 5, 2025, which helps compare the draw event period against the GovInfo transcript note that the reporter exchange occurred at 11:13 a.m.\\n\\nTechnical reports:\\n[plaintiff] Plaintiff source-search and capture ledger\\nSearched exact market/strike phrases, White House domain, public video pages, YouTube video IDs, and Kalshi live market URL. Submitted official White House page capture and YouTube metadata capture. Kalshi live page returned a Vercel security checkpoint/429; local browser was unavailable; Python pip/ensurepip unavailable for yt-dlp; direct YouTube caption/open paths were throttled or unavailable. Remaining best evidence would be a full official video/transcript or Kalshi resolution rationale if later accessible.\\n\\n[defendant] Defendant source-search and capture ledger\\nInspected current AAR evidence and exact contents of plaintiff's White House and YouTube captures. Retrieved GovInfo official HTML transcript with curl from DCPD-202501162; local full HTML was 51,571 bytes with SHA-256 eadbceeecf3e94f5bd423bcb8e8511165fdc7265dd8c1e025870c2e8f34dfd99, then submitted a focused material text capture as DX-1. Searched official draw timing and submitted the FIFA official page timing statement as DX-2. Remaining gaps: full Kalshi market source hierarchy/resolution rationale and full WH/FIFA video were not captured, but official GovInfo timing/title plus FIFA start time resolve the material timing issue.\\n\\nCall submit_council_vote with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated.\\nKeep the rationale brief: no more than three sentences.\\n\\nCouncil API instructions:\\nYou are a council member. Decide the proposition from the admitted record.\\nYou may examine admitted evidence through read-only tools when exact bytes, metadata, or exhibit contents matter.\\nDo not search the web, introduce new facts, create new evidence, or upload evidence.\\nWhen ready, call submit_council_vote exactly once with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated and a concise rationale.\\n\",\"state\":\"ready\",\"status\":\"ready\",\"tools\":[{\"description\":\"Return the current visible arbitration record for this council member.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"get_case\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"List visible immutable record evidence.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"list_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Return metadata and read limits for one visible evidence item.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"stat_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Read a bounded byte range from one visible evidence item as base64.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"length\":{\"minimum\":1,\"type\":\"integer\"},\"offset\":{\"minimum\":0,\"type\":\"integer\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\",\"offset\",\"length\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"read_evidence_range\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Submit one council vote for the current deliberation opportunity.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"rationale\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"vote\":{\"enum\":[\"demonstrated\",\"not_demonstrated\"],\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"vote\",\"rationale\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"submit_council_vote\",\"read_only\":false}],\"turn\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"completed\":false,\"deadline\":\"2026-06-29T22:18:45.386037689Z\",\"deliberation_round\":1,\"member_id\":\"C2\",\"opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C2\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"remaining_ms\":889046,\"role_id\":\"council\",\"turn_number\":10},\"wait\":{\"reason\":\"ready\",\"state_version\":14,\"version\":17}}"}],"structuredContent":{"after_opportunity_id":"deliberation:1:C2","after_version":17,"case_id":"arb-ex03a-20260629214245","limits":{"attempts_max":3,"attempts_remaining":3,"max_evidence_read_bytes":65536,"max_evidence_read_bytes_per_opportunity":524288,"max_evidence_reads_per_opportunity":32,"max_response_bytes":131072,"remaining_evidence_read_bytes_for_opportunity":524288,"remaining_evidence_reads_for_opportunity":32},"member_id":"C2","message":"An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.","ok":true,"prompt":"Role: council member\nMember ID: C2\nDeliberation round: 1\nProposition: For the Kalshi market \"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\", the strike \"Ronaldo\" should resolve Yes because Trump said \"Ronaldo\" in public remarks at the World Cup Draw venue immediately before the formal program, and the market wording plus the governing mention-market terms did not clearly exclude those event-linked remarks.\nStandard of evidence: Preponderance of the evidence.\nPersona:\nYou are a careful juror and council member.\n\nEvaluate the record faithfully. Decide only from the evidence, the stated rules, and the applicable burden of proof. Do not favor either side, fill gaps with speculation, or ignore uncertainty.\n\nGive weight to reliable sources, direct evidence, consistent reasoning, and clear admissions. Discount unsupported claims, rhetorical force, irrelevant facts, and conclusions that exceed the record.\n\nWhen the evidence supports one answer, state it plainly. When the evidence is incomplete or balanced, say so. Be concise, honest, and exact.\n\nRecord:\nOpenings:\n[plaintiff] Council members, this case is not about whether the word \"Ronaldo\" would count if President Trump clearly said it. The current packet makes that part straightforward: the market is the Kalshi PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION market titled \"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\"; the strike is \"Ronaldo\"; Kalshi’s challenged resolution is No; and plaintiff seeks Yes.\n\nThe real dispute is temporal and contextual. Did the market phrase \"during the FIFA World Cup Draw,\" read with the governing mention-market terms, include public event-linked remarks at the World Cup Draw venue immediately before the formal draw program? Or did it clearly confine countable words to a narrower formal broadcast segment? Plaintiff’s position is that a No resolution cannot stand unless the record shows that the counting window clearly excluded those event-linked remarks.\n\nThe admitted terms matter. They define the underlying as words used by the specified entity during the specified time period. They expressly recognize event-based time periods, and they say the payout criterion is satisfied when the word is said by the entity during that period. They also contain exclusions: behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings do not count unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period; captions or text alone do not count; and the word must appear as a distinct standalone unit. Those exclusions are important, but they do not by themselves answer this case. A public remark at the event venue, tied to the Draw and immediately before the formal program, is not automatically a rehearsal, sound check, or private behind-the-scenes moment.\n\nAt this opening stage, the record proves the market identity, the challenged resolution, the requested resolution, and the generic governing terms. It does not yet prove the utterance itself, the exact sequence of the venue remarks, the source-agency hierarchy or any market-specific time-period language beyond the packet, or Kalshi’s reason for treating the strike as No. Those are the factual links that should decide the case under a preponderance standard.\n\nPlaintiff expects the decisive proof to be the full official or otherwise reliable event video or transcript, with enough surrounding context to show whether Trump said \"Ronaldo\" aloud as a standalone word; when he said it relative to the Draw event; whether the remarks were public and event-linked rather than backstage or a sound check; and whether any market-specific rule clearly excluded that segment. Plaintiff also expects the market page, archived market details, and any resolution rationale to be important because ambiguity in the market’s own event wording should not be resolved against Yes after the fact.\n\nThe defense will likely argue that \"during the FIFA World Cup Draw\" means only the formal draw ceremony or broadcast, and that anything before the formal program is outside the counting period. That theory can win only if the evidence shows a clear exclusion or a source record that separates the alleged remarks from the event itself. If the evidence instead shows public remarks at the Draw venue, officially connected to the event, immediately before the formal program, and no clear rule excluding them, then the terms favor counting the word and resolving the Ronaldo strike Yes.\n\n[defendant] Council members, the defense position is straightforward: the admitted record does not yet prove that the Ronaldo strike should resolve Yes. It proves a market title, a generic mention-market rule set, and Kalshi's challenged No resolution. It does not prove that any qualifying utterance of \"Ronaldo\" occurred during the market's countable time period.\n\nThe plaintiff's opening usefully narrows the dispute. This is not primarily a word-boundary case. If President Trump said \"Ronaldo\" as a standalone spoken word during the countable FIFA World Cup Draw period, the generic terms would ordinarily treat that as the kind of word that can count. The real question is whether plaintiff can carry the burden of showing that alleged pre-program, venue-adjacent remarks were part of the market's specified time period: \"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\"\n\nThe case-packet terms matter, but they cut both ways. They say the underlying is words used by the entity during the specified time period. They recognize that a time period can be an event, and they allow the Exchange to specify what is included when an event is involved. They also distinguish official event presentation from material outside the event: behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are not included unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period; text or captions alone do not count; and the relevant word must be spoken aloud by the entity. Those provisions do not support a rule that every public comment inside the same building, or every press exchange near the formal program, is automatically \"during\" the Draw.\n\nThat is the burden problem for plaintiff. The admitted market-page file identifies the public title, contract family, strike, challenged resolution, and requested resolution. It does not supply a full market-specific source hierarchy, a formal start time, a transcript, a video, a resolution rationale, or the alleged remarks. The terms file supplies the generic framework, but not the factual bridge from \"immediately before the formal program\" to \"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\" Without that bridge, the No resolution is not shown to be wrong by a preponderance of the evidence.\n\nThe defense expects the decisive proof to be source-chain evidence, not characterization. The council should want the market's full rule page if available, the source agency hierarchy, the official draw program or broadcast, any official transcript or recording of the alleged exchange, and enough surrounding timestamps to separate the formal draw from pre-event reporter access, red-carpet exchanges, arrivals, or other ancillary material. If later evidence shows that the alleged Ronaldo comment was in a segment officially presented as part of the Draw itself, plaintiff's argument becomes stronger. If the evidence instead shows a separate exchange with reporters before the draw, or an event-linked but pre-program interaction not incorporated into the official presentation, the generic terms support Kalshi's No.\n\nSo the defense opening is not that the word Ronaldo could never count. It is that this record has not established the necessary time-period link. The proposition asks the council to overturn No because the market wording and terms did not clearly exclude pre-program remarks. That reverses the burden. Plaintiff must show that the remarks were included in the countable period. Ambiguity about the outer edge of an event is not the same as proof that a specific pre-event utterance satisfies the payout criterion.\n\nArguments:\n[plaintiff] Council members, plaintiff has now supplied the record links that were missing at opening.\n\nFirst, the market packet fixes what this dispute is: the Kalshi market title is \"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\"; the contract family is PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION; the strike is \"Ronaldo\"; Kalshi's challenged resolution is No; and plaintiff seeks Yes. That is PX-1.\n\nSecond, the governing terms make this an event-period mention question, not a narrow formal-program-only question. PX-2 says the underlying is words used by the entity during the time period, recognizes that a time period may be a specific event, and sets the payout criterion as the word being said by the entity during that period. It also tells us what does not count: text/captions alone, unofficial behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, and sound checks unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. Those exclusions matter, but none says that public event-linked remarks at the venue immediately before the formal program are categorically outside \"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\"\n\nThird, the source-chain evidence now points to the disputed event and the Ronaldo utterance. PX-3 is an official White House page titled \"President Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing,\" dated December 5, 2025, with a full-video link and related World Cup Draw videos. That establishes an official White House event-video source for Trump's attendance at the World Cup Drawing. PX-4 is a public YouTube watch-page metadata capture for video ID Cb2yO0lLEnM, titled \"Trump Talks Cristiano Ronaldo at FIFA Draw -- 'He's a Great Person'.\" Its description states that at the FIFA World Cup Draw Ceremony, Trump shared a story about meeting Cristiano Ronaldo at the White House, said Ronaldo was a great person, and mentioned Ronaldo spoke with his son. PX-4 is not as strong as an official transcript, and plaintiff says that plainly. But it is admitted source content that directly links Trump, Cristiano Ronaldo, and the FIFA Draw ceremony.\n\nOn a preponderance standard, that is enough to defeat the challenged No resolution unless the defense can supply a clearer exclusion. The market did not ask only what Trump would say during the ball-pulling segment, during the televised main show, or after a particular formal start cue. It asked what he would say \"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\" The terms recognize event-based periods and exclude particular non-event categories. A public remark at the Draw venue, tied to the Draw, is far closer to the event period than to a rehearsal, sound check, caption, or private backstage recording.\n\nThe defense's burden framing is too strict. Plaintiff must prove Yes by a preponderance; plaintiff need not prove that Kalshi drafted every boundary with perfect precision. Once the admitted sources show a Ronaldo mention in connection with the FIFA Draw ceremony, the remaining question is whether the rules clearly remove that event-linked remark from the counting period. They do not. Ambiguity in a mention market's event wording should not be converted into an unstated formal-program limitation after the fact.\n\nProvenance and gaps: plaintiff attempted to retrieve the live Kalshi page, official/full video, caption, and transcript. Kalshi returned a Vercel security checkpoint; the local browser tool was unavailable; Python pip/ensurepip was unavailable for yt-dlp; and direct YouTube caption/open paths were throttled or unavailable. That leaves PX-4 weaker than ideal, but not weightless. PX-3 supplies official event context, PX-4 supplies the Ronaldo-at-FIFA-Draw metadata, and PX-2 supplies the rule that event-linked spoken words count absent a clear exclusion.\n\nThe council should resolve the proposition Yes: the Ronaldo strike should have resolved Yes because the record more likely than not shows Trump said Ronaldo in public remarks tied to the FIFA World Cup Draw, and the market wording plus governing terms did not clearly exclude those remarks.\n\n[defendant] Council members, the merits record now shows why the challenged No resolution should stand.\n\nPlaintiff's best point is that Trump did say the word \"Ronaldo.\" The defense does not need to fight that. The question is whether he said it during the market's countable time period: \"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\" On that decisive question, the strongest official sources favor No.\n\nThe admitted GovInfo transcript, DX-1, is an official Compilation of Presidential Documents capture. Its title is not merely \"World Cup Draw\" or \"FIFA ceremony.\" It is \"Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw.\" That same transcript contains the Ronaldo passages: Trump says he met Ronaldo at the White House, later says he was \"not Ronaldo or Messi,\" and the note identifies Ronaldo among the people referenced. So DX-1 is not adverse to the defense because it confirms the word; it is decisive because it places the word in an exchange with reporters prior to the Draw.\n\nDX-2 supplies the timing anchor. The official FIFA Final Draw page states that the Draw at the Kennedy Center commenced at 12:00 local time on Friday, December 5, 2025. DX-1 states that the President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the Kennedy Center. A reporter exchange at 11:13, officially titled as prior to a 12:00 draw, is not more likely than not \"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\" It is before it.\n\nThat reading matches the governing PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION terms. PX-2 says the payout criterion is satisfied when the word is said by the entity during the specified time period. It recognizes event-based periods and permits the Exchange to specify what is included for an event. It also treats official presentation differently from adjacent material: pre-recorded content counts if presented as part of the official event presentation, while behind-the-scenes, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings do not count unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. The point is not that this reporter exchange was a rehearsal or sound check. The point is that the terms require a link to the time period itself. Plaintiff has supplied no market-specific language saying pre-event reporter availability, arrivals, or venue interviews count as part of the Draw.\n\nPlaintiff's new exhibits do not fill that gap. PX-3, the White House page capture, establishes that the White House had a page titled \"President Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing,\" but plaintiff's own capture says the embedded/full video was not captured. It does not prove that the Ronaldo words occurred inside the official draw program. PX-4 is weaker still: it is metadata from a nonofficial YouTube channel. It says the clip is about Trump talking Ronaldo at the FIFA Draw, but it is not a transcript, not an official source, and not an audio extraction. When a nonofficial clip description is weighed against GovInfo's official transcript title and FIFA's official start time, the official sources control.\n\nNor is this a burden-shifting problem. The proposition asks the council to overturn Kalshi's No because the market supposedly did not clearly exclude remarks immediately before the formal program. But the preponderance burden is on Yes. The record must show that the strike satisfied the payout criterion. The admitted terms do not say that ambiguous pre-event remarks count by default; they say the word must be said during the specified time period. Here, the best evidence identifies the remarks as prior to the Draw and before the official commencement time.\n\nProvenance also matters. DX-1 is an official government transcript with a correction note and an audio-incomplete caveat. That caveat affects stray inaudible portions, but it does not weaken the title, the 11:13 timing note, or the Ronaldo passages preserved in the transcript. DX-2 is an official FIFA timing source. Plaintiff's YouTube metadata may explain why the dispute arose, but it cannot outweigh those primary sources on timing and event classification.\n\nThe council should resolve the proposition against plaintiff. Trump said Ronaldo, but the record more likely shows he did so in a reporter exchange prior to the FIFA World Cup Draw, not during the countable Draw event. Kalshi's No resolution should be upheld.\n\nRebuttals:\n[plaintiff] Council members, defendant’s new evidence narrows the case but does not end it.\n\nPlaintiff accepts the important parts of DX-1 and DX-2. The GovInfo transcript is official; it labels the item an exchange with reporters \"Prior to\" the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw; it places the exchange at 11:13 a.m. at the Kennedy Center; and the FIFA capture states the draw commenced at 12:00 local time. Plaintiff should not pretend those facts are weak.\n\nBut defendant asks those facts to do more than they do. The market was not drafted as \"what will Trump say after the official 12:00 commencement,\" \"during the televised draw program,\" or \"during the ball-drawing segment.\" PX-1 says the public market title was \"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\" That is ordinary event language, and PX-2 recognizes event-based time periods while leaving room for the Exchange to specify what is included. The record still contains no market-specific exclusion for official venue press remarks immediately before the formal program.\n\nDX-1 also helps plaintiff on the facts defendant originally said were missing. It confirms the relevant spoken word. Trump said he met Ronaldo, that Ronaldo is great, and that he was not Ronaldo or Messi. It also places those remarks at the Kennedy Center in a FIFA World Cup Draw-centered exchange with reporters, not in an unrelated private dinner or stale campaign setting. The transcript’s own subject metadata includes the FIFA World Cup, the Kennedy Center, news media, presidential interviews, and soccer. That is event-linked public context.\n\nThe terms’ exclusions do not fit defendant’s leap. PX-2 excludes captions alone, rehearsals, sound checks, behind-the-scenes content, and unofficial recordings unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. DX-1 is not a rehearsal transcript. It is not a sound check. It is not merely a caption. It is an official presidential transcript of a public reporter exchange at the venue, released in the Compilation of Presidential Documents. If Kalshi meant to exclude that category because it occurred before a formal noon commencement, the market needed to say so clearly.\n\nSo the dispositive question remains one of market construction: does \"during the FIFA World Cup Draw\" clearly exclude public, official, event-site remarks immediately before the formal program? Defendant has proved \"prior to\" the formal draw start. Defendant has not proved a clear market rule that treats the broader Draw event as beginning only at 12:00 for mention purposes.\n\nUnder a preponderance standard, the record now confirms the Ronaldo utterance and confirms the FIFA Draw setting. The challenged No resolution should not be upheld by importing a narrow formal-program limitation that the market title and generic terms did not state.\n\nSurrebuttals:\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff's rebuttal usefully clarifies the remaining dispute: plaintiff accepts that DX-1 is official, that it labels the relevant item an exchange with reporters \"Prior to\" the FIFA World Cup Draw, that the exchange occurred at 11:13 a.m. at the Kennedy Center, and that DX-2 places the official Draw commencement at 12:00 local time. Those concessions should decide the case.\n\nPlaintiff's answer is that the market did not say \"after 12:00,\" \"during the televised program,\" or \"during the ball-drawing segment.\" But the market also did not say \"at the venue before the Draw,\" \"in pre-event reporter exchanges,\" or \"in any public remarks connected to the Draw.\" The phrase it chose was \"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\" Ordinary event language has a start, and the official FIFA source fixes that start at noon. Official GovInfo then fixes this exchange at 11:13 and titles it as prior to the Draw.\n\nThat is not a technicality. The terms require the word to be said during the specified time period. They recognize event-based periods and allow event-specific inclusions, but no admitted market-specific rule includes pre-event press access. Plaintiff's construction would turn any event-adjacent public remark into part of the event unless expressly excluded. That reverses the payout criterion. The claimant must show the word occurred during the time period; it is not enough to show the same venue, the same general topic, and official publication.\n\nPlaintiff says the exclusions do not fit because DX-1 is not a rehearsal, sound check, caption, or private backstage recording. Fair enough; the defense is not relying on those categories as labels. The defense relies on the affirmative timing requirement. A remark need not be a rehearsal to be outside the event. A reporter exchange officially described as prior to a noon event and occurring at 11:13 is outside because it is before the event began.\n\nThe record therefore proves the wrong fact for plaintiff. It proves Trump said Ronaldo, but in a pre-event reporter exchange. The proposition requires Yes only if those words count during the FIFA World Cup Draw. On this record, they do not. Kalshi's No resolution should be upheld.\n\nClosings:\n[plaintiff] Council members, the final record leaves one legal question.\n\nThe easy factual question is resolved in plaintiff’s favor: Trump said \"Ronaldo.\" The official GovInfo transcript confirms it twice in substance: he said he met Ronaldo, praised him, and later said he was not Ronaldo or Messi. That is a spoken standalone use of the strike word. The record also places the remarks at the Kennedy Center in a FIFA World Cup Draw-centered reporter exchange. This was not an unrelated dinner, a caption, an AI voice, or a social-media paraphrase.\n\nThe hard point is timing. Defendant has the strongest evidence on the formal program boundary: GovInfo titled the exchange as \"Prior to\" the Draw, notes 11:13 a.m., and FIFA states the Final Draw commenced at 12:00 local time. Plaintiff does not ask the council to ignore that. The question is what the Kalshi market actually required.\n\nPX-1 did not say \"after 12:00.\" It did not say \"during the televised draw program\" or \"during the ball-drawing segment.\" It asked, in public market wording, \"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\" PX-2’s generic terms recognize event-based periods and say the Exchange may specify what is included when a time period refers to an event. They also give specific exclusions: captions alone, rehearsals, sound checks, behind-the-scenes content, and unofficial recordings unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. None of those exclusions is this case. The GovInfo transcript is an official public presidential record of an event-site reporter exchange, not a rehearsal or sound check.\n\nDefendant’s best argument is that ordinary events have start times. True. But this market dispute is about public remarks at the venue immediately before the formal program, in the official context of the Draw, where the market and rules did not clearly define a noon-only boundary. If Kalshi wanted that narrower rule, it could have said so in the strike, the market title, or the event inclusion language. It did not.\n\nThe preponderance record therefore shows: Ronaldo was spoken; the remarks were public and officially documented; they were at the Kennedy Center in the FIFA World Cup Draw setting; and the governing market language did not clearly exclude that immediately-before-program event context. The challenged No resolution depends on importing a formal commencement limitation that is absent from the market packet.\n\nFor that reason, the Ronaldo strike should resolve Yes.\n\n[defendant] Council members, the closing record is narrow and concrete.\n\nEveryone now agrees on the easy fact: Trump said \"Ronaldo.\" The official GovInfo transcript proves that. But the proposition is not simply that Trump said the word somewhere near the FIFA World Cup Draw. The proposition asks you to overturn Kalshi's No because remarks immediately before the formal program should count under a market asking what Trump would say \"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\" Plaintiff has not carried that burden.\n\nThe two strongest sources are official and aligned. GovInfo, in DX-1, titles the relevant document \"Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw.\" It notes that the President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the Kennedy Center. FIFA, in DX-2, states that the Final Draw commenced at 12:00 local time. Those facts are not peripheral. They answer the timing question: the Ronaldo words were in a reporter exchange before the Draw began.\n\nPlaintiff's closing says the market did not specify \"after 12:00,\" \"during the televised draw program,\" or \"during the ball-drawing segment.\" True, but that does not prove Yes. The market did specify \"during the FIFA World Cup Draw.\" The ordinary function of \"during\" is to define the event period, not to include anything public, official, and thematically related that happens beforehand. A 47-minute-before reporter exchange officially titled as prior to the Draw is outside that period unless the market or governing terms affirmatively include it. The record contains no such inclusion.\n\nThe governing terms reinforce that conclusion. They require the word to be said by the entity during the specified time period. They recognize event-based periods and allow the Exchange to specify event inclusions. They include official-presentation concepts for material presented as part of an event. But they do not say that pre-event press availability counts by default. Plaintiff's argument turns the absence of an exclusion into proof of inclusion. That is backwards under a preponderance standard.\n\nPlaintiff also leans on setting: Kennedy Center, FIFA World Cup subject matter, official transcript, public reporters. Those facts show why the issue is understandable. They do not move 11:13 into a 12:00 event. A source can be official and still describe something outside the event. Indeed, that is exactly what DX-1 does: it officially documents the remarks and officially labels them prior to the Draw.\n\nThe weaker evidence points the same way once weighed properly. The White House page capture does not include the video or transcript. The YouTube metadata is nonofficial and not an audio transcript. Neither overcomes GovInfo's title and timing note plus FIFA's commencement time.\n\nSo the final answer is simple: the word was spoken, but not during the countable event period shown by the best evidence. Plaintiff has not shown that Kalshi's No resolution was wrong. The council should reject the proposition and uphold No.\n\nExhibits:\n[plaintiff] PX-1 Market page packet: Ronaldo strike and challenged No resolution\nMarket URL: https://kalshi.com/markets/kxtrumpmentionb/trump-mention-b/kxtrumpmentionb-25dec06\n\nPublic market title: What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\n\nContract family: PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION\n\nStrike at issue: Ronaldo\n\nChallenged resolution: No\n\nRequested resolution: Yes\n\n\n[plaintiff] PX-2 Governing PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION terms\n                                         NEWMENTION\n\nScope: These rules shall apply to this contract.\n\nUnderlying: The Underlying for this Contract is words used by <entity> <time period>.\nRevisions to the Underlying made after Expiration will not be accounted for in determining the\nExpiration Value.\n\nSource Agency: The Source Agencies are <source>.\n\nType: The type of Contract is an Event Contract.\n\nIssuance: After the initial Contract, Contract iterations will be listed on an as-needed basis at\nthe discretion of the Exchange and corresponding to the risk management needs of Members.\n\n<entity>: <entity> refers to the speaker, writer, performer, or communicator specified by the\nExchange. This may include (but is not limited to): a specific named individual, multiple\nindividuals specified using AND/OR logic, an individual identified by position or title, a group,\nband, team or collective entity, a specified member or members of a group, an organization,\ncompany, or institutional entity, or any combination of the aforementioned.\n\nWhen <entity> is defined by a position or title, the Contract tracks whoever holds that position\nduring <time period>, even if the individual holding the position changes. When <entity> is a\nspecific named individual, the identity remains consistent throughout. Name changes (e.g.,\nstage names, married names) do not create a new entity. When <entity> is a group or\norganization and the Contract does not specify particular members, any official\ncommunication or statement by any member or designated spokesperson counts. When using\nAND logic, all specified entities must independently say <word> during <time period>. When\nusing OR logic, at least one of the specified entities must say <word> during <time period>.\nThe Exchange may specify additional conditions such as “at least X members of” a group or\n“the majority of” a group.\n\n<source>: <source> refers to a Source Agency or ordered collection of Source Agencies\nspecified by the Exchange at the time of Contract listing, which will be incorporated into the\nSource Agency hierarchy above and used to determine the occurrence of the Underlying.\n<source> may refer to a singular agency, multiple agencies, an agency by distinguishing\ncharacteristics, by category or type (e.g., “official government statistical body,” “primary wire\nservice”), or any combination thereof. When multiple agencies are specified, they may be\napplied in the hierarchical order designated by the Exchange if so specified, with the highest-\nranked available and responsive agency taking precedence for purposes of determining the\nExpiration Value. A lower-ranked agency shall only be consulted if all higher-ranked agencies\nare unavailable, unresponsive, have not reported on the Underlying by the Expiration time, or\nif the Exchange, in its sole discretion, determines that a higher-ranked agency’s reporting is\nincomplete, erroneous, or otherwise insufficient to determine the Expiration Value. If <source>\ndesignates multiple agencies without specifying a hierarchical order, the Exchange shall\nresolve any conflict between reporting agencies at its sole discretion.\n\n<word>: <word> refers to the particular word or phrase potentially to be mentioned by\n<entity>. It may refer to a word being said a minimum number of times. It may also refer to\none of multiple words/phrases, any of which are acceptable (e.g., “Doge/Dogecoin”).\n\f<time period>: <time period> refers to a specific range of time, event or discrete date and\ntime specified by the Exchange. This may be defined by, but is not limited to: a specific event\nor context (e.g., “during the State of the Union address”), exact dates or times, relative time\nmarkers (e.g., “before July 1, 2027,” “in Q1 2026”), event-based periods (e.g., “during any\ncampaign rally in October 2026,” “during the awards ceremony”), and broader intervals (e.g.,\n“Q1–Q2 2027,” “January–March 2026”).\n\nUnless stated otherwise, “Between” is inclusive of both endpoints, while “before” and “after”\nexclude the specified date. <time period> may also refer to “Any” or “None”, to multiple dates\n(even if non-consecutive), or to a singular and discrete date or time.\n\nWhen <time period> refers to a specific event (such as an address, speech, performance, or\nbroadcast), the Exchange may specify what is included, including whether it includes both live\nand pre-recorded segments (including whether advertisements are included). Where a\ntimezone is not specified, ET is assumed.\n\n\nPayout Criterion: The Payout Criterion for the Contract encompasses the Expiration Values that\n<word> is said by <entity> <time period>.\n\n\nThe word must appear as a distinct, standalone unit, not buried inside another word. Plural\nand possessive noun forms count. Other grammatical changes (tense, conjugation, derivation)\ndo not. If <word> appears separated from other words by a space or hyphen or in a\ncompound form with a space or hyphen, it counts. If <word> is fused into a single\nunhyphenated word, it does not count.\n\nIf <time period> refers to an event and that event is cancelled, and the market contains a\nstrike stating “Event does not qualify/occur”, such a strike shall resolve “Yes” and all others\n“No”. If <time period> refers to an event and that event is cancelled but such strikes are NOT\nlisted, the Contracts will resolve to the last fair price determined at the discretion of the\nExchange. If the event is postponed, and such a postponement is announced by the end of the\nfollowing calendar day to be rescheduled to a time within 14 calendar days, the markets shall\nremain open. If the event captured in <time period> is a live-stream or broadcast, the\nExchange may keep the market open for 24 hours for the release of an official recording.\nFurther granular details on conditions for these Contracts is available below.\n\nAdditional clarification(s):\n\n     Possessive noun forms of <word>, plurals, and possessive plural noun forms are\n     INCLUDED:\n          <word> is “Immigrant” → “Immigrants” counts\n          <word> is “Egg” → “eggs’ shells” counts\n          <word> is “Russia” → “Russia’s” counts, “Russian” does not\n     If <word> exists only in adjective form, no plural form exists:\n          <word> is “Economic” → “Economics” does not count (“Economic” is an adjective\n          for which “Economics” is not a plural)\n     Plural nouns occurring within proper nouns and noun phrases are included:\n          <word> is “Cat” → “Cats the musical” counts\n\f    Grammatical variations beyond plurals/possessives are NOT included:\n         <word> is “Immigrant” → “Immigration” does NOT count\n         <word> is “Run” → “Running” or “Ran” do NOT count\n    When <word> specifies a plural form, the singular does NOT count:\n         <word> is “Veterans” → “Veteran” does NOT count\n    Words that are spelled the same as the plural form of <word> (if such exists) but are\n    themselves not a plural noun are included:\n         <word> is “Wind” → “Winds up the clock” counts\n         <word> is “Border” → “The United States has strong borders” counts\n    Open compounds (words separated by spaces) count:\n         <word> is “fire” → “fire station” counts\n         <word> is “couch” → “couch potato” counts\n    Hyphenated compounds (words connected by hyphens) count:\n         <word> is “Palestine” → “pro-Palestine” counts\n         <word> is “fat” → “non-fat” counts\n    Closed compounds (single word, no spaces/hyphens) do not count:\n         <word> is “fire” → “wildfire” does not count\n         <word> is “fire” → “firefighter” does not count\n    Multi-word <word> in larger constructions: When <word> is a multi-word phrase\n    appearing within a hyphenated construction, it counts only if <word> appears as a\n    complete, unmodified element:\n         <word> is “New York” → “New York-based” counts (complete element)\n    Portmanteaus (words blended from two words where parts of each are combined) are\n    NOT included unless the portmanteau clearly contains <word> as a distinct, unaltered\n    element:\n         <word> is “MAGA” → “MAGA-nificent” counts (MAGA appears as distinct element)\n         <word> is “magnificent” → “MAGA-nificent” does NOT count (portmanteau blend)\n\nDictionary determination: Both the Merriam-Webster Dictionary (available online) AND the\nOxford English Dictionary shall be used to determine compound type and/or conventional\nspelling patterns. Inclusion in either dictionary as an open or hyphenated compound shall\nsatisfy the Payout Criterion. If neither provides clarity (or the word is not included),\ndetermination is based on whether written as single unit (closed/doesn’t count) vs. spaces or\nhyphens (open or hyphenated/counts) and/or context and previous usage.\n\nPHONETIC EQUIVALENCIES\n\n    Homophones (same sound, different spelling) do not count:\n        <word> is “write” → “right” does not count\n    Homonyms and homographs (same spelling) COUNT regardless of meaning or\n    pronunciation:\n        <word> is “bass” → both “bass guitar” and “bass fishing” count\n    Proper and common nouns are treated identically:\n        <word> is “Apple” → both “Apple Inc.” and “apple” (fruit) count\n        <word> is “Will” → both “Will Smith” and “I will go” count\n    Minor unintentional mispronunciations COUNT if context makes intent clear:\n        <word> is “Mamdani” → “Mandani” counts\n    Severe mispronunciations that make <word> unrecognizable do NOT count.\n    Trademarked spellings do not count, even when pronounced identically, unless the word\n\fitself is the same:\n      <word> is “lift” → “Lyft” (pronounced “lift”) does not count\n      <word> is “uber” → “Uber” counts\nWords with non-standard transliteration to English count within reason, provided they are\nphonetically equivalent:\n      <word> is “Zelensky” → any of “Zelenski,” “Zelenskii,” “Zelensky,” or “Zelenskiy”\n      count if pronounced equivalently\nContractions do not count for their constituent words unless otherwise explicitly specified\nby the Exchange:\n      <word> is “not” → “won’t,” “can’t,” “don’t,” “isn’t” do not count\nNumbers spoken as words COUNT, when spoken exactly (not part of a larger number):\n      <word> is “five” → saying “five” or reading “$5” aloud as “five dollars” counts,\n      saying “five hundred” does NOT count\n      <word> is “410” → “four hundred ten”, “four one zero” or “four ten” counts\nOrdinals COUNT when <word> is written numerically OR a phrase that includes a\nnumber:\n      <word> is “January 6” → “January 6th” counts\n      <word> is “3” (written numerically) → “3rd” (spoken as “third”) counts\n      <word> is “Eight War” → “8 Wars” and “Eighth War” will count\nCardinal and ordinal number words are distinct:\n      <word> is “one” → “first” does NOT count\n      <word> is “first” → “one” does NOT count\nAcronyms and abbreviations count when pronunciation or letter-by-letter spelling\nmatches <word>:\n      <word> is “NASA” → “NASA” (pronounced “NAH-suh”) counts\n      <word> is “NASA” → “N-A-S-A” (spelled out) counts\nAcronyms and abbreviations count as <word> when pronounced as the full word:\n      <word> is “Doctor” → “Dr.” (pronounced “Doctor”) counts\nExpanded forms of acronyms do NOT count:\n      <word> is “AI” → “artificial intelligence” does not count\nWords in foreign languages do NOT count unless they are perfect cognates with an\nEnglish word:\n      <word> is “fire” → “fuego” (Spanish) does NOT count\nEnglish words within foreign sentences count:\n      <word> is “policy” → “Nuestra policy es clara” counts\n<word> in organization/company names counts:\n      <word> is “Securities” → “Bank of America Securities” counts\nWords in URLs, emails, handles, and hashtags (exclusive of domain structure, email\nprovider or symbols) are treated as compounds when spoken as complete words, with the\ntype of compound subject to aforementioned rules:\n      <word> is “fire” → “firestation.com” pronounced “fire station dot com” counts\n      <word> is “fire” → “wildfire.com” pronounced “wildfire dot com” does NOT count\n      <word> is “apple” → “apple.com” pronounced “apple dot com” does count\n      When presented in URL, email, handle, or hashtag form, <word> shall be treated as\n      a compound, not a multi-word word\nSung, rapped, or poetic words COUNT if phonetically recognizable:\n      <word> is “money” → “moneyyy” (extended in rap) counts\n      Extreme distortion making <word> unrecognizable does NOT count.\nPhonetic alphabet spelling (“Foxtrot India Romeo Echo” for “FIRE”) does NOT count.\n\fCANCELLATIONS AND DELAYS\n\n   The Exchange may list an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike for any Contract. If listed,\n   such a strike refers to the structural conditions of the market, and is NOT adjudicated as a\n   <word> needing to be said by or validated by having been said by <entity>. If listed, this\n   strike resolves to “Yes” whenever the event fails to occur or qualify under the Payout\n   Criterion, or any other circumstance prevents normal resolution.\n   If no such strike is listed, and <time period> refers to a specific event, the following rules\n   apply if the event is cancelled, postponed, rescheduled, or materially altered (including\n   being closed to press) such that no video is released within one calendar day of the\n   original start time of the event:\n         If the event is cancelled, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price determined in\n         the sole discretion of the Exchange.\n         If the event is postponed or rescheduled, the outcome depends on whether a new\n         date is publicly announced within one calendar day (i.e. if the event was scheduled\n         to begin on Monday, any time up to 11:59PM on Tuesday falls within this period) of\n         the originally scheduled start time:\n               If no new date is announced within one calendar day, the Contract will resolve\n               to the last fair price determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\n               If a new date is announced within one calendar day, the outcome depends on\n               when the rescheduled event is set to occur:\n                     If the rescheduled date falls within fourteen (14) calendar days of the\n                     originally scheduled date, the Contract shall remain open and <word>\n                     stated during the rescheduled event will count.\n                           The fourteen-day window begins at 12:00 AM ET on the originally\n                           scheduled date and ends at 11:59 PM ET fourteen days later, unless\n                           an alternate timezone is explicitly specified.\n                           Example: <time period> is “during the State of the Union on January\n                           15, 2026” rescheduled to January 20, 2026 → words spoken during\n                           the rescheduled address count.\n                     If the rescheduled date falls more than fourteen (14) calendar days after\n                     the originally scheduled date, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price\n                     determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\n         Any Contract that cannot be resolved through the Source Agency hierarchy will\n         instead be settled at the Last Fair Price. The Exchange will disclose the methodology\n         used to determine the Last Fair Price (e.g., Last Traded Price, Time-Weighted\n         Average Price) at the time of Issuance.\n         If an event begins but is interrupted, abbreviated, or ends prematurely, words\n         stated by <entity> during the portion of the event that did occur will count and the\n         market will otherwise resolve.\n   If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window but the venue, format, or medium\n   changes (e.g., moved to a different location, changed from in-person to virtual (with the\n   exception of being closed to press)), words stated during the event will count.\n   Special condition: Across both cases, whether an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike is\n   listed or not, if the event specified as or in <time period> is a live-stream or broadcast (or\n   relayed as such) but the live stream/broadcast does not occur, the Exchange will instead\n   use an officially released recording as the Underlying, and may delay resolution by up to\n   one calendar day to allow for the release of such a recording.\n\f          If partial snippets are released, Contracts on words that do not appear will be\n          resolved to last fair price, and Contracts on those that do will be resolved to “Yes”.\n          If no recording is released, the relevant outcomes triggered by the\n          presence/absence of an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike shall occur as outlined\n          above.\n\nTECHNICAL DETAILS (UNLESS OTHERWISE SPECIFIED)\n\n     When <time period> refers to a specific event, pre-recorded content broadcast,\n     streamed, or published as part of that event is included if presented as part of the official\n     presentation.\n          Example: <time period> is “during the concert” with pre-recorded video interlude\n          where entity speaks → words from interlude count\n          Example: <time period> is “during the television appearance” with pre-taped\n          segment aired during broadcast → words from segment count\n     Behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are NOT\n     included unless officially broadcast or published as part of <time period>.\n     Subtitles and captions that display <word> on screen but are not spoken aloud by\n     <entity> do NOT count.\n     Sign language interpretation or usage by entity does NOT count as saying <word> unless\n     the Contract explicitly specifies that sign language counts.\n     Text that entity displays on screen (presentation slides, teleprompter visible to audience,\n     signatures) does NOT count unless entity reads it aloud.\n     Content generated by AI, deepfakes, or synthetic voice technology impersonating entity\n     does NOT count unless the synthetic content is officially commissioned, authorized, or\n     published by entity, OR the Contract explicitly specifies that AI-generated content counts.\n     If <word> is muted due to technical failure or censorship it shall not count unless\n     corroborating contextual evidence (including surrounding speech, or an official\n     uncensored recording or transcript) confirms that <entity> specifically uttered <word>\n     during the muted period.\n\nMinimum Tick: The Minimum Tick size for the Contract shall be $0.01.\n\nPosition Accountability Level: The Position Accountability Level for the Contract shall be\n$25,000 per strike, per Member.\n\nLast Trading Date: The Last Trading Date of the Contract will be the Expiration Date. The Last\nTrading Time will be the Expiration time.\n\nSettlement Date: The Settlement Date of the Contract shall be no later than the day after the\nExpiration Date, unless the Market Outcome is under review pursuant to Rule 7.1.\n\nExpiration Date: When <time period> refers to a specific event: The latest Expiration Date of\nthe Contract shall be fourteen (14) calendar days after the originally scheduled date of the\nevent. If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window, expiration will be moved to an\nearlier date and time in accordance with Rule 7.2. When <time period> is defined by specific\ndates: The latest Expiration Date of the Contract shall be two weeks after the end of <time\nperiod>. If an event described in the Payout Criterion occurs and a consensus has been\nreached on all terms, then expiration will be moved to an earlier date and time in accordance\nwith Rule 7.2.\n\fExpiration time: The Expiration time of the Contract shall be 10:00 AM ET.\n\nSettlement Value: The Settlement Value for this Contract is $1.00.\n\nExpiration Value: The Expiration Value is the value of the Underlying as documented by the\nSource Agency on the Expiration Date at the Expiration time.\n\nContingencies: Before Settlement, Kalshi may, at its sole discretion, initiate the Market\nOutcome Review Process pursuant to Rule 7.1 of the Rulebook. If an Expiration Value cannot\nbe determined on the Expiration Date, Kalshi has the right to determine payouts pursuant to\nRule 7.1 in the Rulebook.\n\f\n\n[plaintiff] PX-3 Official White House World Cup Drawing video page capture\nSource capture from official White House page https://www.whitehouse.gov/videos/president-trump-attends-the-fifa-world-cup-drawing/\nRetrieval: 2026-06-29T21:52:12Z via OpenClaw web_fetch and web.open.\n\nVisible page facts captured:\n- Page title: President Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing\n- Date shown on page: December 5, 2025\n- Page section: Videos\n- The page contains a link labeled View Full Video to Instagram.\n- Related video listed: FIFA World Cup 2026 Draw at The Kennedy Center, duration 00:45, dated December 6, 2025.\n- Related video listed: FIFA World Cup Drawing Announced to Take Place at The Kennedy Center, duration 00:56, dated August 23, 2025.\n- Related video listed: President Trump on the 2026 FIFA World Cup, duration 01:22, dated May 6, 2025.\n\nRelevant extracted lines from web.open capture:\nL142: Videos\nL143: # President Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing\nL145: December 5, 2025\nL133: ... View Full Video [instagram.com] ...\nL151: FIFA World Cup 2026 Draw at The Kennedy Center\nL153: December 6, 2025\nL167-L170: President Trump on the 2026 FIFA World Cup, May 6, 2025\n\nNotes on capture limits: readability extraction returned minimal content, so the above preserves visible lines from the page capture. The embedded/full video itself was not captured in this item.\n\n[plaintiff] PX-4 YouTube metadata capture for Ronaldo-at-FIFA-Draw clip\nSource capture: YouTube watch page https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Cb2yO0lLEnM\nVideo ID: Cb2yO0lLEnM\nRetrieval: 2026-06-29T21:53:00Z via web search and curl of the YouTube watch page.\n\nCaptured title / page metadata:\n- Title shown in search and page metadata: Trump Talks Cristiano Ronaldo at FIFA Draw — ‘He’s a Great Person’\n- Channel shown in page metadata: interestingText You / @InterestingTextYou\n- Subscriber count shown in page metadata at capture: about 10.3K subscribers\n\nCaptured description text from YouTube page metadata:\n\"Trump Talks Cristiano Ronaldo at FIFA Draw — ‘He’s a Great Person’\n\nAt the FIFA World Cup Draw Ceremony, Donald Trump shared a story about meeting Cristiano Ronaldo at the White House. Trump said Ronaldo was “a great person” and even mentioned that Ronaldo spoke with his son about soccer during the visit.\n\nThis unexpected crossover between world politics and one of the biggest global sports stars quickly caught viewers' attention.\n\nTrump FIFA Draw\nDonald Trump FIFA World Cup\nTrump Cristiano Ronaldo\nCristiano Ronaldo Trump meeting\nFIFA World Cup draw 2026\nRonaldo White House visit\nTrump soccer comments\nWorld Cup trending 2025\nsports politics crossover\nCristiano Ronaldo story\nDonald Trump viral moment\nFIFA draw ceremony Trump\nWorld Cup 2026 news\nRonaldo fan reaction\npolitical celebrity moments\nviral sports clips 2025\nFIFA draw highlights\nTrump speech FIFA\nglobal sports news\"\n\nCapture limits and provenance caveat: direct video/caption extraction was attempted but YouTube transcript/open paths were throttled or unavailable in this environment. This item preserves the public watch-page metadata and description, not an independently extracted audio transcript. It is not an official White House or FIFA source.\n\n[defendant] DX-1 GovInfo official transcript: remarks prior to FIFA World Cup Draw\nSource: GovInfo, Compilation of Presidential Documents, DCPD202501162\nURL retrieved: https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/DCPD-202501162/html/DCPD-202501162.htm\nRetrieval time: 2026-06-29T22:00:00Z\nLocal captured HTML size/hash: 51,571 bytes; SHA-256 eadbceeecf3e94f5bd423bcb8e8511165fdc7265dd8c1e025870c2e8f34dfd99\n\nMaterial captured text from official GovInfo HTML/web.open:\n\nAdministration of Donald J. Trump, 2025\n\nTitle: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\nDate: December 5, 2025\n\nOpening note: [The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\n\nExcerpt - The President's Interest in Soccer (web.open lines 196-203):\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\"football,\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\n\nExcerpt - The President's Interest in Soccer (web.open lines 322-329):\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\nThe President. But they have a little more speed. But no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\n\nTiming/context note (web.open lines 461-462):\nNOTE: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. In his remarks, he referred to Trey Yingst, chief foreign correspondent, Fox News Channel; Cristiano Ronaldo, forward for Saudi Pro League club Al-Nass and Portugal's national soccer team; and Lionel Messi, forward for Major League Soccer club Inter Miami and Argentina's national team. A reporter referred to New York State Attorney General Letitia James.\nThe transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\n\nDocument category/location/name/subject metadata (web.open lines 463-468):\nCategories: Interviews With the News Media: Exchanges with reporters, Washington, DC.\nLocations: Washington, DC.\nNames include: Cristiano Ronaldo and Lionel Messi.\nSubjects include: Federation Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) World Cup; John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts; News media, Presidential interviews; Soccer.\nDCPD Number: DCPD202501162.\n\nCapture limits: This item is a focused text capture of the material official transcript title, Ronaldo excerpts, timing/correction note, and metadata. It is not a full video or audio artifact. The official transcript itself notes some portions could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\n\n[defendant] DX-2 FIFA official Final Draw start-time capture\nSource: FIFA official page, FIFA World Cup 2026 Final Draw\nURL: https://www.fifa.com/en/tournaments/mens/worldcup/canadamexicousa2026/live-draw\nRetrieval time: 2026-06-29T22:01:00Z\n\nMaterial captured text from web search/open result:\n- Page title/source: FIFA World Cup 2026™ Final Draw\n- The draw takes place at the Kennedy Center in Washington DC, USA.\n- The draw commences at 12:00 local time (17:00 UTC) on Friday 5 December 2025.\n\nCapture limits: This is a focused text capture of the official FIFA page timing statement located by web search. It is not a video capture of the draw ceremony.\n\n[defendant] DX-3 Governing PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION terms\n                                         NEWMENTION\n\nScope: These rules shall apply to this contract.\n\nUnderlying: The Underlying for this Contract is words used by <entity> <time period>.\nRevisions to the Underlying made after Expiration will not be accounted for in determining the\nExpiration Value.\n\nSource Agency: The Source Agencies are <source>.\n\nType: The type of Contract is an Event Contract.\n\nIssuance: After the initial Contract, Contract iterations will be listed on an as-needed basis at\nthe discretion of the Exchange and corresponding to the risk management needs of Members.\n\n<entity>: <entity> refers to the speaker, writer, performer, or communicator specified by the\nExchange. This may include (but is not limited to): a specific named individual, multiple\nindividuals specified using AND/OR logic, an individual identified by position or title, a group,\nband, team or collective entity, a specified member or members of a group, an organization,\ncompany, or institutional entity, or any combination of the aforementioned.\n\nWhen <entity> is defined by a position or title, the Contract tracks whoever holds that position\nduring <time period>, even if the individual holding the position changes. When <entity> is a\nspecific named individual, the identity remains consistent throughout. Name changes (e.g.,\nstage names, married names) do not create a new entity. When <entity> is a group or\norganization and the Contract does not specify particular members, any official\ncommunication or statement by any member or designated spokesperson counts. When using\nAND logic, all specified entities must independently say <word> during <time period>. When\nusing OR logic, at least one of the specified entities must say <word> during <time period>.\nThe Exchange may specify additional conditions such as “at least X members of” a group or\n“the majority of” a group.\n\n<source>: <source> refers to a Source Agency or ordered collection of Source Agencies\nspecified by the Exchange at the time of Contract listing, which will be incorporated into the\nSource Agency hierarchy above and used to determine the occurrence of the Underlying.\n<source> may refer to a singular agency, multiple agencies, an agency by distinguishing\ncharacteristics, by category or type (e.g., “official government statistical body,” “primary wire\nservice”), or any combination thereof. When multiple agencies are specified, they may be\napplied in the hierarchical order designated by the Exchange if so specified, with the highest-\nranked available and responsive agency taking precedence for purposes of determining the\nExpiration Value. A lower-ranked agency shall only be consulted if all higher-ranked agencies\nare unavailable, unresponsive, have not reported on the Underlying by the Expiration time, or\nif the Exchange, in its sole discretion, determines that a higher-ranked agency’s reporting is\nincomplete, erroneous, or otherwise insufficient to determine the Expiration Value. If <source>\ndesignates multiple agencies without specifying a hierarchical order, the Exchange shall\nresolve any conflict between reporting agencies at its sole discretion.\n\n<word>: <word> refers to the particular word or phrase potentially to be mentioned by\n<entity>. It may refer to a word being said a minimum number of times. It may also refer to\none of multiple words/phrases, any of which are acceptable (e.g., “Doge/Dogecoin”).\n\f<time period>: <time period> refers to a specific range of time, event or discrete date and\ntime specified by the Exchange. This may be defined by, but is not limited to: a specific event\nor context (e.g., “during the State of the Union address”), exact dates or times, relative time\nmarkers (e.g., “before July 1, 2027,” “in Q1 2026”), event-based periods (e.g., “during any\ncampaign rally in October 2026,” “during the awards ceremony”), and broader intervals (e.g.,\n“Q1–Q2 2027,” “January–March 2026”).\n\nUnless stated otherwise, “Between” is inclusive of both endpoints, while “before” and “after”\nexclude the specified date. <time period> may also refer to “Any” or “None”, to multiple dates\n(even if non-consecutive), or to a singular and discrete date or time.\n\nWhen <time period> refers to a specific event (such as an address, speech, performance, or\nbroadcast), the Exchange may specify what is included, including whether it includes both live\nand pre-recorded segments (including whether advertisements are included). Where a\ntimezone is not specified, ET is assumed.\n\n\nPayout Criterion: The Payout Criterion for the Contract encompasses the Expiration Values that\n<word> is said by <entity> <time period>.\n\n\nThe word must appear as a distinct, standalone unit, not buried inside another word. Plural\nand possessive noun forms count. Other grammatical changes (tense, conjugation, derivation)\ndo not. If <word> appears separated from other words by a space or hyphen or in a\ncompound form with a space or hyphen, it counts. If <word> is fused into a single\nunhyphenated word, it does not count.\n\nIf <time period> refers to an event and that event is cancelled, and the market contains a\nstrike stating “Event does not qualify/occur”, such a strike shall resolve “Yes” and all others\n“No”. If <time period> refers to an event and that event is cancelled but such strikes are NOT\nlisted, the Contracts will resolve to the last fair price determined at the discretion of the\nExchange. If the event is postponed, and such a postponement is announced by the end of the\nfollowing calendar day to be rescheduled to a time within 14 calendar days, the markets shall\nremain open. If the event captured in <time period> is a live-stream or broadcast, the\nExchange may keep the market open for 24 hours for the release of an official recording.\nFurther granular details on conditions for these Contracts is available below.\n\nAdditional clarification(s):\n\n     Possessive noun forms of <word>, plurals, and possessive plural noun forms are\n     INCLUDED:\n          <word> is “Immigrant” → “Immigrants” counts\n          <word> is “Egg” → “eggs’ shells” counts\n          <word> is “Russia” → “Russia’s” counts, “Russian” does not\n     If <word> exists only in adjective form, no plural form exists:\n          <word> is “Economic” → “Economics” does not count (“Economic” is an adjective\n          for which “Economics” is not a plural)\n     Plural nouns occurring within proper nouns and noun phrases are included:\n          <word> is “Cat” → “Cats the musical” counts\n\f    Grammatical variations beyond plurals/possessives are NOT included:\n         <word> is “Immigrant” → “Immigration” does NOT count\n         <word> is “Run” → “Running” or “Ran” do NOT count\n    When <word> specifies a plural form, the singular does NOT count:\n         <word> is “Veterans” → “Veteran” does NOT count\n    Words that are spelled the same as the plural form of <word> (if such exists) but are\n    themselves not a plural noun are included:\n         <word> is “Wind” → “Winds up the clock” counts\n         <word> is “Border” → “The United States has strong borders” counts\n    Open compounds (words separated by spaces) count:\n         <word> is “fire” → “fire station” counts\n         <word> is “couch” → “couch potato” counts\n    Hyphenated compounds (words connected by hyphens) count:\n         <word> is “Palestine” → “pro-Palestine” counts\n         <word> is “fat” → “non-fat” counts\n    Closed compounds (single word, no spaces/hyphens) do not count:\n         <word> is “fire” → “wildfire” does not count\n         <word> is “fire” → “firefighter” does not count\n    Multi-word <word> in larger constructions: When <word> is a multi-word phrase\n    appearing within a hyphenated construction, it counts only if <word> appears as a\n    complete, unmodified element:\n         <word> is “New York” → “New York-based” counts (complete element)\n    Portmanteaus (words blended from two words where parts of each are combined) are\n    NOT included unless the portmanteau clearly contains <word> as a distinct, unaltered\n    element:\n         <word> is “MAGA” → “MAGA-nificent” counts (MAGA appears as distinct element)\n         <word> is “magnificent” → “MAGA-nificent” does NOT count (portmanteau blend)\n\nDictionary determination: Both the Merriam-Webster Dictionary (available online) AND the\nOxford English Dictionary shall be used to determine compound type and/or conventional\nspelling patterns. Inclusion in either dictionary as an open or hyphenated compound shall\nsatisfy the Payout Criterion. If neither provides clarity (or the word is not included),\ndetermination is based on whether written as single unit (closed/doesn’t count) vs. spaces or\nhyphens (open or hyphenated/counts) and/or context and previous usage.\n\nPHONETIC EQUIVALENCIES\n\n    Homophones (same sound, different spelling) do not count:\n        <word> is “write” → “right” does not count\n    Homonyms and homographs (same spelling) COUNT regardless of meaning or\n    pronunciation:\n        <word> is “bass” → both “bass guitar” and “bass fishing” count\n    Proper and common nouns are treated identically:\n        <word> is “Apple” → both “Apple Inc.” and “apple” (fruit) count\n        <word> is “Will” → both “Will Smith” and “I will go” count\n    Minor unintentional mispronunciations COUNT if context makes intent clear:\n        <word> is “Mamdani” → “Mandani” counts\n    Severe mispronunciations that make <word> unrecognizable do NOT count.\n    Trademarked spellings do not count, even when pronounced identically, unless the word\n\fitself is the same:\n      <word> is “lift” → “Lyft” (pronounced “lift”) does not count\n      <word> is “uber” → “Uber” counts\nWords with non-standard transliteration to English count within reason, provided they are\nphonetically equivalent:\n      <word> is “Zelensky” → any of “Zelenski,” “Zelenskii,” “Zelensky,” or “Zelenskiy”\n      count if pronounced equivalently\nContractions do not count for their constituent words unless otherwise explicitly specified\nby the Exchange:\n      <word> is “not” → “won’t,” “can’t,” “don’t,” “isn’t” do not count\nNumbers spoken as words COUNT, when spoken exactly (not part of a larger number):\n      <word> is “five” → saying “five” or reading “$5” aloud as “five dollars” counts,\n      saying “five hundred” does NOT count\n      <word> is “410” → “four hundred ten”, “four one zero” or “four ten” counts\nOrdinals COUNT when <word> is written numerically OR a phrase that includes a\nnumber:\n      <word> is “January 6” → “January 6th” counts\n      <word> is “3” (written numerically) → “3rd” (spoken as “third”) counts\n      <word> is “Eight War” → “8 Wars” and “Eighth War” will count\nCardinal and ordinal number words are distinct:\n      <word> is “one” → “first” does NOT count\n      <word> is “first” → “one” does NOT count\nAcronyms and abbreviations count when pronunciation or letter-by-letter spelling\nmatches <word>:\n      <word> is “NASA” → “NASA” (pronounced “NAH-suh”) counts\n      <word> is “NASA” → “N-A-S-A” (spelled out) counts\nAcronyms and abbreviations count as <word> when pronounced as the full word:\n      <word> is “Doctor” → “Dr.” (pronounced “Doctor”) counts\nExpanded forms of acronyms do NOT count:\n      <word> is “AI” → “artificial intelligence” does not count\nWords in foreign languages do NOT count unless they are perfect cognates with an\nEnglish word:\n      <word> is “fire” → “fuego” (Spanish) does NOT count\nEnglish words within foreign sentences count:\n      <word> is “policy” → “Nuestra policy es clara” counts\n<word> in organization/company names counts:\n      <word> is “Securities” → “Bank of America Securities” counts\nWords in URLs, emails, handles, and hashtags (exclusive of domain structure, email\nprovider or symbols) are treated as compounds when spoken as complete words, with the\ntype of compound subject to aforementioned rules:\n      <word> is “fire” → “firestation.com” pronounced “fire station dot com” counts\n      <word> is “fire” → “wildfire.com” pronounced “wildfire dot com” does NOT count\n      <word> is “apple” → “apple.com” pronounced “apple dot com” does count\n      When presented in URL, email, handle, or hashtag form, <word> shall be treated as\n      a compound, not a multi-word word\nSung, rapped, or poetic words COUNT if phonetically recognizable:\n      <word> is “money” → “moneyyy” (extended in rap) counts\n      Extreme distortion making <word> unrecognizable does NOT count.\nPhonetic alphabet spelling (“Foxtrot India Romeo Echo” for “FIRE”) does NOT count.\n\fCANCELLATIONS AND DELAYS\n\n   The Exchange may list an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike for any Contract. If listed,\n   such a strike refers to the structural conditions of the market, and is NOT adjudicated as a\n   <word> needing to be said by or validated by having been said by <entity>. If listed, this\n   strike resolves to “Yes” whenever the event fails to occur or qualify under the Payout\n   Criterion, or any other circumstance prevents normal resolution.\n   If no such strike is listed, and <time period> refers to a specific event, the following rules\n   apply if the event is cancelled, postponed, rescheduled, or materially altered (including\n   being closed to press) such that no video is released within one calendar day of the\n   original start time of the event:\n         If the event is cancelled, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price determined in\n         the sole discretion of the Exchange.\n         If the event is postponed or rescheduled, the outcome depends on whether a new\n         date is publicly announced within one calendar day (i.e. if the event was scheduled\n         to begin on Monday, any time up to 11:59PM on Tuesday falls within this period) of\n         the originally scheduled start time:\n               If no new date is announced within one calendar day, the Contract will resolve\n               to the last fair price determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\n               If a new date is announced within one calendar day, the outcome depends on\n               when the rescheduled event is set to occur:\n                     If the rescheduled date falls within fourteen (14) calendar days of the\n                     originally scheduled date, the Contract shall remain open and <word>\n                     stated during the rescheduled event will count.\n                           The fourteen-day window begins at 12:00 AM ET on the originally\n                           scheduled date and ends at 11:59 PM ET fourteen days later, unless\n                           an alternate timezone is explicitly specified.\n                           Example: <time period> is “during the State of the Union on January\n                           15, 2026” rescheduled to January 20, 2026 → words spoken during\n                           the rescheduled address count.\n                     If the rescheduled date falls more than fourteen (14) calendar days after\n                     the originally scheduled date, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price\n                     determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\n         Any Contract that cannot be resolved through the Source Agency hierarchy will\n         instead be settled at the Last Fair Price. The Exchange will disclose the methodology\n         used to determine the Last Fair Price (e.g., Last Traded Price, Time-Weighted\n         Average Price) at the time of Issuance.\n         If an event begins but is interrupted, abbreviated, or ends prematurely, words\n         stated by <entity> during the portion of the event that did occur will count and the\n         market will otherwise resolve.\n   If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window but the venue, format, or medium\n   changes (e.g., moved to a different location, changed from in-person to virtual (with the\n   exception of being closed to press)), words stated during the event will count.\n   Special condition: Across both cases, whether an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike is\n   listed or not, if the event specified as or in <time period> is a live-stream or broadcast (or\n   relayed as such) but the live stream/broadcast does not occur, the Exchange will instead\n   use an officially released recording as the Underlying, and may delay resolution by up to\n   one calendar day to allow for the release of such a recording.\n\f          If partial snippets are released, Contracts on words that do not appear will be\n          resolved to last fair price, and Contracts on those that do will be resolved to “Yes”.\n          If no recording is released, the relevant outcomes triggered by the\n          presence/absence of an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike shall occur as outlined\n          above.\n\nTECHNICAL DETAILS (UNLESS OTHERWISE SPECIFIED)\n\n     When <time period> refers to a specific event, pre-recorded content broadcast,\n     streamed, or published as part of that event is included if presented as part of the official\n     presentation.\n          Example: <time period> is “during the concert” with pre-recorded video interlude\n          where entity speaks → words from interlude count\n          Example: <time period> is “during the television appearance” with pre-taped\n          segment aired during broadcast → words from segment count\n     Behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are NOT\n     included unless officially broadcast or published as part of <time period>.\n     Subtitles and captions that display <word> on screen but are not spoken aloud by\n     <entity> do NOT count.\n     Sign language interpretation or usage by entity does NOT count as saying <word> unless\n     the Contract explicitly specifies that sign language counts.\n     Text that entity displays on screen (presentation slides, teleprompter visible to audience,\n     signatures) does NOT count unless entity reads it aloud.\n     Content generated by AI, deepfakes, or synthetic voice technology impersonating entity\n     does NOT count unless the synthetic content is officially commissioned, authorized, or\n     published by entity, OR the Contract explicitly specifies that AI-generated content counts.\n     If <word> is muted due to technical failure or censorship it shall not count unless\n     corroborating contextual evidence (including surrounding speech, or an official\n     uncensored recording or transcript) confirms that <entity> specifically uttered <word>\n     during the muted period.\n\nMinimum Tick: The Minimum Tick size for the Contract shall be $0.01.\n\nPosition Accountability Level: The Position Accountability Level for the Contract shall be\n$25,000 per strike, per Member.\n\nLast Trading Date: The Last Trading Date of the Contract will be the Expiration Date. The Last\nTrading Time will be the Expiration time.\n\nSettlement Date: The Settlement Date of the Contract shall be no later than the day after the\nExpiration Date, unless the Market Outcome is under review pursuant to Rule 7.1.\n\nExpiration Date: When <time period> refers to a specific event: The latest Expiration Date of\nthe Contract shall be fourteen (14) calendar days after the originally scheduled date of the\nevent. If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window, expiration will be moved to an\nearlier date and time in accordance with Rule 7.2. When <time period> is defined by specific\ndates: The latest Expiration Date of the Contract shall be two weeks after the end of <time\nperiod>. If an event described in the Payout Criterion occurs and a consensus has been\nreached on all terms, then expiration will be moved to an earlier date and time in accordance\nwith Rule 7.2.\n\fExpiration time: The Expiration time of the Contract shall be 10:00 AM ET.\n\nSettlement Value: The Settlement Value for this Contract is $1.00.\n\nExpiration Value: The Expiration Value is the value of the Underlying as documented by the\nSource Agency on the Expiration Date at the Expiration time.\n\nContingencies: Before Settlement, Kalshi may, at its sole discretion, initiate the Market\nOutcome Review Process pursuant to Rule 7.1 of the Rulebook. If an Expiration Value cannot\nbe determined on the Expiration Date, Kalshi has the right to determine payouts pursuant to\nRule 7.1 in the Rulebook.\n\f\n\n[defendant] DX-4 Market packet: Ronaldo strike and challenged No resolution\nMarket URL: https://kalshi.com/markets/kxtrumpmentionb/trump-mention-b/kxtrumpmentionb-25dec06\n\nPublic market title: What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\n\nContract family: PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION\n\nStrike at issue: Ronaldo\n\nChallenged resolution: No\n\nRequested resolution: Yes\n\n\n[plaintiff] PX-R1 GovInfo transcript confirming Ronaldo utterances and Kennedy Center/FIFA Draw context\nSource: GovInfo, Compilation of Presidential Documents, DCPD202501162\nURL retrieved: https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/DCPD-202501162/html/DCPD-202501162.htm\nRetrieval time: 2026-06-29T22:00:00Z\nLocal captured HTML size/hash: 51,571 bytes; SHA-256 eadbceeecf3e94f5bd423bcb8e8511165fdc7265dd8c1e025870c2e8f34dfd99\n\nMaterial captured text from official GovInfo HTML/web.open:\n\nAdministration of Donald J. Trump, 2025\n\nTitle: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\nDate: December 5, 2025\n\nOpening note: [The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\n\nExcerpt - The President's Interest in Soccer (web.open lines 196-203):\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\"football,\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\n\nExcerpt - The President's Interest in Soccer (web.open lines 322-329):\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\nThe President. But they have a little more speed. But no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\n\nTiming/context note (web.open lines 461-462):\nNOTE: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. In his remarks, he referred to Trey Yingst, chief foreign correspondent, Fox News Channel; Cristiano Ronaldo, forward for Saudi Pro League club Al-Nass and Portugal's national soccer team; and Lionel Messi, forward for Major League Soccer club Inter Miami and Argentina's national team. A reporter referred to New York State Attorney General Letitia James.\nThe transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\n\nDocument category/location/name/subject metadata (web.open lines 463-468):\nCategories: Interviews With the News Media: Exchanges with reporters, Washington, DC.\nLocations: Washington, DC.\nNames include: Cristiano Ronaldo and Lionel Messi.\nSubjects include: Federation Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) World Cup; John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts; News media, Presidential interviews; Soccer.\nDCPD Number: DCPD202501162.\n\nCapture limits: This item is a focused text capture of the material official transcript title, Ronaldo excerpts, timing/correction note, and metadata. It is not a full video or audio artifact. The official transcript itself notes some portions could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\n\n[plaintiff] PX-R2 FIFA timing capture showing formal commencement time but not market-specific exclusion\nSource: FIFA official page, FIFA World Cup 2026 Final Draw\nURL: https://www.fifa.com/en/tournaments/mens/worldcup/canadamexicousa2026/live-draw\nRetrieval time: 2026-06-29T22:01:00Z\n\nMaterial captured text from web search/open result:\n- Page title/source: FIFA World Cup 2026™ Final Draw\n- The draw takes place at the Kennedy Center in Washington DC, USA.\n- The draw commences at 12:00 local time (17:00 UTC) on Friday 5 December 2025.\n\nCapture limits: This is a focused text capture of the official FIFA page timing statement located by web search. It is not a video capture of the draw ceremony.\n\n[plaintiff] PX-R3 Event-period terms and exclusions\n                                         NEWMENTION\n\nScope: These rules shall apply to this contract.\n\nUnderlying: The Underlying for this Contract is words used by <entity> <time period>.\nRevisions to the Underlying made after Expiration will not be accounted for in determining the\nExpiration Value.\n\nSource Agency: The Source Agencies are <source>.\n\nType: The type of Contract is an Event Contract.\n\nIssuance: After the initial Contract, Contract iterations will be listed on an as-needed basis at\nthe discretion of the Exchange and corresponding to the risk management needs of Members.\n\n<entity>: <entity> refers to the speaker, writer, performer, or communicator specified by the\nExchange. This may include (but is not limited to): a specific named individual, multiple\nindividuals specified using AND/OR logic, an individual identified by position or title, a group,\nband, team or collective entity, a specified member or members of a group, an organization,\ncompany, or institutional entity, or any combination of the aforementioned.\n\nWhen <entity> is defined by a position or title, the Contract tracks whoever holds that position\nduring <time period>, even if the individual holding the position changes. When <entity> is a\nspecific named individual, the identity remains consistent throughout. Name changes (e.g.,\nstage names, married names) do not create a new entity. When <entity> is a group or\norganization and the Contract does not specify particular members, any official\ncommunication or statement by any member or designated spokesperson counts. When using\nAND logic, all specified entities must independently say <word> during <time period>. When\nusing OR logic, at least one of the specified entities must say <word> during <time period>.\nThe Exchange may specify additional conditions such as “at least X members of” a group or\n“the majority of” a group.\n\n<source>: <source> refers to a Source Agency or ordered collection of Source Agencies\nspecified by the Exchange at the time of Contract listing, which will be incorporated into the\nSource Agency hierarchy above and used to determine the occurrence of the Underlying.\n<source> may refer to a singular agency, multiple agencies, an agency by distinguishing\ncharacteristics, by category or type (e.g., “official government statistical body,” “primary wire\nservice”), or any combination thereof. When multiple agencies are specified, they may be\napplied in the hierarchical order designated by the Exchange if so specified, with the highest-\nranked available and responsive agency taking precedence for purposes of determining the\nExpiration Value. A lower-ranked agency shall only be consulted if all higher-ranked agencies\nare unavailable, unresponsive, have not reported on the Underlying by the Expiration time, or\nif the Exchange, in its sole discretion, determines that a higher-ranked agency’s reporting is\nincomplete, erroneous, or otherwise insufficient to determine the Expiration Value. If <source>\ndesignates multiple agencies without specifying a hierarchical order, the Exchange shall\nresolve any conflict between reporting agencies at its sole discretion.\n\n<word>: <word> refers to the particular word or phrase potentially to be mentioned by\n<entity>. It may refer to a word being said a minimum number of times. It may also refer to\none of multiple words/phrases, any of which are acceptable (e.g., “Doge/Dogecoin”).\n\f<time period>: <time period> refers to a specific range of time, event or discrete date and\ntime specified by the Exchange. This may be defined by, but is not limited to: a specific event\nor context (e.g., “during the State of the Union address”), exact dates or times, relative time\nmarkers (e.g., “before July 1, 2027,” “in Q1 2026”), event-based periods (e.g., “during any\ncampaign rally in October 2026,” “during the awards ceremony”), and broader intervals (e.g.,\n“Q1–Q2 2027,” “January–March 2026”).\n\nUnless stated otherwise, “Between” is inclusive of both endpoints, while “before” and “after”\nexclude the specified date. <time period> may also refer to “Any” or “None”, to multiple dates\n(even if non-consecutive), or to a singular and discrete date or time.\n\nWhen <time period> refers to a specific event (such as an address, speech, performance, or\nbroadcast), the Exchange may specify what is included, including whether it includes both live\nand pre-recorded segments (including whether advertisements are included). Where a\ntimezone is not specified, ET is assumed.\n\n\nPayout Criterion: The Payout Criterion for the Contract encompasses the Expiration Values that\n<word> is said by <entity> <time period>.\n\n\nThe word must appear as a distinct, standalone unit, not buried inside another word. Plural\nand possessive noun forms count. Other grammatical changes (tense, conjugation, derivation)\ndo not. If <word> appears separated from other words by a space or hyphen or in a\ncompound form with a space or hyphen, it counts. If <word> is fused into a single\nunhyphenated word, it does not count.\n\nIf <time period> refers to an event and that event is cancelled, and the market contains a\nstrike stating “Event does not qualify/occur”, such a strike shall resolve “Yes” and all others\n“No”. If <time period> refers to an event and that event is cancelled but such strikes are NOT\nlisted, the Contracts will resolve to the last fair price determined at the discretion of the\nExchange. If the event is postponed, and such a postponement is announced by the end of the\nfollowing calendar day to be rescheduled to a time within 14 calendar days, the markets shall\nremain open. If the event captured in <time period> is a live-stream or broadcast, the\nExchange may keep the market open for 24 hours for the release of an official recording.\nFurther granular details on conditions for these Contracts is available below.\n\nAdditional clarification(s):\n\n     Possessive noun forms of <word>, plurals, and possessive plural noun forms are\n     INCLUDED:\n          <word> is “Immigrant” → “Immigrants” counts\n          <word> is “Egg” → “eggs’ shells” counts\n          <word> is “Russia” → “Russia’s” counts, “Russian” does not\n     If <word> exists only in adjective form, no plural form exists:\n          <word> is “Economic” → “Economics” does not count (“Economic” is an adjective\n          for which “Economics” is not a plural)\n     Plural nouns occurring within proper nouns and noun phrases are included:\n          <word> is “Cat” → “Cats the musical” counts\n\f    Grammatical variations beyond plurals/possessives are NOT included:\n         <word> is “Immigrant” → “Immigration” does NOT count\n         <word> is “Run” → “Running” or “Ran” do NOT count\n    When <word> specifies a plural form, the singular does NOT count:\n         <word> is “Veterans” → “Veteran” does NOT count\n    Words that are spelled the same as the plural form of <word> (if such exists) but are\n    themselves not a plural noun are included:\n         <word> is “Wind” → “Winds up the clock” counts\n         <word> is “Border” → “The United States has strong borders” counts\n    Open compounds (words separated by spaces) count:\n         <word> is “fire” → “fire station” counts\n         <word> is “couch” → “couch potato” counts\n    Hyphenated compounds (words connected by hyphens) count:\n         <word> is “Palestine” → “pro-Palestine” counts\n         <word> is “fat” → “non-fat” counts\n    Closed compounds (single word, no spaces/hyphens) do not count:\n         <word> is “fire” → “wildfire” does not count\n         <word> is “fire” → “firefighter” does not count\n    Multi-word <word> in larger constructions: When <word> is a multi-word phrase\n    appearing within a hyphenated construction, it counts only if <word> appears as a\n    complete, unmodified element:\n         <word> is “New York” → “New York-based” counts (complete element)\n    Portmanteaus (words blended from two words where parts of each are combined) are\n    NOT included unless the portmanteau clearly contains <word> as a distinct, unaltered\n    element:\n         <word> is “MAGA” → “MAGA-nificent” counts (MAGA appears as distinct element)\n         <word> is “magnificent” → “MAGA-nificent” does NOT count (portmanteau blend)\n\nDictionary determination: Both the Merriam-Webster Dictionary (available online) AND the\nOxford English Dictionary shall be used to determine compound type and/or conventional\nspelling patterns. Inclusion in either dictionary as an open or hyphenated compound shall\nsatisfy the Payout Criterion. If neither provides clarity (or the word is not included),\ndetermination is based on whether written as single unit (closed/doesn’t count) vs. spaces or\nhyphens (open or hyphenated/counts) and/or context and previous usage.\n\nPHONETIC EQUIVALENCIES\n\n    Homophones (same sound, different spelling) do not count:\n        <word> is “write” → “right” does not count\n    Homonyms and homographs (same spelling) COUNT regardless of meaning or\n    pronunciation:\n        <word> is “bass” → both “bass guitar” and “bass fishing” count\n    Proper and common nouns are treated identically:\n        <word> is “Apple” → both “Apple Inc.” and “apple” (fruit) count\n        <word> is “Will” → both “Will Smith” and “I will go” count\n    Minor unintentional mispronunciations COUNT if context makes intent clear:\n        <word> is “Mamdani” → “Mandani” counts\n    Severe mispronunciations that make <word> unrecognizable do NOT count.\n    Trademarked spellings do not count, even when pronounced identically, unless the word\n\fitself is the same:\n      <word> is “lift” → “Lyft” (pronounced “lift”) does not count\n      <word> is “uber” → “Uber” counts\nWords with non-standard transliteration to English count within reason, provided they are\nphonetically equivalent:\n      <word> is “Zelensky” → any of “Zelenski,” “Zelenskii,” “Zelensky,” or “Zelenskiy”\n      count if pronounced equivalently\nContractions do not count for their constituent words unless otherwise explicitly specified\nby the Exchange:\n      <word> is “not” → “won’t,” “can’t,” “don’t,” “isn’t” do not count\nNumbers spoken as words COUNT, when spoken exactly (not part of a larger number):\n      <word> is “five” → saying “five” or reading “$5” aloud as “five dollars” counts,\n      saying “five hundred” does NOT count\n      <word> is “410” → “four hundred ten”, “four one zero” or “four ten” counts\nOrdinals COUNT when <word> is written numerically OR a phrase that includes a\nnumber:\n      <word> is “January 6” → “January 6th” counts\n      <word> is “3” (written numerically) → “3rd” (spoken as “third”) counts\n      <word> is “Eight War” → “8 Wars” and “Eighth War” will count\nCardinal and ordinal number words are distinct:\n      <word> is “one” → “first” does NOT count\n      <word> is “first” → “one” does NOT count\nAcronyms and abbreviations count when pronunciation or letter-by-letter spelling\nmatches <word>:\n      <word> is “NASA” → “NASA” (pronounced “NAH-suh”) counts\n      <word> is “NASA” → “N-A-S-A” (spelled out) counts\nAcronyms and abbreviations count as <word> when pronounced as the full word:\n      <word> is “Doctor” → “Dr.” (pronounced “Doctor”) counts\nExpanded forms of acronyms do NOT count:\n      <word> is “AI” → “artificial intelligence” does not count\nWords in foreign languages do NOT count unless they are perfect cognates with an\nEnglish word:\n      <word> is “fire” → “fuego” (Spanish) does NOT count\nEnglish words within foreign sentences count:\n      <word> is “policy” → “Nuestra policy es clara” counts\n<word> in organization/company names counts:\n      <word> is “Securities” → “Bank of America Securities” counts\nWords in URLs, emails, handles, and hashtags (exclusive of domain structure, email\nprovider or symbols) are treated as compounds when spoken as complete words, with the\ntype of compound subject to aforementioned rules:\n      <word> is “fire” → “firestation.com” pronounced “fire station dot com” counts\n      <word> is “fire” → “wildfire.com” pronounced “wildfire dot com” does NOT count\n      <word> is “apple” → “apple.com” pronounced “apple dot com” does count\n      When presented in URL, email, handle, or hashtag form, <word> shall be treated as\n      a compound, not a multi-word word\nSung, rapped, or poetic words COUNT if phonetically recognizable:\n      <word> is “money” → “moneyyy” (extended in rap) counts\n      Extreme distortion making <word> unrecognizable does NOT count.\nPhonetic alphabet spelling (“Foxtrot India Romeo Echo” for “FIRE”) does NOT count.\n\fCANCELLATIONS AND DELAYS\n\n   The Exchange may list an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike for any Contract. If listed,\n   such a strike refers to the structural conditions of the market, and is NOT adjudicated as a\n   <word> needing to be said by or validated by having been said by <entity>. If listed, this\n   strike resolves to “Yes” whenever the event fails to occur or qualify under the Payout\n   Criterion, or any other circumstance prevents normal resolution.\n   If no such strike is listed, and <time period> refers to a specific event, the following rules\n   apply if the event is cancelled, postponed, rescheduled, or materially altered (including\n   being closed to press) such that no video is released within one calendar day of the\n   original start time of the event:\n         If the event is cancelled, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price determined in\n         the sole discretion of the Exchange.\n         If the event is postponed or rescheduled, the outcome depends on whether a new\n         date is publicly announced within one calendar day (i.e. if the event was scheduled\n         to begin on Monday, any time up to 11:59PM on Tuesday falls within this period) of\n         the originally scheduled start time:\n               If no new date is announced within one calendar day, the Contract will resolve\n               to the last fair price determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\n               If a new date is announced within one calendar day, the outcome depends on\n               when the rescheduled event is set to occur:\n                     If the rescheduled date falls within fourteen (14) calendar days of the\n                     originally scheduled date, the Contract shall remain open and <word>\n                     stated during the rescheduled event will count.\n                           The fourteen-day window begins at 12:00 AM ET on the originally\n                           scheduled date and ends at 11:59 PM ET fourteen days later, unless\n                           an alternate timezone is explicitly specified.\n                           Example: <time period> is “during the State of the Union on January\n                           15, 2026” rescheduled to January 20, 2026 → words spoken during\n                           the rescheduled address count.\n                     If the rescheduled date falls more than fourteen (14) calendar days after\n                     the originally scheduled date, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price\n                     determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\n         Any Contract that cannot be resolved through the Source Agency hierarchy will\n         instead be settled at the Last Fair Price. The Exchange will disclose the methodology\n         used to determine the Last Fair Price (e.g., Last Traded Price, Time-Weighted\n         Average Price) at the time of Issuance.\n         If an event begins but is interrupted, abbreviated, or ends prematurely, words\n         stated by <entity> during the portion of the event that did occur will count and the\n         market will otherwise resolve.\n   If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window but the venue, format, or medium\n   changes (e.g., moved to a different location, changed from in-person to virtual (with the\n   exception of being closed to press)), words stated during the event will count.\n   Special condition: Across both cases, whether an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike is\n   listed or not, if the event specified as or in <time period> is a live-stream or broadcast (or\n   relayed as such) but the live stream/broadcast does not occur, the Exchange will instead\n   use an officially released recording as the Underlying, and may delay resolution by up to\n   one calendar day to allow for the release of such a recording.\n\f          If partial snippets are released, Contracts on words that do not appear will be\n          resolved to last fair price, and Contracts on those that do will be resolved to “Yes”.\n          If no recording is released, the relevant outcomes triggered by the\n          presence/absence of an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike shall occur as outlined\n          above.\n\nTECHNICAL DETAILS (UNLESS OTHERWISE SPECIFIED)\n\n     When <time period> refers to a specific event, pre-recorded content broadcast,\n     streamed, or published as part of that event is included if presented as part of the official\n     presentation.\n          Example: <time period> is “during the concert” with pre-recorded video interlude\n          where entity speaks → words from interlude count\n          Example: <time period> is “during the television appearance” with pre-taped\n          segment aired during broadcast → words from segment count\n     Behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are NOT\n     included unless officially broadcast or published as part of <time period>.\n     Subtitles and captions that display <word> on screen but are not spoken aloud by\n     <entity> do NOT count.\n     Sign language interpretation or usage by entity does NOT count as saying <word> unless\n     the Contract explicitly specifies that sign language counts.\n     Text that entity displays on screen (presentation slides, teleprompter visible to audience,\n     signatures) does NOT count unless entity reads it aloud.\n     Content generated by AI, deepfakes, or synthetic voice technology impersonating entity\n     does NOT count unless the synthetic content is officially commissioned, authorized, or\n     published by entity, OR the Contract explicitly specifies that AI-generated content counts.\n     If <word> is muted due to technical failure or censorship it shall not count unless\n     corroborating contextual evidence (including surrounding speech, or an official\n     uncensored recording or transcript) confirms that <entity> specifically uttered <word>\n     during the muted period.\n\nMinimum Tick: The Minimum Tick size for the Contract shall be $0.01.\n\nPosition Accountability Level: The Position Accountability Level for the Contract shall be\n$25,000 per strike, per Member.\n\nLast Trading Date: The Last Trading Date of the Contract will be the Expiration Date. The Last\nTrading Time will be the Expiration time.\n\nSettlement Date: The Settlement Date of the Contract shall be no later than the day after the\nExpiration Date, unless the Market Outcome is under review pursuant to Rule 7.1.\n\nExpiration Date: When <time period> refers to a specific event: The latest Expiration Date of\nthe Contract shall be fourteen (14) calendar days after the originally scheduled date of the\nevent. If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window, expiration will be moved to an\nearlier date and time in accordance with Rule 7.2. When <time period> is defined by specific\ndates: The latest Expiration Date of the Contract shall be two weeks after the end of <time\nperiod>. If an event described in the Payout Criterion occurs and a consensus has been\nreached on all terms, then expiration will be moved to an earlier date and time in accordance\nwith Rule 7.2.\n\fExpiration time: The Expiration time of the Contract shall be 10:00 AM ET.\n\nSettlement Value: The Settlement Value for this Contract is $1.00.\n\nExpiration Value: The Expiration Value is the value of the Underlying as documented by the\nSource Agency on the Expiration Date at the Expiration time.\n\nContingencies: Before Settlement, Kalshi may, at its sole discretion, initiate the Market\nOutcome Review Process pursuant to Rule 7.1 of the Rulebook. If an Expiration Value cannot\nbe determined on the Expiration Date, Kalshi has the right to determine payouts pursuant to\nRule 7.1 in the Rulebook.\n\f\n\n[defendant] DX-S1 GovInfo official transcript: prior reporter exchange\nSource: GovInfo, Compilation of Presidential Documents, DCPD202501162\nURL retrieved: https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/DCPD-202501162/html/DCPD-202501162.htm\nRetrieval time: 2026-06-29T22:00:00Z\nLocal captured HTML size/hash: 51,571 bytes; SHA-256 eadbceeecf3e94f5bd423bcb8e8511165fdc7265dd8c1e025870c2e8f34dfd99\n\nMaterial captured text from official GovInfo HTML/web.open:\n\nAdministration of Donald J. Trump, 2025\n\nTitle: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\nDate: December 5, 2025\n\nOpening note: [The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\n\nExcerpt - The President's Interest in Soccer (web.open lines 196-203):\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\"football,\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\n\nExcerpt - The President's Interest in Soccer (web.open lines 322-329):\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\nThe President. But they have a little more speed. But no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\n\nTiming/context note (web.open lines 461-462):\nNOTE: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. In his remarks, he referred to Trey Yingst, chief foreign correspondent, Fox News Channel; Cristiano Ronaldo, forward for Saudi Pro League club Al-Nass and Portugal's national soccer team; and Lionel Messi, forward for Major League Soccer club Inter Miami and Argentina's national team. A reporter referred to New York State Attorney General Letitia James.\nThe transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\n\nDocument category/location/name/subject metadata (web.open lines 463-468):\nCategories: Interviews With the News Media: Exchanges with reporters, Washington, DC.\nLocations: Washington, DC.\nNames include: Cristiano Ronaldo and Lionel Messi.\nSubjects include: Federation Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) World Cup; John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts; News media, Presidential interviews; Soccer.\nDCPD Number: DCPD202501162.\n\nCapture limits: This item is a focused text capture of the material official transcript title, Ronaldo excerpts, timing/correction note, and metadata. It is not a full video or audio artifact. The official transcript itself notes some portions could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\n\n[defendant] DX-S2 FIFA official draw commencement time\nSource: FIFA official page, FIFA World Cup 2026 Final Draw\nURL: https://www.fifa.com/en/tournaments/mens/worldcup/canadamexicousa2026/live-draw\nRetrieval time: 2026-06-29T22:01:00Z\n\nMaterial captured text from web search/open result:\n- Page title/source: FIFA World Cup 2026™ Final Draw\n- The draw takes place at the Kennedy Center in Washington DC, USA.\n- The draw commences at 12:00 local time (17:00 UTC) on Friday 5 December 2025.\n\nCapture limits: This is a focused text capture of the official FIFA page timing statement located by web search. It is not a video capture of the draw ceremony.\n\nSubmitted evidence:\n[plaintiff arguments] Official White House video page capture: President Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing (ev_db357d4e9407_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-db357d4e9407)\nSource: https://www.whitehouse.gov/videos/president-trump-attends-the-fifa-world-cup-drawing/\nSHA-256: `db357d4e940728d417ae4f7f3caac6b78d3fd3e4aba70d46fe10c6132d45997a`\nBytes: 1300\nRelevance: Establishes that the White House officially published a video page titled President Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing, dated December 5, 2025, with a full-video link and related World Cup Draw videos; relevant to source chain and event context.\n\n[plaintiff arguments] YouTube metadata capture: Trump Talks Cristiano Ronaldo at FIFA Draw (ev_4e1045905547_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-4e1045905547)\nSource: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Cb2yO0lLEnM\nSHA-256: `4e10459055477440085fe5e20d970eb2488e61d13a5e2b3133a3656bed7526d7`\nBytes: 1779\nRelevance: Provides a public clip source and page metadata asserting that at the FIFA World Cup Draw Ceremony Trump shared a story about meeting Cristiano Ronaldo and said Ronaldo was a great person; relevant to the alleged Ronaldo utterance, though weaker than an official full transcript or video.\n\n[defendant arguments] GovInfo official transcript capture: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the FIFA World Cup Draw (ev_a1b1f6b1b7bd_submitted-evidence-03-defendant-a1b1f6b1b7bd)\nSource: https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/DCPD-202501162/html/DCPD-202501162.htm\nSHA-256: `a1b1f6b1b7bd0b691c7fe8d97467dd0d085e2b22387ae4198270764de66e56e2`\nBytes: 3070\nRelevance: Official transcript identifies the relevant Trump remarks as an exchange with reporters prior to the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw; it includes the Ronaldo utterances and timing/correction notes, directly bearing on whether the utterances were during the countable event period.\n\n[defendant arguments] FIFA official page capture: 2026 World Cup Final Draw start time (ev_3973dc8f98c0_submitted-evidence-04-defendant-3973dc8f98c0)\nSource: https://www.fifa.com/en/tournaments/mens/worldcup/canadamexicousa2026/live-draw\nSHA-256: `3973dc8f98c01702174f61f5548eb1e80efe64dd72b44f21ed0fa7d944f93248`\nBytes: 598\nRelevance: Establishes the official Final Draw start time as 12:00 local time on December 5, 2025, which helps compare the draw event period against the GovInfo transcript note that the reporter exchange occurred at 11:13 a.m.\n\nTechnical reports:\n[plaintiff] Plaintiff source-search and capture ledger\nSearched exact market/strike phrases, White House domain, public video pages, YouTube video IDs, and Kalshi live market URL. Submitted official White House page capture and YouTube metadata capture. Kalshi live page returned a Vercel security checkpoint/429; local browser was unavailable; Python pip/ensurepip unavailable for yt-dlp; direct YouTube caption/open paths were throttled or unavailable. Remaining best evidence would be a full official video/transcript or Kalshi resolution rationale if later accessible.\n\n[defendant] Defendant source-search and capture ledger\nInspected current AAR evidence and exact contents of plaintiff's White House and YouTube captures. Retrieved GovInfo official HTML transcript with curl from DCPD-202501162; local full HTML was 51,571 bytes with SHA-256 eadbceeecf3e94f5bd423bcb8e8511165fdc7265dd8c1e025870c2e8f34dfd99, then submitted a focused material text capture as DX-1. Searched official draw timing and submitted the FIFA official page timing statement as DX-2. Remaining gaps: full Kalshi market source hierarchy/resolution rationale and full WH/FIFA video were not captured, but official GovInfo timing/title plus FIFA start time resolve the material timing issue.\n\nCall submit_council_vote with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated.\nKeep the rationale brief: no more than three sentences.\n\nCouncil API instructions:\nYou are a council member. Decide the proposition from the admitted record.\nYou may examine admitted evidence through read-only tools when exact bytes, metadata, or exhibit contents matter.\nDo not search the web, introduce new facts, create new evidence, or upload evidence.\nWhen ready, call submit_council_vote exactly once with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated and a concise rationale.\n","state":"ready","status":"ready","tools":[{"description":"Return the current visible arbitration record for this council member.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{},"type":"object"},"name":"get_case","read_only":true},{"description":"List visible immutable record evidence.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{},"type":"object"},"name":"list_evidence","read_only":true},{"description":"Return metadata and read limits for one visible evidence item.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"evidence_id":{"type":"string"}},"required":["evidence_id"],"type":"object"},"name":"stat_evidence","read_only":true},{"description":"Read a bounded byte range from one visible evidence item as base64.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"evidence_id":{"type":"string"},"length":{"minimum":1,"type":"integer"},"offset":{"minimum":0,"type":"integer"}},"required":["evidence_id","offset","length"],"type":"object"},"name":"read_evidence_range","read_only":true},{"description":"Submit one council vote for the current deliberation opportunity.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"rationale":{"type":"string"},"vote":{"enum":["demonstrated","not_demonstrated"],"type":"string"}},"required":["vote","rationale"],"type":"object"},"name":"submit_council_vote","read_only":false}],"turn":{"attempts_max":3,"attempts_remaining":3,"completed":false,"deadline":"2026-06-29T22:18:45.386037689Z","deliberation_round":1,"member_id":"C2","opportunity_id":"deliberation:1:C2","phase":"deliberation","remaining_ms":889046,"role_id":"council","turn_number":10},"wait":{"reason":"ready","state_version":14,"version":17}},"isError":false},"server":"aar","tool":"wait_for_opportunity"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1782770636345}]}
